<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DIGS AT ASHCROFT DURING HEALTH CARE APPEARANCE AT MU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ President Clinton said
it once. Then he said it again and again:
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate needs one more vote _ just one _ to pass a
sweeping patients' bill of rights that the president can sign.
</P>
<P>
   In a Missouri visit Thursday laden with political overtones,
Clinton never mentioned the name of the senator whose vote he
needs. But almost everyone in the crowd of 1,300 at Jesse
Auditorium at the University of Missouri knew who was on the
president's mind.
</P>
<P>
   That was John Ashcroft, the Republican senator seeking
re-election this year against the man who stood alongside the
president Thursday _ Gov. Mel Carnahan, a fellow Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton expressed frustration at the bill's narrow failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so close,'' the president told an enthusiastic crowd in
one of the most Democratic areas of the state. ``I came here
because I don't think we ought to stop one vote short.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill is designed to give patients more choices in health
care and the authority to sue their insurance providers for bad
service. The version the president backs easily passed the House
last fall but was defeated in the Senate last month on a 51-48
count.
</P>
<P>
   But one Democratic senator who was absent has said he would have
voted for the bill, making the tally 51-49. If one Republican
switches sides, the count moves to 50-50, and Vice President Al
Gore would break the tie in favor of passing the House version.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's other senator, Republican Kit Bond, also voted
against the bill. Bond, however, was re-elected in 1998 and is not
on the political radar screen this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survey after survey after survey shows that more than 70
percent of all Americans, whether they identify themselves as
Republicans or Democrats or independents, support a strong,
enforceable patients' bill of rights,'' Clinton said. ``And,
therefore, in Washington we have an obligation to pass it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's visit, with its dual purposes of lobbying for a
favored bill and promoting Carnahan in one of the year's most hotly
contested Senate races, apparently failed to persuade Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the president's 24-minute address, the senator's
staff released a pair of news releases that underscored Ashcroft's
continuing support for a Republican-backed Senate version of the
patients' bill of rights. Clinton says that proposal falls far
short of what's needed.
</P>
<P>
   Using some of the same rhetoric that Clinton employed, Ashcroft
said he'll continue to back a ``real'' patients' bill of rights
``that puts doctors and patients in control of health-care
decisions instead of insurance claims adjusters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People want the job accomplished,'' Ashcroft said in his news
release. ``They expect leadership to fix problems, not fix blame.''
</P>
<P>
   With the war of words continuing to escalate over the issue, the
main differences continue to center on who should be covered by a
patients' bill of rights and how much money an injured patient
should be able to recover from a health care provider in a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft and most Senate Republicans want damages limited to
$350,000 in federal court. Supporters of the House bill that has
drawn bipartisan support want no limits on damage awards.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton argues that a federal bill should cover all Americans.
The Senate version would cover people in self-insurance plans only
in which employers pay medical bills directly.
</P>
<P>
   In his address, the president argued passionately that the
Senate bill falls short in several areas: All Americans are not
covered under the Senate plan, he said. Access to specialists is
not guaranteed. Nor is emergency room care or access to clinical
trials that allow at-risk patients access to new treatments for
cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version excludes 135 million Americans from coverage,
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when you hear people say, `Well, I support a patients' bill
of rights,' the operative word in that sentence is `a' as opposed
to `the,' '' the president said. ``The difference in the one-letter
word and the three-letter word is 135 million of your fellow
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what this whole debate's about.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ashcroft and business interests pointed to several
shortcomings in the bill Clinton backs. The first is the emphasis
the House bill would place on lawsuits as a way of settling medical
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The House version ``has a provision that really moves people
into the courts, into lawsuits,'' Ashcroft said during a visit to
Kansas City Wednesday. ``I think when you're sick, you need
treatment. One of the things about this bill that we passed in the
Senate is we get people to treatment quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the drawbacks that Clinton cited, an aide to
Ashcroft said only that the plan the senator backs is stronger in
several respects than a law the Missouri General Assembly passed in
1997. Clinton lauded that law Thursday as a model for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ashcroft said the patients' rights bill he backs
calls for medical-care disputes to be resolved within 14 days.
Missouri law requires that such disputes be remedied within 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Sullivan, spokeswoman for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
also disagreed with Clinton. She said employers may drop
health-care plans as a fringe benefit because of the unlimited
liability involved in the bill Clinton backs. Businesses could be
at risk if they provide their workers with faulty coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers just simply cannot afford to take on that type of
risk with the trial lawyers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, companies may wind up giving workers lump-sum cash
payments so that they can buy their own coverage, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Carnahan said passage of Missouri's bill of rights
has not resulted in the litigation nightmare that Republicans had
forecast. Democrats, he suggested, have credibility on the issue
because of the success of the state's law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to report to you that the critics were dead wrong,''
he said to applause. ``We know there are many advantages to living
in the Show-Me State, and health-care protection is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton went out of his way to avoid mentioning Ashcroft by
name. The closest he came to a direct knock on the senator was when
he pointed out that during his years as governor of Arkansas he
served with four Missouri governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Mel Carnahan is clearly one of the very best governors I
ever served with,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Clinton only served at the same time with three
Missouri chief executives: Joseph P. Teasdale, Kit Bond and
Ashcroft. Carnahan was elected in 1992, the same year Clinton was
elected president. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
