<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS RISES ABOVE HYPE, SUSPICIONS TO REACH WIMBLEDON FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When it was over Thursday afternoon outside of London,
Venus Williams put her arm around her little sister and walked her
off Centre Court.
</P>
<P>
   Serena, the reigning U.S. Open champion, had just lost to Venus
in the semifinals of Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the all-Williams matchup, while emotional for the
young women, will allow Venus her second chance at a first Grand
Slam title. She will play fellow Californian Lindsay Davenport in
the final Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always the big sister. I always take care of Serena. She
does what I do, but I'm still the big sister,'' Venus said after
the highest matchup of sisters in a Grand Slam event since the
inaugural Wimbledon in 1884.
</P>
<P>
   But for the uneasiness of their sibling showdown, there they had
been, fulfilling the prophesy, becoming unavoidable opponents.
</P>
<P>
   They were two of the last four players in the biggest
championship in tennis. Considering the curve they're on, soon
perhaps they will more consistently be the final two, each the
other's best friend, fiercest protector, supportive critic and
challenging rival.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, in the postmatch interviews, which were piped from the
All England Tennis Club via the Internet for worldwide access,
mostly what everyone wanted to know was whether the match had been
fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Did the father of these two top-ranked tennis professionals
ordain which one would win?
</P>
<P>
   Venus and Serena, too savvy to be caught in this latest round of
tactics, knew how to deal with the insinuation that Venus' win was
a conspiracy, as if it were Venus' turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I'm aware of,'' Venus said, cagily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't answer that question,'' Serena said.
</P>
<P>
   At every phase since their emergence onto the tennis circuit, at
each stage of their development, the Williams sisters have dealt
with the inquiries, the quizzical attempts to define them, their
father, their family and their place in this game.
</P>
<P>
   From a purely athletic point of view, experiments like the one
Richard Williams has performed are not completely uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Marinovich's father notoriously groomed his son to be an
NFL quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods' father stuck a driver in his son's hand when the
kid was 6 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. learned much of what he knows about life inside
major league clubhouses.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, however, the experiment Richard Williams
undertook with his two daughters warrants a little bit more awe.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Williams clan has attracted more than its share
of curiosity, but perhaps it is time to pair that with a great deal
more appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Everything Richard Williams predicted has come true.
</P>
<P>
   His daughters have accomplished just about everything he said
they would, starting from the moment Venus, now 20, walked onto a
court in Oakland six years ago and made her professional tennis
debut.
</P>
<P>
   At first, her game powerful and raw, Venus was sometimes
dismissed for her failure to break down points and her uneven shot
selection.
</P>
<P>
   But as people kept talking about the beads Venus and her sister
used to wear in their hair, the two prodigies were busy upgrading
their shot selection, learning to focus their concentration on what
works on grass and what doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Venus, despite injuries this year that have kept her to just
four tournaments, seems to have risen up over the speed bump of
last year's U.S. Open loss to Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   By beating Hingis in the Wimbledon quarterfinals, Venus
announced her comeback. She has shown there is still upside to her
game and championship aspirations, while Hingis, once seen as the
successor to the reign of Chris Evert, Monica Seles and Steffi
Graf, may have peaked.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Venus was asked what is different about her from 1997,
when she last played in a Grand Slam final at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't even full-time on the tour then. I didn't understand
some things. I didn't know how to break down certain points,'' she
said. ``These are totally different circumstances. It's extremely
different now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Venus first, and later Serena, handled the pressure of
rising to the top of their game by circumnavigating much of the
hype and pressure. That has not always been easy, since their
talk-the-talk mode of self-confidence has served to increase the
hype and suspicion about them.
</P>
<P>
   By race and sociology and by the economics of their start back
in their native Compton, these young women are outsiders to tennis.
But these outsiders have now become fixtures at the top of women's
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   And watching them accomplish this has been fascinating,
especially in the white-washed world of the professional tennis
tour.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is Venus Williams' turn to win a Grand Slam, but not
because her father predicted that one day she would. It is her time
because she has earned this chance.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
