<SLUG> BC-OVITZ-CANAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVITZ CROSSES OCEAN IN GLOBAL FILM ALLIANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Gregory J. Wilcox 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles _ Hollywood power broker Michael Ovitz's filmmaking
endeavors received a boost when his Artists Production Group formed
a joint venture with a European company to produce as many as 15
films whose total budgets could top $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with StudioCanal, the European studio operation of
Canal Plus, calls for the films with global appeal to be made over
the next three years. The average budget could top $50 million,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the first collaborations between a major European
studio and a domestic production company.
</P>
<P>
   The new enterprise will be run on both creative and strategic
fronts by a management team consisting equally of executives from
APG and StudioCanal. Ovitz, the former Walt Disney Co. president
and once the entertainment industry's most powerful agent, will be
its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty excited considering we've been in business for 18
months,'' Ovitz said Thursday on the partnering with StudioCanal.
``They are really savvy and they really get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Five projects are in development with production a year to 18
months away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, what we've done is create a ministudio with very
little overhead and a big development fund,'' Ovitz noted.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 18 months Ovitz burst back onto the Hollywood scene
in grand fashion with companies focused on artist management, the
Internet, episodic television and film production. APG was founded
by Ovitz, Rick Yorn, Julie Silverman-Yorn and Cathy Schulman.
</P>
<P>
   The new deal combines StudioCanal's global reach and the
multitiered pan-European distribution network with APG's A-list
talent and production expertise. StudioCanal produces, finances and
distributes feature films and television programs and is modeled
after other major Hollywood studios.
</P>
<P>
   Clients signed on with Ovitz's Artists Management Group include
Cameron Diaz, Robin Williams, Leonardo Di Caprio and authors Tom
Clancy, James Ellroy and Michael Crichton.
</P>
<P>
   His clients will get first crack at projects, but there will be
work for the rest of Hollywood, too, Ovitz said. And he is not
concerned about any perception of a conflict of interest from
representing talent and making movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the opportunity to make five more pictures a year and
there is nothing wrong with that. It's very positive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Garzilli, co-president of Beverly Hills-based Canal Plus
US, considers the deal with Ovitz a coup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is a tremendous asset to any type of project like this.
Because of his contacts and experience in the industry, this is a
terrific relationship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The French film company likewise holds American products in high
regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. films travel very well. They are clearly an important
ingredient in setting up your studio. U.S. films clearly have a
global market,'' Garzilli said.
</P>
<P>
   Canal Plus is 50 percent owned by Vivendi, the big French
conglomerate that snapped up Seagram Co. Ltd. to take control of
Universal's entertainment operations. It renamed the company
Vivendi Universal and installed Canal Plus chief Pierre Lescure as
its head.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Ed Hatch at SG Cowen Securities Inc. in New York said
the deal with Ovitz follows what is now a trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film industry is becoming increasingly global due to the
great upgrade in the exhibition business overseas, which has made
the international market in total even more important than the
domestic market now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz agrees, noting that what's hot in Los Angeles is likewise
hot in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Films produced by the new joint venture will capitalize on it,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really are looking to make pictures that appeal to a
worldwide audience,'' Ovitz said. ``Kids are kids. It's really
interesting. If you walk through Paris, aside from their different
culture, my teen-agers could fit right in and vice versa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 0005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5160 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-COURT-FAMILIES-1STLD-     07-07 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-FAMILIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE NOT ALWAYS BLIND WHEN KIN ARE PRESENT (OR ABSENT) IN
COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 18th graf to clarify) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The families fill the courtrooms and hallways of this
city's courthouses each day, a stream of human traffic driven by
surging arrest rates and crowded court calendars.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases they arrive in force: parents, siblings and
children determined to show support for a loved one with their
sheer numbers. But in most cases they are women who arrive alone or
with young children they cannot leave at home: a solitary mother,
wife or girlfriend intent on supporting a scorned defendant, or
serving as a poignant reminder of a murder victim.
</P>
<P>
   They are the families of the accused and the victims, and they
are all in some form of mourning. They often display remarkable
grace and loyalty, and say their experiences in the grim
courthouses can be cathartic.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of families are those that have long been seen in the
criminal courts _ the poor. But defense lawyers say that they have
seen a different type of family arrive in recent years as the
city's quality-of-life crackdown continues. More working-class
families who have never before had brushes with the law arrive in
shock after a loved one is arrested and jailed overnight for a
minor offense, like driving with a suspended license.
</P>
<P>
   But despite high divorce rates and the far-flung nature of
modern families, one longstanding legal truism endures: the concept
of family remains a potent weapon in court. The presence of family
members often has an impact, great or small, on the outcome of the
trial or arraignment they have come to see.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with judges, jurors, prosecutors and defense lawyers
suggest that the presence of these families _ some tattered, some
durably faithful _ can be a critical factor in the balance of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   A frantic wife or a grieving mother staring intently at a judge
or jury can humanize a defendant or a murder victim, they said. And
the lack of any family members in the audience _ a situation that
roughly half of defendants face _ can sully the accused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for juries,'' said Acting Justice John P.
Walsh of State Supreme Court, a former police inspector who
supervises the city's arraignment courts. ``It shows that a
defendant's family hasn't abandoned them. Psychologically for
jurors, if it's a close case, it will have an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Judges said that jurors sometimes do not realize the subtle
emotional impact families have on them by sitting in a courtroom.
Jurors also may disregard instructions to pay no attention to the
audience, the judges said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jurors in the first trial of Andrew Goldstein, a schizophrenic
man convicted in March of murdering Kendra Webdale by pushing her
in front of a subway, were instructed to draw no inference from the
failure of Goldstein's family to testify in his defense or to
attend his trial.
</P>
<P>
   But several jurors said they found the absence of Goldstein's
family suspicious. And after Goldstein's first trial ended in a
hung jury last November, jurors apologized to members of Webdale's
family and hugged them in front of the courthouse. Jurors said they
owed it to the Webdale family to have reached a verdict. They said
they had noticed the victim's relatives sitting resolutely in the
courtroom each day.
</P>
<P>
   But the human tales that play out in the courtrooms and the
crowded, often loud, sometimes menacing hallways of the courthouses
typically do not receive much notice. The families come intent on
doing the right thing and on perhaps gaining an edge in the pending
legal fight, but anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   David Kapner, a defense lawyer who supervises arraignments for
the Legal Aid Society in Manhattan, said the city's quality-of-life
crackdown had brought a different type of family to the city's
criminal courthouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality-of-life arrests suck up a lot of people who have
never been in trouble before, and those are the people who are more
likely to have their families show up in court,'' he said. ``There
are more teen-agers for drinking beer, or immigrants for
peddling.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One morning last month in the Manhattan Criminal Courts Building
was typical of a justice system in which a thousand people a day
are arrested and thousands of cases are handled every week.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Cabrera, 49, wept as she, her husband, her two daughters,
her daughter-in-law and her nephew walked into the lobby
desperately searching for her son, who had been arrested by
immigration officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would get run over by a bus or a train if that would make
them let him go,'' said Cabrera, who sobbed and said she was afraid
her son would be deported.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, Blanca Santiago, 18, sat on the floor waiting
with her father-in-law for her husband to be released. The husband
had been arrested and accused of selling flowers without a permit.
A few feet away, a Chinese man tried to comfort his two children as
he and his sister-in-law tried to find out when his wife would be
released after being arrested on a charge of buying untaxed
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Cabrera and Santiago were hardly alone in their wait for the
release of husbands, boyfriends and sons who had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Anguished conversations on the bank of pay phones that line the
lobby wall are common. Family members break the news that someone
has been arrested, try to hire a lawyer or struggle to raise bail
money.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most of the women are financially dependent on the men, defense
lawyers said. Mothers who say they have no place to leave their
children take them to the courthouse. At night, strollers and
crying infants are common sights and sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `I'm looking for my baby's father,''' said Sgt.
Stephen Crisafulli, a court officer who supervises the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mothers who struggle to keep the children quiet in courtrooms
often retreat to the hallways. There, the children play impromptu
games, sitting on the floor or running in circles and shrieking as
their mothers wait.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Wednesday night, Angela Medina, 18, gave her
one-month-old son a bottle as she sat in the lobby waiting for her
sister's boyfriend to be released. ``I want to support him and my
sister,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other cases sometimes draw immigrant families who arrive in
force. During one night court shift, 12 relatives of a woman from
Senegal who was arrested in a domestic dispute arrived at 1 a.m. to
find her. The group included her 2-month-old niece.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents and spouses accept defendants' claims that they
were victims of false arrests by officers overzealously enforcing
the city's quality-of-life crackdown. But others fly into a rage at
their loved one.
</P>
<P>
   The most heated confrontation in the Manhattan Criminal Courts
Building in the last several years was between a father and son,
Crisafulli said. The father, who had spent time in prison, flew
into a rage after his own son was arrested. ```How could you do
this! I work every day for you!'' the father thundered as court
officers restrained him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really ripping the boy to keep him from going down the
same path,'' the sergeant said. ``It was fear and frustration, not
anger.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Judges said that in less serious cases, defendants' ties to
their families are factors in how much bail they set or whether
they offer plea bargains involving probation or drug rehabilitation
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's got a mother, brother, sister and wife sitting in the
audience, it shows he has a support system,'' Walsh said. ``That
support system is important for him to take his medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyers said that the presence of families can also
complicate matters. Some young defendants will refuse to plead
guilty in front of their mothers, for example, if they have sworn
to their parents they did not do the crimes. Other family members
give terrible legal advice, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   While the building's ground floor is filled with families
usually suffering smaller heartaches, its upper floors are lined
with families enduring far larger ones. There, defendants face more
serious felony charges, most involving drugs, that can result in
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Racial and class tensions can also hover over the courtrooms.
Poor families frequently complain that their loved ones receive
longer sentences because they cannot afford ``a real lawyer,'' and
that fury finds expression in the court buildings. After a drug
addict who killed a man with his car while on PCP was sentenced to
15 years in prison last month, one of his relatives shouted ``let
it be a Mercedes-Benz, and you'll walk away no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many family members seem to fall into stereotypical roles in the
courthouse, judges and lawyers said. Mothers generally attend
trials religiously and are better able to express their emotions,
they said. Fathers, by contrast, appear intermittently and seem to
struggle with their anger.
</P>
<P>
   Many relatives on the building's upper floors are hoping to
influence judges or to simply catch a glimpse of a jailed defendant
during a brief court appearance.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the mother, two aunts, girlfriend and three cousins
of Victor Rhymer, 19, waited hours for him to be sentenced for
robbing a man of his beeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a strain to come here because we love him,'' his aunt
Claudette said.
</P>
<P>
   Courthouse veterans said that explaining the continuing power of
families in the court system is simple. Jurors and judges, like all
people, may groan about their own nagging mothers, distant fathers
and crazy siblings. But blood is still expected to bind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is that if you're alone in this world,
it's much harder to rehabilitate yourself,'' said David Kapner, a
defense lawyer with the Legal Aid Society. ``But if you have some
people in your life, you have a better chance of pulling yourself
together. Intuitively, judges and juries understand that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers and judges say one of the most depressing sights
in court is the roughly 50 percent of defendants who arrive alone,
with no family members. Many are long-term drug abusers whose
addictions have shattered their ties to their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are acquitted and they walk out of the courtroom
and there is no one there,'' said David Stern, a Manhattan defense
lawyer. ``Some are convicted and no one sheds a tear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
