<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS OWNER TAKES A TURN IN WRONG DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A funny thing happened on the way to Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of this bus _ an otherwise judicious fellow named
Hicks _ took a left turn and pointed the Rangers back toward
Oakland, Anaheim and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to a man who vacations in Alaska, this is nothing. In
Tom Hicks' world, a man can fish in any time zone.
</P>
<P>
   But gee whiz, Tom. The kids have homework. We newspapers have
deadlines. If the Rangers were ever to clinch a pennant in, say,
the Pacific Northwest, it would be grand if someone other than
Conan O'Brien and the late shift at Denny's were awake to see it.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? The Rangers were in the driver's seat, motoring
blithely toward realignment. Baseball commissioner Bud Selig was
quoted as saying that he owed the franchise one _ imagine that _ in
the form of a promise he once made to then-owner George W. Bush,
who at the time was also doing business as The First Son.
</P>
<P>
   Several oblique realignment proposals later, it appeared that
the worst the Rangers could end up is being co-Alpha dog in a
six-team American League Central. Annual visitation rights to
Houston were included.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad. The inequities of possibly being in baseball's only
six-team division were duly noted. We can do the math.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, we hear owner Hicks saying to hold everything.
Hicks has been saying that he likes the ``tradition'' of his guys
playing the Oaklands, the Anaheims and the Seattles. For
tradition's sake, he wants the Rangers to remain in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. Randy Johnson. Mark McGwire. Tony La Russa.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, what do you mean they're gone?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they're gone. Some traditions come and go _ like
ballparks. Rangers fans may have grown attached to seeing their
heroes battle Junior and McGwire. But how many hearts soar now when
John Halama and Olmedo Saenz come to town?
</P>
<P>
   Hicks told our paper's T.R. Sullivan the other day, ``... our
fans would like to see us play Seattle, Oakland and the Angels
rather than the Twins and the Royals.''
</P>
<P>
   They would? Says who?
</P>
<P>
   Those alleged blood-rival Athletics, young and brimming with
talent, attracted only 28,964 to The Ballpark for the series closer
on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, lest the owner forget, were once division mates of
the same Twins and Royals that Hicks wants to shield the fans from.
Not all that long ago, those same two teams were the class of the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   In today's game, fans fill seats either to watch superstars play
or to revel in the excitement of a game of importance. If it's late
August or September and the game is important, let me suggest that
it doesn't matter whether the opponent is named the Angels or the
Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the aforementioned fan must first be awake. Which
brings us back to the original issue.
</P>
<P>
   With the planned unbalanced schedule, the Rangers would be
playing even more road games starting at 9 p.m. or later. Yes, the
true fans will watch. But in the long run, the fan base will suffer
because your young audience will be asleep.
</P>
<P>
   It seems elementary _ teams should try to play as many games as
possible in the same time zone where their fans live.
</P>
<P>
   Recent history might be telling owner Hicks that the Rangers can
handle this AL West. Three division titles in four years speak for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   So who's to fear in the AL Central? Don't say the Cleveland
Indians. They're almost 10 games back.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there don't appear to be any more big spenders in the
Central division than in the West. So what's Hicks' big fear?
</P>
<P>
   If his most important objective is playing interleague games
against the Astros every year, someone needs to ask why. Mitch
Meluskey is fine, but I think I'd rather see Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   A Rangers-Astros rivalry would attract initial curiosity, but it
will never be like the Mets-Yankees or Cubs-White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if that's the trade-off _ the Rangers staying in the AL
West, just for the privilege of playing the Astros each year _ that
doesn't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Nor good business sense, at any hour of the night.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
