<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>

(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.2000
Fort Worth Star-Telegram
Cordero returns home
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rangers are expected to be without pitcher Francisco Cordero
during their three games with the San Diego Padres this weekend.
Cordero, who has been used in middle relief for most of the season,
has returned to his home in the Dominican Republic to attend his
grandmother's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin said the Rangers won't make a move,
leaving manager Johnny Oates with a five-man bullpen for the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem, but there's nothing we can do about it,''
Melvin said. ``We could option him out, but we wouldn't have him
for the first three games after the All-Star break.''
</P>
<P>
   If a player is optioned to the minors, he must stay for 10 days.
 &QL; 
Torre considered Alicea, Wetteland
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre of the New York Yankees said he considered
both Rangers second baseman Luis Alicea and reliever John Wetteland
for the American League All-Star team. But Torre said the
overwhelming offensive numbers put up by first basemen and
outfielders made it difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult, especially with Luis,'' Torre said
yesterday. ``I know this would have been his first All-Star Game.
But the glut of first basemen and outfielders really tied my hands.
I did consider John and Luis, but I just decided to go in a
different direction. Last year, I came close to picking \RChicago
second baseman\S Ray Durham, but at the last minute I did something
else. This year, I didn't want to omit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez will be the Rangers' only All-Star
representative for the game, scheduled Tuesday in Atlanta.
Rodriguez is participating for the ninth consecutive year and is
starting for the eighth consecutive year.  &QL; 
Padres without Gwynn
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, with the resumption of interleague play, open a
three-game series tonight against the San Diego Padres, who are
without future Hall of Fame outfielder Tony Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-time batting champion underwent arthroscopic surgery
on his left knee last week and is expected to be sidelined for two
to three weeks. Gwynn, who has 3,108 hits in his career, was
hitting .323.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and the Padres are 5-5 against each other since
interleague play began. The Rangers have won four of five from the
Padres at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, after yesterday's loss to Los Angeles, have lost 18
of their past 27 and are 27-38 after a 10-9 start. The Padres went
into yesterday's game having committed 78 errors, the most in the
major leagues.  &QL; 
Zimmerman's numbers
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zimmerman has a 6.29 earned-run average, the third highest
relief ERA in the American League. His biggest problem has been
having yielded seven home runs in 34 innings. But in some other
areas, Zimmerman ranks in the top 10 among American League
relievers:
</P>
<P>
   Opponents are hitting .137 (7-for-51) off Zimmerman with runners
in scoring position. That's seventh lowest in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman has allowed only 20 percent (7-for-35) of inherited
runners to score. That's the ninth-lowest ratio in the league.
</P>
<P>
   He has held first batters to a .188 average (6-for-32), the 10th
lowest in the league.  &QL; 
Adjusting for Davis
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have adjusted their farm system with an eye toward
Doug Davis being with the team after the All-Star break by
promoting three top pitching prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure what we're going to do with Davis after the
All-Star break,'' Doug Melvin said. ``This is just a sign we need
pitching at Triple A and Double A.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers replaced Davis on the Triple-A Oklahoma roster by
promoting pitcher Jose Martinez, who was 5-6 with a 3.14 ERA at
Double-A Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed pitcher Andy Pratt, who was 7-4 with a 2.72 ERA at
Class-A Charlotte, was promoted to Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed pitcher Matt Kosderka was promoted to] Charlotte
from Class-A Savannah, where he was 5-4 with a 2.57 ERA.  &QL; 
Time change
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers game at Seattle on Saturday, July 22, has been
changed from 8:05 p.m. to 3:10 p.m. to accommodate Fox, which is
planning to include the game in its regional telecasts. The game
will be shown locally on KDFW/Channel 4 rather than Fox Sports Net.
 &QL; 
Hot hitters
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez has a nine-game hitting streak, equaling his
season high, accomplished twice previously. He is batting .378
(14-for-37) during the streak. He has reached base by hit or walk
in 17 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer, who is hitting .293, has a seven-game hitting
streak, with 12 hits in his past 31 at-bats. He also has at least
two hits in 14 of his past 17 games, hitting .403 in that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui has hit safely in 10 of his past 11 games, batting
.378 (17-45).
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lamb, after going 3-for-5 in Wednesday's game, is batting
.364 in his past 18 games. He has also reached base in nine of his
past 15 plate appearances.
nn
</P>
