r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX     07-07 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>

(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By JESSE SANCHEZ c.2000
Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ When Ruben Mateo gets out of his black sports
utility vehicle and inches toward The Ballpark in Arlington from a
nearby parking lot, he knows shagging fly balls won't be a part of
his daily routine. The major-league uniform he wore at the
beginning of the season has been replaced by a white T-shirt and
pair of black wind shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a broken right leg, the rookie who once patrolled
center field for the Rangers now hobbles on crutches to a
rehabilitation center in a suite above the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I thought about is that I would not be able to
play baseball again,'' said Mateo, who suffered a broken right
femur running to first base against Arizona on June 2. ``I feel bad
because I cannot play, but I got hurt trying my best at my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Mateo, 22, has someone close to him who can help
him through tough times. Rookie reliever Francisco Cordero, also
22, lives with Mateo and Ruben's mother, Ancelma Perez Coldero, in
a modest two-story home in Arlington. Cordero has known Mateo since
they were teen-agers playing on the same team, Escogida, in the
Dominican Republic. Cordero knows firsthand what his friend is
going through, having suffered a season-ending elbow injury in July
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it is hard for him to have to sit there and watch
someone else play your position,'' said Cordero, who came from
Detroit in the trade that sent Juan Gonzalez to the Tigers in
November. ``I care about him and I know this is very hard for him
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo said his mother's support and Cordero's friendship have
helped keep his spirits up since his injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Francisco is a good person, and I talk to him about a lot of
things,'' Mateo said. ``He keeps me from getting sad. He misses his
family, but we all do in the beginning. Seven months without family
is difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo said his mother ``does everything for us. I thank God she
is here with me at such difficult time. She tells me not to feel
bad. She is my support.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordero's mother, Martina, and 11 siblings live in Santa
Domingo. He wants to bring her to the United States next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very far away from my family and I miss my mother,'' said
Cordero, who lives with his mother when he goes back to the
Dominican Republic. ``My mom worked very hard for me to get me
where I am at now.
</P>
<P>
   ``She worked for 21 years as a housekeeper to give me what I
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Cordero's father, Diego, died of cancer. Diego Cordero
introduced Francisco to baseball as a toddler, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was big baseball fan, and he always took me to baseball
games,'' Cordero said. ``We used to go everywhere. It was hard for
me when he died, very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordero, who had planned to return home during the All-Star
break, left early yesterday to attend his grandmother's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero, as Mateo, is trying to fulfill large expectations
within the organization. He believes he can be the team's future
closer. In 39 innings, he's 1-1 with a 4.28 earned-run average, 27
strikeouts and 28 walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a closer full time,'' Cordero said. ``I think I
can close for the Rangers or any team.''
</P>
<P>
   What will keep both happy, they said, is solidifying their
future with the Rangers. General manager Doug Melvin said there's a
possibility Cordero can develop into a full-time closer with what
he calls a ``power arm and a good slider.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a few unknowns in Mateo's game because he has been
hurt so often, having been on the disabled list twice last year in
his first major-league season, and now must come back from a
serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping for 20 home runs and 65-70 RBIs this year from
Ruben, and it is unfortunate that he was injured,'' Melvin said.
``It was a big loss for us. Now, we have to wait until next season
to see if he performs at the big leagues for a full season.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Stauffer, site coordinator at HealthSouth Sports Medicine &AMP;
Rehabilitation Center, works with Mateo and said he should be able
to walk without crutches within the next two to three weeks. Mateo
will be required to continue two-hour, five-day-a-week
rehabilitation sessions until spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo said he'll continue to visit The Ballpark each weekday for
treatment, but tries to be home with his mother before the first
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to go to the ballpark and watch others play,'' he
said. ``I like to go there and play baseball. It still bothers me
to watch.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
