<HEADER>
A5167 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-T     07-07 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ While everybody awaits the blockbuster John
Wetteland trade, just remember the name Ed Vosberg.
</P>
<P>
   Vosberg, when last seen in these parts, was a capable but
obscure left-handed relief pitcher who served the Rangers well for
two-plus years. Too many people remember him more for his failed
ticket-scalping scheme than for being a valuable part of the 1996
bullpen that may have lacked a standout closer but still had plenty
of depth.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Marlins recognized Vosberg's value the following
year, when] they made their historic run to become the first
wild-card team to win a World Series. Needing a left-handed
reliever, the Marlins snatched Vosberg on Aug. 12, 1997, when the
Rangers had fallen out of the race and general manager Doug Melvin
was trying to get a head start on next year.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Melvin got Rick Helling in return, easily the best
trade he has made in six years as the Rangers' general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, Melvin is likely to consider few players
untouchable when it comes time in the next few weeks to start
getting ready for 2001 and the best trade may not be what he gets
for Wetteland or David Segui but for Dave Martinez or Chad Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, yes, the Rangers would need a designated hitter if
Segui were traded. But, right now, Melvin said Pedro Valdes and not
Ruben Sierra would be the likely player promoted from Triple-A
Oklahoma. Still, it wouldn't be surprising if the Rangers need
Sierra, their one-time superstar, who is making an impressive
comeback with the Redhawks.
</P>
<P>
   That said, it seems inexorable that changes are coming to the
Rangers in the next few weeks, even after the three-game sweep of
the Athletics. As much as Melvin and owner Tom Hicks keep saying
the team is not out of contention, it's no longer a question
whether the Rangers can compete].
</P>
<P>
   A wild-card playoff spot holds little lure for Hicks, who was
once the proud owner of Lord Stanley's tankard and lustily dreams
of Bud Selig handing over a World Series trophy. Hicks knows that
even if the Rangers squeak through to win the wild card or the
American League West, the playoffs are likely going to result in
the same frustration experienced in all three of the Rangers'
playoff appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, it has to be really driving Hicks nuts that
his team has gone south the same year in which the Yankees have
done so as well. George Steinbrenner might throw some more money at
some of his pitching problems, but right now his team looks
eminently beatable.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks isn't interested in throwing more money at problems that
can't be fixed, the way Peter Angelos did in Baltimore. Angelos
went blindly searching for a World Series championship with a bunch
of thirtysomething relics and ended up driving his franchise in the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks and Melvin know the Rangers are a wild-card team at best.
Even so, that's a fantasy not even worth pursuing, not when there
are glaring needs that must be met if this team ever hopes to win
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the Rangers are going to need another big bat. This
lineup drops off too quickly after Segui, and no team is going to
go far in the American League with Martinez and Curtis _ two nice
role players _ platooning in what should be the power-laden sixth
spot. Whatever happened to Mickey Tettleton? Dean Palmer? Todd
Zeile?
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will also have to take a hard look at their bullpen,
especially with Wetteland due to become a free agent, and another
starting pitcher will likely be needed if they don't hit the
complete trifecta on Doug Davis, Ryan Glynn and Matt Perisho.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin is getting ready to talk. He has Hicks' blessing. It
won't be a complete makeover. The idea is to put together a World
Series contender. Another Vosberg-for-Helling deal would be a
start.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
