<HEADER>
A5169 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-JOCKEYS-AUTOGRAPH     07-07 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-JOCKEYS-AUTOGRAPHS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ It's true. People will do almost anything
for an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   It's no different when the jockeys walk through the winner's
circle after a race at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be 100 kids here on some days, and they can get
desperate,'' said Chuck Tynan, the assistant clerk of scales at
Lone Star who assists jockeys with autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day, a grown man comes out here with a sign made,''
Tynan said. ``The sign read something like `Today is my daughter's
birthday, and she's sick and couldn't come out to the track.'
People use all sorts of tricks. And that guy, we went ahead and
gave him one.''
</P>
<P>
   What they gave him is different from any sports venue where
autographs are signed. Baseball players sign baseballs or bubble
gum cards. Golfers sign visors.
</P>
<P>
   But at the racetrack, jockeys sign goggles.
</P>
<P>
   Goggles? Clear-plastic goggles are used by a jockey every time
he rides a horse. He has to have them to protect his eyes from wind
generated when a horse is running 30 mph and faster and also from
the sand that gets kicked back when a jockey is behind other
horses.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's probably a better idea to give away goggles to a
youngster than to give away a whip.
</P>
<P>
   While autograph seekers collect signatures before baseball
games, they line up at Lone Star after each race. After the jockey
has his picture taken on the winning horse, he dismounts and walks
over to ``weigh out'' to ensure for the racing stewards that his
weight plus the weight added to his saddle add up to the amount he
was assigned to carry.
</P>
<P>
   After he weighs out, Tynan gives the jockey a clean pair of
goggles to sign. It can be a challenge to write on a slick plastic
surface that's no more than 8 inches long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy,'' jockey Roman Chapa said. ``You don't have
your whole arm to sit somewhere. It's not perfect, but it'll do for
these kids. They appreciate anything you can do for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the goggles are signed, they can be delivered in a number
of ways. Some jockeys give them to youngsters who are with a group
that's allowed to enter the winner's circle after a race. Some
jockeys throw them into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But that makes people scamper for them like a foul ball. Fingers
can get stepped on. Elbows scraped.
</P>
<P>
   So most jockeys walk along the railing next to the winner's
circle and find someone to hand them to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants them,'' Chapa said. ``But I like handing them
to the little girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a jockey gives his own goggles away. But a more
custom-fit pair of goggles _ some of them are tinted for protection
from the sun _ can cost $6.
</P>
<P>
   So Lone Star provides a generic pair of goggles for jockeys to
sign and give away. Steve Sexton, general manager at the track,
said Lone Star can purchase them for between $3 and $4. Sexton
estimates the track spends at least $4,000 a year on goggles. He
said the track writes it off as a marketing expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always looking for things where we can reach and touch
the public with,'' Sexton said. ``People remember things when they
were growing up as a kid. So hopefully this creates a fan for
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fact that the signatures come on a piece of equipment
that can't be found at a major sporting event, Sexton said there
are other things about the autograph session conducted between
races that make it unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball players or other pro athletes never sign an autograph
in the middle of the game,'' Sexton said. ``And here you're always
getting the winner.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
