<HEADER>
A5172 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-JOCKEYS-TEX     07-07 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-JOCKEYS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ On the day in December when Laffit Pincay
Jr. broke Bill Shoemaker's world record for all-time number of
victories as a jockey, European rider Cash Asmussen was in Houston
for the Texas Champions Day racing card at Sam Houston Race Park.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Asmussen if he had watched satellite dish network
TVG and its live coverage, when cameras were isolated on Pincay's
rides leading up to the record-breaking race.
</P>
<P>
   It was powerful, insightful coverage because it showed how adept
Pincay was at getting a horse out of the starting gate, gathering
the horse's balance and immediately scanning the field in the first
moments of a race. It gave viewers an idea of what must go through
Pincay's mind as he starts judging if the race is setting up as he
thought it would before the race, when he looked at the past
performances of his horse respective to the rest of the field.
</P>
<P>
   It gave you an idea that the guy breaking the record, this guy
who everyone thought was washed up two or three years ago, was
still pretty darn good and deserving of ``Shoe's'' record. He's
still a top jockey, not a guy who has hung around long enough to
break a record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time someone's about to break a record,'' Asmussen said,
``that person gets more attention, and you can get a chance to see
how talented that person is and why he's breaking that record in
the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't always require setting a record to instruct us
about someone's talent. Sometimes talent becomes apparent when
other competitors leave the scene.
</P>
<P>
   You see the talent, and it becomes apparent: What were we
thinking about when we were overlooking these guys a few weeks ago?
</P>
<P>
   That's what has been happening the past two weeks at Lone Star
Park at Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   When leading jockey Donnie Meche had to take off mounts because
of his injured shoulder, and when a handful of jockeys moved to
Louisiana Downs when that track opened two weeks ago, things looked
pretty bleak at Lone Star. This looked like a watered-down jockey
colony.
</P>
<P>
   But it has allowed us to see what we shouldn't have been
missing. Now, we can't help but see that Curt Bourque and Ronald
Ardoin really should be considered among the top jockeys in this
region.
</P>
<P>
   While Ardoin has been in that top-jock consideration for a
generation of horseplayers who made the trip east on Interstate 20
to Louisiana Downs, he has sort of suffered from the same thing
that afflicted Pincay in recent years. He has been shuffled to the
side to a degree, while a collection of younger riders have hit
this circuit.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who paid attention to a race last week when Ardoin
lost the lead on a horse named Yoyoyo, then regained it in deep
stretch and won, knows that Ardoin can still ride. Yoyoyo was like
a real yo-yo, and Ardoin was pulling the right string.
</P>
<P>
   He had the lead, then went back in second. Horses are usually
done at that point, but Ardoin sensed his horse wasn't responding
to the whip. So he put away the whip and flipped the reins
underneath Yoyoyo's cheek. That, his horse liked.
</P>
<P>
   Race over. Yoyoyo comes back and wins, and Ardoin brushes some
color to an otherwise mundane midweek racing program.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque hasn't quite enjoyed the same profile that Ardoin has
earned. But his rides in two of the three biggest stakes races at
Lone Star last week were as good as anyone will find.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he might have been on the best horses, though neither was
favored. But Bourque didn't get them beat. He put them in the
perfect position to win.
</P>
<P>
   He hugged the rail on Gran Mujer and was able to charge ahead on
the inside when the front-runners eased outside in the $100,000
Sundance Stakes. He had another ground-saving trip on Watch in the
$150,000 Walmac Lone Star Oaks and absolutely pushed and drove her
to win while world-class jockey Yutaka Take was wide and running
late on favored Islay Mist.
</P>
<P>
   There's no isolation camera at Lone Star, but your actions are
always isolated when you win. Ardoin and Bourque made the most of
their time in the spotlight.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
