<HEADER>
A5173 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-     07-07 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Call it the Sugar Ray Leonard Syndrome.
Coaches and athletes find that the ease of retirement is a poor
replacement for the adrenaline surge of competition. Soon after
they quit, they are lured back to the sports spotlight like moths
to the flame.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you remember Bill McCartney. Coached at Colorado. Took
over a woebegone program in 1982, coached the Buffaloes for 13
seasons, won a share of the national championship in 1990. After
the 1994 season, McCartney retired from coaching. And he's still
retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaching college football was intoxicating,'' McCartney said.
``I wanted to be a coach since I was 7 years old. But I'm no longer
under its lure. When you're part of \Rcoaching a team\S, it seems
like it's the most important thing. In stepping out of it, I don't
feel that way anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   A devout Christian, in 1990 McCartney formed Promise Keepers,
which describes itself as ``a Christ-centered ministry dedicated to
uniting men through vital relationships to become godly influences
in their world.'' PK will have one of its national meetings today
and tomorrow at Reunion Arena in Dallas. McCartney will address the
group tomorrow. His topic will be nobility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good word for our times,'' McCartney said. ``I
think it should be defined as superior moral character. It means to
be willing-hearted, it means to be generous. I think it's a message
men need to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   PK is a nonprofit organization that has been rich in
controversy. Critics assail the group's stance against abortion and
say that its position on gays is homophobic, that PK is a male
supremacist movement backed by radical right-wing religious groups.
McCartney says those criticisms are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Two Big 12 Conference coaches _ Colorado's Gary Barnett and
Oklahoma State's Bob Simmons _ were assistant coaches on
McCartney's staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know Bill McCartney, he has a singleness of purpose in
the things he does,'' Barnett said. ``It doesn't surprise me that
he could walk away from coaching football. He willed Colorado to a
national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett left McCartney's staff in 1992 to take over at
Northwestern before returning to Colorado last season. When
McCartney left Colorado, Simmons was passed over for the job, so he
left for Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill shared with me the vision of Promise Keepers, and he's
helped me in my walk with the Lord,'' Simmons said. ``I'm not
surprised he walked away from college football. He has done what he
wanted to do, to bring men into the Lord's presence. Bill is
totally at peace and contented.''
</P>
<P>
   McCartney occasionally visits Barnett's practices in Boulder. As
the years pass, McCartney's name drifts further off the coaching
radar screen. And that's fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 60 years old and I'm over the hill,'' McCartney said.
``It's not that I have any less love for football. There are 27
million children who go to bed every night without a father in
their house. I can help, I can be part of solving that problem.
That to me is what's really important.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly UCLA
officials are miffed that Missouri has pulled out of a
home-and-home football series with the Bruins. UCLA was scheduled
to play at Missouri in 2001, with the 2002 game in Los Angeles.
Missouri officials said the games were scheduled more than 10 years
ago, before the school wound up in the Big 12 Conference. UCLA,
which believes it could lose $500,000 in potential television
revenue, is considering legal action. And, UCLA officials say they
will consider not playing Missouri in any sport. The schools are
scheduled to play in the 2001 John Wooden Classic.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
