<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5176 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DNC-PROTEST-LADN     07-07 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-PROTEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTORS TARGETS WILL BE VARIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``n'' state news file.) 
 &HT;    By BILL HILLBURG  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Threatening to shut downtown Los Angeles
businesses, banks and corporate offices during the Democratic
National Convention, protest organizers said Thursday they will
flood the streets daily with as many as 50,000 demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters said they plan to target businesses -- not delegates
or the convention -- with daily rallies, marches and disruptions
between Aug. 14 and Aug. 17. And they said they refuse to be
confined to a designated protest area outside Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is not to shut down the convention,'' said organizer
Lisa Fithian of Echo Park, during a news conference in Washington,
D.C. ``We want to face and confront the institutions that oppress
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, organizers said, they will target the World Trade
Center, banks and corporate offices downtown with a ``March Against
the World Trade Organization and Corporate Globalization''
beginning at Pershing Square at 2 p.m. Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry if some people are inconvenienced, but the issues
we are raising inconvenience people around the world every day of
their lives,'' Fithian said.
</P>
<P>
   Business and building owners said they are contemplating whether
to close during the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned for our businesses, we're concerned for the
safety of our employees, we are concerned for the safety of
peaceable protesters,'' said Hilary Norton Orozco, director of
legislative affairs for the Central City Association, which
represents downtown businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to board up, we want to be open for business and
trust people when they say they are going to act peaceably,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wells Fargo Bank skyscraper, spokeswoman Mary Trigg said
the bank has been involved with security planning for the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working with the LAPD and other security people with
the convention to make sure that our property in any of the
affected areas, our employees and our customers and clients are all
going to be fine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police said they have 2,000 officers ready to
aggressively protect businesses, property and lives with a much
stronger show of force than displayed during the Lakers
championship riots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If individuals are unlawful and intent on being arrested, we
have the plans and resources to accommodate them -- all of them,''
said Cmdr. David Kalish, the department's top spokesman. ``It is an
important issue to the Police Department and every effort will be
made to protect individuals and their businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The LAPD has canceled all vacations, extended shifts and made
arrangements to call in the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department
and 42 other police agencies from throughout the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers said they expect 50,000 protesters
representing more than 100 groups -- and myriad causes -- to
descend on Los Angeles. The organizers said they plan similar
actions in Philadelphia from July 31 to Aug. 3, during the
Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   For Los Angeles, protesters said they hope to cause widespread
traffic tie-ups downtown, cutting off access for workers, employers
and merchants.
</P>
<P>
   The April protests in Washington against the World Trade
Organization and World Bank spanned four days and eventually led
police to seal off 20 square blocks of the downtown area. While
largely peaceful, the protesters staged hit-and-run marches and
rallies at a number of sites, forcing police to deploy their forces
over a wide area.
</P>
<P>
   They closed dozens of major streets and several subway stations.
Many offices and retail stores in the affected area lost business
or elected to close during the protests.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, two planned events include a 5 p.m. ``March for
our Lives'' from downtown to Staples Center on Aug. 14, and a
candlelight vigil outside the center the evening of Aug. 17, when
Vice President Al Gore is scheduled to make his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   Fithian said the protesters -- including many who participated
in December's violent demonstrations in Seattle against the World
Trade Organization and an April WTO protest in Washington, she said
-- are also planning an Aug. 15 march and rally in the Garment
District to urge better working conditions and to urge total
amnesty for all undocumented aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators would ``use creative ways'' to evade police lines
and other restrictions, Fithian said, declining to provide more
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our country and these are our streets,'' Fithian said.
``We're going to get our message out and rally support for our
issues with or without permits.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizers said they would go beyond the sanctioned protest
area to take their messages to the city's streets at will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The protest pen is like a prison and none of us intend to go
there,''said Margaret Prescod of Los Angeles, one of the lead
organizers of four days of demonstrations being billed as ``The
Democratic Intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said their protests would be peaceful. ``The only
violence we're worried about is police violence,'' Prescod said.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters represent an array of causes and concerns,
including gay and lesbian rights, racism, universal health care
coverage, improved services and benefits for welfare recipients,
assistance for the homeless, globalization of the economy,
abolition of the death penalty, immigrant rights, campaign finance
reform and disbandment of the nation's military.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writers Lisa Van Proyen and Alexa Haussler contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
