<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5181 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ARIZONA-REPUBLIC &LR;      07-07 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA-REPUBLIC </SLUG>
  
BC-INITIATIVES-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    INITIATIVE HARVEST GROWS IN ARIZONA(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ROBBIE SHERWOOD(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- Jim Pederson called it a ``great day for Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Others called it a great day for Pederson.
</P>
<P>
   Pederson almost single-handedly financed an initiative drive to
change the way Arizona draws its legislative districts, and he
stood triumphantly in front of a wall of boxes carrying 250,000
petition signatures to place the issue on the Nov.7 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Arizona politics, 2000-style, where deep-pocketed
individuals such as Pederson, grass-roots groups that have been
ignored by the state Legislature and legislators themselves have
turned over the responsibility to voters via the initiative
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have certainly put a lot of money into this, but that's
only part of the issue,'' said Pederson, a developer from Casa
Grande and chairman of the Citizens Independent Redistricting
Commission. ``It was something I could do. I've lived in the state
my whole life, and I don't like the direction our representative
democracy is moving. I thought that this one issue probably meant
more to the state of Arizona, to our kids, than any other.''
</P>
<P>
   Backers of three other citizens initiatives dropped off hundreds
of thousands of petition signatures before Thursday's deadline,
hoping to join one of the most crowded ballots in state history.
</P>
<P>
   The general election ballot already lists 10 questions put on by
lawmakers and citizens groups. Three others await verification of
signatures and four more were filed Thursday. Added Thursday were
initiatives on using the state's share of the $3.2billion
nationwide tobacco settlement for health care, ridding Arizona of
its state income tax, taking away the job of drawing legislative
voting districts from lawmakers and allowing phone giant USWest to
set its own rates in areas where it has no competition.
</P>
<P>
   If those four make it, along with all the others, the ballot
will have 17 questions, two short of an all-time high of 19 reached
in both 1980 and 1950.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the ballot, an initiative to change state law
requires 101,762 valid signatures. An initiative to amend the state
Constitution needs 152,643. Initiative backers must deliver far
more than the minimum to have any chance at the ballot, state
Elections Director Jessica Funkhouser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a higher and higher percentage of invalid
signatures because more and more drives are using paid petition
circulators,'' Funkhouser said.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, a ``buffer zone'' of 25percent above the minimum
was fine; but now, initiative backers must have up to 50percent
more than the minimum or face sweating out the state's monthlong
verification process.
</P>
<P>
   The Healthy Arizona II initiative delivered 172,000 signatures.
The initiative would use a share of Arizona's tobacco windfall to
expand the Arizona Health Care Cost Containment System to cover all
people under the federal poverty line of $16,500 for a family of
four. The initiative would triple the income cap to be eligible,
providing coverage for more than 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years is too long to wait for health insurance,'' said
Dr. Eve Shapiro, chairwoman of Healthy Arizona II. Healthy Arizona
passed overwhelmingly in 1996, but never was funded by the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   It faces stiff competition from a hospital-backed initiative to
spend tobacco money for insurance and other health programs for
40,000 working poor with children. The other initiative would
change the state Constitution to create a five-person, politically
neutral team to redraw Arizona's legislative districts. The job now
lies with incumbent legislators who routinely give one side or the
other such a lopsided advantage that opposing parties often don't
even field challengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will create more competitive districts where you have
strong candidates fighting each other over ideas,'' said Arizona
Attorney General Janet Napolitano, who supports the initiative.
``Will it work or be perfect? Who knows? But it's a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate president, Senate minority leader, speaker of the
House and House minority leader each would appoint one member of
the redistricting committee. The leaders then would choose the
fifth member, who could not be a member of either political party.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Robbie.Sherwood(a)Arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republic.com or (602) 444-8146.
</P>
