<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THEWEEK-NYT &LR;      07-07 0182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
K.D. LANG'S `INVINCIBLE SUMMER,' ROMANCE AND RETRO POP 
</HEADLINE>
 WEEK-NYT   By   JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While there are countless Christmas albums, it took K.D. Lang to
follow through on the old Beach Boys and build a theme album for
Warner Brothers around the opposite season: summertime. It's
justification enough for her to look again at ``the beauty of
desire,'' this time with blissful optimism. For Lang, summer is
time for heady new romance and glimmers of retro pop. Writing with
new collaborators, she harks back to 1960s styles without turning
archival.
</P>
<P>
   She's bubbly over a ``Summerfling,'' surrounded with vocal
harmonies and nonsense syllables; she's elated amid the
near-psychedelic funk of ``It's Happening With You'' and the
orchestrated folk-rock of ``Extraordinary Thing.'' She finds
contemplative rapture in ``Love's Great Ocean'' and ``When We
Collide.''
</P>
<P>
   Now and then she recognizes that things might not turn out, but
for the moment _ a moment she sustains through the album _ it's too
sunny for any second thoughts.  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-AMISTAD-NYT &LR;      07-07 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AMISTAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMISTAD REPLICA DEPARTS; PIER PROBLEMS CITED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Conn.)  By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Amistad freedom schooner, a reproduction of a
historic ship on which slaves rebelled, pulled out of New York
Harbor early Thursday morning to the disappointment of thousands of
visitors who showed up at a pier off Battery Park to see the
vessel.
</P>
<P>
   The ship left because the pier where it was supposed to moor,
which is under construction, did not have adequate bumpers and
safety guards to prevent the 136-ton ship from banging repeatedly
against it, said Will H. Mebane, vice president of Amistad America,
the owner and operator of the vessel. The crew was afraid the ship
would be damaged if it remained there any longer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Amistad America had surveyed the site before the ship
set sail, Mebane said he did not expect the docking problems that
would arise when 20,000 boats entered harbor for OpSail, creating
enormous waves.
</P>
<P>
   But Annie Bliss, director of design for Pier A Operations, which
runs the pier, said she had warned the Amistad crew that the waters
were turbulent. She added that most large ships traveled with their
own system of safety guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rough water on that side,'' she said. ``But I would say
the inexperience of the Amistad crew working together was not
helpful to the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mebane said that with only one exception, every member of
the nine-member crew had extensive sailing experience, many with
similar schooners, and that the captain, Bill Pinkney, had
circumnavigated the globe. He said the crew had been working
together since April, and added, ``I'm not sure how that impacts
whether or not there's an appropriate dock that's adequate to
protect our vessel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amistad is a reproduction of the vessel on which 53
Africans, destined for a life of slavery on a Cuban plantation,
staged a violent revolt against their captors in 1839. The new ship
made its maiden voyage on Monday, when it left Mystic, Conn., where
it was built, to join Operation Sail 2000 in New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Mebane said tens of thousands of sightseers visited the ship on
Tuesday, although they were not allowed to board because there was
a private, $100-per-person event on the pier that evening.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the vessel sailed to the Harlem piers, where the
Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture and Amistad America
held a special event, with presentations by the poet Maya Angelou
and former Mayor David Dinkins of New York. About 1,000 people
attended the event, Mebane said, and 600 of them boarded the
Amistad.
</P>
<P>
   Public viewing of the Amistad was to resume at Pier A Thursday
morning, but after three days of working around the clock, fighting
the currents to create makeshift bumpers to bolster the ship
against crashing waves, the crew wearily set sail for Mystic, where
the ship will be checked for damage.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of visitors were disheartened when they arrived at
Pier A Thursday to see the ship. ``How annoying,'' said Leonard R.
Pace, 55, a taxi driver from the Clinton Hill section of Brooklyn,
when he arrived in front of a shuttered gate at the end of West
Street, hoping to get a glimpse of the ship and perhaps meet its
captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping to meet Capt. Pinkney,'' he said, ``or if not
that, at least get pictures to show the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amistad will participate in Operation Sail 2000 in Mystic
beginning Wednesday and will then sail to New Haven for public
viewing there on July 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
