<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-OREL-RETIREMENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER CALLS IT QUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Not only did Orel Hershiser's stay with the Los
Angaeles Dodgers end after an eight-run second inning June 26, his
career also ended.
</P>
<P>
   After contemplating his future for more than a week, Hershiser
announced his retirement Thursday during a conference call that was
hurriedly put together after word of a since-canceled Friday press
conference leaked out.
</P>
<P>
   What came out of a hectic day in which a Dodgers legend retired
was that Hershiser will remain affiliated with the team. He will do
a little of everything for the next three months, including
scouting and possibly helping the on-field talent of the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, 41, cleared release waivers last Friday and had
offers from other teams, but decided to end his 17-year playing
career.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to retire, Hershiser, who was 204-150 with a Cy
Young Award and World Series MVP to his credit, went back to a
meeting he had in 1988 with his attorney and close friend, Robert
Fraley, who last year died with golfer Payne Stewart in a plane
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser said he listed five criteria for knowing when to
retire, which was part of his statement Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   ``One, Jamie (his wife) and I are still in love,'' Hershiser
said in reading the statement. ``Two, I know and love my two boys.
Three, My reputation is intact. Four, I am financially secure.
Five, God is still at the center of my life. I am humbly thankful
to say these criteria have been met.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will honor the right-hander during ``Orel Hershiser
Day'' later this season, but a date is yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   It's a ceremony Dodgers managing general partner and CEO Bob
Daly believes in whole-heartedly, especially given the way
retirement day turned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think this is the way this should have been done, but
we have no other choice but to go down this road, but I must say I
am extremely upset and I will apologize to (Hershiser),'' Daly
said. ``This is not the way a man of his stature, who's been a
member of the Dodger organization, this is not the way it should be
done, but unfortunately I have no other choice because it's been
leaked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser said he wanted to work with the organization for the
next few months to earn the remainder of the $2.5 million he was
guaranteed when he signed a deal in the offseason. Daly said
Hershiser would have a place in the organization after the season,
but Hershiser wouldn't commit to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't talked about anything in the future at all,''
Hershiser said. ``This is not something that I'm preparing for - a
specific job or anything. This is really just kind of an informal
apprenticeship for me to be able to gather knowledge. The Dodgers
are giving me access to the organization and I'm giving the Dodgers
access to me. This is very mutual, and I don't think you need to
read anything into this or where it's headed.''
</P>
<P>
   Before moving to the front office for good, Hershiser could
become either a coach or manager. If the Dodgers falter during the
second half of the season and the coaching staff changes, Hershiser
would be the front-runner to be pitching coach next season, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   This season didn't turn into the triumphant return many hoped it
would be. Despite an awesome spring training, Hershiser faltered in
every area with the Dodgers. Starting didn't work, pitching out of
the bullpen was a fiasco and even a minor-league stint did nothing
for him to return to form.
</P>
<P>
   While the glory days of 1988 were never a serious notion,
Hershiser going 1-5 with a 13.14 ERA wasn't expected. But the
Dodgers plan to teach Hershiser the daily operations of the club
from the ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous competitor and he did so much for the
Dodgers,'' Dodgers senior vice president and former manager Tom
Lasorda said. ``He was a tremendous role model for the ballclub. No
matter where he went he exemplified what the Dodgers represented. I
think this announcement is what he should have done. He's done a
great job his entire career, and he's had a wonderful career and
now it's time for him to start looking in a different direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
