<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NY-YANKS-METS-NYT &LR;      07-07 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-YANKS-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE ME OUT TO THE BALLGAMES   (BY SUBWAY, CAR OR CANOE) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``It's a subway series _ you gotta take the train,''
Tom Milan was saying with such an adamant certainty that his
buddies at the bar just had to disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you don't,'' said one of them, Jerry Beyrer, putting his
beer momentarily aside. ``You don't take the train at all. You get
a nylon jacket, print `security' in orange on the back and you
sneak on the team bus. That's what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Manny Feliu, sitting next to Beyrer at the Yankee Tavern
Wednesday night, saw it even differently. ``You stay at home,'' he
said, swirling his gin with quiet authority. ``You click the remote
from station to station, then you relax. Trust me, it's the
quickest trip you'll ever take.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was some of the chatter among the city's baseball fans this
week as they sought to unravel a truly unusual sports conundrum.
With the Mets and Yankees poised to play an exceedingly rare
split-park doubleheader Saturday, how much chaos would ensue as
legions of fans (not to mention two entire Major League ball clubs)
traveled between the two games, from Shea Stadium in northern
Queens to Yankee Stadium in the South Bronx?
</P>
<P>
   The games on Saturday _ the first at Shea at 1:15 p.m., the
second at Yankee Stadium at 8:05 p.m. _ promise to be a movable
feast of baseball. They also promise to be part sports novelty,
part transit brain-teaser and, of course, an all-out example of New
York City excess as police escorts accompany both teams along what
is likely to be the chosen route: down the Grand Central Parkway,
over the Triborough Bridge and up the Major Deegan Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   The split-park two-fer, the result of a rain cancellation at
Yankee Stadium on June 11, also brings with it a host of logistical
headaches. Subway motormen will have to brace themselves for beery
cheering and perhaps some nastiness among desegregated fans. The
fans will have to manage some quick commuting calculus, faced with
the choices of strap-hanging, driving or canoeing through Flushing
Bay past Rikers Island to get from park to park.
</P>
<P>
   Even Charlie Samuels, the Mets' equipment manager, has
acknowledged having a minor crisis to avert: he and his staff must
wash and dry a roster's worth of dirty underwear in the interlude
between the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe in years to come, to look back and say, yeah, in the
year 2000 we had a day in which we played two games in two separate
parks, it might be something to talk about,'' said Al Leiter, one
of the Mets' starting pitchers, sounding decidedly unconvinced.
``But Saturday, for the most part, guys are going to view it as an
inconvenience.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time that two big league ball clubs played a day game
in one park then decamped for a later game in another was on Sept.
7, 1903, when the New York Giants and the Brooklyn Superbas (later
to become the Dodgers) faced off twice, winning one game each. The
first game was played before 9,300 fans in Washington Park in
Brooklyn, which predated Ebbets Field; the second was played before
a crowd of more than 23,000 at the Polo Grounds in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   While there were no reports in the newspapers of the day on how
the teams and their retinues traveled from Brooklyn to Manhattan,
one thing is sure: They did not ride the subway or cross the
Triborough Bridge. Neither existed at the time.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the possibility of an entire baseball stadium _
even a third of a baseball stadium _ picking up their plastic cups
and felt pennants and riding the rails in an interborough swarm to
yet another baseball stadium, city transit officials have added
seven subway trains to each of the three lines that are expected to
be hit: the 7, the D and the 4.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Pettinato, a conductor on the 7 line, had a dire
prediction about what would happen on the subways between games.
``As soon as the Mets fan hit the Bronx,'' he said, ``the Yankee
fans are going to set them on fire. They're going drop some
gasoline on them and light a match.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees manager, said he, at least, was
unconcerned about the traffic. ``That's why we have a police
escort,'' he said. ``We can just have all the fans follow us and
we'll E-ZPass them through.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The authorities have taken the situation seriously. The police
said that each team had been escorted through the city separately
in the past but that they had never received such treatment on the
same day.
</P>
<P>
   One potential kink, given baseball's inherently lax attitude
toward time, is what happens if the first game at Shea runs into
extra innings? Would the teams wind up on the road together,
traveling in a single Bronx-bound convoy?
</P>
<P>
   Rich Levin, a spokesman for Major League Baseball, said he was
confident that there was enough time between the games.
``Obviously, the record is 26 innings, and if it goes 26 innings we
might be in trouble,'' he said. ``But we're expecting everything to
be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on an unscientific survey (asking around on the Yankees
and Mets Internet bulletin boards), most fans lucky enough to have
tickets to both games seem to be leaning toward the subway as their
mode of transportation. The 7 train from Flushing to Grand Central.
Switch. Head over to the 4 train to the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   But even so, the Yankee Tavern was still filled with hot debate
about the transit problem Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's going to be doing the dumbest thing they can, like
riding a bike,'' said Feliu, who once more advocated staying home.
``We all know what New Yorkers are like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you could probably catch a good fight or two on the
train,'' Milan offered.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Joe Bastone, the owner of the bar, chimed in.
``You know what I would do if I was going,'' he said. ``Park the
car at Yankee Stadium. Take the train over to Shea. Then come back
to the Bronx by train. And then drive home.''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, the pub fell into silence. It looked as if the
answer had finally been found. But then the barmaid, Natalie
Grigas, had to chip in with her two cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was me,'' she said, polishing a pint glass with a rag.
``I'd hitchhike.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
