<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-RESTRUCTURING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUACKENBUSH AIDES QUIT, PART OF INSURANCE
DEPARTMENT  RESTRUCTURING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Moving swiftly to distance the Department of
Insurance from the scandal surrounding Insurance Commissioner Chuck
Quackenbush, the department's new caretaker accepted the
resignations Thursday of six top deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Kelso, who was named interim chief deputy Wednesday, said
the move is part of the department's restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is simply to establish new leadership and to keep the
department fulfilling its important role in protecting and serving
consumers and regulating the insurance industry,'' said Kelso, who
will become acting commissioner Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush announced his resignation last week to avoid almost
certain impeachment by the Legislature. Lawmakers were
investigating Quackenbush's creation and use of a nonprofit
foundation financed by his department's settlements with insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Kelso said in a statement that the decision to accept the
resignations ``does not reflect any judgment by me or the
department on their past years of service.''
</P>
<P>
   But the removal of Quackenbush's executive staff was widely
expected after his top aides were repeatedly interrogated by
legislative investigators, who said they often found their
testimony to be questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oversight investigation raised a number of troubling
issues involving the leadership of the department,'' said
Assemblyman Darrell Steinberg, D-Sacramento. ``I think a fresh
start for the department is healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's resignations came from six of the department's 12
deputies and include those most directly involved in the
questionable foundations.
</P>
<P>
   A department spokesman said he did not know the effective dates
of the resignations or whether the aides would seek to move to
different civil service jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear if any other staff members will leave the
department under the restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have faith in Mr. Kelso's judgment and his ability to
determine who should remain on the executive staff,'' Steinberg
said. ``For those not involved in any aspect of what happened,
there does not seem to be a reason to start anew.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff members who resigned Thursday are Michael Kelley,
chief deputy commissioner; Brian Soublet, chief counsel; Jim Dong,
deputy commissioner for administration; Steve Suchil, deputy
commissioner for research and special projects; Mark Lowder, deputy
commissioner for enforcement; and David Langenbacher, deputy
commissioner for consumer affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Kelso also named Deputy Attorney General Steven Green as the
acting chief counsel for the department.
</P>
<P>
   Kelso, a law professor at Sacramento's McGeorge School of Law,
was recommended to take over as a caretaker by the attorney
general's office. He will hold the position until Gov. Gray Davis
appoints a successor. That person, who must be confirmed by the
Legislature, will hold the office until Quackenbush's term ends in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said last week that he hopes to nominate a new
commissioner in the next month. He said he will look for someone
who is not political.
</P>
<P>
   Kelso has said he will try to put off most policy decisions
until a permanent successor is in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In initiating the restructuring of the department, I have
taken the first step in the transition to a permanent insurance
commissioner and a new department leadership that will be appointed
by Gov. Davis in due course,'' Kelso said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
