<HEADER>
A5193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COL-LOVE-NYT &LR;      07-07 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-LOVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: FOR HUNTER-GATHERERS, LOVE IS A CHEMICAL THING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When trying to explain why his affections had shifted
from his wife to another woman, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani told a news
conference, ``The fact that we've grown independent, we've grown
more separate over the years _ who knows why those things happen?''
If he really wants an answer, he might enroll in Helen Fisher's
experiment. She's ready to scan his brain.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, an anthropologist at Rutgers University, has been trying
to find out why people fall in and out of love by putting
romantically infatuated New Yorkers into a magnetic resonance
imaging machine. Working with scientists at Albert Einstein Medical
College and the State University of New York at Stony Brook, she is
analyzing which parts of the brain are activated by thoughts of the
beloved.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is testing a grand unified theory of love that she began
developing after noticing a pattern in divorce statistics from
around the world: in all types of societies, the peak time for a
couple to divorce tends to be in the fourth year of the
relationship. Fisher believes the cycle is the remnant of our
ancestors' breeding season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among hunter-gatherers,'' she said, ``it's my gess that a
male and female had to stay together at least until the child was
walking and weaned and could be cared for by others. So the human
brain evolved with the circuitry to promote pair-bonding for at
least four years. It's like robins in Central Park who are
programmed to stay together for one breeding season.''
</P>
<P>
   The human brain promotes what Fisher identifies as three
distinct aspects of love: lust, attraction and attachment. Lust is
triggered by testosterone and gives you the initial impetus to find
a partner. Then comes attraction, the romantic infatuation that
Fisher attributes partly to low levels of serotonin, the brain
chemical associated with Prozac and feelings of well-being.
</P>
<P>
   In selecting infatuated New Yorkers for her experiment, Fisher
was looking especially for those in the throes of what
psychologists call ``intrusive thinking,'' and what songwriters
call ``can't stop thinkin' 'bout my baby.'' Intrusive thinking
about your mate, like obsessive-compulsive disorders, has been
linked to low levels of serotonin.
</P>
<P>
   Other commonly reported symptoms of romantic love are euphoria,
hyperactivity, loss of appetite and sleeplessness. Fisher believes
they're triggered by high levels of dopamine and norepinephrine _
natural stimulants activated by drugs like cocaine and
amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love being in love because it's a chemical high,''
Fisher said. ``But the high often ends after about a year, probably
because the brain produces less of the chemicals or the receptor
sites become dulled. Romantic love wears off _ as it should, or
we'd all die of sexual exhaustion. It evolved so you could
distinguish between potential mating partners and conserve your
mating energy by focusing on just one.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time your energy has produced a child, your brain has
moved on to the next phase, attachment, which produces feelings of
security, comfort and spiritual union with a long-term partner.
Fisher believes it is triggered by higher levels of vasopressin and
oxytocin, which have been demonstrated to trigger attachment in
animals. Attachment is a more durable emotion than lust or
infatuation, but it too can wane _ or eventually be overridden by
other emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rub is that these different systems in the brain aren't
always very well connected,'' Fisher said. ``You can feel deep
attachment for one individual while you feel romantic love for
someone else while you feel lust for a stranger in a magazine. You
might get all three together when you're walking up the aisle to be
married, but the brain isn't built to keep it that way forever.
We're built to be restless in long-term relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   When divorce does come, it involves more than just the
emotion-inducing chemicals in the brain. Humans also evolved with a
prefrontal cortex capable of rationally overriding those
extramarital temptations. The prospect, say, of winning a U.S.
Senate seat may be enough to keep a certain man _ or a certain
woman _ in a marriage when the chemicals are no longer flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prefrontal cortex is constantly calculating the
perquisites and deficits of the relationship,'' Fisher said. ``We
have only so much mating energy, and we have to decide how to spend
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani fits the stereotype for the high-profile divorce in New
York: the alpha male dumping his wife after he gains power or
money. But most divorces are actually instigated by women, for
reasons that are only just becoming apparent to researchers. More
on that next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5195 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CT-STUDENT-SUSPENSION     07-07 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-STUDENT-SUSPENSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCIPLINE FIGURES PROMPT CALL TO IMPROVE SCHOOL BEHAVIOR
</HEADLINE>
  By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ It is a statistic that troubles many educators
in Connecticut, and encourages others: Nearly 14 percent of public
school students in the state were expelled or suspended from school
at least once during the 1998-99 school year.
</P>
<P>
   Some administrators see the figure, disclosed in a June report
by the state's Department of Education and first reported Thursday
by The Hartford Courant, as a sign of stricter discipline in
Connecticut public schools, which produce some of the
highest-achieving students in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the figure, which represents one of every seven public
school students in the state, has also prompted Theodore Sergi, the
state commissioner of education, to issue broad new directives to
Connecticut's 166 school districts to improve the behavior of what
he called an increasingly belligerent student body.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real collective feeling among administrators that
it's time to be more aggressive in addressing the behaviors of our
youngsters in our schools,'' Sergi said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be equally concerned with the personal development
of kids as we are about academic achievement,'' he added. ``The
challenge is, we are not providing enough teaching around personal
responsibility in kindergarten and grades one, two, three and
four.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut education officials cautioned against comparing the
data, compiled for the first time this year, with statistics for
public schools in other states or for the nation. But some experts
said that, no matter how the figure was viewed, 14 percent was an
unusually large proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a high number,'' said Michael Casserly, executive
director of the Council of the Great City Schools, in Washington.
``It sounds like Connecticut needs to make its own judgment about
whether suspending 14 percent of its students is a good idea or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Most violations committed by the state's 544,657 public school
students, prekindergarten through 12th-grade, were minor
infractions like cutting classes, talking back to teachers or using
foul language. But the report also found that students were removed
from their classes 32,030 times during 1998-99 for violent offenses
like fighting, making threats or bringing weapons to school.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, most of the bad behavior occurred among students in
grades 7 through 12. Ninth-and 10th-graders were, statistically,
the worst behaved, accounting for 44,564 violations, or 36 percent
of the total.
</P>
<P>
   About 51 percent of the students suspended or expelled were
white, and 45 percent were black or Hispanic students, who make up
slightly more than 25 percent of the public student body, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal laws required state officials to compile the
disciplinary report. The results suggest that Connecticut schools
suspended or expelled their students in the 1998-99 school year at
a rate double that of public schools nationally.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997-98 school year, 3.2 million suspensions and 90,000
expulsions were given to 46 million public school students in the
United States, said Chris Chapman of the National Center for
Education Statistics, who quoted data compiled by the Office of
Civil Rights, a unit of the federal Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The data revealed only the number of these punishments, not the
number of students who received them. But even if the punishments
were meted out at a rate of no more than one per student, the
national rate would still be only 7 percent, half that measured in
Connecticut last year.
</P>
<P>
   As in Connecticut, black public school students nationally were
suspended and expelled at a rate disproportionately higher than
their school populations.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Connecticut school officials believe that the state's
suspension or expulsion rate is terrible news. In the Stratford
School District, in Fairfield County, Superintendent Raymond
O'Connell said he was encouraged by news accounts of the report,
which he had not yet read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expulsion rate is probably up there,'' he said.
``Actually, I'm a little bit encouraged by it. Our Saturday
detention program seems to be having a positive effect on the
kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
