r a BC-AIR-RAGE-SFCHRON &LR;      07-07 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-RAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FLIGHT ATTENDANTS FIGHT `AIR RAGE'  &HT;     By STEVE RUBENSTEIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Christine Black remembers a flight when a
passenger started shoving her and swearing because he didn't get
fish for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we had left was steak and chicken,'' she said Thursday.
``He didn't want steak or chicken. He wanted the fish.''
</P>
<P>
   The passenger threw his tray against the wall of the airplane
galley and began pushing Black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really scared,'' she said, recalling the incident that
happened three years ago aboard a San Francisco-to-Tokyo flight.
``This is not something you want happening at 30,000 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Black was one of eight flight attendants passing out leaflets
Thursday in front of San Francisco International Airport as part of
a nationwide campaign against the growing problem known as air
rage.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants maintain that the near-constant access to
in-flight liquor and a reluctance by airlines to offend customers
have contributed to the a dramatic increase in air rage incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Black, who managed to subdue the passenger with the aid of her
crewmates and had him arrested when the plane landed in Japan, said
such incidents are no longer isolated and that most of her
colleagues have similar tales to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines are providing champagne and hard liquor to
passengers before the plane ever leaves the gate,'' said Dawn Marie
Bader, a flight attendant and chapter president of the Association
of Flight Attendants. ``They're drinking before breakfast, before
dinner. They're drinking during dinner, after dinner and during the
movie. Passengers are drinking all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants' union is urging airlines and airports to
post signs and warn passengers at check-in that interfering with
flight crews is subject to a $25,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The union also wants airlines to practice ``more responsible
alcohol service (and) mandatory training for flight crews in
dealing with abusive passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants say oversold flights, crowded planes and small
seats are making passengers grumpier, and that air rage frequently
involves liquor, drugs or anger over bans on smoking and electronic
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Most departing passengers who stopped to chat with the
leafleting flight attendants said they supported &LR;  the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for them to serve people two and three
drinks at a time,'' said one Los Angeles-bound man.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Andre of Berkeley, who flies 100,000 miles a year and
sits in the part of the plane where passengers' legs do not fall
asleep in flight, said banning liquor on planes would be ``sort of
idiotic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They should cut off unruly drinkers, but not everyone else,''
she said. ``When I fly, I like to drink myself into oblivion and
then I go to sleep. It helps. I don't feel so good when I land,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   Airport spokesman Ron Wilson said reported incidents of air rage
aboard flights arriving in San Francisco increased 70 percent last
year. There were 85 incidents in 1999, 50 incidents in 1998 and 29
incidents in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
