r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     07-07 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER HAD AN EVERYMAN QUALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's only one thing for a Los Angeles Dodgers
fan to do at a Hallmark moment like this.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a retirement card. Then, mail it to yourself. Pick out a
gold watch. Then, strap it onto your own wrist. Stock up on
streamers and balloons. Then, throw a party for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Do this because, when Orel Hershiser announced his retirement
Thursday afternoon, he ended not only his own remarkable pitching
career, but also the vicarious career of every fan who lived
baseball's highs and lows through him.
</P>
<P>
   Which is pretty much all of us.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary thing about Hershiser wasn't the 200-plus
games he won, the scoreless-innings streak, the Cy Young Award, the
postseason heroics, the comeback from shoulder surgery, the
celebrated craftsmanship or all of the special moments it produced
- the elements of a Hall of Fame candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary thing is that he allowed his fans to feel as
if we were doing those things along with him.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, he looked, from a distance, like Everyman: pale,
gawky, reliant on contact lenses on the field and eyeglasses off
it, an all-around ``Poindexter,'' as his 1988 teammate Rick Dempsey
said affectionately after the Dodgers released Hershiser last week.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he was kind enough to allow us the illusion that he
was no more a physical marvel than you or I, just a scrawny kid
scraping by on guts and guile.
</P>
<P>
   The truth, which you realize if you stand next to him, is that
Hershiser is a born athlete, tall and trim and angular. Poindexter
couldn't throw 90 mph, but Orel could.
</P>
<P>
   His pitches had natural, nasty movement. And he could hit. He
might look bookish, but you can't learn any of that from a
textbook. He had a gift.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in discussing any of his 204 victories, he would never make
it sound as if he overpowered opponents. It was more like he
outthought them, or he won because he managed to ``stay within
myself,'' the Hershiserism that so amused the nation's
sportswriters at the 1988 World Series and made his reputation as a
baseball intellectual.
</P>
<P>
   It always sounded like he was some pipsqueak corporal who'd just
taken down the entire Russian Army with one cleverly directed
grenade.
</P>
<P>
   As lies go, it was exactly what we wanted to hear. Hershiser was
the cool, crafty pitcher we'd be if only we got the chance.
</P>
<P>
   He always seemed to understand - better than any other athlete
I've known - how the public saw him, his team and his sport, his
role as an entertainer and the media's part in the equation.
</P>
<P>
   He played that role right to the end Thursday. He played down
his brawn and played down his brains. He played down his talent and
played up his labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you work real hard to get somewhere, when you're
not the best from the beginning, when you're a 17th-round draft
choice ... you realize there's always something to learn, whether
it's from the man sweeping the floor or the president of the
company,'' he said, trying to explain his perspective, unusually
broad for a ballplayer. ``I just like to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Do I seem to imply that Hershiser was somehow cynical about this
put- on, out to manipulate the press and public in order to cash in
on the resulting popularity? I don't mean to.
</P>
<P>
   I think he is a genuinely nice man, one of the best to step onto
a diamond, court or ice rink in this big-league sports city. And I
think one of the nicest things about him is that he brought us with
him. (Now if he'd like to bring us with him when, inevitably, he
steps into Dodgers management, we've got some ideas ...)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought it was special to put the uniform on and
walk on the field,'' Hershiser said early in his all-too-short
final season.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was special to be out there. You must have felt it
yourself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
