<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MOBILE SNEAKERS RUNNING OUR WAY  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
A Russian has invented gas-powered shoes, which is cruelly ironic,
since most Russians can't afford gas or shoes.
<P>
   But the shoes could solve a major problem in San Francisco: Cars
go too fast and take up too much room; pedestrians go too slow and
become roadkill.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the ideal compromise. We outlaw cars in San
Francisco, make gas shoes available to everyone, and the streets
become a wonderful scene of smoothly flowing fast-foot traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The power shoes have pistons that push off the ground with each
step, giving the walker a huge boost. Top speed is about 25 mph, so
during rush hour you could even walk the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   The power shoes would level the playing field. As it is now,
cars and buses level the pedestrian field.
</P>
<P>
   We'll have no need for Muni buses when you can hop around town
faster than they can. All the buses could be donated to the PD for
target practice.
</P>
<P>
   Parking? Parking schmarking. We could turn the parking garages
into homeless shelters and playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   No plan is perfect. People wearing BMW and Volvo shoes would
still assume they own the road. People wearing Chevy Suburbans
would still hog more than their share of the space.
</P>
<P>
   But basically, a groovy scene.
</P>
<P>
   And we'll save one pair for Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   JURY DUTY came calling to Selma Guthertz, so she sent back a
letter explaining that she recently fell and needs a walker to
move, and she must have an attendant with her 24 hours a day, and
she is blind in one eye, and she is 96 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Selma got an immediate reply. She is excused this time, but they
might be calling on her in the future.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR GUYS were motorboating on the Fourth, about 6 p.m., when
they spotted a man struggling desperately in the water under the
Golden Gate Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The man was the skipper of a sailboat, he had fallen out of the
boat into the freezing water, and in the heavy wind his
inexperienced ``crew,'' mostly his family, was having no luck
maneuvering to fish him out. It was a mini version of ``The Perfect
Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   The four motorboaters zoomed in and plucked the man out of the
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was blue and half dead,'' says Dr. Jordan Shlain, one of
the four.
</P>
<P>
   But the adventure was far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Shlain and the boys yelled to the sailboaters to power up and
head for the shelter of the Fort Mason Marina.
</P>
<P>
   At the dock, the sailboat crew tried to tie up, but their line
toss was wild and the rope fouled their prop. The wind began to
blow the boat toward a cement wall.
</P>
<P>
   Shlain cell-phoned 911 and begged the Coast Guard to help save
the 40-foot sailboat from crashing into the wall. But when no help
arrived, the motorboat zipped near the sailboat, Yariv Baum and
Steve Nolan leapt aboard with a line, and the yacht was towed back
to safety. The Coast Guard never did show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we buy you guys a drink?'' asked someone on the frazzled
sailboat crew.
</P>
<P>
   On the powerboat, Nolan, an emergency medical technician, called
back, ``Thanks, but no thanks. This is what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   SLOWLY, BUT surely, all the personality is being sucked out of
radio. Or is it just my imagination?
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, Live-105 dumped local comic Johnny Steele so
the Bay Area could be treated to a daily dose of Howard Stern's
syndicated potty prattle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, KFOG has dumped Stan Sinberg and his weekly two-minute
topical humor commentary, ``Take a Stan,'' reportedly to make more
room for music.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sinberg, the commentary spot was held down by Scoop
Nisker. So there was a kind of tradition going. Now, FOGheads get
less punchy local humor and one more Dave Matthews song.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEWS of the death of famed showbiz tap-dancer Harold
Nicholas brought a pang of sadness to the old gang from Harding
Park Golf Course.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Nolan was part of an informal group of golfers back in the
'70s, the Harding Park Rabbits. They played every afternoon for 25
cents a round.
</P>
<P>
   The Rabbits kind of blended themselves in with a group of black
men who also played regularly at Harding. Nolan and Nichols hit it
off, became a daily team, won their fair share of friendly wagers
against the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teamed up for two years, '75 and '76, until a new
management ended the Rabbits,'' Nolan says. ``Harold was a great
guy, and never let on that he'd been a famous dancer. We played
together for a year and a half before I knew he'd been in show
business.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SIGN posted at 15th and Judah says, ``Please Stop the `Bird
Calling Machine' That Sounds in the Middle of the Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone has scribbled under that, ``Shoot the mockingbird?''
</P>
<P>
   It's no machine, it is indeed the lovely yet pesky mockingbird
and its mating-season serenade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the prettiest songbirds;it mimics every pretty
bird call,'' says Arthur Feinstein, executive director of the
Golden Gate Audubon Society. ``But it also mimics answering
machines, phone rings, car alarms. And it sings all night. We get
calls from people on the verge of insanity.''
</P>
<P>
   The best we can hope for is that the birds aggressively attempt
to mate with car thieves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
