u a BC-OBIT-WEINMEISTER-NYT &LR;      07-07 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WEINMEISTER-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Wash.)  
 ARNIE WEINMEISTER, 77, A GIANTS STAR IN THE '50s 
By RICHARD GOLDSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arnie Weinmeister, the Pro Football Hall of Fame defensive
tackle who starred for the Giants in the early 1950s then forged a
second career as a leader of the Teamsters union, died June 28 at a
hospital in Seattle. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was congestive heart failure, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Weinmeister was among the biggest players of his day, at 6 feet
4 inches and 235 pounds, but was known for his quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonder to see him on the field,'' said Dante Lavelli,
the star end for the old Cleveland Browns, who lined up opposite
Weinmeister when the Giants and Browns built their rivalry. ``He
was one of the first big men who could move that quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Buck Shaw, the coach of the San Francisco 49ers, said in 1954:
``Weinmeister is the outstanding tackle in the NFL. One man can't
handle him.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinmeister was born in Rhein, Saskatchewan, to German
immigrants who moved to Portland, Ore., when he was a child, and
then to Seattle. He played three seasons for the University of
Washington as a tackle and end, before and after serving in the
Army artillery during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating with a degree in economics, Weinmeister joined
the New York Yankees of the All-America Football Conference in
1948. He played both offensive and defensive tackle for two
seasons, then went to the Giants of the NFL, with the Yankee
defensive back Tom Landry, when the All-America league went out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   In Weinmeister's first three seasons with the Giants, they were
conference runners-up to the Browns, using coach Steve Owen's
umbrella defense, which featured an innovative four-man secondary.
Weinmeister and his fellow tackle Al DeRogatis were anchors of the
line while the defensive backs _ most notably Landry and Emlen
Tunnell _ spread out like an umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve was a very down-to-earth guy, a great defensive coach,''
Weinmeister recalled. ``We wound up having the best defense in the
league, but we didn't score any points to speak of.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry, who would gain renown as coach of the Dallas Cowboys,
once remarked how Weinmeister was adept at analyzing plays. ``If
you wanted to know where the opponent's ball was, all you had to do
was look for Arnie's jersey number,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weinmeister played for the Giants from 1950 to 1953 and was
selected for the Pro Bowl each season. He then joined the British
Columbia Lions of the Canadian Football League as a player-coach,
winning a court battle with the Giants, who maintained that he
still belonged to them.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected to the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving football in 1956, Weinmeister became an organizer
for the International Brotherhood of Teamsters. He was director of
the 13-state, 400,000-member, Seattle-based Western Conference of
Teamsters in the late 1980s and early 1990s and served as the
union's second vice president. He was also president of Joint
Council 28, covering 20 Teamsters locals in Washington, northern
Idaho and Alaska, and was secretary-treasury of Local 117 in
Seattle before retiring in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, when the Justice Department filed suit to remove the
Teamsters' senior leadership, charging that it had made a ``devil's
pact'' with organized crime, it accused Weinmeister and the 17
other members of the executive board of failing to root out
corruption. Under a consent decree, scores of union officials were
removed by overseers. Weinmeister remained in office. He said in a
1988 deposition that he had no knowledge of organized crime other
than what he had read in the newspapers or had seen in the
``Godfather'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   Weinmeister is survived by his wife, Joey, of Seattle; two sons,
Hans, of Anchorage, and Jason, of Scottsdale, Ariz.; two daughters,
Kirsten Weinmeister, of Duvall, Wash., and Gretchen Slater, of
Anchorage; eight grandchildren; and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In his football days, Weinmeister could be as hard on teammates
as he was on opponents. Roosevelt Brown, the Giants' longtime
offensive tackle, would recall having met his match when he faced
Weinmeister during workouts. Brown, who like Weinmeister was noted
for his quickness, would also become a Hall of Famer. But when he
practiced pulling out and cutting off the inside defender, he could
not shake off Weinmeister.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Weinmeister, it was impossible,'' Brown remembered. ``He
was very, very fast himself and one of the toughest to go up
against. Fortunately, I only had to do that in practice.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
