</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WEAK-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECIPE FOR WEAKER SCHOOLS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 7:
</P>
<P>
   Private prep schools often provide a fifth year of high school
for students who performed poorly in their earlier years and need
to strengthen themselves academically before moving on to college.
The American Federation of Teachers has suggested that public high
schools formally add a fifth year for struggling students. This is
not a good idea at this point. Public high schools need to make far
better use of the four years they already have.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of formalizing a fifth year was floated this week by
the federation's president, Sandra Feldman, during a conference of
the teachers union in Philadelphia, where Feldman called for a
``transitional-year'' program, before ninth grade or in high
school, in which teen-agers who lacked basic skills could be
prepared for college's more challenging course work. The optional
fifth year, she said, would serve ``kids who are just absolutely
falling through the cracks because no one's paying attention to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   These are noble sentiments. But an extra year for a few students
would quickly be expanded to cover a greater number of students.
These students would be passed unprepared from grade to grade, on
the theory that there would be time for them to catch up
academically somewhere down the line.
</P>
<P>
   The most important task now is to improve the four-year system.
A forthcoming study of national achievement data by the Education
Trust, a Washington foundation devoted to school reform, shows that
the public high schools have declined dramatically over the last 10
years _ and now yield less academic growth among their students
than in any other phase of the public school system. According to
the foundation's director, Kati Haycock, the new data show smaller
gains in high school than in the lower grades, a consequence of a
less rigorous curriculum that includes fewer challenging reading
assignments than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Those who favor a five-year approach argue that many students
already take that long to graduate. This is certainly true in New
York City, where only about half of all students receive high
school diplomas in four years. Encouraging those students to
graduate, even if they need more time, is the right thing to do.
But allowing high schools five years to graduate students as a
matter of policy would weaken the system, ensuring that more and
more students take longer to graduate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
