A5210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-CITYSCAPE-NYT     07-07 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-CITYSCAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A STREET CROSSING LONG AGO
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 7:
</P>
<P>
   In about 1835 an artist named George Harvey painted a small
watercolor of the intersection of Broadway and Houston Street. The
painting, called ``Night-Fall, St. Thomas Church, Broadway, New
York,'' now belongs to the Museum of the City of New York and is
reproduced in a new book called ``Picturing New York: The City From
Its Beginnings to the Present,'' by Gloria Deak. Like his friend
Washington Irving, whose house at Sunnyside he helped design,
Harvey was a romantic, with a romantic's love of atmosphere. He
painted what he called ``atmospheric landscapes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Night-Fall, St. Thomas Church'' is an atmospheric cityscape in
the period of summer. The lamplighters are at work, and the lamps
have just begun to take effect in the twilight. A saddlemaker
stands under a canvas awning, lit by the shop's light spilling onto
the walk. Carriages make their way across the cobbled intersection,
as do pedestrians and two riders, one accompanied by a small dog,
the other raising his horse in a levade. A squad of
white-pantalooned soldiers is about to pass the doors of St.
Thomas, whose twin towers frame a glowing leaded window. On the
street darkness is taking hold, but above St. Thomas the sky is
pale with midsummer. Looking at this painting you can feel the
mixture of diffusion and directionality in the light, so strongly
characteristic of the season, so familiar still.
</P>
<P>
   In 1835 there were perhaps a quarter-million people living in
Manhattan. Forty-eight of them are visible in Harvey's watercolor,
whose only unreality is the unreality of all figurative paintings,
the protracted seizing of an instant. As Harvey depicts it, the
intersection at Broadway and Houston might have been a village
square, so orderly and placid does it seem, so rural that
overarching sky. And yet you can sense the continuity that city
streets always imply, the way they reach into an unseen distance.
</P>
<P>
   St. Thomas is long since gone from that spot _ it is now at 53rd
Street and Fifth Avenue _ and saddles and harnesses are no longer
made anywhere in the city. The cobblestones have nearly all been
taken up and the hand-lit streetlamps all taken down. The 48 people
in Harvey's painting, and their quarter-million neighbors, have all
passed into the oblivion on which the present serenely rides. Three
tides of traffic now cross at Broadway and Houston, and every
pedestrian who pauses there for a light carries within him an
intuitive sense of the city's volume, its voltage, just as the
pedestrians in Harvey's watercolor surely did. That is perhaps the
only thing that has not changed in 165 years. That, and on fair
summer nights, the pale western sky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
