<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER AT `WIT'S END' UPON GOING ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Tim Belcher has always been known as a tough
competitor, but the 38-year-old pitcher is also a realist.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher was placed on the 15-day disabled list Thursday with a
strained flexor muscle in his right elbow, the same injury that
eventually required surgery last year. While doctors are saying the
latest setback is not directly related to the surgery, Belcher said
he knows there's a chance his career could be finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've struggled with the whole scenario for a year now, when it
started bothering me last year in mid-May,'' said Belcher, who is
2-2 with a 9.49 ERA in four starts this season. ``Because I never
had an elbow problem before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a long discussion with my wife (Wednesday) night. My
last couple of (bad) outings, it had kind of gotten to the point
where I had a different emotional reaction than what there had
been. I told my wife the frustrating part was that in the last game
I got knocked out in the first inning, and it was the shortest
outing of my career. But when I came out I didn't have the energy
to throw things around. It was like I'd rather sit down and cry
than break stuff up. ... It's certainly an indication of being at
my wit's end.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Belcher makes a decision to end his career, he's going to
take the steps required to get back to the mound. He had a
cortisone injection Thursday and plans to play catch this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher said he could have made his scheduled start tonight but
didn't want to put a strain on the bullpen like he did his last
time out, when he gave up seven runs in one-third of an inning and
was taken out.
</P>
<P>
   What's missing, Belcher said, is ``life'' on the ball out of his
hand. He hasn't had the same movement in his past two starts as he
had in his first two, when he went 2-0 with a 3.18 ERA. Instead,
his pitches have been flat and hitters are teeing off.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he is feeling, Belcher said: ``About as miserable as
you can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher is making $4.6 million this season, the second year of a
two-year contract. The Angels have an option worth about $5 million
for next year but are more likely to exercise their $1-million
buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz recalled: Ramon Ortiz has been called up from Triple-A
Edmonton and will make the start in Belcher's place tonight. Ortiz
was 2-2 with a 6.90 ERA in six starts for the Angels when he was
sent to Edmonton on May 10. In 10 starts for Edmonton, Ortiz was
4-3 with a 4.58 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz was called up instead of Seth Etherton because Etherton
started a couple days ago and threw 120 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen gets boost: In an effort to get help for a weary
bullpen, the Angels optioned starter Brian Cooper to Lake Elsinore
and called up reliever Lou Pote. Cooper pitched Wednesday night and
was not going to get another start before the All-Star break.
Cooper will make a start for Lake Elsinore to stay on a five-day
schedule, then return to the major- league club and start July 17
in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus sits: Third baseman Troy Glaus was not in the starting
lineup Thursday, partly because of fatigue in his right shoulder,
and partly because of his ongoing hitting slump. In his past nine
games, he is 2 for 33 with 18 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you look and we're playing Seattle, but I'm looking at
the big picture,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``When a guy needs a
day off you give him a day off. He'll be better off in the long
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehabbing: Shortstop Kevin Stocker is expected to be activated
from the disabled list today or Saturday. Stocker has been on the
DL since June 22 with tendinitis in his left knee. ... Pitcher
Scott Schoeneweis (strained rib-cage muscle) threw off the mound in
the bullpen Thursday and is scheduled to throw a simulated game
this weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
