<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EGYPTNYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: EGYPT ARRESTS AN ACTIVIST 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 7:
</P>
<P>
   Egypt arrested a prominent sociologist last week, along with at
least eight of his colleagues, and shut down the democracy
institute where they work. The government said the sociologist, Dr.
Saad Eddin Ibrahim, was suspected of, among other things, accepting
funds from the European Union and harming Egypt's image by making a
voting rights video that discussed past election fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests follow a campaign of attacks on Ibrahim in the
Egyptian media and represent the latest harassment of advocates of
democracy and human rights by the government, which appears to be
trying to silence them before parliamentary elections this fall. If
Egypt is truly worried about its image, it should end its
embarrassing assault on independent activists.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations against Ibrahim and other staff members of his
institute, the Ibn Khaldoun center, are similar to those brought in
the past two years against other activists. The Egyptian
authorities also tightened regulations on nongovernmental
organizations last year with a law that was recently declared
unconstitutional on technical grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt's human rights community is understandably alarmed that
the government would move against the prominent and well-connected
Ibrahim, who also holds U.S. citizenship and is a professor at the
American University in Cairo. According to one of Ibrahim's
lawyers, several of his staff members are still in jail, and no one
has been able to visit Ibrahim since Monday. The government has 15
days to investigate charges against him, but can renew his
detention indefinitely. His request for bail was denied.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt seems to be harassing Ibrahim for his democracy work and
for activities like accepting foreign donations and criticizing
government actions. This is not criminal conduct and should not be
treated as such. Washington, which gives Egypt $2 billion a year,
says its ambassador has raised the case with Egypt's prime
minister. The United States should continue to press for the
release of Ibrahim and his staff, and for the political rights of
all Egyptians.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
