<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5215 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-SFCH     07-07 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE DRAFTS CAMPAIGN FINANCE OVERHAUL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ Showing uncharacteristic speed, the Legislature
has drafted and approved a major overhaul of the state's campaign
finance laws to limit contributions and encourage candidates to
restrict spending.
<P>
   The reform legislation, written last week and adopted Wednesday
by the Senate and Thursday by the Assembly, needs voter approval to
become law.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis' expected approval is needed soon to meet a
deadline for placing it on the November 7 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Good government groups such as Common Cause and the League of
Women Voters say the legislation is too weak. They contend believe
 &LR; it was hurried through the Legislature in an effort to pre-empt
Proposition 208, a much stricter measure adopted by voters in 1996
but sidetracked by legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the new measure are limits on the size of
contributions to candidates, as well as voluntary ceilings on
campaign spending.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, a candidate for the Legislature could receive no
more than $3,000 from a donor each election. That amount would
climb to $5,000 for all statewide offices except that of governor.
Contributions in the governor's race would be capped at $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause and the League of Women Voters say the new bill's
changes aren't strong enough to slow the torrent of campaign cash
lavished on candidates by special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, the Legislature gives us a weak package that is
nothing like what the voters wanted,'' said Trudy Schafer, a
lobbyist for the League of Women Voters of California.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's especially galling is this is so premature, because 208
is going back to court next week,'' she said. ``Even lawyers
opposing 208 say they think it will be upheld.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 208 calls for contribution limits of $250 per donor
for legislative candidates and $500 for those seeking statewide
office.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there are no limits on contributions, a point
Assembly Speaker Bob Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys, used in urging the
lower house's approval of the plan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it better than what we have on the books now? There is
nothing on the books now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Legislature approved a broad overhaul of
campaign finance laws was in 1994. The plan never appeared on the
ballot because it was vetoed by then-Gov. Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, voters approved Proposition 208, a tough
campaign finance measure, but it was declared unconstitutional in
1998 without ever taking effect.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Davis said the governor had no position on the
new campaign finance reform package. But Senate President Pro Tem
John Burton, D-San Francisco, the architect of the plan, said the
Democratic governor will sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers originally set a $10,000 ceiling on gubernatorial
contributions, but Davis wanted the $20,000 level.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is a voracious fund-raiser. He has already amassed more
than $20 million 21/2 years before his re-election, much of it in
$25,000 to $100,000 chunks.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage a higher number of smaller contributions, the
Legislature's plan would allow political action committees financed
by more than 100 people kicking in no more than $200 each annually
to give double the individual contribution limits for legislative
and statewide races.
</P>
<P>
   The $20,000 cap still would apply in the governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   In the 80-member Assembly, which sent the plan to Davis on a
42-to-21, largely party-line vote, GOP critics said the limits
would help rich candidates by forcing less well-heeled candidates
to spend more time trolling for money.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative proposal would also create voluntary spending
limits in campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Spending in the governor's race would be capped at $6 million in
the primary and $10 million in the general. By contrast, Davis
spent $34.4 million in his successful run for governor in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly races would be limited to $400,000 in the primary and
$900,000 in the general election. State Senate races would be
capped at $600,000 in the primary and $900,000 in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   As an incentive to adhere to the voluntary limits, candidates
who refused to limit their spending would be identified in voter
pamphlets as doing so.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate adhering sticking  &LR; to the limits could also pay to
include a 250-word statement in the sample ballots mailed to
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Stiff penalties would be imposed if the limits are accepted and
then exceeded.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by voters, the limits would not take effect for
statewide officeholders, such as Davis, until after the November
2002 election. The limits would be imposed on legislative races
beginning in next  &LR; January.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of Proposition 208 complained that the Legislature's
proposal is designed to replace the much lower limits the voters
approved in 1996: $250 for legislative candidates and $500 for
statewide candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Those low spending limits were among the reasons Proposition 208
was declared unconstitutional. A new hearing on the measure's
constitutionality is scheduled for Tuesday in Sacramento federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the proposition are optimistic that a recent U.S.
Supreme Court decision upholding $1,000 contribution limits in
Missouri will lead to Proposition 208's reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   But San Francisco lawyer Joe Remcho, who leads the opposition to
Proposition 208, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposition's limits are totally unconstitutional,''
Remcho said. ``The cost to communicate with voters in California is
much higher than in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, the cost of 1998 elections and recent case law
have proved the judge was right the first time around in saying
208's limits prevent a candidate from amassing enough money to run
an effective campaign,'' Remcho said.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 208 would banned &LR;  fund-raising prior to one year
before the date of a primary for statewide candidates and six
months before the primary in a legislative race. The Legislature's
plan would does  &LR; not.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 208 would also banned &LR;  transfers among candidates,
one of the tools legislative leaders use to shore up weaker
candidates. The Legislature's plan would allow transfers but would
cap them at the contribution limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
