<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, July 7.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ There is a go-for-broke
quality to the Israeli and American approach to the coming Camp
David summit meeting, which starts Tuesday with the stated goal of
ending a 52-year-old blood-steeped conflict. But for the
Palestinians, whose participation is more reluctant, there is at
best an aspiration that the three-way meeting will serve as a
stop-gap measure to keep alive the stalemated peace process so that
a partial deal can be achieved by September. A news analysis by
Deborah Sontag. 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo, NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-HIGHSCHOOL (Weaverville, Calif.) _ When it learned last
year that a private company was offering college-level Advanced
Placement courses over the Web, the lone high school in this remote
gold-rush town thought it had finally discovered a perfect way to
mine the genuine academic potential of the Internet. It took the
Clinton administration up on its pledge that there was educational
salvation in new technology, and that the Web could help the
poorest schools approximate the offerings of the wealthiest. But so
far the results here and elsewhere have been ragged, suggesting
that a computer can be a crude substitute for a live teacher,
particularly when the students are so young, the stakes for them
are so high and the technology is so new. By Jacques Steinberg.
1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-FAMILIES (New York) _ They fill the courtrooms and
hallways of the city's courthouses each day. In some cases they
arrive in force: siblings, children, friends, all there to show
support for a loved one. In other instances, they are women who
arrive alone, a solitary mother, wife or girlfriend there to
support a scorned defendant or bring to life a murder victim. They
are the families of accused criminals and crime victims, and they
are all in some form of mourning. They often display remarkable
grace and loyalty, but in just as many instances, those families
that show up show a more fallible side. Fights break out.
Relationships in the process of coming apart unravel completely in
public. Still, the families who fill the courthouses in ever
increasing numbers are not anonymous, and they very often have
impact _ great and modest _ in the outcomes of the trials they have
come to witness. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-VACCINE (Durban, South Africa) _ Though a vaccine to
prevent AIDS is years away, steps should be taken now to enable a
vaccine to be distributed widely in the Third World as soon as it
becomes available, a leading group in the vaccine effort said here
as the 13th International AIDS Conference prepared to open Sunday.
By Lawrence K. Altman. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-JUDGE (Columbus, Ohio) _ Candidates for State Supreme Court
here are usually so unknown that contestants with familiar names
have often won because, political scientists say, voters thought
they were actually voting for someone they knew. But this year, at
least two candidates for Ohio Supreme Court _ and quite possibly
all seven members of the panel _ may soon be wishing for those days
of glorious obscurity. By William Glaberson. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEBT-NORRIS-COLUMN (New York) _ When things go great, the
winners go into debt. Sometimes they go too far. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-WORKERS (Tulsa, Okla.) _ In promoting permanent
normal trade relations with China, which the House approved in late
May and the Senate is expected to vote on in late July, President
Clinton predicted an ``almost incalculable'' increase in exports of
U.S. goods to China. But the move also seems likely to encourage
exports of some U.S. jobs. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent toNYT graphic clients)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ECON (Undated) _ Instead of the turmoil that many feared
a close election in Mexico could spark, Vicente Fox's 7 percentage
point margin of victory, wider by far than most polls had
predicted, has buoyed the spirits not just of Mexican voters but of
investors and business executives across North America. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CBS-BIGBROTHER (Undated) _ ``Big Brother'' was certainly big for
CBS in its first broadcast Wednesday night, scoring a higher rating
for its first episode than either of the two previous summer
reality television hits, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' on ABC
and ``Survivor'' on CBS. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   DEODORANT-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Tom Green, the outrageous MTV
comedian, is best known for stunts like dropping a live mouse into
his mouth, as he does in the hit gross-out comedy film ``Road
Trip,'' or snorkeling for change in a shopping mall fountain. Not
exactly the kind of guy typically embraced by corporate America,
right? Wrong. By Patricia Winters Lauro.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-B2B-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ As companies in practically
every industry rush to join business-to-business exchanges on the
Internet, regulators are growing concerned that they will face a
rash of new antitrust questions for which they are not prepared.
Known as B2B Web sites, these business-to-business exchanges create
a place for companies in the same industry, be it automobiles or
grain, to buy and sell goods, potentially saving millions of
dollars in back-office costs by setting up a national marketplace
online. By David Leonhardt. 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SEASIA-ECON (Singapore) _ Despite Southeast Asia's economic
recovery from the crisis that began three years ago this month,
foreign investors have been dumping stocks and currencies from the
region. Its markets this year are the worst-performing in the
world, having dropped more than 22 percent on average. By Wayne
Arnold.
</P>
