<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TWINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX DON'T LET MOMENTUM SWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ What had once been an 8-1 eighth-inning laugher
gradually faded into a life-and-death situation, with five
ninth-inning Minnesota runs already home and the tying run a bloop
or bleeder away on second base.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been the worst loss of the first half, period. And
there have been some beauties.
</P>
<P>
   Notice the tense. What woulda or coulda happened didn't happen.
There are good vibes floating around the Boston Red Sox right now,
and The Worst That Could Happen didn't. Derek Lowe induced Matt
Lawton into a grounder to second, and the 8-7 W was in the books.
And nothing was going to keep Jimy Williams from feeling good about
his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``No bad feelings whatsoever,'' said the skipper. ``It goes in
the lefthand column, and that's what matters.''
</P>
<P>
   How this one got there might matter even more. While there was
more of the offensive thunder that characterized this four-game
sweep of Tom Kelly's Twins, the feel-good story was the poised,
professional, and definitely most welcome six-hit, one-run,
zero-walk performance of 22-year-old righthander Paxton Crawford,
who picked up the first win of his major league career.
</P>
<P>
   Young Mr. C was supposed to be a onetime gap-plugger, wasn't he?
He was supposed to do what he could last Saturday in Chicago and
then pack his bags and head to coal mining country in Scranton and
Wilkes-Barre, where he could make a start for the PawSox. But he
looked much better than the final pitching line in his 5 1/3
innings Saturday, and he looked like a serious major league pitcher
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I'm telling you,'' said Crawford. ``I'm tickled to death.
This is one of the happiest days of my life. My first big league
win. And the way my teammates reacted. I was getting hugs.''
</P>
<P>
   And why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched extremely well,'' said Jason Varitek. ``It's nice
to see somebody get us through seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford was staked to a quick 2-0 lead when Carl Everett drew a
two-out walk from Brad Radke, Minnesota's new $36 million man, and
Nomar Garciaparra hopped on a 3-0 pitch and drove it over the
Office Max sign in deep left-center for the first of his two home
runs. And the sound! Let's just say they don't sound like that
when, no offense, Manny Alexander or Jeff Frye manages to poke one
over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford gave a run back in the first, but it could have been
worse because the inning started with men on the corners with
nobody out and yet only one man scored, and that via a Ron Coomer
sacrifice fly. He knew he was in the Bigs in the second when Frye
flashed some serious leather, first running down a foul pop down
the first base line, and then turning a snappy 4-6-3 double play to
erase David Ortiz, who had singled. He got help from both Cristian
Guzman and Everett in the third. With men on first and second and
one out, Lawton flied to medium-deep center. Cummings moved to
third, but Guzman foolishly tried to challenge Everett's arm and
was erased, 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   From then on it was ``The Paxton Crawford Show.'' The kid
retired 10 in a row and 13 of his final 14, the only blemish being
a one-out Corey Koskie double in the seventh. Crawford's reaction
to that aberrational occurrence was to get Ortiz on a foul pop and
then fog pitch No. 102, a high-rising fastball, past Chad Moeller
for only his second strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one had a little hair on it,'' Varitek advised.
</P>
<P>
   By that time he had a 8-1 lead. The Sox got two in the fourth
when Frye _ notice how often you've been reading that name of late?
_ singled and Brian Daubach launched a bomb to dead center for home
run No. 14. That made him the 11th Boston player to homer in this
four-game series, which, if not a verifiable record, is still an
amazing factoid. Two more runs came across in the sixth when
Everett walked and Nomar smacked Radke's first pitch for a garden
variety line-drive homer to left. The final two came courtesy of a
Daubach two-run double down the right-field line in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   There was a scary moment in the eighth. Rheal Cormier was on the
mound when Jay Canizaro hit a one-out fly to left. Troy O'Leary
came in, calling off Garciaparra, who unsuccessfully tried to avoid
colliding with his teammate. Nomar rammed O'Leary in the chest,
forcing him from the game. Afterward, Nomar was in a joking mood,
but O'Leary, a man of few words in almost any circumstance, was
visibly annoyed when questioned about it. ``I'm fine,'' he said
tersely.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Young was on in the ninth with an 8-2 lead but he didn't
handle things very well, hitting Koskie and giving up a two-run
homer to Ortiz. When he walked Moeller, Williams called upon Lowe
for the 38th time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe wasn't as bad as his line would indicate, giving up two
ground ball singles and a check-swing single. The fact is he got
the man he had to get in order to save the game.
</P>
<P>
   And the facts are that in this four-game series the Red Sox had
44 runs and 53 hits, 28 for extra bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our attitude's a little different now,'' said Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   You think?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
