<HEADER>
A5226 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-L     07-07 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUNS HELP ANGELS EARN SERIES SPLIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It might have been difficult to find someone
in the Anaheim Angels clubhouse to say Thursday night's game
against the Seattle Mariners was more important than any other
game. But it was.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels began the night seven games behind the first-place
Mariners in the AL West, and a loss would have left them eight
games out going into the weekend series before the All-Star break.
Also, the Angels won't play the Mariners again until the final
three games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So their 5-1 victory before 18,790 at Edison Field was big in a
sense. It meant the Angels are now six games out, and only three
behind second- place Oakland, which is the wild-card leader. The
Angels split the four-game series against the Mariners, although
Seattle has won six of 10 overall against them this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels did it by making the most of what little they had on
this night. They got only five hits, but two were home runs by Mo
Vaughn (No. 22) and Tim Salmon (No. 18).
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Jarrod Washburn (5-2) managed to get through
just five innings, but he didn't allow a run and gave up only four
hits. Mike Fyhrie relieved Washburn to start the sixth and gave up
one run in 2 innings. Mark Petkovsek (1 scoreless innings) finished
it off.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad led off the Angels' half of the first inning with a
single but was thrown out at second on a botched hit-and-run
attempt when Orlando Palmeiro swung and missed. It cost the Angels
a run because Vaughn followed with his home run.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels lost another run in the third inning after another
attempted hit-and-run, only this time it was first-base umpire Mike
Winters who cost the Angels. Erstad led off the inning with a walk
and was on his way to second on a pitch to Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro reached out and slapped the ball into the ground on the
infield grass. Shortstop Alex Rodriguez initially broke to cover
second but recovered in time to field the ball. His throw to first
was obviously late to get Palmeiro, but Winters called him out
anyway, drawing a protest from Angels manager Mike Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   It ended up costing the Angels a run because one out later,
Salmon hit a home run, good for two runs instead of three.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Washburn seemed to struggle but got big outs when he
needed them. With Jay Buhner on second (double) and David Bell on
first (walk) with two out in the second, Washburn got Joe Oliver on
a liner to right.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Stan Javier and Rodriguez singled with two
out, bringing up Edgar Martinez. But Washburn struck him on with a
91-mph fastball on a 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, the Mariners had runners on first and second with
none out and the heart of the lineup due up. But Washburn struck
out Javier, then got a break when Mark McLemore's baserunning
blunder resulted in an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hit a liner to the gap in left-center, but the ball
stayed up long enough for left fielder Erstad to run it down.
McLemore, however, broke from second, rounded third and was doubled
up easily to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   That marked the end for Washburn, who threw five scoreless
innings but needed 97 pitches to do it. He walked three and struck
out five. In his past six starts, Washburn has allowed two runs or
fewer five times. Thursday was only the second time in those six
starts he hasn't pitched into the seventh inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
