<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-MYSTICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS STREAK REACHES 11
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ With WNBA President Val Ackerman in
attendance, the Los Angeles Sparks stretched the league's best
winning streak of the season to 11 against the gutsy Washington
Mystics.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Leslie led five Sparks in double figures with a game-high
21 points as Los Angeles kept its home record perfect at eight with
a 79-70 victory at the Forum on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Mystics (8-8) tried the spoil the Sparks' visit from the
president with a late run. Washington star Chamique Holdsclaw, who
had a relatively quiet first half, helped trim an 11-point Sparks
lead to two with 4:53 to play.
</P>
<P>
   But Sparks center Lisa Leslie, Holdsclaw's Olympic teammate,
scored her 19th point on a layup and Washington got no closer.
</P>
<P>
   The victory brings the Sparks within four games of the
league-record 15- game win streak set by the Houston Comets in
1998. The three-time defending champions remain a half-game ahead
of the Sparks (16-2) in the Western Conference after their win over
Seattle on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second Sparks game for Ackerman, who was in
Sacramento Wednesday for the Sparks' 76-61 victory. She spoke of
the low overall attendance, which she contributed to the
early-season start to accommodate the USA team members in the
Olympics. The Sparks' DeLisha Milton and the Mystics' Nikki McCray
join Leslie and Holdsclaw on the national team. Ackerman was
optimistic about the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our history has been that July and August have been our better
months,'' she said. ``We'd like to see our attendance get better.``
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, which drew 5,109 Thursday, has the ninth lowest
home attendance average (6,090), despite the second-best record in
the league and an 8-0 mark at home. Earlier this year the franchise
was awarded a 10-year operating contract extension, indicating the
league's confidence in the Sparks' organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think L.A. has great potential to be a great market for
women's basketball,`` Ackerman said. ``We have a lot of confidence
in the market. There's a lot of support from (Lakers owner) Jerry
Buss. ... Personally, I'm grateful to Jerry for being behind the
league.``
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back on the court the Sparks were trying to win the
series against the Mystics, who they defeated 74-72 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks led by as many as 13 in the first half, but
Washington got back on track with the resurgence of Holdsclaw. She
scored 12 of her 16 points in the second half, including five of
six in the run that trim the Sparks lead to 66-64 with less than
five minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sparks held strong defensively. With a minute to play
Mwadi Mabika blocked a shot and Ukari Figgs drove the court for a
diving layup to make it 76-69.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie added 13 rebounds and two blocks shots to her efforts,
while Allison Feaster came off the bench to contribute 14 points.
Mabika and DeLisha Milton had 13 points apiece and Tamecka Dixon
had 12.
</P>
<P>
   McCray had 20 points for Washington, which saw its two-game win
streak end.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie and Dixon scored 21 of the Sparks 42 first-half points.
The Sparks stretched the game out early, building a 18-10 margin
after getting six consecutive points by Dixon, a 3-pointer from
Mabika and a 18-foot jumper from Leslie. They led by as much as 13
when Dixon knocked down a 3-pointer at the 3:32 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks shot 47 percent to take a 42-31 lead at the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
