<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUNS HELP ANGELS EARN SERIES SPLIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Before the first pitch, it might have been
difficult to find someone in the Anaheim Angels clubhouse to say
Thursday night's game against the Seattle Mariners was more
important than any other game. But it was.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels began the night seven games behind the
first-place Mariners in the AL West, and a loss would leave them
eight games out going into the weekend series before the All-Star
break. Also, the Angels won't play the Mariners again until the
final three games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So their 5-1 victory before 18,790 at Edison Field was big in a
sense. It meant the Angels are now six games out, and only three
behind second-place Oakland, which is the wild-card leader. The
Angels split the four-game series against the Mariners, although
Seattle has won six of 10 overall against them this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels did it making the most of what little they had on
this night. They got only five hits, but two were home runs by Mo
Vaughn (No. 22) and Tim Salmon (No. 18).
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Jarrod Washburn (5-2) managed to get through
just five innings but didn't allow a run and gave up only four
hits. Mike Fyhrie relieved Washburn to start the sixth and gave up
one run in 2 innings. Mark Petkovsek (1 scoreless innings) finished
it off.
</P>
<P>
   After the victory, many Angels conceded it was an important
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big game for us,'' Fyhrie said. ``Anyone who says it
wasn't, I think they'd be lying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you're ever satisfied with a split, but we won
two games against a very hot club,'' Angels manager Scioscia said.
``Obviously, it was a big game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels won despite having to nurse Washburn through his five
innings. He had a couple of knots in his back that needed work
between innings. He said it didn't affect his pitching, but he made
97 pitches in just five innings, accelerating his departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't real pleased with the way I threw,'' said Washburn,
who walked three and struck out five. ``But I kept putting up
zeroes and we won the game, so I have to be happy with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think I can pitch like that every five days and
win. I have to improve on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Washburn struggled, he got big outs when he needed them.
With Jay Buhner on second (double) and David Bell on first (walk)
with two out in the second inning, Washburn got Joe Oliver on a
liner to right.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Stan Javier and Alex Rodriguez singled with
two outs, bringing up Edgar Martinez. But Washburn struck him on
with a 91-mph fastball on a 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, the Mariners had runners on first and second with
none out and the heart of the lineup due up. But Washburn struck
out Javier, then got a break when Mark McLemore's baserunning
blunder resulted in an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hit a liner to the gap in left-center, but the ball
stayed up long enough for left fielder Darin Erstad to run it down.
McLemore, however, broke from second, rounded third and was doubled
up easily to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   In his past six starts, Washburn has allowed two runs or fewer
five times. Thursday was only the second time in those six starts
he hasn't pitched into the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy shows you every start what he's made of,'' Scioscia
said. ``It's why he's going to be a consistent winner in the major
leagues. He doesn't back off. He knows he can get the ball where he
needs to in tough situations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
