<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 ANGELS CHASE ABBOTT, ENDS SEATTLE`s STREAK  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Mariners came away from a big road trip
with a winning record, but a losing feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to its inability to hit Anaheim lefty Jarrod Washburn,
Seattle lost to Anaheim, 5-1, Thursday night. The Mariners return
to Safeco Field Fridan night for a series against Los Angeles
having won four of seven on the road swing through Texas and
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our record could have been better, but it is what it is,''
second baseman Mark McLemore said. ``It's over, so now we have to
concentrate on (Friday).''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners return home to Safeco in much better position than
when they left a week ago. Seattle left with a half-game lead over
Oakland in the American League West. Going into the opener against
L.A., the Mariners have a three-game lead over the suddenly
slumping A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased, I really am,'' Seattle skipper Lou Piniella said.
``It wasn't an easy trip, and we knew it wasn't going to be before
we left. But any time you go on the road and come back with a
winning record, you have to be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we were able to pick up ground in the division and not
lose any. From that perspective, you've got to be pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were pleased, too, because a loss Thursday would have
put a crimp in their hopes to be competitive in the AL West.
Seattle had taken two of the first three, and had the Mariners won,
the third-place Angels would have been eight games out of first.
Now, they're only six back.
</P>
<P>
   They made up ground because they were able to convert a couple
of Paul Abbott pitches into runs early in the game. Abbott allowed
just three hits in the first five innings, but among them were
homers by Mo Vaughn (a solo shot in the first) and Tim Salmon (a
two-run bomb in the third) that put the Mariners in a hole.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott had pitched well enough to claim a spot in the rotation
the second half of the season. He was 4-0 in June and July. But
nothing concerning his status as a starter has been finalized, so a
good outing Thursday was Priority No. 1 for Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   The early homers hurt him, and he got chased from the game in
the sixth when he walked two, setting the Angels up for the final
two runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abbott pitched well for five innings,'' Piniella said. ``But
he seemed to get tired in the sixth.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only Mariner to feel that way. McLemore talked
about the club looking ``a little flat'' Thursday night. Shortstop
Alex Rodriguez said, ``the energy of the club has been really good
lately, but tonight the energy wasn't as good.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella noticed it. He wouldn't admit to the club being tired,
but he noticed the dropoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you this, I'm going to rest the entire team some
over the weekend,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   One of those getting time off might be center fielder Mike
Cameron, who was scratched from the lineup just before the game
started. He has a sore right knee that is the result of a run-in
the outfielder had with the Edison Field wall.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Cameron-less Mariners lose, Piniella said he
planned to ``use my bench this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Mariners fatigue had to do with Washburn, who
pitched well enough to take advantage of any lapse of energy on
Seattle's part.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn surprised Seattle with his pitch selection, then was
out of the game before the Mariners could adapt. He pitched just
five innings, but the Mariners didn't touch him for a run and only
had four hits. Even so, it was obvious he was tiring by the fifth,
closing in on 100 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The lefty, who had a no-hitter for six innings in his previous
start, against Oakland July 1, came into the game with one previous
appearance against Seattle, a win in a start in Anaheim two years
ago. When he was done after five innings and 97 pitches, he left
with a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Although his pitch total was high, he only walked three and no
runner got past second base. Seattle's only run came against the
bullpen when Jay Buhner singled home Edgar Martinez in the eighth,
averting the shutout.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' one charge at Washburn was set up by a McLemore
single and a walk to Rickey Henderson to open the fifth inning.
Washburn battled back to strike out Stan Javier, but Rodriguez
lined a shot to left-center. McLemore said he assumed the ball
would drop for a double, but left fielder Darin Erstad ran down the
ball and McLemore was doubled off base. End of rally. End of
Washburn, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they could tell we were getting closer to getting
him,'' Rodriguez said. ``But he surprised us. He threw a lot of
fastballs, really challenged us, which we weren't expecting. I
think the next time we see him, it might be a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   It may take a while. The Mariners and Angels don't play again
until the final weekend of the season.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
