r k BC-TEXMEX-POLITICS-ECONO     07-07 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXMEX-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-300&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NAFTA-IZATION OF MEXICAN-AMERICAN RELATIONS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors...NOTE 75-word trim)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 975-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (NOTE: 75-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 300. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,050 WORDS.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Americans may come to look back on 2000 as a
decisive political year. The reason will not be the election of
President Gore or President Bush, but the election of President
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The victory of Vicente Fox in Mexico seems like a vindication of
Americans' belief in the possibility of worldwide political
progress.
</P>
<P>
   It would be too much to say that the man who persuaded Mexicans
to drink Coca-Cola has now got them to swallow another American
export, since democracy is neither specifically American, nor a
fizzy consumable _ and there is always a chance that the vanquished
PRI may return.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Fox's victory is another big stride away from autocracy,
following the victories of opposition parties in South Korea and
Taiwan in the past three years and the spread of democracy
throughout Latin America and Eastern Europe in the past two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, this week's election marks the moment when the
worldwide trend towards greater democratization washed back over
the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   There are around 20 million Mexicans in America, making it
easily the most important mother country for immigrants. Mexicans
are also the fastest growing group of new American citizens,
accounting for a fifth of the total. As a result, their country is
becoming a touchstone of sorts for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Fostering relations with Mexico has become a way for American
politicians to display their credentials as people mindful of
America's future as a multi-ethnic nation.
</P>
<P>
   When Gray Davis became governor of California he invited so many
Mexican politicians to his inauguration that people joked it would
have been more convenient to hold the ceremony in Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's election came one day after the moment when whites
officially became a minority in California. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (75-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 300) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Nothing represents the growing domestic significance of Mexico
better than the family history of the Bushes.
</P>
<P>
   Prescott Bush, a senator from Connecticut, epitomized the
Waspish traditions of the Eastern Seaboard. George Bush began the
drift to the Southwest by moving to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, with his halting Spanish, won 49 percent of the
Latino vote on reelection as governor of Texas partly by reaching
out towards Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   His nephew, George P. Bush, whose mother is Mexican and who
speaks fluent Spanish, represents the next stage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Mexico's significance in American domestic politics
has grown over many years. That has nothing to do with Fox. But his
triumph owes much to one vital event in that process.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in part, a vote for the North American Free-Trade
Agreement (NAFTA) and, by extension, it is a vindication of the
strategy of successive American presidents of seeking to influence
foreign countries' behavior by opening up their markets to trade.
</P>
<P>
   That trade tends to promote freedom is often doubted _ most
recently at the time of the congressional vote to grant permanent
normal trade relations to China this June.
</P>
<P>
   Trade liberalization is obviously not a sufficient condition for
democracy, since there are free-trading autocracies. But as the
Mexican vote suggests, trade and freedom are disposed to go
together.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a case in which the political elite chose to open up to
trade against their own narrow self-interest. Once trade
liberalization is achieved, political liberalization can be kept at
bay only at an ever-higher cost.
</P>
<P>
   Though the parallels between Mexico and China should not be
pressed far, it is worth remembering that 25 years before Mexico
signed NAFTA, it had a Tiananmen Square massacre of its own.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968 the president ordered his troops to open fire on
students protesting in Mexico City. Hundreds died. And though
Mexico's authoritarian history is not nearly as long as China's,
its habits of government antedate even the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's victory makes it that much harder to argue that any
country's political traditions or habits of thought leave it
invulnerable to economic liberalization. For the Chinese Communist
Party, too, this was an important election.
</P>
<P>
   This is all very satisfactory for the United States. But not
entirely so. Some consequences of this week's election will be
uncomfortable for America, however desirable for Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the American relationship with its southern neighbor
has been a partnership of unequals, with Mexico the prickly,
reluctant supplicant, America the condescending benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   This had advantages for the United States. It could negotiate
bilateral deals with the Mexican president with the expectation
that they would be implemented in full, without any subsequent
revisions. NAFTA is a good example.
</P>
<P>
   That will change. In a democratic Mexico, the new president will
be more constrained by his local constituencies and Washington will
find it harder to get its way. Relations with Mexico will become
negotiations of political equals _ more like those with Germany (on
a good day) or France (on a bad one).
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, this must mean rethinking American policy
towards its southern neighbor. The two countries now talk past one
another. America wants to discuss drugs and illegal immigration.
Mexico wants to discuss legal migration, poverty, foreign
investment and trade flows.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one day the two will be able to have a rational
discussion about immigration. Perhaps one day the border between
the two will be as airy and open as that with Canada.
</P>
<P>
   This would be no bad thing. But the impact will be a balance of
gains and losses, not an unalloyed benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of Mexico into a real democracy may even
subtly change how Americans see their place in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must always remember,'' said John McCain earlier this year,
``that America is a beacon of hope and freedom.'' This notion _
that America is engaged in a battle for democracy _ runs deep. It
plays a vital role in maintaining the domestic constituency for the
country's continued engagement in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's election, which leaves the United States as just one part
of a North American democracy that stretches from the Arctic Circle
to well below the Tropic of Cancer, is another victory in that
crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Yet paradoxically, this crusade's growing success may make it
harder to keep alive the idea that America is a special beacon. For
how can you do that as more and more countries get lights of their
own? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
