<HEADER>
A5265 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-ABDULLAH-REPORTCARD-E     07-07 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABDULLAH-REPORTCARD-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING ABDULLAH'S GROWING PAINS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (NOTE: 50-word trim at 850; 1,000 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 950-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   AMMAN _ Ask the King of Jordan what knowledge he most lacked
when he unexpectedly came to the throne last year, and he explains
how difficult he has found it to work out the hidden agendas and
personal rivalries among his advisers, ministers and court
officials.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, although he does not put it so bluntly himself,
Abdullah II knew little about Jordanian politics. A lifelong
soldier, he had served as crown prince for only a week before his
father, King Hussein, died.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, thanks to his schooling at military academies in Britain
and America, he could barely get by in the language of his
subjects. ``The king's Arabic has improved,'' says one, ``but he
still has trouble with his h's and his r's.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Jordanians were hoping for other improvements too,
especially to their country's stagnant economy and stalled
democratization process. Since 1996, the population has grown at
least twice as fast as the national income.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with this dire economic picture, and with widespread
popular opposition to Jordan's 1994 peace treaty with Israel, King
Hussein spent his last few years trying to rein in the democratic
debate that he had previously encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   At his accession, King Abdullah promised to steer his country
towards free markets and a constitutional monarchy. He strode off
on his reforming tasks with resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks of his father's death, he went first to the Gulf,
to persuade his wealthy Arab brethren to provide more jobs and aid,
and then to Europe (and sent his finance minister to Japan) to
plead for relief from Jordan's hobbling $8.5 billion debt.
</P>
<P>
   He even persuaded the United States to start negotiations on a
free-trade pact, a rare distinction.
</P>
<P>
   At home, he spoke of turning Jordan into an Arab Singapore, and
prodded his government to reform education to that end.
</P>
<P>
   A new intellectual-property law and lower import duties helped
win the country admittance to the World Trade Organization.
Long-delayed privatizations, of the state-run freight railway and
telephone systems, finally got off the ground, as did much-needed
tax reform.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Bill Gates, charmed by the king during a meeting of
the World Economic Forum, announced that he would think about
setting up shop in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the regal vigor the king exudes, Jordan remains
stubbornly uninvigorated. The real keys to growth are out of the
government's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli security concerns and the international embargo on Iraq
strangle trade with two of Jordan's closest markets: Iraq and the
West Bank. A huge proportion of the budget goes on debt repayment
and salaries, and there is no easy way of changing this pattern.
Jordan already receives the best deal it can hope for from its
biggest creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, with unemployment at 25 percent, laying off workers
would be political suicide.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how he will get the economy going again, Ali
Abul-Ragheb, the recently appointed prime minister, can think of
nothing more dramatic than following up on the privatization and
trade policies of his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, the record looks equally equivocal. Even
as the king toured the world, confiding his liberal inclinations,
the government in Jordan was hounding critical journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, although the king has condemned the systematic
discrimination against Jordanians of Palestinian origin (who make
up as much as two-thirds of the population), he also took the
controversial step of closing down the local offices of Hamas, a
radical Palestinian group allowed to operate by his father.
</P>
<P>
   A royal adviser who had the temerity to discuss the
Palestinians' role in Jordan's future found himself out of work. An
academic who spoke openly about the king's inexperience also lost
his job.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, many of these decisions came not from the king
himself, but from his more conservative advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Abdel-Rauf Rawabdeh, King Abdullah's first prime minister, who
revels in the nickname of ``the bulldozer.'' spent his time doling
out jobs to his chums and strong-arming his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Sami Battikhi, the head of the secret police, has also made his
mark on policy, to the extent of sitting in on the meeting at which
the king appointed Abul-Ragheb.
</P>
<P>
   An old guard of such reform-leery native Jordanians has
succeeded in driving the best-known liberals from office. On the
other hand, King Abdullah stood by and let the old guard have its
way.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that he needed intimidating figures to ensure a smooth
succession, and says that he will now allow more progressive types,
such as Abul-Ragheb, to take center stage.
</P>
<P>
   But King Abdullah preserves a soldier's obsession with security,
talking of shadowy ``extremists'' on the Jordanian political scene,
and hinting darkly at plots to overthrow the present order. He
suggests that he will not concede parliament more power until the
electorate, and their representatives, learn to behave more
responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Jordan's main political forces, including its prominent
Islamic movement, seem remarkably moderate. But they certainly
differ from King Abdullah in their hostility to the peace treaty
with Israel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (50-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 850) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the political parties and professional associations have
pursued an aggressive campaign against normal nongovernmental ties
with Israel. Next year's parliamentary elections will doubtless
give this view more publicity, especially if the government sticks
to its promise to alter the electoral law to increase
representation in towns where Palestinians are the majority. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,000) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   King Abdullah's dismissal of anti-peace agitation as a passing
trend that will fade as the economy grows may be overly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   He has misjudged his people before, most visibly over a laudable
but heavy-handed drive to stamp out the tradition of murdering
young women in the name of family honor.
</P>
<P>
   He sounds more comfortable talking about computer moguls in
Davos than about Islamist politicians in his own country. His
latest initiative, a Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi poster campaign designed to
lift morale, has met with bemusement.
</P>
<P>
   While he has improved his grasp of his subjects' language, he
still seems uneasy with their political views. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
