<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFER-FOREST-FIRES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FORESTS: WHERE THERE'S SMOKE, THERE'S CONTROVERSY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 725-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Along with the stifling heat, devastating fires are
part of summer in the Southwest. Whether caused by lightning or the
cigarette butt of a thoughtless camper, they ravage thousands of
acres in the region each year.
</P>
<P>
   This year's conflagrations in New Mexico, Arizona and Colorado
are worse than anything nature has produced for a long time past.
</P>
<P>
   Drought and strong winds propelled them; but the biggest fires
were begun by government workers. This raises new, and troubling,
questions about the stewardship of America's forests.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts began in May with the Cerro Grande fire that raged
through Los Alamos, in New Mexico. When the smoke finally cleared,
the fire had destroyed more than 47,000 acres and more than 400
houses, causing an estimated $1 billion in damage and barely
missing the National Laboratory, home of America's nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   This turned angry eyes on the policy of ``controlled burning,''
which has been used by the National Park Service for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Controlled burns are fires deliberately set by park officials in
order to clear out grass, brush and deadwood that could be the fuel
for later, accidental, blazes. In essence, the practice is an
attempt to restore the natural fire cycle that existed 100 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   As more people have moved into the region (in recent years, the
Southwest has been the fastest-growing part of America), natural
wildfires have been suppressed by humans. This has led to an
enormous buildup of scrub brush and deadwood, the elements that
turn forests into tinderboxes.
</P>
<P>
   It is to burn away this buildup that the National Park Service
has quadrupled the number of controlled burns in the past four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, a controlled fire is often an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   According to a damning Interior Department report on the Cerro
Grande fire, park officials made ``seriously flawed'' calculations
about how the fire was likely to behave, underestimating the effect
of high winds and dry weather.
</P>
<P>
   They also failed to have enough firefighting equipment ready.
Two other notably uncontrollable ``controlled fires'' have happened
at the Grand Canyon, where the blaze spread over 14,000 acres and
forced the closure of several tourist lodges, and at Seven Springs,
in New Mexico, where the town had to be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the conditions that lead to the best controlled
burns (usually, dryish weather and strong enough winds to spread
the fire) are nearly the same as those that cause a fire to burn
out of control. And drought in the Southwest has made things worse.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steve Gatewood, executive director of the
Arizona-based Society for Ecological Restoration, any decision to
order a controlled burn under current conditions is bound to be
risky.
</P>
<P>
   He also points out that the forest agencies are behind schedule
on controlled burns, and may have felt pushed to approve burns that
tested the limits of fire safety.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative way to restore forests, based on research by
Professor Wallace Covington of Northern Arizona University, is
being tested on 100,000 acres of dense pine forests near Flagstaff,
Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   This method involves first thinning out the forests by selective
logging, turning dense woods into pine cluster _ the sort of forest
that used to be the norm a century ago. Such a forest can then be
left, or subjected to limited controlled burns.
</P>
<P>
   Selective logging enjoys the support of the sensibly green
secretary of the interior, Bruce Babbitt, and many scientists.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists, never friendly to anything with the word
logging in it, see it as a scam to help the logging industry (which
would inevitably have to cut down those trees).
</P>
<P>
   This enrages Covington: ``As soon as I advocated tree-thinning,
they immediately assumed I was trying to rape the forest.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the issue has inevitably turned into a battle
between western Republicans (with strong logging-company
connections) and liberal Democrats (with green contributors).
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics of a preservationist elite are driving this
administration's environmental policies,'' says Helen
Chenoweth-Hage of Idaho, a hard-line Republican congresswoman.
</P>
<P>
   On June 30, Republicans pushed through a plan to increase the
government's budget for fighting forest fires to $350 million, with
much of the money going to forest thinning.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats whimpered about their foes exploiting national
disasters. The hot air, it seems, does not blow merely in the
West. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
