<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (UNDATED) _ The growing realism of computer games makes it even
harder for players to tear themselves away from their screens to
attend to their daily lives. For some players, however, the
distraction of having to earn a living may now be a thing of the
past. They have learned to make real money in the imaginary world
of online fantasy games. How did things become so deadly serious? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `BOWLING ALONE': WHAT'S MISSING IN AMERICAN SOCIETY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE-BOWL-ALONE-USA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Americans used to bowl in leagues. Now they bowl
alone. In New London, Conn., they bowl alone while watching giant
television screens, thus further reducing their changes of forming
meaningful social connections. For Harvard political scientist
Robert Putnam, bowling alone is an extended metaphor for much that
ails both modern America and modern Americans. In his ambitious new
book, ``Bowling Alone,'' he argues that while America has recently
witnessed record growth in physical and human capital, its stock of
``social capital'' _ informal social connectedness and formal civic
engagement _ has fallen dangerously low. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Book Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
