<P>
   &UR; TIRED INTERNS SEEK REMEDY FOR OVERWORK, UNDERAPPRECIATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOUNG-DOCS-UNIONIZE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ America's 400 teaching hospitals may not immediately
resemble ``Tom Brown's Schooldays,'' but for young resident
doctors, life at a 19th-century English public school might seem
familiar. Young trainee doctors are expected to work until they
drop, often completing 100-hour weeks; many complain of
mistreatment or harassment. Indeed, senior physicians have enormous
power over a trainee's future career. But pressure for change may
be mounting. &QL;
</P>
