<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 09:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5325 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-EBOOKS-BOLICK-NY     07-07 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-EBOOKS-BOLICK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURLING UP WITH AN E-BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Friday, July 7, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By ROBERT BOLICK    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARIEN, Conn. _ I was reading a good book the other day on the
train home: ``Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of
Crowds.'' Before I knew it, the train was stopping, and I was
scrambling to gather my things to get off. So? So, the book was an
electronic book: I was reading it on a hand-held computer.
</P>
<P>
   Like Elmore Leonard's ``Be Cool'' or ``The Education of Henry
Adams'' or Stephen King's ``Riding the Bullet'' _ all of which I
also read as e-books _ that book had pulled me into its world. It
didn't matter that I was looking at a screen, that I was tapping
and pushing buttons to advance the text in readable chunks; just as
if I were sitting with a good print book and turning pages, nothing
mattered but the magic of the book itself.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year ago, there were only a few thousand e-books,
stored at universities, readable only over the Internet on computer
screens and only as scrolling text. Today, there are tens of
thousands, available across different formats and several devices.
But still, that is not nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of American Publishers has created a task force
for e-book standards, some major publishers are launching e-book
initiatives and almost all of our university presses have
experimented with the technology. One of our key national
booksellers is leading in the selling of e-books. But the sense of
urgency should be greater _ not only for the sake of the book
business, which must adapt to the digital world, but also for
readers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those readers are ready now. When a friend of mine who
works for an e-bookseller told her son's school class about her
job, children waved Gameboys in the air and asked, ``When can we
read our books on these?'' College students and professionals now
spend more time doing research on the Web than in libraries:
e-books are the natural next step.
</P>
<P>
   With e-books, I can carry around 50 pounds of books in a device
weighing a couple of pounds, or have access to vast libraries
wherever I can log on to the Web, or share a good book with a blind
friend because an e-book can be read aloud by software.
</P>
<P>
   And with its possibilities for links to other information, like
reference books and maps, as well as to sound and animated
diagrams, the e-book is a challenge to authors and publishers, as
well as readers, to master words, sense and form in a new way.
</P>
<P>
   To be engrossed in a writer's argument, stumble over a word I
thought I knew and be able to look it up on the page, on the
screen, right there and then, with a movement of thumb and
forefinger _ that speeds my growth as a reader. Or to be able to
seek out the passages that interest me with a search engine rather
than an inadequate or nonexistent index _ that gives me a map of my
own discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Like the personal computer before it, the e-book opens a world
of possibilities. It is not necessarily better than printed books,
nor need it supplant them. But its time is here.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Bolick is a vice president at McGraw-Hill.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
