<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0709-B     07-07 1749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0709-BOX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MIDEAST SUMMIT CALLS FOR CREATIVITY TO AVOID NEW VIOLENCE
 &HT;    800&AMP;add
 &HT;    EDS: Material for a box/graphic is at the bottom of this story
 &HT;    For Sunday, July 9
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Despite doomsday rhetoric as they prepare for
Tuesday's Camp David summit, Israelis and Palestinians are closer
than ever to settling their 52 years of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The peace process is getting creative with proposals that could
navigate around the symbolic issues that have kept the two sides
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Have a problem with Israeli settlers on land previously held by
the Palestinians? A solution might be to have Israel officially
recognize Palestinian sovereignty but lease back land where Jews
now live.
</P>
<P>
   On the nettlesome issue of what to do about Palestinian
refugees, perhaps they could get new homes in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   And the question of whether Israelis or Palestinians should
control Israel? Negotiators could impose overlapping layers of
authority over the holy city, letting both sides claim it as
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, they could add up to $100 billion in international aid for
both sides to make the compromises come easier.
</P>
<P>
   True, these are just ideas for a region that usually defies
simple or even logical solutions. Meanwhile, Israelis and
Palestinians continue preparing the rifles _ and attack helicopters
_ for the street fighting that could follow a summit failure.
</P>
<P>
   Time is running out, making the potential and the risk of this
summit great.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, with fewer than seven months left in office,
cajoled Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to come meet Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak at Camp David. It's Clinton's final
chance to push for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Barak and Arafat are facing a self-imposed Sept. 13
deadline as the end of their negotiating period.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has vowed he will declare statehood then, with or without
Israeli agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He has also said it could come with a new violent uprising. In
response, Israel has threatened to use attack helicopters and
tanks. Already, at a base in the West Bank, troops have practiced
storming the streets of a model Palestinian village.
</P>
<P>
   But, the talks offer hope. Even if they do not produce a
breakthrough in the first week, they could be the first of several
closely timed rounds of meetings aimed at forestalling a violent
fall.
</P>
<P>
   As Israeli columnist Oded Granot(cq) wrote in the Ma'ariv
newspaper last week: ``If peace cannot be achieved by September, at
least get through September in one piece.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the goal is bigger. It is, as Clinton put it this past
week, ``an agreement on the core issues that have fueled a
half-century of conflict between Israelis and Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel steps in as the more powerful party. It has a dominant
army backed by the United States and its soldiers ride patrol in
the disputed land.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have the weight of United Nations resolutions
that say, in broad terms, that occupied land should be returned.
They also have the support of the oil-rich Arab world and the power
to disrupt _ through uprising or protest.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are framed by the Oslo peace process, which began with
an agreement reached in Oslo, Norway. Signed in 1993, it set out a
rough schedule for Israel to withdraw from Palestinian lands in The
Gaza Strip and the West Bank, which Israel captured in 1967. In
return, the Palestinians are supposed to let Israelis live
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Over seven years there have been Palestinian terrorist attacks,
riots and angry anti-Israel rhetoric. Israeli troops have
frequently confiscated Palestinian land and occasionally shot
unarmed Palestinians. But, the process has ground on.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians control most of the Gaza Strip now. About 40
percent of the West Bank, which is home to about 2 million
Palestinians, is under partial or full Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   But, Oslo set aside the toughest issues for the end.
</P>
<P>
   They include questions of who should control Jerusalem, what the
final borders will be between the two sides, what will happen to
the 3.7 million Palestinian refugees and how the region's meager
water supply can be shared. Also, what kind of Palestinian state
should be allowed?
</P>
<P>
   The key to solutions, experts say, is building practical
solutions that have enough conceptual room to let both sides claim
victory before their peoples.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible to find linguistic formulations that will
satisfy both sides,'' said Ron Pundik(cq), one of the original
Israeli architects of the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Rasheed, a Palestinian negotiator, indicated
flexibility last week. Stressing that he was speaking
theoretically, he said if they encounter sacrifices that no Israeli
prime minister could ask of his public, ``We are ready to deal with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The solutions will need to recognize some realities beneficial
to both sides while giving each a symbolic victory.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Jerusalem has been under Israel since 1967 and
Israelis say they will never let it be divided. But the reality is
that 210,000 Palestinians live there in largely segregated areas.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians could get local autonomy for the neighborhoods they
populate and be allowed to fly their flag on their holy sites. They
could put their capital in a suburb that is technically beyond the
Jerusalem border but, to the eye, looks like part of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Life would be the same for Israelis and they could claim overall
control of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians say this is not enough because they should get
absolute sovereignty over their Israeli-occupied areas. But, this
kind of formula could let both sides tell their public that
Jerusalem is theirs.
</P>
<P>
   On borders, Israel has already offered the Palestinians up to 87
percent of the West Bank, though (it) would be transferred over
several years.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part comes with the more than 200,000 Jewish settlers
who Israel has encouraged over the last 30 years to build housing
developments on confiscated Palestinian land.
</P>
<P>
   Barak talks of moving 40,000 settlers back to Israel and
grouping the rest in a few large blocks, already like small cities.
Palestinians reject that and say the West Bank, interpreting U.N.
resolutions, is theirs.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israel could recognize Palestinian ownership of the land,
then agree to lease back the land it needs for settlers. Also,
Israel could compensate the Palestinians with vacant land inside
Israel's borders.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee problem will require money.
</P>
<P>
   There are 3.7 million refugees in Gaza, the West Bank, Jordan,
Syria, Lebanon and elsewhere. They, or their parents, fled what is
now Israel in 1948 and, in some cases, from the West Bank in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians demand the ``right of return'' to Israel, something
that Israel, with just 5 million Jews, will never allow.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israel could agree theoretically to something like a right
of return. Then, it might let a few hundred thousand Palestinians
slowly back into the West Bank. Palestinian officials know that's
about all their struggling economy could handle, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The rest could be compensated with money, better conditions
where they live, or permanent homes in America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed said the Palestinians seek more than $25 billion from
international donors and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   On water, the solution depends on technology. Israel controls
and uses the vast majority of the water and Israelis use far more
per capita than Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But, Oslo architect Pundik said both sides recognize there's not
enough to go around. The region needs better wells, water imports
or costly new water plants. The concept would be to ``increase and
share.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the terms will have to be set out for what kind of
limits might be imposed on a new Palestinian state. For example,
can it have an army or make alliances with Israel's enemies? The
options there are wide.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Arafat and Barak will be able to make a
deal their publics can accept.
</P>
<P>
   Barak promises to put the agreement to a referendum. In the
meantime, members of his own government are defecting and
threatening his term in office just because he is going to the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has promised his people a state with Jerusalem as its
capital _ whether through negotiation or violence. But,
Palestinians appear to be tiring of the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My aim is to get more, but if this is all I can get I will
take it and ask for more,'' Palestinian Nafez Abu Shalbak, 43,
said.
</P>
<P>
   A former Palestinian fighter and prisoner in Israeli jails, Abu
Shalbak now runs a business and drives a Mercedes. ``It might be
the end of the resistance for my generation but the next generation
will continue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peacemakers hope that by the time the Palestinians of the next
generation grow up, they will be accustomed to a peace they can
live with.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kaplow can be e-mailed at: larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Box/Graphic material follows:
</P>
<P>
   KEY ISSUES IN THE CAMP DAVID SUMMIT:
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM: Israel controls it and claims total sovereignty. But,
about 210,000 Palestinians live there and they want a piece for
their capital.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE SOLUTION: Palestinians get partial sovereignty in their
areas and can put their capital just outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS: Palestinians have full or partial control over about 40
percent of the West Bank, but 205,000 Jewish settlers still live on
other areas taken by Israel in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE SOLUTION: Israel recognizes Palestinian rule over the
entire area, but leases back land for settlers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES: Palestinians demand the ``right of return'' for the
3.7 million refugees from Israel and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE SOLUTION: Refugees get some theoretical right to
return, but only a few hundred thousand are let back to the West
Bank. Others get compensation and new homes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WATER: Israel controls most of the region's water and lets its
citizens have more than the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE SOLUTION: Use new technologies or water imports to
increase, then share, the supply.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STATEHOOD: Palestinians want a state, but Israel fears the
development of a Palestinian army and alliances with anti-Israel
countries like Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE SOLUTION: Allow statehood with limits.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT.
