<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-REVOLUTION-0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICANS PINCHING THEMSELVES AS THEY START SECOND REVOLUTION
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (i) International and (k)
commentary categories.
 &HT;    With MEXICO-PRI
 &HT;    For Sunday, July 9
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Stunned observers around the world are calling
Mexico's historic elections the Second Mexican Revolution, Mexico's
Berlin Wall or the Electoral Earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   By any name, what happened on July 2 is more like a dream for
average Mexicans. They're pinching themselves, waking up to the
fact that for the first time in their 500-year modern history - and
after 71 years of the same party in the presidency - they're headed
for a peaceful transition of power from one political force to
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me by surprise. The forces of fraud were gathering,
but in the end, honesty and decency prevailed,'' said Homero
Aridjis, 60, a former ambassador, poet and environmental activist
who voted last Sunday for Vicente Fox Quesada and against Mexico's
Institutional Revolutionary Party, the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned to defeat the PRI,'' Aridjis said. ``And now we all
have to learn how to live in a real democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Fox, who has beefed up his bodyguard detail, is
already facing rumblings of potential difficulties just ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Marginal, rock-wielding PRI supporters upset at losing in local
mayors' races attacked opponents and electoral officials in Mexico
state Wednesday, claiming fraud in those elections.
</P>
<P>
   Among political interest groups, grassroots environmentalists
were the first out the chute, pressuring Fox not to name a
political ally _ the controversial president of Mexico's small
Green Party _ to his cabinet. And the leftist Democratic
Revolutionary Party, which refused to join Fox's coalition, has
implied it could be a thorn in the new president's side.
</P>
<P>
   But since Fox's election as a centrist candidate of change,
Mexicans seem prouder and more confident. Even many voters who were
assumed to be a fountain of PRI support _ such as federal workers _
are also welcoming a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for Fox and so did most of my friends at work. But we
never said we were going to do that openly in our office,'' said
Roberto Torres, 35, a lawyer at the federal Treasury Department.
After Sunday he no longer feared speaking publicly about his
preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support change and I'm not afraid to lose my job now that
Fox has said he wants the best people for the government. I
consider myself capable,'' Torres said, referring to Fox's
ambitious plans to accelerate improvements of Mexico's civil
service and crack down on corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1929, no one in the federal government has ever labored
under an administration other than one run by the PRI. The world's
longest-ruling party until last Sunday, the PRI built up an
infrastructure of inertia or coerced loyalty over the decades by
offering favors to public workers and through unions and other
groups.
</P>
<P>
   That old-fashioned system was already on its knees before the
election. It now appears headed for its deathbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those in Treasury who seem deflated,'' Torres said,
``but that's normal if they were PRI supporters to the core. And to
tell you the truth, some of them aren't that brilliant for the
positions they're in. Maybe they're afraid because they won't fit
the profile of the new government.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox supporter Carolina Galinda, a secretary at the Social
Services Institute for Government Workers, said, ``For me this
change is like the real independence of Mexico. I think even the
PRI will be helped by its defeat and learn to fight cleanly.''
</P>
<P>
   A non-union worker, Galinda said her unionized colleagues were
given extra days off if they agreed to go to PRI rallies.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer at a government food subsidies program said she
supported Fox, too. ``But everybody here thought that (PRI
candidate) Francisco Labastida would win,'' she said, ``I did
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said she still
is afraid of reprisal because there are five more months of PRI
government left. ``Those who supported the PRI are in total pain,''
she said. ``They look like they're in mourning.''
</P>
<P>
   The employee said she was forced by supervisors _ who kept lists
of cooperative employees _ to don a Labastida jacket and cap and
join other government workers passing out election propaganda and
balloons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so degrading,'' she said. ``People would roll their car
windows up. The only people who would take the propaganda were the
poorest people. And after a while even they weren't interested.
Just kids who would take the balloons.''
</P>
<P>
   Since February, she said, the directors of her office had been
withholding raises for the employees. They were so sure that
Labastida would win, she said, that by Monday _ the day after the
election _ the back pay had suddenly appeared in her bank account.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of system has to end now,'' she said. ``This
election was marvelous for Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled public employees were part of a silent majority of
young, middle-class workers in Mexico who took advantage of the
secret ballot and gave Fox a victory margin of roughly seven
percentage points over Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   That was a much higher margin of victory than most professional
American and Mexican pollsters believed Fox would win by, if at
all.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of two privately commissioned polls that went
unpublished in the media here, most surveys showed Fox and
Labastida in a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coercion of the vote worked in some places, but overall it
didn't,'' said Dan Lund of MUND Opinion Services, whose exit
polling revealed that some people who were given traditional PRI
handouts of food or building supplies voted their conscience.
</P>
<P>
   In response to polls, some people declared for the PRI but ended
up being very ambiguous, Lund said. ``We found that in extended
families, there were people who wanted to vote against the PRI. But
they wanted to talk about it with their families and know they
weren't alone.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Lund said, Fox, Mexico's new Congress and
election officials will have to address coercion and vote buying to
achieve truly clean elections. In some of Mexico's poorest southern
states, like Guerrero, Tabasco and Hidalgo, where the regional PRI
remains strong, Lund found a distinct link between votes and
coercion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Federal Elections Institute failed in that regard,'' he
said, ``but where the elections institute had muscle _ the secret
ballot _ it used it beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican broadcast media and some newspapers, Lund pointed
out, took a leap toward independence with this election cycle. But
they still offered biased news coverage more favorable to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials quantified and denounced the bias, but
couldn't do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   But what a difference a day made.
</P>
<P>
   Newscasters are now eager to interview Fox and are effusively
congratulatory. So much so that a popular television comic
performed a sketch pretending to be a newscaster who had donned
black cowboy boots, Fox's trademark, and a silver belt buckle that
said FOX, another trademark of the president-elect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been with you, Vicente,'' comic Adal Ramones
gushed to guffaws from his live audience.
</P>
<P>
   Irreverent political humor on Mexican television is still young
and cautious. Under Fox, it has a chance to take off, just as news
organizations now have an opening to push for freer and more
independent coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Only within the last 10 years have editorial cartoonists
gradually started lampooning Mexican presidents in print.
Television and movies are a final frontier.
</P>
<P>
   After Ramones performed his newscaster sketch last Tuesday, he
called Fox from his set and got him to play straight man. Fox, a
showman himself, sternly hinted that Ramones deserved to be fired.
Then he burst into laughter and congratulated the comic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Constructive criticism accepted,'' Fox said as the audience
went wild and flashed Fox's symbol, the victory sign.
</P>
