<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for
 &UR; SATURDAY, July 8, &LR;  of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-TEST (Washington) _ On a test of the U.S. missile
defense system that is scheduled for Friday night, between 10 p.m.
and 2 a.m. EDT. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-REPARATIONS (United Nations) _ An independent panel
assembled by the Organization of African Unity said Friday that a
``significant level of reparations'' should be paid to Rwanda by
nations and institutions that failed to prevent or stop the 1994
genocide that killed up to 800,000 people. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BANK-CHINA (Washington) _ The World Bank is scheduled
Friday to vote on a $40 million loan to China that would involve
relocating 58,000 farmers to land that is traditionally used by
Tibetan herders. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-ISRAEL (Geneva) _ Switzerland's highest court sentenced a
confessed Israeli spy Friday to a one-year suspended prison
sentence for his role in a bungled 1998 wiretap attempt by the
Mossad secret service. By Elizabeth Olson.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _ General
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ABORTION (Austin, Texas) _ There's little doubt that the
next president will have a major role in shaping the make-up and
prevailing attitudes of the Supreme Court. Republicans expect, and
Democrats fear, that Gov. George W. Bush will use his appointments
to the court to restrict women's access to abortion. But if his
appointments to the Texas Supreme Court are any indication, those
expectations may not be fulfilled. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `p' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA-MISSING-EDITOR (Negril, Jamaica) _ Frederick and Mary
Ann Kirschhoch have made two trips to Jamaica, where their
daughter, a travel editor, vanished around May 27. They came
because they believed they could describe their daughter to
Jamaicans in a way that only parents could. By Edward Wong.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOLICS-MODERATION (Seattle, Wash.) _ After she founded a
self-help program called Moderation Management seven years ago,
Audrey Kishline became a national spokeswoman for the notion that
problem drinkers could be taught to cut back without abstaining
altogether. Having recently pleaded guilty to two counts of
vehicular homicide after a binge drinking episode last March,
Kishline said through her lawyer that she has a new message:
Moderation Management ``is nothing but alcoholics covering up their
problem.'' By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BANK-RUSSIA (Washington) _ The World Bank says that an
internal investigation has found no proof that a former Russian
official passed confidential information to a Russian bank in 1993.
By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Just 11,000 jobs were created in June,
much fewer than expected and the smallest increase in four years,
in the latest sign that the U.S. economy is slowing. By Louis
Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   SEASIA-ECON (Singapore) _ Despite Southeast Asia's economic
recovery from the crisis that began three years ago this month,
foreign investors have been dumping stocks and currencies from the
region. Its markets this year are the worst-performing in the
world, having dropped more than 22 percent on average. By Wayne
Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (This article was scheduled yesterday but later eliminated.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   WAR-CRIMES-DEFINED (Undated) _ From the grisly amputations of
the hands of innocents in Sierra Leone to the systematic sexual
abuse of women in Bosnia and Rwanda _ or, some would say, to the
bombing of Kosovo refugees by NATO war planes _ modern conflicts
raise new and complex issues. There still is not total agreement on
universally accepted moral codes. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move with an ``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WRITING-FOR-KIDS (Undated) _ As those who do it best have
testified, writing well for children is, first and last, very
difficult. And as memoirs and biographies have shown, the great
children's works have often been the products of personal
difficulty and stress, a distillation in narrative form of
anguished experience. By Eden Ross Lipson.
</P>
<P>
   GUERNICA-DOCUMENTARY (Guernica, Spain) _ It's hard to imagine
the scene as it was here some 60 years ago, when one of the first
major atrocities of World War II took place. A new documentary
film, ``The Bombing of Guernica: The Mark of Men,'' produced by a
peace research center here, includes the voices of the people who
survived the Luftwaffe attack. By Herbert Mitgang.
</P>
