<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEMORIAL (San Francisco) _ The late civil rights leader Mike
Masaoka wrote in 1940 about how much he loved America. Now he has
become the focus of a seething controversy over a national monument
that will carry his name and the words he wrote long ago. He is
among seven individuals _ including former Rep. Norman Mineta,
D-Calif., commerce secretary-designate _ whose quotations will
grace the $11 million National Japanese American Memorial to
Patriotism, which will be dedicated in Washington, D.C., on Nov. 9.
By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (San Francisco) _ Los Angeles and San Francisco
continue to be among the top 10 locations in the world with the
highest known breast cancer rates. Yet health officials won't be
able to reverse the increase until they find the causes, experts
agree at an environmental health forum here. They say the missing
link is a national database that would allow tracking of chronic
diseases to environmental factors such as air pollution,
pesticides, plastics and household chemicals. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITALS (San Francisco) _ Unionized workers at 10 area
hospitals return to work after a 24-hour strike that inconvenienced
administrators and some patients and their families, drew attention
to labor's concerns and caused no serious health problems. By CAROL
NESS and PIA SACKAR.
</P>
<P>
   SF-WHARF (San Francisco) The developer of a revamped Fisherman's
Wharf project is mounting an aggressive campaign to win community
and political support. He is changing the name of the project and
scrapping plans for faux fog. Gone is the original name ``San
Francisco at the Wharf.'' Its new moniker: ``The San Francisco
Interactive History Museum.'' By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR-RILEY (Albany, N.Y.) _ If there's such a thing as civic
plagiarism, Joseph P. Riley Jr., the six-term mayor of Charleston,
S.C., and architect of the city's downtown revitalization, did
nothing on a recent visit here to discourage it. And the mayors of
Albany, Troy and Cohoes, N.Y. seemed to be on the same page with
Riley, whose philosophy is that beautiful urban design is the way
to revive dying downtowns. By PAUL GRONDAHL. (For release Sunday.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SWINGING-NUN (Altamont, N.Y.) _ To help her fellow golfers see
spirituality in everything from a missed putt to a hole-in-one,
Dominican Sister Dorothy Ederer has written ``A Golfer's Day with
the Master: Spiritual Wisdom From the Fairway.'' According to
Ederer, golf is ``a great time to really listen to God.'' By THEOLA
S. LABBE.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES (Brimfield, Mass.) _ This week the Brimfield Outdoor
Antique and Collectible Show opens with more than 4,000 dealers in
tents spread out over 22 fields along a mile-plus stretch of Route
20, Brimfield's main thoroughfare. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HINES. (For
Sunday release.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-BIG-BROTHER (Undated) _ After the success of ``Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire'' last summer on ABC, all the networks broke their
ankles leaping aboard the bandwagon by putting on game shows of
their own. But they missed the point. We wanted contestants, yes,
but we craved the real-life drama. We wanted reality and we still
wanted game shows. Put them together and we go nuts. By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SCARY (Undated) _ In ``Scary Movie,'' director
Keenen Ivory Wayans and two of his brothers, Shawn and Marlon
Wayans, blend the elements from recent rude comedy hits, horror
spoofs and other popular pictures to create the raunchiest movie of
the summer. Also, one of the funniest. By MIKE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-THEKID (Undated) _ In what will stand as the middle
flick in the unofficial yet-to-be-completed Bruce
Willis-and-small-metaphysically-gifted-boy trilogy, ``The Kid''
follows the ``The Sixth Sense,'' pitting Willis against another
problem child. This time the boy has wandered into Willis' fortress
of solitude from his childhood, and captures his heart in the
process. Since the film is Disney's ``The Kid,'' look out that he
doesn't walk off with yours as well. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOT-COM-POLL (San Francisco) _ Americans are wildly enthusiastic
about the future of Internet companies. Just don't ask them to put
their money where their mouth is. So says a survey by Scudder
Kemper Investments, Inc., a Boston-based financial firm that polled
2,900 Americans to gauge their confidence in the new economy. While
71 percent of Americans believe the CEOs of Internet companies can
run a successful company, 65 percent of them say they haven't even
considered putting aside money for riskier technology or dot-com
investments. By ALAN T. SARASEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   SECURITIES-FRAUD (San Francisco) _ An investment manager has
pleaded guilty to securities fraud in the operation of a hedge fund
that allegedly cost his investors nearly $7 million. Michael
Timothy Higgins, 36, of San Anselmo, Calif., admitted that he lied
about the performance of Ballybunion Capital Partners and provided
false documents to lure investors between November 1998 and April
of this year. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I'm a ``Survivor'' survivor. In
fact, I love the show. I love all those shows, in this summer of
televoyeurism. What is television but voyeurism, and what is much
of life? By ROB MORSE.
</P>
