<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, July 8 and Sunday, July 9,
2000 are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ A friend sent me a list called ``Tips for a
Lifetime.'' Most of these tips, although useful, would be more
appropriate for someone who ran a Martha Stewart-styled household.
That's not me. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVEDMINTER-COLUMN _
Our cousin, Don Harp, is a preacher. He knows exactly what to say
when a family member crosses the Jordan. One of the things he
pointed out at Aunt Ida Mae's funeral was that we are running out
of what Tom Brokaw and a lot of us think of as The Greatest
Generation. ``Who among us is going to take their place?'' Don
asked. It is a worrisome question. (Minter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Mary Ann Wietze, the beloved principal at Helke
Elementary School, died June 23, at 67, from cancer, at her home in
West Milton. But her presence will continue to be felt at the
Vandalia-Butler school that she ran with high spirits and high
expectations. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The big winner in the Mexican election was
Mexico itself, but the hero of the election was not the successful
presidential candidate, Vicente Fox. It was the outgoing president,
Ernesto Zedillo, whose party's nominee got walloped. (Tom Teepen is
national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ With each passing day, we are exposed to
newer and more imaginative forms of political correctness. It is
obvious that there are no bounds, no time limits. Last week, the
Hartford Courant, the nation's longest continuously published daily
newspaper, apologized in a front page story for accepting
advertising from 1764 until 1823 for the sale of slaves and the
capture of runaways.(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY
FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ TV broadcasters have reneged on their pledge to
Congress and the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to roll
out high-definition TV (HDTV) by the middle of the decade. They've
come with another idea on how to use the free public spectrum,
allotted for HDTV broadcasts and worth tens of billions of dollars.
(Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington
bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
