<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Principal's legacy will linger on
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The wooden plaque on Mary Ann Wietzel's desk at
Helke Elementary School summed up her philosophy as principal:
``Let them be children first.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that meant she had to be a child too _ rolling up her
trousers to wade in the stream, leading nature walks at Aullwood
Audubon Center _ then so be it.
</P>
<P>
   If that meant staying up late into the night, writing grant
proposals so students could experience ballet, the symphony,
puppetry, all the riotous variety of the arts, then so be it.
</P>
<P>
   If that meant baby pigs visited story hour at the library _
creating pandemonium when they made their escape during a reading
of Charlotte's Web, then so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to get them back in the pen now, won't we?'' Ms.
Wietzel said calmly, recruiting students to corral the renegade
swine.
</P>
<P>
   The beloved principal died June 23, at 67, from cancer, at her
home in West Milton. But her presence will continue to be felt at
the Vandalia-Butler school that she ran with high spirits and high
expectations. ``She wanted them to experience things in that
innocent naive way children can, and grasp it all,'' said Karla
Brooks, who worked with Ms. Wietzel for many years as a media aide
_ or ``storyteller,'' as she prefers to call it, in the school
library. ``She encouraged children to get messy, to get out and
play in the grass and take it all in.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalls interim principal Diane Lileas, ``If a teacher was
conducting a stream study, Mary Ann would be right there with her,
pant legs rolled up, testing the water with her kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wietzel wanted them to experience the wonders of nature
through Aullwood Audubon Center, a living laboratory in Helke's
back yard. Ms. Wietzel worked tirelessly to create community
sponsors _ the PTA and VFW Post 9582 _ to enable students to
participate in all-day ``Aullwood Adventures'' at least twice a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Each kindergarten class planted a class tree and watched it
grow. Each student brought home a sapling on Earth Day. The effect
was far greater than a once-a-year-field, notes first-grade teacher
Sherry Hartings: ``It was carried through from one year to the
next, so love of nature was instilled in them.''
</P>
<P>
   How fitting, then, that Ms. Wietzel's memorial service will be
held tomorrow at Aullwood Audubon Center. A nature walk will follow
the 10 a.m. service.
</P>
<P>
   What better place to reflect on Ms. Wietzel's legacy? Think of
the generations of children who will be enriched by the time they
spent here.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place to learn about the world's natural beauties, to
develop an affinity for nature, the environment. It's a place to
explore, to learn about prairie grasses and owls, to make homemade
candles, tap trees for maple syrup.
</P>
<P>
   It's a world remote from computer games and cable channels, a
timeless place where their ``schedule'' consists of nothing more
complicated than riding in a horse-drawn wagon on bundles of hay,
listening to an owl screech, or savoring the glint of sunlight
through a canopy of leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is going to be missed; it's not going to be an easy start
to the school year,'' Lileas said. ``Mary Ann was a person who
touched everybody's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking around the school building she adds, ``You can see her
in everything that's here.''
</P>
<P>
   That will continue to be true, one suspects, as long as Helke
remains a place where children can be children first.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
