<HEADER>
A5362 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN08-COX     07-07 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The greatest: 'Who among us is going to take their place?'
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We gathered at a little Methodist church, as we have too often
in recent years, to say goodbye to our Aunt Ida Mae, who would have
celebrated her 93rd birthday on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   We are fortunate in funerals. Our cousin, Don Harp, is a
preacher. He knows exactly what to say when a family member crosses
the Jordan. One of the things he pointed out at Aunt Ida Mae's
funeral was that we are running out of what Tom Brokaw and a lot of
us think of as The Greatest Generation. ``Who among us is going to
take their place?'' Don asked. It is a worrisome question.
</P>
<P>
   He eulogized Aunt Ida Mae as one of the great women of our
little community, who, like Dorcas in the Bible, did good things.
One thing she did, besides teaching me to read the newspaper, was
teach a Sunday school class.
</P>
<P>
   We had only two youth classes. Lacking rooms in the church, one
met in Uncle Walter Burch's 1941 Ford, the other in Aunt Ida Mae's
Studebaker. Don said the first building program was when Aunt Ida
Mae and Uncle Welden traded their Studebaker for a Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing he said was each of us ought to call or drop a
note of appreciation to the men and women who fought World War II
for us.
</P>
<P>
   His reminder brought back one of my most vivid memories of WWII,
which for a teenager at home was mostly headlines in the newspaper
and saving tinfoil to be recycled into airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   This Methodist church stands on the very site of Mr. Marvin
Lamb's general store. When Gray Burch, one of the family of cousins
I consider the embodiment of The Greatest Generation, was in pilot
training he wrote home that he would circle Mr. Marvin's store at a
certain time on a certain afternoon. We of the home front gathered
at the appointed hour.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 o'clock we heard the roar of motors. A huge B-25 bomber in
dusky war paint appeared out of the northern sky. The bomber flew
low, tilted so that we could see into the cockpit, made two
circles, then leveled out and flew south toward Woolsey, passing
over the Reeves' house and the Burch homeplace.
</P>
<P>
   Gray went on to the Pacific, flew missions, was wounded and came
home to raise a fine family and enjoy a productive life. He never
had complaints or developed a neurosis.
</P>
<P>
   Walking out of the church after Aunt Ida Mae's funeral I
realized we were standing on the exact spot I had stood more than
50 years ago waiting for Gray to fly over in his bomber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray,'' I said, ``do you remember an afternoon when a big
bomber came out of the sky and circled over Inman?''
</P>
<P>
   He grinned. ``I sure do. You know what I remember? I remember
how the chickens scattered.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed since 1942. We no longer have yard chickens for
a low-flying B-25 to scatter. I hope things haven't changed so much
that we've forgotten the values The Greatest Generation took to war
and then brought home.
</P>
<P>
   I was remiss on personally thanking veterans on July 4, as
Cousin Don suggested. But I can tell you what I am going to do.
There is a presidential election coming up, and I'm going to try to
thank the veterans of World War II, of Korea and Vietnam and the
Gulf, in the best way I can. I'm going to cast my vote for the
candidate most likely to see to it that our military is strong
enough so that our children, as General Eisenhower said on a visit
to the American cemetery in Normandy, will never again be called
upon for such sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good time to remember the summer of 1950 when young
Americans, unprepared and underequipped, were sent piecemeal to be
butchered by a Communist juggernaut pouring into South Korea. It
was a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Colin Powell crying into the wilderness, nobody seems
to notice that once again the nation's military is being neglected.
The prosperity we enjoy is bought partly at the expense of the men
and women in our armed services.
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War is over, we hear. All that's needed is a police
force to show up, here and there, now and then. I wouldn't bet on
it. Look around. The world is still a dangerous place.
</P>
<P>
   These are prosperous, carefree times. Never have so many had so
much. This would not be so if young Americans had not been willing
to do what they were asked to do in defense of freedom here and
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In this election year the best way we can show our appreciation
is to seriously examine issues and candidates, and then cast our
votes as close as we can to the values that made their generation a
national treasure.
</P>
<P>
   To contact Jim Minter, write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, 692 N. Glynn St., Suite A, Fayetteville, GA
30214.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
