<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friend's list of helpful household pointers not relevant in this
case
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend sent me a list called ``Tips for a Lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   I've read the list carefully trying to pick up on the message
that applies to me. I don't see it.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these tips, although useful, would be more appropriate
for someone who ran a Martha Stewart-styled household. That's not
me.
</P>
<P>
   My three-bedroom house is used to store motorcycle gear. One
bedroom is used for street riding gear. Another is used for race
gear. The one I sleep in holds touring gear.
</P>
<P>
   A long wrap-around sofa in the living room holds helmets, gloves
and miscellaneous gear that I grab last before going out the back
door.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one place to sit at the far end of the sofa next
to a reading lamp where I can easily reach for stacks of motorcycle
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Similar stacks of motorcycle magazines are in both bathrooms and
beside the half of the king-sized bed where I sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the bed, as well as a nearby bedroom sofa, is
a staging area for packing for motorcycle weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The den, which is a converted garage, is filled with motorcycle
parts, tools, tires and other equipment used on two roadracing
bikes, one dirt track bike, one street bike and a d mall.
</P>
<P>
   My tip is better. Eat ice cream out of the container it came in.
There's no need for sugar cones or miniature marshmallows. Avoid
malls.
</P>
<P>
   Another tip from the ``Tips for a Lifetime'' list suggests using
a meat baster to ``squeeze'' your pancake batter onto the hot
griddle _ ``perfect shaped pancakes every time.''
</P>
<P>
   If you have friends who think less of you because your pancakes
aren't perfectly shaped, you need to get new friends. Besides, if
you want a perfectly shaped pancake all you have to do is pour
enough batter in the skillet to cover the entire pan.
</P>
<P>
   ``To determine whether an egg is fresh, immerse it in a pan of
cool, salted water. If it sinks, it is fresh. If it rises to the
surface, throw it away,'' suggests my ``Tips for a Lifetime'' list.
</P>
<P>
   That's interesting _ if it's true. Since I've had little trouble
in my lifetime with rotten eggs that I bought at a grocery store
and stored in my refrigerator, this suggestion appears to be a lot
of unnecessary work.
</P>
<P>
   I crack eggs into a skillet. If one stinks, it isn't fresh.
Scrape it into the garbage disposal. If the next two or three also
are rotten, take the rest of the eggs outside and throw them at a
tree or other targets of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't throw out all that leftover wine: Freeze it into ice
cubes for future use in casseroles and sauces,'' suggests the
``Tips for a Lifetime'' list.
</P>
<P>
   What leftover wine? Just when you think you've heard it all,
you're hit with a brand new concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a splinter, reach for the Scotch tape before
resorting to tweezers or a needle. Simply put the Scotch tape over
the splinter, then pull it off. Scotch tape removes most splinters
painlessly and easily,'' suggests the ``Tips for a Lifetime'' list.
</P>
<P>
   That's a handy tip. If Scotch tape works on most splinters, duct
tape should work on all splinters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep rolls of duct tape with you at all times.'' That's my tip
for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the Senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
