<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5373 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-07 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BIG BROTHER IS WATCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I'm a ``Survivor'' survivor. In fact, I love the
show.
</P>
<P>
   I love all those shows, in this summer of televoyeurism. What is
television but voyeurism, and what is much of life?
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who follow national politics, for example, aren't
interested in Al Gore's ideas about pharmaceutical companies or
George W. Bush's education plan.
</P>
<P>
   We're waiting to see them fall on their faces (maybe literally,
like that young guy running against Hillary), say dumb things, get
caught with their hands in naughty places _ and then have to eat
something much worse than rat meat but found abundantly in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Voting them out of the political jungle is an afterthought, and
we make odd choices.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Clinton. Sometimes the most egregious character is the
prize-winning survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead. Vote me out of the profession. I'm the last columnist
in America to make strained ``Survivor'' comparisons, and I never
wrote about Darva at all.
</P>
<P>
   I've been out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   Although filled with obnoxious slackers, yuppies and corporate
trainers not native to the island of Pulau Tiga, ``Survivor'' is
supposed to be exotic escapism. Sometimes it seems uncomfortably
close to real life.
</P>
<P>
   The premiere of CBS's ``Big Brother'' was on after ``Survivor''
Wednesday night, and it should be a great show. There are dozens of
cameras in the house to follow the lives of the contestants, and
all the contestants they introduced seemed like real jerks, except
for the New York guy with one leg.
</P>
<P>
   I can't wait to see how he takes a shower or how long the beauty
queen takes to put on her makeup, and whether their bathroom time
gets them kicked out of the house. You know that chubby mini-golf
fan will be heading back to his chubby family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' is wish fulfillment for young people who live in
expensive places, where they have to share apartments with a
half-dozen people. It's great to watch jerks get the boot _ one
deviation from reality.
</P>
<P>
   Voyeurism, we love to watch it. In some ways, it's even better
than voyeurism itself.
</P>
<P>
   We love to watch Springer's audience egging on grappling
transvestites. We love the sight of special prosecutors
transcribing every gruesome detail of a president's love affair. We
love watching idiots watch each other on islands and in bugged
houses, while they make nasty comments about each other.
</P>
<P>
   The unanswered questions are so alluring. Who's boinking whom?
Was that really dog food they ate from the can? Where'd they get
that green pepper? Where do they go on that island to poo?
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' has a camera over the can, but the pompous host
(who calls everyone ``my friend,'' when no one is anyone's friend)
says it won't be turned on unless contestants start holding
conferences in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holding conferences'' in the bathroom _ I want to see that on
a family network.
</P>
<P>
   In typical form, PBS has offered up a costume drama version of
``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother.'' The British ``1900 House'' shows
a middle-class family living with the same discomforts, lack of
amenities and confining clothing as typical British families had
100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This show, almost as hyped as ``Survivor,'' is billed as
educational, but come on. It's like PBS's ``Antiques Road Show.''
You don't tune in for education, but to see people with pained
looks on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Antiques Road Show,'' they're pained because they're stuck
with old junk. The people on ``1900 Show'' are stuck in old junk.
</P>
<P>
   The most memorable moments, of course, concerned the gruesome
details of the lady of the house's undergarments. But the thing
about living 1900-style that drove the women craziest was the fact
that they had to wash their hair with some kind of soap goo.
</P>
<P>
   The hell with getting the vote. Getting shampoo was more
liberating for women, and getting vacuum cleaners a close second.
</P>
<P>
   That's the educational message of ``1900 House,'' as far as I
can see. Strange how the man of the family seemed to love living in
1900.
</P>
<P>
   One thing missing from ``1900 House,'' though. Neighbors. There
were no 1900 neighbors to have to tea and talk about later, and no
1900 neighbors to watch while they played Lady Chatterly with the
gardener.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't have TV then. They had to take their voyeurism
straight, or well, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   One of the objects found in my great-aunt Blanche's 1900 house
in Maine, and passed down to me, was a pair of antique U.S. Army
binoculars she used to see which of her husband's employees was
visiting the liquor store.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't get kicked off a show. They got booted from their
jobs at the lumber mill.
</P>
<P>
   You really had to be tough to survive back then, and Big Aunt
was watching. Times haven't changed, just channels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1233EDT &QL; 
