<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-SWINGING-NUN-HNS &LR;      07-07 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINGING-NUN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SWINGING NUN MIXES NINE IRONS WITH THE TEN COMMANDMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By THEOLA S. LABBE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTAMONT, N.Y. _ Dominican Sister Dorothy Ederer doesn't sing,
she swings.
</P>
<P>
   To help her fellow golfers see spirituality in everything from a
missed putt to a hole-in-one, the swinging nun has written ``A
Golfer's Day with the Master: Spiritual Wisdom From the Fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Ederer, co-director of the Altamont-based Joshua
Foundation, which offers retreats that focus on bringing out the
relevance of the Gospel in everyday life, golf is ``a great time to
really listen to God.''
</P>
<P>
   While other sports may have hustle and bustle, ``in golf you
have to be quiet when the other person is teeing off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And what might a golfer ponder when stepping up to the tee? Try
Psalm 16:7-11, which Ederer calls the Prayer Against Opponents,
where a player can ask God for guidance ``along a crooked fairway''
and protection against brand-new balls sinking into muddy waters.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the Ten Commandments for Golfers, such as, ``Thou
shall not covet thy neighbor's golf sweaters,'' and using God's
name only to praise. Another section of the book, Beatitudes for
the Golfer, offers lighthearted ways of looking at the ups and
downs of the game. In the book's Personal Reflections section,
Ederer uses game terms like handicap, dogleg, and sand trap to
teach life lessons that can be applied on and off the greens.
</P>
<P>
   Ederer started playing golf a few years ago after two knee
surgeries forced her to give up racquetball. She was working as a
campus minister at Western Michigan University and took lessons
from a golf pro in her parish. After getting a set of clubs for
Christmas, she started playing golf three days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I became addicted,'' she said. The idea to bring
God and golf together came to Ederer years later as a vision in the
middle of the night, when she reflected on Psalm 139 and turned it
into a psalm for a golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not rewriting Scripture,'' noted Ederer, who said she
shared her work with her brother, a priest, and he gave the idea a
hearty thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Ederer said she put together homemade copies of her
writings and gave them to friends as Christmas gifts. But demand
and interest grew so quickly that Ederer found herself filling book
orders for a book that, at the time, did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Ederer, a previously published author, already had an agent, so
when she mentioned the golf book to him, ``He thought it was a
great idea,'' she said. Doubleday, which published the book in May,
also published Ederer's ``Colors of the Spirit'' in 1998, which has
sold about 8,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   The golf book costs $15.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Corbin, a Doubleday editor, described Ederer as a
practical writer who gives people spiritual ideas to think about
``in concrete circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Ederer, who now is working on a third book about how God brings
surprises into our lives, said her latest book probably will not
improve someone's golf game, but that wasn't her goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is for people to stop and think about God more,'' she
said. ``Even when you can't get on the golf course, you can pick it
up and read it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
