<SLUG> BC-TV-BIG-BROTHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOW TO BE A NETWORK SURVIVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television executives have a very simple blueprint for
programming, if not successful programming:
</P>
<P>
   Step One: Milk every last laugh, tear and cent out of
conveyor-belt dramas and sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   Step Two: When the critical yammering gets too loud, throw
something on of value and distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Step Three: Yank it after three weeks if the numbers aren't
there (two weeks if it's set in a mental hospital). Practice shrug
and pained expression in front of mirror before going out to
explain this decision.
</P>
<P>
   Step Four: See what's working in Britain, or Sweden, or Belgium,
or all those other countries that think Jerry Lewis is funny.
</P>
<P>
   Step Five: Steal it, Americanize it, promote the hell out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Step Six: If the other guy gets it first, copy it to death.
</P>
<P>
   Step Seven: When your facsimile of the facsimile fails
miserably, write it off the whole genre as a passing fad.
</P>
<P>
   Step Eight: Repeat Step One.
</P>
<P>
   After the success of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' last
summer on ABC, all the networks broke their ankles leaping aboard
the bandwagon by putting on game shows of their own. But they
missed the point.
</P>
<P>
   We wanted contestants, yes, but we craved the real-life drama _
or at least manufactured real-life drama. We wanted reality, and we
still wanted game shows.
</P>
<P>
   Put them together and we go nuts. Proving the enduring appeal of
backstabbing and rodent cuisine, ``Survivor'' has been this
summer's megahit, outpacing even ``Millionaire'' (often in reruns).
This week, ``Survivor'' got a brother in arms.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the castaway contest was teamed on CBS with ``Big
Brother,'' a voyeurfest in which 10 strangers are locked in a house
with each other as cameras record every move for both television
and the Internet (http://www.bigbrother2000.com). Last one standing
after the others are voted out by viewers wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' airs at 8 p.m. five times a week (taking off
Sundays and Wednesdays.) Between this and ``Survivor,'' you'll be
left with little time for your own reality. Depending on who you
are, that might be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, reality shows are just a blurred, manufactured
parallel to real life. Where things get really blurry is when the
CBS newsfolks, both at the network and the local levels, get into
the game by promoting the shows during newscasts. It is inevitably
wrong as is it inevitable in the infotainment era.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no place to hide,'' ``Big Brother'' host
Julie Chen intoned Wednesday night. How right she is: Chen
moonlights as a CBS morning news anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Stick with the day job, Julie. Normally, I have a high threshold
for news-entertainment crossover, but this blatant self-promotion
is just unseemly. Maybe it's because it's done without any trace of
guilt or shame.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Millionaire'' and ``Survivor,'' ``Big Brother'' was
stolen from Europe. (During this patriotic season, let's remember
that the ultimate American sitcom, ``All in the Family,'' was in
fact a remake of the British comedy ``Till Death Do Us Part.'')
</P>
<P>
   Their other common element is that all these shows allow us to
become couch participants, virtual contestants who watch them
either vicariously and/or with a sense of superiority.
</P>
<P>
   There's the ``What would I do?'' factor: Would I have the guts
to ride a motorcycle through a ring of fire? Would I jump into the
bear den to save a fallen child? Would I really think that a rat
cooked over an open flame tastes like chicken?
</P>
<P>
   Or we sit back with a ``what a moron'' smirk as we watch people
who were stupid or desperate enough to make fools of themselves on
national television. No, we wouldn't give lip to a cop when there's
a camera peering over his shoulder. No, we wouldn't eat beetle
larvae. No, we wouldn't cheat on our cousin-girlfriend with her
father's dentist. And c'mon, Regis: Everybody knows the democracy
with the biggest population is India.
</P>
<P>
   More reality is coming, even to sitcoms: In the new CBS comedy
``Bette,'' Bette Midler is essentially playing herself. But this is
not the death of drama or comedies; like the cockroach, they will
survive television Armageddonor ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire II,'' whichever comes first. Remember, it was the
news magazine that was squeezing dramas and sitcoms off the air.
But, like all ``next big things,'' this will eventually fade, and
everyone will be back to Step One.
</P>
<P>
   A final thought on a show that should have worked, but didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Extreme: When Things Go Wrong'' had everything. Disasters.
Crashes. Mayhem. The word ``extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem: Nobody dies, gets it, takes a dirt nap.
</P>
<P>
   Now, is that reality?
</P>
<P>
   The show didn't get picked up by enough stations, and it appears
it won't make the air. Serves 'em right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
