<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT-COM-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLL SHOWS CONCERN ABOUT INVESTING IN TECH COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Americans are wildly enthusiastic about the
future of Internet companies. Just don't ask them to put their
money where their mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   So says a survey released by Scudder Kemper Investments Inc. of
Boston, which polled 2,900 Americans to gauge their confidence in
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   While 71 percent of those surveyed said they believe Internet
executives are ``smart and well-educated individuals who can run a
successful company and succeed for their investors,'' 65 percent of
those polled said they have shied away from technology or Internet
investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting. There are some real contradictions between
perception and behaviors,'' said Dianne Michael, a spokeswoman for
Scudder Kemper, an investment company. ``It's clear investors are
bullish on Internet stocks and digital investing. They feel Net
companies will be the largest and most influential in the future.
But, they are still reluctant to invest outright in technology
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey, sponsored by Scudder Kemper, was conducted following
the mid-spring drop in technology stock prices, which could explain
why investors were hesitant. Dot-com riches are still fresh in
their memories, said Michael, and so are dot-com disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other findings of the survey:
</P>
<P>
   _ Nearly four in five Americans do not think executives of
Internet companies are ``too young and inexperienced to lead and
safeguard investors' money.''
</P>
<P>
   _ More than half of those surveyed (52 percent) do not think it
is foolish to invest in Internet and technology companies that have
not made a profit.
</P>
<P>
   _ While 59 percent express concern that the U.S. economy may not
be quite as healthy as it appears, 71 percent do not believe that
the bottom is going to fall out of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The rich remain bullish. Of those surveyed with an annual
income exceeding $100,000 per year, 60 percent chose the statement,
``The economy is strong and will remain healthy'' over ``The
economy appears strong, but underneath it's not as healthy as it
looks.'' In contrast, fewer than half of middle-income Americans
and only one-quarter of those with household incomes below $36,000
had such a positive outlook.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
