<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of MON., JULY 10, 2000,
and anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OXYGEN-MISCARRIAGE-LINK-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIFE OR DEATH. Too much oxygen may be the key to many
miscarriages. According to a team of British researchers, a sudden
surge in oxygen levels reaching the fetus in the first trimester of
pregnancy may help explain why one in six pregnancies come to a
premature end.
</P>
<P>
   WEST-NILE-HITS-USA-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEWARE THE BIRDS. West Nile virus, the deadly disease that
killed seven New Yorkers last year, has now spread to birds in all
corners of the Americas. U.S. researchers warn that if enough birds
catch the virus it will eventually reach humans. Despite the
warning, proposals to screen birds have not yet been funded.
</P>
<P>
   MIND-GHOSTS-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIND PHANTOMS. There's nothing supernatural about out-of-body
experiences or even ghosts. A Swiss neuroscientist says that when
people see their body from the outside, they are seeing their
phantom ``double'' as a result of damage to visual areas of the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-SURFING-PARROT-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GIVE THAT BIRD A MOUSE. Arthur is learning to surf the web,
which is no mean feat nowadays for a normal four-year old _ but it
is if you're a parrot. Arthur's owner believes that by teaching
Arthur how to use the Internet they could liberate thousands of
captive parrots and other pets from a life of boredom.
</P>
</TEXT>
