<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SURPLUS-$ADV09-COX     07-07 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURPLUS-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT THE SURPLUS BALL, FEW THINKING ABOUT MIDNIGHT
 &HT;    With SURPLUS-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, July 9.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's Cinderella economy has turned a fairy
tale into reality: Washington is taking in money faster than
politicians can spend it.
</P>
<P>
   But the country's glittering coach of budget surpluses could
turn back into a deficit pumpkin, some analysts say, if new plans
for federal spending and tax cuts collide with an economic
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   For now, everyone's focused on happy endings. Within a week or
so, the Congressional Budget Office will raise, once again, its
projections for future budget surpluses, already $4.2 trillion over
the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even setting aside Social Security revenues, the White House
foresees surpluses totaling $1.9 trillion _ that's an entire year's
worth of federal spending _ in the decade to come.
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton and his Republican adversaries in
Congress have both claimed credit for balancing the federal books
for the first time in a generation, the true slayer of the deficit
dragon has been the dazzling economy.
</P>
<P>
   Showing unprecedented strength beyond all forecasts, it is now
hurtling through its tenth consecutive year of investment-led
growth stretching back to March 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Far from losing steam, the economy grew at an inflation-adjusted
annual rate of 5.4 percent during the first three months of this
year, following a blistering 7.3 percent rate in the fourth quarter
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters, both government and private, believe the country's
economic metabolism has sped up, placing growth on a permanently
higher plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the long run, we think that the economy can grow faster
than in the past,'' said Gerald Cohen, senior economist with the
New York investment firm, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1973 and 1995, said Cohen, economic growth averaged
between 2.5 percent and 3 percent a year. Looking forward, he said,
Merrill Lynch projects growth rates averaging between 3.5 percent
and 4 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is huge. A swing in growth rates of one
percentage point is worth $99 billion in economic output.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, in its midyear review of budget data, the White
House projected that economic output would swell to a breathtaking
$16.1 trillion by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   That represents growth averaging about 3 percent a year, after
adjusting for inflation. That's nearly half a percentage point
higher than White House aides expected last February, when Clinton
submitted the 2001 budget proposals currently making their way
through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy has been stronger over the last six months than
appeared likely in the late fall, when the budget was forecast,''
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers explained to reporters in
releasing the administration's midyear review of budget data.
</P>
<P>
   That means ``substantially more revenues this year and a higher
jumping-off point for future growth,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   A large pie yields large slices.
</P>
<P>
   For every dollar of activity the economy generates, the federal
government takes in 20 cents. That means taxpayers will pour a
projected $27 trillion into the U.S. Treasury over the coming
decade, the White House reckons.
</P>
<P>
   That's a full $1.1 trillion more than the administration had
dared hope for just six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   So far, spending hasn't kept pace with the rush of unexpected
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Between October and May, for instance, taxes paid by individuals
and corporations rose 15.2 percent from a year earlier. Government
spending, however, rose just 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a $120 billion surplus, up $80 billion from a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But as the economy giveth, so it taketh away. A downturn could
have a vicious impact on the rosy projections of good times to
come.
</P>
<P>
   If growth slows much below 2 percent a year, for example,
economists would expect to see a rise in unemployment, now at a
generational low of 4 percent. As workers go off the payroll, tax
revenues decline even as federal payments for unemployment benefits
go up.
</P>
<P>
   In such an economy, the ambitious surplus numbers could quickly
turn around.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to predict what might put the brakes on the
runaway economy, or when it might occur.
</P>
<P>
   Rising oil prices haven't hurt yet, but affordable energy
supplies are clearly critical to economic vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing trade imbalances _ the U.S. trade deficit soared to a
record $265 billion last year and is still growing _ could drive
down the value of the dollar against other world currencies.
</P>
<P>
   That would either drive up the price of imports or force a hike
in U.S. interest rates to strengthen the greenback, or both.
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, and many others, Clinton has warned that the
country shouldn't eat its surplus chickens before they hatch.
</P>
<P>
   He has proposed using the Social Security surplus, projected at
$2.3 trillion over the coming decade, to help pay down the $5.6
trillion national debt accumulated during 30 years of deficit
spending.
</P>
<P>
   If the government could retire the $3.2 trillion of that debt
owed to banks and other public investors, it would mean hundreds of
billions of dollars in interest savings.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has spending as well as saving in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, what are we going to do with this'' surplus,
President Clinton told several thousand government workers gathered
a week ago in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``How a country handles its moment of prosperity and opportunity
is just as stern a test of our vision, our judgment and our
character as how we handle adversity,'' warned Clinton. ``We will
never be forgiven if we blow this.''
</P>
<P>
   He has proposed $460 billion in spending hikes over 10 years,
mostly to add a prescription drug benefit to Medicare and to extend
health care coverage to low-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also has proposed tax cuts, mostly targeted toward
lower-income or middle-class workers, amounting to $360 billion
over 10 years. He would partly offset those programs, though, with
a long list of tax code changes that he calls loophole-closers, and
corporations call tax hikes, that would raise an estimated $96
billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have their own plans for the surplus. Already, some
fiscal conservatives in Congress are complaining that next year's
spending bills are too bloated.
</P>
<P>
   The main GOP focus, though, is on tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Congress approved a $492 billion tax cut, which
Clinton vetoed. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the expected GOP
presidential nominee, has proposed his own tax cut of roughly half
a trillion dollars over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have also called for sharp cuts in estate taxes paid
by wealthy Americans and for a $50 billion cut in taxes paid by
married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are ``intolerably overtaxed,'' Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
</P>
<P>
   said in a radio address broadcast last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Official Washington now has too much money on its hands,''
Lott said. ``Government doesn't tax to get the money it needs.
Instead, it finds a need for the money it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the proposals can quickly eat up a surplus,
projected or real.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, that's really the swing factor,'' said Cohen.
``Once you start talking about spending this money, or lowering
taxes, then some of these surpluses go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, say budget stewards, the two parties haven't yet
agreed on either approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gridlock,'' concludes former congressional budget director
June O'Neill in the current issue of Policy Review magazine,
``seems to be good medicine for the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
