<HEADER>
A5437 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-SCARY-HNS     07-07 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SCARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN `SCARY MOVIE,' GROSS HUMOR AND PARODY ABOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MIKE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget the gross scenes from ``There's Something About Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie'' barely compares.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Scary Movie,'' several of the Wayans brothers blend the
elements from recent rude comedy hits, horror spoofs and other
popular pictures to create the raunchiest movie of the summer.
Also, one of the funniest.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: Before you see ``Scary Movie,'' rent the following if
you have not already seen them: ``Scream,'' both ``I Know What You
Did Last Summer'' movies, ``The Matrix,'' ``American Pie,'' ``The
Usual Suspects'' and ``The Blair Witch Project.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``Scary Movie'' is funny on its own _ you don't have to
have seen the above films to laugh _ its fullest humor comes from
the exaggerated parody scenes re-enacted from the pictures it makes
fun of. Director Keenen Ivory Wayans and two of his brothers, Shawn
and Marlon Wayans (who also star and co-wrote), re-create
everything perfectly: camera angles, scenarios and even the bad
acting _ except this time it's intentional.
</P>
<P>
   Is it enough for a film only to poke fun at pop culture and
other movies? In this case, sure. The Wayans' previous parody
movies about urban life, ``Don't Be A Menace to South Central While
Drinking Your Juice in the Hood'' and ``I'm Gonna Git You Sucka,''
have the same immature-yet-smart ability to turn dramatic scenes
into hilarious ones. With ``Menace,'' the Wayans were limited in
comedic range, because the content of the movies they were poking
fun at was serious.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Scary Movie,'' however, they leave nobody unscathed. The
movie begins with a funhouse-mirror image of a scene from
``Scream,'' the film that ``Scary Movie'' mocks more than any
other. ``Baywatch's'' Carmen Electra plays the damsel in distress,
with all the details from ``Scream'' intact, but turned 180
degrees. The chase scene between Electra and the killer, wearing
the familiar ``Scream'' mask, quickly becomes something out of a
Playboy video, with Electra running in slow motion beneath
sprinklers. Midchase, Electra comes to two road signs. One points
to safety, the other to death. You can guess which path she
chooses.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the movie then starts, and the name game begins. It
gets confusing, so pay attention: Newcomer Anna Farris plays the
main character, Cindy Campbell (in ``Scream,'' Neve Campbell played
the lead role, named Sidney). Gale Hailstorm (Cheri Oteri of
``Saturday Night Live'') is the nosy reporter from ``Scream,'' who
in that movie was named Gail Weathers, while Electra's short
appearance gives her the name of Drew Becker (Drew Barrymore played
Casey Becker in ``Scream''). And a David Arquette look-alike named
Dave Sheridan plays the dimwitted Special Officer Doofy (Arquette
was ``Scream's'' Officer Dewey).
</P>
<P>
   The over-exaggerated acting and script keep the movie rolling,
and it all hits the fan in a scene with Cindy and her aptly named
gym teacher, Miss Mann. The boundary of tasteless sight gags is
pushed to the maximum when Miss Mann, by exposing parts of anatomy
she's not supposed to have, gives ``dodge ball'' a new definition.
The spoofs continue, with a scene out of ``Blair Witch'' showing
Oteri dropping softball-size globs of mucus onto the camera below
her crying eyes. A hilarious murder scene with Buffy Gilmore
(played by the scantily clad Shannon Elizabeth), together with a
quick jab at ``The Sixth Sense'' and an unexpected Budweiser scene,
keep the movie from being predictable or repetitive, a problem with
many slapsticks.
</P>
<P>
   Every character in the movie has at least one exaggerated
characteristic. Ray (Shawn Wayans) is an in-the-closet homosexual
who is beyond obvious with his actions. Shorty (Marlon Wayans) is
higher than a space shuttle throughout the movie, and Elizabeth
plays the ditzy girl we've come to expect in every horror movie.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and the weak-of-stomach, beware: The movie is lewd.
Flat-out lewd. No way around it. Whether dealing with the firehose
power of a character's bodily fluids or the object that Shawn
Wayans gets an earful of, the situations are astonishingly graphic.
</P>
<P>
   If gross humor and parody movies are what you're looking for,
``Scary Movie'' is for you. It has no great plot lines, no touching
emotions and no cinematic miracles. In other words, leave your
brain and moral objections at home and just enjoy the vulgarity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5452 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-EARNHARDT-BOS &LR;      07-07 1721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-EARNHARDT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMATED EARNHARDT ISN'T RESTRICTED FROM SPEAKING HIS MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Dale Earnhardt sat comfortably in his
hauler at Daytona International Speedway, holding court with
several reporters during an interview last Friday, when the
seven-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion became clearly revved up _
if not agitated _ by the subject of restrictor-plate racing.
</P>
<P>
   Restrictor-plate racing, as far as Earnhardt was concerned, was
an oxymoron. They might as well just call it restrictor-plate
ridin'.
</P>
<P>
   And, as most drivers on the competitive Winston Cup circuit will
tell you, ridin' ain't racin'.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since NASCAR mandated the use of restrictor plates at its
superspeedway venues at Daytona and Talladega _ a move aimed at
slowing cars by reducing the amount of horsepower generated by the
engines _ it has become one of Earnhardt's pet peeves. It has
turned trips to those high-banked, high-speed, triovals from a
thrill ride into a visit to the dentist's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish we could just race,'' Earnhardt said before last
Saturday's Pepsi 400 at Daytona. ``We go to Pocono (Pa.) and to
Loudon (N.H.) and these places and race and have a good time. We
come here (to Daytona) and it's aggravation just to get through
inspection for qualifying. You qualify and it's even more
aggravation getting out of that mess and changing your cars over to
the race deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dang, let's just race. If they'll just take the restrictor
plates off, they won't have to worry about shocks and springs and
stuff. People will have those damn blades up in the air, hollerin'
`I need more spoiler.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there is no room for wimps on Earnhardt's track. You
either race, or you get out of the way. He doesn't suffer fools or
colleagues who complain about the high speeds at NASCAR's
superspeedways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard some drivers saying, `We're going too fast at
Charlotte. We're going too fast here (at Daytona).' Well, get the
hell home,'' he said. ``If you're not a race car driver and not a
racer, stay home. Don't come here and grumble about going too fast.
Stay the hell home.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, this weekend in the New England 300 at New Hampshire
International Speedway, Earnhardt will get his wish. The No. 3
Goodwrench Chevrolet Monte Carlo he has driven the last 16 years
for car owner Richard Childress will be liberated of its restrictor
plate and allowed to gallop unbridled around the 1.058-mile oval in
Loudon. And he'll get to race, finally.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All of this, of course, will likely cause a devilish grin to the
curl beneath the Intimidator's trademark mustache.
</P>
<P>
   But Earnhardt has had more to grin about this year than he has
in the last five, a turbulent span in which he stumbled in the
points, going from fourth to fifth to eighth from 1996-1998. It was
all exacerbated by a winless 1997 that left many with the mistaken
impression the man in black had suddenly become the man in back.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at him now. At 49, he's running stronger than ever,
proving he's far from making a farewell tour. Earnhardt has reason
to smile as he arrives at NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   He's second in the Winston Cup standings, 52 points behind Bobby
Labonte. He has proudly watched his son, Dale Earnhardt Jr., a
rookie driver, win twice this season with the No. 8 Budweiser
Chevrolet, one of two cars Earnhardt fields as a Winston Cup car
owner. He has cemented a strong working relationship with his
second-year crew chief, Kevin Hamlin, and longtime car owner,
Childress, who last season awarded him with a three-year contract
extension that will make him driver of the No. 3 car through 2003.
He no longer drives in neck pain after undergoing preseason surgery
for an old disk injury that bothered him all last season. Most
important of all, he remains in the hunt for a record-eighth
Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Dale Earnhardt driving harder and more aggressive than
I've seen him the last three years,'' said Jeff Burton, 33, winner
of last week's Pepsi 400 and the last three July races at NHIS.
``Dale Earnhardt's in a great position to win the championship. He
may be the oldest active driver, I don't really get into age, but
he's sure older than me. But I don't see him bowing over by any
means.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Dale Jarrett, the reigning Cup champion who is third in
the points, 24 behind Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he has more experience at winning these
championships than Bobby and I put together, and we could take a
lot of other people and throw them into the mix and he'd still have
more experience,'' Jarrett said. ``We know that he's going to be
tough as this goes on and as the season winds down. If he can hang
around, and we certainly feel he will, it's going to be interesting
to see.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what if Earnhardt were to win his eighth championship? How
would it compare, say, with winning his first Daytona 500 in 1997?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I've won a lot of Daytona 499s,'' he chuckled. ``But I
don't weigh winning this race over that race or this championship
against that championship. I've really enjoyed them all, again,
I've been so damn fortunate to grow up in a family that raced _
with my dad (the late Ralph Earnhardt) _ then to get into it myself
and accomplish what I have in my life, is pretty awesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then to have your kids come along with you. I mean, I didn't
make Dale Jr. want to be a racer; the kid wanted to be a racer. I'd
just as soon him be a doctor or a preacher or whatever, but not a
lawyer _ then again that's another subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Has watching his son win points races at Texas and at Richmond
given him a different sense of satisfaction as a car owner?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're so proud of your kid, that's a given,'' Earnhardt said.
``You see that happen and you're proud of your kid, but when you
win a race as a driver, that's pretty damn exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I'm driven to do and that's why I get up in the
mornings _ it's to go race and win. Yeah, I'm proud of (Dale Jr.)
winning and I'm excited about it, but I'll probably get more
excited as I become a full-time owner instead of driver-owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reckon I've got to the best of two worlds: I'm a winning
driver and a winning car owner and have accomplished a lot. It's
hard. You look around and not many people have done it the way I
have; I drove for another guy and won while racing against his own
team.''
</P>
<P>
   So why didn't he strike out on his own and drive for himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I could drive for myself,'' Earnhardt
acknowledged. ``That would be tough. I'm pretty set in my ways and
I'm set to drive that 3 car as long as Richard's there and the team
that we have is there. We've got a great opportunity and a great
organization, and I've got to stick with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's competitive fire has largely been stoked by the move
Childress made to switch crew chiefs in June 1998, pairing Mike
Skinner with Larry McReynolds, Earnhardt's old crew chief, and
Hamlin with Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us a very short time to see that we both had the same
mental focus,'' Earhardt said. ``Kevin is more my kind of style of
crew chief. He's a guy who's constantly thinking and he never quits
on making it better, but he's not the kind of guy who blows it up
and throws things and kicks and screams. He's the kind of guy who
comes back down here (to the garage) and listens to what I say and
talks about what we're doing and try to make an improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so much like Kirk Shelmerdine,'' Earnhardt added,
referring to one of his former crew chiefs. ``When I say something,
he's already thinking that way, and that's the way Kirk was. We're
thinking alike. I'm so happy that Richard made that change. I
haven't regretted it one bit. I love Larry McReynolds to death as a
person, and we won the Daytona 500 together, but day in and day
out, I work better with Kevin.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt has the results to prove it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he finished seventh in the points after recording
three victories (including two at Talladega) and 14 Top 10
finishes. This year, with Hamlin's stewardship, Earnhardt has 15
Top 10s in the previous 17 races, including a victory at the
Cracker Barrel 500 March 12 in Atlanta. He moved into second in the
point standings after finishing second in the Kmart 400 at Michigan
International Speedway and has remained there for the last four
races.
</P>
<P>
   Earhardt might have vaulted into the lead the following week at
Pocono had it not been for Jeremy Mayfield's ``bump-and-run''
victory. Mayfield caused quite a stir when he bumped Earnhardt from
behind in the final turn, causing him to lose control of his car
and drop out of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That deal was a racin' deal,'' Earnhardt said. ``I don't know
why he made such a big deal out of it, like he was guilty of
something. Then the fans all said stuff about it. Heck, it's over.
I mean I wasn't jumping up and down, screamin' and hollerin' after
the race. It happened, OK? I'm a big boy. I can take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had it in my mind to get into the corner the best I
could and get back on the throttle as best I could, but he got to
me, got into me and got me loose,'' he added. ``Then it was a
situation of controlling the car (to preserve a fourth-place
finish) . . . I will be bold and say this: There ain't many (guys)
who could've sat in that seat and not wrecked that car.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Earnhardt managed to bring it home in one piece,
retaining his solid second position in the points. It was much the
same last week at Daytona, where Earnhardt made the best of a bad
situation (a restrictor-plate race) and turned it into a
sixth-place finish to close the gap on Labonte in the points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of racing you've got to do,'' Earnhardt said.
``You've got to make a terrible day into a fair day. Bobby is doing
it and Dale Jarrett has won a championship doing it, (Jeff) Gordon,
all of us. You just have to keep going to each race with that
mindset, `I've got to go to the front, I've got to get to the
front, I've got to race in the front.' I've got to be serious all
day about where I'm at. I'm not guarding points. I'm just trying to
better my position as best as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Restrictor plates, be damned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
