<HEADLINE>
ALL-STAR GLITTER FADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Major League Baseball All-Star Game is yet another example
of declining ratings for network sports programming.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, the All-Star Game generated a 20.5 rating on
NBC, about 20 million households. The numbers have dropped
significantly over the years, largely the result of cable TV and
the emergence of the Internet. Last year, the All-Star Game
received a 12 rating, about 12 million viewers. In today's
television landscape, a 12 rating is still good.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in ratings has little to do with the product. Last
year, for example, the game took place at Fenway Park and featured
the dramatic return of Ted Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's Keith Olberman had it right. It was ``an epic moment''
when Williams was surrounded by Hank Aaron, Willie Mays, Juan
Marichal, Carl Yastrzemski, Ken Griffey, and Mark McGwire. Joe Buck
had an even better line: ``Look at them all, smiling like Little
Leaguers.''
</P>
<P>
   Though this year's game is the first of the millennium, it won't
have anywhere near the same drama. For one thing, Atlanta's Turner
Field is no Fenway. And while Joe Morgan remains one of the better
baseball announcers in the game, his return to Atlanta is not a
tear-jerker. The last time an All-Star Game was played in Atlanta
was 1972. In the 10th inning, Morgan singled in San Diego's Nate
Colbert with the game-winning run. Morgan played in nine All-Star
Games during his 19-year Hall of Fame career and described the '72
game as ``my personal favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC spokesman Kevin Sullivan said the All-Star Game remains one
of the highest rated prime time sporting events of the summer and
will receive big-time coverage.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has about 125 people producing the game Tuesday, starting at
8 p.m. The network has 22 cameras, including remote control units
in each bullpen, a telestrator, a radar gun, and microphones on
three bases. Morgan and Bob Costas will call the action.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN also is devoting big-time coverage. The cable sports
network has Chris Berman, Mike Piazza, and Morgan calling the
two-hour coverage of the Home Run Derby Monday, July 10 at 8 p.m.
Griffey is the defending champion, but McGwire stole the show last
year with towering shots out of Fenway. Nothing better than Berman
calling home runs.
</P>
<P>
   And, this year, Berman will be aided by a new technology
developed by ESPN and Sportvision. ``ESPN True Track'' measures the
distance of home runs. Two cameras will be located in the upper
deck near the foul poles and will be equipped with sensors that
will follow the path of the ball. Computers will calculate the
distance an unimpeded ball would have traveled.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Run Derby also marks the start of ESPN telecasts of
baseball games in Spanish. The Spanish language simulcasts will
include graphics, commercials, player interviews, and on-air
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The simulcasts will continue with ESPN's seven remaining Sunday
night baseball games and conclude with the network's Division
Series games. ESPN International's Ernesto Jerez and Alfredo
Alvarez call the simulcasted games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic Coast Conference has signed a 10-year deal with
ESPN/ESPN2 to air a minimium of 23 mens' basketball games, starting
with the 2001-02 season. The deal calls for ACC teams to appear on
ABC at least 10 times per year.
</P>
<P>
   NBC airs the women's Wimbledon final Saturday starting at 10
a.m. with Ted Robinson, Chris Evert, and Bud Collins. The men's
final starts at 9 a.m. Sunday with Robinson, Collins, and John
McEnroe. Ratings for the first four days of the tournament are up
25 percent from last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
