<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MASSACHUSETTS TOWN OFFERS A ROAD SHOW OF ANTIQUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 9)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIMFIELD, Mass. _ The weather has gone from 90 degrees to
temperatures akin to February in just 24 hours. People dressed in
clothing suitable for the previous day's heat wave shiver as they
speak in hushed tones or into walkie-talkies. But there is an
excitement building.
</P>
<P>
   This is the lull before the storm on the opening day of the
first of the series of Brimfield Outdoor Antique and Collectible
Shows. The shows occur three times a year and are the largest of
their kind in the country, featuring more than 4,000 dealers. This
year's second show opens this week.
</P>
<P>
   The day is also typical of the fickle weather that bounces off
the Berkshires and into this bucolic town of 3,500 residents in
south-central Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers' tents are spread out over 22 fields along a mile-plus
stretch of Route 20, Brimfield's main thoroughfare. The opening of
each field is staggered, starting at 6 a.m., to give dealers a fair
crack at the buyers who make this pilgrimage three times a year.
</P>
<P>
   It's nearing the 9 a.m. opening time for the Heart-O-The-Mart,
the third largest field, boasting 550 dealers. Hundreds of people
are quietly queued up outside, some sipping hot coffee, some
checking their watches and waiting for the gates to part.
</P>
<P>
   There's a final countdown of the last 10 seconds when a bell
rings out in the cool and damp morning air, signaling the stampede
to round up pieces of antiquity.
</P>
<P>
   The double main gate flies open. Three other gates are just as
quickly pulled open by organizers, to accommodate the continuous
sea of flesh that is now cheering, smiling and waving at the
organizers and volunteers and racing through the isles of the
15-acre field to the treasures beyond.
</P>
<P>
   This throng is clearly on a mission, and continues to pour past
the dealers set up on both sides of the entrance isles.
</P>
<P>
   The buyers are armed with shopping carts, wagons, dog carts,
baby strollers and armfuls of sturdy opaque trash bags. No stopping
just yet to finger the goods. Not only might it be dangerous to try
to stop for a look, but there's actually a method to this mad rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening day at our field is like the running of the bulls at
Pamplona,'' laughs Tracey Houle, show manager for Heart-O-The-Mart.
``Opening day is like nothing else for the rest of each show, which
calms down a bit in the days that follow. Almost everybody has
their own plan of attack when they come here. Many of them know a
lot of the dealers and/or have been coming here for years. It's
almost like a family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many dealers, who are here to buy, know who and what they are
looking for and so they run from booth to booth, while the rest of
the crowd rushes to the back and works their way forward,'' Houle
explains. ``Sometimes families or dealers split up and work all
sides of the field toward the center. A good majority of the people
who come here already know what they are looking for and then often
discover other finds along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Harriet Bridges, owner of North Bridge Antiques in Concord, has
had a tent at the Brimfield show for 15 years and has requested the
same location just shy of the front gate for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really feel offended that they pass me by,'' Bridges
says. ``I know that they will check me out when they are leaving. I
enjoy watching them rush in and they are always careful not to
knock anything over or off tables.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brimfield show, which is billed as the world's largest
outdoor antiques and collectibles megafair, evolved from George
Reid's small flea market, which he began holding on his auction
grounds in 1959. His daughters continue the family business, J&AMP;J
Auction Acres, which has grown to be the largest field at
Brimfield, with 700 dealers.
</P>
<P>
   As Brimfield's reputation grew, it became a well-known trade
secret, drawing other antiques dealers who purchase for their
shops, and architects and interior designers shopping for clients.
But as word spread, Brimfield quickly became a show for collectors
as well.
</P>
<P>
   The show runs for six days three times a year beginning on a
Tuesday and ending the following Sunday in May, July and September,
and draws 60,000 or more people per show.
</P>
<P>
   With each show, some dealers are open each of the six days,
while others open for selected days or move their booth from field
to field. Show operators in charge of each of the major and
secondary fields maintain lists of dealers and only they can
distribute dealer information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the size, it's almost impossible to see it all in
one day,'' stresses Pam Moriarty, who began Heart-O-The-Mart with
her husband, Don, in 1984 with 46 dealers. ``It really takes two to
three days. The best three days where you get to see all of the
dealers is Wednesday through Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for something in particular and don't see it
early in the week, inquire with a dealer who carries similar items,
according to Moriarty. They may know where to get it or have what
you are looking for still packed in a box at their booth.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers need to take enough inventory to last the show and they
will often add or replace items to keep their booths fresh,
especially for those who attend several days in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Brimfield draws dealers from all around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had dealers from Germany, France and Africa,''
Moriarty says. ``It's all very educational and the dealers are very
knowledgeable. You'll see just about anything at this show, from
the bizarre to the elegant, and prices from 50 cents to $50,000 or
more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Check out the red vintage Coca-Cola machines in the back of
the field,'' adds Moriarty. ``You might say, `So?' But I'll tell
you, they sell like crazy. People come to Brimfield to buy, sell,
bargain, barter or to simply check it out and have fun. And many
dealers expect you to bargain. You never know what you'll find or
see!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
