<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBRACED IN THE ARMS OF SISTERHOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the big event approaches, Melanie Harris and her sorority
buddy Denise Kahn talk of sisterhood, but I imagine something more
akin to a big family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Family reunions, I've attended. But a gathering of Alpha Kappa
Alphas is a whole other matter for this sister. It never occurred
to me to pledge in college, not even when the Delta Sigma Theta
sorority was courting me.
</P>
<P>
   So I let them speak of their excitement, breathe the
anticipation of another annual gathering of pink-and-green-clad
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you meet someone with similar experiences, it's a
wonderful thing,'' Kahn said. ``Whether you're 18 or 88, we share a
common history. There is a bond.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris is 20 and Kahn is, well, old enough to know better than
to tell her age. She is also president of the Fort Worth chapter of
AKAs, the oldest and largest black Greek sorority in the country.
</P>
<P>
   That, Kahn says, makes her sorority all the more special.
</P>
<P>
   So is this week in the sorority's nearly 100-year history, when
an estimated 10,000 sorority sisters are gathering for their 59th
national convention in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The convention will run through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There will be the normal convention fare: workshops to attend,
connections to make, issues to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   But the women will also celebrate their triumphs, the community
services the group has rendered in the past year. Chapters will be
recognized for work with at-risk children, part of the ON TRACK
program that national President Norma Solomon White began in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the community service organization also collected
20,000 coats for the needy and distributed brochures on women's
health, medicines and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   There are many more projects, including local efforts that don't
have the same national appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are women still devoted to community, serving mankind
and being part of the sisterhood,'' said Harris, a member of the
Kappa Psi chapter at the University of Oklahoma, where she is a
junior.
</P>
<P>
   So you can see, perhaps, why Harris is so excited. But just as
important as the services they render, she and Kahn said, are the
sisters they meet, the relationships they build.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited because I get to meet women with the same
mind-set, same goals, and also women I can look up to,'' Harris
said. ``I can't really explain the feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   But this being her first convention, Harris is also nervous. It
can be intimidating, she said, being around women who have such
long histories with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn said that 39 women who have been AKA members for 75 years
will be at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   She knows, she said, that the sisterhood bit ``sounds corny,''
and maybe it does, but I understand. Conventions can be much like
family reunions. It's how I feel when I attend the annual gathering
of the National Association of Black Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' mother, Debra, is an AKA. Her stories about the sorority
sparked an interest in her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 150,000 women strong,'' Melanie Harris said. ``I wanted
to be a part of that. I wanted to feel the sisterly love.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know much about sorority life, but sisterhood and family
I understand. There's nothing quite like them.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
