<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SETZER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING NEW ZING IN SWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer-enhanced rhythms are changing the sound of rock 'n'
roll and hip-hop. That's a given. But they're also about to change
a more unlikely genre _ the nostalgic, retro-obsessed world of big
band swing music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like year 2000 swing. I'm really happy with the way
it came out,'' says Brian Setzer, the Grammy-winning big band
leader, referring to four songs on his new album, ``Vavoom!,'' to
which he added computer-altered beats to the Brian Setzer
Orchestra's classic swing and jump-blues sound.
</P>
<P>
   Setzer put ``some cha-cha beats and hip-hop beats into the
computer and came up with something that's really different to me''
on the album's opening track, a cover of Glenn Miller's humorous
``Pennsylvania 6-5000.'' The computer processing doesn't harm the
song, but gives it more resonance, for the beats merge with those
of Setzer's drummer.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a young computer whiz named David Darling,
Setzer also punched up a new, horn-dominated original tune,
``Americano.'' Says Setzer: ``David was interested in taking what I
had recorded and putting it into a computer and making it sound
sort of scuffed up. He changed the sound of the horns. We actually
took the horns and reversed them. We made them go backwards into
the chorus on `Americano.' And we put different beats in there,
electronic beats. That was my first experience with anything like
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I say, it gives it a real year 2000 sound, as opposed to
1940s music,'' says Setzer, who still sings and plays guitar with
the enthusiasm of a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   On stage, Setzer will do the new songs without computer
enhancement: ``You really don't miss it live. It's more for when
you're sitting down _ things to catch your ear. Live, it's more
about the performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Setzer, formerly with the once-hot rockabilly band the Stray
Cats, has spurred a swing revival in recent years that has seen the
emergence of not just his own 17-piece band, but of such acts as
Big Bad Voodoo Daddy, the Squirrel Nut Zippers (now broken up), the
Cherry Poppin' Daddies, and Boston's Four Piece Suit.
</P>
<P>
   But where some swing revivalists are ``uptight'' (Setzer's word)
and treat the music like museum pieces, Setzer believes in keeping
the integrity of the sound, but also in shaking things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people can make a big mistake of getting caught up in
playing something exactly the way it was done, rather than messing
with it,'' he says. ``They get so caught up in the retro thing. I
think you've got to take chances with it and fool around with it.
You don't have to be period-perfect about it. That's not what it's
there for. That stuff was made for you to take little pieces of it
and go somewhere else and do your own thing with it.''
</P>
<P>
   On his new album, which comes out Aug. 1, Setzer experiments
further by adding doo-wop singers 14 Carat Soul to a spicy new
original, ``That's the Kind of Sugar Papa Likes.'' ``I'm from New
York and I'm a big doo-wop fan,'' he says. On another song,
``Gloria'' (a cover of a 1954 song by the Cadillacs, not the Van
Morrison tune), Setzer offers a fresh twist by having his horn
section replace the doo-wop harmonies of the original version. He
says he partly got the idea from a conversation with pop legend
Dion of Dion &AMP; the Belmonts fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dion came to see us in Florida and said, `Oh, man, I love this
big band. You know, when we (the Belmonts) first started, we
couldn't afford players like that, so we just got neighborhood guys
and we would try to sound like horns.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I thought,'' says Setzer, `` `Wow, maybe I'll make my
horns sound like your singers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The result is remarkably effective, as are most of the
experiments on the first-rate ``Vavoom!'' It's a worthy successor
to the Setzer Orchestra's ``Dirty Boogie'' CD (in 1998), which sold
2 million copies at the height of the neo-swing craze and earned
Setzer two Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Setzer is always experimenting with the big band swing
idiom. On the new disc, he also chooses to do a near-exact replica
of Bobby Darin's jive-snapping, storytelling hit, ``Mack the
Knife.'' Notes Setzer: ``People have been yelling for me to do that
song, so I said, `OK, I'm going to give it to them.' But I didn't
want to scuff that up, as opposed to the other ones. I wanted some
real traditional stuff on there, too, so I just left that one
alone. It was my tribute to Bobby Darin.''
</P>
<P>
   Setzer, who grew up on Long Island, enjoyed his first taste of
swing music as a child by listening to Doc Severinsen's big band on
``The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson.'' Some people think
Setzer learned swing music from his parents' record collection, but
that wasn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``My folks were really '50s rockers. My dad was a rockabilly guy
into Carl Perkins. And my mom was an Elvis lady. She had an Elvis
poster above her bed. My dad used to joke, `I don't mind Elvis
above the bed, but I bet Elvis got his supper on time.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After Setzer's Stray Cats folded, he opted to try the big band
format eight years ago _ well before the swing revival took root.
``At our first show (at the Roxy in Hollywood), people didn't know
what a big band was. I think we sold 34 tickets and the promoters
wanted to cancel the show. I said, `Look, I've come all this way
and I've got charts and I know this is good. You're not going to
cancel this show. I'll pay the band out of my pocket.'
</P>
<P>
   ``From there, we just kept moving up because of word-of-mouth
from fans,'' says Setzer, who now lives in Malibu and proudly notes
his band was selling out the 6,000-seat Greek Theatre in Los
Angeles on word of mouth, before his last album went big.
</P>
<P>
   Because of ceaseless touring over many years, the Setzer
Orchestra has also been better insulated from the ups and downs
that have hit the more recent, bandwagon-jumping swing groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really follow the other bands' careers,'' he says.
``But I know the scene is still there. I can turn on the TV and
still hear swing music behind TV ads. And I'm still out there doing
well, luckily. People are buying a lot of tickets to our shows.
We're doing well all over, and our new album isn't even out yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say, though, that swing falls into a fad. There's
nothing you can do about it. But swing music is great music. It's
based in jazz, so it's always going to be there. And it struck a
chord bigger than rockabilly did. I guess because, back in the day,
it was more prevalent. It was really popular for 10 years (in the
'40s), where rockabilly was never popular. Rockabilly was always an
underground music.
</P>
<P>
   ``So swing definitely struck a bigger chord in people. That's
why I'm probably still playing places like the FleetBoston
Pavilion,'' says Setzer. ``People are still coming down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
