u k BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-07 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLING INTO THE US TOURIST TRAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEYSTONE, S.D. _ And to think how smoothly things had gone
before I crossed the border into this seemingly innocuous state. I
had driven more than 3,200 miles, paused in the great industrial
behemoths of the Great Lakes, helped an appreciative rodeo
announcer broken down on a lonely stretch of Nebraskan highway, and
survived a night in a roadside establishment called the Settle Inn.
Seattle beamed brightly ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Then I entered the Black Hills. It was there, amid the towering
pines and plunging canyons that I came face to face with the
vilest, most rudimentary creature imaginable, the exact beast I had
so fastidiously been trying to avoid: the American tourist.
</P>
<P>
   They travel in herds, or prides, or schools. They don a uniform
of Fannie Paks, white sneakers, and ill-fitting T-shirts emblazoned
with the name of a destination they had just visited, like, for
instance, Reptile World. They scrunch their brow when they
encounter the word ``salad,'' as if they've been presented with
French. They love nothing so much as a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   I raise this point after visiting Keystone, a place so
laughably, ludicrously fake that it of course draws gratified
tourists in droves. It makes Route 28 in Hyannis look like Rodeo
Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Keystone is also, unfortunately, home to Mount Rushmore, a
stunning tribute to American history and ingenuity just a mile or
so from downtown. Rushmore is located within the beautiful Black
Hills National Forest, where I patted a wild burro and came within
feet of a herd of grazing buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   But such things appear to be lost on most tourists, who would
make the necessary trip to the miraculous monument, snap a few
pictures, pay homage to the snack bar, stampede the gift shop, then
exchange relieved looks with each other as they descended the hill
for something more comforting: blinking lights and schlock.
</P>
<P>
   And there was plenty of it. As I sat on the boardwalk of a faux
western restaurant called ``Ruby's House,'' I looked past a throng
of tank-topped humanity toward a shop called ``Dakota Gold,'' which
sits beside ``The Gold Mine,'' which sits beside ``Old-fashioned
fudge.'' Half a block away, the ``World's Greatest Bargains,'' the
``Bargain Store'' and ``Discount City USA'' were clustered within a
lasso throw of each other. What might Thomas Jefferson, or the less
tactful Teddy Roosevelt, say about this?
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, a graybearded cyclist with a Levi's jacket and
an Anheuser-Busch gut started his Harley with a thunderous boom
that created waves in my sarsaparilla. Helicopters giving tourists
aerial views of Rushmore buzzed implacably overhead. In the street,
the constant flow of RV traffic came to a sudden halt when a
pseudo-gunfight broke out between two men wearing pleather chaps,
causing the the slump-shouldered tourists to fall silent with
appreciative glee.
</P>
<P>
   And then they were off, these tourists, some to the nearby
Flintstone's theme park complete with Brontosaurus Burgers and Dino
Dogs, others to Yogi's Jellystone Park campgrounds and swimming
hole, still more to Bear Country USA (``Where beauty is alive and
natural''), not to mention Everything Prehistoric (``It's a blast
from the past!''). Mount Rushmore, which took more than 14 years to
sculpt, seemed little more than coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   It was like that, too, in the nearby Badlands, where ancient
rock formations rise from the prairie in haunting shapes that
extend for miles. Tourists would invariably breeze through the
national park, then head straight for Wall Drug, which bills itself
as the world's largest drugstore.
</P>
<P>
   And I have no doubt that it is. In the middle of absolutely
nowhere, in room after added room, jostling tourists grab for
rhinestone cowboy figurines, T-shirts that declare they were there,
candles shaped like moose. They push quarters into a slot to see
stuffed bears dance and sing a song.
</P>
<P>
   I pumped a dollar's worth of quarters into the El Toro machine,
where you literally grab the bull by its horns in a test of
strength, twice achieving the unfairly unimpressive designation of
``Athlete.'' The well-fed tourist after me brought the bull to its
knees, causing lights to flash, alarms to sound and my navigator to
look at me with something that resembled shame. Time to put South
Dakota in my rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   So I found a quiet stretch of two-lane road and headed west
toward safety, toward Wyoming. Seattle, thankfully, is but a few
days away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
