<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5473 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-SHABBY-WHITEHOUSE-BOS     07-07 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHABBY-WHITEHOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$300 MILLION OVERHAUL EYED FOR CRAMPED WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To the thousands of tourists who troop each day
through a few of its elaborate rooms, the White House is a grand
mansion suited for a head of state. But get behind the public part
of the president's house, deep in the bowels of the 132-room
estate, and professionals come to a different conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   What a dump.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities are out of date, the meeting rooms too small, the
storage spaces cramped. There is no recreational area in the East
Wing where the first family lives _ no place to relax in private or
for children to play _ though there is a movie theatre and a
bowling alley on the compound. The White House press corps is
jam-packed into two small, musty rooms. Parking is near-impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Something, the Clinton administration decided, has to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been comprehensive planning for the site in
the site's history,'' said Ann Bowman Smith of the National Park
Service, which has developed a massive renovation plan.
</P>
<P>
   The solution the service has come up with is a 20-year, $300
million overhaul of the White House itself and the grounds
surrounding the building.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on ever-tightening security, the inevitable aging of
the structure, the wear and tear of serving as both the seat of
presidential power and a major national monument. The White House
is, after all, 200 years old, and well over a million visitors,
lobbyists, foreign dignitaries and guests tramp through it every
year.
</P>
<P>
   It has housed 41 families, many of whom had small children and
pets ranging from ponies to a goat. And the architects who designed
the presidential mansion did so in the era of the carriage and
horse, and at a time when presidents could take an unaccompanied
evening stroll, feeling no need for elaborate security measures.
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes an expanded, 60,000-square-foot visitors
center, a recreation room for the first family, an underground
press room and briefing area, a subterranean parking garage, new
meeting spaces and a overall of the building's pre-computer age
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of plan that should have been done a long time
ago, but wasn't,'' said Charles Atherton, secretary of the
Commission of Fine Arts, which is also involved in the project.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed overhaul would be just the second major
rehabilitation of the country's most famous home since 1814, when
the White House was repaired after being burned by British troops
in the War of 1812. The interior of the building was extensively
repaired under President Harry S Truman; Truman also added a
balcony to the building.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of construction, which could begin in several
years, would add new parking facilities, including 290 spaces under
Pennsylvania Avenue for staff and dignitaries, and underground
meeting space under West Executive Avenue west of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors center would be next on the construction schedule
and would include a museum, videos and other multimedia exhibits
about the White House and its inhabitants. From the visitors center
_ planned as an enlargement of the existing one in the Commerce
Building near the White House _ tourists would glide to the grounds
surrounding the White House on a moving underground sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Later, another 850 parking spaces would be constructed under the
Ellipse _ the green oval park south of the White House _ for staff
and visitors, reducing traffic congestion that now mars what early
planners had meant to be a grand park.
</P>
<P>
   Congress must approve the construction, spelled out in a
500-plus-page design plan released recently by the Park Service.
Taxpayers would bear the cost, although the government is likely to
accept some private donations, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lengthy approval process _ including a debate over
what to do with the streets bordering the White House grounds _
construction won't be starting soon.
</P>
<P>
   But to many people who work, walk through, or have lived in the
White House, the work can't start soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of tourists routinely wait outside for hours, in
Washington's unbearably humid summers and wet winters, to get in
the White House. A special crossing guard is needed to escort the
crowds across E Street from the Ellipse, as frustrated motorists
often refuse to stop, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The new vistors center, where time-specific tickets would be
issued, will solve that problem, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like an awful lot of money, but it is a national
shrine,'' said Texas tourist Gail Wilson, 53, as she craned her
head to examine the antique sofas in the White House's ornate Red
Room.
</P>
<P>
   The planned recreation room, enthusiastically backed by former
White House residents interviewed by the park service, would be
either inside or underneath the White House.
</P>
<P>
   President Abraham Lincoln was one who could have used such a
designated recreation room. The 16th president let his children
have the run of the place, according to White House historical
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   When Lincoln was holding a Cabinet meeting, young Tad Lincoln
bombarded the door with his toy cannon. The child also reportedly
stopped his father's guests to sell refreshments, and he pressed
them for money for war charities at stands he set up in the
executive mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Roosevelt's children slid down the stairways on trays
snatched from the White House pantry, and they bicycled and skated
on newly-polished floors.
</P>
<P>
   With no small children, Bill and Hillary Clinton haven't
encountered those play-time crises (though Buddy, the president's
chocolate Labrador, can sometimes be seen scampering around the
gardens, sniffing at plants). Still, the next president with young
children is going to want a safe, secluded place for the youngsters
to play, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very formal house,'' she said. ``There's no interior,
secure, recreation space. The day is coming when someone will say,
`I can't live here like this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The news media would also have upgraded facilities, including a
new briefing room, underground between the White House and the Old
Executive Office Building. The media would still retain part of its
old space, in the colonnade area linking the West Wing to the main
house, appeasing worries by the press corps that they would be
moved far from the presidential offices.
</P>
<P>
   Proximity to the president ``is one of the most important and
dramatic symbols of American democracy and of the First
Amendment,'' Helen Thomas, the former UPI reporter and longtime
dean of the White House press corps, wrote to the Parks Service.
</P>
<P>
   The media's basement workroom _ now a poorly ventilated, crowded
space where radio reporters work _ would be used for storage,
another serious White House need. With little on-site storage
space, the White House must now cart tables and other items into
the building every time there is an official event, adding to the
security burden of the Secret Service, which must search all
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Still open is the question of what to do with the stretch of
Pennsylvania Avenue along the north side of the White House. The
street was closed in 1995 after the Oklahoma City bombing. The fate
of the space will be dealt with later, following a study by the
Treasury Department, which oversees the Secret Service and security
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Public response to the long-term project has been mixed. While
many acknowledge the need to modernize, they also complain about
the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are in no position to build a palace to
humor the president and his lady,'' Sheridan Arnold wrote in a
public comment to the Parks Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always wondered how the first family can relax in such
a formal atmosphere,'' said a more-sympathetic Steve Adams. ``These
folks definitely need a place inside to get away and relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Other writers _ none of their hometowns were identified _ had
different gripes. Why should staff get the first shot at parking
spaces? Why not move the media out of the White House grounds
completely? What can be done to help the homeless people who now
reside in Lafayette Park, north of the White House?
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton, whose administration spearheaded the
renovation project, won't be in office to benefit from the changes,
he still was the target of some dissatisfied taxpayers skeptical of
the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it looks real good as it is now,'' an anonymous writer
said in an e-mailed comment. ``The only improvement I could suggest
would be a new tenant in the White House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
