u i BC-RWANDA-REPARATIONS-40     07-07 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-REPARATIONS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE AND U.S. TOLERATED GENOCIDE IN RWANDA, NEW REPORT CLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ An independent panel assembled by the
Organization of African Unity said Friday that a ``significant
level of reparations'' should be paid to Rwanda by nations and
institutions that failed to prevent or stop the 1994 genocide that
killed up to 800,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The panel of seven international experts singled out France, the
United States, Belgium, the United Nations and the Roman Catholic
and Anglican churches as those most guilty _ in addition to
Rwanda's Hutu-led government _ of complicity or negligence when
Hutu militias rampaged through the country, massacring ethnic
Tutsis and moderate or anti-government Hutus who defended them.
</P>
<P>
   In a report full of stinging rebukes issued here Friday, the
panel asked U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to establish a
commission to name the countries that owe Rwanda the money to
rebuild a devastated country, and to formulate an appropriate scale
of compensation. The report, ``Rwanda: The Preventable Genocide,''
also demanded the cancellation of Rwanda's international debts.
</P>
<P>
   The events of 1994 cannot be assigned to history, the panel
said. The long-term effects of those weeks of horrific bloodshed
and brutality continue to be felt throughout the region, especially
in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1994 genocide in one small country ultimately triggered a
conflict in the heart of Africa that has directly or indirectly
touched at least one-third of all the nations on the continent,''
the report said. It added that Rwanda should no more be assigned to
``ancient history'' than the Nazi Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which goes over the same ground and reaches many of
the same conclusions as another independent experts' study
commissioned by Annan, takes a deeper look at the roots of the
ethnic conflict in Rwanda, beginning with 60 years of Belgian
colonial rule that it says exacerbated, if not manipulated, ethnic
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of African Unity report is also far harsher in
its criticism of Security Council members, especially France and
the United States, saying that the former could have prevented the
genocide and the latter could have stopped it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course there would have been no genocide if certain
Rwandans had not organized and carried it out; there is no denying
that fundamental truth,'' the report said. ``But it is equally true
that throughout the past century external forces have helped shape
Rwanda's destiny and that of its neighbors.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The report does not absolve the present, Tutsi-led government in
Rwanda of sometimes failing to meet challenges it inherited,
despite the ``resilience and vigor'' shown by the survivors in
rebuilding the country and their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandans still confront human rights abuses under the Tutsi-led
government formed from the Rwanda Patriotic Front, which seized
power in the summer of 1994. The country, struggling with refugee
resettlement, is still at war in Congo, where ethnic Hutu militias
remain a menace, the Rwanda government says.
</P>
<P>
   Those militias instigated the genocide in April 1994, after a
Hutu president, Juvenal Habyarimana, was killed in a plane crash in
Kigali, possibly caused by a missile attack. The report
characterizes the four-year period leading up to the outbreak of
violence as ``the triumph of ethnic radicalism'' among the majority
Hutu population that set the scene for the nightmare that followed.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the report found, France had ``unrivaled
influence at the very highest levels'' of the Hutu-led government
in Rwanda and chose not to exercise it to derail well-laid plans
for the genocide.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday, Ambassador Stephen Lewis, a
Canadian member of the OAU panel and a former deputy executive
director of Unicef, said that the new report chose to focus more
heavily on the role of the Security Council, especially France and
the United States, than the report prepared for Annan last year.
Lewis said that French behavior was particularly indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We repudiate the position of the government of France, the
position that asserts they had no responsibility,'' he said. ``They
were closer in every way to the Habyarimana regime than any other
government. They could have stopped the genocide before it began.
They knew exactly what was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Lewis said, the French peacekeeping mission eventually
sent to the region allowed a huge number of Hutu attackers to flee
the country to neighboring Congo, then Zaire, ``thereby ushering in
the larger Great Lakes catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is almost no redemptive feature to the conduct of the
government of France,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the United States, which blocked the Security Council
from sending peacekeepers to Rwanda once the massacres had begun,
Lewis said its role was ``an almost incomprehensible scar of shame
on American foreign policy.'' Speaking personally, he said, ``I
don't know how Madeleine Albright lives with it.'' Secretary of
State Albright was then the U.S. representative at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, on a subsequent visit to Africa, apologized
to Rwanda for the lack of international response, as has Belgium.
France has never expressed remorse or accepted blame.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of African Unity report is very critical of the
Roman Catholic Church. ``We were shocked by the role of the
church,'' Lewis said Friday. Although priests and lay Catholics
were among those who tried to save Tutsis, there were other church
officials who did not; some helped lure Tutsis to their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   There were ``leaders of the church who did not speak out
strongly and take stands,'' Lewis said. ``Since Rwanda is a very
Catholic country, we felt we had to say something.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lewis, who introduced the report here Friday, the
panel consisted of Sir Ketumile Masire, a former president of
Botswana and the panel leader; Ahmadou Toumani Toure, former
president of Mali; Lisbet Palme, a Swedish child psychologist and
expert on the U.N. Committee on the Rights of the Child; Ellen
Johnson-Sirleaf, former finance minister of Liberia; P.N. Bhagwati,
former chief justice of India's Supreme Court; and Hocine Djoudi,
an Algerian judge and diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Anglican church authorities have apologized for ignoring human
rights abuses or for acts that encouraged Hutu death squads. The
Roman Catholic Church has not, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The 315-page report is available online at www.oau-oau.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
