<HEADLINE>
HIT-OR-MISS JOKES CAN'T KILL THE FUN OF `SCARY MOVIE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SCARY MOVIE 
Directed by: Keenen Ivory Wayans 
Screenplay by: Shawn Wayans &AMP; Marlon Wayans &AMP; Buddy Johnson &AMP; Phil
Beauman and Jason Friedberg &AMP; Aaron Seltzer 
Starring: Jon Abrahams, Carmen Electra, Shannon Elizabeth, Anna
Faris, Kurt Fuller, Regina Hall, Lochlyn Munro, Cheri Oteri, Dave
Sheridan, Marlon Wayans, Shawn Wayans 
Running time: 85 minutes 
Rated: R (strong crude sexual humor, language, drug use and
violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's summer gross-out movie envelope-pusher isn't ``Me,
Myself and Irene.'' It's ``Scary Movie.'' There's nowhere it won't
go, no taboo or body orifice beyond its rude and sometimes very
funny reach. Essentially, it's a parody of the parodies that the
``Scream'' movies were, played out in the lively style of ``In
Living Color.'' The common denominator of course is the Wayans
brothers _ three of them in this case: Keenen Ivory, who directed,
and siblings Shawn and Marlon, doing double duty as screenwriters
and actors. ``Scream'' is hardly the only movie being spoofed. ``I
Know What You Did Last Summer'' is fair game here, too, and a
couple of hilarious jabs are reserved for ``The Matrix'' and ``The
Blair Witch Project'' (one not-so-hilarious bit takes a shot at
``The Sixth Sense'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Scary Movie'' peaks pretty early when an endangered teen flees
her house, gets as far as her swmmming pool, then sees two traffic
signs. One says ``Safety,'' the other says ``Death.'' Fans of the
genre will know which she'll heed. Ever since ``Friday the 13th,''
``Halloween,'' and ``The Evil Dead,'' the genre has rested on a
solid, if inexplicable, base of teens rushing to dark, lonely
places where they know violent murders occur. Certainly the
teenaged students (played by actors in their 20s and early 30s) who
attend B.A. Corpse High School know every cliche of the horny teen
horror genre, with its jocks, sex kittens, know-it-alls, and fringe
characters like the student pothead and the doofus cop.
</P>
<P>
   They're all trying to dodge the knife-wielding maniac in the
black hooded cape and, in this case, white molded plastic mask
dominated by a big smile, as if the killer left the costume shop in
a hurry and grabbed the mask of comedy instead of the mask of
tragedy. Cheri Oteri makes the most of the by-now obligatory
exploitative TV reporter role, shoving her mike into the faces of
the glazed teens and shrieking at her cameraman while trying to
harvest material for a sequel to her best-seller, ``You're Dead,
I'm Rich.'' The new face in the cast is Anna Faris as a sweet girl
with a drug-dealer father. Carmen Electra, of ``Baywatch'' fame,
has most of the flatulence jokes. Shannon Elizabeth, the ``American
Pie'' dish, plays Buffy, hottest of the hot.
</P>
<P>
   The question facing the target audience for ``Scary Movie'' is
whether the funny bits will be enough of a payoff for sitting
through the tedious stuff between them. ``Scary Movie'' reminds us
repeatedly that not every joke involving bodily functions, or
malfunctions, is automatically funny. Its structure is, to put it
softly, ramshackle. Much of it plays like a weekly TV show, where
the hope is that the laughs will be enough to compensate for a
thrown-together quality. With the Wayans brothers doing the
throwing, the satire is sharp and knowing. Obviously, they've sat
through a lot of prurient slasher movies. Even though it's a little
late in the genre's history (most slasher movies these days parody
themselves), they are quick enough on the draw to yank laughs from
this less-than-fresh subject matter before genre cliches and this
film's flimsiness close in for the kill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1347EDT &QL; 
