<HEADER>
A5477 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-JESUS-BOS &LR;      07-07 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-JESUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JESUS' SON' PARALLELS DRUGGIE'S HIGHS, LOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
JESUS' SON 
Directed by: Alison Maclean 
Screenplay by: Elizabeth Cuthrell, David Urrutia and Oren Moverman
(based on Denis Johnson's book of short stories) 
Starring: Billy Crudup, Samantha Morton, Denis Leary, Jack Black,
Will Patton, Greg Germann, Holly Hunter, Dennis Hopper 
Running time: 109 minutes 
Rated: R (graphic drug use, strong language, sexuality and some
violent images) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The downside of drugs, William S. Burroughs once said, was that
you spend hours on end zonked out somewhere, staring at the tips of
your shoes. ``Jesus' Son,'' Alison Maclean's film of Denis
Johnson's short stories that hopscotch around the 1970s drug scene,
is too honest not to face up to the fact that it's often a downer,
with a sweet but largely passive protagonist. The film's strategy,
not unlike that of drugs, is to hook you on the highs so that
you'll be willing to ride out the lows. Certainly the cast couldn't
be more diverting. Billy Crudup draws on an endless supply of
vacant charm and sweetness as the protagonist, FH, short for a
nickname that cannot be printed in these pages.
</P>
<P>
   His convincing innocence makes you hope he survives this
fractured, episodic narrative that fitfully aspires to be a cross
between ``Drugstore Cowboy'' and ``Natural Born Killers,'' although
the only ones FH and his pals seem likely to kill are one another.
The film begins with FH in voiceover, recalling a hitchhiking
episode about which he had a bad feeling. Not that it stopped him
from getting into the car anyway. FH is that kind of guy, never one
to buck his karma. The film stumbles through a series of violent
collisions and encounters that FH always seems to walk away from,
including a bad drug trip that kills one of his acquaintances.
Brains are not FH's strong point, but he does bring to his druggy
odyssey a gift for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Maclean, a transplanted New Zealander from Canada, keeps the
film afloat by surrounding FH with a string of vivid diversions,
most notably Samantha Morton's dazzlingly harrowing turn as a
cocaine addict, Michelle, for whom FH falls heavily. Following her
extraordinary performance as Sean Penn's mute but eloquent
girlfriend in Woody Allen's ``Sweet and Lowdown,'' Morton confirms
the impression she made as an electrifying actress in ``Under the
Skin.'' She has no hard edges; her intensity crackles from within.
Her performance here is thrillingly fearless, stripped of all the
kinds of sentimentality with which drug addicts (especially women)
are usually portrayed. Morton's Michelle is open-eyed, powered by a
doomed desperation into which you're quite willing to believe
Crudup's dimwitted latter-day Candide would be swept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus' Son,'' as its title implies, is not entirely divorced
from the idea of redemption. Yet it's a long time coming, and until
it does, the film relies almost entirely on this or that character
coming along to inject dramatic fireworks. Some are overt, such as
Jack Black's manic, pill-popping emergency room orderly and kindred
soul to FH. It's a juicy follow-up to Black's motor-mouthed record
store clerk in ``High Fidelity.'' We may, I think, consider Black's
movie career launched. And just when the film seems ready to
subside like a punctured balloon, along comes Holly Hunter with an
extraordinarily graceful performance as an unexpected dance partner
for FH. The good news is that ``Jesus' Son'' has some delicious
diversions. The bad news is that it constantly needs them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1348EDT &QL; 
