<HEADER>
A5478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-KID-BOS &LR;      07-07 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-KID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIS AMUSES IN INNER-CITY BUDDY PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE KID 
Directed by: Jon Turteltaub 
Screenplay by: Audrey Wells 
Starring: Bruce Willis, Spencer Breslin, Emily Mortimer, Lily
Tomlin, Jean Smart, Chi McBride, Daniel Von Bargen, Dana Ivey 
Running time: 101 minutes 
Rated: PG (mild language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Kid,'' charm goes to war with sentimentality, and
sentimentality wins. But before the film succumbs to a gelatinous
pace that hangs its rigging out to dry, Bruce Willis brings a
becomingly deft economy to his performance as a prosperous but
unhappy image consultant named Russ who would rather not get in
touch with his inner child, but does. Strictly speaking, his
8-year-old self, Rusty, makes contact with him, all in the name of
therapy. When Russ shows up with a chronic twitching eye at a
therapist's and tells her he left his childhood in the past, she
replies, ``It doesn't want to stay in the past, does it?''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Russ doesn't want to be reminded of the pudgy loser he
was as a kid. Not that the time-traveling kid is all that impressed
with the 40-year-old he has become, either. Young Rusty thinks old
Russ is a loser because he isn't married and doesn't even have a
dog. It takes Russ a long time to figure out that their interface
isn't about him going back in time and helping the kid replay a
scuffle with bullies in a schoolyard, but about taking a cue from
the kid and learning to lighten up and loosen up. Although ``The
Kid'' contains fleeting resemblances to ``Back to the Future'' and
``Big'' and, for that matter, ``A Christmas Carol,'' it never
generates the sense of lift those films have. It's a reluctant
buddy comedy, with both halves of Russ's bifurcated self stumbling
toward integration as they learn to cut each other some slack.
</P>
<P>
   While Willis is busy keeping the older Russ's consternation
comically viable, young Spencer Breslin projects a screenful of sad
pre-pubescent clarity as he removes any doubt that the older Russ's
troubles have their origin in those of the younger Rusty. Perhaps
significantly, the shrink drops out of the picture moments after
she enters it. Clearly, it's up to Russ to heal himself, or,
perhaps more accurately, his selves. One helping hand comes from
Jean Smart's good-hearted TV anchorwoman, whom he meets on an
airplane. Others come from Lily Tomlin, underutilized in a generic
role as his overburdened assistant, and from Emily Mortimer as a
photographer who's soft on him and is gamely trying to hang in
there until he grows up.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, we have a handful of women graciously, patiently
waiting for a man to grow up, a scenario far from unknown in
Hollywood, not to mention other quarters. ``The Kid'' has to work
hard to convince us it's the stunted man who deserves our sympathy,
not the women. It isn't every man who gets the opportunity to
behave both figuratively and literally like an 8-year-old. Willis
and Breslin manage it ingratiatingly. Willis underplayed to very
funny effect in his recent farce, ``The Whole Nine Yards.'' He
repeats the feat here, although marginally less hilariously, while
Breslin cements his hold on our sympathies. Too bad ``The Kid''
gets bogged down in its sentimental manipulations. It has more
going for it than you might suppose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
