<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-TRIXIE-BOS &LR;      07-07 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TRIXIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WINNING EMILY WATSON STRIVES TO SAVE `TRIXIE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
TRIXIE 
Written and directed by: Alan Rudolph 
Starring: Emily Watson, Dermot Mulroney, Nick Nolte, Nathan Lane,
Brittany Murphy, Lesley Ann Warren, Will Patton, Stephen Lang 
Running time: 117 minutes 
Rated: R (some language, sexuality and violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Trixie'' is a film that needs to be carried past its
imperfections, and Emily Watson almost succeeds in carrying it.
It's an Alan Rudolph film, which is another way of saying that it's
an idiosyncratic mood piece. It's too elliptical to be the
screwball noir Rudolph set out to write. It's just too wispy. But
like the dogged waif named Trixie, with a Chicago working-girl
accent and a determination to succeed as a professional sleuth,
Watson perseveres even though everyone Trixie meets seems almost
eager to morph into someone unexpected. Trixie is the kind of girl
who talks in malapropisms, yet is a pretty straight thinker who
makes herself understood.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's Trixie, bright eyes burning like coals in her pale moon
face, is at her best when she sits down at an old-boy restaurant
with Nick Nolte's state senator who's pickled in his own corruption
and incapable of talking straight talk. He simply babbles on in
double talk (much of it taken, Rudolph says, from actual political
speeches) until the problem goes away. She doesn't understand his
empty rant; he doesn't understand her fractured English. And yet
when their mutual non-communication is over, he understands that
her righteous anger is a threat to him and she understands that the
corrupt pol has done some pretty awful things.
</P>
<P>
   Trixie is determined to bring to justice the killer of Lesley
Ann Warren's crumbling cabaret singer, who before her death was
humiliatingly used by the pol and a rich developer played by Will
Patton, in one of his sinister turns. The guy's henchman, played by
Dermot Mulroney, considers himself a ladies' man, but Trixie thinks
she detects something sincere beneath the verbal oil slick of his
mechanical advances. All this is a sideline to Trixie, whose
sleuthing ambitions take the form of a security job in a drab
lakefront casino. There she befriends the house comic, played by
Nathan Lane with a gloss of sentimentality on his Broadway belter
persona. Even he has his secrets, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trixie'' might have proved more enticing if Trixie had a few
secrets. She's the only one in the film who doesn't. There's
nothing to be revealed about Trixie. She isn't given enough range
in this script, where promising element after promising element
dwindles into nothingness. Yet Watson, against the odds, keeps
finding ways to wring appeal from Trixie's bruised working-class
sparrow, even when Rudolph sends the mixed metaphors and
malapropisms into overdrive. They'd count for more if there were
fewer of them. Just as the film would count for more if there were
more of it.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many wonderful moments in ``Trixie'' and so few
films like it that you wish Rudolf had given it a few more
rewrites. Even though this latest film stalls out, even when he
isn't on his best game, Rudolph remains a simpatico filmmaker. He's
a romantic, determined to persist in believing in victories of the
heart. Watson says she chose to do the role because it gave her a
chance to play a comic role for once, a woman discovering her own
strength. Obvious as the limits of the script may be, it's
impossible to dislike Trixie and her tinny little voice, especially
when she narrows her eyes and says things like ``The sword of
Damocles is hanging over Pandora's box.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
