<SLUG> BC-TV-LONGITUDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE TIME FOR THIS CLOCK SAGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
LONGITUDE 
Starring: Michael Gambon, Jeremy Irons, Ian Hart, Gemma Jones 
Directed by: Charles Sturridge 
On: A&AMP;E 
Time: Sunday at 8 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compared to the no-brainerism of TV voyeurism, a four-hour
British movie about two men fixated on clocks sounds like a night
at the SATs. Tick-toxic.
</P>
<P>
   But I urge you not to let the plot description of ``Longitude,''
with its 18th-century search for a pendulum-free timepiece that
could keep true time on a ship, scare you away. Directed by Charles
Sturridge of ``Brideshead Revisited,'' ``Longitude'' is a
surprisingly terrific saga whose easy-to-follow scientific themes
are simply the backdrop for two stirring stories about passion,
obsession, and madness. And driving those two stories are
picturesque ocean adventures, clocks that look like fragile
sculptures, the coming specter of World War II, and a pair of
beautifully paced performances by Michael Gambon and Jeremy Irons.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant plot, set in the 1700s, follows a Yorkshire
carpenter named John Harrison (Gambon), who is bent on building a
clock that will help sailors determine their longitude. It's easy
to underestimate the importance of measuring longitude dependably,
but at one time, inaccurate longitude readings were a common cause
of gruesome disasters at sea. Harrison is motivated by the desire
to save lives, but also by Parliament's promise of a 20,000-pound
prize to anyone who can solve the longitude problem. He is assisted
in the rigors of his miniaturized work by his son (Ian Hart), a
loyal boy with whom he seems to have a nonverbal connection. In
scenes that range from the comic to the horrifying, the haughty
Parliament board continually sets up unfair obstacles for the
Harrisons, as though it would prefer that they fail.
</P>
<P>
   The Harrisons' struggle, which threatens their father-son bond,
is interwoven with the 20th-century struggle of a World War I
veteran officer named Rupert Gould (Irons), who is obsessed with
Harrison's clocks. Having recently survived a nervous breakdown,
Gould pours his hope into the reassembly and restoration of the
clocks. It's as though he identifies with the complex mechanisms
and their need for protection from the coming upheaval of World War
II. As he refuses to turn away from his unpaid work on the Harrison
clocks and pursue a living, his marriage and his ability to cope
begin to fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Irons is incredible, underplaying the strains on Gould until
those critical moments when Gould can no longer contain himself.
It's the kind of performance that shifts and deepens in the course
of the movie. But ``Longitude'' surely belongs to Gambon, who gives
a sympathetic turn as the impolitic, genius carpenter. While the
cracks in Gould's modern consciousness are compelling, Harrison's
unending ingenuity and willpower make the movie rousing from scene
to scene. You feel the weight of his achievement, not only in his
devoted work but in his persistence in the face of those in
authority.
</P>
<P>
   As it moves back and forth between the two plots, ``Longitude''
never loses direction. Sturridge cleverly plays the two men's lives
off each other, and the parallels click despite the differences in
the time periods. Clocks may change over the centuries, and
Harrison's time of hope may fade to Gould's time of dread, but the
heart remains the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
