A5483 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-BOS &LR;      07-07 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HUMOROUS ESSAYS, SEDARIS GOES TO PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
Me Talk Pretty One Day 
By David Sedaris 
Little, Brown, 288 pp., $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing up in North Carolina, David Sedaris felt betrayed by his
own tongue. Relegated to speech lessons for a lisp, he bought a
pocket Thesaurus and memorized an s-free vocabulary, much to the
dismay of his therapist. (``If I wanted to spend my life as David
Thedarith, then so be it.'')
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for readers, Sedaris has found his voice. In ``Me Talk
Pretty One Day,'' the National Public Radio humorist has written a
savagely funny laugh track for his own life. Following two popular
books, ``Naked'' and ``Barrel Fever,'' his latest collection of
essays moves him to Paris and continues to come to terms with his
fractured family history.
</P>
<P>
   Sedaris fleshes out the characters who surround him: his
tough-talking, truth-telling mother and his IBM engineer father,
the one with the yen for Blue Note jazz artists. His profane
brother Rooster, who ``by the time he had reached the second grade,
spoke much like the toothless fishermen casting their nets into the
Albemarle Sound.''
</P>
<P>
   He comes to term with his own oddness early on. Back to fifth
grade speech lessons: ``None of the therapy students were girls.
They were all boys like me who kept movie star scrapbooks and made
their own curtains. `You don't want to be doing that,' the men in
our families would say. `That's a girl thing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What's new for this gay Greek sort-of scion of Carolina is the
Continent. With scornful honesty (``. . . according to several
reliable sources, I tended to exhaust people''), Sedaris
reconstructs his relationship with boyfriend Hugh and a certain
house in Normandy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see this as a romantic idea,'' he writes. ``It had
nothing to do with France itself, with wearing hats or writing
tortured letters from a sidewalk cafe. I didn't care where
Hemingway drank or Alice B. Toklas had her mustache trimmed. What I
found appealing in life abroad was the inevitable sense of
helplessness it would inspire.'')
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving New York, Sedaris enrolls in a beginning French
course, where he memorizes the kind of dialogue that never, ever
materializes when traveling abroad. Characters steer clear of the
past tense. Skies are often blue. Sedaris despairs. ``Taken one by
one, the assorted nouns and verbs were within my grasp, but due to
drug use and a close working relationship with chemical solvents,
it's all I can do to recite my zip code, let alone an entire
conversation devoted to the pleasures of direct sunlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Language, as always, is a snare. ``Hugh and I returned to
Normandy the following summer, and I resumed my identity as the
village idiot. `See you again yesterday!' I said to the butcher.
`Ashtray! Bottleneck!' . . . On the following trip I sanded the
floors and began the practice of learning ten new words a day.
Slum, facial swelling, death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every essay hits the mark. His attempt at toilet humor
(``Big Boy'') falls flat, and his riff on nouvelle food in New York
seems dated. ``A Shiner Like a Diamond,'' about his father and
sister Amy, is too disjointed to resonate.
</P>
<P>
   But Sedaris, the twisted American in Paris, is still pretty
funny by any standard, and somewhere, there is meta- in the
madness. Much of his writing is arch, over-the-top, and frankly
gay. But like ``Will and Grace,`` the television sitcom starring
gay characters, Sedaris swims in the mainstream. There's nothing
underground about NPR or NBC; gay sensibility can be unpacked,
unwrapped and laughed at. Ethnic Jewish humor, after all, moved
from the private confines of family and tribe to the public art of
Sid Caesar and Woody Allen.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of his self-loathing and super-sibilant past, David
Sedaris is fomenting the same sort of revolution. As he himself
puts it, ``Paris, it seems, is where I've come to dream about
America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
