<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINT OVER THE OLD STAIN ON STUCCO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July   09, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I splashed oil stain/sealer on my stucco wall. How can I
repair it without damaging the paint or the stucco? Some friends
recommend acid wash.
</P>
<P>
   BENEDICT, Tracy, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's hope you read this soonerr or later, because my e-mail
answer to your e-mail question got hurled back in the handyman's
face.
</P>
<P>
   So, the answer is: Getting an oil-based stain off stucco or any
other concrete is virtually impossible, unless it is just minutes
old. It can be dissolved with paint thinner when it is still wet,
but once it dries, that's all she wrote. You have to let it wear
off, which would take years. An acid wash won't work because the
stucco is painted, and acid takes off only lime in the stucco.
Chemical paint remover will remove the stain, but also take off the
paint.
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet is to paint the stain with a latex house paint or
a latex solid color stain. If the stain is quite dark, apply a
stain killer such as latex-based Kilz first. Otherwise the stain
might bleed through paint or stain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I need a new burner. The oilman wants to sell me a rebuilt
burner, which will cost $400 vs. $700 for a new one. Is that
reasonable?
</P>
<P>
   SUE SAVARESE, South Hamilton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, that is reasonable. It is reasonable if there's a
guarantee with it, and if it falls under your service contract,
which you should have anyway. No guarantee, no deal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The linoleum in my kitchen, hall, and den is worn out, and
the only thing I can do for the moment is to put a rug over it.
Could I cover it with the stick-on vinyl tile? A floor man offered
to install hardwood over the linoleum for $5,000. I thought that
was high.
</P>
<P>
   RUTH FOSTER, Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can put the stick-on tile over the old linoleum, as long
as the old material is flat and even, and not coming loose. It is a
jury rig of sorts, but will do well enough, and you can still put
down your favorite carpet.
</P>
<P>
   The price for the hardwood floor job sounds high, although I
don't know how much flooring would be used. But I think you could
save a bundle if you install prefinished hardwood. With prefinished
flooring, you eliminate the sanding and three coats of polyurethane
varnish or any other finish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some asphalt shingles made several tarry marks on my
bluestone steps during a roofing project. In fact, a lot of little
marks. How can I remove them?
</P>
<P>
   MAUREEN McNEIL, Marblehead, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try pressure washing the stains; it will not hurt the
bluestone or any mortar between stones. If that doesn't work, try
scraping off any that will come off with a putty knife. Then sand
the rest of it off; sanding will leave light marks on the
bluestone, but weathering will even them out in a short time.
</P>
<P>
   If the tar is really stubborn, dissolve it with paint thinner,
then put baking soda on the stain to absorb the dissolved tar.
Leave it for half an hour, and sweep it off. Repeat as necessary.
The bluestone will absorb almost anything, and if you do not use
the baking soda, the dissolved tar will go deeper _ and more
permanently _ into the bluestone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The ceilings in my 1950s house are skimcoated with calcimine;
they are smooth but peeling off the plaster. The ceiling is full of
shallow craters, 10 inches in diameter. Can I fill them with joint
compound to smooth out the ceiling before repainting?
</P>
<P>
   MARJ NEEDHAM, Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If it is calcimine, it is probably paint rather than a
skimcoat. Calcimine was popular before and after the war, and an
inexpensive, good-looking finish. But it was not compatible with
any paints; people would paint over calcimine with latex or oil
paint and the paint would come right off on the roller.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot fill those craters with anything; the joint compound
may stick to the plaster but will not stick to any calcimine;
nothing sticks to calcimine except more calcimine or a calcimine
substitute.
</P>
<P>
   You can do one of two things: Scrape, sand, and wash off all the
calcimine, revealing that fine old plaster. Real plaster. The
calcimine should wash off with one or more washings, and you must
get rid of every trace. Then paint with a latex ceiling paint.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is to sand the ceiling smooth, feather-edging
the borders of the craters to even them out. Then paint with
Kal-Coat or other calcimine substitute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You suggested using Era with oxygen bleach to clean mold off
my semitransparent stained shingles. I can't find it; I can only
find Era with a bleach alternative. Where can I find it with oxygen
bleach?
</P>
<P>
   J.F., Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I believe the bleach alternative is oxygen bleach. Try it; if
it works, fine. If it doesn't, go to the next best thing: one part
household belach and five or more parts water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5488 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      07-07 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTERS FOR THE INTELLIGENT FAN'S ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For fans of intelligent rock, the pairing of the Red Hot Chili
Peppers with Foo Fighters is manna from heaven. For Foo Fighters'
frontman Dave Grohl, it's something more than simply a fine tour
match. Grohl played drums in a group that opened up for the Peppers
nearly a decade ago, as both alternative rock and Grohl's former
band _ Nirvana _ were poised to revolutionize mainstream rock
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I saw these guys were nine years ago, when
Nirvana and Pearl Jam opened up for the Peppers,'' Grohl recalls in
a phone conversation from his manager's office in L.A. ``Yeah, it
brings back memories. This has been the most exciting tour, besides
the first one, that we've ever done. I guess most of all I feel
good about myself, because I know in some way I've kept the ball
rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Grohl is equal parts facetious and sincere _ devoted to music
while at the same time harboring a healthy cynicism about the music
industry machinery, and a healthy sense of humor about himself. In
November, Foo Fighters released its third CD, ``There Is Nothing
Left To Lose.'' Since then, the band has fielded tour offers from
Oasis, No Doubt, and Korn _ all of which Foo Fighters graciously
declined. When the Peppers called, there wasn't a moment's
hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Peppers came up from punk, but they have hard rock
elements and ballads, too,'' Grohl says, pointing up similarities
between the two bands. ``It seems like they're about music, not
about image or roaring, crazy, dangerous youth dynamics. With the
other bands, we weren't sure the styles were compatible. I'm a fan
of those bands. But if we were to get out in front of Korn's
audience and play something that sounded like the Eagles, we'd get
our (butts) kicked.''
</P>
<P>
   Grohl and bandmates have ventured into more sophisticated,
melodic, sensitive-guy terrain on the latest Foo's album, and
Grohl, a veteran of punk bands, has no shame. On the contrary:
``I'm a little unhappy with popular music these days, and the lack
of introspection is my biggest problem. People aren't inspiring
audiences to reach inside themselves. When I was younger I was in
hardcore bands that were about being hard, fast, and loud. Then I
was in a band (Nirvana) that was hard, fast, and loud with feel and
melody. It was an awakening. Kurt made it seem so simple, simpler
than it is. ''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 Grohl stepped out from behind the drum kit and released
Foo Fighters self-titled debut, made up mainly of material he began
writing and recording before Nirvana ended with Cobain's suicide in
1994. He then formed a band to promote it. And that, Grohl says,
was the genesis of the many personnel changes Foo Fighters has seen
in its brief life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bass player (Nate Mendel), the intellectual of the group,
came up with a theory that makes sense,'' says Grohl. ``We've never
really had time to grow up as a band. The first record was a fluke:
a demo tape recorded and then used as an excuse to have a band.
After about a year of touring the drummer didn't want to play
someone else's drum parts, then Pat (guitarist Pat Smear), who's
never been in a band for very long, said `you guys should be a
three-piece'. (Two more guitarists have followed in his wake.) Most
bands go through that sort of thing before they even make a record.
We finally feel like the band is what it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The current line-up _ Grohl on vocals and guitar, Mendel,
drummer Taylor Hawkins, and guitarist Chris Shiflett _ recorded
``There Is Nothing Left To Lose'' in the studio Grohl built in his
suburban Virginia home _ lovingly described as ``kind of the '70s
hippie house amid the Colonials.'' Grohl credits the casual,
comfortable atmosphere _ no label executives offering suggestions,
no clock ticking, and most of all recording his guitar parts
sitting on the couch he's owned for eight years _ for the album's
natural, breezy feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what I hated about L.A. (where Grohl relocated from
Seattle after forming Foo Fighters) was brought on by missing
Virginia,'' says Grohl, a native Virginian who also has an
apartment in New York City. ``At a time in your life when you feel
lost, and are searching for things that are real, L.A. is the worst
place to be. Here, noone questions anyone's intentions. People live
for the sake of being happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Foo Fighters, which has been on the road for nearly a year, will
tour for another six months, Grohl says, before retreating to his
house to record another album. ``I think the new record will come
out a lot sooner than people expect; maybe early next year,'' says
Grohl. ``With a studio in the basement, we could make one once a
month!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the Children Friends and colleagues of the late Morphine
frontman Mark Sandman have established the Mark Sandman Music
Education Fund, to develop and support innovative music education
for children in Cambridge, Mass. The organization will fund grants
for instruments and recording-studio time, develop a music program
for kids with substance-abuse problems, and create an database of
music professionals online as a resource for the community. For
information and guidelines write to: MSMEF, Box 382085, Cambridge,
MA, 02238.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free Love Making good on a promise she made at the Digital
Hollywood Conference last month, Hole frontwoman Courtney Love is
making a generous quantity of her band's material available for
free download at the Hole Web site (www.holemusic.com). The 50
available MP3 tracks include live cuts and outtakes in addition to
album tracks that span Hole's career. Said the outspoken Love in a
lengthy manifesto posted on Salon.com: ``Since I've basically been
giving my music away for free under the old system, I'm not afraid
of wireless MP3 files. If record companies aren't going to do for
me what I can do for myself with my 19-year-old Webmistress on my
own Web site, then they need to get the hell out of my way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attention: budding lyricists British pop brat Robbie Williams is
having an uncharacteristic spasm of altruism, most likely inspired
by his deep-pocketed Internet sponsors. The winner of a contest to
write lyrics to a new song on Williams' Web site,
www.robbiewilliams.co.uk, will get 1,000 British pounds and a
publishing contract with EMI. Don't get any fancy ideas about
raking in the bucks from sales of the Robbie Williams album with
your song on it, though. Williams isn't making any promises that
he'll actually record the future masterpiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
