   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN-HOUSE _ President Clinton will announce plans for
restoring Abraham Lincoln's summer retreat home, three miles from
the Capitol. The14-room Gothic-Revival cottage is where Lincoln
drafted the Emancipation Proclamation. David Long, history
professor at Eastern Carolina University in Greenville,N.C., will
be at Clinton's side. Long has led a battle to preserve the
historic residence. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-UTEXAS _ Free airfare and a good time apparently worked
in favor of the University of Texas Law School. The number of
African-American students who plan to attend UT in the fall is
double the number from last year and officials believe it's because
of an outreach effort this spring that brought accepted students to
campus for a look-see. They want to expand to hispanic students
next spring. (Jayson, Austin American-Statesman). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-FORUM _ATLANTA _Expectations were high in parts of
Georgia's Latino community six months ago. Four people appointed by
Gov. Roy Barnes were recommending changes to state laws and
policies to help Georgia's growing Latino population. They held a
press conference to give their report to the governor, but his
staff said Barnes was too busy to attend.
</P>
<P>
   His absence frustrated some Latinos. Now some Latinos are more
frustrated because not much has become of recommendations made by
the Latino Forum that Barnes appointed. It's a different story in
North Carolina, another state with a fast-growing Hispanic
population where thousands of Latinos work in construction,
poultry, agriculture and hotels and restaurants as they do in
Georgia. Latino leaders in North Carolina meet regularly with
high-ranking state official and the governor. In fact the Office of
Hispanic/Latino Affairs, is part of the governor's office. (Bixler,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIALNETHAWAY-COLUMN _ A friend sent me a list called
``Tips for a Lifetime.'' Most of these tips, although useful, would
be more appropriate for someone who ran a Martha Stewart-styled
household. That's not me. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVEDMINTER-COLUMN _ Our cousin, Don Harp, is a preacher. He knows
exactly what to say when a family member crosses the Jordan. One of
the things he pointed out at Aunt Ida Mae's funeral was that we are
running out of what Tom Brokaw and a lot of us think of as The
Greatest Generation. ``Who among us is going to take their place?''
Don asked. It is a worrisome question. (Minter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Mary Ann Wietze, the beloved principal at Helke
Elementary School, died June 23, at 67, from cancer, at her home in
West Milton. But her presence will continue to be felt at the
Vandalia-Butler school that she ran with high spirits and high
expectations. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
