<HEADER>
A5496 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX     07-07 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME THINGS CHANGE, SOME STAY THE SAME AT SPECIAL PLACE CALLED
NOTRE DAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two weeks ago I told of my return to Notre Dame with my dear
friend, Don Hellinghausen of Midland, Texas, for the 50th reunion
of our class.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the column focused on memories of our undergraduate
years stirred by our return to the place we called home from 1946
until 1950. Today's focus will be on the university Don and I found
on our return last month and the reunion itself.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 buildings have been added. But all have been built on
the perimeter of the campus we knew 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Little has changed about the campus that existed then.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a change in the student body. It is larger, smarter
(I doubt if I could meet today's scholastic requirements) and
better diversified.
</P>
<P>
   The camaraderie that existed in our days is alive and well
today. The athletes still do not receive special privileges, other
than the training table, during the season of their sports. It is
difficult to distinguish between the rich and the not-so-rich.
</P>
<P>
   I was impressed by the students I encountered on my return. The
university provided 30 vans to transport the returning exes around
the campus. They were driven by students who were attending summer
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure that members of the Class of '50 appeared ancient to
them. That's OK. They appeared so very young to us.
</P>
<P>
   I found each to be gracious and prepared to go out of his or her
way to make the oldtimers' visit as pleasant as possible. As I was
getting out of a van, the driver noted my nametag and said,
``You're from Fort Worth. I'm from Grapevine.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Frost undoubtedly is the brightest chauffeur I ever had
_ she will receive her doctoral degree in civil engineering next
month. When she learned I was still writing a column for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, she wanted to know if I ever knew Ellen
Thornley.
</P>
<P>
   I said that not only did I know her, but I was instrumental in
hiring her as a copy editor many years ago when I was managing
editor. Heather explained that her mother used to babysit for
Ellen's son.
</P>
<P>
   I informed Heather that Ellen had done very well in the news
business. Today she is a managing editor of this newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame went out of its way to welcome back the Class of '50,
which it described as its ``beloved sons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Edward A. ``Monk'' Malloy, the university's president,
was present at many of the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   So was president emeritus, the Rev. Theodore M. Hesburgh,
credited by many with elevating the academic reputation of the
university. Most people know Father Ted as an outstanding
administrator. Many in our class also knew him as an outstanding
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The most important part of the return was the opportunity to
embrace classmates we had not seen since graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Note the use of the verb ``embrace.'' Fifty years ago, we were
more comfortable with a manly handshake, confining embraces to
family members. Some changes are good.
</P>
<P>
   There was an embrace for the Rev. Len Constantini and
recollections of the nights we tried to evade our Zahm Hall floor
monitor, ``Creeper'' Murray, who would prowl darkened halls with a
flashlight after lights-out at 11 p. m.
</P>
<P>
   There was an embrace for Don Derivaux, who became a Trappist
monk after leaving Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   I listened in almost disbelief as he described how a dentist
taught him to perform dental work _ including the extraction of
wisdom teeth _ on fellow monks. Fortunately they also taught him
how to give deadening injections.
</P>
<P>
   Father Don finally gave up the silence of the monastery _ and
his unlicensed dental practice _ to become involved in parish work
in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   There was a note of sadness when we received the list of nearly
400 classmates who had died. A number fell during the Korean War,
which started three weeks after our class of 1,100 graduated.
</P>
<P>
   It also was sad to see how many classmates had been slowed by
strokes, heart ailments and other afflictions faced by those in
their 70s. This made me realize how blessed I am to be able to
still get on the tennis court two or three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   When I graduated half a century ago, I knew I had been fortunate
to have been a part of a special place called Notre Dame. When I
returned 50 years later, I quickly determined it is still a very
special place where its ``beloved sons (and daughters)'' become
devoted to God, family, country and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to the
Star-Telegram and is the newspaper's professional in residence at
Texas Christian University's Department of Journalism. He can be
contacted at precord(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
