<SLUG> BC-sat </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN 
 

</HEADLINE>
 city budget-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   FOOTBALL LEASE  _ Finishing its football stadium lease with the
county, NFL team and rodeo is the second most important piece of
business the sports authority faces this year. But like its arena
deal, a completed lease has been delayed for months. If delays last
much longer taxpayers will be hit for millions because of spiraling
interest rates. Moreover, by August or September the sports
authority, which needs to sell bonds but can't do so without a
lease, will run out of money to pay the contractors. An analysis of
what's holding up the lease, and its repercussions.  Eric Berger . 
 
 DOCTOR _  One week after her father was acquitted on charges of
sexually molesting her over a period of 11 years, a 20-year-old
Houston college student says that her father bought the not guilty
verdict with his money, power and high-priced attorneys. Dr.
Bradley Wertman says that's silly and that even though he was found
not guilty that he still hopes his daughter can get help. Wertman's
three-week trial was a fascinating study of how a family can be
torn apart by sexual abuse charges and the defense says it shows
how a psychologist can reinforce ``manufactured memories'' of
sexual abuse. Good stuff. Reax from all sides. Developing. Steve
Brewer 
 
  SETTLE  _ City wants to pay a former customs agent $100,000 to
settle a lawsuit over his arrest in connection with the ``party
planning service'' known as the Salad Sisters. Edwin Heitschmidt
has accused the city, and local law enforcement, of false arrest,
malicious prosecution and of causing nerve damage to his wrists by
keeping a pair of handcuffs on him for three hours during a search
of his girlfriend's home. He was convicted of promoting
prostitution, but that conviction later was overturned.  Matt
Schwartz  
 
 LAWRENCE  _ Lee Wells-Flowers has observed her only child's
birthday without him for eight years now. Lawrence Wells' body has
never been found, and his killer has never been charged.
Wells-Flowers discovered the only thing that got her through the
grief and anger was tireless work on behalf of victims' rights, and
haunting the prime suspect in her son's death, a multi-convicted
felon who is presently on the lam again. w/art  S.K. Bardwell 
 
AUTOS  _ As part of its technology upgrades, the Harris County Tax
Assessor-Collector's Office will now allow county residents to
register their cars and trucks on the Internet. This will require
payment by credit card, but visits to the tax office or mailings
are no longer necessary. Joe Stinebaker.  
 
 RECORDS  _ The state Supreme Court ruled psychologists don't have
to reveal a child's mental health records to parents if it isn't in
the child's interests to do so. The decision overturns a court of
appeals' decision in a Houston case. The appeals court had ordered
a psychologist to divulge a child's records to a father.  Bill
Murphy  
 
 JAILDEATH  _ Court of Appeals affirmed a district court decision
that the family of an inmate who died at Harris County Jail has no
basis to sue the county for the man's death. The man, who suffered
from high-blood pressure, died after a doctor gave him cold
medicine that raised his blood pressure. The county can't be sued
because the doctor was an independent contractor, not a county
employee, the courts have said.  Bill Murphy  
 
 CRAWFORD  _ The family of tow truck driver Steven Hardin got some
satisfaction Friday when they saw his murderer hauled off to jail.
But it still angers the family that Houston firefighter Barry
Crawford will only spend six months behind bars as a condition of
the probated sentence given to him by jury in April 1998. Crawford
had appealed his sentence and the terms of probation couldn't be
enforced until his appeal was heard. That happened and state
District Judge Ted Poe laid down the strict conditions again for
Crawford. Reax from defense and family of victim, who is fighting
to change law that allows murderers without criminal records to be
eligible for probation. Developing.
 Steve Brewer  
 
 LARONIA  _ The wife of an ex-Houston police officer convicted of
rape pleaded guilty Friday to attacking her husband's victim after
he was sentenced to prison. Laronia Haywood was placed on probation
and given a very hard time in court by Judge Poe. Developing.
 Steve Brewer 
 
LIBRARY  _ Houston Public Library customers who are connected to
the Internet can forget about library hours for the next six
months. Twenty-four hour access to some 1,500 books is now
available electronically in a pilot program with netLibrary, a
provider of eBooks and an Internet-based content and collection
management service. Using the new service, any person with a
Houston Public Library card can gain access to an eBook, or
electronic book. w/art.  Raffat Rashid 
 
GENOME  _ In an attempt to secure patients' medical privacy in the
age of human genetic code mapping, Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Houston,
Thursday explained proposed legislation that would limit financial
institutions _ particularly those affiliated with insurance
companies _ from sharing information about a person's genetic code.
``If we can forecast from an individual's genes that he or she is
likely to get cancer or heart disease, how could this information
be used?'' Bentsen said. ``Unless we provide legislative
protections, employers could decide to save millions of dollars by
not hiring individuals likely to get sick.''  Kelly Pedersen  
 
 THAI  _ A guilty plea coming out of a federal case of an Asian
prostitution smuggling ring. Jo Ann Zuniga  
 
 METRO RAIL  - U.S. Rep. Tom DeLay is not likely to change his mind
about allowing the Metropolitan Transit Authority to receive
federal funds for a light rail line on Main Street, but the
powerful congressman will fight for the agency's other funding
requests for fiscal year 2001, Metro board members were told in a
briefing Friday. The board's main goals now are to protect funding
for its bus and HOV projects, get the rail line built by other
means, and persuade DeLay not to continue the rail funding ban into
future years. A hoped-for tool of persuasion will be a study of
regional congestion, to be funded by the Greater Houston
Partnership and performed by the traditionally pro-highway Texas
Transportation Institute at Texas A&AMP;M University. About 10 inches.
 Rad Sallee  
 
