<HEADER>
A5543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-THEKID-HN     07-07 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-THEKID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRUCE WILLIS' KID FLICK: CALL `WHINE-1-1' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what will stand as the middle flick in the unofficial
yet-to-be-completed Bruce
Willis-and-small-metaphysically-gifted-boy trilogy, ``The Kid''
follows the ``The Sixth Sense,'' pitting Willis against another
problem child. This time the boy has wandered into Willis' fortress
of solitude from his childhood, and captures his heart in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   This being Disney's ``The Kid,'' look out that he doesn't walk
off with yours as well. In his Kevin Spacey-est role yet, Willis
plays Russell Duritz, a Los Angeles image consultant who cruises
around town concocting bogus but salable personas for the imperiled
and self-esteemless. Russell says things like ``somebody call the
wahbulance,'' which happens to be the movie's favorite line. And
it's not long before it seems unlikely that the makers will call
whine-1-1 on themselves. Russell is one of those grown-ups who,
through some boyhood tragedy starring his father, is divorced from
his sense of fun, his ability to love and his capacity for
humility. His childhood is way in the past _ you know, ``where it
belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Pudgy little Rusty (Spencer Breslin) has mysteriously traveled
30 years into the future more or less to tell his older self ``ah
ah ah'' in the waning days before his 40th birthday. Breslin often
belts out his lines as if the script was written by Okeh records.
He's more charming than the film deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Russell, though, seems to grasp why the boy is there, so
they spend the duration of the film trying to get to the bottom of
this puppy, confounding women like administrative assistant Lily
Tomlin and sort-of girlfriend Emily Mortimer in the process. A
puzzle for them is all-too-evident to us. Russell is inexplicably
estranged from his father and sister, he has no wife and is an
unsparingly crotchety 39-year-old in navy blue power suits. If you
don't smell an allegory, you've accompanied your child on a
bathroom break.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jon Turteltaub and written by Audrey Wells, ``The
Kid'' is self-satisfied: a dishonest baby-boomer melodrama of
inner-selfness and increased sensitivity for yuppie dads. Somehow,
young Rusty goes straight for the 39-year-old Russell and his first
midlife crisis, instantly disapproving of his impatient workaholic
bachelor status. What about the story of his first time, his first
bong hit and the story of those four piercings dotting Russell's
left ear? Surely it wasn't all poker-face moodiness.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, this being Disney at their most unapologetically
Disney, ``The Kid'' wields its Middle America values and moralistic
flogging of idiosyncratic lifestyle choices like a flipped bird.
(Matthew Perry commits a cameo as a shaggy hippie whom Willis says
must shed his growth in order to be taken seriously as a finance
guy.)
</P>
<P>
   It's friendly, but a flagrantly judgmental experience akin to
being accosted by a variety pack of Jehovah's Witnesses, Mormon
elders, Scientology majors, Jews for Jesus and Robert Bly fiends.
</P>
<P>
   There's no rest for a middle-aged white guy content to drift
through life. This is the kind of family-outing movie Fred
MacMurray made for Disney 40 years ago; this time, there's
finger-pointing and a score by Marc Shaiman that in itself thinks
it's good for you. It's some Randy Newman-John Williams prefab that
never stops, but simply shape-shifts from one form of schmaltz to
the next until you feel you've been transported to a medley of
score nominees at the Oscars. That's too bad. At least the Academy
provides more schmaltzy music to drown out the speechifying.
Where's a wahbulance when you need one?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1431EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
