<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN08-CO     07-07 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Shameful battle rages for hallowed
ground
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREDERICKSBURG, Va. _ During the Civil War, four battles were
fought here for the control of this strategic area. Another one is
under way.
</P>
<P>
   These battlefields _ chief among them, Chancellorsville _ are
considered the bloodiest ground in all of North America, ``the
cockpit of the Civil War,'' says Robert K. Krick, chief historian
for the Fredericksburg and Spotslvania National Military Park.
</P>
<P>
   As costly as it was in lives, today the land is even costlier,
property values being what they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hallowed ground is going to be full of townhouses if we
don't do something to protect it,'' Krick said.
</P>
<P>
   This time the threat isn't federal troops. It's a new federal
highway bypass, creating yet another ``epicenter for nacho parlors
and tanning spas,'' Krick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine,'' he said. ``A whole corridor through undeveloped
country. That's a lot of convenience stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Krick, 56, a veteran of 33 years with the park service and
author of 12 Civil War books, is hoping otherwise. Through the work
of both private and government sources, efforts are under way to
raise funds to preserve the battlefields that so many soldiers,
North and South, died fighting for.
</P>
<P>
   The National Trust for Historic Preservation agrees that a
crisis exists. Last year, it listed this area among the 11 most
endangered sites in North America.
</P>
<P>
   You can see it along the highways approaching Fredericksburg.
For all its history, the outer city looks like any other in
America, surrounded as it is by strip mall after strip mall.
</P>
<P>
   Not until you reach downtown do you find the historic
Fredericksburg that George Washington knew as a boy. Here,
according to legend, young Washington sailed the dollar across the
Rappahannock River, 420 feet, and chopped down the cherry tree but
couldn't lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   But more than that, this is Civil War country, located as it is
midway along the 100 miles that separate Washington, D.C., and
Richmond, Va., the capitol of the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting for this area began early in the war. The effort to
preserve the battlefields came late. Not until the 1920s did the
government begin buying strips for roads that follow those sites.
</P>
<P>
   What sites they are!
</P>
<P>
   There is the spot among the pines where Robert E. Lee and
Stonewall Jackson met for the last time, on the eve of the battle
of Chancellorsville, the first week of May, 1863.
</P>
<P>
   Here it was agreed that Jackson should take the mass of their
force, 30,000 troops, and circle to the West, flanking the Union
Army of some 80,000 and _ in perhaps the Confederacy's greatest
victory of the war -- sending the Yanks fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   On hearing the disastrous reports from the battlefield,
President Lincoln was beside himself. ``My God, my God,'' he
moaned. ``What will the country say? What will the country say?''
</P>
<P>
   But with the South's victory also came its greatest individual
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, shot by mistake by his own men during a night
reconnaissance, first had to have his left arm amputated and then
developed pneumonia. He died May 10.
</P>
<P>
   The outbuilding where he spent those final few days _ a small
office located behind a plantation that was serving as a
Confederate hospital _ is still here, though the plantation house
is gone. Tourists can see his death bed and the shroud that covered
him.
</P>
<P>
   The very first tourist, history notes, was Gen. Ulysses S.
Grant, who stopped here in 1864 to pay his respects. Britain's
leader in World War I, David Lloyd George, on visiting the site,
said: ``Here, too , died the Confederacy.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's Jackson's last words that are best remembered.
</P>
<P>
   As the delirium of the fever passed away and a calm relief
seemed to settle over him, he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us cross over the river,''he said, ``and rest under the
shade of the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   To which I would only add the words of historian Krick,
surveying the prospects of encroaching urban development:
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people need to get their poodles trimmed somewhere, but
why on this battlefield?''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas 75915; email address, jmurray(at)txucom.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
