A5564 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-SECURITIES-FRAUD-HNS &LR;      07-07 0275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECURITIES-FRAUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     INVESTMENT MANAGER PLEADS GUILTY IN FRAUD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An investment manager has pleaded guilty to
securities fraud in the operation of a hedge fund that allegedly
cost his investors nearly $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Timothy Higgins, 36, of San Anselmo, admitted Thursday
that he lied about the performance of Ballybunion Capital Partners
and provided false documents to lure investors between November
1998 and April of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors said Higgins raised over $7.6 million by
telling investors the fund was making impressive gains. The fund's
assets had dropped to $750,000 by March of this year, prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Nanci Clarence said Higgins based the fund's
investment strategy on his belief that the technology stock bubble
would soon burst. When that failed to happen as quickly as he
thought, he misrepresented the fund's returns in hopes of
recovering its losses, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By all accounts he has led an exemplary life and this is the
only transgression,'' Clarence said.
</P>
<P>
   A hedge fund is a private, largely unregulated investment
partnership, which caters to wealthy investors and often adopts
strategies that allow it to profit when the market drops.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement requires Higgins to make his best efforts to
repay his investors. Clarence said federal sentencing guidelines
call for a term of 33 to 41 months in prison, but she will ask U.S.
District Judge William Alsup for a lower sentence. Sentencing is
scheduled Dec. 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
