<HEADER>
A5592 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DREAMS08-COX     07-07 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAMS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EVEN HAPPY PEOPLE HAVE MOSTLY BAD DREAMS, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There's apparently no escape for the stresses of
life, even while you're asleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people generally have more negative dreams than positive
dreams,'' said Mark Blagrove, vice president for the Association of
the Study of Dreams and co-author of a new report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although our study found that people who were happy had more
positive dreams than people who are unhappy, happy people still
have more negative dreams than positive ones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blagrove issued his study at the International Conference for
the Association for the Study of Dreams here this week.
</P>
<P>
   Nightmares and other bad dreams can be caused by negative waking
emotions, such as stress, anxiety, fear and sadness, Blagrove said.
He added that traumatic experiences, such as divorce or surgery,
can also lead to more frequent nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   A separate 1998 study also found that there is a connection
between particular negative emotions, such as fear and sadness, and
bad dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, co-authored by Cerri Price of the University of
Wales Swansea, also found that older people have more bad dreams,
but Blagrove couldn't offer a definite explanation for this
finding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be because older people wake up more when they are
sleeping, and that would lead to them remembering more of their bad
dreams,'' Blagrove said. ``But it also could be that older people
simply have more bad dreams than younger people, which is
surprising because young children seem to have a lot of
nightmares.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the study were rated on the frequency that they
could recall their past dreams, Blagrove said. The average rate of
recall was 2.4 dreams per week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our results have implications on whether dreams mirror the
full range of waking emotions or are instead more responsive to
negative emotions or challenges and threats,'' Blagrove said. ``And
we found that people, even those who consider themselves happy,
tend to have more bad dreams than good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Association for the Study of Dreams: www.ASDreams.org
</P>
<P>
   The Dream and Nightmare Laboratory of Montreal's Sacre-Coeur
Hospital:
4montreal.4anything.com/network-frame/0,1855,4946-35819,00.html
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
