<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-HILL-NYT &LR;      07-07 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOING AS FAST AS THEY CAN TO LAND HILL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture the Knicks' Scott Layden, the Nets' Rod Thorn, Miami's
Pat Riley, San Antonio's Gregg Popovich and Chicago's Jerry Krause
standing in a hotel lobby making small talk while each nervously
awaits his turn to speak with the coveted Grant Hill. The goings-on
in Detroit this week have not been that dramatic, but that is
essentially what is taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from those five teams visited Hill this week to
attempt to sell the Detroit Pistons star on their franchise.
</P>
<P>
   With Hill having all but slipped into an Orlando Magic uniform
after last weekend's visit to Disney World, the extra efforts may
be wasted time, but even in the National Basketball Association,
teams must give it that old college try.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful,'' said an official from a team that recently
met with Hill. ``We're obviously hoping that the reports of him
going to Orlando are not true. We want him to take his time to make
a decision. He owes it to himself and his family to take a long,
hard look at his options.''
</P>
<P>
   Options abound for the five-time All-Star, who will likely turn
his team of choice into an immediate conference contender. The
Knicks met with Hill in a suburb of Detroit on Wednesday, and the
San Antonio Spurs met with him later that day.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, a surprise entry in the Hill sweepstakes, made their
pitch Thursday morning, and Miami and Chicago are believed to have
met with Hill Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of those teams is a long shot to land Hill, who has
stated publicly that he is ``leaning strongly'' toward signing with
Orlando. Proof of his preference for the Magic is the fact that he
flew to Orlando on Saturday and went house hunting with his wife,
Tamia, on Monday. Unlike everyone else, the Magic did not have to
run to Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great, but it will feel greater when we _ if we _ can
sign him on Aug. 1,'' Orlando General manager John Gabriel said
Thursday of the privilege his team was afforded. ``We expected
there would be interviews by all of the candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Knicks to acquire Hill, a sign-and-trade deal most
likely involving Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby would have to be
worked. What is unfounded is the talk of the Knicks' signing Hill
for the $2.25 million midlevel exception and then giving him a
maximum money contract the next season. The Knicks will not have
the salary cap room to make such an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Layden and Coach Jeff Van Gundy confirmed that they had met with
Hill but would not comment. The Knicks are hoping to get him to
visit New York soon, but no date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who are in the process of revamping their franchise,
would also have to work a sign-and-trade deal for Hill. Keith Van
Horn would likely be involved, and the Nets would also have to
throw in a couple of other players, perhaps Jamie Feick and Elliot
Perry, to satisfy base-year compensation rules.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio and Miami are in similar situations. Both offered
Hill the $2.25 million exception for this season and then will be
in position to give him a six-year contract worth at least $90
million next season. Several players around the league have said
that Hill's top priority is playing with a top-flight big man; both
San Antonio and Miami would qualify.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, of course, are hoping to keep Tim Duncan from going
to Orlando, and though he denies it, Hill's decision may hinge on
Duncan's. If Duncan decides to go to Orlando, Hill will almost
certainly join him there. If Duncan stays in San Antonio, Hill may
decide to play with Duncan in San Antonio or to play for Riley and
with Alonzo Mourning in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, despite its ability to pay Hill a maximum money
contract this year, is perhaps the longest shot of them all. But
the Bulls, whom Duncan apparently is not even considering, placed
their bid as well.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS ...
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have little chance of obtaining BRIAN GRANT from the
Portland Trail Blazers, a person with knowledge of the teams'
discussions said. The Blazers were not interested in the Knicks'
offer of MARCUS CAMBY and CHRIS CHILDS and the Knicks are not
willing to give up either LATRELL SPREWELL or ALLAN HOUSTON, one of
whom Portland wants, to obtain Grant ... Two league officials said
the Knicks spoke with the Los Angeles Clippers about MAURICE
TAYLOR, but a deal is unlikely because the teams can not agree on
the players for a trade ... The Nets are looking to sign the
Orlando shooting guard RON MERCER as a free agent with the $3.8
million disabled player exception they are expected to receive for
JAYSON WILLIAMS' retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
