<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5606 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-MUNIS-$ADV09-     07-07 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MUNIS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OPPORTUNITY IN RISING RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For fixed-income investors, there appears to be a silver lining
in the cloud of rising interest rates: Buying opportunities among
closed-end municipal bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their particular structure, closed-end funds were
affected by higher rates in several ways _ leaving many at
attractive prices.
</P>
<P>
   Closed-end funds issue a fixed number of shares, which may trade
at a discount or a premium to their net asset value. Moreover,
closed-end municipal funds often leverage their portfolios by
issuing short-term preferred stock at a low rate and reinvesting
the proceeds in longer-term issues with higher yields. So fund
investors in leveraged bond funds fetch higher yields than they
would in nonleveraged portfolios when interest rates are falling.
</P>
<P>
   But because long-term issues are generally more vulnerable to
rising rates than shorter-term debt, the leverage tends to backfire
when rates kick up, as they have been doing recently. That has made
it difficult for some closed-end bond funds to maintain their
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the only issue weighing on closed-end muni funds.
Many of them were started in the early 1990s, and the call
protection on bonds they bought then has begun to expire. Call
protection prevents issuers from refinancing existing bonds,
protecting bondholders' yields for a fixed period, typically 10
years; as these higher-yielding bonds are called, many funds are
replacing them with lower-yielding alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of factors has prompted many of the funds to
reduce dividends. The cuts began after the Federal Reserve began
nudging up short-term interest rates last year, and the pace of the
reductions accelerated sharply last month.
</P>
<P>
   In June, all nine of the Eaton Vance closed-end municipal bond
funds cut their dividends by 10 to 12 percent. Soon thereafter,
Nuveen Investments reduced dividends on 43 of its 59 municipal bond
funds. Over all, 66 closed-end municipal bond funds cut dividends
in June, according to Thomas J. Herzfeld Advisors, closed-end fund
specialists in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But that is where the buying opportunity comes in. Dividend cuts
worry shareholders, who typically react by selling shares.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the selling pressure depresses share prices in two
waves: One comes several days after the announcement of the
dividend cut, and the other comes several months later, when
investors who did not hear the announcement receive smaller
dividend checks.
</P>
<P>
   What investors often fail to understand, Herzfeld said, is that
because bond yields move in the opposite direction of prices, the
sales have the effect of pushing up yields on closed-end bond
funds. A result is that yields are now roughly equal to what they
were before the latest round of dividend cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Putnam Investment Grade Municipal Trust cut its monthly
dividends 8 cents a share on June 4, when shares traded at $12.625,
roughly a 22 percent premium to net asset value. The annual
dividend before the cut was 96 cents a share, and it yielded 7.6
percent. A week later, the share price dropped to 9.75, or a 7
percent discount. At that point, the fund's yield was 7.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson for investors is to evaluate closed-end bond holdings
closely. If you find that a fund holds bonds yielding more than 10
percent, check to see if the call protection will soon expire.
</P>
<P>
   Also find out if net income per share is falling short of
current dividends. In either case, the fund may be a candidate for
a dividend cut and may be ripe for a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, you could consider buying shares of funds that have
recently cut dividends and that trade for discounts of 10 or 15
percent or more, Herzfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   A Roster of Value All-Stars
</P>
<P>
   Litman/Gregory Fund Advisors of Orinda, Calif., is known for
putting together all-star funds _ portfolios divided among
successful, well-known outside fund managers. Masters' Select
Equity, for example, is managed by seven domestic fund managers
overseeing six portfolios, while Masters' Select International is
managed by five managers of five foreign stock portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Now previously beleaguered value managers are getting their
turn, as Litman/Gregory introduces the Masters' Select Value. The
managers are Mason Hawkins of Longleaf Partners, William Miller of
the Legg Mason Value Trust, Bill Nygren of the Oakmark fund and
Larry Sondike of the Franklin Mutual Series funds.
</P>
<P>
   Each manager will assemble a portfolio of 8 to 15 stocks, mainly
in mid- and large-capitalization American stocks. The minimum
investment is $5,000, and $1,000 for individual retirement
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``All four managers use a value approach to stock-picking,
looking for companies whose stocks they deem undervalued,'' said
Craig Litman, director of Litman/Gregory. ``But each of them has a
slightly different idea of what constitutes value.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins and Miller are two of the seven managers of the flagship
Masters' Select Equity, which has returned 21.7 percent,
annualized, from its inception at the end of 1996 through June 30,
compared with 19.7 percent for its category of large blend funds
and 23.1 percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index,
according to Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterly Disclosure Sought
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds should be required to disclose to investors on a
quarterly basis the fees charged to their individual accounts, the
General Accounting Office said in a report to Congress last week.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO said the Securities and Exchange Commission should draft
rules instructing mutual funds to include in quarterly reports the
specific dollar amount of each investor's share of operating
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation was contained in a report requested by Reps.
Michael Oxley, R-Ohio, and chairman of the House Commerce
subcommittee on finance, and John D. Dingell, D-Mich., and a
ranking member of the Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the SEC, Oxley and
Dingell urged him to ``take the necessary steps'' to put the
report's recommendations into effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors deserve to know exactly what they are paying for
mutual fund services on a regular basis,'' Oxley said in a
statement. ``You shouldn't have to have a degree in high finance to
figure out whether your mutual fund is giving you a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund fees paid by investors include the day-to-day costs
of running a fund, called operating expenses. Also, some mutual
funds charge investors sales charges, called ``loads,'' which can
be paid at the time of purchase or over a specific period or when
shares are redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   Current disclosure practices inform investors only of the fees
they are likely to incur, Oxley said. Specifically, the disclosures
list only percentages of fees and hypothetical examples in
prospectuses, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The mutual fund industry organization, the Investment Co.
Institute, responded that mutual funds already make extensive
disclosures about fees and that funds compete on the basis of
performance, according to comments included in the GAO report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reservations about the account statement
recommendation,'' Matthew Fink, president of the Investment Co.
Institute, said in a letter to Thomas McCool, the GAO's director of
financial institutions and market issues. ``This requirement could
erode the value of the standardized, all-inclusive fee information
in the prospectus.'' The letter said such a rule could ``diminish
rather than enhance investors' overall understanding of fund
fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry researchers are concerned that although the fund
industry has been growing rapidly, funds themselves are not
operating more efficiently and fees are not declining enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth in the mutual fund industry has been powerful,
particularly in the last decade,'' Oxley said. ``This growth gives
mutual fund companies economies of scale, and investors ought to
know whether these benefits are being passed on to them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1550EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
