<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EDITOR-PETPLACE-NYT &LR;      07-07 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITOR-PETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITOR TAKES LEAP TO WEB, AND PETS' WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Let's skip the gamut of canine cliches _ ``he's gone
to the dogs'' keeps trotting to mind _ and cut to the reaction that
Arthur J. Browne's wife had when Browne, until last Friday the
senior managing editor of The Daily News, told her that he was
thinking about surrendering his 27-year tenure to join
PetPlace.com, an Internet start-up dedicated to pet health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the dog has driven you crazy!'' howled Gretchen
Browne, director of the Rockville Centre Public Library and
Browne's spouse since 1973, the year he signed on as a Daily News
copy boy for $119 a week plus tips (those were the days when copy
boys fetched food and drink for reporters in addition to
hot-footing copy from typewriter to typesetter; Browne recalls them
fondly because they stoked a romance for the newsroom that cured
his post-adolescent apathy).
</P>
<P>
   Regarding that perceived threat to his sanity, the dog is a
15-month-old yellow Labrador retriever, Grady, Browne's jogging
companion (most mornings they do a five-mile swing through
Hempstead Lakes State Park near their home in Rockville Centre in
Long Island), stress reducer, and yes, his unofficial consultant.
</P>
<P>
   When Browne, who often converses with Grady as they chug along,
solicited the dog's take on the quantum career leap that presented
itself in June, three months after he was _ again _ passed over for
promotion to editor in chief, he's sure the dog said, ``Go for it,
dude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That dog has changed my life,'' Browne, 49, admitted Wednesday
afternoon as he cleaned out his corner office, retaining just a few
framed front pages (``My Secret Life With Bill'' and ``Farewell
Yankee Clipper'' were keepers). ``But he's not the reason I'm
leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the newspaper install and discard top editors, none of
them him, four times in the last four years, was the reason.
Besides noticing that his head hit a glass ceiling once he became
senior managing editor two years ago, Browne felt it was only a
matter of time before he wore out his welcome with whatever
hierarchy came next. And the wheel, as he says, keeps on turning at
The News: ``I'm just like a piece of furniture that's always been
there that's not there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Choice metaphor, Browne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fortunate to have lived through all the changes, but any
rational person in my place would question if that was going to
hold forever,'' said Browne, who survived nine regimes, made
enemies when he kept the paper going in the 1990 strike, but had a
reputation as a square-shooter with a clear sense of the paper's
role with its readers.
</P>
<P>
   As for his role on the editorial staff, which was unprecedented
in its longevity, Browne said, ``You serve at the pleasure of the
editor and publisher, and at some point some person is likely to
say, `I don't want Arthur Browne around,' so better to go out
standing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, he informed Edward Kosner, the newest editor in
chief, and Mortimer Zuckerman, the publisher, of his resignation in
a brief meeting with no negotiations or recriminations. He did not
tell them that he was following Kosner's predecessor, Debby Krenek
(her two-year stint as editor of The News ended acrimoniously) to
PetPlace.com, where she is the chief creative officer and he (at
last!) is editor in chief. He just said his decision was
``irrevocable,'' and money or catchy titles wouldn't change it.
</P>
<P>
   He did not even give the standard two weeks' notice. Not that he
burned his bridge to The News, but he did burn rubber as he crossed
it: resigned on Friday, took a four-day weekend in Cutchogue,
cleared out of his office on Wednesday, announced his affiliation
with PetPlace.com, and the site's affiliation with America Online,
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could be jumping out of an airplane without a parachute for
all I know,'' Browne said. ``It's time to do something radically
different.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Browne wasn't always the enterprising, button-down
guy in the corner office, the up-and-comer who worked days in the
Queens bureau and earned a 1978 St. John's law degree by night to
make himself a better investigative reporter, not a lawyer: radical
was his middle name in his teens.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Brooklyn, he grew up in Freeport on Long Island, with
two better-behaved siblings and patient parents. He attended a
Jesuit high school but went haywire the summer he was 15: wrecked
the family's new car, sank the family boat, and when he couldn't
find any other capitalist trappings to trash, set fire to his
bedroom. ``If my kids did that to me, I don't know what I'd do,''
mused Browne, who has four.
</P>
<P>
   He grew his hair to his shoulders, went to Woodstock and,
terrified of the draft and Vietnam, allowed his parents to drop him
off at Boston College, from which he emerged in 1972 with an
English degree but no career clues. He was a lifeguard, bummed
around Europe, and then, at 22, went to The Daily News, which had
impressed him at 10 when he visited a relative who worked there, to
ask for a copy boy position while he figured out a real career step
elsewhere. The editor who hired him told him that he'd be better
off, with his nice suit and college degree, going straight to Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me copy boys never get promoted to reporter, that
there was no career in it for me,'' said Browne, who proved him
wrong within a year and kept it up for a quarter century. He's
hoping for something similar at PetPlace.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
