<HEADER>
A5625 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-JUNKBONDS-ART     07-07 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-JUNKBONDS-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVERGING FORCES HAVE KEPT JUNK BONDS IN A SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By KATE BERRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember junk bonds?
</P>
<P>
   They were the play stuff of Michael Milken, the mother's milk of
the 1980s leveraged-buyout craze and eventually a symbol of that
decade's decadence.
</P>
<P>
   This year, junk bonds, also known as high-yield bonds, have
posted some of their worst performance in almost a decade. A total
of $7.92 billion flowed out of junk-bond funds from January through
May this year, according to estimates by AMG Data Services, a fund
tracker in Arcada, Calif. They returned a negative 0.32 percent on
average last quarter and negative 1.4 percent over the last 12
months, according to Morningstar Inc. For the five years through
June 30, the funds' average annualized return was just 6.5 percent,
only half a percentage point more than long-term government bond
funds. So far this year, investors who crave the extra yield of
junk are actually worse off than they would have been in
Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost feel like an ostracized asset class,'' said Peter
Andersen, portfolio manager of the Conseco High Yield fund. The
sector's returns have previously fallen two years in a row, he
said, but ``now we're entering our third year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investor is saying: `I'd be better off putting my money
somewhere else, like a CD,''' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Problems arose for junk bonds in the Asian financial crisis of
1997 and 1998, as collapsing demand for shipping, paper and oil on
the Pacific Rim pummeled those sectors and led to bond defaults.
About the same time, junk was also becoming a crucial source of
financing for risky technology, telecommunications and Internet
companies; when the default rate began rising last year, investors
fled junk bonds for stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the high-yield market really didn't finance
technology companies,'' said Martin Fridson, senior high-yield
strategist at Merrill Lynch. ``Portfolio managers preferred
companies that had established cash flows, so that recoveries were
likely to be high if a company failed.'' By contrast, he said,
there is little chance of recovering anything if a technology
start-up with no revenue defaults.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, the Federal Reserve's efforts to head off
inflation with increases in short-term interest rates have forced
junk bonds to move in lock step to maintain an attractive spread.
</P>
<P>
   The spread is the interest premium that investors demand to
compensate for the greater risk of default or interruption of
interest payments. When yields on investment grade bonds rise,
junk-bond prices must fall to keep their yields at an appetizing
altitude above them.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, a typical bond rated a notch or two below investment
grade yielded 10.05 percent, or 426 basis points _ hundredths of a
percentage point _ above the 5.79 percent to be had on a 10-year
Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Fed has pushed up short-term rates by 175 basis
points, and junk-bond yields have had to follow, with that same
typical bond's yield climbing to 11.81 percent. Longer-term
government rates have not risen nearly as much as short-term rates,
so the spread over 10-year Treasuries has widened considerably, to
577 basis points.
</P>
<P>
   The implication of all that arithmetic is that junk-bond prices
have fallen much more sharply than long-term government bond
prices, as is evident in the performance of the funds that hold
these bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The risk of default on junk bonds has also worsened lately and
is unusually high for good economic times. Today, 18 percent of
junk bonds are considered distressed, meaning that default is a
real possibility, Fridson said. That is the highest rate since
January 1992, when 22.3 percent were called distressed.
</P>
<P>
   A rising default rate is bad for bond prices, of course, so
holders of junk bonds suffer, just as they do when spreads over
Treasuries widen. But the allure for new buyers is increasing. ``We
think the high-yield market is attractively valued and that the
high default rate is priced in,'' said Tom Price, co-portfolio
manager of the Strong High-Yield Bond fund, which has returned 0.75
percent this year. ``Those credits that have been struggling have
been taken out to the woodshed, and if they default, it won't
affect the overall rate.''
</P>
<P>
   One difficulty in analyzing the junk-bond outlook is in
measuring the default rate with precision. Experts differ markedly
on how to go about it. Moody's Investors Service includes the
high-yield debt of developing nations, as well as convertible
bonds, which are often below investment grade; it draws the bearish
conclusion that defaults will worsen in coming months. But Sam
DeRosa Farag, director of global high-yield portfolio strategy for
Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, argues that including those asset
classes skews the default rates upward, and that investors should
look at the domestic corporate high-yield market by itself.
Donaldson's forecast is for falling default rates.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is important for investors, because the junk-bond
market is extremely cyclical, and the payoffs for those who call
the bottom accurately can be big.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a quiet storm about this, and most indicators are
that the worst isn't over,'' said David Hamilton, an analyst at
Moody's risk-management services. ``There is still a large
proportion out there at risk of defaulting.''
</P>
<P>
   Moody's version of the default rate for speculative-grade issues
was 5.4 percent for the 12 months ended May 31, more than three
times the 1.5 percent in the same period three years earlier. By
June 2001, Moody's expects the default rate for the trailing 12
months to peak at 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty big deal,'' said Hamilton, who estimated that
junk-bond downgrades outnumbered upgrades by three to one in the
first quarter of this year. Defaults have been widely distributed
among industry sectors, he said, though price-sensitive commodity
and shipping companies were among the first to default on their
junk debt in the first quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, DeRosa Farag said, returns and defaults have
tended to reach peaks together. ``There is this assumption that if
default rates go up, the returns are going to be poor,'' he said.
``But the historical pattern is that whenever defaults peak, this
is when we have the best returns ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Junk bonds are now ``attractively valued,'' he said, because the
average issue is trading at less than 85 cents per dollar of face
value, the lowest rate since July 1991. He attributed last year's
surge in defaults to the 1997-98 Asian woes, conditions that have
since eased; by his estimation, the default rate is now falling
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever view best describes the bigger picture, an important
day-to-day issue bothers the junk-bond market: Liquidity. Junk-bond
funds have experienced cash outflows in 18 of the last 23 weeks,
according to AMG. ``Week after week of outflows from the funds is
an insurmountable barrier'' to a recovery in prices, said Fridson,
at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   So there may be a glint of light in the figures for the last
three weeks, which show the flow turning positive. Some hardy
investors may be responding anew to the siren call of those fat
yields.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
