u l BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      07-07 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, July 9, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEDDING-PHOTO-OP (New York) _ The brides were tacking in white
satin, trains billowing, veils lofting like the topsails of the
Tall Ships entering New York harbor. A Salvadoran bridal party
sailed toward a Custard Beach outlet, breaking through a throng of
tourists gathered for the 18th Annual Brown family reunion. The
setting for this odd apparition was the World Financial Center's
Winter Garden. This sort of thing takes place here all the time;
the midpoints of winter and summer are high season for wedding
photography in this vast lobby, a de facto chapel of love that also
happens to be a corporate headquarters for Dow Jones and others. By
Patricia A. Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   BERGDORF-BOOKSELLER (New York) _ Tucked all the way in the back
of the top floor at Bergdorf Goodman is a book-filled nook titled
Jane Stubbs. And tucked behind the stacks of rare and vintage books
is a woman tucked behind an enormous shirt and thick glasses, with
the milky complexion of an attic-dwelling bookworm who seems
perennially startled at the notion of visitors. One shopper,
surveying the mounds of books jumbled on tables and ladders and
chairs, spotted her and asked, ``Do you ever look through them?''
Stubbs, 42, peered at her nervously. ``Oh, goodness, it's what I do
all the time ... It's my life's mission to uncover the flotsam and
jetsam of the publishing world and force people to have libraries
of same. It tickles me so much.'' By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   SHOP-NATASHA-LYONNE (New York) _ Natasha Lyonne sat on a bench
outside a coffee bar near her studio apartment, shuddering slightly
even in the 90 degree heat. She was detoxing from Hollywood.
``Welcome to breakfast,'' said the 21-year-old actress whose quirky
performances in `Slums of Beverly Hills,` `American Pie,` and `But
I'm a Cheerleader,` which opened this weekend, have marked her as
the New York doppleganger of such plump-lipped ingenues as Neve
Campbell and Jennifer Love Hewitt, a sort of anti-starlet. By Nancy
Hass.
</P>
<P>
   FAKE-HANDBAGS (Undated) _ A look at a new breed of sidewalk
shopper: consumers of evident style and means who can afford to pay
retail but enjoy the thrill of adding a $30 counterfeit or two to
their wardrobes. Where the shoppers stooping to inspect street
merchandise were once mainly office workers and tourists, now they
are as likely to be chic passers-by, clutching a genuine Prada
shoulder bag style or a tote emblazoned with real Gucci double G's.
By Ruth LaFerla.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Giant perennials. By Patricia A.
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
