<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5630 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-MANAGERS-ART-     07-07 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MANAGERS-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTING ON THE UNLOVED TO BEAT A DOWNTURN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MUTFUND-RETIRE) 
(Art available on request; call 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867 for
info.) 
(For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were swoons and rebounds, and then more again of the same.
But by the end of the second quarter, the stock market had provided
enough bad news to push every major category of U.S. diversified
equity funds into negative territory for the period. Over all,
domestic diversified stock funds lost 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What funds managed to shine as stormy weather lashed the
markets? Generally, the winners owned shares in companies in
old-economy sectors, like oil and gas, as well as in health care
and some financial services.
</P>
<P>
   Managers of three top-performing funds talked about the
resurgence of once-beaten-down sectors and what they expect from
the stock market during the remainder of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Helped by a U-Turn
</P>
<P>
   Cheap, small stocks propelled the $262.7 million Ariel fund into
second place among funds for the quarter, with a return of 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our stocks were so extraordinarily cheap at the beginning of
the quarter that they were really poised to move up sharply,'' said
its manager, John W. Rogers Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, 42, looks for companies that sell for a discount of at
least 40 percent to their private market value (what they would be
worth to an acquirer), and whose shares trade at less than 14 times
projected earnings for the next year. The fund holds just 35
issues.
</P>
<P>
   One big winner was Central Newspapers of Phoenix, owner of The
Arizona Republic, The Indianapolis Star and other papers.
``Newspapers are cheap because investors are worrying about the
impact of the Internet,'' Rogers said, ``and publishers worry about
rising paper prices.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's share price was so depressed, he added, that
management put the business up for sale. Last month, Gannett agreed
to buy it for $2.6 billion; the stock rose 89 percent for the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Another holding, Hussmann International of St. Louis, agreed to
be acquired during the quarter by Ingersoll-Rand for a premium of
more than 100 percent, Rogers said. The company makes refrigeration
equipment for supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an industry that no one cared about earlier in the year,
when people were enamored of dot-com companies,'' he said. ``And it
missed a few quarters' earnings, which gave people an excuse to
neglect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers also made money on Littelfuse, the fund's only technology
stock. The company, based in Des Plaines, Ill., is a leading
provider of miniature electrical fuses for the automobile industry;
it recently began making fuses for cell phones, personal digital
assistants and other electronic devices. The stock rose 33.6
percent in the quarter, helped by improving earnings and the move
into the new markets.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Rogers sees more gains for small- and
mid-capitalization value stocks, even after their second-quarter
sprint. ``So many boards of directors and CEO's are saying that the
stock price of their company doesn't reflect the value of the
business,'' he said, ``and they're taking steps to realize that
value.''
</P>
<P>
   Energy and Health Care Bets
</P>
<P>
   Edward J. von der Linde took the No. 13 place for the quarter
with his $456.4 million Lord Abbett Mid-Cap Value fund, with a gain
of 8.4 percent. ``As the market broadens out and diversifies away
from large-cap growth stocks,'' said von der Linde, 40, ``investors
have gravitated to the types of stocks that we buy.''
</P>
<P>
   One big winner was EOG Resources in Houston, up 57.6 percent,
helped by rising natural-gas prices. ``Investors are realizing that
gas producers haven't been able to keep pace with demand,'' he
said. Enron is more leveraged to natural-gas price increases, he
said, than any other domestic gas company.
</P>
<P>
   He also made money in Caremark Rx, a Birmingham, Ala., company
that organizes drug benefit programs for health insurers and HMOs.
The stock rose 62.7 percent in the quarter. The drivers of its
performance included the divestiture of its unprofitable physician
practice management business and the settlement of litigation
involving a convertible bond issue. ``The company has annual
revenue growth of 20 percent,'' von der Linde said, ``so once the
clouds were gone, the stock price began to take off.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Jude Medical, a St. Paul maker of heart valves and
pacemakers, rose 77.8 percent. Investors began bidding up the price
in anticipation of the Food and Drug Administration approval,
expected by year-end, of a new, lightweight cardiac device, he
said. Moreover, a new chief executive, Terry Shepherd, who took
over in 1999, has smoothed out the company's problems meeting
earnings expectations. ``He is communicating with Wall Street and
rebuilding the earnings numbers,'' he said, ``which is generating
confidence in the company as it moves toward its new product
introduction.''
</P>
<P>
   von der Linde is optimistic about the stock market. ``I wouldn't
be surprised to see the rally in the old leaders continue for
another few months,'' he said. ``Investors suddenly seem to be
taking notice of earnings. The next logical step is that they'll
pay attention to valuations, which will broaden out leadership in
the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Profiting From Credit Risk
</P>
<P>
   Buying companies with strong earnings growth while keeping a
sharp eye on prices pushed the $200 million Wasatch Core Growth
into the No. 7 place, up 10 percent. ``In the last three quarters,
we've seen the strongest earnings growth in our portfolio companies
that we've ever seen,'' said J.B. Taylor, 28, co-manager of the
fund with Sam Stewart, 55.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the annual earnings growth of the companies in the
fund has been nearly 30 percent, even though their trailing
price-to-earnings multiples have been less than 20, which is
relatively low. ``With high-tech investments in vogue,'' he said,
``a lot of great, solid companies are being passed over.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them, he said, is Rent-a-Center, in Plano, Texas, which
rose 50 percent in the quarter. The company operates a
``rent-to-own'' business that leased electronics, appliances,
furniture and other goods to consumers, including those without
credit cards or checking accounts or with poor credit histories.
Its earnings are growing at an annual rate of 25 percent, while
shares trade at about 10 times its earnings for the previous 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Another company that caters to people with poor credit is
Americredit, a consumer finance company in Fort Worth whose stock
rose 4.3 percent. Americredit's customers ``are good loan
applicants now, because they've turned around or they're willing to
pay premiums for their loans,'' Taylor said. Annual earnings growth
exceeds 25 percent, and shares trade for about 13 times trailing
12-month earnings.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Express Scripts of St. Louis, a drug benefits
management organization. Its cash flow has been growing 20 percent
a year, Taylor said, but its share price was depressed because of
the general downturn in many health care stocks. It rose 47.9
percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Taylor expects value stocks to dominate. ``I see
an increasing focus _ or return to focus _ on fundamentals, because
so many investors have been burned by hyped stocks,'' he said. ``In
the last couple of months, Wall Street has been shifting its focus
to earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
