<HEADER>
A5633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WAR-CRIMES-DEFINED-2T     07-07 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-CRIMES-DEFINED-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO PUNISH WAR CRIMINALS, THE WORLD MUST DEFINE WAR CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In first-century Rome, where historians knew a glorious war when
they saw one, Lucius Annaeus Seneca raised a troubling question: on
the battlefield, do whole nations go mad and lose their humanity?
``We check manslaughter and isolated murders,'' he wrote in his
Epistles, ``but what of war and the much-vaunted crimes of
slaughtering whole peoples?''
</P>
<P>
   Almost since the first rock was thrown in anger, international
legal experts say, people have tried to rein in the excesses of
conflict and make them punishable. Benjamin Ferencz, a legal
scholar who was a young prosecutor at the Nuremberg trials for Nazi
war crimes after World War II, goes back to Ecclesiastes for an
early Biblical guide to good behavior. ``You weren't supposed to
kill your enemy and his suffering babes,'' he said. ``You take them
as slaves. That was a big advance forward for the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, Abraham Lincoln commissioned the first
modern war crimes code, which was duly written by Francis Lieber,
the president's chief counsel during the Civil War. Next came the
1949 Geneva conventions, which codified rules for the humane
treatment of civilians and combatants, including prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   Now another historic step has been taken. A week ago, legal
delegations from more than 100 nations gathered at the United
Nations and agreed to an exhaustive catalog of acts that will
constitute war crimes, crimes against humanity and genocide for the
world's first permanent International Criminal Court, now in the
final stages of creation. The definitions of crimes cover dozens of
pages in an effort to list unambiguously the most terrible things
that people do to each other in the course of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But from the grisly amputations of the hands of innocents in
Sierra Leone to the systematic sexual abuse of women in Bosnia and
Rwanda _ or, some would say, to the bombing of Kosovo refugees by
NATO war planes _ modern conflicts raise new and complex issues.
There still is not total agreement on universally accepted moral
codes.
</P>
<P>
   It was easier at Nuremberg, and at the Tokyo trials for Japanese
war criminals. The war crimes were more or less traditionally
defined, and the victorious allies were in charge. Today, most
experts say, crimes are less easy to define, violations less easy
to agree on. More actors are on the stage as well: human rights
groups and other nongovernmental organizations are now instrumental
in collecting information and lobbying for trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've seen in modern wars, especially many internal
conflicts, is that war crimes and crimes against humanity are
layered upon each other,'' said Michael P. Scharf, the director of
the Center for International Law and Policy at the New England Law
School in Boston, who is studying the changing face of atrocity.
``It's not just the military. You get neighbor fighting neighbor.''
Civilian culpability in what were once thought of as military
crimes is a concept being thrashed out in tribunals for the Balkans
and Rwanda, Scharf said. Along the way, he added, ``a whole new
jurisprudence is emerging.''
</P>
<P>
   Scharf has been asking questions about how important trials are
to peace and reconciliation. ``There is a conventional wisdom that
if you could have a credible, neutral trial for war criminals, that
would create a historical record that everybody could agree on and
that would withstand the forces of revisionism,'' he said. ``This
theory really emerges from the Nuremberg precedent.'' Scharf
decided to test it in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many towns in Bosnia where there was the worst ethnic
cleansing,'' he said, ``the Muslims and Serbs, victims and
perpetrators, have moved back into their old houses and are living
once again as neighbors.'' They know about the war crimes trials at
the Hague, because the George Soros Foundation is having them
broadcast into Bosnia with the idea that if people ``actually saw
the testimony of the victims and the perpetrators, they couldn't
deny it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Scharf found instead was that both local people and
outsiders who spoke with them could come away with very different
interpretations of what the trials proved or did not prove. Scharf
matched some of these reactions with his own research on what he
calls ``the myth of Nuremberg'' _ that is, that all you have to do
is establish an international tribunal, create an historical record
``and that's that.'' He said that polls taken in Germany only 10
years after the Nuremberg trials, by which time many Nazi sentences
had been commuted, showed that ``90 percent of the people thought
that these were show trials, political trials.'' It took another
generation or two to change that perception, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It does not help when governments introduce their own national
interests into the discussion. Ferencz, who at 80 still writes on
war crimes and has been active in debates surrounding the
International Criminal Court, says that during the Cold War neither
side wanted itself or its friends or clients held up to scrutiny.
And Scharf notes that groups defined as ``political'' are not
protected against genocide because the writers of the genocide
convention of 1949 wanted Stalin's Russia on board, and Stalin had
annihilated political and social groups. ``Your very definition of
genocide has been corrupted from the very beginning by the
necessity of Cold War politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War is over but the story continues. Take Saddam
Hussein's gassing of his troublesome Kurdish minority in 1988, and
the world's response. ``Rather than simply going after rebel
fighters,'' said Kenneth Roth, the executive director of Human
Rights watch, Saddam ``would drop chemical weapons on Kurdish
villages, killing some people and driving others out, and then
rounding up those who were fleeing and bringing them to a series of
concentration camps. Virtually every male of fighting age was
executed _ about 100,000 people.'' But this crime, Roth said, ``was
inconvenient for the international community to address.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
