<HEADLINE>
BOOK GUIDES THE SPIRITUAL TRAVELER TO RELIGIOUS SITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traveling is one of my favorite pastimes; I like to see what's
over the next hill.
</P>
<P>
   When I visit a place, large or small, I'm likely to end up
visiting religious sites.
</P>
<P>
   In England, I've sought out famous churches of which Charles
Haddon Spurgeon, noted Baptist evangelist, and John Wesley were
pastors.
</P>
<P>
   While in Kerrville, Texas, visiting friends and playing tennis
recently, I took a side trip to Bandera and visited St. Stanislaus
church, one of the state's oldest Roman Catholic parishes founded
by Polish immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   I sometimes write about what I see. But sometimes I go just for
the fun of learning about the amazing diversity of religious
experience that exists.
</P>
<P>
   So I was intrigued by a recently released book, ``The Christian
Traveler's Companion: USA and Canada,'' Fleming H. Revell ($14.99).
</P>
<P>
   I was expecting to find some new places to visit on my travels.
</P>
<P>
   And I wasn't disappointed. Amy S. Eckert, an enthusiastic
traveler and free-lance writer, and William J. Peterson, a
Christian author and editor with Revell, list more than 3,000
destinations in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The authors called upon their own travel experiences, convention
and visitors bureaus, and personal research in compiling the
paperback volume. The authors are more interested in pointing their
readers toward the spiritual than just the obviously
religious-related site.
</P>
<P>
   Spiritual travel may include finding a place to worship while
visiting a city, touring a museum with religious significance or
just finding a quiet place to read the Bible, Eckert said this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The paperback book has highly interesting entries about places
in both the United States and Canada. For example, I learned that
the Notre-Dame-de-Quebec I visited in Quebec City last summer is
the oldest Catholic basilica in North America, dating from 1647.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that Jonathan Edwards' sermon ``Sinners in the Hand of
an Angry God'' was first preached in Enfield, Conn. We are told
that the old hymn ``Jesus Paid It All'' was scribbled by Elvina
Hall on the flyleaf of a hymn book during worship at the Monument
Street Methodist Church in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But the book is not simply a storehouse of religious sites in
North America. Other books, including ``America's Religious
Treasures,'' a 1976 effort of Marion and Pierre Vuilleumier
published by Harper &AMP; Row, give more details on special religious
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we mean by Christian travel is travel that rejuvenates
your spirit as well as your body, travel that doesn't leave your
spiritual life behind on the coffee table,'' Eckert and Peterson
wrote. ``Christian travel is not necessarily ... a vacation to the
Holy Land. It doesn't have to be a service trip where you
participate in mission work. ...''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1613EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WAR-CRIMES-DEFINED-2N     07-07 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-CRIMES-DEFINED-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: to address.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States was supporting Iraq in a war against Iran at
the time. ``The U.S. became interested in the crime only after the
gulf war,'' Roth said. ``At this stage, the U.S. does support a
tribunal, but there is no chance of getting it past Russia, China
and France on the Security Council.'' All three have, to one degree
or another, backed Iraq in its standoff with the United Nations and
the United States. The Security Council set up tribunals for the
Balkans and Rwanda but not for Saddam or, for that matter, for Pol
Pot, the Khmer Rouge leader responsible for the deaths of more than
a million Cambodians. ``The Security Council can't be trusted to
bring criminals to trial,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, many have turned their attention to the U.S.-led
bombing in 1999 of Serb targets in Yugoslavia to stop Serb
atrocities in Kosovo. Some groups, like Amnesty International, say
they have found evidence of war crimes. Human Rights Watch, while
not accusing NATO of war crimes, has been concerned about the use
of cluster bombs near populated areas, attacks on civilian targets
like factories or a major power plant, the bombing of a bridge near
a busy market during daylight hours and air strikes against mobile
targets (among them a column of refugees) from 15,000 feet without
solid assurances that the targets were military. Roth said that
advanced technologies required new ways of looking at the conduct
of war.
</P>
<P>
   Carla del Ponte, the chief prosecutor of the Balkans war crimes
tribunal, decided against an investigation of NATO's conduct of the
war, but even the idea that she would explore such a move raised
tempers in the Pentagon. This only contributed to the U.S.
military's determination never to have anything to do with the
International Criminal Court, fearing it would single out Americans
for political or ideological reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Wedgwood, an expert on international law at the Yale Law
School, sees some justification in those fears. She said that it
was sometimes harder to make judgments on military behavior than
one might think just by looking at the results of any given action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to say that NATO should rethink some of its war
plans and find ways to fight better,'' Wedgwood said, ``and it's
another thing to instantly criminalize them. There seems to be a
rush to the most extreme category.'' The issue is complicated, she
added, by the absence of military expertise on criminal tribunals.
</P>
<P>
   Wedgwood said that attempts to include sanctions _ the Clinton
administration's weapon of choice after precision bombing _ in the
loosely defined area of war crimes opened another range of issues.
Opponents of sanctions on Iraq, imposed in 1990 after the invasion
of Kuwait and still in place, say that they are killing thousands
of Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have seriously argued,'' Wedgwood said, ``that just as
in the law of war, you can't target civilians for their own sake,
by that same logic, sanctions that try to press civilians to
overthrow their leaders should also be forbidden.'' She went on:
``Some people will argue that enemy morale as such has always been
and must be a military objective. Other people say that leads you
down the path where you would actually seek to terrorize
civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   No one says bringing clarity or universality to an understanding
of war crimes will be easy. ``It's all imperfect,'' said Ferencz,
who has watched the world grapple with elusive war criminals for
half a century. ``But I see progress. We are crawling toward
civilization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
