<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-ISUZU0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUV's toughness a product of its truck roots
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although the 2000 Isuzu Rodeo is a quite civilized
sport-utility vehicle, it will issue reminders that Isuzu is a
truck manufacturer and not a carmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is noticeably trucklike, and not even Isuzu's
Intelligent Suspension Control system (ISC) prevents that. It's a
heavy SUV (about 4,000 pounds), and once it starts flexing its coil
spring suspension's 7.9 inches of travel, body motion sets in. It
also leans and rolls in corners.
</P>
<P>
   But the Isuzu, even in line-topping LSE trim, looks and drives
like a very competent off-roader. It seems safe to say that its SUV
characteristics are going to be underutilized.
</P>
<P>
   Pricewise, the Rodeo, which is rebadged and sold as Honda's
Passport, is hardly a bargain. The base model S with four-cylinder
engine (129 horsepower) and five-speed transmission is $18,080,
while the LSE lists for $31,265. The test LSE came to $31,820, and
it had all the features expected of a sedan: all-power, leather,
CD/cassette players and air conditioning, albeit one that struggled
to cope with recent 90-degree weather.
</P>
<P>
   Between its height _ ground clearance is 8.2 inches _ and the
fact the Rodeo has enough glass to give a window washer nightmares,
visibility is really good. The rear mirror view is limited and can
be reduced to almost nothing by rear seat passengers, but the power
side mirrors are large enough to facilitate lane changes and
checking clearance when going off-road.
</P>
<P>
   With the 205-hp V-6 engine making 214 pounds-feet of torque, the
Rodeo's acceleration is better than that of many of today's
fuel-saving cars. The penalty comes in fuel mileage, however, with
the V-6 carrying EPA figures of 16 and 20 mpg. They must have been
obtained by a very light-footed driver, because the test LSE fell a
couple of mpg short of matching them.
</P>
<P>
   The Rodeo's interior offers plenty of room for adults, even in
the rear. The rear cargo room is easily utilized because the rear
glass opens upward and the bottom portion swings open to the left.
Fold the rear seat, and cargo room jumps from 33 cubic feet to
81.1.
</P>
<P>
   The ride, in addition to not matching the comfort level of some
SUVs in the Rodeo's price range, can be noisy with both wind and
road noise coming into the cabin. The standard CD/cassette stereo,
although relatively low on the center dash, is easily operated and
provides decent sound.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the amenities, the Rodeo does remain a truck at heart,
and while that may offend some SUV buyers, those who really need or
want four-wheel drive with toughness, the Rodeo will make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
