<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BICYCLE-IMMIGRANTS (Harlingen, Texas) _ Border Patrol agents say
they have uncovered a new scheme to smuggle illegal immigrants into
the United States: dress them up in helmets and jerseys and have
them race past agents on 10-speed bicycles. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-DEATHROW (Houston) _ About 65 percent of the inmates
sentenced to die by the federal courts are black, a dramatic
increase from the 10 percent before federal capital crimes were
expanded in 1988 and 1994, an analysis of U.S. Bureau of Prisons
data shows. Meanwhile, the Clinton administration has postponed the
Aug. 5 execution of Juan Raul Garza, the only Hispanic ever
sentenced to die for a federal crime. By DEBORAH TEDFORD.
</P>
<P>
   BILINGUAL-EDUCATION (Undated) _ Opponents of bilingual education
in Arizona have filed 165,000 signatures with the Secretary of
State's office, about 64,000 more than needed to get their measure
on the November ballot to kill bilingual education. By KIM COBB.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ The Justice Department files a
response to a federal judge's request for comment on the antitrust
lawsuit that seeks to keep the Hearst Corp. from buying the San
Francisco Chronicle and transferring its flagship San Francisco
Examiner to a weekly newspaper publisher. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ No matter who is president, the
church vs. state controversy will continue, especially after the
Supreme Court's ruling last month outlawing student-led prayers at
public high school football games. The next chapter could come when
the court decides, probably next year, on statutes, such as one
recently passed Virginia, that permit a moment of silence in public
classrooms. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday. For release
Sunday, July 9.)
</P>
