<HEADLINE>
A SEVEN-YEAR LESSON IN INVESTING: EXPECT THE UNEXPECTED, AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, July 9) 
(See also MUTFUND-MANAGERS) 
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a way, it has been a seven-year cold shower for the idea that
an ordinary investor can do any better than the market, even with
expert advice.
</P>
<P>
   Because saving for retirement had become a crucial issue for
Americans, The New York Times in 1993 asked five mutual-fund
experts how they would invest a hypothetical nest egg of $50,000
for someone who planned to retire in 20 years or more. Each quarter
since then, the five portfolios have been reviewed and fine-tuned
and their performances compared in these pages.
</P>
<P>
   With results from the second quarter of 2000, the exercise
concludes, and the participants discuss what they, and investors,
have learned along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the five participants tripled their money in the seven
years ended June 30. The portfolio overseen by Eric Kobren,
president of the Kobren Insight Group and editor of Fidelity
Insight in Wellesley Mass., did the best over all, with a
cumulative gain of 210.19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Close behind were the portfolio of ``socially responsible''
funds assembled by Jack Brill, vice president of Natural Investment
Services in San Diego, with a cumulative gain of 204.42 percent,
and the portfolio managed by Sheldon Jacobs, editor of the No-load
Fund Investor, in Irvington, N.Y., at 200.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In fourth place was a portfolio tended most recently by Russel
Kinnel, editor of Morningstar Fund Investor in Chicago, at 146.97
percent. The fifth entry, managed by Harold R. Evensky, an
investment adviser in Coral Gables, Fla., finished at 123.63
percent, according to Lipper Inc.
</P>
<P>
   None of the portfolios, however, managed to outperform the
market over the seven-year period. In retrospect, simply investing
the whole stake in the Vanguard S&AMP;P Index 500 fund and letting it
ride would have done better, yielding a gain of 277.51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But overall performance was intended to be just one dimension of
the exercise. Investors also had a chance to explore the thinking
behind mutual fund management as the managers discussed strategies,
styles and selections each quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The object lessons were limited by the unexpected way the
economy and the stock market have moved over the last seven years _
almost exclusively straight up. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index returned an annual average of 20.25 percent over the period;
by contrast, stocks returned an annual average of 12.1 percent in
the 65 years from 1926 to 1990, according to Ibbotson Associates in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Big growth stocks dominated the stock market for much of the
last seven years, lifting the performance of large-capitalization
index funds and dragging down the returns of actively managed
mutual funds, which tend to own smaller stocks. According to
Morningstar Inc., just 17.2 percent of 970 actively managed
domestic diversified equity funds in its database outperformed the
S&AMP;P 500 over the period.
</P>
<P>
   And the stock market has become more volatile in the 1990s,
jumping or slumping abruptly _ as a whole or sector by sector _ in
hard-to-predict ways. Fast-moving markets stumped the experts
several times along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, stocks _ and funds that hold them _ are still the best
way to meet long-term financial goals like retirement, the experts
said, because they have always outperformed other investments over
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This exercise shows what a prudent, diversified mutual fund
portfolio can return, given time and compounding,'' Kobren said.
``It isn't necessary to dart in and out of the market, take foolish
risks in the hopes of scoring a home run or get overly complicated
by owning dozens of funds.''
</P>
<P>
   All five participating managers continue to recommend
diversified fund portfolios, even though diversification was a far
from optimal strategy during much of the last seven years.
Carefully balancing big stocks with smaller ones, or American
issues with international issues, turned out to be
counterproductive because of the relentless market leadership of
the big-growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no way of knowing if the same will be true in the
future. ``I still thoroughly believe in diversification for my own
portfolio and for my clients,'' Kobren said, ``because you can
never know with certainty which sectors of the market will yield
the biggest returns in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Sticking to a diversified portfolio while market favorites come
and go can be trying, the experts conceded. ``Long-term investing
is my mantra and my faith,'' Evensky said, ``but I will admit that
sometimes, long-term seems interminable.''
</P>
<P>
   The exercise also reaffirmed the power of the financial markets
to confound expectations, said John Rekenthaler, now director of
research at Morningstar, who started the portfolio that was later
managed by Susan Dzuibinski and then Kinnell. He stuffed his
initial portfolio with funds holding small stocks, value issues and
overseas holdings; they had been superior performers over the long
term but had slumped around the time the exercise began, and
Rekenthaler thought they looked ripe for a rebound. As it turned
out, though, none caught up with the large caps. ``Expect to be
surprised,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rekenthaler said his own results occasionally caught him off
guard. ``I remembered my good picks,'' he said, ``and then forgot
the fact that I had a big stake in emerging-markets funds as the
whole sector tanked.'' The lesson: Track your investment results
carefully, so you can learn from your decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Brill's success ratifies an investing approach that seemed
unorthodox and untried in 1993. ``Socially responsible investing
works,'' he said. ``We have competitive returns because our
screening identifies high-quality, well-managed companies.'' He
added, ``I never tried to outsmart the market or get in on hot
sectors.''
</P>
<P>
   When he started, he said, there were only about 15
comprehensively screened social-investing funds, plus an additional
25 funds without the social label that qualified based on the types
of stocks they held. Those 40 choices have grown to more than 150
today, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Evensky recommends diversifying within asset classes. In that
vein, he used to include in client portfolios three funds run by
managers who choose large-cap growth stocks. In his hypothetical
portfolio for this exercise, though, he felt he had room for only
one, and chose the Yacktman Fund, whose subsequent performance was
disappointing. These days, he prefers index funds for large-cap
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Evensky said he learned another lesson the hard way: Not to make
a big bet on a new fund idea. At the outset he allocated some of
his portfolio to the Barr Rosenberg Market Neutral fund, which aims
to neutralize market volatility through a mix of long and short
sales. The idea fell flat; Evensky said the fund's managers told
him its undoing was a run of extraordinary behavior by the stock
market that no one could have anticipated. Now, Evensky said, he
advises waiting for a few years until a new concept has proved
itself in different market environments.
</P>
<P>
   Realigning a portfolio periodically is wise, all five experts
said, because strong performance in one area could lead to an
ill-advised concentration of assets. The five hypothetical
portfolios could be rebalanced quarterly, and generally were; once
a year is probably often enough for most long-term investors.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, don't be too quick to sell, Evensky said. After he
researches a fund and buys its shares, he will stick with it
through two years of bad times if performance seems likely to
improve. But he dumps funds immediately when managers change their
stripes, say by adding big overseas positions or by switching style
from growth to value-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
