<HEADLINE>
FLOWERING SCREENS: PERENNIALS FOR PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 9)  
 By PATRICIA A. TAYLOR  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Little did I realize the price to be paid that fall when my
neighbors told me the dying maple tree edging our property line
would be cut down. All I could think of was the sunshine that would
bathe the garden borders I had been trying to create. But then, the
following spring, I realized that the gift of sunshine had led to
the loss of privacy between our small lots.
</P>
<P>
   To recapture some feeling of our own space, my husband replaced
the 4-foot wire fence with a wooden lattice fence 6 feet tall, as
high as allowed in our community. That helped, but not enough. So I
turned to giant perennials, plants that would form a wall of
greenery and soar above the fence with colorful flowers. I reasoned
that they would be a stopgap while I decided on an appropriate tree
for the area.
</P>
<P>
   To add a bit of flair, I chose little-known flowers. To guard
against gaps in my privacy screen, I made sure the plants were all
easy-care natives. This unusual, relatively inexpensive planting _
perennials cost much less than trees or shrubs _ has been so
successful that I've never changed it. Indeed, I've added perennial
screens in several other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Two Joe-Pye weed cultivars (in the Eupatorium genus) are
essential components of these screens. Magnets for bees and
butterflies, both feature flower clusters that form huge umbrellas
crowning each 7- to 8-foot plant for at least four midsummer weeks.
Gateway is doused with rosy purple, and Bartered Bride is covered
with white. When their flowers are cut for arrangements (in the
early morning to beat the insect rush), new blossoms take their
place in about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The stalks can be cut back in late spring to hold the final size
of the plants to 5 feet. I do this to get a layered look: stalks
nearest to the front of the border are cut, and those in back reach
their full height.
</P>
<P>
   These are supposed to be moisture-loving plants. Yet, to my
great delight, they performed splendidly (although with a shorter
bloom period) in last year's severe drought.
</P>
<P>
   Adding three more giant perennials, I can decorate my privacy
screens with uninterrupted color through summer and often into
fall. They are tough prairie plants, ones that can take both
drought and deluge in their stride.
</P>
<P>
   The first to bloom, usually by late June, is the regal
Queen-of-the-Prairie (Filipendula rubra Venusta). This magnificent
plant bears cotton candy plumes of pink flowers for two to three
weeks and grows to 6 or 7 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   In its natural habitat, Queen-of-the-Prairie wanders through
tall grasses and has to be a bit aggressive to compete. Where there
is no competition, as in my border, it takes off. I've finally
hemmed it in by surrounding it with orange day lilies.
</P>
<P>
   The lemon-yellow flowers on cup plant (Silphium perfoliatum)
start their four- to six-week bloom period in mid-July, decorated
by myriad butterflies. Undecorated, they look like 2-inch-wide
daisies and are lovely in arrangements. When they finish flowering,
they leave seed heads that are goldfinch favorites.
</P>
<P>
   The cup plant, which grows up to 8 feet, gets its name from the
unusual configuration of its leaves. These fold out from set
intervals on stout stems, forming small cups. Hummingbirds have
been known to quench their thirst from these troughs after a light
rain.
</P>
<P>
   The equally tall yellow coneflower (Rudbeckia Herbstsonne) is an
example of an American native that has been refined by German plant
breeders; the cultivar name means autumn sun in English. In my
garden, however, the flowers usually open in late July, a week or
so after the first cup plant flowers unfurl. The coneflower's bloom
period is much longer, often up to 10 weeks, and its flowers are a
richer yellow.
</P>
<P>
   The two plants look lovely together or as attractions in their
own right. Both have rich, dark green leaves that form a handsome
backdrop for the shorter plants placed in front.
</P>
<P>
   All these perennials get a bit top-heavy when in flower and need
some propping up. I slip dark green garden string through holes in
the lattice and tie it around the plant stems once they have
reached 5 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Queen-of-the-Prairie, all increase slowly over time,
both through self-seeding and through root spread. This has allowed
me to tinker with the color combinations over the years. The plants
are all easy to move in spring when new growth starts to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Which all goes to show that you can have your sunshine and enjoy
your privacy, too.
</P>
<P>
   All plants described are available from Milaeger's Gardens
through www.garden.com or (800) 466-8142. Bartered Bride and
Queen-of-the-Prairie are also offered by Forestfarm, 990 Tetherow
Road, Williams, Ore. 97544-9599; (541) 846-7269 or
www.forestfarm.com; catalog, $4.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK: Chase Away Pests, Fungus and Mildew &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By PATRICIA JONAS
</P>
<P>
   Rhododendrons require good drainage: their shallow roots may
suffocate in waterlogged soil, and in heat they're susceptible to
Phytophthora wilt, an overall wilting that begins with new growth.
If drainage is improved, the plant may fight this fungal disease.
If it succumbs, remove and destroy it, and do not plant another
rhododendron (or azalea) in the same spot.
</P>
<P>
   Horticultural oil is now recommended for treatment of powdery
mildew _ as well as for control of soft-bodied insects like aphids
and mites. At the first sign of infection, begin spraying plants
weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Control slugs with organic bait containing iron phosphate.
Diatomaceous earth will also control both slugs and ants, but must
be reapplied after rain.
</P>
</TEXT>
