<P>
   WORLD-BANK-CHINA (Washington) _ _ Under heavy pressure from the
United States, the World Bank's board on Friday overruled the
bank's leaders and denied funding for a sensitive Chinese
antipoverty project that had sparked a North-South struggle over
development aid. The $160 million Chinese project, part of which
would have resettled 58,000 ethnic Chinese in an area that nomadic
Tibetan herdsman once dominated, divided some of the bank's leading
borrowers from rich nations, including the United States. Rarely
has any World Bank project aroused as much internal dissent and
outside protest. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-SEX-CHARGE (Washington) _ The two-star Army general
accused of sexually harassing the service's highest-ranking woman
has decided to retire, the Army announced Friday. Maj. Gen. Larry
Smith was given a written reprimand for conduct unbecoming an
officer and of sexually harassing another officer, but it appeared
unlikely that he would be reduced in rank. By Christopher Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-PLATFORM (St. Louis) _ Democrats release a draft of their
party's platform. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ After a disastrous May, American
companies added modestly to their payrolls in June, creating
206,000 new jobs, the Labor Department reported Friday _
reinforcing the impression that the economy is gradually slowing.
Job creation has now clearly slowed from an average of 244,000 a
month in the first quarter to only 110,000 a month from April
through June. But if companies are more reluctant to hire, they are
not laying off people either. The unemployment rate edged down to 4
percent in June from 4.1 in May. And some economists argued that
inflation could rise, even as the economy slows. By Louis
Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WAR-CRIMES-DEFINED (Undated) _ From the grisly amputations of
the hands of innocents in Sierra Leone to the systematic sexual
abuse of women in Bosnia and Rwanda _ or, some would say, to the
bombing of Kosovo refugees by NATO war planes _ modern conflicts
raise new and complex issues. There still is not total agreement on
universally accepted moral codes. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
