<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE THE MEDIA HYPE, DEATH PENALTY STILL ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm always reading or hearing on television that the public has
turned against capital punishment, that it's only a matter of time
until Death Row is a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you saw the article in USA Today:
</P>
<P>
   ``From Oregon to Maryland, grass-roots efforts to abolish or
impose a moratorium on the death penalty are multiplying rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Church-based groups are lobbying city councils. Prominent
former and current members of Congress are speaking out on the
issue and heading ballot initiatives. Death-penalty opponents
looking at the national political landscape have rarely been more
encouraged...''
</P>
<P>
   Gee whiz. Maybe I ought to just throw in the towel. Maybe I
should forget about capital punishment and the pure form of legal
and social justice that it represents.
</P>
<P>
   Yep. It must be time to kiss the death penalty goodbye. Long
live the serial killers. Long live the vermin who gun down cops for
the sheer sport of it. Long live the murderous sociopaths who rape,
rob, torture, mutilate, shoot, stab _ the list could go on, but you
get the idea _ and then claim that their own precious lives should
be spared because they couldn't afford to hire Johnnie Cochran to
defend them in court.
</P>
<P>
   The American people, it says here, have decided that capital
punishment is bad.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. If everyone thinks the death penalty is bad, why do I
keep hearing from readers who say it's good?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to commend you for your recent article, `Gary Graham
got what he deserved,' which was printed in the opinion section of
the Los Angeles Daily News dated June 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your voice is a breath of fresh air to offset ... those who
favor the miscreants over ... the victims in our crime ridden
society. Your point of view is seldom heard above those who favor
criminals' rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The column that this reader found so refreshing had to do with
my reaction to the long overdue lethal injection of Texas murderer
Gary Graham, who stalled the executioner for nearly two decades
before sanity prevailed against the bleeding-heart hysteria of the
anti-death penalty lobby.
</P>
<P>
   I'm far too humble to quote myself, of course, so in case you
missed the column I hereby offer a nutshell summary. ``Columnist to
Graham: Good riddance.''
</P>
<P>
   Several California readers replied in a similar vein, which was
interesting since big-deal members of the Hollywood acting
fraternity were prominent among the weepers and gnashers demanding
mercy for the merciless Graham. Danny Glover led the pre-execution
clamor to spare Graham's life while post-needle mourning was
provided by the likes of Susan Sarandon and Mike Farrell.
</P>
<P>
   Ubiquitous headline-grabber Jesse Jackson and jet-setting
activist Bianca Jagger hauled their bleeding hearts and mindless
slogans all the way to Texas to witness Graham's demise. Now that's
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your characterization of the `famous' people was a delight to
read,'' wrote another L.A. reader.''
</P>
<P>
   Humility notwithstanding, I'm inclined to agree. What could be
more fun than dismissing Bianca Jagger as a ``dilettante''?
</P>
<P>
   I did hear from a reader or three who took issue with such
characterizations, but the naysayers were vastly outnumbered by
positive responses such as this one from a reader in Alabama:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank goodness there's a level-headed media columnist still
around! It's a real relief being able to read a sensible op-ed
column in a left-wing rag such as the Birmingham News.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you ever notice how many people are convinced that the
hometown newspaper _ any hometown newspaper _ is a left-wing rag?
</P>
<P>
   That reader who called me level-headed, by the way, said he
taught journalism for 12 years at three different universities.
</P>
<P>
   Finally. Some respect from academia.
</P>
<P>
   Back here in the hinterlands, meanwhile, the evidence is
overwhelming that the death penalty is alive and well. Just plain
folks are unambiguous in their belief that the Gary Grahams of this
world should be dispatched from this world.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
