<HEADER>
A5671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WRITING-FOR-KIDS-925(     07-07 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRITING-FOR-KIDS-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULAR CHILDREN'S BOOKS HAVE ROOTS IN ANGUISH 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDEN ROSS LIPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All across the United States today children and adults are
lining up at bookstores, clamoring to begin reading J.K. Rowling's
fourth Harry Potter adventure.
</P>
<P>
   All across the country, too, untold numbers of would-be Rowlings
are sitting at home feverishly typing, trying to turn out a
best-selling children's book, perhaps hoping that it will become a
children's classic. Many if not most of them assume that writing
children's books is simple _ easier, surely, than writing for
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Very wrong.
</P>
<P>
   As those who do it best have testified, writing well for
children is, first and last, very difficult. Adults who read ``The
Tale of Peter Rabbit'' as children remember the images of
blue-jacketed bunnies hopping through the cabbages in Mr.
McGregor's garden as sweet and funny, but children generally grasp
the fact that Beatrix Potter was writing about life and death.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as memoirs and biographies have shown, the great
children's works have often been the products of personal
difficulty and stress, a narrative distillation of anguished
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics have observed the central role of outsiders in
children's literature. The heroes are typically underdogs, youngest
children, orphans or, like Harry Potter, some combination of these.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there have been many cheerful storytellers who have
beguiled young readers with what the biographer and critic Leonard
Marcus has called ``innocent thoughts, and happy endings, and
little more than that.'' But the masterpieces, those often tough
tales that people chew over long after they turn out the lights,
are commonly survivor literature, for both the teller and the tale.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to modern scholarship, we know that many of the 19th- and
early-20th-century greats were beset by trauma. There was Hans
Christian Andersen, broody and reclusive, and Louisa May Alcott,
who romanticized the confusion of her own childhood in the
self-portrait of Jo in ``Little Women.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Carroll's obsession with little girls has become a staple
of academic commentary, discussed in greater detail than almost any
reader of ``Alice in Wonderland'' would ever want or need. And
Beatrix Potter's diaries show us a young woman determined to resist
the stifling environment of her boorish, wealthy family. As the
novelist and critic Alison Lurie has put it, Potter ``escaped from
prison with the help of a rabbit'' _ Peter Rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at a shelf of modern classic titles for children from
babyhood to early adolescence indicates how little has changed.
Those who tell the tales that endure have struggled. Many
contemporary writers whose best-known work is deceptively
lighthearted have written troubling, even depressing, memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Boy,'' published for children, and ``Going Solo,'' for
children and adults, Roald Dahl set out his childhood in terms as
stark as any fairy tale. Although his biographer, Jeremy Treglown,
has demonstrated that he exaggerated and misstated some points, the
reality of his boarding school misery _ the cruel teachers, wicked
shopkeepers and nasty pranks _ and of his strangely intense
relationship with his widowed Norwegian mother remain unmistakably
disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   For many children and adults Ramona Quimby is the quintessential
modern American heroine of early-grade fiction. Beverly Cleary's
affectionate family novels about Ramona, her sister Beezus, her
parents and her friends on Klickitat Street are beloved as much for
their characters' ability to deal calmly with misfortune as for
their accounts of comic mishap.
</P>
<P>
   Cleary's sunny prose seems to have been hard won, because in her
two memoirs, ``A Girl from Yamhill'' and ``My Own Two Feet,''
written for older children and adults, she recounts a fairly grim
childhood in Portland, Ore., during the Depression. The strain of
living through hard times with a severe, demanding mother who never
hugged or spoke of loving her is set out plainly.
</P>
<P>
   Transforming early childhood stress can take many forms.
Everyone today understands that Maurice Sendak's ``Where the Wild
Things Are'' is about early childhood temper tantrums and
permission, but when it was published in 1963 it was stunningly new
and was quickly understood in Freudian terms. Sendak, who spent
many years in psychoanalysis, has explained that the book's fanged
creatures were, in fact, his relatives who came for his mother's
Sunday dinners and patronized the children.
</P>
<P>
   Sendak has also described the frightening impact on him, as on
so many others raised in the 1930s, of the kidnapping of Charles
Lindbergh's baby son. It was one of the explicit sources for his
lushly illustrated and alarming tale of Ida and her baby sister,
``Outside Over There.''
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Paterson, the internationally acclaimed novelist whose
fiction has ranged widely from feudal China and Japan to the
Industrial Revolution in 19th-century Vermont, has been open about
the painful experiences that inspired two of her most widely
admired contemporary novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Gilly Hopkins'' emerged from a brief spell as a
foster parent. The 1978 Newbery Medal novel, ``The Bridge to
Terabithia,'' now considered a classic, is about an improbable but
powerful friendship between a boy named Jess and a girl named
Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   Young readers often find themselves sobbing over the section of
the novel after Leslie's accidental death. Accepting the Newbery
Medal, Paterson explained that the book was her way of dealing with
the death of a friend of one of her sons and with her own recovery
from cancer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The sustained popularity of Gary Paulsen's 1987 novel
``Hatchet,'' about a 13-year-old boy who spends 54 days alone in
the Canadian wilderness with only a hatchet for a tool, along with
its sequels, ``The River,'' ``Brian's Winter'' and ``Brian's
Return,'' leaves it poised to become a children's classic.
</P>
<P>
   Paulsen's prose is Hemingway-terse, and his plots tend to
involve tests of endurance. He has talked about his miserable
childhood with alcoholic and abusive parents. As a boy he spent
much of his time escaping _ staying with relatives, building
himself a hiding place in the cellar behind the furnace, fleeing
into the woods. ``Whenever I went into the woods, all the hassles
of life were very quickly forgotten,'' he has said.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Jo Rowling? The story of a young divorced mum on the
dole, sitting in Edinburgh cafes with her infant daughter and
writing ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone'' in 1994 is
legend. It omits the fact that she'd begun sketches for some
characters as early as 1976, when she was a teen-ager, and
continued working on them steadily thereafter; the Harry Potter
character came into her mind more than five years before the first
novel was finished.
</P>
<P>
   In its sketchy portrayal of a difficult life, the legend is not
wrong; it just skips over the 10-year struggle of Rowling's mother
with multiple sclerosis before her death in 1990 at age 45,
Rowling's bad marriage to a television journalist, her bouts of
depression and the very hard work that went into plotting the world
of Hogwarts.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a full generation for a book, no matter how successful,
to shift into classic status, and the jury is not even out on the
unfolding Harry Potter. Time will tell. For the moment it's a
phenomenon. But hard work, luck and travails like those of Rowling
may be the stuff of which a children's classic is made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
