<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5703 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-FAKE-HANDBAGS-ART-$AD     07-07 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAKE-HANDBAGS-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAKES NOW DANGLE ON ARMS THAT ONCE SPORTED BRAND NAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, July 9)  
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last year, Anri Yasuda bought a Fendi baguette, the
most coveted bag of the season. In a matter of weeks her purchase
had lost its allure, becoming about as exciting to her as a
plateful of warmed-over cabbage. ``With a luxury bag, you're bored
of it after one season,'' said Yasuda, a philosophy major at
Columbia University. ``That's when the new ones come out.''
</P>
<P>
   So nowadays, Yasuda, 19, feeds her passion for style and novelty
by prowling the stands of the street vendors dotting Manhattan from
upper Madison Avenue to the Lower East Side and Canal Street. A
counterfeit python cowboy hat, a rayon ``pashmina'' _ if it looks
good and the price is right (no more than $30), she'll take it.
Recently, she expanded her list of desirable knockoffs to include
high-status handbags. She's on the lookout for a fake Hermes Birkin
bag (priced at $4,800 to $5,500 for the real thing).
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get tired of it, I'll put little stickers all over it
to make it look special,'' she said. ``And if everyone has the same
bag, so what?''
</P>
<P>
   Like Yasuda, Selma Scheinbach scours street vendors' stalls for
bargains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street accessories are cheap and accessible,'' she said. ``You
don't have to run all over the stores to find them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm walking, I'm shopping,'' Scheinbach, who is in her
60's, added. ``Whether it's a hot dog or a handbag, if I see what I
want on the corner, it's mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Both women are typical of a new breed of sidewalk shopper:
consumers of evident style and means who can afford to pay retail
but enjoy the thrill of adding a $30 counterfeit or two to their
wardrobes. Where the shoppers stooping to inspect street
merchandise were once mainly office workers and tourists, now they
are as likely to be chic passers-by, clutching a genuine Prada
shoulder bag style or a tote emblazoned with real Gucci double G's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real shopper, you can tell who they are by their designer
labels,'' said Christian, a vendor selling bags last week at
Madison and 59th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The new upscale customer seems to be responding to an upgrade in
the counterfeit merchandise that's available and a trend among
done-it-all shoppers for cheap ``trophy'' purchases.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, sidewalk fakes were limited mainly to
generic-looking black nylon ``Pradas'' and impostor ``Louis
Vuittons.'' But styles today are more diverse, sophisticated and
authentic-looking, among them the currently sought-after Prada
bowling bag shapes, Kate Spade-style straw totes and minuscule
evening bags that imitate Fendi and Judith Leiber designs.
</P>
<P>
   The counterfeits sell on the street for $20 to $50 or more, as
against $250 to more than $5,000 for the designer originals. Where
once only a handful of peddlers catered to the status-starved, now
they crop up on every other block, staking out turf along Madison
Avenue between 50th Street and 70th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, there is a certain badge value in getting
things at a reasonable price,'' said Richard Leonard, vice
president of the Zandl Group, a New York consumer research firm.
``If that item is actually counterfeit, bought in the street, to
that consumer it really doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have been describing Lauren Stax of Houston, a student
at the University of Texas. Stax says she owns a genuine Kate Spade
canvas bag.
</P>
<P>
   She also has a handsome Spade impostor, bought on the street.
Poring over a table strewn with handbags at 59th Street and Madison
Avenue, she said, ``I don't care if these are real or fake, and
most people I know don't care either.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor do many shoppers appear to be concerned that the vendors
they buy from are flouting the law. Counterfeit accessories _ those
with the logo or the identifiable colors and designs of brand-name
bags and accessories _ violate Federal and local trademark laws.
Moreover, the vendors who sell them are often unlicensed, subject
to periodic sweeps by the New York City police, who confiscate
their wares.
</P>
<P>
   But the laws are enforced only fitfully. On Madison Avenue on
Thursday, a security guard hired by the Madison Avenue Business
Improvement District looked on serenely as, just yards away on 66th
Street, a vendor peddled ``Tod's'' fake patent leather shoulder
bags, plastic ``Vuitton'' clutches and canvas ``Gucci'' slings.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury makers are not amused. The International
AntiCounterfeiting Coalition in Washington says counterfeiting has
tripled in the last 10 years and now costs legitimate businesses
$350 billion in annual sales. That figure encompasses auto parts as
well as fashion accessories and is somewhat inflated, since many
people who buy bogus goods might not have purchased the
higher-priced originals. Nevertheless, counterfeit accessories
cheapen the image of legitimate brands.
</P>
<P>
   Most high-end handbag look-alikes are made in China or Korea,
the anticounterfeiting coalition says. Often, bogus logos and
signature hardware are later glued, sewn or riveted on in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Such telltale signs of counterfeiting as poorly sewn labels,
inferior stitching and materials that reek of petroleum don't seem
to deter many shoppers, especially the young. Ever alert for a
bargain, ``they're more independent and less easily manipulated
than some older shoppers are,'' said Leonard of the Zandl Group,
``and they are increasingly likely to shop in the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Many shoppers turn to counterfeit wares out of disenchantment
with legitimate brands. Posting a message at Hintmag.com, a fashion
Web site aimed at young women, one disgruntled shopper wrote:
``Kate Spade bags are rectangular totes, done in different
materials . . . yawn. They're very easy to make, no wonder all the
counterfeits.''
</P>
<P>
   Most days of the week, such shoppers are likely to be found
perusing the wares spread on sheets on Lexington Avenue near
Bloomingdale's. There, imitation Prada ostrich purses and impostor
Fendi baguettes lure shoppers young and old. But at the first hint
of trouble _ the appearance of a security guard _ the merchandise
goes under wraps, vanishing faster than Brigadoon.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Christian, who declined to give his last name for
fear of arrest, displayed Coach and Kate Spade look-alikes. ``We
had a police sweep yesterday, so I don't have by best
merchandise,'' he said. ``On good days, we have Fendi, Prada,
Gucci, you name it. And they sell for about $35.''
</P>
<P>
   As he talked he kept watch for potential customers, the ones
already displaying designer labels, whom he claimed to be able to
spot a half-block away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to stop the real shoppers,'' he said. ``The others, you
try to get them, too. But you're not going to stress yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely he would put himself out to attract Samantha
Adam, a young tourist who writes for Madame Figaro, the French
style weekly. She was eyeing the bags a little furtively as she
stood on a corner waiting for a friend. Adam, who was simply
dressed and showing no logos, said she shuns counterfeit bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer to pay for the real one,'' she said. ``Even if it
goes out of the trend right away.''
</P>
<P>
   But she conceded that certain kinds of merchandise might tempt
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoes make me crazy,'' Adam said. ``Imagine if these people
sold them in the street. A woman could really get wild.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
