<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5713 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-WEDDING-PHOTO-OP-$ADV     07-07 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-PHOTO-OP-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD CLASS SETTING FOR WEDDING ALBUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, July 9) 
 By GUY TREBAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The brides were tacking in white satin, trains billowing, veils
lofting like the topsails of the tall ships entering New York
harbor. Gliding across a marble expanse, Guatemala circled Korea,
with Jamaica and China close at hand. A Salvadoran bridal party
sailed toward a Custard Beach outlet, breaking through a throng of
tourists gathered for the 18th annual Brown family reunion.
Briefly, the wedding group changed course to join the Browns in
slurping French ice cream from Belgian waffle cones.
</P>
<P>
   The setting for this odd apparition was the Winter Garden of the
World Financial Center on the Fourth of July weekend. Just as a
light breeze bellied the white sails floating up the nearby Hudson,
blasts of freon-treated air puffed the many net tulle spinnakers
indoors. It was a special moment for the people involved, but no
special occasion. This sort of thing takes place here all the time.
The midpoints of winter and summer are high season for wedding
photography in this vast lobby, a de facto chapel of love, which
also happens to be a headquarters for Dow Jones, American Express
and the accounting romantics at Deloitte &AMP; Touche.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sometimes counted 10 white stretch limos parked at
once,'' said Melissa Coley, the World Financial Center's vice
president for arts and events. The Winter Garden's photo op appeal
is obvious to anyone. With a 14-story vaulted atrium paved in
tricolor marble, a tiered and platformed Loretta Young stairway and
an anomalous grove of 16 50-foot palm trees, it might be the
grandest photo studio in New York. Although corporations pay as
much as $33,000 to rent it, as a public space it is essentially
free. Unlike Conservatory Garden in Central Park, the Angel of the
Waters statue on Bethesda Fountain or the Vale of Cashmere in
Prospect Park _ other wedding photography favorites _ it is
weatherproof. As a bonus, the sun bouncing off the World Trade
Center tends to fall through the atrium's glass ceiling, bathing
the Winter Garden lobby in lambent pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wedding picture thing has been going on since before the
palm trees were even here,'' Coley said, or since 1988. On a good
day there can be as many as two dozen marital parties trooping
through. They pose on the stairs, on the plaza, even on escalators,
and then proceed to the covered footbridge vaulting Liberty Street,
where a floor of coral marble reflects flattering light on brides.
``You see them sitting in the windows looking wistful,'' Coley
said.
</P>
<P>
   So what if it is not Bachrach Studio? So what if your wedding
pictures may contain scores of people you have never met? Does it
necessarily detract from the day that perfect strangers stop to ask
if you have carefully considered what you are about to undertake?
Relatives won't do that. (Well, all right, Uncle Al will.) And
relatives are not typically as cute as, say, Nari Lee, 5, and Seri
Lee, 3, sisters who insinuated themselves into numerous wedding
shots as they twirled down the stairs in petal pink skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it possible that the grandkids will enjoy the wedding
narrative more if it involves the appearance of unhinged strangers
making wisecracks at the tenderest moments? Take the bystander who
stopped a bridesmaid during the Jones-Davis wedding photo shoot to
ask what is black and white and red all over. The man was wearing a
Bazooka-color baseball cap, lime green hot pants and an Abe Lincoln
goatee. ``I don't know,'' replied the bridesmaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newspaper,'' said the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really,'' the bridesmaid said. ``I was thinking something more
along the lines of a skunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Wing Zhong Lam lifted a bouffant-gowned and radiant Mei
Mei Liu onto a planter so a friend could videotape her in the
round. Lam and his wife chose the Winter Garden for their wedding
pictures, he said, ``just for, like, a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lam wedding party was small, principals only, plus a maid of
honor in a tinsel tiara and six friends talking on cell phones. If
their casual clothes made them look, as David Sedaris once remarked
of Americans abroad, as though they had come to mow somebody's
lawn, they certainly fitted into the Winter Garden's gorgeous
mosaic.
</P>
<P>
   There was the usual mini-General Assembly on hand: people in
saris, in salwar kameez, in skullcaps and side curls, in safari
outfits and in crisp white nautical uniforms. There were
representatives of the 50 states, most wearing cargo shorts, many
packing Snugli baby carriers, all trooping through the atrium in
happy surprise as they observed the nuptial costumes and folkways
of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been variable over the years,'' Coley said of trends in
wedding-party costume. ``There was a peach phase in the early '90s.
Then that went into pink. Lately, everyone's into purple and a lot
of red.''
</P>
<P>
   For the wedding of Maurice Rico and Judy Lombardi, the four
bridesmaids had chosen dresses in
always-tasteful-if-shocking-for-daytime black chiffon. The actual
nuptials, which had not yet occurred, would wait until a lunchtime
ceremony at Windows on the World. The photo session was scheduled
first to capitalize on midday light, gloriously diffused on the
stairway between the lobby's revolving doors and the Coco Marina
``outdoor'' cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to do marriage pictures here,'' said Edgardo
Jiminez, a photographer who uses the Winter Garden for modeling
shoots. ``It gives the people a lot of luck. With the water right
outside, it's got kind of a holy feeling for me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the mood Rudy Pollack, a 35-year veteran of the wedding
photography trade, was trying to capture. Sprawled on his stomach
across the stairs, he had Lombardi and her uncomfortable
bridegroom-to-be framed in the viewfinder of his Hasselblad. With a
series of almost imperceptible hand waves, he subtly managed to
direct their poses to the great wedding album cliches: the ``I Got
You, Babe'' handclasp, the ``We've Only Just Begun'' embrace and
the ``My Heart Will Go On'' middle-distance gaze.
</P>
<P>
   Then he abruptly waved Rico out of the frame and got down to the
business of commemorating the dress _ a custom-designed strapless
confection with an impressively cantilevered bodice and a cloth
rose pinning the train. ``I had a vision of something that's good
for evening after you detach the train, so you can wear it to a
black-and-white affair,'' Lombardi explained, as an attendant
draped satin across the lobby steps in light that caused the fabric
to glow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I do think it's nice getting married in here,'' remarked
Charlene Brown, part of the Brown family reunion, happening upon
the scene. ``Yes, she is looking really, really cute,'' added
Charlene's twin sister, Zoelene, who tactfully waited until she was
out of earshot to voice her doubts about the wisdom of using your
best dress to buff a lobby floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
