A5724 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX     07-07 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRETCH THOSE PATRIOTIC MUSCLES AND SING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL HARRAL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' my wife said Tuesday, ``that I've ever seen
anybody fluff a flag before.''
</P>
<P>
   We were watching the posting of the colors at the Fourth of July
service at First Presbyterian Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth of July should cause reflection on the founding
principles on which the United States was established; it should
elicit thanks for the sacrifices of many who fought first for
independence and then to continue that independence; and it should
celebrate who we are and what we stand for.
</P>
<P>
   First Presbyterian's service does all that.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a holiday tradition for many, mostly a sing-along with
a pickup choir. Best you get there early if you want a seat, in
part because of the added benefit that the sidewalk area outside
the church is an excellent vantage point from which to view the
city's fireworks display.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Airman James Horan of Grapevine, Texas, and Master Sgt.
Sean Baumgartner of Fort Worth of the 136th Airlift Wing Honor
Guard, Air National Guard, posted the colors.
</P>
<P>
   That's always a solemn occasion, since the flags are being
handled by men and sometimes women who have sworn that they are
ready to give their lives in their defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Baumgartner, handling the Stars and Stripes, did something
extra. After he had placed the flagstaff in its stand, he wasn't
satisfied with the way the flag was draped. So he arranged it the
way he was taught at Air Force honor guard school at Bolling Air
Force Base in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   When he was finished, the stripes to the audience's right were
horizontal and tucked beneath the field of stars on the audience's
left. The gold fringe on the flag's edge cut diagonally and
precisely across the display from upper left to lower right and
then tucked under the cascade of red and white stripes on the left.
</P>
<P>
   It was beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   We said the Pledge of Allegiance. And then we sang ``The
Star-Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how the National Anthem is meant to be sung _ not solo
by some name-brand star but by people with ordinary voices, some
straining to hit those impossibly high notes.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know when the trend to listen rather than sing started,
but I've noticed in the last few years that fewer and fewer people
sing at public gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's because someone decided that the ``The
Star-Spangled Banner'' ought to be a presentation by someone well
known instead of the common sharing of heritage that it always used
to be.
</P>
<P>
   But when we only listen, we miss part of the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday we sang an armed forces medley, made up of songs from
all of the branches of service, and as we sang each song, audience
members who had some connection with that branch _ their own
service, the service of a relative, the loss of a loved one _ were
asked to stand.
</P>
<P>
   I was never in the military, but my wife and I stood during the
Army song in honor of her father who served in World War II, my
father who served in World War I, my brother who served in Vietnam
and our son who is a member of the Army National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the way the invitation was issued, everyone in the
audience had the opportunity to stand at some point.
</P>
<P>
   I raise this issue because I suspect that love of country is
like a lot of things _ the more you practice it, the better you are
at it.
</P>
<P>
   You never completely forget how to hit a baseball, but you can't
go long periods of time without swinging a bat and expect to be a
good batter.
</P>
<P>
   I'm afraid that we aren't practicing patriotism quite enough.
Too many people do not stand and remove their hats when the flag
passes by. Too many talk while the ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' is
being performed and too few sing.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Smart, a friend who has spent some time outside the United
States, told me recently that you don't realize how patriotic you
can be until you've lived somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   At home, we've let patriotism become routine.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a suggestion: If you are staging an event, don't bring a
name singer in to perform the Anthem. A band, sure. Perhaps a
chorus.
</P>
<P>
   But the point is that for the 60 seconds that it takes the
audience sing the first verse of the National Anthem we are, in
fact, ``one nation under God, indivisible, with liberty and justice
for all.''
</P>
<P>
   And we need to be reminded of that regularly.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is vice president and editorial director for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His e-mail address is
harral(at)star-telegram.com. You may telephone him at (817)
390-7836 or write him at P.O. Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
