<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5725 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-FLOW-ART-$ADV     07-07 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-FLOW-ART-$ADV09-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHIPWRECK FAILS TO HALT THE TECHNOLOGY TIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By DANNY HAKIM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Keith Brown, the top marketing executive for the $512
million Amerindo Technology fund, one of the most prominent stars
in the firmament of technology offerings, the second quarter was,
if not the best of times, then not too shabby. Investors deposited
some $12 million into his fund during the quarter _ even amid the
gyrations of the technology-driven Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
   For his boss, the money manager Alberto Vilar, the second
quarter was, by contrast, definitely disappointing: The fund lost a
stomach-churning 26.7 percent for its investors.
</P>
<P>
   The story played out much the same at other mutual funds with a
sweet tooth for technology _ whether aggressive-growth funds that
populate so many 401(k) plans, the scores of technology sector
funds that run tens of billions of dollars or the dozens of
Internet funds that have emerged virtually overnight over the last
two and a half years. For these fund groups, the second quarter of
2000 turned out to be a tale of two executives.
</P>
<P>
   While the honeymoon ended for techno-centric money managers,
their marketers still seem to be enjoying a surprisingly easy sell.
No matter that the average technology sector fund was down 11.2
percent in the quarter. Or that the Nasdaq composite index lost
13.3 percent. Or that Internet companies were forced into a round
of belt-tightening, layoffs and, in the case of online retailers
like Boo.com and Toysmart.com, into bankruptcy. Or even that
institutional investors seemed to be displaying a distinct coolness
to the sector.
</P>
<P>
   Indefatigable individual investors kept buying technology funds.
Cash flow into technology sector funds totaled $1.97 billion for
April, the worst month of the technology sell-off, according to AMG
Data Services, a research firm in Arcata, Calif.; investors sank an
additional $1.09 billion into the funds in May. Although that is
far below the record $10.97 billion that flowed into such funds in
February, the month before the Nasdaq composite peaked, it is in
line with what investors were putting into the funds in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Weekly figures compiled by AMG, which cover a smaller universe
of funds, show the trend continuing in June: Cash flows increased
assets by an estimated 2 percent for the month.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, individual investors have not turned tail from
technology in the way that scores of institutional money managers
and analysts had predicted they would in the event of a market
correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``What surprises me about the numbers is that they've held up so
well,'' said Robert Adler, president of AMG. ``Investors haven't
abandoned the market, and they haven't abandoned technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with investors' behavior during another period of
market extremes, the emerging-markets meltdown of 1998. According
to AMG, outflows from emerging-markets stock funds totaled $4.05
billion for the year, 12.3 percent of total assets.
</P>
<P>
   In a market environment that many people see as increasingly
driven by individual investors, sentiment is crucial. Even as
institutional investors _ pension and hedge funds in particular _
showed signs of retreat, individuals are charting their own
direction. If their money continues to pour into technology and
aggressive-growth funds, the shocks of April and May may well
register as only a breather in the aging bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is still perceived, correctly or not, as the
likeliest indicator of the market's future direction, if for no
other reason than that more than one-third of the market
capitalization of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index is in
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Technology, of course, takes several avenues into the American
portfolio. Sector funds are only one, accounting for only about 2
percent of the $7 trillion mutual fund industry. Far more important
are the nation's growth funds, the 800-pound gorillas of the
industry that form the backbone of so many portfolios and
retirement plans. During the meteoric run-up in technology stocks
in 1998 and 1999, many growth funds became de facto technology
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the $29.8 billion Fidelity Growth Co. fund, the sixth
most popular fund in defined-contribution retirement plans,
according to a study by Pensions &AMP; Investments magazine. At the end
of the first quarter, 53.2 percent of the fund's portfolio was in
technology, more than double the fund's position a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the $28.2 billion Fidelity Blue Chip Growth fund,
another top 10 retirement fund, was 43.4 percent invested in
technology, up from 26.2 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Other popular growth funds were even more heavily weighted in
the sector. At the end of the first quarter, the $31.8 billion
Janus Twenty fund had nearly 60 percent of its portfolio in
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Investors continue to strongly favor these growth funds over
funds whose managers practice a value strategy, which emphasizes
stocks that are priced at a discount relative to their intrinsic
worth. Though the sales gap between value and growth narrowed in
the second quarter, value-oriented funds still suffered net
outflows of $6.6 billion in April and May, while growth funds took
in $31 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big picture is that people are still playing where the
action has been,'' said Donald Cassidy, a senior research analyst
at Lipper Inc. ``They haven't panicked and they're not bargain
hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rekenthaler, research director of Morningstar Inc., added:
``I don't think anybody's faith in aggressive-growth investing has
been rocked, or fundamentally changed. Two months doesn't change
people's belief system.''
</P>
<P>
   So are investors showing foresight or folly in their continuing
rush into technology? Or have investors just become used to buying
on dips in volatile markets?
</P>
<P>
   Avi Nachmany, president of the consulting and research firm
Strategic Insight, called it ``a renaissance of national
optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The theory I have, why the commitment to new-economy investing
transcends the price level, is that in the end, you look at your
own personal experiences and ask, `How has my life changed with the
Internet?''' Nachmany said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many experiences that are fundamental to your
well-being. The e-mail you get from your grandmother in Florida,
the health advice you can get before you go to the doctor, the
cheaper plane tickets. We're just in the beginning of these kinds
of experiences. They will continue, regardless of the prices on the
Nasdaq.''
</P>
<P>
   Vilar, whose fund remains one of the top 10 performers over the
past three years despite last quarter's drubbing, agreed. ``The
trading in Internet stocks has been dominated by individuals. A lot
of people who bought the AOL's, the eBays or Yahoos were the people
who used them, the clients,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   It seems natural, of course, that if investors continue to buy
technology stocks, technology stock prices will keep going up.
Perhaps that was one reason the Nasdaq recovered in June, gaining
16.6 percent. But James Grant, editor of Grant's Interest Rate
Observer and known for his bearish views, says continued flows into
technology will just make the day of reckoning that much more
painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disappointment will be sharper,'' Grant said. ``Artificial
support under a fundamentally deteriorating market does not change
the fundamentals. It deepens the ultimate disappointment. We do
live in an age of technological miracles, but that does not change
the cyclical nature of markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flows will help at the margins, but they can't perpetuate a
trend indefinitely,'' Grant added. ``They can't perpetuate
technology indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as individuals went in, institutional investors showed
signs of pulling back. In May, $315.4 million flowed into the
technology sector from small trades _ those of less than 10,000
shares _ according to Birinyi Associates, which tracks money flows
in and out of the market; such small trades generally come from
individual investors. But larger block trades from institutional
investors took $502.4 million out of the sector in May; it was the
fourth month of outflows in the last five.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a total surprise. Institutional money managers are
more prone to short-term portfolio shifts, because they are usually
judged on a quarterly basis and adjust their allocations to conform
with risk benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say retail investors will play the tune for the
current market. ``I don't think investors will go on strike,''
Vilar said, ``and the reluctant brides, the institutional
investors, will be dragged to the altar.''
</P>
<P>
   It is testimony to the resilience of technology fund investors
that fund families have had the confidence to add technology
offerings _ and be rewarded for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   When Munder Capital Management, the company that runs the
nation's largest Internet fund, Munder NetNet, started an
international Internet fund, Munder International NetNet, on April
10, into the teeth of a collapsing market, investors still poured
money in. By the end of May, despite losing money in the market,
the fund had $367 million in assets.
</P>
<P>
   And Fidelity Investments, the nation's largest mutual fund
company, filed on June 30 with the Securities and Exchange
Commission to start Fidelity Select Networking and Infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   To John C. Bogle, the retired founder of the Vanguard Group,
America's continued infatuation with technology sector funds has
not brought out the best in the mutual fund industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has had fads all through its history,'' Bogle
said, citing bursts of interest for atomic energy funds in the
1950s and biotechnology funds in the early 1990s. Last quarter also
saw the start of a genomics-only fund, tapping into enthusiasm over
the mapping of the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to sell what we made,'' Bogle said. ``Now we make what
sells.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
