<HEADER>
A5729 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-DOWNTOWN-REVIVAL-1STL     07-07 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNTOWN-REVIVAL-1STLD-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAYOR BEHIND CHARLESTON'S REVIVAL SHARES HIS WISDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 9)  
 &HT;     (Eds: SUBS lede to add dropped word; pickup: It helped.   
 &HT;     (Stands for MAYOR-RILEY)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If there's such a thing as civic plagiarism,
Joseph P. Riley Jr., the six-term mayor of Charleston, S.C., and
architect of that city's downtown revitalization, did nothing on a
recent visit to upstate New York to discourage it.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that Albany Mayor Jerry Jennings, Troy Mayor Mark
Pattison and Cohoes Mayor John T. McDonald III seemed to be on the
same page with Riley, whose philosophy is that beautiful urban
design is the way to revive dying downtowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fan of Mayor Riley's and have been for a long time,''
said Pattison, who read Riley's writings promoting urban rebirth
for years before he became the mayor of Troy.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's reputation preceded him. He was named municipal leader
of the year in 1991 by American City and County magazine.
Washington Post columnist David S. Broder said that ``what has been
achieved here under his (Riley's) leadership is extraordinary.''
Newsweek magazine recently named Riley one of the 25 most dramatic
mayors in America.
</P>
<P>
   For a coastal city with a population of 100,000 and
approximately 500,000 in its tri-county metro area, Charleston
boasts a broad array of attractions and historic texture that have
earned it recognition as one of the most vibrant and livable cities
of its size in the country _ as well as a strong tourist
destination.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Riley's leadership, numerous historic buildings have been
renovated and reused in the downtown historic district. Affordable
housing has been built. A picturesque Waterfront Park has been
developed. A major hotel and retail shopping complex that includes
a Saks Fifth Avenue store has opened.
</P>
<P>
   The Spoleto Festival U.S.A. draws arts lovers and extends the
tourist season. A minor-league baseball team plays downtown in a
baseball park named for Riley. A new aquarium is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminded us that we all share similar problems, but he
helped point out that we need creative solutions to make things
happen,'' said Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent tour of downtown Albany following a breakfast
meeting with the quartet of mayors, an off-the-cuff remark by Riley
that he'd gamble on an Albany rebound and snap up available
property downtown wasn't lost on Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very impressed with what he saw here,'' Jennings said.
``He said it took him 10 years to begin to turn things around in
Charleston. It's frustrating to all of us as mayors that we can't
get things done more quickly than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience has taught Riley, who was first elected mayor in
1975, that reviving a moribund downtown is a marathon, not a
sprint. ``The Charleston miracle,'' as its civic boosters like to
characterize it, has been a quarter-century in the works.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, Charleston was in a sorry state of decay.
``Downtown Charleston was in total disarray, overgrown and weedy,
home to drug dealers, with 1.2 million square feet of vacant
commercial space on the main street through downtown,'' recalled
Ken Gifford, who ran Charleston's downtown revitalization program
from 1975-1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made it work is that we marshaled forces in real estate
and development, took away the incentives in the suburbs and made
it more attractive to do projects downtown,'' said Gifford, a
landscape architect by training who oversees an $87 million
expansion on the campus of the State University College at
Purchase, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other factor was Joe's genius in working the
chicken-dinner circuit, selling our vision and knitting together
coalitions among blacks downtown and white suburban voters,''
Gifford said. ``It was just a lot of hard work block by block,
project by project. That's why it's taken 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In an engaging drawl, Riley displayed his Southern charm and a
talent for wringing emotion and conveying passion out of a
discussion about old buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful and invigorating cities are vital to the future of
this country,'' he said. ``What goes on in the center, the city,
sparks and shapes life for the entire region around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley drew comparisons between Albany and Charleston for their
similar size, founding in the 17th century, proximity to rivers and
the fact both have been named an All-America City. (Riley didn't
gloat about his city's temperate climate, robust recent economy,
bustling port and the Atlantic Ocean at its doorstep.)
</P>
<P>
   Riley, 57, harkened back to his childhood and a time when ``the
hysterical society'' allowed the landmark historic Charleston Hotel
to be torn down to make way for a drive-through motel. Also, the
nation's first orphanage was razed for a Sears department store.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the stories of those buildings we didn't save that will
make you cry,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   Historic preservation, he declared, ``has made Charleston what
it is today'' and saved downtown from ``the bland streets of
sameness'' found in most recent suburban development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historic buildings are what give a community memories,
texture, a rhythm and a pleasing scale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Riley recounted how he said no to high-rise public housing
projects and built them to a smaller scale and sprinkled them
throughout city neighborhoods, causing controversy. ``I can show
you beautiful public housing that started the rebirth of certain
neighborhoods,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Riley turned thumbs down, too, on ``a big, ugly parking garage''
in downtown and made a huge drainage pump station downtown ``to
look beautiful, the way the Romans did their public works.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good urban design works every time,'' he said, creating a
vibrant and diverse downtown where the poor, working-class, wealthy
suburbanites and tourists shop and linger in grand public spaces.
``There's no excuse to build anything that does not add to the
beauty,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a dead downtown and transformed it into one of the
liveliest you'll find anywhere, with billions invested and more
than 150 buildings restored,'' Riley said. ``The heart of our city
now engenders pride and nourishes our people. That's why we did
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
