<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5737 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS &LR;      07-07 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NATIONAL DATABASE NEEDED TO REVERSE RISING CANCER RATES, GROUP
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Metropolitan Los Angeles and the San Francisco
Bay area continue to be among the top 10 locations in the world
with the highest known breast cancer rates.
</P>
<P>
   Yet California health officials won't be able to effectively
reverse the increase in cases of cancer or asthma and other
diseases until they find the causes, experts agreed at an
environmental health forum here this week.
</P>
<P>
   The missing link is a national database that would allow tracing
of chronic diseases to environmental factors such as air pollution,
pesticides, plastics and household chemicals, said community
leaders and health officials who testified at the hearing at City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have a right to know what they're carrying around in
their bodies, a right to know what they're passing along in their
breast milk,'' said Andrea Martin, founder and executive director
of the Breast Cancer Fund in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Yet people have little information, she said. The Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention can monitor 200 chemicals in the
human body but this year will release a study on only 25 of them,
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists would like to see the United States follow the
practice of other countries of routinely monitoring breast milk,
which can contain DDT, PCBs, dioxin, PVC plastics, pesticides and
polyaromatic hydrocarbons.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Supervisor Michael Yaki and Rep. Nancy Pelosi
conducted the hearing as a way of drawing attention to particularly
high cancer rates here and outbreaks here and elsewhere of
childhood asthma.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the World Health Organization's International Agency
for Research on Cancer published data showing that from 1988 to
1992 non-Hispanic white women in Los Angeles County had the highest
breast cancer rate among those in monitored localities worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The bay area _ according to data on cancer rates in San
Francisco, San Mateo, Marin, Alameda and Contra Costa counties _
ranked second for non-Hispanic white women. Central California's
non-Hispanic white women ranked 13th, and black women in those
counties of the bay area ranked 20th.
</P>
<P>
   Without close surveillance, public health officials don't have
necessary data to make decisions regarding the creation of
environmental health laws, said Dr. Gina Soloman, senior scientist
at the Natural Resources Defense Council in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   She said it is difficult to link asthma to bad air days, for
instance, because it isn't a disease that doctors are required to
report.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking the disease is also spotty when it comes to such
factors as indoor pollution from mold, household chemicals, dust
mites, cockroach parts and pets. Most health databases don't
include occupational exposures, Soloman said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the government phased out the insecticide
chlorpyrifos also sold as Dursban or Raid, because officials found
it in children's blood and urine in the 1980s and 1990s. They also
linked it to asthma.
</P>
<P>
   National figures show that 17 million Americans, including 5
million children, suffer from asthma, which rose 75 percent in the
United States between 1980 and 1994. The rates for children 4 and
under rose 160 percent. Health-Track, a nonprofit monitoring group,
found that 27 states don't monitor for asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Most of San Francisco's industrial sites lie in southeast San
Francisco in Bayview-Hunters Point, home to the largest minority
population. The two Superfund sites, Hunters Point Naval Shipyard
and Bay Area Drum, are located there.
</P>
<P>
   A new study conducted by Kaiser Permanente in San Francisco
revealed that people living in that area had the highest rate of
asthma hospitalizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1700EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0708-COX     07-07 1744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Fashionable late arrival
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush is making plans to put his own stamp on the
Republican convention in Philadelphia, including an unusual midweek
arrival and a push to limit attack speeches. While the convention
is slated to begin on Monday, July 31, USA Today reports that Bush
will not arrive until Wednesday, the night he is scheduled to
become the GOP's official presidential nominee. On the first two
nights of the convention Bush is expected to make visits to nearby
states that would be beamed into the convention hall by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN FOCUS ON WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore went to Pittsburgh today to appeal to core Democrats,
and said he'll fight for ``every woman in the land'' by pushing his
agenda for health care reform. He noted that women pay more for
prescription drugs, live longer and earn less than men, and have
higher overall health costs, making them the biggest winner under
his proposal to bolster Medicare. Gore's health care proposals
benefiting women, according to his background papers, include a
$3,000 tax credit for the 9 million women caring for sick or
disabled relatives.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY HIBERNATION ALMOST OVER
</P>
<P>
   After months of political hibernation and a less than
enthusiastic embrace of Al Gore, defeated Democratic presidential
candidate Bill Bradley is about to meet publicly with his former
rival in a show of solidarity. Democratic officials said Gore and
Bradley are expected to make a joint appearance next week, possibly
in Green Bay, Wis., where Bradley is expected to demonstrate his
support for the vice president. ``We are getting close on nailing
this down, but nothing is yet set in stone,'' said Eric Hauser, a
Bradley spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   THEY ALL WANT TO PLAY CENTER FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's presidential campaign is brushing aside concerns from
the Democratic Party's liberal wing to write a platform affirming
centrist stands on trade, education reform, debt reduction and
foreign intervention. Such positions in the proposed platform being
unveiled in St. Louis today underscore the Gore campaign's
determination to regain the political middle after a primary season
in which he moved to the left to beat back a challenge from Bill
Bradley. In some ways, the maneuvering by the Gore campaign
resembles efforts by George W. Bush to wrest control of his party's
platform-writing process from the most ideological elements of the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK REFORMISTAS GO FOR HAGELIN
</P>
<P>
   Positioning itself firmly against Pat Buchanan, the New York
Independence Party, the state branch of the Reform Party endorsed a
little-known physicist for president. John Hagelin hopes to wrest
the nomination from front-runner Buchanan in the nationwide,
mail-in primary that started this week. He is a founder of the
Natural Law Party, which grew out of the teachings of
Transcendental Meditation leader Maharishi Mahesh Yogi. Since party
founder Ross Perot declined to run, Hagelin has emerged as the sole
challenger to Buchanan for the nomination and $12.6 million in
federal election funds.
</P>
<P>
   NADER CANDIDACY SWINGING VOTES
</P>
<P>
   George Bush is leading Al Gore among likely voters in Michigan
with an assist from Ralph Nader in a big state the Democrats won in
the last two presidential elections. Bush drew a 46-34 percent edge
in poll conducted by EPIC/MRA of Lansing (4 percentage point margin
of error) and published today in the Detroit Free Press. Green
Party candidate Ralph Nader was backed by 8 percent and likely
Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan by 3 percent. When Nader's name
was omitted from the choices, it was Bush 45 percent, Gore 40 and
Buchanan 4. Michigan has 18 electoral votes, eighth most in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   A PENNY SAVED IS A _
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore accused George W. Bush of neglecting poor children at
home in Texas because the state could lose $449 million in federal
funding for a children's health insurance program. Texas is among
dozens of states that have not used all of the federal funds
allotted them in 1997, when Congress authorized $48 billion in
matching funds for the Childrens' Health Insurance Program. The
Dallas Morning News reported that Texas has not spent $449 million
of the $561 million it received in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   SEEING DOUBLE
</P>
<P>
   Call them hedge-betters, fence-sitters or maybe just folks with
lots of money who can't make up their minds _ but at least 169
Americans have given large campaign donations to both of the major
presidential contenders. The double donors were identified through
a computer analysis of Federal Election Commission campaign records
conducted by Scripps Howard News Service. The study found that they
have given Al Gore a total of $163,000 while also handing $152,000
to George W. Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE PUSH FOR THE UNDECIDED
</P>
<P>
   Who's undecided about the presidential election? Whether it's
one in 20 or one in three depends on the poll and how much people
were pushed to make a decision. Some pollsters say nudging voters
toward a decision often yields more reliable results. ``There is a
high correlation between actual voting behavior and what they tell
you when you force the undecideds,'' said Frank Newport of the
Gallup Poll. ``The behavior you're trying to learn is the behavior
of a voter who is forced to pull a lever.'' Andrew Kohut of the Pew
Research Center for the People and the Press, agrees: ``If you
don't push, you find a lot of people who won't make up their minds
even close to the election.''
</P>
<P>
   CHOOSING UP SIDES WITH TEACHERS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore appealed to the nation's teachers to make his election
fight their own, saying his race with George W. Bush boils down to
a simple question: ``Whose side are you on?'' Gore was given a
rousing reception by thousands of delegates at a convention of the
National Education Association in Chicago, as he had been a day
earlier by the American Federation of Teachers in Philadelphia.
``We are the mainstream majority,'' he declared as he sought to
energize the teachers to play a big role in battleground states
that could decide the presidential election in November.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL BIRTHDAY `GIFTS'
</P>
<P>
   On the occasion of his 54th birthday, George W. Bush received
from Hispanic Democrats a gift of two prepaid phone cards and a
round-trip bus ticket to visit housing developments for the poor on
the Texas-Mexico border. Frumencio Reyes, vice chairman of the
Texas Democratic Party and a member of the Tejano Democrats of
Harris County, said his group hopes Bush will use one of the phone
cards to call on Texas' Republican Sens. Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey
Hutchison and ask them to rescind their opposition to El Paso
lawyer Enrique Moreno's appointment to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   PUSHING FOR OPEN TRADE IN PLATFORM
</P>
<P>
   Reaching an agreement on trade language won't be easy, but
Democrats working on party policy for the next four years insist
it's possible. Alan Blinder, an adviser to Al Gore and a former
Federal Reserve vice chairman, urged the drafting committee to
embrace open trade: ``America gets cheaper, better and more
preferred goods, and that raises the standard of living.'' He said
it isn't true that open trade causes unemployment. Blinder was
among about 50 witnesses who addressed the committee at the
University of Missouri-St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   A STAB AT CAMPAIGN REFORM
</P>
<P>
   A bill to limit California's virtually unrestricted campaign
contributions won approval in the Legislature. The Assembly passed
the measure 42-21 and sent it to Democratic Gov. Gray Davis. The
Senate already approved it 32-2. If Davis signs it, the proposal
will be put before California voters in November. Under the bill,
donors could give no more than $20,000 to a candidate for governor,
and lesser amounts for other statewide offices and the Legislature.
Political parties could contribute unlimited amounts. The limits
would not apply to any federal offices.
</P>
<P>
   FISHING FOR MORE THAN CLUES
</P>
<P>
   While political operatives and journalists fish for information
about the status of Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating in the Republican
vice presidential sweepstakes, Keating is actually set to go
fishing in Alaska next week. And it turns out that he was supposed
to have been accompanied by Dick Cheney, the man charged with
helping George W. Bush select a running mate. A few days ago,
according to the New York Times, Keating called Cheney and offered
to stay home, lest their trip set too many tongues to wagging. But
Cheney had already decided he was too busy to go.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS' CASH COLLECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee raised $60 million in the
first six months of the year, nearly half of it at a huge dinner
honoring President Clinton in May. The party had $30 million in the
bank as of July 1. The Democrats raised $26 million in the first
three months of the year and $34 million from April to June. On May
24, the party reaped $26.5 million at a single event: a tribute to
Clinton orchestrated by Terry McAuliffe, the Democrats' most
prolific fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   BLANKET PRIMARY AT ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Democratic Party in Washington state, Paul
Berendt, has threatened to go to court unless state election rules
are changed before the Sept. 19 primary to prevent a ``blanket
primary.'' Washington has long used such a system, under which
voters may choose any candidate for any party in the primary. The
Supreme Court recently struck down such wide-open primaries in a
ruling involving California. But Gary McIntosh, the Washington
elections director, said only the Legislature can change the
system.
</P>
<P>
   BOOMER DADS IN FULL
</P>
<P>
   You have your soccer moms and waitresses, but the latest
must-have voter is the boomer dad. The Christian Science Monitor
reports that sensitive, middle-aged guys will make the critical
difference in this year's presidential contest. So far, they are
swinging George W. Bush's way, despite being more in step with Al
Gore and the Democrats' views on ``soft'' issues like health care
and education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
