<SLUG> BC-MY-MONEY-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY MONEY, MY LIFE: LIVE FROM NEW YORK, IT'S TRADING DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By LINDA CARROLL MARTIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am tempted to blame O.J. Simpson. It was his trial, after all,
that led me to discover how addictive live television can be.
Perhaps he is also to blame for my current, more obscure obsession.
Obscure, because I am not a broker, a financial adviser or even a
day trader. Heck, I don't even own a single share of stock
outright. So why can't I stop watching CNBC?
</P>
<P>
   First, it was idle curiosity. At home with young children during
the recent years of market fury, I wondered what financial drama
could possibly warrant minute-by-minute coverage by a cable
channel. (A silly question, considering that even the weather gets
24-hour reporting.) I quickly found CNBC's morning program,
``Squawk Box,'' to be a fair place to grab the early news. Before
long, and between my children's play dates, I was peeking in on the
Dow's ups and downs. Eventually, ``Market Wrap'' became essential
at day's end. I mean, what's news without analysis?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you just miss working in an office,'' a friend responded
to my confession. That is an interesting hypothesis, because it has
occurred to me that the CNBC staff more closely resembles a typical
office staff than the usual buffed and polished news crew. The
banter seems real and unrehearsed, and I can even pick out the
familiar workplace personalities, like the professorial fellow who
makes the pithy end-of-day comments and the guy who I suspect is
constantly primping.
</P>
<P>
   I enjoy the coverage even if I can't tell you why. I enjoy the
more peripheral content, too, like the trivia questions. (Sample:
What year did Pan Am's financial troubles ground its planes?)
Mostly I entertain myself by trying to envision the type of person
who can answer such questions. (The answer, by the way: 1991.)
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the commercials. I can't find a better
self-esteem boost. This channel appears to advertise only to
successful mavericks, visionaries too bright to be stifled by
conventional news sources. No ads for macaroni and cheese here, or
for toilet bowl cleaners. But you might find a pitch for Jaguars,
or a new online trading service.
</P>
<P>
   So when I watch, I, too, feel a blue chip on my shoulder. I
might even feel a little richer, too.
</P>
<P>
   I reason that my viewing habits may well be a result of a
budding midlife crisis. Aren't 40-year-olds supposed to know what
the market did yesterday? Apparently so. One morning I saw the
former drummer for Todd Rundgren (of the famed rock 'n' roll title
``Hello, It's Me''), dressed in collar and tie, offering investment
advice. Need I say more about what's become of my generation?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, I am fast becoming a wealth of eccentric
information. Eccentric, because I have not once heard mention of
the Hang Seng index in my social circles. Fortunately, market news
does occasionally seep into my real life. I am pretty sure, for
example, that I will know of breakthrough diabetes medication even
before my diabetic sister-in-law, because of reports of drug trials
that influence pharmaceutical stocks. (Just ask me about the liver
toxicity problem.)
</P>
<P>
   I am also fascinated by the reports that may be good news for
the market but bad news for most everyone else, especially to us as
consumers. Before OPEC met last month, for example, Algeria said it
was refusing to step up oil production _ a boost for the oil sector
but a signal of continuing price increases at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I am tempted to act on some of my newfound lessons by
trying my own market trades. But I can't think of a finer example
of the old saying, ``a little knowledge is a dangerous thing.''
After all, my viewing adds up to about an hour a day; if I were an
active trader _ one who subscribes to all the insider newsletters
advertised on the channel _ I would probably want to live my entire
life within view of CNBC's stock ticker. So for now, though with an
ever watchful eye, I'll leave it to the mutual fund managers to
secure my retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But I confess to one personal wish: I want to be asked for a
stock tip. Not because I have one to offer, but because, thanks to
CNBC, I know just how to deliver it _ with just the right tone,
blending swagger and style, and speaking in the plural form like
all the pros. ``We're bullish on health sciences,'' I'd say with a
nod and a furrowed brow. ``We see them on the upswing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
