<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HOSPITAL-STRIKE-HNS &LR;      07-07 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-STRIKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STRIKING HOSPITAL WORKERS RETURN TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS and PIA SARKAR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Unionized hospital workers returned to work
Friday after a 24-hour strike to protest staffing levels.
</P>
<P>
   State health monitors said the hospitals were adequately staffed
during the daylong work stoppage by 4,000 members of the Service
Employees International Local 250. The walkout affect 10 hospitals
in the San Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   Officials confirmed that unionized workers were returning to
eight of the hospitals as the strike ended at 6 a.m., although a
union spokeswoman said a lockout or extended striking remains a
possibility at two medical centers.
</P>
<P>
   Picket lines thrown up early Thursday by technicians, licensed
vocational nurses, respiratory therapists, clerks and cooks were
honored by many nurses in the California Nurses Association, who
had just settled their own contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But the hospitals, which had 10 days to plan for the one-day
work stoppage, coped by canceling elective procedures, re-deploying
staff and, in some cases, sending patients to other hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the dispute, which has been fought bitterly through
radio and television advertising, is not about wages and benefits,
but about staffing, union representatives said.
</P>
<P>
   The union charges the hospitals have not been staffing adequate
numbers of workers, resulting in work-related injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the strike brought Local 250 and the 10 hospitals
closer to settling their differences remained an open question.
Local 250's contracts with the hospitals expired in May, and
federal mediators are running negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The strike left the union claiming victory in educating the
public about its problems with staffing levels, which they say
threaten patient care, and other issues. The hospitals continued to
maintain their public position that the staffing issue is just a
ploy to sway public support to the union side during negotiations
over pay, benefits and job security.
</P>
<P>
   The strike involved three Catholic Healthcare West hospitals in
San Francisco, five Sutter Health medical centers, including Alta
Bates and Summit in the East Bay, and Children's Hospital in
Oakland and Alameda Hospital in Alameda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been just a very, very successful day all the way
around,'' SEIU President Sal Roselli said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did our members unite and strike unanimously,''
Roselli said, but they won support from pharmacists and physical
therapists at Catholic Healthcare West's St. Mary's, St. Francis
and Seton and from registered nurses at many of the hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``So from our point of view, it's a historic day for patients
and consumers, because health care workers are uniting to force
these corporations to change the way they provide health care,''
Roselli said.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Healthcare West spokesman Robert Polzoni responded by
calling the strike by 1,600 workers at its three San Francisco
hospitals reckless and irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations will continue July 14 between the union and
hospital managers under a federal mediator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
