<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5787 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-BERGDORF-BOOKSELLER-$     07-07 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERGDORF-BOOKSELLER-$ADV09-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIBLIOPHILE'S NICHE AT BERGDORF'S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Miss.)  (For release on Sunday, July 9) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tucked all the way in the back of the top floor at
Bergdorf Goodman, behind the pillows and the coffee tables, the
Manon chocolates and the tins of caviar, is a book-filled nook
titled Jane Stubbs. And tucked behind the stacks of rare and
vintage books is a woman tucked behind an enormous shirt and thick
glasses, with the milky complexion of an attic-dwelling bookworm
who seems perennially startled at the notion of visitors. One
shopper, surveying the mounds of books jumbled on tables and
ladders and chairs, spotted her and asked, ``Do you ever look
through them?''
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs, 42, peered at her nervously. ``Oh, goodness, it's what I
do all the time,'' she answered in her soft-spoken Southern drawl.
``It's my life's mission to uncover the flotsam and jetsam of the
publishing world and force people to have libraries of same. It
tickles me so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Which would explain why this is the place to find books like
``Candy Hits'' by ZaSu Pitts, billed on its cover as ``The famous
star's own candy recipes.'' Or Edith Head's ``How to Dress for
Success,'' with the subtitle: ``In business, in love, in society,
in marriage, in school, in old age, for your husband, for your
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Book-savvy New Yorkers know Stubbs from her previous business,
Stubbs Books and Prints, which she owned with her former husband,
John Stubbs. The store, which closed in 1997 after the couple's
marriage ended, specialized in architectural books and prints,
though, as time went on, its inventory had started to include
Stubb's ``flotsam and jetsam.'' As she said, ``I'd go to book fairs
and think, If I see one more copy of `The History of American
Houses' I'll die. I looked for books that amused me and started
selling them.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's somewhat surprising to find someone like Stubbs on
the premises with Prada, but many department stores have been
searching out attractions and novelties to compete with the boom of
downtown boutiques that entice customers with everything from DJs
to computerized dogs roaming the racks.
</P>
<P>
   At Bergdorf, vintage books aren't that odd an offering; the
store already sells vintage hotel silver and tea-themed
merchandise, all of which qualify as one-of-a-kind gifts. Stubbs'
boutique has also proved popular with the store's bridal registry.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Manville, the buyer for Bergdorf's decorative home
department, says that the store's next Christmas catalog will
feature a ``well-rounded library'' assembled by Stubbs that will
include ``75 linear feet of vintage cloth and leather volumes,
first and later editions covering art, fashion, travel, gardening,
food and wine, poetry, literature and reference.'' That comes to
about 750 books. Price tag? $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Well, style-challenged men and women aren't above seeking the
counsel of a personal shopper when they need guidance getting
dressed. Why not have someone who can fashionably outfit the life
of the mind?
</P>
<P>
   ``I interview people and find out their interests,'' Stubbs
explained, settling at a table in the store's employee's cafeteria.
``I recently did a little project for Yves Saint Laurent and Pierre
Berge, for their house in Tangier. There were books on Morocco, fun
guest room things. I'm not a good houseguest myself. I hate the
idea of waking up at 3 a.m. and the panic of not finding anything
to read.'' She ran her hand through her bluntly chopped hair. ``A
lot of this business has come from my own neurosis. I traveled
around with two big bags of books for so long it was ridiculous.
I'm trying to be braver.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Stubbs' favorite projects was creating a library for Greg
Jordan, a decorator based in Manhattan. ``He wanted books on
revolution,'' she said, ``so I started with revolution in thought _
classical ideas, political thought and philosophy and ended with
modern-day armed revolutions, which included biographies and
decorative arts of an era under that umbrella. I was given a
deadline of six weeks to fill 150 feet. It was hard but a great
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs finds her merchandise at book fairs, flea markets,
sometimes even on the Internet, though there is nothing else about
her that seems remotely contemporary. She seems to have stepped out
of a story by Flannery O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Natchez, Miss., she described her mother,
with a demure smile, as ``absolutely barking, howling mad.'' She
continued: ``My earliest memories are of going to country auctions
with her. She had a little antique shop she ran from time to time,
unless she couldn't get out of her bed. We lived in a very
beautiful house and she had a remarkable eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs' father died when she was 12. ``My mother had her pilot's
license, and she flew me to summer camp in her little airplane,''
she recalled. ``I got to steer. It was so dramatic. But then she
forgot about me. I stayed with the owner of the camp for three days
after it ended. She was off somewhere _ what could you do?'' She
sighed. ``She was a combination of highs and lows. At that early
age I learned that everything had a price.''
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite escape was reading. ``It's all I've ever really
done,'' she said. ``I came to New York in 1981 with a suitcase and
13 boxes of books.'' She planned to attend film school, but instead
married John Stubbs, a distant cousin, and their business began.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Between the store's demise and her reincarnation at Bergdorf,
which started last December, Stubbs mounted exhibitions for the
Municipal Arts Society. ``I had a little sinking spell, and then I
bounced up,'' she said with a shy smile. ``It was hard to turn 40,
have my husband leave me for a younger person and have my business
close. But they all were the best possible things. I never would
have had the courage to go out on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   We returned to the book nook so she could help me assemble a
theoretical collection. Though her custom-made libraries are
ordered by the linear foot, individual books here sell mostly in
the $75-to-$300 range _ which is why I was sticking to the
theoretical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people to choose what reflects their interests,''
Stubbs said. ``It's crazy to have just what is considered to be
classic literature if it has nothing to do with people's interests.
You have to make a library a living thing. One of the goals is to
have it in place, then add to and subtract from it as the household
grows and acquires new interests. I'm as fond as the next person of
beautiful bindings, but it's boring to have pristine fancy bindings
of books that never leave the shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   I told her that I liked reading cookbooks, biographies,
especially about show business, and anything about behavior, past
and present.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant there was a pile before me:
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Do It, or the Lively Art of Entertaining'' by Elsa
Maxwell was first. I paged through and read, ``In someone else's
house, above all leave the furniture alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was ``Our Favourite Dish: The Theatre Recipe Book,''
a compilation of 250 recipes contributed by members of the
``British Theatrical Profession.'' One look at Adele Dixon's
``Stuffed Rashers of Bacon'' convinced me to put it right down.
</P>
<P>
   I loved the idea of staying in bed with ``The Heart Has Its
Reasons: The Memoirs of the Duchess of Windsor,'' and I also loved
``The Working Girl Must Eat,'' whose cover read: ``This cookbook,
with its menus, recipes and instructions for almost a hundred
easy-to-get dinners, was written especially for this girl and the
thousands like her who hold down jobs and also do some
housekeeping. Open it anywhere and see why she is still smiling
when dinner is on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs also suggested ``The Top Drawer: Random Recollections by
One Who Was Born in It.'' Published in 1928, its author remains
anonymous. Then she found ``Reno,'' a novel about divorce by
Cornelius Vanderbilt Jr., and ``The Title Market,'' a novel by
Emily Post, about the fine art of marrying a man with a title.
</P>
<P>
   She had read all these books and described each one lovingly. I
asked what she was reading now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curious Punishments of Bygone Days,'' by Alice Earle, she said
promptly. ``It's a history of public punishment in America. I'm in
the dunking chapter now. I was reading it while I had a pedicure
yesterday.'' She sighed. ``It just gives me so much pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably doesn't even occur to her to shop at places like
Barnes &AMP; Noble, much less worry about them as competition.
</P>
<P>
   She shook her head. ``With my kind of quirky things, nobody else
has exactly the same stuff.'' Her smile seemed both content and
conspiratorial. ``To be very special, or very weird,'' she said,
``can save you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
