<HEADER>
A5797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DULUTH-SISTERCITY-ART     07-07 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DULUTH-SISTERCITY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AND CULTURE GAIN FROM SISTER-CITY PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Japan, Russia, Sweden)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DULUTH, Minn. _ On the street here these days you hear French,
Swedish, Russian, Japanese and at least half a dozen other foreign
tongues. It's not tourists who give the city this cosmopolitan air,
but business executives slinging around expressions like
``informationsteknologi'' (Swedish for ``information technology'')
and ``keizai kaihatsu'' (Japanese for ``economic development'').
</P>
<P>
   Not too bad for a city that 80 years ago, under the alias
Zenith, was branded as hopelessly small-minded and provincial by
Sinclair Lewis in his novel ``Babbitt.''
</P>
<P>
   Duluth is still no New York or Los Angeles, of course. Or even a
place like Rochester, home of the Mayo Clinic. But it has focused
more on the wider world not just because of its shipping trade
through the Great Lakes but also because of its sister-city program
_ the nonprofit city-to-city network inspired by President Dwight
D. Eisenhower's suggestion in 1956 that citizen diplomacy might
lessen the chance of future world conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which really took off around the United States in
the 1970s and '80s, began largely with international cultural
exchanges, and support for health and education. Now the emphasis
is changing to a more bottom-line approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a new interest in business and economic
development,'' said Lewis F. Harwood, a spokesman for Sister Cities
International, the U.S. service association based in Washington
that administers the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see it last April at an international conference in
Merida, Mexico, where representatives from about 20 American cities
came looking for international business links and trade
opportunities with other municipalities throughout the Americas,''
Harwood said. ``We think they were quite successful at making these
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Economic development has long been pursued at the national level
by the Commerce Department, Harwood acknowledged. And states and
large municipalities, which can afford to have offices of economic
development and send trade missions around the world, have long
been doing business internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, more and more cities are reaching out
internationally through city-to-city relationships. ``It's
definitely a trend,'' Harwood said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some people think the program is a waste of time and
money. In the early 1990s, for example, an editorial writer in
Duluth wondered aloud what the city's mayor was doing in Japan on
what the writer called a sister-city ``junket'' when he ought to be
at home in Minnesota minding the store. But despite such sniping,
this city and many others are hoping to use the program more
actively to pursue development projects in a globalizing economy.
</P>
<P>
   And in the case of Duluth that switch in emphasis to
international business seems to have been, at least in part, a
recognition of problems in the local economy. Between 1980 and
1990, for example, the Duluth-Superior, Wis., region lost more than
26,000 people, increasing the incentive for local officials to take
advantage of every possible program.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1999, about 1,280 U.S. cities were involved in the
sister-city program, some more deeply than others. Seattle, for
example, has 20 sister cities around the world, from Christchurch,
New Zealand, to Haiphong, Vietnam. New York City has six, including
Madrid, Spain, and Cairo, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Duluth now has four: Thunder Bay, Canada; Ohara, Japan;
Petrozavodsk, Russia; and Vaxjo, Sweden. These partnerships have
generated over $10 million in direct revenue for the city over the
last few years, according to Duluth's mayor, Gary L. Doty.
</P>
<P>
   More important, programs that started as cultural ties have
become profit-centered enterprises. The Duluth-Vaxjo link, for
example, resulted in an ambitious project that its investors, who
anted up $24 million, hope will make Duluth a major port for
information technology as it has long been for timber, grain and
iron ore.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Doty led a delegation to Vaxjo seeking to expand
cultural exchanges based on the Swedish heritage of a large segment
of the city's population. But it was something they stumbled on in
the nearby town of Ronneby that provided the big inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, the city of Ronneby had been host to a technology
campus that brought together under one roof about 100
high-technology businesses, branches of academic institutions,
professors working as research-and-development consultants, and
students taking classes and serving internships. Such interactions
at the campus, Soft Center Ronneby, provide among other things a
sorely needed supply of well-trained information technology
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we should be doing,'' Doty exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. McNamara, who had joined the delegation as a
representative of the Duluth Chamber of Commerce, got the message,
too. ``It's a school-to-work model for the information-technology
industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, a four-story technology campus rose in downtown
Duluth, financed by city, state and private money. It is one of a
growing number of such centers throughout the world based on the
Ronneby model.
</P>
<P>
   Christened Soft Center Duluth, the enterprise held an open house
for prospective tenants last month. Visitors came from England,
Scotland, France, Norway, West Africa, South Africa, Canada and
many parts of the United States. The building is now 30 percent
occupied, by tenants including academic institutions,
high-technology concerns and a big-name investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The center is attracting the kind of tenants they want at a
somewhat slower rate than anticipated,'' said Kjell Knudsen, dean
of the School of Business and Economics at the University of
Minnesota-Duluth, who once served as an unpaid board member of the
Soft Center. ``But the prospect is that it will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those working at the video terminals in the new building
recently was Joe Allert, 19, a sophomore majoring in business at
the Soft Center branch of the University of Minnesota-Duluth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here because I like the idea of having educational
institutions in the same building as employers and even Salomon
Smith Barney and other business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Duluth's sister-city partnerships are focused on
hard-headed business plans. The relationship with Petrozavodsk is
thus far purely philanthropic, recently involving an effort to
raise funds for clothing and supplies for children in orphanages.
And the link with Thunder Bay, only a few hours away by car, is
largely cultural.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But another tie that may result in a business deal is Duluth's
relationship with Ohara, which set the stage for all four of
Duluth's sister-city partnerships. This tie began during the U.S.
occupation of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   One night, a gang of sailors from the heavy cruiser Duluth
returned from shore leave with a 750-pound, medieval temple gong in
tow. The bronze gong, covered with ancient inscriptions and
fanciful dragons, is recognized in Japan as a national treasure.
</P>
<P>
   The captain considered the gong a legitimate war trophy and
arranged to have it delivered to the ship's namesake: the city of
Duluth. For the next decade, the gong was on display first in City
Hall and then suspended in a shuro, or gazebolike structure, in
Duluth's Enger Park.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, a visiting Japanese college professor happened to see
the gong. He explained to Duluth's mayor how important it was to
Japan, and asked to have it returned.
</P>
<P>
   A lengthy correspondence followed, and eventually the gong was
sent back to Ohara _ a small fishing village 90 miles southeast of
Tokyo from which it had been taken. In gratitude, the Japanese
delivered a full-scale replica of the gong for display in Enger
Park.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Duluth and Ohara became sister cities. And last month a
group of 15 visiting Japanese dignitaries and several dozen
Duluthians held a ceremony in Enger Park to rededicate the replica
as a symbol of peace and mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
   A soprano sang the Japanese national anthem and then the
American. Next, Doty and Soichiro Oya, a petroleum entrepreneur who
led the Japanese sister-city delegation, jointly clanged the gong
with a huge striker in the name of everlasting peace.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, the conversation turned to golf.
</P>
<P>
   While golf is an expensive sport in Japan, where the links are
crowded and reservations hard to come by, Duluth, by contrast, is a
golfer's paradise, ranked by Golf Digest as the best of the United
States' 309 small cities for access to good, affordable links.
</P>
<P>
   So why not market golfing vacations in Duluth for Japanese
tourists?
</P>
<P>
   Carl Seehus, Duluth's director of parks and recreation and a
former director of the city's sister-city program, was talking up
the idea. And Oya, an avid golfer, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last decade was for cultural exchanges,'' Oya added. ``The
next decade will be for business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
