A5828 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     07-07 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
DOES OUR ENERGY POLICY HAVE SPINE OR SPIN? (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Those who cannot remember the past are condemned to repeat
it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ George Santayana
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it seems we can't learn for forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   The energy crunch of the 1970s confronted American political
statesmanship with its severest test since World War II. Yet, for
all the lessons it taught, some of us might as well have amnesia.
</P>
<P>
   How may of us remember 1973? '79?
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices tripled while motorists queued up for blocks to
get a tank full. New England couldn't get sufficient home heating
oil; big northern cities suffered natural gas shortages, utility
rates in rural Texas went through the roof. Driven by soaring
energy prices, the inflation reached double digits.
</P>
<P>
   The OPEC cartel was showing it could jerk our economy up and
down like a yo-yo.
</P>
<P>
   Well, we muddled through and launched bold comprehensive plans
to avert any future repetition of that experience. They were good
plans, long-term bipartisan plans. Members of both parties
participated, working with Presidents Ford and Carter. It was a
matter of national security.
</P>
<P>
   Never more would America be hostage to foreign oil producers, we
swore. We'd become energy independent, whatever the cost!
</P>
<P>
   Then, the crisis past, we began thinking that some of the plans
were a trifle uncomfortable. New political leaders and consumer
trendsetters began plucking the leaves, one by one, from the flower
of energy independence.
</P>
<P>
   Energy was old hat, and, after all, who cared?
</P>
<P>
   Tax incentives for energy-efficient homes, cars and factories
fell to a new idol of tax ``reform'' in 1986. The 55 mph speed
limit saved energy and lives but became politically inconvenient
and was abolished. Inducements for domestic oil exploration;
investment in alternate energy sources; plans for quality mass
transit: all fell like so much grass before a mower.
</P>
<P>
   With steady resolve, we could have been energy-independent by
now. Instead, we're more dependent on oil imports than we were in
the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   We're driving SUVs, and hinting at placating motorists by
suspending the taxes that build our highways. We're counting on
diplomats to talk Arab producers into selling us more crude.
</P>
<P>
   So here sits America, like a pitiful alcoholic at the bar,
pleading with OPEC for just a little more of the joy juice. A hair
of the dog!
</P>
<P>
   Oil is addictive, surely enough. And the politics of oil seem
inherently divisive. They split consuming states from producing
states.
</P>
<P>
   But we're a nation, after all, and a transcendent national
interest is at stake. The three Es _ energy, economy and
environment _ are inseparably interlinked. And price is a function
of supply.
</P>
<P>
   The only way we can control our own destiny in the long run is
to adopt a long-range plan and stick with it until we do achieve,
or at least approximate, domestic energy-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Pandering to voters in an election year by offering to suspend
the gasoline tax _ which builds American highways and public
transportation systems _ would be, it seems to me, the very worst
form of a copout.
</P>
<P>
   The pay-as-we-go Highway Trust Fund is one of America's great
success stories. It has built the world's greatest highway system
without adding a penny to the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Our interstate highways, which it finances, have generated
private job-creating investments along their routes of easily $50
for every tax dollar that went into their construction.
</P>
<P>
   If we were foolish enough to wipe those taxes out, we'd shave
mere pennies off the price of gas at the pump _ and have to come up
with some new tax to pay for our roads. It's a non-policy.
</P>
<P>
   A balanced energy policy must include incentives to maximize
domestic exploration and ultimate recovery, and promote fuel
conservation, public ground transportation and alternate
environment-friendly fuels. And we'd have to stick with it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately I see no comprehensive plan emerging from
Congress. I hear none advocated. The prevailing mood in the GOP
House is to avoid doing anything bold. It is better, present
congressional leaders think, just to appear to do something while
actually doing very little.
</P>
<P>
   Recent House votes have been shams, masquerading as real
campaign finance reform, actual Medicare coverage of prescription
drugs and effective authority to sell medicines to sick people in
Cuba. The bills are illusory as mirages. None of the three does
what it pretends to do.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the public sees through the pretense.
</P>
<P>
   Congress needs leadership with spine, not spin.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
