<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCKING ABOUT BY THE JUSTICE DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July   09)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the high drama of the impeachment saga we have lurched down
into low comedy. How low can we go? Try this:
</P>
<P>
   The media flack for Kenneth W. Starr, President Clinton's
persecutor, is now going to trial on criminal charges that he
leaked sensitive info from the Starr chamber inquisition to The New
York Times. The Justice Department is accusing Charles Bakaly III
of telling the Times that Starr had concluded in January of last
year that he had constitutional authority to indict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal. A press secretary leaking something to The New York
Times. Happens hundreds of times a day. Before it becomes ``all the
news that's fit to print'' it is probably going to be leaked, if
it's juicy enough. Been going on that way since the printing press
was invented.
</P>
<P>
   What's different now is the way judges twist and turn and
wriggle their way into the great mass of things that should be left
untouched. Stewing in their own juice is quite often the proper
remedy for things political. But Judge Norma Holloway Johnson of
the federal district court in D.C. is one of the many federal
judges who seem bent on making a career out of the Bill-and-Monica
romp. She ordered Bakaly to trial over his bit part in the farce.
</P>
<P>
   So the flack gets hung out to dry, joining such characters as
Linda Tripp and Julie Hiatt Steele as footnotes in this endless
circus. Federal judges have wide powers, and apparently wider egos;
their penchant for keeping this scandal-pot boiling at monstrous
cost to the taxpayers is incredible. The news biz plays its part
dutifully. ``Editors at The Times have said they do not and will
not discuss the sources for the article,'' the Times intoned
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This comes at a time when we need to see and hear less about
judges, it seems to me. The loftiest judge of New Hampshire has
just been recommended for impeachment by that state Legislature's
Judiciary Committee. Chief Justice David Brock stands accused of
trying to fix cases by intervening with other judges. Justice David
Thayer resigned rather than face charges he tried to fix his own
divorce trial. A third justice claimed his fellow judges routinely
took part in discussions of cases from which they were
disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not just the buttinsky judges of the Clinton Scandal
Machine era who are playing favorites and putting their money on
partisan political horses. With 1 million lawyers practicing in
America, it seems judges are trying to find work for all of them.
Why do they call it ``practice'' anyway? Isn't practice supposed to
make perfect? Do they ever get it right?
</P>
<P>
   The proper place for a lot of this stuff to be evaluated and
either acted upon or ignored is in the political process. Let the
voters pass on Clinton and his associates, his fund-raising, Al
Gore's culpability, Hillary's carpetbagging nerve, etc. Junking up
the legal process with these two-bit cases that waste court time
and cost taxpayers money is a fruitless exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The voters are not short of opinions. A recent column in which I
praised Clinton's job performance sparked a flurry of responses.
Some sample excerpts: ``I would vote for Bill Clinton in a minute.
He is one of the smartest presidents we have ever had. One stupid
mistake. So if we checked around the others I am sure we would find
mistakes in their lives. I am 80 years of age plus. . . . I am from
Texas but Al is my man. Dorothy Warren.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Texan read the column in the Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
``lovingly known as the StartleGram which is why your column is
printed, I am sure. . . . We do not need King Billy or his Queen
any longer. We can really thank the conservative leadership in this
country for `his' accomplishments by keeping `him' in check and
pointing out the truths about him. Carey Rector.''
</P>
<P>
   That dim view was echoed by Amos Cliff of Texas. ``Good God,
man. What is in the air in Boston? . . . I can understand how
living in a state that elected and reelects a clown like Ted
Kennedy must warp your perception of reality. . . . (I)n spite of
your prediction about his approval ratings, the majority of the
American people and history will remember Bill as just another dark
period we came through together.''
</P>
<P>
   James Harper of Everman, Texas, read it in the Stephenville
(Texas) Empire Tribune. His comments: ``Dear David:,
HHHhhhhhiiiiiiiiiiiya! (Pause. Budweiser sip ) HHHHhhhhhhiiiiiiiya!
Many Texans are not charmed by the Clintons, as birds out of the
Oleander bush and Johnson (LBJ) Grass. Not one dog on my street
could be talked off of the meat wagon by Bill Clinton or Slick
Hillie (as we call Hillary R.) . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Equally unconvinced was Dennis Roberson of e-mail land, who is
recovering from gastric disturbance: ``I just read your column. . .
. (I)t made me vomit. I want a president who will not look me in
the eye every day and willfullly lie to me over and over (and do
the same thing to his wife, daughter, cabinet, vice president,
etc.). (Clinton) is a self-serving, lying snake. Sure, you and your
kind will be wanting Slick Willie back in the year 2001. Because
you're weak.''
</P>
<P>
   To Dick Gibbs Ellis, Maximum Bill is ``The Great Prevaricator.''
Ellis believes in Ronald Reagan and Louis Rukeyser and The Wall
Street Journal editorials. Clinton was smart? ``So was Hitler.''
</P>
<P>
   To Jim Lockwood of Hot Springs, Ark., Clinton is ``the most
skilled manipulator of our time, also the luckiest. . . . We would
be where we are today with him or without him. . . . I can never
respect him for what I perceive to be expediency . . .
insincerity.''
</P>
<P>
   The mail on that column was about evenly divided, but I give the
critics more space today because I had my shot last time. The point
is that the voting booth is the place to decide these issues. Not
the courtroom, nor the judge's chambers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
