A5855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-LINCOLN-HOUSE08-COX     07-07 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-HOUSE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON DECLARES LINCOLN'S RETREAT A NATIONAL MONUMENT
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To escape the brutal heat of the 19th century White
House, President Abraham Lincoln would venture a few miles north,
to a 14-room Gothic-revival cottage surrounded by trees.
</P>
<P>
   The residence, where Lincoln wrote the final draft of the
Emancipation Proclamation, in more recent years has led a less
prominent existence as office space in a beautifully landscaped
housing complex for military retirees.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declared Lincoln's summer home a national
monument Friday, ensuring that the residence will no longer be home
to conference tables, fax machines and copiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is fragile, vital history in this house,'' Clinton said.
``Today we come to reclaim it, to preserve it, and to make it live
again.''
</P>
<P>
   At a morning ceremony, the president also announced $15 million
in grants by Save America's Treasures _ including a $750,000 award
for the cottage _ to preserve historic sites nationwide. The
cottage site was renamed the President Lincoln and Soldiers' Home
National Monument.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the residence ``has almost been forgotten for more
than a century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, more than 1 million people visited Ford's Theater
alone. But barely 100 made it here to Anderson Cottage, where
Lincoln lived and worked; where his son played and his wife found
solace.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's ceremony culminated a five-year quest for David Long,
professor of history at East Carolina University in Greenville,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   On a private tour of the residence in 1995, Long said he
experienced an epiphany as he stood in the room where Lincoln
drafted the Emancipation Proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said: 'We're sitting in a place as important to American
liberty and independence as Independence Hall, Philadelphia, and
nobody knows about it. Something has to be done to preserve the
historic importance of this building.''
</P>
<P>
   As fate would have it, a member of the tour group was a close
friend of Richard Moe, president of the National Trust for Historic
Preservation, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   Moe immediately became interested in the project and called
Long, who flew to Washington to make a presentation that started
the process.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's ceremony, Long marveled that the cottage ``sat here
unknown'' for 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even most Lincoln historians didn't know of the existence of
this place. It's absolutely amazing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Long said that Lincoln spent one-fourth of his presidency at the
summer house and that the family loved staying there, especially
Lincoln's wife, Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the one place that she found happiness during that
presidency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cottage also provided the president and his family relief
from the environment around the White House, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington was an awful place in the 1860s,'' he said. ``They
had an open sewer that ran next to the White House. You have to
remember this thing was built on swampland. In the summer it would
get hot and muggy and almost unbearable.''
</P>
<P>
   Long said that ``if everything comes to fruition,'' the grounds
will eventually be home to a center for the study of the Lincoln
presidency, with the cottage as a centerpiece. He hopes the final
project will include a shrine that celebrates Lincoln and the
central act of his presidency _ the Emancipation Proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the national monument designation under the 1906
Antiquities Act, designed to protect sites and objects of antiquity
on federal land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservation applies not only to places of great natural
splendor, but to places of great national import. This cottage in
its way is just as precious as a giant sequoia, as irreplaceable as
the ruins of cultures long past,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government purchased the land in 1851 to establish a
home for invalid and disabled soldiers of the U.S. Army, the first
such attempt to provide for members of the regular army.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Soldiers Home, it was also used as a summer retreat
by Presidents Buchanan, Hayes and Arthur. It is known as Anderson
Cottage in honor of Major Robert Anderson, the commanding officer
at Fort Sumter at the outbreak of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   The grants announced by the White House are being awarded by
Save America's Treasures, a partnership of the White House
Millennium Council, the National Park Service and the National
Trust or Historic Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso's e-mail address is eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
