<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-PRI-0709-1stLD     07-07 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PRI-0709-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO'S RULING PARTY DOESN'T KNOW WHERE TO GO IN DEFEAT
 &HT;    RESENDING TO FIX TRANSMISSION GARBLES
 &HT;    With MEXICO-REVOLUTION
 &HT;    For Sunday, July 9
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ When it suffered public repudiation in 1968 for
gunning down students demanding freedom of speech, Mexico's ruling
party recovered.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, when its top officials engaged in fratricidal
assassinations to settle scores and mismanaged the economy so badly
that the peso's value was slashed in half, the party regrouped.
</P>
<P>
   But after last Sunday, Mexico's legendary Institutional
Revolutionary Party, the PRI, is facing its ultimate test. Can it
survive the shock of finally losing Mexico's presidency _ its seat
of power _ for the first time in 71 years?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said Rafael Oseguera, the PRI's vice coordinator in the
federal Chamber of Deputies. An optimist, Oseguera didn't let
defeat stop him from jetting off to Madrid, Spain, for a
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't reject any reforms as we consider our future,'' he
said before he leaving. ``The colors of the party, the name, the
symbol, everything. We have to have a revolution inside the PRI so
it can enter a new stage.''
</P>
<P>
   After suffering a crushing defeat Sunday to presidential
opposition challenger Vicente Fox Quesada, the long knives came out
at PRI headquarters, a stark gray cement complex in Mexico City
that matches supporters' funereal mood right now.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has lost governors races before, but seven decades of
control over the powerful federal government are not relinquished
easily or without rancor.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's presidential candidate, Francisco Labastida, wept
after losing last Sunday's election. Insiders say PRI member were
utterly stunned. They fully expected its vaunted electoral machine
to muster enough voters who'd always marched to the polls like
sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, voters handed the PRI a crisis, and an already fragile
conglomeration of divergent political tendencies and interests have
exploded into warfare. The president and secretary general tried to
resign ``in the name of dignity,'' but were persuaded to stay until
the party holds a convention to chart its future.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI was born from the Mexican Revolution, and ever since
1929 it has remained in power by employing a flexible ideology
borrowed from socialism, capitalism, nationalism _ and most will
admit now, intimidation, favoritism and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   As it slides into second place _ second in Congress and the
Senate _ the party doesn't seem to have a clear message or reason
for being. The one thing it could surely offer _ access to
executive power _ is gone.
</P>
<P>
   If it can summon its warring factions, it may remake itself as a
center-left party with a huge task: convincing Mexicans it's become
a modern political party that will represent people's interests
instead of lining its pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the party's old guard, known as the ``dinosaurs,''
are furious at Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo for supporting
free-market economic reforms that extended the gap between rich and
poor and making the PRI look unrevolutionary. They are also upset
at Zedillo for appearing to cozy up to the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo is a Yale-educated economist who was pushed into running
for president in 1994 when candidate Luis Donaldo Colosiouchable
authority _ with caring more about his personal image as a reformer
than the party's future.
</P>
<P>
   For many, a symbolic insult was seeing Zedillo congratulate Fox
before returns were officially in on election night and watching
the two embrace the next day in the presidential residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI should distance itself from the current president of
the Republic because for six years he dedicated himself to changing
party leaders at will and dismantling the strength of our political
organization,'' said a stricken Manuel Fuentes, who resigned a
month ago from a top party post.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anti-PRI attitude of Zedillo has been manifested,''
Fuentes said. ``He played Gorbachev and ended up affecting our
party.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``technocrats,'' Zedillo's wing of the PRI _ some of whom
were in charge of Labastida's campaign _ say they prefer to
modernize the party and prepare it for competition, while
continuing to guide Mexico into global capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to reach out to the new thinking of society _ and
young people with new values,'' said Javier Trevino, a
Harvard-educated international affairs advisor to Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   And outside the PRI, there are those who believe the party has
become, mostly, a collection of crooks.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who reveled in such attacks during the campaign, was
magnanimous in victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the great opportunity the PRI has to make itself a
real political party,'' Fox said. ``Certainly defeat is painful.
But defeat can also be a departure point for reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Political scientist Edna Jaime, who studies the PRI, said a
bloodbath after defeat ``is totally natural. The first phase of the
PRI's restructuring is going to be one of lynchings and looking for
scapegoats. But if there is something we know about the PRI, it's
that it is pragmatic.''
</P>
<P>
   But already, signs are strong that the PRI governors of the
southern states, where the party still reigns and has a strong
machine, are rising to the top of the boiling cauldron.
</P>
<P>
   Tabasco governor Roberto Madrazo, who ran in second place
against Labastida in a gimmicky primary election last fall, appears
eager to capture the leadership that's up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately released a letter to the party urging it to
pursue ``the recuperation of our social essence'' as an alternative
to Fox's National Action Party, the PAN. Even among many voters who
choose Fox this time, the PAN is perceived as too conservative,
Catholic and indifferent to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But someone like Madrazo, who is so lean and hungry, knows he
can't win the presidency just on a populist platform,'' said
political analyst Federico Estevez. ``He's also got to re-invent
imself and appeal to a modern Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The technocrats, Estevez said, are the ones who could get their
marching orders right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always Cuba,'' he joked. ``They need people like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the southern governors are lining up with Madrazo, along
with the large PRI-affiliated teachers union.
</P>
<P>
   Other PRI labor unions, part of the party's old political
infrastructure, seem paralyzed, unsure of what to do next. The oil
workers' union issued a statement to Fox, reiterating its
opposition to all attempts to privatize Mexico's oil _ a move Fox
has already said he won't make.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows if this will happen, but the party would do well to
dissolve PRI associations such as the ``Peasant Torch,'' an
organization that mobilizes lower-income supporters to intimidate
the opposition in provinces, Estevez said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a band of ``Peasant Torch'' members in Mexico state
rose up in a violent but isolated protest against what they
charged, ironically, was electoral fraud against the PRI in local
mayors' elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're shock troops, `` Estevez said, ``so maybe now, like
good old soldiers, they'll just fade away.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Ferriss can be e-mailed at: susanf(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
