<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Unusually hot weather will linger over most of the Plains and
Mississippi Valley, where high temperatures of more than 95 degrees
will be common. The central and southern Rockies will not be as hot
as in recent days because the arrival of moist air will promote
increased afternoon clouds and scattered thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of thunderstorms will gradually dissipate early
Saturday over the northern and central Great Lakes states. But a
new area of thunderstorms will erupt over northern Minnesota late
Saturday and will drift east into Wisconsin and Michigan Saturday
night. Locally heavy rain will heighten the risk of flooding,
especially where recurrent thunderstorms pass over ground saturated
by recent rain.
</P>
<P>
   After a chilly dawn in the Northeast and Middle Atlantic states,
ample sunshine in most areas will increase temperatures to
comfortable levels Saturday afternoon. A few light showers will
linger in the cool air mass over northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: PALL OF SMOKE
</P>
<P>
   Near Fairbanks, Alaska, where the peaks of the Alaska Range more
than 100 miles away are usually visible, smoke from forest fires
has blocked the view since June 23. Gently sinking air associated
with high pressure has limited the vertical dispersion of the
smoke, resulting in the persistent pall. Fires are common over
interior Alaska in summer when lightning from scattered
thunderstorms ignites dry vegetation.
</P>
</TEXT>
