<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5887 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MEMORIAL-HNS &LR;      07-07 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JAPANESE AMERCAN BECOMES A FOCAL POINT OF CONTROVERSY OVER NEW
MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANNIE NAKAO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Mike Masaoka wrote in 1940 that he was
proud to be ``an American citizen of Japanese ancestry'' and loved
his country, he was a brash young idealist expressing a lifelong
devotion that some say made him an important civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   But 60 years later, the late Masaoka has become the focus of a
seething controversy over a national monument that will carry his
name and the words he wrote long ago _ words that critics say mask
the painful legacy of his disputed wartime leadership in the days
following Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Masaoka is among seven individuals including the newly nominated
commerce secretary, former Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif., whose
quotations will grace the $11 million National Japanese American
Memorial to Patriotism, which will be dedicated in Washington,
D.C., on Nov. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The privately funded memorial honors the valor of 33,000
Japanese Americans who fought in World War II, including 800 who
died. It also tells the story of 120,000 people of Japanese
ancestry, forced from their West Coast homes and imprisoned in
desolate inland camps during the war.
</P>
<P>
   For months now, critics of Masaoka's role during the war have
been fighting to get his name removed from the memorial. With the
memorial's dedication just four months away, the controversy seems
far from dissipating, as letters, pro and con, fill the pages of
the Japanese American Citizens League's weekly newspaper, the
Pacific Citizen, and other Japanese American publications.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Committee for a Fair and Accurate Japanese
American Memorial submitted a petition with 707 signatures to
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, asking for a review of the
memorial's ``problematic and controversial inscriptions.''
</P>
<P>
   While the National Park Service could not be reached for
comment, sources on the memorial board say they have been told
Masaoka's name will remain on the monument.
</P>
<P>
   The matter is also expected to be debated once again at the
National Japanese American Memorial Foundation board's quarterly
meeting in San Francisco on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, Masaoka and other leaders of the JACL advocated
complete cooperation with the government, squelching protest by
labeling as troublemakers and dissidents those who questioned the
abrogation of their civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   In his zeal, Masaoka even suggested a ``suicide battalion'' of
Japanese Americans who would prove their loyalty as soldiers while
having their families held hostage by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   The JACL, according to its wartime records, also provided
information on community members to the FBI and other federal
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of Masaoka's name with an excerpt of his creed on
the memorial is abhorrent to those who say it puts in the limelight
someone who evokes decades-old pain and anger.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Masaoka and his words, later adopted as the JACL
Creed, do not reflect the wartime resistance and protest of other
Japanese Americans, which many feel have long been muzzled in the
name of patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's going on is a reflection of the divisions that
occurred among Japanese Americans during the war partly between
those who wanted to cooperate and those who wanted to resist,''
said Dale Minami, a San Francisco civil rights attorney. ``Most
people felt compelled to cooperate. In hindsight, it's hard to
fault that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``But looking back with today's standards, we've come to respect
those who did protest, those who did resist. The memorial omits
that diversity of responses from Japanese Americans, and to that
extent, it does not reflect a true history.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Clifford Uyeda, 83, of San Francisco was more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it seem like what Japanese Americans want is a pat on
the back from white people, saying, `You're nice little Japs,'''
said Uyeda. ``That's the wrong message to give to the public. Mike
Masaoka made a big mistake. Why should that be remembered as an
expression of Japanese Americans forever, inscribed in stone?''
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Hosokawa, 85, an author, historian and former Denver
Post editor, said the charge that Masaoka ``colluded with the
government is a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Hosokawa added, ``I know the vigor and intensity with which we
opposed the evacuation. The military came and said, `Get out or
else.' So I think the opposition to Mike is unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one deserves to be on that wall more than Mike Masaoka,''
said Grant Ujifusa, 57, a book editor from Chappaqua, N.Y. ``What's
going on here is there are still those resentments from that period
of pain, and we can't deal with it. Mike cut such a powerful
charismatic figure. So let's not think of the Chandlers or the
McClatchys or the Hearsts, who sold a ton of papers s - - - - - - -
on Japanese Americans. Let's blame one of our own. Let's think of
Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   But to Rita Takahashi, a San Francisco State University
professor of social work, Masaoka's inclusion on the monument is
``a total contradiction of what the memorial is about.``
</P>
<P>
   Takahashi is one of eight dissidents on the 42-member memorial
board, who have questioned how the names and inscriptions were
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Other individuals, besides Mineta, who will be on the
monumentare former Presidents Harry Truman and Ronald Reagan; Sen.
Dan Inouye and the late Sen. Spark Matsunaga, both of Hawaii; Rep.
Robert Matsui, D-Calif., and poet Akemi Matsumoto Ehrlich.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Rear Adm. Melvin Chiogioji said the memorial board he
chairs has voted on the matter five times: ``The last vote was 27
to 6. Not even close. But these people just won't let loose, no
matter what. Anyway, it's a fait accompli. It's being carved right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, the JACL apologized to the resisters for failing
to recognize their loyalty but also strongly supported including
Masaoka's inscription.
</P>
<P>
   His backers look at his postwar leadership and achievements in
Washington, where he was respected by influential congressional
leaders who liked his upfront style.
</P>
<P>
   Masaoka successfully fought for the Walter-McCarran Act in 1952,
which allowed issei or immigrant Japanese to finally become
naturalized citizens. And though he initially opposed redress for
camp survivors, Masaoka later worked to win $1.2 billion in
reparations.
</P>
<P>
   He also lobbied hard for the 1964 Civil Rights Act and helped
found the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
