u f BC-SYCAMORE-SALE-BOS &LR;      07-07 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYCAMORE-SALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYCAMORE NETWORKS IN MAJOR DEAL WITH CANADIAN COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: 360networks is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sycamore Networks Inc. has made its biggest sale to date of
optical networking gear, a deal valued at up to $420 million that
includes the first reported sale of the Chelmsford, Mass. company's
premier optical switch.
</P>
<P>
   360networks of Vancouver, B.C., a ``carrier's carrier'' that
handles wholesale traffic for telephone and data communication
companies, said it will use Sycamore's gear to build out what is
planned to be by the end of next year a 100-city, 56,000-mile
global network. The system will handle up to 10 gigabits per
second.
</P>
<P>
   For Sycamore _ tabbed by Wall Street as the star of a pack of
Massachusetts optical communications start-ups _ the deal provides
revenue to help justify its $31 billion market valuation.
</P>
<P>
   News of the 360 pact, announced Friday, sent Sycamore's stock
soaring $16.75 to $126.9375 in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   The $420 million figure, representing planned purchases over
several years, was described as a likely ultimate contract value.
But it's not guaranteed. It includes the first reported sales of
Sycamore's SN 16000 switching device.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sycamore went public in October, its shares have soared by
a factor of 10, on Wall Street's faith that it will compete with
Nortel Networks, Lucent Technologies, and other giants to become a
leader in fiber-optic communications.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction was described by both companies as one of the
world's largest deployments of a so-called optical mesh network,
providing a credibility boost for a radically new way of designing
international calling networks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most phone and data traffic moves over interlocking
fiber-optic rings of sometimes different capacities. That requires
telecommunications companies to spend weeks or months working out
how to establish a specific capacity link between different cities
over a series of rings.
</P>
<P>
   Among other features, Sycamore's switches use advanced software
to map out their own connections over fiber-optic lines, creating a
mesh of overlapping voice and data routes.
</P>
<P>
   That capability should make it possible for 360networks to
connect customers in days rather than in months, and almost
instantaneously reroute traffic if lines are damaged, said
Harminder Gill, the company's director of engineering and planning.
</P>
<P>
   Within several months, 360 customers may be able to order their
own increased bandwidth if, for example, they suddenly need to
handle more traffic between two cities.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore faces strong competition from dozens of other
start-ups. But ``There are very few vendors out there who have real
products,'' Gill said.
</P>
<P>
   Other major contracts, previously announced by Sycamore, include
a $400 million, four-year sale to Williams Communications and a
three-year, $200 million deal with Enron Broadband Services, a unit
of the Houston energy giant. There have also been major deals in
England and Scandinavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5909 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HOLLYWOOD-BOWL-LADN &LR;      07-07 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-BOWL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEREVER SHE GOES, MCDONALD LIGHTS THINGS UP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's hard to pin down diva Audra McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to the three-time Tony winner on July 4 by phone from
Washington, D.C., she was about to rush off to rehearse for that
night's big concert at the Capitol Building which was being
broadcast live on PBS. Coincidently, at that very moment you could
hear her singing tunes on a local National Public Radio station as
part of a tribute taped last month for Stephen Sondheim.
</P>
<P>
   After the concert she would be heading back to Toronto to
continue filming an adaptation of Jim Lehrer's ``The Last Debate''
with James Garner for Showtime. Then she would be off to Los
Angeles where she headlines tonight's Hollywood Bowl concert.
</P>
<P>
   All this flying around is in keeping with singer-actress who has
taken Broadway by storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned about planes early,'' quips McDonald, explaining
that growing up in Fresno, where she started doing dinner theater
at the age of nine, was not a drawback in her ambition to make it
on the Great White Way. ``I grew up in a musical family,'' she says
of her parents who are educators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd be nearby if I got to a school in New York,''
McDonald says. Of course, never doing anything halfway, she went to
Julliard. Not long afterward she made her mark in the 1994 Nicholas
Hytner revival of Rodgers and Hammerstein's ``Carousel,'' for which
she won her first Tony. She subsequently won Tonys for Terrence
McNally's ``Master Class'' in 1996 and for Ragtime in 1998, the
musical adaptation of the E.L. Doctorow novel.
</P>
<P>
   All this before she turned 30, which which happened on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the soft-spoken McDonald you would never know that
she has one of the most extraordinary singing voices to come around
in years _ ``a force of nature,'' esteemed critic John Lahr calls
her.
</P>
<P>
   And that praise seems restrained compared to some. Here's
Stephen Holden in the New York Times: ``When Audra McDonald ...
unfurls her operatic mezzo soprano with its bright, quickening
vibrato, then breaks into a triumphal cry before dipping into an
ominous funk-tinged blues shout, a better musical future seems not
only possible but upon us, right here, right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew _ a heavy burden, but it also describes McDonald's penchant
for taking chances. Earlier this year she was nominated for a Tony
for her lead role in ``Marie Christine'' by composer Michael John
LaChiusa, an edgy musical retelling of the myth of Medea. But the
show, described as difficult work about race, betrayal and the role
of women, closed early despite McDonald's drawing power, and there
was no fourth Tony.
</P>
<P>
   Though she has ``no plans at the moment'' to returned to
Broadway, McDonald has other worlds to conquer.
</P>
<P>
   In February, she released her second solo album, ``How Glory
Goes,'' to critical acclaim. While the album has its share of
familiar songs _ ``Anywhere I Hang My Hat Is Home'' and
``Somewhere'' from ``West Side Story'' _ McDonald doesn't just
stick to easy standards, highlighting lesser known numbers like
``Come Down From the Tree'' from ``Once on This Island.'' She also
opens herself up to comparisons with two singing greats in ``A
Sleepin' Bee,'' which Barbra Streisand recorded, and one of Judy
Garland's signature tunes, ``The Man That Got Away.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald talks about about admiring Garland for living life to
the fullest, but you hear a difference in the way the song is
interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get into the character,'' McDonald says about how she
approaches a song. In Garland's version of ``The Man That Got
Away'' the pain is evident, but McDonald's is more wistful,
contemplative. Something like McDonald, who seems to put as much
thought as she does passion into what she performs.
</P>
<P>
   As for tonight's show, which is only McDonald's second
appearance in southern California ever, she will be teamed up with
another Broadway superstar, Patti LuPone, along with John Mauceri,
who will be conducting his 200th concert at the Hollywood Bowl, for
a night that promises plenty of musical fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, McDonald has turned her attention to acting. In the
spring, she guest-starred NBC's ``Law and Order: Special Victims
Unit,'' and co-starred in the ABC/Disney production of ``Annie.''
After ``The Last Debate,'' she'll co-star with Emma Thompson in the
filmed adaption of Margaret Edson's acclaimed play ``Wit,'' being
directed by Mike Nichols for Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she was attracted to the two cable-TV movies, McDonald
says they offered roles that weren't stereotypical for an
African-American woman. But by now you realize there is nothing
stereotypical about McDonald or her career.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Well, there's a wedding. McDonald has been engaged
to bassist Peter Donovan for about a year. And she's going back to
the studio to record another album with _ get this _ a big band.
``It should be fun,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. It's hard to pin down Audra McDonald.!end! &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
What: Audra McDonald and Patti LuPone with John Mauceri and the
Hollywood Bowl Orchestra. &QL; 
Where: The Hollywood Bowl, 2701 N. Highland Ave, Hollywood. &QL; 
When: 8:30 tonight. &QL; 
Tickets: $5 to $70. Call 323-850-2050. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
