<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVOIDING SPOTLIGHT, DAVENPORT EASES INTO FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ She's still being treated like the answer to a trivia
question, but she does not decry this affront to her regal status.
Lindsay Davenport rather prefers traveling beneath the radar,
actually.
</P>
<P>
   It's the inconspicuous course she followed to the Wimbledon
women's singles title last year, and here she comes again, having
slipped through the side door to Centre Court of the All England
Lawn Tennis &AMP; Croquet Club to face Venus Williams in Saturday's
final.
</P>
<P>
   While everyone else was distracted by various commotions,
particularly Thursday's seismic sibling semifinal between Venus and
Serena Williams, Davenport was busy tiptoeing to the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, that's the way I like it,'' she said after
carving up unseeded 17-year-old Jelena Dokic, 6-4, 6-2, in the
semifinal nobody noticed. ``I don't really like to have a lot of
hoopla and a lot action and activity around what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   At 24, the 6-foot-2-inch Californian stands out as a weirdo on
the women's tour because she evidently is so normal. She has no
intrusive, abusive parents pulling the strings, she never raises a
ruckus like the divas around her, and, unlike the Williamses,
there's only one of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that the only reason why I'm here is just to
play tennis, get through it, see personally what I can achieve, and
leave all the business to the other players and let them deal with
it,'' said Davenport. ``That's always been my take on it. I think
that's what has helped me play better. I don't have to really deal
with a lot of the outside things and just really concentrate on my
tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been more than enough to occupy her time. Davenport,
who also owns the 1998 US and 2000 Australian Open crowns, missed
two months on the WTA Tour with back problems. She has been
struggling to regain her form here.
</P>
<P>
   The opening round of her title defense was truncated by a fall
that forced her doubles partner, Corina Morariu, to retire from the
match. In her first full go, Davenport dropped the opening set to
Yayuk Basuki. And Monica Seles took her to the limit in the
quarterfinals before Dokic fell in 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   So much the better, the champion reckons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny to look at the difference between this year and
last year,'' said Davenport, ``because last year came so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   And quietly. Her semifinal and final victories in 1999 were
overshadowed by Alexandra Stevenson's roots and Steffi Graf's
retirement, respectively. This time around, the suspense has
involved her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seemed like I was playing so well (last year) in the
matches,'' said Davenport. ``Just everything clicked from the first
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Wimbledon, I've had to fight a lot harder, come back in a
few situations and matches, really hang in there. In some ways,
this is much more satisfying because I got through the first week
not playing well, really fought it out, got to the position where
in the second week, I started to play a little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   She's been able to work things out in the background. Meanwhile,
Venus Williams has had no place to hide. Because of her captivating
game and personality and the novelty of the sibling clash _ the
first time in the 32 years of open tennis sisters met in a Grand
Slam semifinal _ the No. 5 seed has encountered nothing except
glamour and glare.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether she can remain at a psychological peak
following the challenge presented by top seed Martina Hingis in a
three-set quarterfinal and the trauma of having to rough up Serena,
6-2, 7-6, in the semis. And just in case she doesn't have enough on
her mind, Venus will be trying to become the first African-American
women's champion here since Althea Gibson in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   She thinks she's up to the demands. Asked if she would find it
difficult to prepare for Davenport after what she's been through,
Williams said, ``No, I don't think so, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena dolefully touted her sister's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she plays the way she did against me,'' said Serena, ``then
she should have a pretty good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve more than that, Venus, who has missed much of the
season with tendinitis in both wrists, knows she can't let up.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's had injuries just like I have,'' said Williams, ``so
we're kind of in the same boat. Definitely we are going to want to
raise the level of our games. I feel like I've raised the level of
my game already, especially (against Serena) and in the last match
(against Hingis) also. When the final comes, it's a grand occasion.
I think we're both going to go at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is an inch taller than Williams but can't match her
power. She must find ways to get around that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played her a lot of times in the past,'' Davenport said.
``A lot of times, I found the key was to find a way to get her
serve back, get them back deep so she obviously doesn't have
put-away shots. On grass, that's going to be a little more
difficult than on other surfaces. I'll have to concentrate on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience favors Davenport, who is three years Williams's
senior. Williams has been in one Grand Slam final, losing to Hingis
at the 1997 US Open. Davenport has been in three and won them all.
They've hardly jaded her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm psyched to get into another Grand Slam final,'' she said,
``especially the second year here in a row. That means a lot to me
to be able to come back and do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone may have been looking the other way while she was doing
it, but once again, ultimately they can't avoid Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
