u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-BOS     07-07 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFTER SENDS DISGRUNTLED AGASSI PACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It was riveting theater, a two-man show featuring
dueling virtuosos. It bedazzled the critics. It enraptured the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   There were metronomic rallies filled with one acrobatic return
after another. There were improbable volleys highlighted by sublime
athletic grace and cast-iron wills. There were sideline-to-sideline
and baseline-to-net (or vice versa) dashes, gravity-defying dives,
lethal leaping smashes. And most of all, there was endless
suspense.
</P>
<P>
   Unsurpassed artistry and entertainment. What superlatives could
possibly describe it all?
</P>
<P>
   Well . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned,'' said Andre Agassi, ``the match
sucked.''
</P>
<P>
   There's always one grouch in the bunch, isn't there?
</P>
<P>
   But Agassi could be forgiven his ornery assessment. This
five-act thriller had an unhappy ending for the world's top-ranked
male tennis player, who acknowledged, ``I have no objectivity''
regrading the match's quality after he was outperformed by No. 21
Patrick Rafter, 7-5, 4-6, 7-5, 4-6, 6-3, in the Wimbledon
semifinals Friday.
</P>
<P>
   That means there will be no encore of last year's championship
showcase, when Agassi lost to Pete Sampras. Only Sampras will get
to repeat his role, because he completed his cakewalk to history's
doorstep with a 7-6 (7-4), 6-2, 6-4 disposal of Vladimir Voltchkov.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Sampras should have an asterisk beside his name in the
billing for Sunday's final at the All England Lawn Tennis &AMP; Croquet
Club, because he didn't face a single seeded player. But all that
matters is that if he beats Rafter, Sampras will share the record
for the most Wimbledon men's singles crowns (7) and own it outright
for the most Grand Slam notches in his belt (13).
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was shoved into the background on Centre Court because
of the Agassi-Rafter spectacular that preceded him there. And even
the perennial champion expected a different outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (Agassi) was the slight favorite,'' said Sampras.
``But it wasn't a guaranteed win.''
</P>
<P>
   It was close to it, according to the consensus. Agassi was
seeded ahead of everyone except Sampras, and no one has a more
multifaceted repertoire than the Las Vegas casino greeter's son.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter's prospects were more unpredictable than realistic. The
two-time US Open winner was rated No. 1 in the world for a brief
spell last year, but in his return to New York, he suffered a
first-round injury to his serving shoulder that forced him to
abdicate and eventually required surgery. His right rotator cuff
was repaired Oct. 24, he was on the mend for an extended period,
his ranking plunged, and while he came here seeded 12th, that was
considered a gift. Even though he had won a tuneup event on grass
in the Netherlands the week before Wimbledon, he was hardly
regarded a threat, even by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's had its ups and downs,'' Rafter said of his
postoperative experience. ``But it's always hard to say how well
you're going to play here. I really hadn't had a lot of runs on the
board coming into Wimbledon. Obviously, the week before was very
successful. (But I) still hadn't proved myself in a big-match
situation yet. I guess today it shows that I'm probably coming
back.''
</P>
<P>
   To Agassi's everlasting dismay. The Australian showed him right
away that he could handle anything Agassi threw at him. He
neutralized Agassi's vaunted returns with aggressive rushes to the
net and matched him slashing volley for slashing volley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he played pretty much like I expected him to,'' said
Agassi. ``He served real well. There are times when you're
surprised by things and other times that somebody really executes a
little bit better at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter picked the perfect time to play the executioner at the
start, holding serve through 6-5 and then breaking for the first
set when Agassi double-faulted and hit a two-hand backhand long.
</P>
<P>
   That showed Agassi that Rafter would not go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like he's found his game,'' said Agassi. ``I thought
he was playing well. At the crucial times of the match, he was the
same player (as before the surgery). He was playing tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Both were as the intrigue built to a climax.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi counterpunched in the second set, allowing Rafter to
break him to 2-0, then answering with one of his own in the next
game and the decisive one to 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   And on the give-and-take went, Rafter eking out the third set,
Agassi answering in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I was feeling pretty good that I was in the fifth
set there after losing the third,'' said Agassi. ``But it's hard to
feel like you have the momentum in the fifth until you get that
break of serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he got broken, reflecting Rafter's serving advantage
(74-40 percent) in the stretch. The turning point came when Agassi
ended yet another extended rally with a forehand into the net,
putting Rafter up a break, 4-2. Rafter clenched his fist as he
sensed the kill, then served out the match and punched the air with
both fists as the crowd roared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end of the fourth, I just started finding the rhythm on my
serve,'' said Rafter. ``When I'm serving well and playing well,
that's the way I serve.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next match, Voltchkov, the bargain-basement Belarussian
who got here without an invitation or endorsements, served notice
that he may be a force in the future.
</P>
<P>
   He was a surprisingly worthy adversary for Sampras, holding
serve through the first set until the tiebreaker, in which Sampras
won three of the last four points to prevail, 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras dominated the second set, then had his hands full in the
third until taking a five-deuce game and breaking to 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to fight, but he was just too good,'' said Voltchkov.
``I mean, I didn't have one chance on his serve, except in the
tiebreaker in the first set, where things could go either way.''
</P>
<P>
   They're still going the Californian's way as he has survived a
lingering injury _ tendinitis in his lower left leg that developed
before the second round _ that was tougher than his draw. He
received treatment for it yet again in the third set from ATP Tour
trainer Doug Spreen.
</P>
<P>
   But it was nothing that another victory wouldn't cure. ``I feel
great,'' said Sampras. ``It wasn't an easy match, playing Vladimir.
I was really a heavy favorite. Not having really seen him play much
or not having played him, it wasn't an easy match. But I got
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was more than Agassi could say, no matter how memorable
his effort. Told what a hit the match had been, he said dryly,
``Good. I'm glad you enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   His tone indicated that he obviously hated it.
</P>
</TEXT>
