<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN-HOUSE _ President Clinton will announce plans for
restoring Abraham Lincoln's summer retreat home, three miles from
the Capitol. The14-room Gothic-Revival cottage is where Lincoln
drafted the Emancipation Proclamation. David Long, history
professor at Eastern Carolina University in Greenville,N.C., will
be at Clinton's side. Long has led a battle to preserve the
historic residence. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-UTEXAS _ Free airfare and a good time apparently worked
in favor of the University of Texas Law School. The number of
African-American students who plan to attend UT in the fall is
double the number from last year and officials believe it's because
of an outreach effort this spring that brought accepted students to
campus for a look-see. They want to expand to Hispanic students
next spring. (Jayson, Austin American-Statesman). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-FORUM _ ATLANTA _ Expectations were high in parts of
Georgia's Latino community six months ago. Four people appointed by
Gov. Roy Barnes were recommending changes to state laws and
policies to help Georgia's growing Latino population. They held a
press conference to give their report to the governor, but his
staff said Barnes was too busy to attend. His absence frustrated
some Latinos. Now some Latinos are more frustrated because not much
has become of recommendations made by the Latino Forum that Barnes
appointed. It's a different story in North Carolina, another state
with a fast-growing Hispanic population where thousands of Latinos
work in construction, poultry, agriculture and hotels and
restaurants as they do in Georgia. Latino leaders in North Carolina
meet regularly with high-ranking state official and the governor.
In fact the Office of Hispanic/Latino Affairs, is part of the
governor's office. (Bixler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
