<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ A friend sent me a list called ``Tips for a
Lifetime.'' Most of these tips, although useful, would be more
appropriate for someone who ran a Martha Stewart-styled household.
That's not me. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ (Latham, Marshall News Messenger)
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ Our cousin, Don Harp, is a preacher. He knows
exactly what to say when a family member crosses the Jordan. One of
the things he pointed out at Aunt Ida Mae's funeral was that we are
running out of what Tom Brokaw and a lot of us think of as The
Greatest Generation. ``Who among us is going to take their place?''
Don asked. It is a worrisome question. (Minter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Mary Ann Wietze, the beloved principal at Helke
Elementary School, died June 23, at 67, from cancer, at her home in
West Milton. But her presence will continue to be felt at the
Vandalia-Butler school that she ran with high spirits and high
expectations. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ FREDERICKSBURG, Va. _ The Civil War
battlefields here _ chief among them, Chancellorsville _ are
considered the bloodiest ground in all of North America. As costly
as it was in lives, today the land is even costlier, property
values being what they are. (JoeMurray, Cox News Service).
</P>
