<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5954 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      07-07 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUSTICE: SALE OF SAN FRANCISCO DAILY ENDED ANTITRUST PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Justice Department, which has approved the
Hearst Corp.'s purchase of the San Francisco Chronicle, told a
federal judge Friday that it closed an investigation of the sale
after Hearst struck a deal to sell its flagship San Francisco
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   In a carefully worded letter to U.S. District Judge Vaughn
Walker, the department said its decision not to challenge Hearst's
$660 million purchase of the Chronicle was contingent on the
privately-held company's agreement to sell the Examiner to a ExIn
LLC, a company headed by Ted Fang, publisher of the San Francisco
Independent. Fang is to pay $100 for the newspaper and get a
subsidy of up to $66 million from Hearst over three years.
</P>
<P>
   But the department said it never had to reach a conclusion on
Walker's question: whether the Chronicle sale would have violated
federal antitrust laws if Hearst had not also agreed to sell the
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department did not approve the sale of the Chronicle to
Hearst, but rather made a decision not to proceed with further
investigation or a challenge in court, in light of the sale of the
Examiner to ExIn,'' wrote Mark J. Botti, the lawyer in charge of
the investigation for the department's Antitrust Division.
</P>
<P>
   Walker had been awaiting the department's reply before ruling on
an antitrust lawsuit by Clint Reilly, an unsuccessful bidder for
the Examiner. Reilly contends the deal with Fang is a sham,
designed to prop up the Examiner for a few years and then leave
Hearst with a local monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Shulman, a lawyer for Reilly, said he was unimpressed by
the department's latest filing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not coming out of their bunker,'' he said. ``He (the
judge) should feel free to decide the thing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Corp. spokesman Paul Luthringer said: ``We believe this
supports the position that Hearst has been taking all along, as
well as the position that we have taken in court throughout this
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst attorney Gerald A. Connell could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department approved the sale on March 30, saying its
concerns about competition were satisfied by the prospect of the
Examiner's continued publication by Fang.
</P>
<P>
   Walker blocked the sale with a restraining order a few hours
later. Since the trial of Reilly's lawsuit ended May 31, the judge
has been pressing Justice for its opinion on whether Hearst's
purchase of the Chronicle, by itself, would have violated antitrust
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has not said why he wants the information, but during the
trial he indicated he was troubled about the Fang transaction,
asking lawyers for Hearst why they agreed to subsidize a competitor
and whether they were merely trying to mollify federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter June 29, Botti told Walker the Justice Department
was initially concerned about a monopoly and doubted Hearst's
claims that the Examiner was a failing newspaper that could not be
sold above liquidation value. But once the Fang deal was announced
in mid-March, the department shifted its focus, considered both
transactions together and decided that competition would not be
damaged, the government lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Unsatisfied, Walker issued a new order the next day, asking
whether the department's approval was contingent on the Fang sale,
or whether the Chronicle purchase would otherwise have violated
antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's letter, Botti said the department's decision not to
challenge the sale was contingent on the Fang transaction _ but he
stopped short of saying what the department would have done if the
transaction had not taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department's decision to close the investigation was based
only on the determination that the sale of the Chronicle to Hearst,
in light of the sale of the Examiner to ExIn, did not result in a
substantial lessening of competition,'' Botti said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle and Examiner have operated under a joint operating
agreement since 1965, combining business operations and splitting
profits while maintaining separate editorial staffs. The agreement
was to run through 2005 but would be terminated by the sale.
</P>
</TEXT>
