<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILM-VILLAINS-NYTR &LR;      07-07 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-VILLAINS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRING ON THE VILLAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Bill Kelley is a correspondent for the NYT Regional Newspapers
Group.) 
 By BILL KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I saw ``Shaft'' last weekend _ twice.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the movie, mind you, which is only slightly above
average, but for two of the performances in it.
</P>
<P>
   Movie villains are such a devalued commodity these days that
when a film contains two great ones, I can't get to it fast enough.
And ``Shaft'' sports a display of duelling bad guys so
extravagantly enjoyable that the film doesn't just deserve to be
seen, it demands it.
</P>
<P>
   They are Walter Wade Jr. (a suavely handsome Christian Bale,
last seen as the title character in ``American Psycho''), a
millionaire yuppie racist who perpetrates the vicious hate crime
that begins the film; and Peoples Hernandez, a flamboyant Dominican
drug dealer played by Jeffrey Wright (star of the 1996 portrait of
a doomed painter, ``Basquiat'').
</P>
<P>
   Their collaboration is the kind of forced contrivance that only
makes sense in a movie while you are watching it. Wade and
Hernandez _ two monsters from different worlds _ meet in jail.
Their unholy alliance isn't specifically designed to confront
detective John Shaft (Samuel L. Jackson), but that's what happens.
</P>
<P>
   Until the movie bogs down in its second hour with a numbing
collision of subplots, the narrative balance is almost sublime:
Wade and Hernandez alternate one-upping each other, and taking on
Shaft.
</P>
<P>
   This type of sleekly contemporary villain, full of psychological
quirks that beg inquiry, isn't new. He first surfaced in two
bristling Robert Mitchum performances _ the maniacal backwoods
preacher, Harry Powell, in ``Night of the Hunter'' (1954), and the
vengeful ex-con, Max Cady, in ``Cape Fear'' (1962). The mark of a
good actor is the ability to play a memorable villain. But for
Mitchum, the mark of a great actor is the ability to do it twice,
and a different way each time.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-hero trend of the '60s and '70s, epitomized by the
films of Clint Eastwood and Charles Bronson, blunted the persona of
the villain, who had to be a drooling caricature to seem worse than
the tarnished protagonist. Believably scary bad guys were hard to
find.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, there were exceptions. The best of them was arguably
Bruce Dern's character, ``Long Hair,'' in the 1972 John Wayne
feature, ``The Cowboys.'' Dern, an Actors Studio graduate who
reluctantly specialized in loathesome villains for a time in the
first half of his long career, got to do the unthinkable in ``The
Cowboys'': He murdered Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview some years later, Dern said there is more to
playing a wholly contemptible villain than merely acting sinister.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to playing a psychotic villain,'' Dern said, ``is
that: One the guy doesn't know he's crazy, which they don't; and,
two you have to give the character a little style, a little flair,
so that the audience despises the guy so much that they begin to
enjoy that sensation ... and want him around for the rest of the
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Dern expressed some of that sentiment to Wayne, as the screen
legend gently chided him during the filming of the controversial
death scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne said, `Boy, when you kill me, the audience is going to
hate you,''' Dern recalled. ``And I told him, `In Orange County,
maybe, but in Berkeley, they're going to stand up and cheer.'''
</P>
<P>
   Taking on John Wayne, a larger-than-life Hollywood icon, is one
thing. Even if you kill him, you don't really win. But the villains
of today must contend with the subtler _ but ultimately just as
palpable _ pressures inherent in doing battle with the millennium's
male superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, if you're a strong, commanding presence, the hunks
of today don't want you as a villain. Ever since Alan Rickman's
breakthrough performance as a wily terrorist in ``Die Hard'' (1988)
_ a modern matrix of evil; only in it for the money _ today's
pretty-boy leading men have been wary of character actors who might
steal the picture away from them.
</P>
<P>
   Think I'm exaggerating? Then name the actor who plays the
villain in ``Mission: Impossible 2.'' (It's Dougray Scott.) You
think Tom Cruise, who co-produced the movie, wants a fight for
dominance with another Alan Rickman? That's what makes the
double-barreled villainy of ``Shaft'' so refreshing. Jackson is too
powerful an actor to be upstaged by anyone, and he knows it; he
lets Bale and Wright play out the full dimensions of their
characters, unencumbered, and the film is enriched by it.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's true that actors as brilliant as Bale and Wright
deserve to be in a better movie than ``Shaft.'' But in a summer
popcorn season, a period not known for creative surprises, this one
is something to savor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
