<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5978 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-CHINATOWN-WANG-N     07-07 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-CHINATOWN-WANG-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD TIMES ARE HURTING CHINATOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, July 8, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By JOHN WANG    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Boom times are the worst thing to have ever hit New
York's Chinatown. Twenty-five years ago, New York needed Chinatown.
The city was on the brink of bankruptcy, and many neighborhoods
were declining. Chinatown was a rare area of growing prosperity in
the tight times, emerging from an area occupying few city blocks to
transform a dilapidated Lower East Side into a thriving community.
</P>
<P>
   And now that things are good, New York doesn't seem to care
about its old friend. As it turns its attention to Silicon Alley
entrepreneurs and Wall Street barons. Meanwhile, Chinatown has
stagnated in the past several years _ hurt by rising rents,
aggressive enforcement of old city laws and a digital divide.
</P>
<P>
   Chinatown's economy, now as in the past, depends largely on a
core of small businesses in mature and declining industries:
small-scale manufacturing, much of it in the garment industry;
restaurants that specialize in Chinese cuisine; retail and
wholesale trade; tourism and gift shops. We in Chinatown need the
city's help in both preserving our traditional businesses and and
generating more modern ones.
</P>
<P>
   The garment industry, which once employed 30,000 people in
Chinatown, has been hardest hit. Foreign competition, low-cost
production overseas and occasional charges of sweatshop operations
have driven manufacturers away from Chinatown: its garment
factories have decreased from 500 to less than 300. This decline
has had a multiplier effect as lost income in the community has
sent sales plunging in other businesses. Now, as garment factories
struggle to pay $10 to $12 a square foot for loft space in
Chinatown, dot-com companies, which are edging in from the outside,
would gladly pay double or triple that. Some provision should be
made to keep at least some buildings operating with affordable
rents.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer has appointed a task force of prominent
business leaders, known as the Group of 35, to find more commercial
space in the city for growing companies. Perhaps a representative
of small business or manufacturing industry should be appointed to
this task force, too, to reflect more diverse business needs.
</P>
<P>
   Lower Manhattan's residential boom has also hurt Chinatown. In
the 1980s and 1990s, the upscale development that started in SoHo
began to to hem Chinatown in, causing economic and cultural
clashes. The sidewalk fish and vegetable stalls that most New
Yorkers once saw as quaint are viewed by some of our new neighbors
as dirty and smelly inconveniences. The wholesale trades of poultry
and groceries, with their early morning deliveries and congestion
on the sidewalks, are seen as a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals have been made to the local community boards to restrict
certain business operations; the Police Department and Department
of Consumer Affairs have dusted off all the rule books, ticketing
sidewalk vendors for all types of violations that had not been
enforced in decades and, in some cases, are still not enforced
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, the city unearthed a quarter-century-old Little
Italy special zoning district, limiting types of businesses and
setting requirements for stores, and attempted to force merchants
to comply with its rules and regulations _ in an area where
properties have been more than 90 percent Chinese-owned and
Chinese-occupied for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Chinatown's own entrepreneurs must recognize the need
to modernize. Within New York's Asian-American community, a yawning
digital divide has appeared. National studies show that
Asian-Americans as a group have the highest computer ownership and
Internet connection rates for any ethnic group in the United
States, but a recent survey by the Asian American Business
Development Center found a different picture in Chinatown. Although
85 percent of the small businesses that responded use computers,
most of those are outdated and cannot be connected to the Internet.
Most Chinatown entrepreneurs don't yet fully appreciate the need to
develop educational and economic resources to turn around the
declining businesses.
</P>
<P>
   What's most important for the preservation of Chinatown,
however, is a recognition by the city itself that this neighborhood
is an endangered asset. The City Planning Commission should study
how best to preserve Chinatown, whose special character has always
been a point of municipal pride. Our city's leaders should
recognize, too, that by helping to sustain New York in difficult
years, Chinatown helped lay the foundation for today's boom.
</P>
<P>
   (John Wang is president of the Asian-American Business
Development Center in Manhattan.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
