<HEADER>
A5979 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-COHEN-SULLIVAN-PROFIL     07-07 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COHEN-SULLIVAN-PROFILE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHIEF OF SULLIVAN &AMP; CROMWELL IS MAN OF ECLECTIC INTERESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 9.)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bridge games. Elvis Presley. Iranian hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Those are some of the topics on the mind of H. Rodgin Cohen, a
leading banking lawyer who on July 1 became chairman of Sullivan &AMP;
Cromwell, the New York law firm. For more than 30 years, Cohen, 56,
has been a sought-after counselor to chief executives of the
industry's largest institutions, including the Bank of New York,
First Union and Societe Generale, advising on 10 of the 15 largest
bank mergers in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Along with his reputation as an expert in banking arcana (he
once wrote an article titled ``Interstate Banking: Myth and
Reality''), he is a man of eclectic personal tastes. How many other
lawyers can boast of spending weeknights as a high school student
at the home of his chemistry teacher perfecting his bridge game?
And few, to be sure, can rattle off the answer to almost any
question about 1950s rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   Such interests give him an added dimension. But it is his skill
as an attentive counselor who not only understands the law, but
also how it is best applied in both business and politics, that
holds sway with clients.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the 1993 acquisition of Dreyfus Corp., a mutual fund
company, by Mellon Financial Corp. Martin G. McGuinn, chief
executive of Mellon, said executives were worried that regulators
would not allow the bank to buy a fund company.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen came up with a structural solution that allowed the deal
to be reviewed by the Comptroller of the Currency, instead of the
Federal Reserve Board, which was expected to be less flexible,
McGuinn said. It was approved.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Terracciano, who retired as president of First Union in
1997 and spent more than three decades at banks like Chase
Manhattan and Mellon, described Cohen this way: ``I used to call
him my legal St. Christopher medal,'' referring to the patron saint
of travelers. Cohen is best in a crisis, able to synthesize
information quickly and come up with a reasoned response,
Terracciano said.
</P>
<P>
   Once, he said, he reached Cohen in a Manhattan cab by cell phone
and asked a complex question. By the time Cohen reached his
destination, he had consulted with an associate and then given
Terracciano the answer.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1980, Cohen handled one of his most complex matters as
part of a team representing several banks in the exchange of
billions of dollars' worth of frozen Iranian assets for American
hostages held in Iran. The lawyers met in midtown Manhattan for
weeks to overcome the practical and legal obstacles of such an
exchange. ``It made you feel like you had a purpose in life,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Sullivan's new chairman, he faces a new set of
challenges. He must stem the flow of young lawyers seduced by
dot-com riches. Cohen has weekly lunches with small groups of
associates. The firm has also hired a consultant who interviews law
school students about why they are, or why they are not, interested
in joining the firm. ``You don't panic over someone going out to
make $10 million by age 30,'' he said. ``You can't compete with
that. What you are trying to deal with is people on the margin.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, which has 525 lawyers, is also responding to the
trends of globalization and technology. Like many other New
York-centered law firms, it is opening a Silicon Valley branch. The
firm has also recently expanded its offices in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   With clients like Disney, Goldman Sachs and Microsoft, Sullivan
&AMP; Cromwell remains one of the most profitable firms in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has spent nearly his whole career at Sullivan. He was born
in Charleston, W.Va., in 1944, the elder of two brothers and the
son of a pharmacist who owned a small chain of drugstores. He did
not stay long. His parents sent him to Deerfield Academy in
Massachusetts for preparatory school, which is where he learned to
play bridge. In the early 1960s, he headed to Harvard University,
where he studied history and, in 1968, graduated from the law
school.
</P>
<P>
   He had not planned on becoming a lawyer, he said, but law school
was to continue his liberal arts education. In fact, he had
considered becoming a disc jockey or a veterinarian, but neither
career seemed promising. He once flirted with the idea of writing,
pitching a story idea to an editor friend at The New Yorker in the
early 1970s. Her response was polite but blunt, he said: ``Stick to
law.''
</P>
<P>
   That he did. He worked two years as an Army staff lawyer at Fort
Monmouth, N.J., trying to disqualify military contractors that
failed to deliver on orders. Then, in 1970, he joined Sullivan &AMP;
Cromwell.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked to join the firm's banking practice, which then
lacked glamour. Cohen changed all that. He has long represented the
New York Clearing House Association of major New York banks, making
him a weekly visitor to legislators and regulators in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he has been a top adviser in the industry's
consolidation wave, including the mergers of Chemical and Chase
Manhattan, Wells Fargo and Norwest, and First Union and Corestates.
Cohen's prowess is not unrivaled. He is often across the table from
Edward Herlihy of Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &AMP; Katz, who is also a
well-regarded banking lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen still expects to spend most of his time with his clients,
devoting about 25 percent of his long day to managing the firm.
That leaves him only limited time with his family. He has been
married since 1969. His wife, Barbara, is a former newspaper
reporter. They have a teen-age daughter and a young son.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen joked that his constituents closest to home were often the
hardest to please. Neither of his children, he said, really
understood all the fuss over 1950s music. ``They don't think it's
that sophisticated,'' he said. Folk singers get a lot more air time
in his house these days, except when the kids are gone. ``Then I
get on the treadmill and turn up the jukebox,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
