<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CARS-BEETLE-ONLINE-NY     07-07 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-BEETLE-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLICK, CLICK AND YOU GET THE KEYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELINE MAYNARD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ The woman in the green Plymouth minivan
honked repeatedly and gestured. Immobilized in rush hour at the
clogged spot where three suburban Detroit freeways converge, I knew
I had not cut her off, nor had our bumpers kissed. Puzzled, I
rolled down my window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that Vapor?'' she asked excitedly, pointing to my shiny
blue Volkswagen, just three days old. I nodded. She responded with
a thumbs-up.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of a dozen such encounters in the month since I
took delivery of my New Beetle, one of 4,000 special editions
available only through VW's Web site. During May and June, VW
offered 2,000 Beetles in Vapor, a pale blue meant to evoke the
original baby-blue Beetle, and 2,000 in Reflex Yellow, a color akin
to that of New York taxis. They were the first new colors since the
Beetle went on sale in the summer of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In buying my Bug, I joined a growing number of consumers who are
making car deals online, in whole or in part. CNW Marketing
Research, a market-research firm in Bandon, Ore., estimates that
nearly 10 percent of new car buyers within the last year _ some 1.6
million people _ ordered or paid for vehicles over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is Rhyder McClure, a computer consultant in New York
City, who recently bought an ML430 sport utility through the
Mercedes-Benz Web site (www.mbusa.com). He likes the convenience of
shopping on the Web, and often orders groceries, gifts and clothing
online. ``Since the day I could buy things on the Internet, I
have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McClure accomplished all but the final step on line. Placing a
deposit on his $45,000 vehicle required a visit to Mercedes-Benz of
Manhattan on West 41st Street, where, in five minutes, a salesman
completed the necessary electronic forms.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, I did not visit a dealership until I went in to
claim my keys. My purchase followed a confluence of events. First,
my next-door neighbors, Trish and Eric Promersberger, asked if I
would consider selling my 1994 Honda Accord.
</P>
<P>
   Almost simultaneously, my young nephews weighed in. Benjamin
Maynard, 8, has been a fan of the New Beetle since it first came
out, giving me gifts of Beetle-shaped cookies and a poster. This
spring, his 4-year-old brother, Parker, asked, ``Auntie Micki, when
will you have your Beetle car again?'' He was referring to test
cars I had driven.
</P>
<P>
   But the deciding factor was a VW press release promoting the
company's online sales. VW thought the program would be successful
because 60 percent of Beetle owners are frequent computer users,
said Elisabeth Vanzura, marketing director for VW of America. ``We
intend to be a leader in this area,'' Vanzura said.
</P>
<P>
   The potential ease appealed to me, and I did not feel a need to
visit a showroom because I was familiar with the car. Logging onto
VW's Web site (www.vw.com) on May 4, the first day the cars were
available, I selected Vapor Blue, picked the engine, chose leather
seats and a trim package that included a sunroof.
</P>
<P>
   My first choice _ with the latest engine, a turbocharged
1.8-liter 4-cylinder _ was not available. So instead, I selected a
car with a 2-liter conventional gas engine and completed the
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   My order was immediately sent to Howard Cooper Volkswagen here.
The entire process took 17 minutes. I immediately received an
e-mail message that said: ``Congratulations. You are well on your
way to owning a Limited Edition New Beetle.'' The note told me I
now had my own home page on www.myvw.com, complete with an e-mail
account that would allow me to discuss terms with my dealer. It
promised I would hear from someone within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Five hours later, Cooper Volkswagen's Internet sales manager,
David McCoy, rang my cellular phone. He was ready to take a deposit
of $500 and offered to let me use a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   But I decided that I really wanted the turbo. McCoy said he
could not guarantee he could get me that car because only VW, not
dealers, controlled the inventory. But later that afternoon, he
fired off an e-mail telling me that a Vapor Blue 1.8T had been
found and would be shipped to Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks of e-mail exchanges followed. I did not meet McCoy or
set foot in the dealership until May 22, when I went to pick up my
car. But through our electronic communications, I knew the car's
identification number; the seaport (Wilmington, Del.) where it had
arrived from VW's factory in Puebla, Mexico; the date it was due in
Ann Arbor; the price ($21,900 before taxes and other fees); and
various financing options.
</P>
<P>
   Because my car was a limited-edition model, there was no
negotiating. I paid the list price, in cash received from the
Promersbergers for my old car along with proceeds from a badly
performing mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   While McClure said he also could have paid cash, he decided to
finance his purchase, and sought alternatives via the Internet. He
spent four minutes completing a form at www.lendingtree.com, which
matches lenders with buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, he had four responses. ``I had never heard of these
people, and they had never heard of me,'' he said. ``But within two
hours, they were willing to loan me $35,000.'' He dismissed two
loan offers, at interest rates of 9.25 and 8 percent, as too high.
Two other banks offered loans at 7.25 and 7.7 percent. The bank
with the higher rate agreed to match the lower one. Within a few
days, he received a check, made out to him and the Mercedes
dealership, which he took to the showroom to redeem and pick up his
vehicle. McClure also shopped on the Internet for insurance.
</P>
<P>
   McClure dealt with the same salesman throughout his transaction.
At Howard Cooper, I was handed off by McCoy, the Internet
specialist, to a salesman, Ed Goldman. Completing the deal took
about two hours. In that time, Goldman verified my insurance,
accepted my personal check, explained the warranty and the owner's
manual in detail, and then gave me a tutorial on the Beetle's
features.
</P>
<P>
   My car was literally under wraps in a garage behind the
showroom, hidden away so that window shoppers wouldn't get the
impression that they could buy a similar car from inventory.
</P>
<P>
   The special handling did not end there. Members of the sales
staff, as well as the general manager, came out to look at the
Vapor Blue car and to congratulate me. I felt vaguely like a bride
when, in a final touch, Goldman handed me a bouquet of daisies, cut
to fit the dashboard bud vase, which is tinted the same color as
the car.
</P>
<P>
   The Vapor Blue Beetles were virtually sold out by June, but
sales of the Reflex Yellow models lagged; some of these have been
sent to dealers. Tony Fouladpour, VW's press relations manager,
said yellow cars tend to appeal to people with outgoing
personalities, perhaps at odds with those who spend hours surfing
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Volkswagen will use the Web again to sell special
models, Fouladpour replied, ``Absolutely.'' A future customer could
be McClure. ``I'm going to do it forever this way,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
