<HEADLINE>
JACK STEIN, 81; MAKEUP ARTIST TO THE STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Stein, a makeup man who made the stars shine and presidents
presentable for the TV cameras, died Thursday at MetroWest Medical
Center in Framingham, Mass. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Stein also helped the plain look pretty. As he wrote in his
``Let's Make-Up'' column in the Jewish Advocate for 15 years,
``There is no such thing as an unattractive woman, just women who
don't know how to fix themselves up.''
</P>
<P>
   He was born Jacob Stein in Boston. As a young boy he acted in
the Yiddish Theater, but soon decided acting wasn't for him. He
said he changed his career plans when he discovered he was better
at applying makeup than delivering lines.
</P>
<P>
   The young Jacob started by mixed makeup in the bathtub in his
parent's home. By 1945, he had established the Jack Stein Makeup
Center, which still operates on Congress Street in Boston. He sold
makeup under his own label.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Stein's theatrical clients included Barbra Streisand,
Lucille Ball, and Tony Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   When TV became important to the political process, he began
doing makeup for political figures, presidents Eisenhower, Truman
and Kennedy among them.
</P>
<P>
   In a story published in the Globe on Nov. 4, 1966, he discussed
his political clients. John F. Kennedy, he said, ``fidgeted and
couldn't wait to get out of the chair.'' Harry S Truman told him in
salty language what he could do with his makeup. Eisenhower was
among the most patient and polite of all his clients, and British
statesman Anthony Eden once mused, ``I wonder what Winston
(Churchill) would have to say about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Stein volunteered his time to assist disfigured patients at
the Burns Institute of Boston's Shriners Hospital for Children, and
other hospitals. For 25 years, he taught at Emerson College, which
awarded him an honorary degree.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Sophie (Shapiro); two daughters, Judy Klamka
of Purdys, N.Y., a daughter, Sharon Weinberger of South Deerfield,
Mass.; two sisters, Sarah Budd of Lawrence, Mass. and Frances Marks
of Easton, Mass.; five grandchildren and a great-grandson.
</P>
</TEXT>
