<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5990 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-$ADV     07-07 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MEXICAN MARVELS: NEW PRESIDENT, CHANCE FOR SMOOTH TRANSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 9)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DUDLEY ALTHAUS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Whether giddy, ambivalent or broken-hearted, many
Mexicans have spent the past week getting their minds around the
idea that their country has finally joined the ranks of the world's
modern democracies.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential election of Vicente Fox of the center-right
National Action Party ended more than seven decades of rule by a
political machine that many charged was venal, violent and
inefficient. Fox's inauguration on Dec. 1 will mark the first time
in generations that power has passed peacefully between political
rivals here.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo, also the de facto leader of the
outgoing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, has promised to
work with Fox for a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps very few, and I include myself, imagined a scenario of
this kind,'' Fox told foreign correspondents during a lengthy press
conference last week. ``Of course I knock on wood that it continues
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many Mexicans, Fox marveled at the passing of the PRI's
71-year rule to a democracy full of citizen participation ``with
stability, speed and tranquility.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Fox must govern a deeply fragmented and impoverished
nation of 100 million people beset with high unemployment,
organized crime and political bossism.
</P>
<P>
   His challenge, analysts say, will be to produce significant, yet
controlled change. And there likely will be a lot of wood knocking
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for democratic government to show results
fast,'' said Edward Gibson, a political scientist at Northwestern
University who has specialized in the democratic transitions in
South America. ``They are under pressure to solve the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But in giving the PRI the boot, voters also denied Fox the blank
check held by every past Mexican president. Undermining Fox's
euphoric victory is the knowledge that more ballots were cast
against than for him.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's National Action Party will hold the largest block in both
chambers of Congress. But it won't have a majority in either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico has a golden opportunity to put in good government,''
Gibson said. ``But the ball is in the hands of the opposition,
because the president is really going to have to be looking for
coalitions.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of any consensus-building will depend on the faction
that eventually wins power in the internal feuding that erupted in
the PRI following Sunday's election, analysts said. Success will
also may depend on whether Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the leader of
Mexico's fractious left, can hold himself and his followers to
their vow of not cooperating with a Fox administration.
</P>
<P>
   Friction also persists between Fox and some leaders of the
National Action Party, which is widely known here by its Spanish
acronym, PAN.
</P>
<P>
   Fox comes from a party wing, sometimes called the Barbarians of
the North, whose more confrontational politics often rankled the
PAN's leaders who favored backroom agreements over street
agitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are constant tensions,'' said Fox adviser Carlos Arce.
``The PAN is a party forged in the opposition to be opposition. Now
it's going to have to transform itself to be a governing party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain uncertainty in all of this,'' Arce said.
``Democracy is complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fox, his advisers and some analysts say that cutting deals
is what both the president-elect and his National Action Party do
best.
</P>
<P>
   Arce, an outgoing National Action congressman and a longtime Fox
ally from his home state of Guanajuato, said the president-elect is
``a man who understands politics as two people sitting at a table
talking and reaching agreement. This Fox at the table is the Fox
who is going to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Coca-Cola now,'' said political scientist Federico
Estevez, referring to Fox's stint as that company's senior
executive in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to cut a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's takes the long view. He's very steady,'' Estevez
continued. ``He's got all the qualities he needs to see him through
the hard times. And hard times are coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Since winning on Sunday, Fox has been meeting with Mexican and
foreign reporters to get out his message that he means to have a
plural government made up of men and women of various political
stripes. While saying he hopes to spread the benefits of Mexico's
free-market economic policies, Fox considers that a long-term goal.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Fox told foreign reporters last week, his
administration will focus on the corruption and illicit
back-scratching that defines Mexican public life.
</P>
<P>
   He proposes to reorganize federal law enforcement, which has
been badly corroded by billions of dollars in bribes by
international narcotics smugglers. And he has called for a new
agency in the Congress to keep tabs on Executive Branch financial
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes down the road will depend upon the success of the
anti-corruption effort, Arce said. The trick, he said, will be to
prevent a PAN government from becoming as corrupt as those in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibilities of corruption are enormous,'' Arce, 45,
said. ``The same corruption that the PRI was exposed to, within a
few years could permeate the PAN.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the PAN manages above all to attack the corruption within
its ranks, we can have two or three governments that are good for
Mexico. If not, there will be a change.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has lagged far behind the rest of Latin America in
working out a formula for peacefully alternating power. And the
experience with democratic government throughout the region has
been decidedly mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Multiparty systems have sunk deep roots in such former military
dictatorships as Argentina, Chile and Brazil, but profound
disappointment with the politicians' inability to address the needs
of most citizens have given rise to strongman-rule in Peru and
Venezuela and brought political chaos to Colombia and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime activists worry that Mexicans, after so many
decades of having most of their political decisions made for them,
will want Fox to simply ape the PRI's authoritian rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now as we bury the symbolic father that marked our lives for a
century, let's not commit the error of substituting him with
another one,'' Segio Aguayo, a long-time democracy advocate who
lost a run for Congress on a left-of-center ticket, wrote in the
daily Reforma last week.
</P>
<P>
   But others say Fox's victory shows that Mexican society has
matured enough to make democratic decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an new consciousness among people of the power they
have,'' said sociologist Maria del Carmen Diaz, an outgoing federal
congresswoman from Fox's party. ``It's beyond parties.````There was
a rupture, and what was broken, was the fear and the
subordination,'' she said. ``Hope lies in two pillars: One is the
Fox government. But the other is the knowledge that if it doesn't
work, they can remove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is that the power is within us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
