<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-$ADV09     07-07 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ZEDILLO EARNS TEPID PRAISE FOR MEXICO'S POLITICAL SHIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 9)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DUDLEY ALTHAUS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Amid the turmoil of his long-ruling party's loss
of national power in the July 2 election, President Ernesto Zedillo
has won wide praise for bringing peaceful democratic transition to
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Zedillo oversaw the electoral reforms that leveled
the playing field between his ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, the PRI, and the political opposition. And those changes led
to the opposition parties winning control of the lower house of
Congress in 1997 and the presidency last week.
</P>
<P>
   But many democracy advocates and political opponents in Mexico
give Zedillo only a grudging nod for his role in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did what he had to do,'' said Sergio Aguayo, a founder of
the Civic Alliance, an elections watchdog group established in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox's election as president marked a milestone on the
country's long and frequently violent path to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The elections culminated decades of political pressure and
agitation in which the PRI's power was whittled away by both
conservative and leftist opponents. Although still strong in many
rural areas and especially in Mexico's impoverished south, by last
week the PRI was a silhouette of its former self.
</P>
<P>
   For many politically active Mexicans, the democratic
transformation began 32 years ago, when army troops slaughtered
hundreds of student in a downtown Mexico City plaza who were
protesting against the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Through the mid-1980s, the National Action Party and several
other opposition factions won a number of city halls along the U.S.
border and across northern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI held on to many cities, and the state government of
Chihuahua through only election fraud, critics say. National Action
activists responded to each fraud with sit-ins, hunger strikes and
other public demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, a coalition of disgruntled left-leaning defectors from
the PRI and members of tiny socialist parties under Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas harnessed a groundswell of popular anger and nearly won
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   After vote-counting computers at the PRI-controlled Interior
Ministry inexplicably broke down on election night, the ruling
party's Carlos Salinas de Gortari was declared the winner. Since
then, Cardenas' supporters say that nearly 650 of their number have
been killed in political disputes with the PRI and the government.
</P>
<P>
   To help win legitimacy and forge an alliance that would allow
him to govern, Salinas recognized a National Action victory for the
statehouse in Baja California in 1989 and later in other states. In
return, National Action frequently voted in favor of Salinas'
economic proposals in the Congress, infuriating Cardenas'
followers.
</P>
<P>
   Then Maya Indian peasants led by leftist intellectuals launched
a bloody uprising in southernmost Chiapas state on New Year's 1994,
the day the North American Free Trade Agreement with Canada and the
United States went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion was quickly contained militarily. But it unleashed
political chaos followed by assassinations, first of the PRI's
presidential candidate, Luis Donaldo Colosio, and five months later
of its second-ranking official. Many Mexicans believe both men were
victims of a power struggle within the PRI itself.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, who had replaced Colosio as the PRI's candidate, won
his presidency in a largely fraud-free vote. But the economy, which
had been propped up by PRI policy-makers to help get him elected,
finally collapsed in late December 1994, setting off the worst of
Mexico's many economic crises under the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Politically weakened and occupied with the economy, Zedillo
yielded to opposition pressure, recognizing more election wins in
state governments across Mexico. At the same time, he distanced
himself from the PRI while maneuvering to maintain control of it,
replacing the party's presidents seven time during his term of
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took any pretext possible to avoid doing dirty business
with the PRI,'' said political analyst Frederico Estevez, who
briefly served on Zedillo's team of advisers.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday's elections, more than half of Mexicans were already
governed by the political opposition on the state and local levels.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Zedillo scrapped a PRI tradition in which a sitting
president hand-picked the country's next president. In its place,
Zedillo allowed a primary in which his candidate handily won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the slightest doubt that the intention was to
sabotage the PRI so that it would lose,'' Cesar Agusto Santiago, a
former PRI congressman and deputy interior minister, said in a
nationally broadcast radio interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo amazed Mexicans last Sunday night just hours after the
polls closed by declaring Fox the next president with only a
fraction of the votes counted and before the PRI candidate had
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the old-line members of the PRI bitterly
accused the president of selling out the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there was a problem, was in the leadership, not the
base,'' Santiago said in the radio interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI was able to defeat the PRI.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5992 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-YOUNG-ARTISTS-LADN &LR;      07-07 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-ARTISTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAWING ON YOUNG RESOURCES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after July 10, 2000 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Lining the walls of the Every Picture Tells a Story gallery for the
next month are drawings that could as easily be attached to a
refrigerator door or tacked to a proud parent's office cubicle.
They bear the distinct mark of a child's imagination and
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Except the subjects are hardly childlike.
</P>
<P>
   You won't see an abundance of sun, rainbows or houses _ images
that typically dominate art by children. Occasionally, the faces
will be smiling. More often, not. A clay modeled hand is covered
with pins. In a crayon and charcoal drawing, the haunted-eyed face
of a single flower grows out of a pile of rocks. In another crayon
drawing, a stick figure adult rescues a child following the bombing
of the federal building in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   The artists' names aren't revealed. We only learn their age,
gender and the element of their lives that makes their stories more
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The young artists featured in ``Childhood Revealed: Art
Expressing Pain, Discovery and Hope,'' suffer from learning
disabilities, attention deficit disorder, anxiety, depression and
schizophrenia. Some have been victims of divorce; others have
suffered physical and sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   And, just like children who have never experienced trauma or
mental illness, these painters and sculptors _ ages 4 to 18 _ have
found a way to express themselves through art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that children's artwork is beautiful,'' says
Dr. Harold Koplewicz, director of the New York University Child
Study Center. ``You can be psychiatrically ill and still be a
child. That's what this is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition will be at the Los Angeles gallery through July
30 before continuing a national tour through the end of 2001.
Proceeds from the exhibition and from an accompanying coffee table
book _ co-edited by Koplewicz and Dr. Robin Goodman _ will benefit
research at the Child Study Center.
</P>
<P>
   During its stay, the art _ which includes water color drawings,
collages and sculpture _ will educate, and, Koplewicz hopes,
enlighten those who see it. The images may disturb people as well,
but as Child Study Center officials note, there's nothing pretty
about mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 million children and teens in the United States
suffer from mental health problems such as depression, eating
disorders, learning disabilities and anxiety, but only a fraction
have been diagnosed and receive treatment. Exhibitions like
``Childhood Revealed'' help give these children and their
afflictions some much-needed recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with an issue that we don't think gets talked
about enough, and dealing with some brutal subjects,'' says Brein
Lopez, Every Picture's curator. ``There's a tendency for adults to
just sort of stay away from emotional issues, but I think it's very
important that we allow ourselves to see that kids do deal with
these types of emotions on a daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the usual fare for Every Picture Tells a Story, which
typically displays art from children's books. But gallery officials
had recently been studying the works and career of Friedl
Dicker-Brandeis, a woman who pioneered art therapy techniques
during the Holocaust, and the subject of a future exhibition. They
concluded that the ``Childhood Revealed'' exhibition was a perfect
fit after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``With art being banned from schools over the last 12 years,
we're losing our ability to experience art on a daily basis,'' said
Lopez. ``When art is used as a way for kids to relate to their
surroundings and emotions, it's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 700 pieces of artwork _ all submitted anonymously by
the children's teachers, counselors and therapists _ were entered
for consideration in the exhibition. A jury of teachers, artists
and educators, including New Yorker art critic Paul Goldberger _
made the final selection for ``Childhood Revealed.''
</P>
<P>
   But as revealing as the artwork may seem, Koplewicz cautions
exhibition visitors to refrain from becoming amateur clinicians
after looking at the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The works themselves are not diagnostic. It would be
inappropriate and unsafe to interpret what they mean.'' says
Koplewicz. ``A child who doesn't have the same disorder can do the
same work. Some of them are just beautiful pieces of art.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, however, the artists themselves provide a window
of interpretation via an extended caption. Under his acrylic and
watercolor titled ``Breaking Through,'' a 15-year-old boy with
bipolar disorder writes: ``In this painting I am portraying myself
on the dark side and other people on the light side. There is a
chain in the middle because I used to put up an emotional wall and
did not let others help me. I used drugs for help instead. Well,
now the chain is broken and I let others help. I am not alone
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Since opening at the Whitney Museum of American Art in New York
last November, ``Childhood Revealed'' has spawned several tie-in
events. Local medical facilities have sponsored forums on mental
health and, in certain cases, have brought in celebrities who
suffered from various forms of illness or physical disabilities as
children. Katie Couric wrote the forward to the book, which also
includes a paragraph from Ted Kennedy Jr. A few of the artists have
even broken their anonymity, appearing at functions to talk about
their works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to educate America about these disorders, and
hopefully we can leave something behind,'' says Koplewicz. ``It's
not that the New York University Child Study Center is coming to
California. The idea is that these kids are everywhere.'' &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
What: ``Childhood Revealed: Art Expressing Pain, Discovery and
Hope.'' &QL; 
Where: Every Picture Tells a Story, 7525 Beverly Blvd., Los
Angeles. &QL; 
When: 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. Monday through Saturday, 11 a.m. to 4 p.m.
Sunday; through July 30. &QL; 
How much: Admission is free. &QL; 
Information: Call (323) 932-6070 or visit www.AboutOurKids.org. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
