<P>
   EDS: Since Sunday, June 4, and continuing for six weeks, The New
York Times has been publishing a series of articles, ``How Race Is
Lived in America.'' The series is the outcome of a yearlong effort
by a team of Times reporters to capture some of the voices of
ordinary people and some of the troubling issues that Americans
continue to face. The following story will move in the `a' category
for release on Sunday. Earlier articles are available to be resent
to clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-COPS-DRUGS (New York) _ On Friday, Feb. 25, at 5 p.m.,
there wasn't a single narcotics officer on the streets of Harlem.
Everyone was being held inside on standby in case of a race riot.
The Amadou Diallo verdict was about to come down. The whites _
officers like Sgt. Maria Brogli and Detectives Lee Macklowe and
John Montes _ hoped the four Diallo officers would be found not
guilty. The blacks _ detectives like Johnny Gonzalez and the
undercovers Derrick and Rob _ felt they should be found guilty on
at least some counts. Feelings ran deep. No case in recent years
has hit the police closer to home. By Michael Winerip.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEY AND BUSINESS (Will move in ``f'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL (Undated) _ Investors who thought they
could lessen their risk by diversifying overseas found little
solace last quarter in international equity funds, many of which
underperformed their domestic counterparts. By Vivian Marino.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-STRATEGIES (Undated) _ On behalf of financial planners,
academics, investment advisers and self-anointed experts
everywhere, I apologize. It appears that much of what you have been
told over the last 30 years about the benefits of international
diversification has been greatly exaggerated. In fact, according to
a new study, those benefits are less than half as great as
originally thought. By Mark Hulbert. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   COHEN-SULLIVAN-PROFILE (Undated) _ For more than 30 years,
Rodgin Cohen has been a sought-after counselor to chief executives
at the industry's largest financial institutions, including the
Bank of New York, First Union and Societe Generale, as well as an
adviser on some of this era's largest mergers. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEK IN REVIEW (Will move in `a' or `i' categories, as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-WORLD-POWER-REVIEW (Washington) _ The
U.S.-Israeli-Palestinian summit meeting raises anew the overarching
question dogging President Clinton, his aspiring successors and
Congress. Toward what ends should America harness the astounding
economic, military, political and cultural power it has accrued in
recent years? By David Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SPECIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Like dolphins, chimpanzees and
other gregarious creatures, humans are a ``highly social species.''
Dining al fresco on crowded sidewalks with cell phones grafted to
our ears. You scratch my back, I'll de-flea yours. Synchronized
swimming, anyone? Biologists say the complexities of social life
are what gave rise to big brains and intelligence in the first
place. Highly social species are, as a rule, the smartest and most
sophisticated. But why is there nothing stupider, nothing more
primitive and dangerous, than a crowd of people? By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-SUPERSTITIONS-REVIEW (New York) _ The ``Macbeth'' curse,
in which productions of that play have been harried by misfortune,
is not the only one hanging over the black-magic-laden world of the
theater, a profession where open incantations of blood lust
(``Break a leg!'') are routine. The list of taboos is lengthy:
Never whistle in the dressing room, never open an umbrella onstage,
never play an electrical fuse. A brief rundown of some current and
ancient omens plaguing the stage. By James McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW (Mexico City) _ The victory of
opposition presidential candidate Vicente Fox has raised hopes
among poor Mexicans, who are indicating that they will no longer
hand over their votes and expect little in return. What they most
expect from Fox are programs and reforms that will help Mexico's
new democracy expand beyond elections. But what some do not quite
realize is that the new president's powers have also been radically
altered _ and in some ways weakened _ by some of the same currents
that carried him to victory: He is not part of the one-party
apparatus that monopolized power but so often failed its people. By
Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-ATROCITIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Thousands of carefully
numbered, white plastic bags stacked on wooden shelves fill two
tunnels behind a morgue in central Bosnia. When the weather grows
warm, the stench is overwhelming. The bags contain the remains of
2,000 bodies collected over the last five years from mass graves
and hillsides around Srebrenica. The limbo in which the bodies
still wait for final burial stands as a symbol of the uncertain
fate of Bosnia itself _ and much else in the Balkans. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT-RETURN-REVIEW (Beirut, Lebanon) _ A journalist describes
his impressions today's Beirut and the Beirut he left in 1985.
Chaos and violence have been replaced by tranquility and order. By
John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Will move in `e' category or as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VERMEER-OPERA (Amsterdam, Netherlands) _ Peter Greenaway, the
British movie director, and Louis Andriessen, the Dutch composer,
are opening the Lincoln Center Festival 2000 with a new opera,
``Writing to Vermeer.'' Focusing on two weeks in 1672 when the
painter Johannes Vermeer made a trip to The Hague, the creators
imagine that he received 18 fictional letters from women in his
life and sensed the crisis gripping the country as it prepared to
breach the country's dikes to hold off invasion by France. (With
photo)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-MUSIC (New York) _ The development of 12-tone composition
was one of the most invigorating occurrences of 20th-century music.
Now two theories persist and conflict: Was there a tyranny of the
atonal composers who seized the intellectual high ground and
intimidated tonal composers or were theose modern composers who
were the beleaguered minority? By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   CIRCUS-LES-COLPORTEURS (Marseille, France) _ ``Filao'' from Les
Colporteurs, the French nouveau cirque, is the story of a French
aristocrat who becomes so disgusted with the world he climbs a tree
and stays there. The trapeze artists mix art forms and execute
their feats to music and with theatricality. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-ULTIMA-VEZ (New York) _ When Wim Vandekeybus, the Belgian
choreographer, presented in New York from 1987 to 1991, dancers
ducked as others threw bricks at them, and the norm consisted of
flying bodies, confrontational games and erotic aggressiveness. The
37-year-old choreographer warns the Lincoln Center Festival that he
no longer has to throw bricks to show intense instinct. Anna
Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-NOCHE-FLAMENCA (Madrid, Spain) _ In the gypsy quarter of
Madrid, Martin Santangelo rehearses five musicians and six flamenco
dancers for a U.S. tour. This New Yorker has found a calling in a
15th-century dance form. By Valerie Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
   PODESWA-FIVESENSES-FILM (New York) _ Laura Winters interviews
Jeremy Podeswa, the Canadian filmmaker whose ``Five Senses'' will
open in New York. He explains how a chance encounter led to the
story of five characters, each linked to a sense. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OZON-FILM (New York) _ The French director Francois Ozon has
made thrillers about homicidal house guests and high school
killers. In satire, he has explored the lighter sides of
cannibalism and incest. But his latest film tackles the horrors of
one couple's life. ``Water Drops on Burning Rocks'' is his screen
adaptation of a play written by Rainer Werner Fassbinder at the age
of 19. By Leslie Camhi. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-MUSIC-POP (New York) _ The composers, visionaries,
theorists, tinkerers and crackpots who invented electronic music
probably never imagined that by the end of the 20th century,
thousands of people would regularly turn out to hear electronic
music in clubs and that the futuristic sounds are now taken for
granted by anyone who tunes in a Top 40 radio station. By Jon
Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOGRAPHY-SACCO (New York) _ Argentine artist Graciela Sacco
uses a heliography technique to place images on suitcases, Venetian
blinds, refrigerators and even postage stamps. In the current
exhibit at the Argentine Consulate here, visitors are confronted
by, among other things, small spoons hanging from a line. On each
spoon an open mouth has been heliographed. She has also hung a
series of clear plastic frames imprinted with the image of eyes as
if the art were looking at the visitor, not vice versa. By Lyle
Rexer.
</P>
<P>
   ROSLER-ART (New York) _ Martha Rosler, the multimedia artist,
critic, theorist, teacher and art-world provocateur, has shown
disdain for the normal rites of passage from galleries to
collectors to museums. That makes it all the more remarkable that
Rosler is now receiving a major retrospective. After stops in
England, France, Austria and Spain, ``Martha Rosler: Positions in
the Life World'' makes its only U.S. in New York. By Michael Rush.
(With photo)
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-GORT (Undated) _ Gort has no shop selling Celtic
knickknacks, no pub with performances of ditties on the half-hour.
Even its name lacks the lyricism of more famous Irish destinations.
But within a 10-mile radius you can find Coole Park, once Lady
Gregory's sanctuary for the leaders of the Irish literary revival;
Thoor Ballylee, the tower of inspiration for William Butler Yeats;
Kilmacduagh, some of the finest monastic remnants in Ireland;
Kinvara, an inviting fishing village; and the Burren, the dramatic
limestone landscape sloping into the Atlantic. Those who pay
attention will see life in the Irish west as it is, not as it might
be imagined. By Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `t' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-IRELAND-BURREN (Undated) _ Bleak and harsh are the
adjectives often used to describe the Burren, a roughly
100-square-mile limestone landscape of cliffs, stony hills and
broad stretches of rock. But Lisa Fugard discovered the profusity
and mystique of wildflowers growing there.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `t' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Kiosks open at seven airports to rent
DVD players and movies; Hotel Savoy reopens in Florence, Italy;
Francis Gary Powers Jr. leads a Cold War tour; a hotel in St.
Thomas offers Nannies in Paradise so parents can have a night out
and rail service is completed for Sydney Airport.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `t' category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLES (Will move in `l' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WEDDING-PHOTO-OP (New York) _ The brides were tacking in white
satin, trains billowing, veils lofting like the topsails of the
Tall Ships entering New York harbor. Gliding across a marble
expanse, Guatemala circled Korea, with Jamaica and China close at
hand. A Salvadoran bridal party broke through a throng of tourists
gathered for a family reunion. The setting for this odd apparition
was the World Financial Center's Winter Garden on July 4th weekend.
This sort of thing takes place here all the time; the midpoints of
winter and summer are high season for wedding photography in this
vast lobby, a de facto chapel of love that also happens to be a
corporate headquarters for Dow Jones, Amex and the accounting
romantics at Deloitte and Touche. By Patricia A. Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   BERGDORF-BOOKSELLER (New York) _ Tucked all the way in the back
of the top floor at Bergdorf Goodman is a book-filled nook titled
Jane Stubbs. And tucked behind the stacks of rare and vintage books
is a woman tucked behind an enormous shirt and thick glasses, Jane
Stubbs. By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   FAKE-HANDBAGS (Undated) _ A look at a new breed of sidewalk
shopper: consumers of evident style and means who can afford to pay
retail but enjoy the thrill of adding a $30 counterfeit or two to
their wardrobes. Where the shoppers stooping to inspect street
merchandise were once mainly office workers and tourists, now they
are as likely to be chic passers-by, clutching a genuine Prada
shoulder bag style or a tote emblazoned with real Gucci double G's.
By Ruth LaFerla.
</P>
