<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-ADS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE-PROMOTING TV ADS GET AXED 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM HAMMETT   
 WineToday.com   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After test-marketing an ad campaign with a catch-phrase of
``Wine. What are you saving it for?'' the Wine Market Council is
opting to put its efforts into the Internet, in-store merchandising
and public relations, rather than into more costly television and
radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is the right message but the medium was the wrong
medium,'' said Wine Market Council president John Gillespie,
explaining why the broadcast campaign was tested only in Albany,
N.Y., and Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was an attempt to enhance the image of wine as baby
boomers, the industry's core consumers, age and the next generation
leans more toward beer and martinis.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the wine industry were disappointed at the decision not
to run broadcast ads. ``It's a shame that it was ruled out,'' said
Martin Johnson, vice president of marketing and advertising for
Robert Mondavi Winery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when Gallo, Taylor Wines and Paul Masson started
advertising in the 1980s, wine consumption rose to its highest
level,'' Johnson said. ``And when those ads stopped we started to
see consumption drop.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted, however, that few premium wineries could afford
television.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was designed to change marginal wine drinkers'
perception that wine is suitable only for special events, and to
get those consumers to consider it an accompaniment to meals.
</P>
<P>
   Bozell Worldwide, the agency that came up with the milk mustache
and the ``Pork, the Other White Meat'' campaigns, developed the
television, billboard and radio commercials for the wine industry.
The campaign showcased special days, like National Hog Day, that
consumers could celebrate by serving wine with a meal.
</P>
<P>
   The test ads ran for three months at a cost of $1.3 million, and
were funded by wine producers, importers, grape growers and
industry organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all knew it was going to be a challenge to get the
industry to fund a national campaign to the tune that would be
required to make this work,'' said Sutter Home's director of public
relations, Stan Hock. ``Many larger wineries who can afford to put
money into it are more likely going to put that money into their
own ad campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutter Home has used broadcast advertising since the early
1990s. The Napa Valley winery spent $5 million to $7 million last
year creating and airing television ads during the Christmas
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is to sponsor Public Broadcasting programs.
Kendall-Jackson, and the Jackson family's Artisans &AMP; Estates wines,
sponsor programs like Jacques Pepin's ``Cooking with Claudine'' and
``Cooking with Jacques and Julia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part philanthropic,'' said John Maxwell, Kendall-Jackson
brand manager. ``But we score with consumers and with the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   While K-J already has spent $1.5 million sponsoring such
programming, there are other costs like the underwriting of dinners
in major markets for 100 or so viewers, with Pepin and Julia Child
as guests of honor. These events raise money for public
broadcasting, and the costs generally are defrayed by sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with most marketing concepts, it isn't the direct cost that
gets you, it's the support you must give to the project to make it
work, which generally costs far more than the advertising
investment,'' said K-J's director of public relations, Jim Caudill.
</P>
<P>
   Some winery officials said the industry has to go beyond
consumer and wine trade publications to reach infrequent drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the industry tends to preach to the choir too much
rather than go for a broader audience to pick up new customers,''
said Johnson of Mondavi.
</P>
<P>
   (Winetoday.com is a daily Internet wine publication published by
the New York Times Co. The Web address is www.winetoday.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
