<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEACHERS-FELDMAN-515&AMP;     07-07 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-FELDMAN-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNING THE TEACHERS UNION IS A BALANCING ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Resplendent in her brand-new heathery indigo
pantsuit, adrenaline still pumping from her keynote address an hour
before, Sandra Feldman, the president of the American Federation of
Teachers, strode through the gleaming convention center, surrounded
by her members, her teachers, her people. They stopped her for
snapshots. They called out congratulations. They waved, and she
smiled that outsized Sandy Feldman smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken a poll, and we all agree,'' Nat LaCour, the
federation's No. 2, whispered as he walked up. ``Blond is
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Yup, Sandy Feldman has dyed her hair blond. Brash, blunt,
Brooklyn-Jewish Sandy Feldman, whose saucy voice and
straightforward manner _ perhaps whose very soul _ practically ooze
brunette, has gone blond.
</P>
<P>
   She tried to downplay it, brushing off questions about her salon
by suggesting that a male leader would never be asked such things.
She called it ``highlights,'' though the entire top layer of her
shoulder-length bob has been colored. Then later, loosening up a
little, she admitted that when she first saw her lightened locks in
the mirror she almost redyed them brown.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Feldman is right, and it is a superficial _ even sexist _
detail hardly worth mentioning. Or maybe making such a bold change
two weeks before your organization's biennial convention _ your big
chance to bond with your members and shine in the media spotlight
for days _ maybe that suggests a comfort and confidence level that
means something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought I'd try it,'' she said over a hotel breakfast
of poached eggs, wholewheat toast and coffee with ``as much
caffeine as you have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was summertime. It was a lark. I might not keep it.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been over three years since the legendary Al Shanker died
and Feldman, his protege, replaced him at the federation's helm.
The smaller but scrappier of the two national teachers unions, the
American Federation of Teachers has swelled by more than 100,000 to
top 1 million members under Feldman's leadership over the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   And there has rarely been a moment when education, particularly
the question of teacher quality, has been higher on the national
political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman, 60, is seizing the opportunity to talk about increasing
her members' salaries and professionalizing their jobs, but also
about educating the poorest and hardest to teach of America's
children. If there is one thing that differentiates her from the
hard-driving Shanker, it is the obviousness of her passionate
commitment to the children, which erupts through the smile
stretched across her face as she escorts a nervous kindergartner
across a stage on July 4 for a musical performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at a moment when the kids who have really been left out
can really get help,'' she said. ``I want to fix those schools. I
know those schools are not what they should be. If we don't
prevail, I'm afraid they're going to be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is who I am,'' she added. ``I'm a poor kid from Coney
Island. I couldn't have had a life of any success if I didn't have
education.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Familiar to those who have been watching since Feldman became
president of New York's United Federation of Teachers in 1986, her
story is an education fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a milkman and a sickly woman who sometimes
worked in a bakery, Feldman grew up in a dirty tenement and then a
public housing project. Her second-grade teacher at P.S. 188 gave
her books like ``A Child's Garden of Verses,'' which she devoured,
often while at home in bed with asthma.
</P>
<P>
   She won a creative writing award at James Madison High School,
studied English at Brooklyn College and, while pursuing a master's
degree in literature, taught first- and fourth-grade at P.S. 34 in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   When Feldman tried to join the union at her school, there wasn't
one. So she built it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a believer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Married after her first year of college and divorced 17 years
later, Feldman never had children of her own but has spent her life
surrounded by them, doting on her nieces and nephews and visiting
schools three times a week during the three decades she worked for
the United Federation of Teachers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now married to Arthur Barnes, a New York businessman, she exults
in his 6-year-old grandson, who has just finished first grade at a
Brooklyn public school.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman lives primarily in New York, commuting to her union's
headquarters in Washington. When not traveling to assist local
leaders with negotiations _ or connect with teachers unions in Hong
Kong or Chile or South Africa _ she and Barnes, 70, go salsa
dancing and frequent jazz clubs.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the union local in New York, Feldman emptied
schools of time-clocks, successfully sued the district over
decrepit conditions, and helped pick chancellors _ even mayors.
Since becoming national president, she has called for shutting down
failing schools, establishing tough tests for entry into the
teaching profession and, this week, creating an optional
transitional year for high school students who lack basic skills.
</P>
<P>
   Though it makes some in the rank and file bristle, Feldman
supports the wave of new standardized tests that have come along
with higher academic expectations over the last decade, and is open
to suggestions about compensating teachers in part based on
performance.
</P>
<P>
   It is a funny balance, running a trade union of college-educated
professionals; the enemy, she said, is the growing cohort of
entrepreneurs eyeing the $3 billion educational industrial complex,
and the Republican politicians who want to give parents vouchers of
public money for private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get power and dismantle the public schools _ or, over
a period of time, decide that we won't educate all our kids _ then
we will be a different country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at me. I've got this in my gut,'' she added. ``Look at
me. If that school wasn't there, I wouldn't be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
