<HEADER>
A6006 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      07-07 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, July 9, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Planned for the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-WORLD-POWER-REVIEW (Washington) _ The
U.S.-Israeli-Palestinian summit meeting raises anew the overarching
questions dogging President Clinton, his aspiring successors and
Congress. Toward what ends should America harness the astounding
economic, military, political and cultural power it has accrued in
recent years? Is it enough to act as the world's peacemaker? Why is
the country having so much trouble establishing its international
priorities? By David Sanger. (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRESCRIPTION-DRUGS-REVIEW (Washington) _ In this election
season, helping the elderly pay for their pills is a political
no-brainer: Everybody's for it. The fight is over how to do it.
Republicans want private insurers to run any prescription drug
benefits plan. Democrats want the government in control. But that
classic liberal-conservative clash masks the real issue: how much
drugs will cost, and who will set their prices. By Sheryl Gay
Stolberg. (Moving in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SPECIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Like dolphins, chimpanzees and
other gregarious creatures, humans are a ``highly social species.''
Dining al fresco on crowded sidewalks with cell phones grafted to
our ears. You scratch my back, I'll de-flea yours. Synchronized
swimming, anyone? Biologists say the complexities of social life
are what gave rise to big brains and intelligence in the first
place. Highly social species are, as a rule, the smartest and most
sophisticated. But why is there nothing stupider, nothing more
primitive and dangerous, than a crowd of people? If human sociality
has its roots in its primate past, it's worth asking whether the
menacing side of a human crowd likewise resembles group behavior
among nonhuman species. By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-SUPERSTITIONS-REVIEW (New York) _ The ``Macbeth'' curse,
in which productions of that play have been harried by misfortune,
is not the only hanging over the black-magic-laden world of the
theater, a profession where open incantations of blood lust
(``Break a leg!'') are routine. The list of taboos is lengthy:
never whistle in the dressing room, never open an umbrella onstage,
never play an electrical fuse. A brief rundown of some current and
ancient omens plaguing the stage. By James McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   SWEATSHOPS-REVIEW (undated) _ Many consumers are displaying
noblesse oblige toward the millions of foreign workers who make the
goods that flood American stores. For years, anti-sweatshop
protests accomplished next to nothing. But as the anti-sweatshop
movement continues to grow _ and grow louder _ manufacturers have
recently taken steps that just might improve working conditions
around the world. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-HYPE-REVIEW (Undated) _ It's movie hype season. Since
1975, when ``Jaws'' devoured the box office and showed the film
industry new ways to get kids to see films over and over again
during the summer, hype has become its own industry. Colossal
promotional campaigns that studios create to sell their films
include the repetitive cover stories in glossy magazines, newspaper
and TV coverage and blanket advertising. Studios usually spend one
and a half times the production budget of a movie on publicity. By
Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   BOYSCOUT-MANUAL-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The recent Supreme Court
decision that allowed the Boy Scouts to expel a gay member dealt in
part with the moral values of Scouting. The first Boy Scout manual,
published in 1910 by Scouting founder Ernest Thompson Seton, says
nothing about homosexuality, but much to say about primal urges and
manly passions. Some passages are excerpted.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW (Mexico City) _ The victory of
opposition presidential candidate Vicente Fox has raised hopes
among poor Mexicans, who are indicating that they will no longer
hand over their votes and expect little in return. What they most
expect from Fox are programs and reforms that will help Mexico's
new democracy expand beyond elections. But what some do not quite
realize is that the new president's powers have also been radically
altered _ and in some ways weakened _ by some of the same currents
that carried him to victory: he is not part of the one-party
apparatus that monopolized power but so often failed its people. By
Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-ATROCITIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Thousands of carefully
numbered, white plastic bags stacked on wooden shelves fill two
tunnels behind a morgue in central Bosnia. In warm weather, the
stench is overwhelming. The bags contain the remains of 2,000
bodies collected over the last five years from mass graves and
hillsides around Srebrenica. The limbo in which the bodies still
wait for final burial stands as a symbol of the uncertain fate of
Bosnia itself _ and much else in the Balkans. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT-RETURN-REVIEW (Beirut, Lebanon) _ A journalist describes
his impressions of today's Beirut and the Beirut he left in 1985.
Chaos and violence have been replaced by tranquility and order. By
John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STORY QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: &LR;
