<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE'S AGNOLUTTO WINS TOUR DE FRANCE 7TH STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMOGES, France _ Erik Zabel knew that what he wanted for his
30th birthday on Friday was not another necktie or a good book, but
exactly what he received for his 25th birthday: A victory in the
Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the stage into Limoges looked promising for the star
German sprinter for the Telekom team. But Zabel had wanted the same
present last year, and the year before too, and came away
disappointed. Although his wife and son may have given him the
power drill of his dreams, nothing lights up a birthday party like
a victory in a Tour stage.
</P>
<P>
   Wait until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Zabel never had a chance for victory Friday because Christophe
Agnolutto, a Frenchman with the AG2R team, went on a 128-kilometer
(80-mile) solo breakaway during this seventh of 21 daily stages,
built a lead that neared 8 minutes and held on to win by 1 minute
11 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph was the first for a Frenchman in the Tour in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Agnolutto, a winner of the Tour of Switzerland in 1997, has done
nothing particularly successful since and ranked 82nd, more than 11
minutes behind the leader, when the 205.5-kilometer (128 miles)
rolling ride began Friday morning in Tours. He won on a nasty day _
sun, rain, rain, sun, cool breezes throughout _ in a time of 5
hours 11 minutes 41 seconds, a speed of 39 kilometers an hour (24
mph).
</P>
<P>
   Because the victor was so submerged in the overall standings,
there was no change at the top. Alberto Elli, an Italian with
Telekom, continued at age 36 to be one of the oldest men ever to
wear the leader's yellow jersey of the Tour, an annual event that
began in 1903 and has been interrupted only by both world wars.
</P>
<P>
   Second was Fabrice Gougot, a Frenchman with Credit Agricole, who
bolted away from the 172-man trailing pack in the final kilometer
in an attempt to reduce his 12-second deficit, but he failed as the
sprinters surged past him.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Marcel Wust, a German with Festina, was second
across the line behind Agnolutto, with Zabel third. Rats, another
birthday ruined.
</P>
<P>
   In the first seven days of this 87th Tour, Zabel has come so
close to ridding himself of what has nearly become an obsession for
victory. On Sunday, he was ideally placed in the last 100 meters
leading into Loudun _ at the front of a mass charge to the line.
The same was true Monday, into Nantes. And the same Wednesday, into
Vitre.
</P>
<P>
   With age, though, Zabel's hallmark is endurance, not the sudden
acceleration that often decides a tight sprint. He finished third,
third and second in those previous sprints _ close but, as he says,
close isn't enough. What he wants is for everybody else to be close
to victory, his victory.
</P>
<P>
   It has been three Tours de France since Zabel crossed a finish
line first. From 1995, when he made his debut in the race, through
1997, he won seven stages. Since then there have been many
second-place finishes, the worst place of all for most racers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident, I feel good,'' Zabel said before the start of
this Tour. ``Yes,'' he said, ``I've won a lot of races this year.''
Including the esteemed Milan-San Remo classic in March, he has 15
victories already, five more than he had in all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   With the triumph in Italy, his third in that race, and a fourth
place in the Tour of Flanders, followed by a third place in
Paris-Roubaix and a victory in the Amstel Gold Race, Zabel leads
the standings in the World Cup of one-day classics. He ranks second
among the world's 800 professional riders. In a recent poll by the
German newspaper Sport Bild, he was a runaway (82 percent) choice
as the country's favorite rider.
</P>
<P>
   Zabel has everything, in short, except what he wants most. After
Stuart O'Grady, an Australian with Credit Agricole, crashed
Thursday and had to leave the race with a broken collarbone, Zabel
remains a leader in the hot battle for the Tour's green points
jersey. The German has won it for a record four consecutive years,
but he does not regard it as highly as a single stage victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't write Zabel off,'' another fine sprinter, Tom Steels,
told the Belgian press Thursday. ``He's not winning, but you notice
that he's among the top finishers every day. One day it will
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Steels, himself, has won two sprint finishes this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
