<HEADER>
A6020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SACAGAWEA-COIN0708-CO     07-07 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SACAGAWEA-COIN0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sacagawea ad campaign is a day late, dollar short
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I've got a problem with that TV commercial for
the new golden-dollar coin: Sacagawea gets shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is all about George Washington. Not Sacagawea. We get to
see a hip George dancing in a nightclub, diving under water, buying
coffee and dropping a coin at a tollbooth. Another version of the
TV ad shows George as president of his book club, teaching aerobics
and floating in space as an astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me, but whose life is it, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Sacagawea, the Shoshone Indian teen-ager who helped Lewis and
Clark on their 3,000-mile expedition through the Northwest, is the
person on the new golden dollar. Not George.
</P>
<P>
   George is old news. George is a piece of green paper.
</P>
<P>
   Sacagawea is new. Sacagawea is golden.
</P>
<P>
   Who gives a coin flip about George when it comes to the new
dollar?
</P>
<P>
   The only time you'll see Sacagawea in any of the $40 million
worth of advertising by the United States Mint is a split-second
image of the golden dollar. Her name is never even mentioned. If
you blink, I guarantee you'll miss the face of Sacagawea that was
designed by renowned sculptor Glenna Goodacre, who also sculpted
the Vietnam Women's Memorial in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe newspapers wouldn't have to print stories about the big
debate on how to pronounce or spell Sacagawea if the government had
bothered to make her the star of ads about her new coin.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to figure out why the U.S. Mint put Sacagawea's face
on the coin but George's face on the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't that make about as much sense as Chrysler trying to sell
its new PT Cruiser by running ads showing the LeBaron?
</P>
<P>
   ``We chose George Washington for a couple of reasons,'' said
Philip Diehl, who headed the U.S. Mint and oversaw the
golden-dollar campaign until he left in March. ``He is the father
of our country, and so he speaks with authority. An endorsement
from George Washington means a lot. It's like a celebrity
endorsement.''
</P>
<P>
   The government thinks Sacagawea's story is too complex and
intriguing to promote in a fleeting commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too rich. You can't tell it in a sound bite,'' Diehl
said. ``Because Glenna Goodacre created such a beautiful coin, the
coin itself evokes the story.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the government thinks we need permission from our country's
daddy before we can understand fully that it's OK to use the new
dollar coin?
</P>
<P>
   George Washington was an accomplished man. We all know that. But
Sacagawea was no ordinary woman.
</P>
<P>
   Sacagawea was chosen for the new golden coin because of her
courage, strength and quiet integrity on the 1804-1806 trek of
Lewis and Clark and their Corps of Discovery from the Great Plains
to the Pacific Ocean and back. Serving as an interpreter and guide,
she became an invaluable member of the expedition. When the boats
overturned, only Sacagawea took the initiative to plunge in and
save travel journals and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   She was only 15 when she made the journey with her husband,
trader Toussaint Charbonneau, and she gave birth to a son before
the expedition. The baby, Jean Baptiste, is pictured on the new
coin with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Clark paid Sacagawea's husband for his help during the
expedition. But Sacagawea got nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Some American Indians think Sacagawea is left empty-handed all
over again by the George commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of disgusting, because even on the
expedition, she wasn't really recognized,'' said Zelda Tillman,
director of the Shoshone Cultural Center in Fort Washakie, Wyo.
``It's like a woman is never recognized for what's she done, like
she's not worthy.''
</P>
<P>
   My two cents' worth? The government blew its golden opportunity
to educate and inspire Americans with the story of Sacagawea.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Mint's argument to use George instead is nothing but
spin that leaves the new coin twirling in a vacuum of knowledge.
Tails, we win. Heads, we lose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
