<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DIANA-ROSS-REVIEW-ART     07-07 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-ROSS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP REVIEW: AS EVER AGLITTER IN THE NAME OF LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Diana Ross and ``the former ladies of the
Supremes'' revived the Supremes' hits on Thursday night at Madison
Square Garden, it was a tribute to three musicians who weren't
onstage: Brian Holland, Lamont Dozier and Edward Holland Jr.
</P>
<P>
   They were the ones behind the Supremes' string of indelible hits
from 1963 to 1967. The H-D-H team wrote and produced lovelorn pop
songs with a gospel kick: ``Where Did Our Love Go,'' ``I Hear a
Symphony,'' ``Love Is Like an Itching in My Heart,'' ``My World Is
Empty Without You,'' ``Come See About Me.'' Under their direction,
Ross pined repeatedly for a distant lover, confessing to lonely,
sleepless nights that would turn to joy if he'd only come back. For
many baby boomers, her girlish, melting croon became the voice of
young love.
</P>
<P>
   The set included the major H-D-H songs and a few lesser-known
ones, like the Supremes' first hit, ``When the Lovelight Starts
Shining Through His Eyes,'' from 1963. The concert's staging made
mild efforts to rekindle thoughts of the 1960s by showing
photographs from civil rights marches during ``Reflections'' and
hinting that ``Back in My Arms Again'' could refer to soldiers
returning from Vietnam. But in an audience that had baby-boomer
couples alongside diva devotees and an occasional drag queen, the
overwhelming nostalgia was not sociopolitical but musical.
</P>
<P>
   To hear the old songs again, the sold-out audience forgave Ross
for touring with two latter-day Supremes, Lynda Laurence and
Scherrie Payne, who joined the group after Ross started her solo
career in 1970, instead of the surviving 1960s Supremes, Mary
Wilson and Cindy Birdsong.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the newer Supremes had a solo spot, with Payne showing
off a multi-octave range in ``Stoned Love.'' But it was Ross' show,
of course. While the women had matching outfits _ sequined and
feathered dresses, along with some ill-advised form-fitting suits _
the two 1970s Supremes generally kept a respectful distance from
Ross, smiling as if their jobs depended on it and curling their
arms in more or less synchronized versions of the Supremes' old
choreography. When the three women stood together for ``Stop! in
the Name of Love,'' there were some near collisions.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than recreate the lean rhythm-and-blues arrangements of
the great 1960s Motown studio bands, the concert deployed a large
orchestra with strings, horns and backup singers, as well as 10
dancers doing a Gap ad version of 1960s go-go routines. In another
modern touch, a teleprompter above the sound booth displayed the
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   But the audience wasn't worried about anachronisms, or about the
shrill edge that came and went in Ross' voice. The people in the
floor seats were on their feet, dancing and singing along,
throughout the nearly two-hour set. They cheered each memorable
H-D-H hook: the jabbing guitar that opens ``You Keep Me Hangin'
On,'' the ``oohs'' that lead into ``Baby Love.'' During ``You Can't
Hurry Love,'' Ross walked down into the audience, accepting hugs
and kisses from fans and giving them her microphone to sing a few
lines; it was like Oprah Winfrey working a karaoke bar.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' fans would have been disappointed if she hadn't included
some of her post-Supremes hits, and she advanced as far as the
disco era to sing ``Ain't No Mountain High Enough,'' ``I'm Coming
Out'' and ``Upside Down,'' as well as Gloria Gaynor's diva staple,
``I Will Survive.'' She also summoned Luther Vandross up from the
audience to sing with her in ``The Best Years of My Life.'' He
didn't know the song, but by echoing Ross with rich, curvaceous
phrases, he brought down the house.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the bustle of the production, there were flashes of the
vulnerability that made the Supremes speak so intimately to
millions of listeners. It appeared in ``Love Child,'' as Ross
blurted, ``Take a look at me!'' and in a tender, slowed-down solo
version of ``Reach Out I'll Be There.'' Most of the time, the
neo-Supremes glittered and belted, and the songs did the rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
