<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-07 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHEN THE GIANTS AND SUPERBAS PLAYED TWO 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Teddy Roosevelt was in Syracuse, N.Y., that Labor Day
for the opening of the New York State Fair when a man was arrested
there for allegedly threatening to shoot the president. Foreign
diplomats were predicting that war in the Balkans was inevitable.
And at a baseball game in Brooklyn between the Superbas, as the
team was known then, and John McGraw's New York Giants, the
multitudes were howling.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point,'' according to the next day's New York Times,
``a riot seemed imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Superbas' Sammy Strang trying to steal second in the
fifth inning, Jimmy Sheckard, who led the National League that year
with nine homers and 67 stolen bases, suddenly raised his bat,
apparently with mischief in mind. When catcher Frank Bowerman's
throw glanced off the bat and rolled near first base, Strang kept
running and scored as the Giants' infielders stood around, assuming
that the only umpire would nullify the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurst, however, gave the tally to Brooklyn and disallowed the
claim of interference,'' The Times reported, referring to the
umpire. ``McGraw and Bowerman, with four or five more of the New
York players, protested while the partisans in the stands kept up
an ear-splitting noise, some applauding and others protesting the
umpire's fiat. Bowerman was ejected.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the way it was nearly a century ago, on Sept. 7, 1903,
in New York's primeval preview of Saturday's Yankees-Mets
doubleheader in Queens and the Bronx _ the Giants' 6-4 triumph in
the morning at Washington Park's wooden grandstand in Brooklyn, the
Superbas' 3-0 victory that afternoon at the rickety Polo Grounds at
Eighth Avenue and West 155th Street in upper Manhattan, under what
is still known as Coogan's Bluff.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody called it a subway series; the city's subway wouldn't
open until late the next year. But the city had elevated trains and
trolleys. Maybe that's how the teams traveled from one ballpark to
the other.
</P>
<P>
   The primary personalties in the interborough rivalry were
McGraw, the Giants' pugnacious manager, and Charles Ebbets, the
Superbas' owner remembered for proclaiming, ``Baseball is in its
infancy.'' So was the feud that endured until the Dodgers and
Giants departed for Los Angeles and San Francisco after the 1957
season.
</P>
<P>
   In that 1903 season New York also had its first American League
team, the Highlanders, the ancestors of the Yankees, who split a
morning-afternoon Labor Day doubleheader with the Boston Pilgrims
(now the Red Sox) at Hilltop Park in Washington Heights. In the
afternoon game, the Highlanders defeated the great Cy Young, 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   But the lead sports headline the next day in The Times (which
sold for 1 cent), the Herald and the Evening Post went to the
winner of the Twin City Handicap at the Sheepshead Bay racetrack.
McChesney, described as ``the great horse of the West,'' equaled
the track record for a mile and a quarter before 50,000 spectators.
</P>
<P>
   The reported total attendance for the four baseball games was
44,000, including 23,000 at the Polo Grounds where Henry Schmidt,
the Superbas' 30-year-old rookie righthander, outdueled Joe ``Iron
Man'' McGinnity, who that August had justified his nickname by
pitching (and winning) both games of three doubleheaders.
</P>
<P>
   McGinnity went on to a 31-20 record, pitching 434 innings with
44 complete games. His teammate, Christy Mathewson, was 30-13 with
267 strikeouts. Together, the future Hall of Famers appeared in 100
games. The Giants finished second, six and a half games behind the
Pittsburgh Pirates, whose Honus Wagner batted .355.
</P>
<P>
   For the Superbas, who finished fifth, Schmidt had a 21-13 record
in his only major-league season. Early the next year he sent the
club a telegram: ``I do not like living in the East and will not
report.'' He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Ebbets, who built the ballpark named for him that opened in
1913, had been a ticket seller, clerk and briefly the manager
before he bought the Dodgers (Brooklynites were known as trolley
dodgers) for $30,000 in 1898. He installed it in Washington Park on
Third Street between Fourth and Fifth Avenues, where a playground
is now.
</P>
<P>
   When Ebbets hired Ned Hanlon as manager, the team was briefly
called the Superbas, after a popular vaudeville act, Hanlon's
Superbas.
</P>
<P>
   The Highlanders, who played at Broadway and West 165th St.,
where the New York Presbyterian Medical Center is now, finished
fourth in 1903, but their crusty manager, Clark Griffith, later the
longtime owner of the Washington Senators, challenged the Giants to
a postseason city series. The established Giants ignored the
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cheap advertising stunt,'' snapped John T. Brush, the
Giants' haughty owner. ``Who is Griffith? I never heard of him.
There is only one club in New York and that is the Giants.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody on the Yankees, not even George Steinbrenner, would dare
say that there is only one club in New York now. And nobody on the
Mets would dare say it. But they all would love to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
