<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CREDIT COMES AT A PRICE: THE CRITICISM IS FREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This is a tale of three central banks. All face
tough choices about whether to raise interest rates, and the
strategies they pursue over the remainder of this year could have a
big effect on the global economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
   _After pushing its benchmark lending rate down to just a notch
above zero in an effort to resuscitate the Japanese economy, the
Bank of Japan is hinting that it will soon tighten monetary policy,
even though many analysts think that deflation is still a greater
risk than inflation, and that the financial system needs more money
and credit, not less.
</P>
<P>
   _With an economic upswing under way across Europe, the European
Central Bank is likely to continue raising rates this year. But the
11 nations sharing a common monetary policy are running at
different economic speeds and are not, at the moment, good
candidates for a one-size-fits-all interest rate prescription.
</P>
<P>
   _In the United States, six interest rate increases over the last
year are beginning to have their intended effect, as illustrated by
Friday's report from the Labor Department showing a slowdown in the
rate of job creation. But there is considerable uncertainty and
debate within the Federal Reserve about how much more tightening,
if any, will be necessary to squelch inflation pressures without
putting the long expansion at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three major central banks, the Bank of Japan faces the
most dire situation and the most second-guessing.
</P>
<P>
   Masaru Hayami, the central bank's governor, has signaled that he
would like to bring to an end what he considers an emergency period
of exceptionally low interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Hayami's rationale seems to be twofold: that higher rates would
force Japanese industry to stop relying on cheap money for survival
and get on with the painful business of restructuring itself, and
that moving rates up now, when the economy is showing tentative
signs of life, would give the Bank of Japan the ability to cut them
again if the economy goes back into a swoon.
</P>
<P>
   But his approach is viewed skeptically even in his own
government's finance ministry. And many economists say Japan's
problems are not linked so much to interest rates _ the cost of
money _ but rather to a lack of available money and credit at any
price.
</P>
<P>
   According to Carl Weinberg, chief economist at High Frequency
Economics, a consulting firm in Valhalla, N.Y., bank credit in
Japan contracted 4.7 percent in the 12 months ended in May,
reflecting the dead weight of bad loans held by lenders and the
continued decline in the value of assets that borrowers can use as
collateral.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than raising rates, he and other critics say, the Bank of
Japan would do better to grease the wheels of the financial system,
perhaps by buying bad loans from banks, to spur new lending and get
the economy humming again.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the head of the new central bank, Wim Duisenberg, is
facing the first big test of his institution's ability to weather
the economic and political strains inherent in establishing a
transnational institution to perform a function that has always
been closely linked to national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   In one group of European countries, including Ireland, Spain and
Finland, inflation is creeping up, putting pressure on the central
bank to raise rates. But in another group, including Germany and
France, the economic and political heavyweights at the European
Union's core, inflation is low and unemployment remains stubbornly
high, a combination that argues for stable or even lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This development raises the prospect that, over the next year,
monetary policy will be trapped between the tightening needs of
overheating countries and resistance to higher real rates from
low-inflation ones,'' economists at Salomon Smith Barney said in a
recent report.
</P>
<P>
   The question in the United States is whether the slowdown in
growth is enough to keep inflation under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fed's meeting in May, staff economists presented a
forecast showing that growth would slow this year to around 3.5
percent, from a 5.5 percent rate in the first quarter. But the same
forecast projected that core price inflation _ which excludes
volatile food and energy prices _ would ``rise noticeably'' this
year.
</P>
<P>
   So both inflation hawks and doves at the Fed have plenty of
ammunition as they debate whether to raise rates again. It may be
some consolation to Alan Greenspan as he tries to sort it all out
that his fellow central bankers around the world are not having it
any easier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
