<HEADLINE>
MEXICO HAS VOTED. ITS ECONOMY HASN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a political party that has been in control for many decades
is beaten at the polls, it's a good sign that voters are clamoring
for sweeping change _ and an indication of how much things already
have changed.
</P>
<P>
   That is the case in Mexico, where last week Vicente Fox Quesada
became president-elect, ending 71 years of rule by the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI. Though Mexico
is in far better shape than it was a decade ago, let alone two
decades ago, it is still a developing country.
</P>
<P>
   Investors charged in after the vote, pushing the Bolsa index up
more than 6 percent for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro-Pablo Kuczynski, president of the Latin America Enterprise
fund, a Miami-based private equity fund with about $450 million
under management, took time last week to talk about the effect of
the election on Mexico's market outlook. Following are excerpts
from the conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Q. Isn't the economy that Fox will inherit from the outgoing
president, Ernesto Zedillo, in pretty good shape?
</P>
<P>
   A. Zedillo is leaving him in a good position in terms of foreign
trade. Exports are running between $160 billion and $170 billion
annually, due mostly to increased trade due to the North American
Free Trade Agreement and not to the recent rise in oil prices. As
recently as 1995, following the peso crisis, Mexican exports were
about $80 billion a year. External debt has evaporated as a
macroeconomic issue; it is about $160 billion today, roughly what
it was in 1995. And the budget deficit is totally under control.
However, unemployment is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the new president likely to take steps to push down the
unemployment rate?
</P>
<P>
   A. Due to a lack of flexibility in the budget, he doesn't have
much room to maneuver. After paying for a number of fixed costs,
like debt service and education expenditures, only 7 percent to 10
percent of the budget is left over for discretionary spending.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What sorts of problems does Fox want, or need, to tackle?
</P>
<P>
   A. So far he has talked about focusing on corruption and on
drugs, which are important. He faces big problems in dealing with
safety issues, especially in Mexico City. And the banking system is
still decimated. In Mexico, credit is scarce for midsize companies
and not there at all for little companies. He also faces challenges
from the unions, which are controlled by the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the prospects for privatization?
</P>
<P>
   A. The biggest opportunity is in privatizing the electric
utility industry, which is a $70 billion to $80 billion business,
half in power generation and half in distribution. The major
impediment to change there is the union. It is totally opposed to
privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Because of his years at Coca-Cola and his positive attitude
about foreign investment, doesn't Fox run the risk of criticism
from Mexican nationalists?
</P>
<P>
   A. What Fox has to do, and what he talked about in his campaign,
is show he has a high priority for social welfare programs. That
means better schools, security for people, rural investment and
roads. If he does that, the private investment from the United
States and elsewhere will be more digestible to the people. There
has to be a social dimension to his program. But he won't have the
money to pay for it unless he privatizes the electric utility
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your fund invests in privately held companies. How is the
money divided?
</P>
<P>
   A. About 10 percent is in manufacturing; between 40 percent and
50 percent is in various types of services, from funeral homes to
telephones; and the balance is in an assortment of things, from
financial companies to Internet companies. Roughly 25 percent of
the money in the fund is invested in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Individual investors who have bet on Mexico and Latin America
have not been well rewarded for some time. Is there reason to
expect higher returns?
</P>
<P>
   A. Currently, valuations in Latin America are reasonably low
relative to prospective earnings growth, and that applies with some
force in Mexico. With its finances in pretty good shape, if Mexico
grows 5.5 percent in 2000, its market should do pretty well over
the balance of the year. For example, Cemex and Telefonos de Mexico
will respond to faster growth in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
