<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: GAY UNIONS BILL
</P>
<P>
   The government presented Parliament with a bill to permit ``gay
weddings'' in which same-sex partners could officially register
their relationship and gain the same tax and inheritance rights as
married couples. It could also give foreigners in homosexual
relationships with Germans a right to German residency. The bill
now goes to a parliamentary committee.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: ACQUITTALS IN BORDER SHOOTINGS
</P>
<P>
   Three former members of East Germany's Politburo were acquitted
on manslaughter charges related to the killings of people trying to
defect across the Berlin Wall. The court said it had not been
proved that Siegfried Lorenz and Herbert Haeber, both 69, and
Hans-Joachim Boehme, 70, could have stopped the killings.
Prosecutors said they would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: ANTI-VIOLENCE DEMONSTRATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Several million people in cities across the country marched in
the largest citizen protest against violence in this nation of 175
million, wearing white and organizing silent vigils in an effort to
pressure the government to take a tougher stance against both
criminal gangs and police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: AID DECISION POSTPONED
</P>
<P>
   The European Union has delayed action on a Colombian request for
economic and social assistance to supplement the $1.3 billion in
largely military aid that the United States will be supplying as
part of an effort to curb drug-trafficking and finance a peace deal
with leftist guerrillas. At a donors' meeting in Madrid, Spain, the
United Nations said it would supply $130 million and lending
agencies agreed to kick in $300 million, but the European group
postponed a decision until September.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: ABORTION PILL TESTS
</P>
<P>
   Canada's first clinical trials of RU-486, the French abortion
pill, have started in four cities: Vancouver, Toronto, Quebec City
and Sherbrooke, Quebec. Dr. Ellen Wiebe, the Vancouver doctor who
is directing the study, won a $35,000 government grant to study the
pill's health effects on 1,000 women. She hopes the trial will pave
the way for government approval for the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: CLAMPDOWN ON MARINES
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Marines in Okinawa will not be allowed to drink alcohol
during a summit meeting that President Clinton is scheduled to
attend on the island this month. The alcohol ban comes after the
arrest on Monday of a drunken Marine who police said entered a
private home and molested a 14-year-old girl who was sleeping
there. The Marines will also be required to be in uniform at all
times during the July 20-24 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: OUSTED LEADER'S WIFE HELD
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested dozens of supporters of former Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif in Punjab province in a bid to prevent his wife,
Kulsoom Nawaz, from leading a procession from Lahore to Peshawar.
Punjab officials said that large political rallies are outlawed,
but Kulsoom Nawaz insisted that her march was to support victims of
drought. Sharif was overthrown in an October coup and is serving a
life prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA: MISSILE PROGRAM ON AGENDA
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. assistant secretary of state for nonproliferation,
Robert Einhorn, will visit South Korea next week to discuss Seoul's
attempt to build longer-range missiles, officials said. The United
States and South Korea have held a series of talks over the last
two years about Seoul's wish to increase the range of its missiles,
now set at 112 miles under a 1979 agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
