<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-CORRUPTION-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIA GOVERNMENT ANGRY AT U.S. REPORT ON CRIME AND CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ The Bosnian government bridled
Friday at a report to the U.S. Congress that said crime and
corruption were blocking the success of the Dayton peace accord.
Bosnian officials insisted that the government itself was pursuing
investigations of local government corruption and tackling
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to President Alija Izetbegovic did not deny that
corruption exists among the three ethnic entities in Bosnia, but
defended government efforts to crack down on it. ``Things are being
done _ dozens, even hundreds of cases are being investigated,''
said Mirza Hajric, the adviser. ``The president has made lots of
statements on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, released by the General Accounting Office in
Washington on Friday, blamed the local authorities in Bosnia for
failing to eliminate corruption and build a state of law in the
four years since the war ended. The Dayton peace agreement, which
the GAO report said was being undercut, was signed in December 1995
by Croatia, Yugoslavia and Bosnia's three major ethnic groups as a
framework for rebuilding a self-sustaining multiethnic Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the GAO, the investigative arm of Congress,
suggested that the Clinton administration should consider
suspending its aid until the Bosnian authorities show that they are
committed to fighting the abuses.
</P>
<P>
   But Hajric responded that the Bosnian government had worked to
cooperate with the international bodies and peacekeepers in the
country. ``You would not find one element that we are not
cooperating on, but we are only halfway through a five- year
transition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials, and some of the international officials
working here, stressed that anti-corruption programs depend on
fundamental reforms to the judicial system and law enforcement
bodies. They pointed out that such changes take time and effort,
and need at least several years to take full effect.
</P>
<P>
   They said that while Bosnia had been impoverished by war, it had
also missed out on years of economic and judicial reforms. The
country suffers all the postwar problems of smuggling and organized
crime, as well as the more usual difficulties of a transitional
economy, like failed banks, tax evasion and privatization of state
companies. They said those economic challenges were compounded
tenfold by the deep ethnic divisions that have perpetuated three
separate ethnic entities in one country and have also allowed crime
to thrive.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bosnia's presidency rotates among its three main ethnic groups _
Muslim, Croat and Serb. Two members of the presidency are elected
from the Muslim-Croat Federation and one from Republika Srpska, but
the entities still run almost entirely separate states, including
separate law enforcement bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Office of the High Representative here, the
highest civilian authority in Bosnia, pointed to some successes, or
at least small signs of progress. They particularly noted the
creation of a countrywide customs service that is now working, and
the financial police and prosecutors who are growing steadily more
bold and are starting to work with their counterparts in other
ethnic entities.
</P>
<P>
   They said customs revenues were finally up because officials
were closing loopholes that allowed goods to travel into Bosnia
through one entity with few checks as to its final destination.
Stolen cars, illegal cigarettes and other goods have been arriving
in Bosnia for years with the central government unable to collect
excise duties.
</P>
<P>
   The high representative, Wolfgang Petritsch, stressed that
efforts to combat corruption would work only when there is a
political breakthrough. ``I am convinced it will continue,'' he
said of corruption, ``as long as there are no central state
institutions or the rule of law and while we have not fully broken
the vested interests of the nationalist parties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
