<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6033 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV09-B     07-07 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAINST PURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July   9, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a bold claim, but for my money is the single most
interesting journalist of all the 700-plus highly-talented
reporters on the Wall Street Journal is G. Pascal Zachary.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a few supporting facts. He is the author of
``Showstopper,'' about innovation at Microsoft Corp. (Dave Cutler,
the former Digital Equipment programmer who is the book's
protagonist, last week was named one of Microsoft's first
Distinguished Engineers, akin to an IBM Fellow) and ``Endless
Frontier,'' a biography of Vannevar Bush, the architect of
America's science policy in World War II and after. He is a
contributing editor to the political fortnightly In These Times. He
writes a column for Technology Review as well.
</P>
<P>
   But the chief exhibit is Zachary's new book on diversity. ``The
Global Me: New Cosmopolitans and the Competitive Edge,'' is a
stunning example of inventive reporting. My hunch is that it will
achieve in the Early Twos what George Gilder's ``Wealth and
Poverty'' did for the 1980s -- confidently and clearly set out the
dominant theme of the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Zachary often sounds like Gilder _ in the new book at
least (in the paper his stories are nearly as sober as the rest.)
Gilder's specialty is the tension between entreprenurs and everyone
else. Zachary zeroes in on the more intimate battlefield between
children and their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diversity defines the health and wealth of nations in a new
century,'' he writes. ``Mighty is the mongrel. The mixing of races,
ethnic groups and nationalities-- at home and abroad -- is at a
record level. The hybrid is hip. . .. Mixing is the new norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no passing fashion but a deep change. Say goodbye to
the pure, the straight, the smooth. Forget the original, the
primordial, the one. They are old news, humpty dumpties, shattered
when the walls fell down. No one can put them together again. The
apostles of purity are doomed. Resistence is futile.''
</P>
<P>
   In between the exuberent prose-poetry at the beginning and the
end of the book is a wealth of shrewd reporting about how, in an
increasingly fluid world, people make decisions to affiliate or
not. Zachary visits Ireland, studies Germany, tours the Balkans,
journeys to Mongolia, surveys Japan and drops in on Zurich to show
the increasing power of border-crossers in the global economy.
Virtually no corner of the world remains uncrissed or crossed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact there are few more intimate choices than the decision
which side of the inevitable hyphen of ethnicity on which to live
one's life. Even more private and inexplicable is the subsequent
decision of whom to marry _ inside or out of the relevant tribe?
The effects of these choices go cascading down the generations
through the years.
</P>
<P>
   Until I read ``The Global Me,'' however, it never occurred to me
that that the sum total of all such decisions might have
significant economic implications.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary makes a compelling case that that hybridization is a key
to growth. He draws on the authority of the great historian William
McNeill, who has argued that contact with strangers has always been
the chief engine of historical change. Some extra little bit of
energy accompanies commingling, collision, intermarriage. He quotes
the writer Salman Rushdie to the effect that ``melange, hotchpotch,
a bit of this and a bit of that is how newness enters the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Who is the Global Me? It is Zachary, of course, and every other
half-breed proud to call him or herself mongrel or a mutt. Born in
Brooklyn in TK to a Jewish mother of Polish-Russian ancestry an a
south Italian Catholic father, Zachary studied philosophy at the
State University of New York in Albany, founded a journal, moved to
California to write for the Berkeley Barb, worked his way up a
chain of business publications, married an Irish farm girl and
moved to London.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I asked him about his experiences. ``My years in
California convinced me that radical mixing of peoples works and
raises the bar (creatively) for everyone,'' he replied. ``While the
US as a whole experiences immigration, California experiences it in
a different way, in part because many of the US born natives aren't
native to California. Perhaps we were all newcomers to the state...
</P>
<P>
   ``Even today, when the rest of the US has become a lot more like
California, I still feel the East Coast remains more locked in the
older-style ethnic consciousness, where people feel the fierce need
to defend their group, indeed even to freeze its boundaries. In
California identity is more fluid, and the elements of social
vitality are too.''
</P>
<P>
   Openess to immigration gives the United States its key
advantage, Zachary concludes. Germany is his chief example of ``the
monoculture in retreat.'' No wonder, then, the economy of
California's economy is bigger than that of Germany _ and still
growing by leaps and bounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
