<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6034 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SPORTS-RAGE-BOS &LR;      07-07 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-RAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS RAGE: THE NEW FACE OF VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA THESING  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First there was road rage. Then came air rage. Now, it seems,
the country is experiencing an outbreak of youth sports rage,
sports officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's fatal beating in Massachusetts of a father after he
apparently argued with another father during a pick-up ice hockey
game is the latest and most serious example of violence stemming
from youth sports, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   But across the country there have been a slew of incidents that
sports officials say point to a worrisome trend.
</P>
<P>
   In Amherst, Mass., police arrested two soccer parents for
disorderly conduct and simple assault after the two fought at a
Memorial Day under-12 boys tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In Greensboro, N.C. last year, a mother was charged with assault
after attacking a soccer referee.
</P>
<P>
   And in Maryland last year a father knocked down and kicked a
baseball coach when his son was not chosen for the all-star team.
It could not be determined if charges were filed.
</P>
<P>
   Youth sports officials nationwide say incidents of parental rage
have become so prevalent that Barry Mano, president of the National
Association of Sports Officials, said his group has begun offerring
``assault insurance'' to its 19,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The program provides members who claim they've been assaulted
while officiating games legal advice and offers to pay a portion of
the cost of any medical treatment resulting from attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten so many reports of assualts, we thought that was
an important ingredient,'' said Mano. ``It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by the growing number of parents becoming unruly at
their children's sporting events, some youth leagues are mandating
good sportsmanship seminars for parents.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Jupiter-Tequesta Athletic Assocation in
Florida to adopt such a requirment garnered national attention
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   And in Michigan, a September seminar focusing on good
sportsmanship and aimed at parents, athletic directors and coaches
involved in high school sports sold out after drawing 2,000
participants.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Avitt, national program director for the nonprofit
Parents Alliance for Youth Sports, said her group developed a good
sportsmanship program after being inundated with phone calls from
parents, coaches, and officials concerned about parent behavior at
sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   Too many angry adults setting poor examples for children, she
said are ``totally destroying the concept of what youth sports is
supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The PAYS program, Avitt said, has been adopted by several youth
leagues in communities across the country. She said, the program
has been used by the Billerica (Mass.) Recreation Department and
has involved about 100 parents.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the program is a code of ethics parents are
asked to sign reminding them that sports are for children, not
adults and that the well-being of children is more important than
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Through videos, workbooks and handouts, the program also
encourages youth league parents to create a safe, positive, and fun
environment for children, Avitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Some communities have taken other initiatives to try to keep
parents' enthusiasm from escalating into rowdy behavior. Two months
ago, the Cambridge, Mass. youth soccer league asked parents and
other spectators not to cheer or yell instructions during several
matches between female teams.
</P>
<P>
   The fact youth sport leagues need to sponsor good sportsmanship
programs and take other anti-violence measures is a sad commentary
on the state of sports in America, said Michael S. Josephson,
founder and president of the Josephson Institute of Ethics.
</P>
<P>
   The California-based organization offers seminars and training
for coaches, athletes and parents that stress ethical sports
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that sports is becoming more and more an arena where
people are allowing unrestrained anger and passion to play out,''
Josephson said. ``We don't know how to control violence. We are
more and more moving from sport to spectacle.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he added, if some parents can't control their
behavior then youth league officials will have be under enve more
pressure to combat the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to, as a society, make a real judgment as to how
much of this violence we're going to allow to stay in sports,''
Josephson said. ``If we continue to allow sports to demonstrate the
worst in human nature and we do not demand and require the referees
and officials to control the game, it will get wilder and wilder.''
</P>
<P>
   And the death in Massachusetts may serve as a clarion call among
everyone involved in youth leagues of what can happen when parents
lose sight of the purpose of youth sports, Josephson noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a window to the problem,'' Josephson said. ``We
have to take sport back or it won't be a safe place for any of us
to be or to send our kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
