<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-VENUS0708-COX     07-07 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENUS0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``We came here to win''
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Venus Williams hasn't been shopping in
London yet or sat in the stands watching tennis or even been out to
dinner in the village just up the hill from the All England Club.
</P>
<P>
   She and sister Serena have spent a few Wimbledons playing some
tennis and exploring one of the greatest cities in the world. But
those years, they came with Mom. This year, they begged their
father to come.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams agreed, but only on the condition he get
something in return for overcoming his fear of flying and boarding
an airplane in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted free time spent on tennis, not clothes. He wanted
meals eaten quietly at their rented home a few blocks from the
courts. He wanted shopping minimized. Venus hasn't even had the
cash to buy a newspaper, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to win,'' Richard Williams said. ``We didn't come this
far to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why he brought two players. One went down in the
semifinals, of course, when fifth seed Venus defeated eighth seed
Serena 6-2, 7-6 (7-3) in the semifinals Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But now Venus can make history.
</P>
<P>
   If she wins her first Grand Slam title at the most prestigious
and most traditional tournament in the world, she will become just
the second black woman to win Wimbledon since the championships
began in 1884.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow American Althea Gibson won in 1957 and 1958, but just one
other black woman has even reached the final since. Martina
Navratilova beat Zina Garrison in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been so few black people to win Wimbledon or even
just play outstanding tennis,'' Venus said. ``Hopefully there will
be more. Naturally, we're going to do our best to change that. We
already have.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams couldn't agree more. He signed more autographs
and posed for more pictures with fans Friday afternoon at the All
England Club after his daughters defeated Anna Kournikova and
Natasha Zvereva 6-3, 7-6 (z-z) to reach their first Wimbledon
doubles final.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he talked with reporters but wouldn't discuss his
feelings ``if'' Venus makes history by defeating second seed
Lindsay Davenport or ``if'' she and Serena defeat Julie
Halard-Decugis and Ai Sugiyama for the doubles title, also making
history as the first all-black team to win Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the problems I've seen a long time ago when
people my color talk about ``if'' this happens,'' Richard Williams
said. ``We're here to make things happen. We're here to set any
kind of history for anyone that wants to see history. Althea Gibson
won the singles here and we're here to follow in the footsteps that
she laid.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're not (saying) if Venus wins, if this happens,'' he
said. ``It's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Serena tries to put aside her bad feelings at her own
loss to cheer for her sister.
</P>
<P>
   She insists that won't be difficult. The sisters watched a movie
together Thursday night and didn't even talk tennis, they said.
Serena did plan, however, to give Venus some confidential advice
about Davenport and a few words about handling a final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just (tell her) not to get too much caught up in the moment
of, `I'm in the final of Wimbledon,' '' Serena said. ``Just got to
relax, go out there and perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams also reports that the hard work is over. He
expects to return to the friends box today after avoiding his
daughters' head-to-head matchup. That would have been too painful
to watch, he said, but he promises today will be joyful for
Compton, Palm Beach Gardens and for Williams fans everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our party,'' he said. ``We came here to win, and we
didn't invite no one to come play at this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport might disagree. She was the one who knew for almost
365 days that, as the defending champion, she would play her
first-round match this year at 2 p.m. Tuesday, June 27, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Californian has won all three previous Grand
Slam finals she's reached and has won nine of her 12 meetings with
Venus. But they've split the past four matches, with Davenport
winning most recently in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times I found the key was find a way to get her serve
back deep so she doesn't have put-away shots,'' said Davenport,
whose ranking will not budge from No.2 win or lose. ``You've got to
not let her step inside the baseline and hit because she hits so
hard that on grass they might be hard to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus has played in just one Grand Slam final, the 1997 U.S.
Open, which she lost to Martina Hingis. It was her first U.S. Open
but she made a splashy run in New York with her beaded hair and
long limbs flying.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing will be the same as that day, Venus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my third Grand Slam. I wasn't even full time on the
tour,'' she said, smiling at the memory. ``I didn't understand any
strategy, as far as you're down break point, maybe you should get
your first serve in. Things like that never came to my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, few thought it would take the young player with the huge
serve and powerful groundstrokes nearly three years to return to a
Grand Slam final. But she needed to learn strategy, refine her
strokes, harness her power and, most importantly, correct her
often-streaky mental game.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's reading the ball very well and she's hitting and moving,
which is a big difference,'' said E.T. Dumas, a coach who has
worked with the sisters off and on for 10 years. ``Instead of
hitting and seeing what she's doing and then reacting, she's
hitting and moving right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams believes Venus is overdue for her Grand Slam
title, and he seemed eager Friday for the trophy to be firmly in
the Williamses' grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for a certainty when Venus learns how easy it is to
win a Grand Slam when she walks on that court, she'll be winning
just like that on and on for a while,'' he said. ``(But) I won't
say she's going to win all of them that Serena's in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
