<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-WIMMEN0708-COX     07-07 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMMEN0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rafter's upset of Agassi proves he's back in the game
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Even if he doesn't win on Sunday, the agony
is over for Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't sure the uncertainty, pain and disappointment created
by tearing the right rotator cuff in his serving shoulder last year
would ever end. He didn't know if his aggressive serve-and-volley
game would ever return and even if it did, he had no idea if it
would be successful.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, all those concerns and questions melted away for the
27-year-old Australian. It happened with a convincing upset of
second seed Andre Agassi in the semifinals of Wimbledon. It was an
intriguing match that Rafter won 7-5, 4-6, 7-5, 4-6, 6-3 in 3
hours, 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long road back,'' Rafter said. ``That's the most
satisfying part about it. Now I'm back in the final. It has been
probably a big shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, who served 18 aces and won 35 points with volleys, will
play top seed Pete Sampras in Sunday's final. Sampras needed a
trainer once during his match against Vladimir Voltchkov but didn't
appeared slowed by the left shin injury he's had since the second
round, winning 7-6 (7-4), 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit unexpected for me, a little bit probably for
everyone else in the locker room, as well,'' Rafter said. ``I've
showed no real signs of coming back very well after the shoulder
surgery. It's very satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the 1997 and 1998 U.S. Open champion lost in
straight sets to Agassi in the Wimbledon semifinals. Rafter came
off the court angry with himself, although this year he recalled it
as a satisfying loss.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months later, the twinges started in his shoulder.
By the U.S. Open, the pain forced him to retire from his
first-round match against Cedric Pioline. On Oct. 24, he had
arthroscopic surgery to repair the rotator cuff and he missed the
rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the tour in February in Delray Beach but played
sparingly and not very well in the months following. Doctors told
him ``there are only so many serves left in your arm.'' They
instructed him to decide whether to use them in practice or in
matches. That information weighed on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't finished and decided to practice his serve until
he was happy with it, disregarding doctors' advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't last that long, it doesn't last very long,'' he
told himself. ``That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he won a small tournament last week in the Netherlands.
And he won a round at Wimbledon and his hopes the shoulder would
really be ready this fortnight seemed to be coming true.
</P>
<P>
   He played stunning tennis against Agassi, taking advantage of
Agassi's eight ill-timed double faults and a few careless shots.
After the two exchanged the first four sets, the fifth seemed like
a fresh slate for Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   But Rafter served to start the set, as he did all five, and
Agassi felt like he was in a hole from the beginning. Down 2-3, he
double faulted to fall behind 30-40. Rafter hit an overhead that
Agassi reached but put into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter got the service break and didn't lose another point on
his serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like at the biggest moments of each set, he
continued to execute and I fell off a little bit,'' Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't appreciate the exciting match for its level of
tennis and drama, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no objectivity on that right now,'' he said. ``As far
as I'm concerned, the match sucked.''
</P>
<P>
   Voltchov, the 22-year-old qualifier from Belarus, also lost but
had an entirely different perspective. It was his first match on
Centre Court, first against Sampras and it carried a badly needed
$193,000 paycheck, even though he lost.
</P>
<P>
   He also didn't play badly. He kept the world's best grass court
player on serve for the first set, losing only after a
heartbreaking error at 4-5 in the tiebreaker. Voltchkov hit two
perfect backhands to get the easy volley from Sampras but hit it
into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot about it,'' he said. ``I guess these things are
decided somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he moves on to Davis Cup in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good run for me here,'' he said. ``I'm actually
pretty satisfied with the way the match went today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter also was satisfied. He hopes never to lose the feeling
that his post-injury tennis is ``a bonus thing,'' but he wants to
remain competitive. He knows it's all up to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're out there struggling, you've got to do it
yourself,'' he said. ``No one can tell you. No one can tell me. I'm
too bloody stubborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
