<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HOCKEYDADS-DEATH-BOS &LR;      07-07 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEYDADS-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT AFTER YOUTH HOCKEY EVENT LEADS TO FATHER'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT AND IEVA AUGSTUMS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   READING, Mass. _ A father of four who was beaten unconscious
Wednesday by another father at an ice rink here was pronounced dead
Friday, turning a merely ugly event into perhaps the most grisly
incident to date in a nationwide wave of parental violence at youth
sports events.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas F. Junta, 42, of Reading, so far faces misdemeanor
assault charges, but Middlesex County District Attorney Martha
Coakley said in a news conference that the case is being considered
a ``possible homicide'' pending an autopsy this morning.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier interview, Reading Police Chief Edward Marchand
said Junta attacked the victim, Michael Costin, 40, of Lynnfield,
after an informal youth hockey skate-around at the Burbank Ice
Arena, during which the men traded insults and argued about the
childrens' rowdy behavior.
</P>
<P>
   While those who knew him described Costin as easy-going and
affable, police records obtained Friday show he had been sent to
prison several times in the 1980s and 1990s for a host of crimes,
including assaulting police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley was reluctant to say who may have instigated the fatal
fight.
</P>
<P>
   According to Marchand, verbal sparring between Junta, who was in
the stands, and Costin, who was on the ice monitoring the
youngsters, resulted in a brief, off-ice shoving match after the
practice. But after a rink employee ordered Junta to leave the
building, the 6-foot-2, 275-pound Junta alledegly returned and
knocked Costin to the ground, Marchand said.
</P>
<P>
   As Costin, described as 5-feet-11 and 170 pounds, lay there,
Junta allegedly sank his knee into the fallen father's chest, and
began ``whacking'' Costin in the face and beating his head into the
floor, Marchand said.
</P>
<P>
   Junta ``was doing a job on him, whacking him... and slapping his
head on the floor,'' Marchand said, adding that 14 to 20 children
were at the practice, but it was unclear how many witnessed the
altercation. When police officers arrived at the rink, Costin was
unconscious and had no pulse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at the Lahey Medical Clinic pronounced Costin brain dead
early Thursday, keeping him on a ventilator until Friday. Costin's
father, Augustine M. Costin, said that when relatives went to see
their injured kin, he was ``unrecognizable.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials and residents in Reading, a community of 23,000, many
devoted to youth hockey _ were stunned by Costin's death, saying
they never imagined parental zeal could ever go so far.
</P>
<P>
   The Burbank Ice Arena, they said, often serves as a frigid town
common. High school hockey games fill the 1,000-seat rink to
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big hockey town, but sometimes in Reading, we don't
think we are part of the world,'' said Town Manager Peter I.
Hechenbleikner. ``We are.''
</P>
<P>
   Hechenbleikner and town Health Services Administrator Jane M.
Fiore will host a meeting Saturday at which clergy, police, and
mental health workers will offer counseling to anyone shaken by the
violent episode.
</P>
<P>
   In Lynnfield, neighbors of Costin, a single father, said they
were appalled that a man they described as shy, gentle, religious,
and utterly devoted to his children could die such a violent death.
</P>
<P>
   Jack McDonald, whose children often spent time with Costin, his
three sons and one daughter, said Costin was the most unlikely
candidate he could imagine to engage in a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a great dad and a real gentleman,'' McDonald said.
``To have this happen to him is unbeleievable to everyone who knows
him. You get an image of parents who are real rah-rah about their
kids' activities, but he's a guy you'd never hear a peep out of. I
used to marvel at his parental diligence.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Costin was a dedicated parent who regularly ferried his
children to Sunday Mass at Our Lady of the Assumption Roman
Catholic Church, he was also a man with a dark, even violent side,
records show.
</P>
<P>
   According to the state's Criminal Offender Registry, Costin was
sent to prison seven times between 1983 and 1995, spending anywhere
from 30 days to 15 months behind bars at a time. His crimes, the
Registry states, ranged from assaulting police officers to drunken
driving to breaking-and-entering with a loaded, unlicensed firearm.
</P>
<P>
   Junta _ who has no criminal record, according to the Registry _
was also described by those who know him as a parent with fierce
devotion to his children and their budding sports careers. Junta's
16-year-old daughter is a key player on the Reading High School
Rockets, the school's girls hockey team, which was formed last
year, thanks in large part to the hard work of Junta's wife,
Michelle.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Still, spokesman for the National Association of Sports
Officials, a Wisconsin organization that represents 19,000 umpires
and referees, said his organization receives at least two reports a
week of physical assaults on referees and umpires by parents. The
problem, he said, was virtually non-existent 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Wolff, a New York sports psychologist and author of
``Coaching Kids For Dummies,'' said parents have grown increasingly
involved and occasionally violent at children's sports events, but
despite that, he said he was unaware of any incident that had ended
in death.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who have been seriously injured,
absolutely,'' Wolff said. ``Over the years, people have fired
shots, brandished knives, brandished guns, thrown punches, but I
don't ever recall any fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the sad part is,'' he continued, ``it's not surprising. It
has become a national epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts have floated several theories to explain the increased
violence, rage, and aggression parents have become to exhibit at
their children's games.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the problem is just another form of road rage, or the
newer ``air rage'' that flight attendants and pilots protested on
Thursday across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of this ahs to do with college sports
scholarships,'' Still said. ``Everyone is pushing for their kid to
be a star athlete so they can get their kid a free ride to school.
A referee's call that hurts their kid is actually worth money to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still also sees increased time-constraints on working parents as
a potential cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents don't have time to go out in the yard and practice
with their kids anymore, so the games are the only involvement they
have,'' Still, who was confronted by an angry father at a high
school baseball game in Racine, Wisc., earlier this week, said.
``Winning becomes everything at that point. That's all they have
left.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe staff reporter Rahael Lewis contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
