<HEADER>
A6051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CAR-IRWIN-SIDE-COX     07-07 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWIN-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio residents remember Kenny Irwin
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Kenny Irwin's death happened miles away at New
Hampshire International Speedway on Friday, but its impact was felt
in Ohio, where Irwin had touched many lives.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton native and racing legend Mack McClellan met Irwin in 1991
and immediately liked what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   Polite. A bit shy. A race driver with a golden future. Those
were McClellan's first impressions. His second and more lasting
impression developed a year later when McClellan was hospitalized
in Indianapolis, broken up from a sprint-car race wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came and visited me in the hospital the whole time I was
there,'' McClellan said. ``He was a really nice person. We were
friends more than anything else. He was a little on the bashful
side, but he was very aggressive on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   McClellan remembered Irwin on Friday in wake of his tragic death
after crashing during practice before qualifying for Sunday's race
for a NASCAR Winston Cup race the New England 300. Irwin, 30, of
Indianapolis, was killed just yards from where another stock-car
racer, 19-year-old Adam Petty, crashed and died two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, the 1998 Winston Cup rookie of the year, was entering
Turn 3 when his stock car crashed into the wall and flipped upside
down. He was taken to Concord Hospital, where he died.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third auto-racing related death in two months.
Besides Irwin and Petty, Scott Baker of Holland, Mich., was killed
during an ARCA race June 23 in Toledo. Sam Schmidt was paralyzed in
January after crashing his open-wheel race car during testing at
Walt Disney World Speedway in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin's death also will be deeply felt by Johnny Vance, owner of
Aristocrat Products in Dayton. Irwin drove for Vance's sprint-car
team in the early 1990s and the two forged a father-son
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Vance was too upset to comment when reached by phone Friday, but
in April he talked about how proud he was of Irwin. He didn't need
to say a word. His mementos and photos of Irwin behind his desk
spoke volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Irwin had moved on to NASCAR racing, he always kept
in touch with Vance, always sought his advice. And whenever he
could, he spent the night at Vance's house.
</P>
<P>
   He visited in April to see a Reds game with Vance's son and to
help around Vance's garage.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was always at home at Aristocrat, tinkering with one of
Vance's sprint cars. In April, he was doing just that but stopped
working on the car for a few moments to talk about his relationship
with Vance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Johnny are good friends,'' Irwin said. ``It's a little
of that (father-son). I talk to him about stuff I talk to my dad
about. But we're friends, too. We go on vacations together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to him about what's going on in my life. I confide in
him a lot. He's helped me more than anybody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Vance, McClellan offered Irwin advice, but his always
centered on racing. Irwin already knew several tricks of the trade.
McClellan was so impressed with Irwin's racing skills, he groomed
him as a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he'd be a star and he proved that,'' McClellan said.
``This is so unbelievable. Kenny was just a great young man. He was
quite a bit younger than me. He was more like a younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I taught him some different things, different aspects on how
to drive a car. He was certainly talented. I can't image this.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Lance at davelance(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
