<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-CONTROVERSY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIGRANTS' DROWNINGS CAUSE TENSION ALONG THE RIO GRANDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MATAMOROS, Mexico _ For one brief moment last month, Walter
Maria Sandoval and Jose Antonio Ramirez made it across the Rio
Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Both had traveled hundreds of miles to get there. Sandoval had
come from the arid lands of central Michoacan state. Ramirez
journeyed from a small town in the southern coastal state of
Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
   But their victory would be fleeting, and fatal. Shortly after
reaching the tall grass on the Texas side of the river, both men
started paddling back to Mexico, fleeing the watchful US Border
Patrol agents who would have detained them and sent them back.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man made it. Caught in an unexpected undertow, Sandoval
and Ramirez drowned while officers on both riverbanks watched. The
agonizing scene was recorded by a television crew and shown hours
later on a Mexican nightly newscast.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were not the only migrants to die trying to cross
the border. Theirs was not even the most recent case.
</P>
<P>
   But the televised drownings have heightened tensions here over
the growing number of migrants who die while attempting
ever-riskier crossings into the United States by land and water. US
figures show that already this year there have been 238
crossing-related deaths, compared to 161 all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you hear now is stories about immigrants drowning in the
river or dying in the desert,'' said Candido Molina, a 23-year-old
father of three who sat one morning last week on the Matamoros side
pondering whether he should swim across the Rio Grande to
neighboring Brownsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for ms in both the US and Mexico attribute the higher
number of deaths to changes in US border enforcement tactics that
have sealed many of the well-known crossing points and forced
desperate migrants to cross over snowy mountains, across sun-baked
deserts, and through swirling rivers.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the Sandoval and Ramirez deaths, US Immigration
and Naturalization officials announced new training programs in
live-saving techniques for Border Patrol officers along the Rio
Grande.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protecting our borders includes an obligation to protect
lives,'' INS Commissioner Doris Meissner said in announcing the
program in Washington two weeks ago. She added that despite having
rescued more than 2,000 migrants in the two years since the tougher
enforcement measures were put into place, ``we will redouble our
security efforts, because one death is too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's president-elect, Vicente Fox Quesada, who won Sunday in
a historic vote that unseated the ruling party after 71 years in
power, has criticized the intensive US enforcement along the
border. He said he favors a policy of more ``open flow'' of
immigrants between the US and Mexico to cut down on violence
against them.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than just a matter of Mother Nature or Washington
policies, activists say. Drug traffickers, illegal smugglers, and
even American ranchers have contributed to an increasing level of
violence against the migrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object of these policies is to move the migrants to more
dangerous places,'' said Arturio Solis, president of the Center for
Border Studies and Human Rights, a nonprofit research and advocacy
group based in Reynosa. ``But it has also put them more vulnerable
to violence by people who either abandon them, no longer need them,
or want them off their property.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the US estimate of 238 deaths, which is considered
conservative because it only counts migrants who die in the act of
reaching US soil, Solis said more than 300 have died this year
trying to cross _ 75 of them along the southern tip of the Rio
Grande.
</P>
<P>
   On May 12, in its largest catch ever in this region, Mexican
immigration officials in Matamoros found 309 Central American
migrants hiding in four tractor trailer trucks. Although all were
alive _ unlike the 58 Chinese migrants whose corpses were
discovered two weeks ago in Britain _ several were suffering from
dehydration and infections of untreated injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the concern about violence against migrants has focused
on an area of southern Arizona, where despite the threats of
poisonous snakes, treacherous desert terrain, and 100-degree
temperatures, illegal crossings have risen sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona border, which is less populated than in California
or Texas and has fewer agents on patrol, recorded more than 470,000
detentions in fiscal year 1999, making it the busiest point for
illegal crossings along the 2,000-mile border.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the stream of migrants trampling through private
property on their cross-border dash, a small group of Arizona
ranchers has taken to rounding them up at gunpoint and holding them
until authorities arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials have publicly denounced such activity as
``migrant hunting'' and complained formally to Washington. Over the
last several weeks, Mexico has also reassigned dozens of federal
police as agents of the new Mexican Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with patrol cars and uniforms, the officers will be
responsible for searching for and detaining smugglers, criminals
who assault migrants, and non-Mexican citizens trying to cross
illegally into the US. Critics, like Solis, say the organization is
a poor imitation of its US counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   The officers will work closely with Grupo Beta, a Mexican
migrant assistance group made up of police from local, state, and
federal agencies whose job is to warn migrants of the dangers of
crossing. By law, however, it cannot detain them.
</P>
<P>
   The Matamoros sector of Grupo Beta came under intense criticism
when it emerged that the two agents who tried to rescue Sandoval
and Ramirez didn't know how to swim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work so hard to help migrants with food, medicine or even
rides home if they decide not to cross,'' said Maria de la Paz
Reyes, the sector director, during her daily 30-mile sweep along
the dusty banks of the Rio Grande in her four-wheel drive. ``Every
death is a setback for us. But we try to warn people: Be careful.
That river is a traitor for a lot of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
