<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-LINCOLN-COTTAGE-BOS &LR;      07-07 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-COTTAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$1.1 MILLION ALLOCATED TO RENOVATE LINCOLN COTTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER WALSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The rundown summer cottage where President Lincoln
wrote a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation was declared a
national monument Friday by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Anderson Cottage, relatively unknown and tucked away in
the northwest corner of the city, Clinton made use of the
Antiquities Act to designate the 158-year-old landmark the
President Lincoln and Soldiers' Home National Monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year more than a million people visited Ford's Theater
alone, but barely 100 made it here to Anderson Cottage, where
Lincoln lived and worked,'' said Clinton. ``In some ways, this
cottage behind me is the most important, as well as the least
known, Lincoln site in the entire United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said $1.1 million has been raised for the renovations,
including a $750,000 matching funds grant from Save America's
Treasures, a public-private partnership between the White House
Millennium Council and the National Trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cottage in its way is just as precious as a giant
sequoia, as irreplaceable as the ruins of cultures long past, and
it is our profound obligation to preserve and protect it for future
generations,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes less than two weeks after the National
Trust for Historic Preservation put the cottage at the top of this
year's list of historical sites in danger of demolition or
deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Moe, president of the National Trust, said, ``At a time
when understanding of American history is at an abysmal level, we
need sites like this more than ever to convey an appreciation of
how we got to be the nation we are.''
</P>
<P>
   As Civil War battles loomed, the hilltop cottage essentially
served as Lincoln's Camp David, where he would retreat from the
heat of the city and the stress of day-to-day operations. The
cottage, built in 1842, was located on the grounds of what was
known then as the Soldiers' Home, the first home for disabled
veterans of the US Army.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-room Gothic revival cottage, where Lincoln spent about a
quarter of his presidency, is in desperate need of renovation with
water damage, rotting wooden window frames, and aging electrical
and plumbing systems. Restoration is expected to start next year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to preserving Lincoln's retreat, Clinton announced
another $15 million in grants from Save America's Treasures for
preserving 47 historic sites and collections nationwide, including
the USS Missouri, where the Japanese formally surrendered to end
World War II, and Babe Ruth's scrapbooks at the National Baseball
Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts sites to receive grants include the Orchard House,
the family home of author Louisa May Alcott in Concord; the
Colonial Theater in Pittsfield; and the American Antiquarian
Society Library in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   Refurnishing the 14-room cottage may be difficult since Lincoln
would move the family's belongings to the summer home in May and
take them back to the White House in November, said Nick Minecci,
spokesman for the cottage and an amateur historian who has done
extensive research on Lincoln's stay there.
</P>
<P>
   Office furniture and equipment for the public affairs department
of the soldiers' home now occupy many of the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was the first president to visit the site since
President Chester A. Arthur more than 100 years ago. Presidents
Franklin Pierce, James Buchanan, Ulysses S. Grant and Rutherford B.
Hayes also used the cottage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's tour Friday was reminiscent of the summer days between
1862 and 1864 when Lincoln roamed the grounds just three miles away
from the White House. Clinton walked the same staircase that
Lincoln would take to retreat to the corner bedroom where he
drafted the famous proclamation that ended slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can still feel that spirit strongly in the room in this
cottage where he worked,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also stood in the cool shade under the copper
beech tree where Lincoln would spend time playing with his son,
reading, or writing correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it is three centuries old, it is our last living link
to Abraham Lincoln,'' Clinton said of the tree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6063 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-RACE-COPS-DRUGS-ABRID     07-07 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-COPS-DRUGS-ABRIDGED-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: to do.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAME SHOW, Nth PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   Narcotics enforcement is a frustrating cat-and-mouse game
between officers and dealers who, after years of crackdowns, are
savvy about dividing and concealing each step of the operation.
Rarely do the police get the drugs, the money and the dealer
together. Repeatedly Brogli's team arrests dealers and, the next
day, standing in that very spot, there is someone else _ or even
the same person.
</P>
<P>
   On these streets, dark-skinned man are often stopped,
questioned, then let go. On May 4, Simonetti's team searched 601 W.
141st St., Apartment 41. As several officers entered the apartment,
others detained 15 men standing on the nearby corner of 141st and
Broadway. Inside the apartment, the cops reported a rare trifecta:
they seized 1.5 kilos of cocaine and about $3,000, and arrested an
18-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
   Outside on the street, the police lined up the detained men
against a wall to see if any had keys to Apartment 41. Sometimes
this works; a few weeks before, on the same block, they caught two
dealers this way. This time no one had a matching key. One man had
a small amount of coke and was arrested; a second had $2,000 in
cash and a Kenwood two-way radio. There was another Kenwood inside
the apartment, but the frequency didn't match. He and the other 14
were let go after half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   As the police searched the men, a mainly Dominican crowd
gathered, joking with the cops. Pointing at the men on the corner,
a young woman called out, ``Why are you bothering them? They're
just working,'' and the crowd and cops shared a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But public reaction makes sometimes narcotics officers feel
bitter, as if it were the 1920s and they were reliving Prohibition.
``Everyone sees this is a joke,'' said Jason, an undercover. ``They
know we ain't putting no dent in drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. James Byrne, who oversees Brogli's team, says the only
answer is legalizing drugs. ``In my humble opinion, we're doing
nothing up here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   THERE GOES THE NEIGHBORHOOD
</P>
<P>
   It's supposedly common knowledge: black New Yorkers distrust the
police. But on the streets where Brogli works, the police's biggest
supporters are African-American. In the last 15 years, this
neighborhood may have changed from primarily African-American to
Dominican, but the citizens council that meets monthly at the local
precinct, the 30th, dominated by African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   At council meetings it is mainly black residents who attend to
ask for  &UR; more &LR;  police enforcement,  &UR; more &LR;  drug arrests, who want
 &UR; more &LR;  people jailed for loitering and trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   Detective John Montes, a Hispanic cop who walked a beat for two
years before joining Brogli's team, says his best informers here
were black. On these streets, the African-Americans are frequently
the older, better-established families, who moved here in the
1950s. Many are middle-class government workers, small-business
owners and professionals, and often they are resentful that Spanish
is now the primary language spoken in the Broadway shops; that
able-bodied Dominican men line the sidewalks all hours of the day;
and that the police consider the neighborhood drug trade,
controlled by Dominicans, the worst in the city.
</P>
<P>
   At a 30th Precinct meeting, an African-American homeowner asked
that the police do loitering sweeps, calling in the National Guard
if necessary. The woman, a single professional with a master's
degree, complained in an interview about the Dominicans: ``They
hang out on the corners _ they have so many children. When I go
into one of their stores, I try to line up to buy something the
American way, but it's all chaos, the Dominican customers all
milling, they don't know how to go in order.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dozen interviews in their homes, African-Americans
complained about Dominicans ruining the neighborhood, sounding very
much like the Jews and Italians who once dominated this area and
began leaving 40 years ago, complaining about the blacks moving in.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone at headquarters has a racial or ethnic identity and
gets needled about it. But the one slur rarely spoken is
``nigger.'' In a year's time, a reporter did not hear it. Whether
that was because, as Brogli says, this generation has been
conditioned against it, or because, as Derrick, a black undercover,
says, racial animosity still runs too deep to joke about the word,
it seemed off limits.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, in these streets where most people arrested
for drugs are Dominican, it's open season on ``Domos.'' Many are
from poor, rural parts of their Caribbean island, where
record-keeping isn't precise, and officers making arrests jokingly
wonder if the Domo will know his birth date.
</P>
<P>
   OUT WITH PREJUDICE
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when Gonzalez was on uniformed housing patrol in Red
Hook, Brooklyn, white officers couldn't tell what he was by looking
at him and were guarded until reading his name tag. ``Then they'd
say, `Oh, you're Gonzalez _ these blacks, aren't they like animals
with all their kids?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm in a Dominican neighborhood,'' he said. ``I'll hear
some sergeant, not knowing I'm around, talking about Domos this,
Domos that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a white cop ask me, `How many in your family are drug
dealers?''' said Gonzalez, who doesn't drink alcohol. ``I told him,
in my family, nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   If the police can be too quick to label, Gonzalez says, they are
only reflecting society.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm afternoon, dressed as usual in plain clothes, he met
downtown with a prosecutor about a case, then stopped in a deli
near Chinatown for an iced tea. One sip and he nearly spit it out.
He knew immediately it was the extra-sweet tea that heroin addicts
on methadone often crave. ``Sorry,'' said the Asian woman behind
the counter, exchanging the drink. ``This is junkie iced tea.''
</P>
<P>
   An honest mistake? Or had she assumed he was a junkie from a
nearby methadone clinic because he is brown-skinned?
</P>
<P>
   You could go crazy trying to get to the bottom of every slight,
says Gonzalez, and he doesn't bother. He is an upbeat family man.
His view of the narcotics officers he deals with each day:
``There's not that much prejudice in the room.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
