<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LATIN-FORUM0708-COX     07-07 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-FORUM0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latinos cooling toward governor, want results
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Expectations were high in parts of the Latino
community six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Four people appointed by Gov. Roy Barnes were recommending
changes to state laws and policies to help Georgia's growing Latino
population. They held a news conference to give their report to the
governor, but his staff said Barnes was too busy to attend.
</P>
<P>
   His absence frustrated some Latinos. Now some Hispanics are more
frustrated because not much has become of recommendations made by
the Latino Forum that Barnes appointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very disappointed. They are saying `Like always,
they tell us something but nothing is done,' '' said Teodoro Maus,
the Mexican consul general for Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   It's a different story in North Carolina, another state with a
fast-growing Hispanic population where thousands of Latinos work in
construction, poultry, agriculture and hotels and restaurants as
they do in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of Georgia's Hispanic population range from 220,000 to
480,000. The U.S. Census Bureau says the state's Hispanic
population increased 102 percent from 1990-98. North Carolina's
Hispanic population went up 110 percent in that time.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Hunt of North Carolina, a conservative Democrat like
Barnes, was instrumental in 1998 in creating a state office for
Latino issues and an advisory council of 15 Hispanic community
leaders and 10 top state officials, such as the commissioner of the
division of motor vehicles and the superintendent of public
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   The community leaders and state officials meet every two months
and meet with the governor once a year, said H. Nolo Martinez,
director of the Office of Hispanic/Latino Affairs, part of the
governor's office. He said council meetings have provided ``an
amazing opportunity for us to do things quickly.'' Martinez's
office has arranged Spanish classes for about a dozen members of
the governor's staff and helped set up a bilingual hotline during
Hurricane Floyd last year. It also lobbied successfully to persuade
legislators to change a law requiring people to show a Social
Security number to get married.
</P>
<P>
   Also, meetings with Latino leaders and state officials before
Hunt created the council prompted North Carolina to let illegal
immigrants get driver's licenses, something Georgia's Latino Forum
has suggested here. Applicants for a Georgia license have had to
show proof of U.S. citizenship or legal residency since 1994, but
Latino advocates say licensing illegal immigrants would teach them
the rules of the road and let them buy auto insurance. Opponents
say illegal immigrants could use a license to access other
services.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes does not support giving driver's licenses to illegal
immigrants, said Howard Mead, a spokesman. ``If someone is in the
United States illegally, they should not be able to get a driver's
license,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver's license issue _ and an arrangement like the one in
North Carolina _ is what Winston Garcia had in mind last month when
his Spanish-language newspaper, Nuestro Semanario (Our Weekly), ran
an editorial saying, ``the time has come for Gov. Barnes to
implement the proposals'' of the Latino Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia remembers the day the forum delivered its report. During
the news conference on the steps of the state Capitol, he asked
members of the forum what would happen if they deliver the report
and nothing happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer was `That's a good question,' '' Garcia said.
``Perhaps it was a good question, but I'm still waiting for the
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Latino Forum and a spokeswoman for the governor
say changes are on the way. Among them: Barnes plans to create a
permanent council to advise him on Hispanic issues _ something the
forum recommended.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly a priority for him,'' said Joseyln Butler,
spokeswoman for Barnes. ``It is one of a number of important issues
to which he is now able to turn his attention.'' She said he hasn't
decided whether to push for it as a state office or an advisory
council.
</P>
<P>
   At least 21 states and Washington D.C. have created offices or
councils dedicated to Hispanic issues. In six of the states,
according to the census, Hispanics make up a lower percentage of
the state population than in Georgia _ Iowa, Michigan, Minnesota,
North Carolina, Ohio and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some Latino leaders plan to meet with state
legislators this fall, said Sam Zamarripa, a businessman who was on
the Latino Forum and is chairman of metro Atlanta's Latin American
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to find legislators willing to introduce bills to
make some of the forum's proposals a reality. ``I think that we
will have a legislative group organized this year,'' he said. ``Am
I hopeful? You bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Maus has met with the governor, lieutenant governor, attorney
general and other top officials since the forum's report, but said
he is frustrated that nothing concrete has happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking to people, they're all very sensitive,
they're all very concerned,'' he said, but ``you go away, and
basically nothing happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Genie Pascual, chairwoman of the Latino Forum, said timing was
one reason the Legislature did not debate the forum's proposals.
The forum presented its report well into the legislative session.
The governor and legislators were consumed with Barnes' massive
education reform bill and other measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very hopeful that something will come out of it,'' she
said. ``Nothing happens very quickly in the government realm.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
