<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-BACKLASH-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BINGE ON MUSIC AT STATE U. 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By MATT RICHTEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ College students who share their music files
on the Internet have been accused of stealing copyrighted works, or
at least of exhibiting questionable morality. Ask the students in a
liberal college town like this one and they will beg to differ. The
dark truth, they say, is that they've been driven to Napster or
Scour Exchange by a global conspiracy arrayed against them.
</P>
<P>
   By the tens of thousands, they have joined services like these,
through which they can get new music free, rather than having to go
to the record store _ which would entail the nasty hurdle of having
to pay money. But the real reason they're sharing files, they say,
is that they've been forced to.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for someone to blame, blame the
universities,'' said Amna Suharwardy, 19, who attended summer
classes at the University of California at Berkeley. Her point is
that the universities give students high-speed Internet connections
that make it so easy to download free music that they'd be
inexcusably dense not to take the bait.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to the conspiracy than just the enablers in
the administration building. The students say the record industry
itself is driving them to subversion.
</P>
<P>
   Stephan Goyne, 24, a new graduate of the University of
California at Santa Cruz, said he had seen through the industry's
clever little ruse: greedy record companies have been trying to
make money. He has taken to Napster to fight back. ``Music should
be made for the sake of music _ it should be free,'' said Goyne,
24, who specifically wants to liberate the music of Willie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   He's not an extremist, mind you. For him, the principle of
people sharing stuff has limits. ``No, you can't have my shoes,''
he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Napster users generally agree with him on the limits thing, but
the difference with music is that it's, well, music, and charging
money for Metallica's ``Kill 'Em All'' is like depriving them of a
basic human need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on _ $15? Some people can't afford a CD,'' said Mario
Garcia, a Berkeley junior who uses Napster to download tracks of
Metallica and Rage Against the Machine. He would be willing to pay
for the music if he had a job, but that would turn the priorities
of a modern society on their head. ``What do they want more _ for
me to have a job and money, or stay in school?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could borrow my toaster, but only if you return
it,'' he added, walking away briskly, careful not to turn his back.
</P>
<P>
   On Telegraph Avenue, John Vance, a Napster user, runs the ``1st
Amendment Center'' _ several portable shelves from which he sells
bumper stickers like ``Robin Hood Was Right'' and ``I Do Whatever
My Rice Krispies Tell Me to Do.'' Vance, 57, said it was
unfortunate that Napster users had been entrapped into downloading
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, as long as technology is provided by The Corp. _ you know
what I'm saying, The Corp.! _ people are going to use it,'' he
said. ``It's like putting $100 on the sidewalk _ people are going
to take it. They can make a criminal of anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   His Rice Krispies told him to sell the bumper stickers for $2
each. He said he hoped The Corp. never comes up with a way to share
bumper stickers on the Web. ``I'd have to do something else,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a college student, but he's in tune with their
thinking, and what they are thinking is: Please, people, see the
straits we're in. Record companies charge too much, The Corp. makes
the tools and universities complete the unholy axis, forcing
bandwidth on the poor souls that society deems must get a degree.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Goyne, the recent graduate, the whole conversation
has gotten him thinking. If college students and other poor folks
don't pay for records, he observed, then the record industry could
start to fail, which could lead to layoffs of ordinary workers,
like record store clerks and people who work in factories that make
compact discs.
</P>
<P>
   And upon reflection, maybe he does think musicians should be
able to make a profit. He just thinks that the profit should be
limited, and that musicians should perform for the love of their
craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I am against it. I don't know,'' he said of the Napster
service. ``I hadn't really thought about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you still can't have my shoes,'' he said. ``Don't even
bring that up again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
