<HEADER>
A6083 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-LOCKHEED-HIGHTECH-ART     07-07 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-HIGHTECH-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE WILD BLUE YONDER TO THE ELECTRONIC FRONTIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release on Sunday, July 9) 
 By STAN CROCK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORESTOWN, N.J. _ The locals call it ``the cruiser in the
cornfield.'' The USS Rancocas rises eerily from a meadow just north
of Exit 4 of the New Jersey Turnpike near here, 50 miles from the
Atlantic coast. What looks like the top half of a Navy vessel is
actually a lab where the Lockheed Martin Corp. tests its ability to
knit together naval communications gear, sensors, radar, and
controls used to fire weapons.
</P>
<P>
   With its berth on land, the Rancocas is an apt symbol for what
has become the most important and promising part of a company that
has run aground. Its 1999 net profits of $382 million on sales of
$25.5 billion were down from $1 billion, on $26.3 billion in sales,
the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin, based in Bethesda, Md., has long been known as
a maker of military wares like fighters, missiles and rockets. But
as its market has shrunk, this military contractor, the world's
largest, has quietly transformed itself. Today, its biggest
business is selling sophisticated electronic gear and integrating
the most advanced equipment from different suppliers, whether for
military or peaceful purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The company still never tires of portraying its most photogenic
products in high-flying action. But ``it's tough to put me on a
calendar,'' jokes Robert Coutts, the executive vice president who
heads Lockheed Martin's systems integration unit.
</P>
<P>
   His operations, however, are having a profound impact on
Lockheed Martin's bottom line. Led by its work on Navy programs
like the Aegis ship-based weapons system, Coutts' businesses
accounted for 54 percent of Lockheed Martin's first-quarter
operating profits of $316 million this year, up from 37 percent for
all of 1997. Its backlog grew last year while the remainder of the
company's shrank. On June 28, his division won a $4 billion
contract for a battlefield missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Systems integration has become the core of this company,''
says Loren Thompson, a consultant and chief operating officer of
the Lexington Institute, a research group in Arlington, Va. ``It's
going to be the earnings powerhouse that drives the company's
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Lockheed Martin _ or other big military contractors _
has much choice. When the government blocked Lockheed Martin's
$11.6 billion acquisition of the Northrop Grumman Corp. in 1998,
industry heavyweights knew they could not continue to grow through
mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Headlong plunges into the commercial world, once the great hope
for military contractors after the Cold War, could also be dead
ends. As Norman Augustine, a former Lockheed Martin chairman, once
wrote, ``The record of massive defense conversion is one
unblemished by success.''
</P>
<P>
   The military procurement budget as a whole offers meager growth
prospects. Electronics and integration, however, should become the
fastest-growing segment. While Boeing, Northrop Grumman and
Raytheon are also competing in electronics and systems integration,
Lockheed Martin's shift has been the most profound.
</P>
<P>
   There, the prominence of Coutts' operation is part accident,
part design. The profits of the company's aeronautics and space
lines have been taking big hits from satellite-launch failures and
production glitches, helping to drive down Lockheed Martin's stock
from a high in 1998 of nearly $60 to a low of just under $17
earlier this year, before rebounding somewhat recently. The steady,
5-percent-a-year growth of Coutts' business, which includes
everything from mail sorting to military systems, makes it loom
larger by default. Other company units ``have bigger win parties
and bigger funerals,'' Coutts said. ``We tend to be able to bring
more smoothness.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lockheed Martin is also banking on his unit, organized last
year, for future growth, as part of a plan devised when the company
bought the Loral Corp., a specialist in military electronics, for
$9.1 billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts, 50, is an engineer who was an executive in the General
Electric aerospace division when it was acquired in 1993 by Martin
Marietta; Lockheed and Martin Marietta merged in 1995. Coutts
(whose name rhymes with ``boots'') rose to chief operating officer
of the electronics division in 1998 and executive vice president of
systems integration a year later.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers who work for Coutts weave together components from
different suppliers, much as computer services companies do. But
they also calculate important tradeoffs, like whether it is cheaper
to make radar and missiles with greater range than to provide a
fighter plane with expensive stealth features. (The farther a plane
can fire, of course, the fewer of those features it needs.) The
work also requires extensive computer simulations that test weapons
without having to fire them.
</P>
<P>
   Concentrating on systems integration represents a shrewd hedge.
If the Pentagon binges on new planes and boats, it will need the
electronic goods and services that the division offers. If the
military chooses instead to upgrade existing planes and ships, it
will still need that hardware and software. ``It's the company's
best business,'' said John Raitt, associate director of Harris
Associates, whose Oakmark fund holds a 2 percent stake in Lockheed
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   But Coutts' unit cannot guarantee strong enough performance
against tough competitors to revive the whole company. In 1998,
Boeing won a $1.6 billion contract to be lead integrator for the
Pentagon's national missile defense program. And last year, a team
led by Boeing won a multibillion-dollar satellite contract from the
National Reconnaissance Office, a big victory in a field that was
virtually a Lockheed Martin franchise for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a hugely competitive marketplace,'' Coutts noted.
``It still has more capacity than it has demand.'' Although his
unit's operating profits last year were 8.7 percent of sales, the
best within Lockheed Martin, Coutts predicted that his margin would
decline slightly this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say Lockheed Martin might be undermining his
operations with its plan to sell off key assets like Sanders
Electronics, the electronic-warfare specialist. But the company
must cut its $12 billion debt load and answer complaints from
rivals and the Pentagon that, in assembling weapons systems, it
favors its own components over those of its competitors _ an
accusation that the company denies.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Wall Street entirely pleased with the systems integration
division. Analysts are especially worried about its forays into
corporate assignments.
</P>
<P>
   While Coutts' operations have for years included air traffic
control systems and Postal Service work, it is now moving further
afield. Over the last several years, the company has won $240
million in contracts to provide information services for General
Motors. Lockheed Martin executives say the acquisition of a former
IBM unit in 1996 gives the company the ability to make corporate
contracts profitable. In fact, Lockheed Martin got into the GM
business because former IBM colleagues at both companies knew one
another.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, corporate contracts, with fixed prices and short
terms, are far different from military ones. ``It makes Wall Street
a little nervous,'' says Pierre Chao, an analyst at Credit Suisse
First Boston. ``Defense companies moving into the commercial world
have been a source of losses.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, investors can heave a sigh of relief that at
least this part of Lockheed Martin has not run aground _ except in
that New Jersey cornfield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
