<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYMENT FIGURES BODE WELL FOR STOCKS AND BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Both stocks and bonds rallied Friday after the June
employment report brought investors the good news of slower growth
and the hope that the Federal Reserve Board might now refrain from
another increase in interest rates next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index jumped over the 4,000 mark for the
first time since April and cut its loss for the year to a little
more than 1 percent. The Standard and Poor's 500-stock index popped
back into the plus column for the year, while the Dow Jones
industrial average narrowed its decline. In the bond market,
interest rates slipped.
</P>
<P>
   Both stocks and bonds are still locked in their recent trading
ranges, however, and are likely to remain there until it is clear
the Federal Reserve has finished raising its short-term
interest-rate target to slow the blistering pace of economic growth
and dampen inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   While private sector jobs continued to increase, the June data
showed that the pace of growth was slowing. At the same time,
income growth _ as measured by average hourly earnings _ remained
moderate. And the increase in aggregate hours worked slowed
somewhat, signaling that worker productivity was still strong.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to conclude that the pace of growth might be
decelerating enough to keep Federal Reserve policy-makers from
raising interest rates when they meet again on Aug. 22.
Inflationary pressures, as measured by wages and productivity, are
also not too threatening.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, economic growth is still robust enough to keep
the corporate earnings outlook positive. The reporting season for
second quarter earnings gets into full swing next week and
forecasters are still expecting a robust quarter, with growth of
about 19 percent over the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have become less certain that the Fed will tighten at
the August meeting, while that was the forecast after the June
meeting,'' said Joseph Liro, chief economist at Stone &AMP; McCarthy
Research Associates in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was reflected in the small decline Friday in the
yield on federal funds futures for August, to 6.53 percent from
6.545 percent. The federal funds rate, which is the interest
charged on overnight loans between banks, is the Federal Reserve's
short-term interest-rate target. It is now at 6.5 percent after a
half-percentage-point increase in May. Policy-makers left the rate
unchanged in June but warned that it might be raised again if the
economy did not slow more.
</P>
<P>
   And, Liro added, investors can be ``confident that there will be
enough aggregate demand out there to keep the economy growing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index jumped 62.63 points, or 1.6 percent,
to 4,023.20 on Friday, while the S&AMP;P 500 climbed 22.23 points, or
1.5 percent, to 1,478.90. The Dow Jones industrial average rose
154.51 points, or 1.5 percent, to 10,635.98. Volume on the New York
Stock Exchange was moderate, with 931.8 million shares changing
hands. The daily average for the year is 1.02 billion shares a day.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's rally turned the week into a nice positive. The Nasdaq
rose 1.4 percent for the week and the technology-heavy index is now
down just 1.1 percent for the year. But it is still 20.3 percent
below its 2000 high in March. The S&AMP;P was up 1.7 percent for the
week and is now up 0.7 percent for the year. But it is still 3.2
percent below its 2000 high in March.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow finished the week 1.8 percent higher. It is still the
worst performer of the three indexes, down 7.5 percent for the
year, and is 9.3 percent from its record high in January.
</P>
<P>
   Liro noted that while investors seem to worry about the impact
of the monthly jobs data on the stock market, the data has usually
been positive for the stock market on the day it is released. He
said that on 15 of the 18 Fridays on which the employment report
had been issued since January 1999, the S&AMP;P index had rallied. And
12 of those rallies saw the S&AMP;P rise 1 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons for this positive response, he said.
One is that investors who are worried about the Fed raising
interest rates think positively if the economy is slowing slightly.
Continued growth is naturally positive. And often just getting the
news out of the way, even if it is negative, is a relief that can
make investors think positively.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were led higher Friday by Hewlett-Packard, Wal-Mart
Stores, Home Depot, IBM, Citigroup, Intel and Dell Computer. The
stocks that fell included Qualcomm, BroadVision, Yahoo, Pfizer,
Merck &AMP; Co., Alcoa and General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, prices were higher, as yields _ which move
in the opposite direction _ fell. The yield on the Treasury's
10-year note fell to 6.00 percent from 6.04 percent on Thursday,
while the price rose 8/32, to 103 19/32. The yield on the 10-year
note has been fighting to get back below 6 percent for the last
four weeks. The yield on the 30-year bond fell to 5.87 percent from
5.90 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After one day of trading at 1 cent below $30 a barrel, the price
of crude oil rose Friday. Oil for August delivery on the New York
Mercantile Exchange rose 29 cents, or 1 percent, to $30.28.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear how much the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries will actually increase its crude-oil
production. Saudi Arabia said Monday that it would raise its
production by 500,000 barrels a day _ less than 2 percent of OPEC
production _ if the price did not decline soon. But other OPEC
members are still discussing how much of an increase they will
accept.
</P>
</TEXT>
