<HEADLINE>
BORDER IMMIGRANT SMUGGLERS SHIFT INTO NEW GEAR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: Smietana in 5th graf is CQ. 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLINGEN, Texas _ In the past, Border Patrol agents have
discovered undocumented immigrants in car trunks, engine
compartments, sealed freight cars and even stuffed into suitcases.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest smuggling ruse uncovered on the Fourth of July
outside Laredo, Texas, has topped them all for sheer brazenness.
</P>
<P>
   A man is accused of smuggling undocumented immigrants past a
Border Patrol checkpoint on Interstate 35 by dressing them up as
bicycle enthusiasts and having them pedal 10-speed cycles past
unsuspecting agents.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants were dressed to look like members of Laredo
cycling clubs, complete with colorful outfits and helmets. The club
often trains on the access road running past the secondary
checkpoint 14 miles north of the border town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unique and it took a little bit of planning and
forethought to come up with this,'' said Assistant Chief John
Smietana, who heads the Border Patrol anti-smuggling detail in
Laredo. ``Obviously, someone was watching our operations and saw
this road being used by bicyclists.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are not sure how the immigrants got past primary
checkpoints along the border. But once in Laredo, the immigrants
paid $1,500 for passage to San Antonio, agents believe.
</P>
<P>
   The subterfuge might have gone on for a year before it was
discovered. Smietana said agents' view of the access road is
obstructed when large trucks or buses are backed up at the
checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   After being tipped to the ploy, agents watched the checkpoint
particularly closely on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   They saw two cyclists speed past the checkpoint on the access
road. The agents watched as the cyclists met up with a man in a
pickup. The man loaded them and their bicycles and drove north on
I-35 until agents pulled him over.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, Pedro Gonzalez-Davila, a 42-year-old Mexican citizen
who lives in San Antonio, was arrested and charged with aiding and
abetting illegal entry. Gonzalez-Davila &UR; ,  &LR; a legal resident, also
could face deportation as a result of the charges. His 1997 Ford
pickup has been seized, Smietana said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the information we gathered ... he's been doing this for
approximately a year,'' Smietana said. ``He'd do it two or three
times a week with two to three aliens at a time, so it would look
like the normal bicycling groups that are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1,500 that Gonzalez-Davila charged each client included the
use of a bicycle, an outfit and helmet, along with a ride to San
Antonio, Smietana said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez-Davila would drop his clients and bicycles off at a
Laredo truck stop south of the checkpoint and meet up with them
after they cruised past the Border Patrol, Smietana said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At $1,500 apiece, he was making some money at it,'' Smietana
said. ``We thought it was kind of a novel idea, and it just goes to
show the ingenuity of the alien smugglers who try and beat our
enforcement methods.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF FILE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
