<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-COTTAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$1.1 MILLION ALLOCATED TO RENOVATE LINCOLN COTTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER WALSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The rundown summer cottage where President Lincoln
wrote a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation was declared a
national monument Friday by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Anderson Cottage, relatively unknown and tucked away in
the northwest corner of the city, Clinton made use of the
Antiquities Act to designate the 158-year-old landmark the
President Lincoln and Soldiers' Home National Monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year more than a million people visited Ford's Theater
alone, but barely 100 made it here to Anderson Cottage, where
Lincoln lived and worked,'' said Clinton. ``In some ways, this
cottage behind me is the most important, as well as the least
known, Lincoln site in the entire United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said $1.1 million has been raised for the renovations,
including a $750,000 matching funds grant from Save America's
Treasures, a public-private partnership between the White House
Millennium Council and the National Trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cottage in its way is just as precious as a giant
sequoia, as irreplaceable as the ruins of cultures long past, and
it is our profound obligation to preserve and protect it for future
generations,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes less than two weeks after the National
Trust for Historic Preservation put the cottage at the top of this
year's list of historical sites in danger of demolition or
deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Moe, president of the National Trust, said, ``At a time
when understanding of American history is at an abysmal level, we
need sites like this more than ever to convey an appreciation of
how we got to be the nation we are.''
</P>
<P>
   As Civil War battles loomed, the hilltop cottage essentially
served as Lincoln's Camp David, where he would retreat from the
heat of the city and the stress of day-to-day operations. The
cottage, built in 1842, was located on the grounds of what was
known then as the Soldiers' Home, the first home for disabled
veterans of the US Army.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-room Gothic revival cottage, where Lincoln spent about a
quarter of his presidency, is in desperate need of renovation with
water damage, rotting wooden window frames, and aging electrical
and plumbing systems. Restoration is expected to start next year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to preserving Lincoln's retreat, Clinton announced
another $15 million in grants from Save America's Treasures for
preserving 47 historic sites and collections nationwide, including
the USS Missouri, where the Japanese formally surrendered to end
World War II, and Babe Ruth's scrapbooks at the National Baseball
Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts sites to receive grants include the Orchard House,
the family home of author Louisa May Alcott in Concord; the
Colonial Theater in Pittsfield; and the American Antiquarian
Society Library in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   Refurnishing the 14-room cottage may be difficult since Lincoln
would move the family's belongings to the summer home in May and
take them back to the White House in November, said Nick Minecci,
spokesman for the cottage and an amateur historian who has done
extensive research on Lincoln's stay there.
</P>
<P>
   Office furniture and equipment for the public affairs department
of the soldiers' home now occupy many of the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was the first president to visit the site since
President Chester A. Arthur more than 100 years ago. Presidents
Franklin Pierce, James Buchanan, Ulysses S. Grant and Rutherford B.
Hayes also used the cottage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's tour Friday was reminiscent of the summer days between
1862 and 1864 when Lincoln roamed the grounds just three miles away
from the White House. Clinton walked the same staircase that
Lincoln would take to retreat to the corner bedroom where he
drafted the famous proclamation that ended slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can still feel that spirit strongly in the room in this
cottage where he worked,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also stood in the cool shade under the copper
beech tree where Lincoln would spend time playing with his son,
reading, or writing correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it is three centuries old, it is our last living link
to Abraham Lincoln,'' Clinton said of the tree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2012EDT &QL; 
