<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-890(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFTER DEFEATS AGASSI IS STIRRING SEMIFINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ For months, Patrick Rafter rode out the
mood swings that turned his good-natured personality inside out.
The same Aussie who had always been ready with a good joke, a toast
and a smile _ the profile of the perfect best man at a wedding _
had his spirits rustled when forced to confront his tennis
mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Rafter underwent shoulder surgery, and the No. 1
ranking he worked so hard to obtain last July had evaporated. But
against a backdrop of rehab setbacks that left him pondering
retirement at times, the 27-year-old Rafter looked at peace Friday.
He realizes there are only so many serves left in his right rotator
cuff, but he did not seem the least bit concerned with the dynamics
of supply and demand on Center Court.
</P>
<P>
   To handcuff Andre Agassi's Houdini-like return game, Rafter
needed a big serve with the high kick of a Rockette. And he needed
as many as possible. As a gray afternoon extended into a crisp and
clear evening, as the first set of this hypnotic semifinal morphed
into the fifth, Rafter ignored the shrinking life span of his
serve. Unfurling his body freely, he pounded a high percentage of
first serves to undermine Agassi's strength on his way to a 7-5,
4-6, 7-5, 4-6, 6-3 victory that put him in position to play Pete
Sampras in Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a match that I couldn't have played any better under
the circumstances, on a big court against one of the best players
ever,'' Rafter said. ``I think it was probably very satisfying to
have actually done it on these grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   As a beaming Rafter lifted his arms in victory and spotted his
brothers sitting in the friends box, Steffi Graf was hustling out
of the stadium, not to return. Agassi's run was over, and the
American dream final had vanished. Only one half of it was alive
after the cash-poor qualifier, Vladimir Voltchkov, allowed one
pivotal shot to undo his upset chance against Sampras and lost, 7-6
(4), 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   With a huffing Sampras scrambling to chase down a deep, sliced
backhand, Voltchkov botched the easy backhand volley that would
have evened the first-set tiebreaker at 5-5. In disbelief,
Voltchkov dropped his racket and hung his head. The unknown
22-year-old from Belarus _ whose vagabond career took a brief
detour through Brooklyn seven years ago _ couldn't believe the
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit a hundred out of a hundred of those in practice,''
said Voltchkov, who came to Wimbledon too cash-strapped to eat out
and left with $193,000 in prize money. ``You miss one here. I guess
it's the nerves.''
</P>
<P>
   Voltchkov never recovered. He went on to lose the tiebreaker and
never posed a threat to Sampras again. The only problem Sampras had
was with his sore lower left shin. At the end of the second set, he
asked a trainer for assistance. Scurrying around with only a slight
limp, he played on. After easing through the tournament without
having to face a seeded player, the top-seeded Sampras was in the
final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking at Sunday as pressure,'' said Sampras, 28, who
can break Roy Emerson's record of 12 Grand Slams with a victory
against Rafter. ``I'm looking at it as an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Unchallenged through the tournament, Sampras will go up against
a player who has had his moments against Sampras in the past. They
have not always been pleasant encounters, either. As a part of an
odd tennis turf war when both were in their early days on the tour,
they exchanged a few heated words.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get along fine,'' Sampras said. ``We'll just go out there
and do the best we can and then shake hands. But everything is
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Rafter wasn't focused on old grudges. He was fixated on
his recovery. Even as Agassi exited the grounds of the All England
Club, he seemed genuinely pleased for Rafter. One year ago, Rafter,
beginning to feel the first unsettling pains in his shoulder, was
crestfallen after his semifinal loss to Agassi at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat's gone through a tough stage here with his injury,''
Agassi said. ``He looks like he's found his game. I thought, in the
crucial times of the match, he was playing tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Every game seemed to present a critical point during a match
that unveiled a glorious contrast of styles. There was the
ponytailed Rafter, a serve-and-volley fiend with a touch as soft as
cashmere at the net, faced with a bald icon who uses his racket
like a laser from the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   For four sets, neither style had a clear edge over the other. To
threaten Rafter's serve in the seventh game of the first set, the
second-seeded Agassi pounced on a second serve and slapped it back
at the feet of the Aussie as he raced to the net. In the same game,
Rafter dared to reach back and go for a second-serve ace that split
the court in half.
</P>
<P>
   This was just part of a riveting back-and-forth. Agassi would
catch Rafter creeping into the net and airbrush a lob just over his
outstretched racket. Rafter would watch Agassi rip a service return
down the line, and then stab it like a swashbuckler for a
half-volley winner. The high level of play left the crowd in a
constant state of awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good enough if you lose,'' said Agassi, who converted
4 of 9 break points while Rafter succeeded on 5 of 12. ``I didn't
serve as well as I wanted to, made some careless errors. To his
credit, he played well at the right time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the end of a 3 hour 18 minute match, the hiccups in Agassi's
game caught up to him. In the sixth game of the fifth set, Agassi
went for too much on a second serve in an attempt to keep Rafter on
his heels. He double faulted. That mistake set up the 12th-seeded
Rafter with a break point. With Rafter at the net, Agassi sent a
forehand passing shot hurdling into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi couldn't break back. Rafter's first serve only got better
as the match progressed. In the first set, Rafter put 53 percent of
his first serves in. By the fifth, he was nailing 74 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As the match unfolded, it was obvious: Rafter's shoulder was
holding up just fine. Just after Rafter left the interview, he was
headed for his strength routines. Twice a day, he ties a rubber
band from a door knob to his racket and begins swinging away
against the resistance. So far, this dedication to rehabilitating
has extended his career. How long, no one knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just taking it week by week, just really grateful to be
out there,'' he said. ``I'm hoping I can get a few more serves out
than what everyone expects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
