A6091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BLACKS-UTEXAS0708-COX     07-07 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-UTEXAS0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University of Texas set about to increase minority law student
enrollmentBy Sharon Jayson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A free ride to Austin this spring for minority
students let the University of Texas School of Law lose some of its
disparaging baggage and boost its ranks for this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 1996 Hopwood court ruling that led to a dismantling
of affirmative action in Texas colleges, the number of African
American students who say they'll attend UT this fall is about
double the number enrolled last year. Though it's a small step up
from seven black students in 1999 _ and next year's group will
still be a small figure _ the double digits are welcome news to
admissions officials struggling to increase student diversity
without affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   This spring efforts to attract a more ethnically diverse
population spurred state Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, an alumni of
the law school, ask airlines to provide free roundtrip flights for
African Americans accepted for the fall to get a firsthand look at
UT. More than half of the 25 liked what they saw and signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican American enrollment is expected to increase only
slightly from last year's 32 students. Law school admissions
officials believe Ellis' effort made headway and they want to
expand the offerings to Mexican Americans this spring, said Shelli
Soto, assistant dean for admissions at UT Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a drastic improvement,'' Ellis said. ``It's
much more than a weekend in Austin. It's making the students feel
that people of color who have leadership positions in the state
want them here. My effort was a small piece in a much bigger puzzle
to figure out how to diminish the devastating effect of Hopwood.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those students, Chris Lopez of Houston, said he chose UT
over Georgetown University and the University of Pennsylvania after
his visit in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me confidence to know I wasn't alone,'' he said.
``They made you feel like you were welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, 26, said he had been nervous about coming to UT because
of the previous few years when the number of entering black
students at the law school were as few as four or five in a class
edging toward 500.
</P>
<P>
   The law school received almost 3,900 applications for the 475
spots for first-year students this fall. Of those, almost 1,000
were accepted. Students guarantee their place with a deposit,
though some change their mind over the summer. Soto said 50 to 100
students on the wait list will be admitted, but she won't know
exact numbers until classes begin. In 1999, when the entering class
comprised 483 students, there were only seven African Americans,
down one from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Cuellar, D-Laredo, another UT Law School graduate,
wants to help improve those numbers next fall. This month, he sent
letters to accepted Mexican American students encouraging them to
choose UT and to call him if they have questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has suffered under the ruling in Hopwood, but UT Law
School is making strides to maintain diversity in a race-neutral
system,'' Cuellar said in his letter. ``Texans have a wonderful
advantage in that they can receive a top caliber legal education at
a fraction of the cost charged by other top tier law schools. I
urge you to take advantage of the education that your family's tax
dollars have helped to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how the program could be expanded is still in question. In
fact, Ellis said his commitment from the airlines was only for the
trial run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the airlines don't do it, I'll be looking at a number
of other avenues to try to bring the students in,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuellar said he's optimistic their efforts will succeed in
increasing the numbers of future minority lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is if we can do it on an incremental basis _ in
the sense of getting more minority students _ that will be a
success,'' he said. ``It can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Sharon Jayson at sjayson(at)statesman.com or
445-3620.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
