<HEADER>
A6092 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-VINEYARD-SWIM-BOS &LR;      07-07 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINEYARD-SWIM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIMMERS TO BRAVE TIDES, SHARKS TO RAISE MONEY FOR POOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Australia)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At 7:45 a.m. July 23, a Boston real estate executive
intends to step off a Martha's Vineyard beach with a blind
Australian man at her side and begin swimming east toward a horizon
that offers nothing more than water and sky.
</P>
<P>
   Their destination will be Nantucket Island, 15 miles across a
maelstrom of tidal turbulance filled with toothy fish (the local
shark tournament ends the day before). The waters they will swim
through can be so confused that sometimes standing waves spit spray
30 feet into the air.
</P>
<P>
   At approximately 3 p.m., the pair will step onto a beach in
Nantucket's Madaket Harbor. They will be the first swimmers to make
the crossing from Martha's Vineyard to Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if all goes according to plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I guess I would have to admit that a lot of things can go
wrong,'' said Debra Taylor, 36. Accompanying her will be James
Pittar, a resident of Sydney who has swum the English Channel, and
last year swam around Manhatten, she said.
</P>
<P>
   They're in it for the money _ not for themselves, but for a
$100,000 aquatic center proposed for Oak Bluffs. The center will
house the Vineyard's first public indoor swimming pools. They have
already lined up $20,000 from private donors, and are looking for
more sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   The swim has not escaped the attention of Charlie Blair, the
harbormaster at Edgartown, a Vineyard port. He knows all 16 tide
rips that slice through the passage, and has lost count of the
number of mariners he has pulled out of trouble in the rips.
</P>
<P>
   Blair had this to say about Taylor:
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time she telephoned me, I thought she was joking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second time she telephoned and told me about the
Australian, I thought she was crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now I'm beginning to think she might make it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is the founder and owner of Link, a company that
furnishes Boston realtors with housing market information. She is
slightly more than five solid feet tall, and Friday, dressed in a
business suit, she nursed a cup of coffee to describe the route she
took from an idea to a plan.
</P>
<P>
   It started back to the early 1990s when Taylor, a graduate of
Northeastern University, founded a small real estate business on
the Vineyard _ but was shocked to learn there was no place to swim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had grown up swimming (in Maryland). It's a way to zone out,
meditate, focus, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 she sold the business and moved back to Boston _ but not
before she met Annie Mechur, a Vineyard resident and distance
swimmer who has spearheaded an effort to build an aquatic center.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Taylor decided to join the effort in ernest, making
the first of what would be dozens of telephone calls to
harbormasters on both islands to learn about the local conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has twice swum from Boston Light to South Boston, a
distance of 10 miles.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, a stray email from Pittar landed in Taylor's
computer. Pittar had wanted to learn about a distance swim
elsewhere, but when he learned of Taylor's goal, he signed on. He
swims with the aid of two kayackers who blow whistles to guide him
_ one toot for a left course correction, two toots for a right
course correction. Pittar, who works for the Australian internal
revenue service, according to Taylor, will pay his own way to make
the swim, as will his kayackers.
</P>
<P>
   The intinerary _ much of it worked out by Blair in Edgartown _
will be as follows:
</P>
<P>
   The pair will leave Chappaquiddick Island about midway down the
beach at 7:45 a.m. They will catch the last of the ebb tide so that
swimming at 2 mph they reach the Muskeget Channel at about 9 a.m.
The channel is a trough where currents reach 5 mph at mid-tide. The
swimmers want to be there when the tide slacks.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the trip, the tides run north and south. But at
Muskeget Island, seven miles west of the swimmers' goal, the
currents flow east and west. Taylor figures she needs to reach
Muskeget by about noon to catch the westerly current toward
Muskeget Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where it gets really interesting. We miss Muskeget,
and we're going to have our hands full,'' she said. The pair would
find themselves caught in a powerful current pushing them north _
and away from their goal.
</P>
<P>
   The swimmers will be accompanied by a power boat and a pair of
kayackers each. In addition, a spotter airplane, provided by a
business associate of Taylor's, will give sponsors rides _ but also
look for schools of bluefish. The pilot will be in radio contact
with patrol craft that will either try to clear the path of the
fish or pull the swimmers from the water. In schools, hungry
bluefish behave like piranha, devouring just about anything in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the man o' war jelly fish, I think we'll just have to
put up with them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She will wear the most brightly colored bathing suit she owns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure the sharks know I'm not a seal,'' she
said, ``and that they have never seen the likes of me.''
</P>
<P>
   This would appear to hold true for Vineyarders as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
