<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-HARASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL ACCUSED IN HIGH-RANKING HARASSMENT CASE RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case that spotlighted sexual harassment at the
highest ranks of the US military, a highly regarded general has
submitted his resignation after being accused of making improper
sexual advances on the Army's first three-star female general, the
Army announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Major General Larry G. Smith, who had been in line to become the
Army's deputy inspector general _ a role in which he would oversee
sexual harassment cases _ was given a written reprimand for conduct
unbecoming of an officer and for sexually harassing an officer. His
retirement is effective Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's inspector general said in a report released Friday
that Smith ``improperly displayed disrespect toward a commissioned
officer . . . by holding her and kissing her against her will.''
For the first time, the Army acknowledged publicly that it had
substantiated the claim made by Lieutenant General Claudia J.
Kennedy against Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The case, initiated after the Army announced Smith's appointment
last year and Kennedy informally expressed her reservations about
the promotion, followed a long line of sex scandals that made it
abundantly clear that sexual harassment was widespread in the armed
services.
</P>
<P>
   But punishment in past cases _ with one notable exception _ had
been criticized by women's rights groups as cursory or
non-existent. They included the groping of women at the Navy's 1991
Tailhook convention and charges that Army drill sergeants assaulted
female recruits at a training base in Aberdeen, Md., in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Major General David R. E. Hale retired after being the
target of a complaint by the wife of colonel who worked for him.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, in his first public comment on the matter, Friday denied
any wrongdoing. In a statement, he said, ``However, for the good of
my family and the Army, we have elected to put it behind us and
move on with our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also made her first public comment on the case, saying
she was ``satisfied with the Army's action. . . .As far as I'm
concerned, this matter is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army's treatment of Kennedy's accusation was being closely
watched by many of the 1.4 million people in the military _ men and
women alike. For many women, it showed that even those with high
rank are vulnerable to sexual advances. Kennedy, who retired from
her position last month after exactly 31 years of service, held a
higher rank than Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, the system worked,'' said a female senior
officer in the Navy, who asked not to be identified. ``He was about
to be in charge of a sexual harassment panel and she was literally
dragged through the mud. But she did it because he was being put in
a position on an issue that she knew he did not have a moral
framework to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Navy officer said, ``I don't see it as an extra layer
of protection. This will be forever judged on a case-by-case basis.
There are still men getting away with it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Air Force Brigadier General Wilma L. Vaught, president
of the Women in Military Service Memorial Foundation, welcomed the
Army's report and predicted that ramifications of the case will be
felt throughout the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's becoming increasingly clear that sexual
misconduct is unacceptable,'' she said. ``It's unacceptable to both
men and women, and that those who err from the proper standards may
well be finding themselves facing investigation and potential
disciplinary action, as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army inspector general, Lieutenant General Michael W.
Ackerman, wrote in his report that Smith and Kennedy were in
``total disagreement'' about what happened in her office on that
day in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's version: He hugged Kennedy and possibly gave her a
``cheek kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's: Smith grabbed her, held her against her will, and
kissed her.
</P>
<P>
   During the investigation, Smith did not shy from defending
himself, providing a list of 52 character witnesses to testify on
his behalf. Ackerman's office interviewed seven of them.
</P>
<P>
   While Ackerman found that Smith was a ``highly respected officer
and gentleman with an unblemished career,'' he sided with Kennedy,
citing her credibility. The report noted that she had no motive for
making a false accusation.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, General John Keane, the vice chief of staff, gave
Smith an ``administrative memorandum of reprimand.'' He saw no
basis for a criminal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Flanders, who researched the role of women in the military
during the Gulf War, said the Kennedy-Smith case comes against a
backdrop of increasing pressure from Christian fundamentalist
groups and other socially conservative groups to limit women's role
in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the military to confirm what Kennedy is saying does fuel
the argument that . . . it's better to not have women in the
military at all, that they are all a big distraction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But women comprise 15 percent of the Army's 479,000 people, and
Flanders strongly doubted that the conservatives' push would yield
any step backward for the advancement of women in the military. ``I
think every time they do this type of investigation, it's a great
step forward for women in the military, and the women's movement as
a whole,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
