<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-585&AMP;ADD     07-07 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS RELEASE A CENTRIST PLATFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Democrats released a draft of their party
platform Friday that strongly articulates the centrist ``new
Democratic'' views of Vice President Al Gore, but also offers
concessions to liberals on several major issues, including trade,
the death penalty and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the 41-page document is an attempt to straddle the
same ideological divide that faces Gore in his quest for the
presidency. Even as he tries to reach out to moderate and
independent voters this fall, Gore will need to energize core
Democratic voters, who tend to be more liberal.
</P>
<P>
   On many major issues, the platform stakes out the centrist views
first championed by President Clinton in 1992. It calls for fiscal
discipline and paying off the national debt by 2012. It proposes
modest tax cuts. It advocates more accountability for schools and
teachers. It views global trade as crucial to economic prosperity.
It endorses tougher penalties, including the death penalty, for
violent criminals.
</P>
<P>
   But on many of those issues, the draft platform _ which will be
finalized at a meeting in Cleveland later this month _ also
includes provisions intended to mitigate the concerns of liberals.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on trade, potentially the most divisive issue for
the party, the 2000 platform includes significantly stronger
language than the 1996 platform about protecting workers and the
environment against the potential downside of globalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore will insist on and use the authority to enforce worker
rights, human rights and environmental protections'' in trade
accords, the draft says. ``We should use trade to lift up standards
around the world, not drag down standards here at home.''
</P>
<P>
   In another tradeoff with labor, the document supports giving the
president broad powers to negotiate trade agreements _ a policy
known as ``fast track'' that is strongly opposed by unions. But it
also endorses legislation prohibiting the permanent replacement of
workers on strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an agreement to disagree,'' said Elaine Kamarck,
Gore's chief domestic policy adviser. ``There is plenty in here
that labor likes.''
</P>
<P>
   In another section, the platform asserts that increasing the
number of police officers and imposing tougher penalties, including
capital punishment, have helped reduce crime. But it will also
include language advocating that people facing the death sentence
have access to DNA testing and ``adequate'' legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The crime-fighting section includes another plank sought by
minority groups: the strong condemnation of racial profiling by
police officers. ``It views Americans as members of groups instead
of as individuals, and it is just plain shoddy policing,'' the
platform says.
</P>
<P>
   In a section with the centrist-sounding title ``Valuing our
families,'' the platform will say that the party ``supports the
full inclusion of gay and lesbian families in the life of a
nation.'' The provision is intended to suggest that the party
supports civil, though perhaps not religious, unions for gay
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Where the platform adopts Republican-sounding ideas, it usually
criticizes the Republican version of those ideas. On tax cuts, for
instance, the platform advocates reductions for ``working
parents.'' But it harshly attacks Gov. George W. Bush's proposed
across-the-board tax cut with populist language.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would let the richest one percent of Americans afford a new
sports car and middle class Americans afford a warm soda,'' the
platform says.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The draft also echoes Gore's repeated attacks on Bush's proposal
to allow taxpayers to invest a portion of their Social Security
payroll taxes in the markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taken together, George W. Bush's $2 trillion tax cut, his
campaign-season spending proposals, his support for privatizing
Social Security add up to an assault on the surplus, causing
Americans to have to choose between drastic cuts in education and
health care or a return to the days of deficit spending,'' the
draft reads.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the platform highlights Gore's core campaign
proposals to preserve Social Security, expand health care, help
senior citizens to buy prescription drugs, overhaul the
campaign-finance system and strengthen gun regulations.
</P>
<P>
   And it devotes its largest section to outlining Gore's education
proposals, which include modernizing crumbling schools, requiring
teachers to pass periodic licensing tests and encouraging states to
take over failing schools.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy, the platform praises the administration's
military interventions in Kosovo, Bosnia and Haiti. But it also
calls for a somewhat vaguely defined policy called ``forward
engagement'' that could defuse international problems before they
boil over into violence.
</P>
<P>
   In its language as well as its policies, the document echoes
Gore's stump speeches. It is divided into three major sections _
prosperity, progress and peace _ which were the themes of a recent
campaign swing by the vice president. It paraphrases the title of
Gore's book on the environment, saying, ``The Earth truly is in the
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   And it closes with a pet Gore slogan: ``Now, we say to America,
`You ain't seen nothing yet.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
