<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6100 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-JOBS-HIRING-BOS &LR;      07-07 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBS-HIRING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOWER US JOB GROWTH SPURS HOPES OF AN EASING ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Job growth across the nation was sluggish for the second
straight month in June, providing more evidence that the racing US
economy may be downshifting to a slower speed.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government reported Friday that business hiring
resumed last month at a modest clip, reversing a surprising decline
in May. But those gains in the private sector were offset by a
large drop in government payrolls as US Census takers, hired as
temporary workers, completed their assignments and were let go last
month. Total employment grew by just 11,000 last month.
</P>
<P>
   The June unemployment dipped by 0.1 percentage points, to 4
percent, a statistically meaningless change in a job market
stretched to capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The government's monthly jobs report is the newest piece of data
to be scrutinized, like tea leaves, by economists seeking any clues
that the nation's nine-year expansion is experiencing a much-needed
cooling off that would also reduce inflationary pressures building
in the economy. The increase of 11,000 in total non-farm jobs
compared with a temporary, Census-inflated rise of 171,000 jobs in
May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is behaving very tamely,'' said Oscar Gonzalez,
economist for John Hancock Financial Services in Boston. Slower job
growth indicates the economy ``may be slowing down and coming into
the soft landing, which is in sharp contrast to what we were
thinking three months ago when there were worries we were on the
brink of overheating.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all economists find the signs of deceleration convincing,
pointing to continued strength in home sales and industrial
production. And if the economy is, indeed, slowing, some wonder
whether it is slowing enough to arrest inflation.
</P>
<P>
   A sign of strength in the June jobs report, for example, was the
rebound in business hiring. After private-sector payrolls had
shrunk 165,000 in May _ a revision from earliest estimates of a
116,000 reduction _ businesses expanded their payrolls in June by
206,000. Much of the hiring was in the services industry, ranging
from hotels and engineering to healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   Public-sector employment, mostly at the Census Bureau, declined
by 195,000 last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no evidence in the world the private sector is
actually shedding jobs,'' said William Dunkelberg, chief economist
for the National Federation of Independent Business, a Washington
trade group for small business. As for the overall slowdown, he
added, ``One of the interesting possibilities we have to face is
that slowing down could still be too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter job creation _ public and private _ was far below
the second quarter: Monthly average job growth, in April, May and
June, was 197,000, compared with 324,000 average growth for the
first three months of the year, according to Hancock's analysis of
US jobs data. Despite stronger business hiring in June, private
payrolls in the second quarter expanded at less than half the rate
during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The US unemployment has stopped declining, too. Since October,
the Labor Department said the jobless rate has stabilized at
between 3.9 percent and 4.1 percent at a time the economy's overall
growth, as measured by the gross national product, also moderated.
</P>
<P>
   If data in coming weeks also point to economic softening prior
to the Federal Reserve's next meeting, scheduled for August 22,
economists said the central bankers would be less likely to raise
interest rates for a seventh time. In their June meeting, Fed
members decided to wait for more economic data before doing so
again, deferring a rate hike; they left the federal funds rate
unchanged at 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the policy statement explaining its decision, the Fed said,
``Recent data suggests that the expansion of aggregate demand may
be moderating toward a pace closer to the rate of growth of the
economy's potential to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock market was counting on that Friday. Each of the major
market indexes surged about 1.5 percent, buoyed by more moderate
job growth. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 154.51 points, to
10,635.98, and the technology-dominated Nasdaq index surged 62.63
points, to 4023.20. The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks also
rose, by 22.23 points to 1478.90.
</P>
<P>
   An end to the long-running bull market in stocks has also
somewhat undermined consumer confidence, albeit from record highs.
Friday there were indications a deflating stock market is hitting
Wall Street. Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., one of the nation's largest
retail securities firms, is considering cutting as many as 2,000
jobs from its brokerage unit _ about 5.4 percent of the unit's
total employment _ to lower costs, the Wall Street Journal
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is not so concerned about growth, per se, as it is that
growth would ignite inflation, spurred both by higher prices for
consumer goods and by rising wages.
</P>
<P>
   Overall prices, as measured by the consumer price index, are
accelerating though not at a pace that alarms economists. But oil
price hikes and rising wages continue to put upward pressure on the
CPI.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department estimated that wages rose 5 cents last
month, to $13.71 an hour; that is slightly above a 3 cent rise in
the previous month. And a predictor of future inflation, the
``future inflation gauge'' published by the Economic Cycle Research
Institute in New York, that is said to be closely watched by Fed
chairman Alan Greenspan edged up again in June after dipping in
May,
</P>
<P>
   Some of the employment gains made by the private sector in June
were attributed to summer's arrival, which brings vacations and
higher spending by Americans on leisure. Hotels and other
amusements saw faster-than-normal growth in jobs last month,
fueling growth in the services sector. The retail industry's
biggest gains were at eating establishments, which provided 35,000
of the 49,000 new jobs last month and bolstered an industry that
has suffered from a softening of consumer spending in recent month.
</P>
<P>
   The rush of graduating high school and college students into the
labor force also allowed some companies to hire for long-unfilled
positions, economists said. While data may show a cooler job
market, anecdotal evidence gathered by Jack Mohan, president in
Boston of Management Recruiters International, shows hiring, at
least in the New England region, is still frantic.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses ``not only can't find people to fill the new jobs,''
Mohan said, ``they can't find people to replace the people who are
leaving. And people are leaving because there are better jobs
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
