u a BC-EATING-PROBLEMS-BOS &LR;      07-07 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EATING-PROBLEMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUFFERERS OF RARE AFFLICTION FIND COMFORT AT CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEGAN SCOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rosaline Wu eats five bites of cantaloupe, and 18 hours
later she is violently ill. When she goes out to dinner, she may
treat herself to a slice of red pepper, while her family and
friends stuff themselves with pizza or hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   Wu is not bulimic or anorexic. She is not on a crash diet.
Instead, she suffers from a rare disease called intestinal
pseudo-obstruction, a painful condition that can have symptoms from
weight loss to cramps to constipation. Eating is so unpleasant for
Wu that she relies on a catheter in her neck for daily nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first find out you're going to be on this stuff, you
feel devastated and alone,'' said Wu, who had to quit her job as a
computer operator because of her illness.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday marks the end of an unusual three-day conference in
Boston for people such as Wu whose daily survival depends on
intravenous and tube-fed nutrition. More than 250 people gathered
from all over the United States with pouches, catheters and IVs in
tow for the aptly titled Conference for People Who Cannot (or do
not need to) Eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really helps to be connected to a lot of people,'' said
22-year-old Malisa Matheny of Doylestown, Pa., who started
suffering from nausea, pain, heartburn and vomiting eight years
ago. ``When you actually talk with somebody who has it, it's a
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, Matheny said she had never even heard of
pseudo-obstruction until she was diagnosed with it. Since then, she
has learned a lot through organizations such as conference
organizer, the Oley Foundation for Home Parenteral and Enteral
Nutrition, as well as the Association of Gastrointestinal Motility
Disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Wu said that connecting with the Oley Foundation ``brings life
back to you.'' Of the conference, she said, ``We all have a goal, a
joint reason why we're here: to learn more and feel better about
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo-obstruction afflicts roughly 11,000 Americans, making it
impossible for them to eat normally. Unlike actual intestinal
obstructions, which often can be removed, a pseudo-obstruction
prevents food from passing through even though there is no physical
barrier. Instead, abnormalities in nerves and muscles prevent the
digestive system from doing its job.
</P>
<P>
   The disorder strikes most frequently in children, about 200 of
whom are diagnosed with pseudo-obstruction each year. For many, the
``false'' blockage forces them to spend their lives receiving food
and nutrition through catheters or feeding tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, because the condition is so poorly understood, it
is often difficult for doctors to recognize and treat.
</P>
<P>
   Wu was diagnosed at birth with Hirschsprung's disease, an
illness akin to pseudo-obstruction in which the victim lacks the
nerve cells that enable the intestinal muscles to move stool
through the large intestine. But Wu knew she also had another
disease because her X-rays showed blockages in the large intestine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter what I ate or how much I ate, I would get
deathly sick,'' said the 52-year-old from Livonia, Mich. ``Nothing
was going through my system. It didn't matter if I had Jello or
water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ate, got sick, but never knew why,'' she said. ``All the air
and fluid would back all the way up to my heart. You really feel
horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Wu had a series of gastroenterology surgeries, doctors
found it difficult to diagnose her condition. In 1989, Wu read an
article in Family Circle magazine about a boy who had
pseudo-obstruction. For the first time, she found a name for her
disease. She took a test at the University of Michigan that showed
she had full-blown pseudo-obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pseudo-obstruction is very rare,'' said Andrea Anastas,
executive director of the American Pseudo Obstruction and
Hirschsprung's Disease Society. ``There are other gastrointestinal
disorders that mimic pseudo-obstruction. There are other tests
(doctors) are going to do before they jump to this conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bette Bond of Levittown, Pa., ate only from a feeding tube for
eight years because of constant gall bladder pain. She went through
$150,000 in three months for the nutrition costs and had to resort
to medical assistance. But the 30-year-old got back on her feet.
She now works full time as an occupational therapist, owns her home
and is engaged to be married.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see other people carrying pumps and being
connected,'' Bond said, referring to her fellow conventioneers.
``In normal, everyday life, you don't encounter a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much of American social life centered around food,
people with pseudo-obstructions find it difficult to always say no.
If Wu gets a craving for something, she enjoys it, but knows that
she's going to pay for it later. Bond said she finds her own
innovative way to socialize, such as carrying her own food to
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't . . never take another bite of food the rest of your
life,'' she said. ``You can't get away from eating. You can't stop
going out. You can't stop living because when you do you'll die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
