A6102 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-ADAMS-HIKELIST09-COX     07-07 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADAMS-HIKELIST09-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Yosemite hikes a Rocky Mountain high
</P>
<P>
   By Susan Laccetti Meyers
</P>
<P>
   Yosemite National Park offers many scenic vistas, but hikers get
the best views when they experience its beauty up close.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service offers visitors a list of recommended
hikes on marked trails in both the valley and the high country. My
husband and I strung a couple of these hikes together to make
wonderful days in the park.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of recommended hikes of varied levels:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lower Yosemite Falls. This easy, 1/2-mile-round-trip hike
begins at the falls parking lot and goes to the base of the falls.
There is lots of spray in spring and early summer. And you can
often see rainbows in front of the falls on spring mornings. The
hike is a flat, 20-minute trip.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing our hike for 5 1/2 miles, we followed the trail past
the park stables, along the base of 7,000-foot-high Royal Arches
outcrop and past the historic Ahwahnee Hotel to Mirror Lake. This
fairly level trail had little elevation gain and often crossed tiny
bridges over waterfalls and streams.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bridalveil Fall. Another easy hike, although there is a slight
elevation gain. The trail from the parking lot to the base of the
falls is a 1/2-mile-round-trip walk. The spray is enormous in
spring and early summer. We left here soaking wet (including the
camera).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Panorama Trail. This hike can be done only after the snow
melts in early summer. The trail is 8 1/2 miles and is a one-way
descent from Glacier Point to the valley floor. The park service
labels this one of the most spectacular trails for its bird's-eye
view down into the valley. The trail passes Nevada Fall before
finishing its 3,200-foot descent. Allow six hours for this moderate
hike.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vernal and Nevada falls. This moderate to strenuous hike can
be broken into two hikes. The hike to the Vernal Fall footbridge is
1.6 miles round trip and includes a 400-foot elevation gain. The
reward is an excellent view of the falls. To continue to the top of
the falls, you must hike one-half mile up more than 600 steps.
</P>
<P>
   To get to the top of Nevada Fall, continue past the top of
Vernal Fall an additional 2 miles along the Mist Trail, making it a
seven-mile-round-trip hike. This trail shaves very close to the
falls themselves. These hikes are often not open until summer
because of snow.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Half Dome. This hike on the famed granite outcrop is
recommended for skilledenuous, 17-mile-round-trip hike takes 10 to
12 hours and includes a 4,800-foot elevation gain. Cables are put
on the mountain to help with the climbing from mid-May until
mid-October. The park service warns not to attempt this climb if
there is any chance of rain, since most of the hike is on sheer
granite.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mariposa Grove. There are various trails throughout the grove,
but the most popular hike is to the Grizzly Giant sequoia tree
among the giant sequoias. This one-hour walk begins at the Mariposa
Grove parking lot. After reaching the 300-foot Grizzly Giant, you
can walk to Upper Grove, another three miles. We took an alternate
trail back through the north end of the grove to the parking lot,
and it was deserted and serene.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Upper Yosemite Falls. This strenuous hike takes six to eight
hours and begins at the Sunnyside Campground parking area. The
park's oldest trail, built in the mid-1870s, it leads to the top of
the world's fifth-largest waterfall. It looks easier than it is. At
7.2 miles round trip, plan on making a day of this hike.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tuolumne Meadows: Soda Springs. This is an easy,
1.5-mile-round-trip hike from the Lembert Dome parking lot on Tioga
Road. What makes this high-country hike through meadows unusual is
that carbonated water bubbles up through the ground at Soda
Springs. Unfortunately, it is believed to be contaminated, and the
park service recommends against drinking it.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Laccetti Meyers writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
