<HEADER>
A6103 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-ADAMS-PLAN09-COX     07-07 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADAMS-PLAN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A proposal to save the park from itself
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 9
 &HT;    By Susan Laccetti Meyers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone who visits Yosemite National Park loves its wide open
spaces, yet, ironically, room to roam can be precious in summer
because of all the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the seasonal tourist hordes, Interior Secretary
Bruce Babbitt recently unveiled a proposal for Yosemite that would
eliminate about 65 percent of parking spaces in Yosemite Valley and
reduce a lot of overnight accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   The park service plans to build satellite parking lots near the
valley's boundaries so visitors could take shuttle buses into the
valley. Officials also anticipate that the proposal would spur
hotel development just outside the 748,000-acre park.
</P>
<P>
   However, for the $343 million plan to be enacted, Congress would
have to fund it, something that may not be a priority with a new
president.
</P>
<P>
   During June, July and August, the park can average 21,000
visitors a day, compared with about 6,000 a day in spring or fall
and 3,400 a day in winter.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, the Yosemite Valley bottleneck can stretch up to
three miles. At the Wawona Road and El Portal Road entrance gates,
the wait to pay the $20 vehicle entrance fee can be 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, roads and bridges and structures have been
constructed, which, in some cases, have contributed to the sprawl
and crowding that visitors to Yosemite are trying to avoid,''
Babbitt said when he announced the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Under Babbitt's proposal, some roads and administrative
buildings in the valley would be torn out and lodging (excluding
campsites) sliced by 20 percent. This despite the fact that
overnight accommodations are at a premium, with rooms often booked
a year in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will not become official until public hearings are
finished this summer. After the hearings, the Interior Department
will review public concerns to consider any potential revisions.
The final plan should become policy in late December, when it is
expected to be signed by park service officials and the interior
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   This proposal has met resistance from some environmentalists _
who say it doesn't go far enough in eliminating cars and park
development _ and local business leaders, who fear it will scare
away tourists.
</P>
<P>
   _Susan Laccetti Meyers writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
