<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6104 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-ADAMS-YOSEMITE09-COX     07-07 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADAMS-YOSEMITE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ansel Adams' Yosemite
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 9.
 &HT;    By Susan Laccetti Meyers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSEMITE VALLEY, Calif. _ Photographer Ed McCormick stands on
Sentinel Bridge and points to an enormous granite outcrop known as
Half Dome, then to the fast-moving Merced River below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot downriver in the morning and upriver in the late
afternoon,'' McCormick advises 20 enthusiastic visitors, eager to
take pictures similar to the majestic landscapes of the late, great
photographer Ansel Adams. ``Watch for the light and emotional
impact the scene creates before you. That's what makes an image
successful. Light is everything, and photography is all about
reflective light. We are just capturing the reflective light off
the subject in front of us.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormick is carrying on the spirit of the legendary landscape
photographer by hosting a two-hour Ansel Adams camera walk in
748,000-acre Yosemite National Park. Adams, who died in 1984,
offered short photography lessons beginning in 1940 as a way for
aspiring photographers to experience this magnificient region of
the Sierra Nevadas through his lens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my destiny when I first experienced Yosemite,'' Adams
wrote in his autobiography. ``Yosemite Valley is a national
shrine.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams lived many years in Yosemite, then made it home away from
home after moving to Carmel, Calif., in 1961. His legacy is the
generations who have identified with his black-and-white images of
nature's grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Yosemite draws 3.6 million visitors a year _ making it one of
the busiest National Park Service sites _ and many credit Adams'
photos for the park's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This park has an international reputation because of Ansel
Adams' photography,'' said the Rev. David Johnson, a Welches, Ore.,
minister who was on the camera walk with his wife, Carol Jean.
``Every year I have to have an Ansel Adams calendar of the park.
Now I want to see the vantage points firsthand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ansel Adams camera walks are offered three days a week in
high season, and one of those days the instructor focuses on
black-and-white photography. The walks are free and sponsored by
the Ansel Adams Gallery, located next to the park visitors center.
The gallery also offers more in-depth, multiday photography
workshops, costing about $100 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to see the park from Adams' perspective is
independently hiking to many of the places he photographed:
Yosemite Falls, Half Dome, Mariposa Grove, Mirror Lake, Vernal
Fall, El Capitan, Bridalveil Fall, Tuolumne Meadows and Tenya Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Adams fell instantly in love with Yosemite in 1916 at age 14,
when his family visited from San Francisco. ``The splendor of
Yosemite burst upon us and it was glorious,'' he wrote of the
experience. ``Little clouds were gathering in the sky above the
granite cliffs, and the mists of Bridalveil Fall shimmered in the
sun.''
</P>
<P>
   The park's staggering beauty later inspired him to forgo a
career as a concert pianist _ for which he had studied _ and choose
photography instead. In 1928, Adams married Virginia Best in
Yosemite Valley at Best's Studios, her father's gallery, which
showed paintings by local landscape artists. The gallery would
later exhibit Adams' famous photos and today operates as the Ansel
Adams Gallery. My husband and I visited Yosemite in spring, and it
was easy to tap into the passion Adams had for the park. Spring is
when the snowmelt feeds the multitude of waterfalls to full force.
I had been here before in the fall, and no matter the season, the
park's beauty is so overwhelming that we felt like we were standing
in a painting. Many times, all we could say was, ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   The temptation to shoot photos of mule deer, wildflowers, the
Merced, giant sequoias, snowcapped peaks, granite cliffs, alpine
lakes and tranquil meadows made roll after roll of film disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cSentinel Bridge and Cook's Meadow. Adams' most famous
Yosemite photo, the 1960 shot of ``Moon at Half Dome,'' was taken
at Ahwahnee Meadow, near the stately Ahwahnee Hotel in the valley,
McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   Another prime place to take a picture of Yosemite Falls is from
the Yosemite Chapel. Shooting from behind the chapel, with the
highest waterfall in North America (2,425 feet) in the background,
was postcard-perfect.
</P>
<P>
   During our four-day visit, we hoped to see the much-raved-about
Tuolumne Meadows, a high-country zone of meadows, lakes and peaks
that is a three-day hike from Yosemite Valley (or a 90-minute
drive). The high country was a favorite of Adams, who was away on a
monthlonark boundaries either in Yosemite Valley, the south end of
the park or in the high-country lodgings (seasonal).
</P>
<P>
   Curry Village, open in the valley year-round, offers three types
of accommodations. Canvas tent cabins are $39.75 daily, regular
wood cabins without bath $57.25 and cabins with baths $74.75.
</P>
<P>
   The motel-like Yosemite Lodge, at the base of Yosemite Falls,
offers rooms for $99.75-$124.75 in peak season (April through
November) and $84.25-$101.50 in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The historic Ahwahnee Hotel has upscale hotel rooms ranging from
$279.50 to $821 nightly most of the year, $253.53-$745.51 in
December and January. A national historic landmark, the circa-1926
Ahwahnee offers all the amenities of a big-city hotel, including
the gourmet Ahwahnee Dining Room (dinner jacket required).
</P>
<P>
   The best place to stay in the south end of the park is the
Wawona Hotel, circa 1879, near the Mariposa Grove of giant
sequoias. Rooms run $94-$128.75 from April to October. During the
off-season, room rates begin at $84 nightly.
</P>
<P>
   In the high country in summer, accommodations may be available
at the Tuolumne Meadows Lodge and White Wolf Lodge. These
metal-framed canvas tent cabins, similar to ones in Curry Village,
have old-fashioned wood stoves and are open from mid-June until
early September. They run $48.50-$52.75.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations may be made up to one year and one day in advance
through Yosemite Concession Services Corp., 559-252-4848 or
YosemitePark
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   CAMERA WALK INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   To sign up for an Ansel Adams camera walk, log on to
www.anseladams.com. They are offered different days during
different seasons but are always free. The multiday workshops,
known as the Ansel Adams Gallery Photography Workshops, usually
cost about $100 per day. One four-day workshop available later this
month, for example, will take participants through the Yosemite
high country and to Mono Lake, outside the park's eastern boundary.
</P>
<P>
   Information on those workshops, too, can be found at
www.anseladams.com or 1-800-568-7398.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Laccetti Meyers writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitutionl.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
