<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6105 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR0708-COX     07-07 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABy Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMOGES, France _ Five years ago, Lance Armstrong was an
entirely different cyclist, far removed from the overall athlete
and defending Tour de France champion that he is today.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite what he accomplished last year, it was here in
Southern France in 1995 that Armstrong created what he still to
this day considers his most cherished sporting memory.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong rode conservatively Friday afternoon and remained 12th
overall as he neared the Pyrenees Mountains. Five years ago this
month, he picked up a stage win in Limoges, the second of his
career, and the last time until Friday that the Tour made a stop in
this city known for its intricate porcelain.
</P>
<P>
   And he dedicated that stage win immediately to his fallen
teammate, Fabio Casartelli, who had died three days before. As
Armstrong crossed the finish line that afternoon, wearing the
colors of Team Motorola, tears were in his eyes as he pointed
toward the sky.
</P>
<P>
   His thoughts were with Casartelli on Friday afternoon as he rode
in the middle of the peloton into Limoges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is a special place for me,'' Armstrong said
after completing stage seven. ``To this day, this is my greatest
memory in cycling because I didn't do it for myself, I did it for
Fabio.''
</P>
<P>
   Casartelli had been a popular teammate with Motorola and one of
the squad's biggest names. The gregarious Italian had won an
Olympic gold medal in 1992. He had a baby just beginning to walk
back home in Italy when he started the 1995 Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loved Fabio,'' said Bill Stapleton, Armstrong's
agent.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Tour had gotten through the majority of the
mountain stages in 1995, Spaniard Miguel Indurain was wearing
yellow and in control of the race. On the final mountain stage in
the Pyrenees, Casartelli was trying to get down the du
Portet-d'Aspet, when he crashed off the course. He hit his head and
died immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after Casartelli's death, Armstrong found himself
among a pack of eight breakaway riders who had left the peloton.
About 12 miles from the finish line, Armstrong broke free of the
group. He finished the final miles alone to claim the stage victory
on his way to completing his first-ever Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was such a hard-fought victory,'' recalled Chris
Carmichael, Armstrong's longtime coach. ``And I remembered how he
pointed toward the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on a team like this, you get really close to these
guys. You're with them 24 hours a day. Fabio's death really
affected Lance.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years removed from that stage victory, Armstrong is
defending his Tour title. On Friday, he was biding his time for the
Pyrenees, riding in the main group of riders who finished 1 minute,
11 seconds in back of Christophe Agnolutto.
</P>
<P>
   Like Armstrong did five years ago, Agnolutto claimed his stage
win by riding solo. Except the 31-year-old Frenchmen rode by
himself for much of the rainswept race, going alone for the final
79.67 miles and finishing in 5 hours, 11 minutes, 42 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Agnolutto started celebrating about 10 feet from the finish line
as he acknowledged the loud cheers from his fiercely proud
compatriots. Until Agnolutto, no French rider had claimed a stage
victory since Jacky Durand did so eight stages into the 1998 Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's race did little to change the overall standings.
Telekom's Alberto Elli still was wearing yellow, after going
through the seven stages in 24 hours, 11 minutes, 32 seconds.
Armstrong is 5:54 behind.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
