<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6106 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ARTS-PROJECTS09-COX     07-07 1737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-PROJECTS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong economy is driving a cultural building boom
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 9.
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to our audio tour of new museums. (Please adjust your
headset volume to a comfortable level.)
</P>
<P>
   Beep.
</P>
<P>
   In the upper left-hand corner of our gallery _ that would be
Tennessee _ you can see two vastly different works. The white art
deco building being gutted and renovated is Nashville's former
downtown post office, built in 1934, the future home of the Frist
Center for the Visual Arts. What's unusual about the Frist is that
it's being built exclusively to host traveling mega-exhibits; it
won't collect art of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Beep.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the Frist, note the burst of activity southwest of
downtown. That's the Cheekwood Museum of Art and Botanical Garden
on the 55 acres of the former Cheek family estate. That freshly cut
swath through the woods is its 1.2-mile sculpture trail. Note the
light flashing from the nearby stables; that's from the video
installations running in each of the remodeled stalls, reborn as
part of the contemporary art galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Beep.
</P>
<P>
   Please move to the center of the gallery and turn to your right.
Consider Savannah. See the sparks flying from the historic
district? Feel the tension in the sultry air? That's where
preservationists and arts leaders are dueling over the details of
the Telfair Museum of Art expansion, a contemporary design
struggling to gain a foothold amid the city's storied squares.
</P>
<P>
   Beep.
</P>
<P>
   Now walk across the lower half of the room, toward the Gulf of
Mexico. Recognize Tampa? You may not in a few years. Plans are
under way to reshape downtown with a cultural district anchored by
a new building for the Tampa Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Beep.
</P>
<P>
   That's the end of this abbreviated tour, but just the beginning
of the story.
</P>
<P>
   When the High Museum of Art in Atlanta completes plans for a
building expansion costing at least $60 million, it won't have the
only crane on the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 other cities in the Southeast are engineering new
art museums or expanding existing facilities in a major way. Just
about everywhere you look _ Biloxi, Miss.; Mobile; New Orleans;
Raleigh _ some city is looking to enhance its cultural calling card
with art repositories. Total cost of this building boom: an
estimated $325 million.
</P>
<P>
   Add the art museums being rolled out in Texas _ in Houston,
Dallas, Fort Worth, Austin, Corpus Christi _ and the South's
current projected expenditures for new building easily surpass half
a billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is hardly a regional phenomenon. Riding the strong
economy, a museum boom has reverberated around the country
throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   It includes history, science and children's museums, but art
museums ``lead the pack,'' says Jack Nokes, director of the Texas
Association of Museums in Austin. They draw the most visitors and
tend to have the richest patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Big museums opened in San Francisco and Los Angeles in the
1990s. Houston's Museum of Fine Arts expansion was unveiled this
year. New York's Museum of Modern Art is planning an expansion the
projected cost of which has reached a staggering $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the whole Zeitgeist of the country,'' says Diane
Lesko, director of the Telfair Museum of Art in Savannah. ``Museums
in the past 15 to 20 years have been trying to become nonexclusive,
to reach out to all aspects of the community, and it's working. The
lines between going to Disney World and going to the museum are
becoming more muddled.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit entrepreneurs
</P>
<P>
   Varied programming is one reason museums are reaching a wider
audience. They've courted families and casual visitors with
affordable, innovative shows that appeal to more mainstream taste.
Impressionism and big-name retrospectives _ Picasso, Matisse,
Norman Rockwell _ have been enormously successful for the High
Museum, where family membership for a year is still a modest $75;
that includes admission for two adults and children 17 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret why the Southeast has gotten caught up in museum
mania _ these facilities play an important role for cities building
their cultural-tourism clout. A recent Wall Street Journal story
noted that museums annually outdraw major-league baseball teams.
According to the National Endowment for the Arts, art museums
outdraw science museums and botanical gardens, respectively, by
almost a 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art museums have become community gathering places and
destinations for visitors from out of the region,'' says Lawrence
Wheeler, director of the North Carolina Museum of Art in Raleigh,
which is raising money for a new building projected to cost about
$60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Success at the turnstiles has prompted a space crunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very clever programmers out there who know how
to get people excited,'' Wheeler says. ``As a result, most of these
(existing) museums have become too small.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stretched to the max,'' says Lani Czyzewski, spokeswoman
for the Tampa Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because there are no national data tracking museum
expansion, the busy rate of building activity in the Southeast
comes as a surprise to some.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unaware of most of it,'' says Michael Shapiro, director
of the High Museum of Art. ``But it's compelling testimony that the
arts are in the ascent in the Southeast. It only confirms
everything we're experiencing here in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Some call this proliferation of art museums part of the region's
cultural maturation. As Southern cities have landed various
professional sports franchises, they're seeking other ways to raise
their profiles and reach out to another kind of tourist.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's precisely the thinking here,'' says Emily Kass,
director of the Tampa Museum of Art. ``What's unique about this is
that it's not San Francisco and New York, it's Mobile and St. Pete
and Nashville.''
</P>
<P>
   Museums have also worked hard to shed their elitist image and
become aggressive entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're working with other community entities _ schools,
service groups _ to broaden their base of support,'' says Esther
Hockett, executive director of the Southeastern Museums Conference
in Baton Rouge, La. ``It doesn't always turn into financial gain,
but it helps as an attitude thing. People say, `If the museum is
going to be there for us in more a broad-based way, then we need to
be there for the museum.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, improvement doesn't always mean getting into the
expensive field of art collection or throwing up a new building.
</P>
<P>
   In Nashville, surveys showed that people were tired of seeing
huge popular exhibits bypass the city and opt instead for, say,
Memphis. So the Frist Center will operate as an exhibition center
filled with rotating collections on loan from museums around the
world. It will also borrow from Nashville institutions and
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Another Tennessee facility, the Hunter Museum of American Art in
Chattanooga, designed an expansion, but decided against building it
when officials discovered there would be little left over for
operating costs. Instead, the museum spent $2 million on
renovations and funneled the remaining funds into its endowment _
which, says director Cleve Scarbrough, has reached $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many art institutions get so ambitious and so excited, they
end up sticking their necks out too far,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   At Nashville's Cheekwood, one of the more popular features of a
recent expansion _ a sculpture trail with 16 pieces of art _ cost
less than $10,000. ``We got some chain saws and a chip machine and
put a trail in the woods,'' says museum director John Wetenhall.
``It's the biggest and best part of our expansion. We took
advantage of natural space that architects can't reproduce and
historical buildings that already existed.''
</P>
<P>
   History vs. expansion
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's nothing like the architectural splendor of a new
museum to stir enthusiasm and grab headlines. In Savannah, however,
a dispute between the forces of historic preservation and
contemporary art is at the heart of the most problematic among the
region's expansions.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, the Telfair Museum of Art has had
Boston-based architect Moshe Safdie redesigning his $16 million
expansion to meet the strict building requirements of that city's
historic district. The annex design calls for a glassy, modern
building to house contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   The sticking point for the city's historic review board is a
bridge over York Lane, an alleyway that bisects the two lots on
which the expansion will be built. Such lanes are strenuously
protected in the design standards adopted for the historic
district, and the board has rejected Safdie's revisions. Another
vote is scheduled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem,'' says Telfair director Lesko, ``is that some
people (on the review board) don't appreciate anything modern and
don't like this building or this architect.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the museum expansions slated for the Southeast vary
in size, shape and mission. Yet museum leaders invariably agree on
one point: The good times won't last forever, and when the economy
takes a downturn, you'd better have a substantial endowment stashed
away _ a savings account that's protected from roller-coaster
economics and political mood swings.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the Southeast's bricks-and-mortar boom is being
accompanied by campaigns to raise endowment funds to operate the
buildings. The Norton Museum of Art in West Palm Beach, Fla., is
raising $20 million for its expansion, but only $12 million is
slated for the new building; the rest is for endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Says Tampa's Kass: ``One of the scarier prospects is, what
happens when the building boom ends and we have all these great
museums? We have to make sure we can fulfill their promise.''
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM INFORMATION
</P>
