<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6107 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-EARLE09-COX     07-07 2120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Americana pushes an edgier country mix
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 9
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nashville singer-songwriter Steve Earle's new album,
``Transcendental Blues,'' winds around the roots of nearly every
form of music that springs from the hearts and history of plain
people _ henpecking bluegrass, lonely Hank Williams country/blues,
Cajun fiddles, bouncy cantina accordion, working-class rock _ with
lyrics about being lonely, broke, tired, in love and even taking
that long, last walk down death row.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a country song, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not in today's Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   You're not going to hear much of anything new on mainstream
country radio that sounds remotely like the unpolished origins of
the genre, the sounds of the front porch, church choir, beer joint,
cotton fields or street corner. Not even hall-of-famers Johnny Cash
or Willie Nelson get much airplay. Too country.
</P>
<P>
   But over the commercial fence, out there in small music halls
and home recording studios, are a slew of younger purists who
travel the musical road laid by the Carters, Jimmie Rogers, Bill
Monroe, Bob Wills, Loretta Lynn and Willie Nelson. Acts such as
Earle, Texas troubadour Jimmie Dale Gilmore and soulful
singer-songwriter Shelby Lynne (who all appear in back-to-back
shows at Variety Playhouse this week), have always cared more about
how they sound than how they're selling.
</P>
<P>
   For years, this nonconformist attitude just about guaranteed you
would spend your career in noble pursuit of your muse while living
in mainstream obscurity and torn-sofa poverty. But today, Earle
sits on a deck overlooking his pool at his home outside Nashville,
basking in the glow of a No. 1 record, sales of 20,000 albums in
the first week of release, and more glowing reviews from major
publications that he can fit in a press kit.
</P>
<P>
   Earle and many other of the loose collection of artists who have
been labeled alternative country are gaining clout professionally
and personally as the music format known as Americana gains
momentum around the country, no doubt something of a backlash
against pop-oriented, mainstream country.
</P>
<P>
   ``My suspicion is we're on the verge of a new outlaw movement,''
says Jessie Scott, Americana editor of the music industry trade
publication, the Gavin Report. ``I think we potentially could
herald the next style of country.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least influence it heavily.
</P>
<P>
   What is Americana? It is perhaps best described as what it isn't
_ commercial or predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defining this music is something we have actively resisted
doing,'' explains Grant Alden, 41, co-editor of the alternative
country magazine No Depression. ``It is song- and lyric-driven
music that has some connection to this country's musical past. That
may be Hank Williams' past or a Duke Ellington past or a Woody
Guthrie past or a Robert Johnson past.''
</P>
<P>
   Although elusive, the common denominator for the genre is a long
taproot that reaches back to regional or country music. But the
roster of artists who now consider themselves Americana are wildly
diverse in style, from the Appalachian wails of Gillian Welch to
the honky tonk rockabilly of BR5-49 or the passionate,
country-tinged rock of Lucinda Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The three artists performing in Atlanta this week are
representative cornerstones of this burgeoning musical family.
</P>
<P>
   With his weathered face and thin, shoulder-length hair, Gilmore
looks more like a 19th-century daguerreotype than a star. With his
mystical lyrics and high-nasal tenor, he has more in common with
Mother Maybelle Carter than Tim McGraw. Lynne is this year's
Americana breakout star. After dabbling in mainstream country in
Nashville in the early 90s, she headed west and hooked up with
Sheryl Crow's former producer, Brian Bottrell. The result is the
critically acclaimed ``I Am Shelby Lynne,'' which springs from the
place where soul meets country. Tattooed Earle draws as much from
gritty, L.A. rock as country. His latest album mixes in some world
music touches _ accordion, harmonium_ but carries on the winning
formula that's made him a star of the format: This is his fourth
album to debut at No. 1 on the Americana charts.
</P>
<P>
   Though roots music has found a home on college and arts radio
stations since the Austin-based ``progressive'' country movement of
the '70s, it was formally dubbed ``Americana'' in the early '90s by
programmers who felt the pop-leanings of mainstream country were
leaving many artists without a forum. Radio stations exclusively
dedicated to the format began springing up around the country,
including WMLB/1170 AM in Cumming, which switched from current
country to Americana in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   For years, they remained a mostly under-the-radar collection of
static-riddled AM signals, or FM frequencies that weren't major
spots on the dial. And for the most part, like WMLB (which you
can't even pick up inside the Perimeter), they still are.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of stations dedicated to the Americana format in
the U.S. has grown from a handful to an estimated 150+. And they
are starting to coalesce as a force in the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Gavin began the country's first Americana music chart,
to officially track airplay of alternative country music. In five
years, it has grown into one of the publication's most sought-after
sources of information. (www.gavin.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In March, a group of musicians, producers and radio
programmers formed the Americana Music Association, dedicated to
promoting the format through radio airplay, publicity and
marketing. Their cheeky slogan (lifted from the Man in Black
himself, Johnny Cash): ``We Walk the Line.''
(www.americanamusic.org)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Americana artists have begun to sell records beyond their
small fan bases. In the past year, acts such as Earle, honky-tonk
torch singer Kelly Willis, Texas swing/boogie band Asleep at the
Wheel, and sweet-voiced bluegrass fiddler Alison Krauss scored gold
records based on Americana airplay.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Perhaps most significantly, Americana is turning out to be the
most popular radio format people turn to when it comes to Internet
listening. When the Arbitron Co. launched its first survey of
audiostream Web listening last October, three of the top radio
sites were Americana stations: KFAN-FM in Fredericksburg, Texas,
KPIG in Monterey, Calif. (www.kpig.com), and KHYI-FM in Plano,
Texas (www.khyi.com).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For the first time, corporate radio has expressed interest in
programming Americana. Atlanta-based Cumulus Communications is
experimenting with the 100,000-watt KBCY/99.5 FM in Abilene, Texas,
by yanking some of the newer Nashville music and replacing it with
tunes by Americana artists. And major labels in Nashville are
starting to sign a few of these acts: Hank Williams III on Curb
Records, Neal Cody on Mercury, Charlie Robison on Monument.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Tony Brown, head of MCA Records, is one of the few
power brokers in Nashville who has shaped the careers of both
Americana artists and mainstream country acts. The one-time
keyboardist for Elvis Presley has not only produced George Strait,
Wynonna, Vince Gill, and Reba McEntire; he is known as a risk-taker
who also signed Kelly Willis, Marty Stuart, the Mavericks, Lynne
and Earle to a major label.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Brown produced Earle's debut MCA album, ``Guitar
Town,'' a poetic musical journey about crawling out of smalltown
Texas. Though it didn't spawn a hit nor make Earle a country star,
the very country record is widely considered a classic _ and early
Americana.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first came out, there wasn't such a thing as
Americana,'' Brown says of ``Guitar Town.'' ``It was honest, and
anytime you do an honest record it just makes more of an impact
than if it is trying to meet the supply and demand of radio.''
</P>
<P>
   He now thinks the album clearly foreshadowed the emergence of
the Americana format, ``which at first everybody felt was a passing
phase. But it's become a good term, and it doesn't seem to be going
away. You can see that the creative sector of the music industry
definitely wants it to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   So, who's listening?
</P>
<P>
   The typical Americana fan more than likely grew up listening to
alternative country artists _ such as Gram Parsons, Emmylou Harris,
Joe Ely, Kinky Friedman, John Prine, Commander Cody. Throw in a
little Grateful Dead (on the left) and Johnny Cash (on the right),
and you have the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Alden says he created No Drepression magazine for this group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of generations of people who discovered
through college radio that there was music outside the mainstream
that was interesting. They've gotten older, so punk and ska don't
interest them anymore. But they know there is something outside the
Backstreet Boys, and they are looking for something. They grew up
with an AM radio out in the garage or in dad's car that played
old-time country music, so it has a welcoming quality to it. As my
generation begins to settle a little bit, things that sound like
home aren't so bad. If it has an edge and sounds like home, it's
even better. That why Steve Earle and Jimmie Dale (Gilmore) are
attractive to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Scott, Nashville editor of the Americana charts for the
music industry trade publication, the Gavin Report (a smaller
version of Billboard) thinks Americana could be described as
``grunge country,'' since it tends to lean toward self-examination
and expressiveness rather than glamor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adults who felt alienated by pop and rock in the early '90s
gave country its huge boost in popularity at that time, because
they were drawn to people like Mary Chapin Carpenter and Dwight
Yoakam,'' Scott says. ``Then country got seduced by MTV. They made
it younger, more like rock, more visually oriented as opposed to
aurally oriented. We saw belly buttons for the first time. And that
didn't speak to the original people who came over to country. And
some of them are finding Americana.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoughit's unlikely the Americana format will ever take away the
majority of mainstream country's audience, it may put the pressure
on Music Row to get back to basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are adults out there who want to hear music,'' says
Earle, who was recently on the cover of the Gavin Report under the
headline ``Americana Kingpin.'' ``But we've created a situation
where it genuinely isn't profitable to have artists who sell less
than 200,000...Record companies aren't just owned by corporations.
They are owned by the most powerful telecommunications companies in
the world. That makes labels kind of a slave to shareholders. So
you're not selling records, you're selling stock. And there ain't
nothin' more anti-art than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom-line broadcasting execs such John Dickey, vice president
of Atlanta-based broadcasting group Cumulus Communications,
question whether Americana will ever be more than an arty stepchild
in the dollars-and-cents world of radio and records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't qualify it as a full-force, homegrown, grassroots
cry for this type of music,'' he says. ``I haven't seen anything
quantitatively that all country programmers should be paying
attention to, or to indicate it's the next big thing in country
music...We own 55 country stations, and what we're seeing in all
the market research is a return to the gold stuff from the late
'80s and early '90s...Country's shares have receded by 20 percent
around the U.S. Stations can't play every me-too act Nashville
throws at them. Americana is hitting on a sensitive chord.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, mavericks of Americana such as Earle _ who are the
antithesis of the 8x10 glossy world of Music Row _ are definitely
feeling new appreciation for their art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm digustingly happy,'' Earle says, eyeing the first date
here in Atlanta of his upcoming tour. ``I'm selling more records
than I have in a long time. I've never been a priority at a record
label before. Nobody is mad at me, and I'm not mad at anybody. We
had to scramble to find $25,000 to make a video, but we did and now
it's going to VH1...I wake up in the morning and do something I
love to do for a living, and I'm grateful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To hear selections from Americana artists, dial 511 and enter
8600 and Soundline number 427 for Steve Earle or 428 for Jimmie
Dale Tilmore and Shelby Lynne. Each call costs 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   CONCERT PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jimmie Dale Gilmore,
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday, $15.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shelby Lynne, 8 p.m. Monday, $15.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Steve Earle, 8 p.m. Tuesday, $22.50.
</P>
<P>
   Variety Playhouse, 1099 Euclid Ave. N.E., 404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
