r l BC-POTTER-BRAILLE08-COX     07-07 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTTER-BRAILLE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Harry' goes to Braille in record time
 &HT;    By Kirk Kicklighter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Robyn Herrera'sson John, 7, loves Harry Potter books.
``He reads them every chance he gets,'' said Herrera, as she
browsed through children's titles at the National Federation of the
Blind convention at Atlanta's Marriott Marquis this week. ``He's
really pumped about the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   The newest book, ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' was
released today, the same day Scholastic Press publishers
transmitted the book electronically to the National Braille Press
in Boston. John, who is blind, will have to wait a couple of weeks
to get his own edition of Harry Potter IV printed in Braille the
system of printing and writing for the blind using raised dots that
are felt with the fingersTen percent of books published in the
United States are printed in Braille, and most of those are delayed
a year or more before they are transferred from the written word.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a big difference that he'll be able to get the book
near the same time as his friends,'' said Herrera. ``He won't feel
left out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braille copies are thick; about seven notebook-size volumes
make up one book. ``But the kids don't mind it one bit ... they say
the bigger the better,'' said Diane Croft of National Braille
Press. ``Just like people with sight, blind children love to have
books they can hold and browse through.''
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 55,000 blind children younger than 18 in
the United States. About 10 percent of them can read Braille. That
number was closer to 50 percent before books on tape became
available. ``There's a handicap much worse than blindness _ it's
call illiteracy,'' said Croft.
</P>
<P>
   The NBP, which publishes a children's book each month and has
offered volumes since 1927, plans a first run of 500 for the new
Potter book. A typical run is 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll print more and more if we have to,'' said Croft.
``Adults want it, too. One woman told me her fingers were going
numb because she couldn't stop reading Harry Potter.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Kicklighter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
