<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6109 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SKUBE-COLUMN09-COX     07-07 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Potter's popularity aside, epic prevails
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 9.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it weren't for Jerry Hall, it might very well have been the
``national humiliation'' that Anthony Holden feared.
</P>
<P>
   People at first wondered why Hall, the supermodel and ex-wife of
Mick Jagger, should be on the jury in the first place. And not only
Hall but also the actress Imogen Stubbs and the politician Ann
Widdecombe. Here you had one of the most prestigious literary
awards in Britain, the Whitbread Prize, and the jury was packed
with pop culture celebrities and a politician. No one needed to ask
if the sun had set for good on the British Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter's invisible cloak was suddenly quite visible and a
bit irritating.
</P>
<P>
   It was one thing to please the kiddies, but when Pottermania
nearly trumps a Nobel Prize-winning poet things are out of hand. By
a 5-4 vote, and only after much acrimony, in January the Whitbread
jury awarded the prize to Seamus Heaney for his new translation of
``Beowulf.'' Heaney must have been humbled even in a moment of
honor, his contemporary rendering of a 1,000-year-old epic
entangled in so unedifying a debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beowulf,'' said those wanting to award the prize to J.K.
Rowling's ``The Prisoner of Azkaban,'' was what it had always been
_ ``a boring book about dragons.'' They liked Rowling's dragons
better, to say nothing of the orphan Potter himself, riding his
broom and slashing his magic wand.
</P>
<P>
   No one wanted to begrudge the kids a good time, and _ brows are
mopped here _ at least they were reading. But a fable that's been
around a while was one thing and hokum about Hogwarts School of
Witchcraft and Wizardry another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shall dissociate myself from (the Whitbread) publicly,''
Holden, a biographer and a juror for the prize, harrumphed during
the deliberations. Joining him, Hall, Stubbs and Widdecombe lobbied
for literature over entertainment, and thus was the English
language spared unspeakable embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers know hard cases make bad law. A 5-4 decision by the U.S.
Supreme Court portends future litigation. But don't tell 3.8
million kids that the jury's still out on their hero. And don't
tell the marketers who've adopted Harry that orphans should be
cared for but not made pecuniary princes.
</P>
<P>
   It was inevitable. The marketing phenomenon would overwhelm the
story. Harry was born in children's imagination as a character,
fabulous in the fullest sense. He will die there as another
commodity.
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable did not happen with C.S. Lewis' Chronicles of
Narnia books, still popular half a century after they were written.
But they are not only of a different time; they were also written
in a culture in which media and marketing had not yet become the
twin engines of commerce. True enough, the Potter books at first
sold by word-of-mouth, but the money men soon caught wind and saw
their real potential: Take a perfectly good-natured, often witty,
unfailingly perky tale, toss in vague allegories of Good and Evil
and get the train rolling. Harry's magic wand turns everything it
touches to green.
</P>
<P>
   Before Scholastic Press spilled the beans two weeks ago, the
title of Harry IV was a tightly held secret. But it hardly
mattered. ``They could call it `Harry Potter and the Brown Paper
Bag,' and it would still sell out,'' one publishing executive said.
</P>
<P>
   One can hardly blame Rowling, a single mother on public
assistance only a few years ago, for cashing in. You'd do it, and I
don't know that I'd be above it myself. ``She's not
anti-merchandising at all,'' says Daniel Romanelli of Warner Bros.,
which will market Harry toys by the truckload. ``She's very
pro-Harry Potter.'' The man is either disingenuous or naive.
</P>
<P>
   The more Harry Potter becomes a marketing phenomenon, the less
it matters whether the books are swell or just so-so. The less
reason there is to read the stories for what they are or to enjoy
Rowling's language for its charms. The latter are taken for
granted, and rather too readily. There are, truth be told, delights
on almost every page. But there are also passages like this, from
``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone,'' the snowflake that
became a snowball that became an avalanche:
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, Gryffindors passing the giant hourglasses that
recorded the house points the next day thought there'd been a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beowulf'' has its difficulties, but this is not especially
wonderful prose. Neither is it a single bad sentence unable to hide
itself; there are others. Kids, especially younger ones, haven't
learned what good prose is and adults have forgotten, if they ever
knew.
</P>
<P>
   The contretemps over the Whitbread Prize is more comedic than
instructive. I keep thinking instead of an 8-year-old girl from
Chattanooga named Gracie McGuire. She told me she liked the Harry
Potter books because she can ``really imagine in my head what all
the characters and places looked like.'' She could imagine them so
well, in fact, that she didn't even want anybody to make a movie of
Harry Potter. It could never be like the picture she already has.
The movie deal's already in the works, but no writer wishes for
much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
