<HEADER>
A6110 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-STEVEHARVEY08-QA-COX     07-07 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEVEHARVEY08-QA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harvey's triumph of `incredible will'
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't let this unusual combo of music and comedy confuse you.
Power belter Eddie Levert and his capable O'Jays will stick to the
band's fat catalog of R&AMP;B hits while Steve Harvey, star of the
recent top-rated television show in black households (``The Steve
Harvey Show''), does the funny stuff, like this revealing round of
``20 Questions'':
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which word or phrase do you most overuse?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``You ain't gonna believe this but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What don't you say often enough?
</P>
<P>
   A: Wow. I don't compliment my wife (Mary) enough. You can never
do that too much.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is your greatest regret?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not going into comedy sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What took you so long?
</P>
<P>
   A: I didn't know how to get into it. I sold life insurance,
worked for a carpet cleaning company, General Electric, sold Amway,
owned a rib joint ...
</P>
<P>
   Q: And what led to comedy?
</P>
<P>
   A: Um, as you can tell, my obvious inability to hold a job.
Basically, while I was doing all of those other things I was
writing jokes for another comedian, and someone said, since you're
writing them, why don't you do them yourself? And I did.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which historical figure do you most identify with?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a combination of Malcolm X and Martin Luther King Jr. I
try to do it peaceful but if you ain't gonna have it that way, then
I'll slap you (big laugh). Fine with me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your most treasured possession?
</P>
<P>
   A: My children (two boys and two girls).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Children aren't really possessions are they?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, yes they are! (Another laugh) They're mine!
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which talent would you most like to have?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'd love to be a basketball coach ... because I love
motivating young men.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you like most about yourself?
</P>
<P>
   A: My will. That's my strongest asset. I have an incredible
will. Tremendous drive. I will things into existence. I pray to God
about it, then put the hard work in behind the faith. That equals
success.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the trait you most deplore in others?
</P>
<P>
   A: Laziness. I hate that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the trait you most deplore in yourself?
</P>
<P>
   A: I work too much. (In addition to ``The Steve Harvey Show,''
he hosts ``Showtime at the Apollo'' and is considering a morning
radio announcer position, he says). I'm a workaholic.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which living person do you most admire?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm going to lose some fans off this one I know. The safe
answer is (famed O.J. Simpson attorney) Johnnie Cochran. My daring
answer, the real one, the one that people would misunderstand, is
Louis Farrakhan ... because of the Million Man March. No one could
else could have come up with the concept. No one else could have
gotten a million black people to do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the quality you most like in a woman?
</P>
<P>
   A: Wow, there are so many... I like a woman with spirit. Get up
and go. A woman that's a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the quality you most like in a man?
</P>
<P>
   A: Spirit. A man's spirit. His ability to get up when he falls
and stand when they push him down. When he has the spirt and
determination to be whatever he's going to be. That's how I pick my
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who's your favorite hero of movies?
</P>
<P>
   A: Whatever Denzel Washington is playing, because he's the man.
His roles are always positive and he's the finest actor I've ever
seen. And he doesn't get enough credit for his work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was the last time you read a book and what was it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, I just finished one, and it was a good one, too,
``Monster (The Autobiography of an L.A. Gang Member,'' by Kody
Scott). Best book I've ever read outside of the Bible. It was just
real. It was telling things the way they are and that's how I like
doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the best album of '99?
</P>
<P>
   A: Whitney Houston's (``My Love Is Your Love''). Banging!
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the best rumor about yourself that you've ever heard?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's funny. I haven't heard any good rumors because they're
usually negative. But I guess I haven't heard one because people
don't talk about me. People are scared of me. I'll confront you.
I'll call you. Get up in your face!
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you see when you look in the mirror?
</P>
<P>
   A: Um (long pause). I see two things: Pain, but then I see
strength to overcome pain.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Harvey and the O'Jays
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight. $45, $50. Fox Theatre, 660 Peachtree St. N.E.
Ticketmaster, 404-249-6400 or www
</P>
<P>
   .ticketmaster
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
