<HEADLINE>
RICHARD PETTY, AT NHIS, OFFERS SOLACE TO IRWIN FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ On the day Richard Petty returned to New
Hampshire International Speedway for the first time since his
grandson, Adam, was killed, tragedy struck the NASCAR community
again.
</P>
<P>
   Petty spoke with reporters Friday morning about his grandson's
crash. At around noon, Kenny Irwin was killed in another Turn 3
crash _ yards away from where Adam was killed May 12.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Petty issued a statement on behalf of the entire Petty
family through Petty Enterprises spokesman Chip Williams: ``The
Petty family would like to extend our deepest sympathies to the
Irwin family. Our thoughts and prayers are, and will continue to
be, with the Irwin family and the employees of Team SABCO (Irwin's
racing team) during this very difficult time.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty, in his 15 minutes with reporters in the morning, said he
and other family members continue to struggle with Adam's death. He
said they have tried to stay busy, so as not to dwell on it. He
said it often doesn't enter his mind unless someone brings it up.
</P>
<P>
   But Petty said coming to NHIS was part of the mourning process _
not only for him but for his son, Kyle, Adam's father.
</P>
<P>
   Petty said he arrived in Loudon Thursday at 6 p.m., but had not
surveyed the turn where his grandson died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of hard to make a decision to come at all. But the
Bahre family (owners of NHIS) has been so nice that I said, `Look,
I've got to face this one day anyway,' '' he said. ``So I talked to
Kyle and he said he just wasn't ready to come yet. So I said, `OK,
I'll go on and face everybody and face the circumstances, I guess.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `OK, I'm just going to go ahead, and then the
next time it will be a lot easier to do it.' Once I come then it
will be a lot easier for Kyle to come back the next time, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty said he could not blame the track _ or any other
racing-related circumstance _ as the cause of his grandson's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the Good Lord put his numbers in the book and it just
happened to come up,'' said Petty. ``It was unfortunate for the
racetrack or for us racing that it happened at the racetrack. We
can't blame racing. We can't blame the track. We can't blame the
circumstances. It was meant to be and it happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
