<SLUG> BC-SPACE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA CONCERNED ABOUT RUSSIAN ROCKET MALFUNCTION 

</HEADLINE>
 STATION-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASA on Friday asked the Russians to thoroughly explain a recent
Proton rocket malfunction before they proceed with the launching of
the long-delayed crew module for the U.S.-led international space
station.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-foot-long Russian crew module is set to blast off from
Central Asia atop an identical Proton on Tuesday night. The
one-of-a-kind spacecraft is intended to furnish the slowly
developing orbital station with housing for its first resident crew
of astronauts and cosmonauts late this year.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration wants
assurances a previously undisclosed malfunction that accompanied
the launching of a Proton earlier this week will not jeopardize the
crew module mission, said space agency spokesman Dwayne Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was noted after an otherwise successful Proton
launch from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan on Wednesday, an
official with the rocket's manufacturer said early Friday. That
Proton placed a Russian military communications satellite into
orbit in spite of the difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's briefing was hosted by Russia's space agency to preview
the crew module flight, which has been delayed 27 months by
economic problems and a pair of 1999 Proton explosions.
</P>
<P>
   In response to NASA's request that accompanied the disclosure,
the Russians scheduled a briefing of the problem for U.S. station
managers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said previously scheduled launch preparations at
the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan will proceed as planned over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already investigated the case. We have a full
understanding of the problem, and it's a minor problem,'' said
Sergei Shayevich, the space station program manager for the
Khrunichev State Research &AMP; Production Center.
</P>
<P>
   NASA spokesman Ed Campion said a pressure loss occurred in a
propulsion system line as the Proton's second stage was completing
its burn.
</P>
<P>
   Shayevich said the problem was a first for the Proton, which has
been a Russian workhorse for more than 30 years, and that it was
not associated with upgrades made in the wake of the last year's
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators attributed Proton explosions last October and July
to poor workmanship of the turbo machinery in the rocket's second
and third stages. They determined that the lapses allowed
contaminants, including metal fragments and a piece of cloth, to
overheat the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   At NASA's urging, the Russians modified the propulsion systems
to include filters that would block future engine contamination.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians and Americans also agreed to a pair of test flights
before the crew module is launched. A June 6 test was successful.
Until several Russian and American news reports disclosed problems
with Tuesday's test, the second was characterized as equally
successful.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the new station by a 16-nation partnership has
been stalled since the first components were joined in late 1998,
in large part by the tardiness of the crew module. Fifteen missions
with new components and supplies are planned in the next year alone
if the crew module mission is successful.
</P>
<P>
   The global partnership plans to use the station as a research
facility for physics, biology and medical experiments. It will also
serve as a high-altitude observatory for environmental studies and
a testing site for hardware needed for future human expeditions to
the moon and Mars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF FILE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
