<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6119 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-AT&AMP;T-FUTURE-ART-3TAKE     07-07 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-FUTURE-ART-3TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AT&AMP;T AT THE BRINK, PRESSURES RISE AT THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the evening of Monday, May 1, and Michael Armstrong, the
chairman of AT&AMP;T, needed help.
</P>
<P>
   Huddled in a conference room at the company's headquarters in
Basking Ridge, N.J., with key members of his executive team,
Armstrong said he turned for advice to two Wall Street analysts,
later identified by people close to the meeting as Frank Governali
of Goldman, Sachs and Jack Grubman of Salomon Smith Barney.
Armstrong asked the two just how he should tell investors that some
of AT&AMP;T's core businesses had stumbled. At least as important,
Armstrong also wanted their assessment of how AT&AMP;T's shares, one of
the nation's most widely held stocks, would react to the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The analysts came in and they said, `Well, look, what you have
to do is just put this on the table, tell it like you're going to
tell it,''' Armstrong recounted in an interview late last month. ``
`You're being forthright, you're talking about something in the
future.'''
</P>
<P>
   Governali and Grubman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their bottom line,'' Armstrong added, ``was, `You'll probably
take a four- to seven- point hit and then bounce back, for a three-
to five-point problem.' That's what their judgment was to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, AT&AMP;T dropped its bomb on the company's
investors. AT&AMP;T said its operations would grow more slowly and earn
less this year than the company had previously led the market to
expect. AT&AMP;T added that its core consumer long-distance unit would
shrink faster than expected. Worst of all, the company said that
its unit that sells communications services to business customers,
which had been one of its bastions of strength, would miss its
previous growth target because it had dropped the ball with some of
AT&AMP;T's biggest accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was swift and harsh. The company's shares, which
had closed that Monday at $49, skidded $7.0625, shaving more than
$25 billion from AT&AMP;T's market value. And the shares did not bounce
back. They continued to slide the next day. And the day after that.
And the day after that.
</P>
<P>
   The pain continues. AT&AMP;T's shares, which traded above $60 as
recently as late March, closed on Friday at $33.25.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just AT&AMP;T's shares that are feeling the burn. For
the first time since he took over as chairman in the fall of 1997,
Armstrong himself is on the defensive. His bet-the-company vision
to transform AT&AMP;T by delivering a package of interactive digital
television, high-speed cyberspace access and local telephone
service over cable television lines is still largely just that, a
vision.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the core long-distance operations that he was
counting on to avoid trouble while the company focused on the cable
strategy have found it instead. Even AT&AMP;T's vaunted offering of a
new stock meant to track its fast-growing wireless operation has
been a disappointment. Mediocre would be a charitable description
of its performance, at least for investors who bought it at the
offering price of $29.50 a share. On Friday, the stock closed at
$25.4375.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bell local phone giants finally moving in force into
the $80 billion long-distance market, the outlook in AT&AMP;T's core
consumer business is not likely to improve anytime soon. With the
company's market value at about $125 billion _ versus, say, the $96
billion that AT&AMP;T spent to acquire the Tele-Communications Inc. and
MediaOne cable television operations over the last two years, a
recurring theme in financial circles this summer has been that the
company would be an attractive target for an unsolicited takeover
and breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong does not appear to be in any danger of losing his job.
Strategically, he appears to have done as fine a job as anyone
could have expected, given the unenviable hand he was dealt. To
survive, AT&AMP;T had to transform itself from a lumbering,
backward-looking long-distance behemoth into something new;
Armstrong's bold moves, especially in the cable arena, appear
poised to do that.
</P>
<P>
   But tactically, he has not yet proved that he can execute on the
broad range of small, unglamorous, nitty-gritty chores that are
required to turn his visionary strategy into a concrete success.
Time is running out, investors are losing patience, and AT&AMP;T is on
the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's a little irrational, but I think people are just
fed up,'' said one Wall Street analyst, on condition of anonymity.
``I know one fund manager who said: `Don't talk to me about this
stock; I'm dumping it. Call me in a year if things turn around.'''
</P>
<P>
   In a year, it should be fairly clear whether Armstrong will
deserve to be placed in the pantheon of great executives or instead
be remembered as the man who valiantly tried to turn AT&AMP;T from
decades of inertia and failed.
</P>
<P>
   It was fear of that inertia's power that made the May 2
disclosures so damaging. The actual numbers were far from
devastating _ a percentage-point change in outlook here, maybe two
points over there. But it has been so long since AT&AMP;T truly
impressed investors with its performance _ years, for sure _ that
the May warning raised fears that beneath Armstrong's beaming
visage at the helm, this was still the same old sclerotic AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   About Armstrong himself, the warning raised an even more pointed
concern: If he cannot mind the shop in AT&AMP;T's core businesses, how
can he be expected to succeed in the new ones?
</P>
<P>
   So how does Armstrong himself think he is doing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we're making some really sound progress,'' he
said, with the unwavering, barrel-chested confidence that has
become his trademark. ``I think a lot of the progress is masked by
financials as a result of the declining voice business.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
