<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6121 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-AT&AMP;T-FUTURE-ART-$ADV0     07-07 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-FUTURE-ART-$ADV09-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: voice business.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What the financials may have masked is AT&AMP;T's belief that it
will be delivering local phone service over cable lines to at least
400,000 households by year-end. And even in states where the
company does not own cable systems, AT&AMP;T is making inroads in local
phone markets. In New York State, for instance, where Bell Atlantic
has made a strong move in the long-distance arena, AT&AMP;T has
counterattacked by signing up more than 475,000 local phone users.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to phone service, the other parts of AT&AMP;T's cable
service are also developing. While interactive television is not
yet a reality in the market, the company has about 300,000 cable
modem users and expects that figure to top 700,000 by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What gives me confidence to respond to that question rather
than go look at the price of the stock and get depressed is that
the investments and the strategy are working,'' Armstrong said. ``I
see it, and the people who take the time to look at our company
know it. But the overhang of the decline in voice and, in a large
part, the consumer business is very depressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depressing to the value,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   What may also be depressing, or perhaps liberating, is the fact
that a big part of AT&AMP;T's troubles _ those in the $20 billion
consumer long-distance business _ are for most practical purposes
out of Armstrong's control.
</P>
<P>
   Since agreeing to break itself up under pressure from the
government in 1984, AT&AMP;T has seen its share of the long-distance
market shrink each year. But what has also begun to shrivel in
recent years is the overall revenue of AT&AMP;T's consumer
long-distance unit.
</P>
<P>
   After battling head-to-head with MCI (which has since been
acquired by WorldCom) and with Sprint for long-distance customers
during most of the 1990s, AT&AMP;T has largely given up that fight
under Armstrong. The incessant marketing in the last decade _ the
television commercials, the print advertising and, most important,
the free long-distance ``checks'' _ meant to persuade consumers to
switch long-distance carriers _ helped prop up revenue in the
long-distance unit, but at a cost to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Under Armstrong, AT&AMP;T has essentially put its consumer
long-distance unit on life support, allowing it to get smaller but
milking it for billions in cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, that is nothing but a concession to the
inevitable. Just about anyone with a few million dollars can start
a long-distance phone carrier by buying access to the big
companies' networks at wholesale and selling long-distance minutes
at a profit, as do small companies like Talk.com and Telecare. Many
of the upstarts initially zero in on AT&AMP;T. And it is only going to
get worse as, with the Federal Communications Commission's
blessing, the Bell companies move into long-distance. By the end of
this month, Bell Atlantic, which changed its name last week to
Verizon Communications, will have probably signed up one million
long-distance customers in New York State alone. July 10, SBC
Communications, which does business as Southwestern Bell, is set to
jump into the consumer long-distance business in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a systemic declining industry, long distance,'' Armstrong
said. ``That is irreversible. And not just for AT&AMP;T, but for the
long-distance industry.''
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason why AT&AMP;T recently tried to raise some of the
prices in its basic calling plan. But that effort met with an
outcry from some Washington regulators and consumer advocates, who
said that AT&AMP;T was reneging on a pledge to reduce those rates. The
criticism forced AT&AMP;T to revise its plan.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong often points out that if AT&AMP;T's consumer long-distance
business were set aside, the remainder of the company would have
shown a 12 percent growth rate in the first quarter of 2000. In the
Internet world, that would impress no one, but 12 percent growth
would be a home run for AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, AT&AMP;T's consumer long-distance business has not been
set aside, at least not yet. But Armstrong's real problem resides
in the continued weakness in that unit, which makes it harder for
him to convince investors of his success in other areas. The
company must find gargantuan amounts of new business just to show
modest growth.
</P>
<P>
   In May, AT&AMP;T said it expected the consumer unit to decline by 6
to 8 percent this year, raising its earlier estimate of 3 to 5
percent. If that unit, which generated about $22 billion in revenue
last year, shrinks by 7 percent, that amounts to about $1.4 billion
in vanished sales. So AT&AMP;T needs to find that much new revenue this
year just to stay even.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T booked $62.4 billion in overall revenue last year, while
earning $3.4 billion. If the company wanted to achieve, say, 10
percent growth _ it is instead hoping for 7 to 8 percent _ the
company would have to find a whopping $7.8 billion in new revenue
(think Paine Webber) this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   If the consumer unit declined an additional 7 percent next year,
and the company again wanted to show 10 percent growth over all, it
would have to find an additional $8.3 billion in new revenue (think
Conseco) in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the decline of the consumer long-distance
business puts a lot of pressure on AT&AMP;T's other operations. And
that is one reason that AT&AMP;T is considering ways to quarantine the
consumer unit's financial results from those of the rest of the
company, perhaps by selling a new stock to track the consumer
operation. The idea seems to appeal to Armstrong, and it appears
that a decision on such a move could come within months, if not
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to tell everybody that a business has to reach
three conditions and then I would consider a segmentation of it,''
he said. ``Is it operationally prepared for public investment? Will
it create a currency that would serve a purpose? And will there be
some value creation as a result of doing it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's 115 years old, so I think it kind of qualifies that
it kind of operationally knows what it's doing,'' Armstrong said,
in answering the three questions. ``The creation of the currency is
more obscure, because it has declining revenue. On the other hand,
the currency would obviously have a value greater than it now has.
And then third, would it create shareholder value? In this case, it
would maybe permit that if there was some segmentation for the rest
of AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-AT&AMP;T-FUTURE-ART-$ADV0     07-07 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-FUTURE-ART-$ADV09-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: of AT&AMP;T.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``So I would say that those three conditions would apply to the
consumer business and that's kind of where it is,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   As Armstrong says, the problems in his company's long-distance
unit are systemic and not likely to change. The missteps in AT&AMP;T's
unit that sells services to business customers, however, are purely
of the company's making.
</P>
<P>
   Put bluntly, the business-services unit tripped on its own
shoelaces. While AT&AMP;T was reorganizing the unit to transfer some
big corporate customers to the Concert international venture that
the company formed in 1998 with British Telecommunications, some of
those customers got lost in the shuffle. AT&AMP;T's sales force
appeared to get lazy in selling new data services to those
customers, opening the door for competitors like WorldCom and
Sprint. As a result, AT&AMP;T said growth in the business-services unit
would be about 8 percent this year, rather than the 9 to 11 percent
it had predicted earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the numbers did not scream failure. But again, they gave
some investors the impression of a ship adrift. And AT&AMP;T is not
going to be able to fix the problem right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the problem happened, I'm accountable, but I don't
operate quite at that level,'' Armstrong said. ``The relationships,
the administrative support, the skill coverage in those accounts
was not carefully managed and we lost the kind of proposing,
anticipating and customer-relationship role. And we've got to redo
that. And you don't do that in weeks or months. It's going to take
quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to view this sort of lapse. The first is that
it is in some way more comforting than the sort of overarching
issues afflicting AT&AMP;T's consumer business, because it can be
fixed.
</P>
<P>
   The other is that it is in fact even more disquieting, because
there were no fundamental underlying reasons for the problem to
have ever emerged. Moreover, the problems in the business-services
operation were a direct result of the sort of organizational change
that is fundamental to Armstrong's overall plan.
</P>
<P>
   There is no more important quality for the chief executive of a
public company than credibility _ credibility that goals can and
will be achieved and credibility that the company will be
forthright in its dealings with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's credibility is intact. But the manner and timing of
the May 2 announcement left a bad taste for many investors and
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Just three business days before AT&AMP;T delivered its bad news, the
new stock meant to track the company's wireless business, whose
offering brought AT&AMP;T a $10.6 billion windfall, began trading.
</P>
<P>
   In the days and weeks leading up to the offering, AT&AMP;T
executives led by John D. Zeglis, AT&AMP;T's president, had
crisscrossed the country touting the new wireless shares to
investors. And in the course of those discussions, it does not
appear that Zeglis gave even a hint of the problems that AT&AMP;T was
about to announce, leading some investors to worry that perhaps
they had been manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people said: `Hey, I just met with Zeglis. What's that
about?''' said one communications analyst, on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Had AT&AMP;T delayed the announcement of the bad news to avoid
tainting the wireless offering, whose ticker symbol is AWE? What
would that say about AT&AMP;T's communications in the future?
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think it was relevant to the AWE offering,''
Armstrong said. ``What I was focused on was how can I maintain the
most credibility by giving shareholders the most lead time to the
bad news that I was coming with.''
</P>
<P>
   If he could do it again, would he handle the disclosure
differently?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, do I think that the perfect thing would have let a couple
weeks go in between the two? Sure, yeah, I'd wait. But I don't
think withholding information is a good idea. And that's what drove
me to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the early 1980s, and IBM had recently introduced a new
device called the personal computer. Critics harped that only IBM's
arrogance would let it believe that people would pay to put a such
a powerful machine on their desks.
</P>
<P>
   It was the early 1990s, and Hughes Electronics had faded along
with the Cold War. Instead of retrenching, Hughes went against the
grain and invested in new civilian satellite systems.
</P>
<P>
   These are the stories Armstrong recounts as he tries to put this
difficult moment in perspective. After all, he oversaw IBM's PC
group in the early '80s, and he was running Hughes in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going through the toughest time, just like I did back in
'83 and '84 with the personal computer,'' he said. ``The same tough
time that we went through back in 1992 and '93 with the
commercialization-of-space strategy. This is more visible. I've
never enjoyed so many critics and authors and helpers from the
outside as to what I should have done and what I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not quite sound beleaguered. The strut, the confidence,
are still there. But the force of personality is not quite as
overwhelming as it was a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rightly or not, AT&AMP;T will always labor under especially intense
scrutiny from investors. As AT&AMP;T has tried to remake itself, its
struggles have at times seemed the same as those of any other old,
powerful, slightly dotty organization pushing to become something
lean and new. But AT&AMP;T has muddled for so long now that only a big
surprise _ a big, good surprise _ will suffice to get investors
excited again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The street has gotten very emotional about this stock,'' said
Daniel P. Reingold, chief telecommunications analyst for Credit
Suisse First Boston. ``It seems that every fear in the world has
found its way into this stock and it has led to a very over-sold
condition. It's going to take good news on revenue or structural
shock treatment, like some spinoffs or additional tracking stocks,
to unlock the hidden value. But patient investors could be rewarded
very handsomely.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Armstrong probably would not describe himself as
patient, nor would investors be pleased if he did. But he does have
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been as tough a challenge as I bargained for,'' he
said. ``This is the toughest of times, when people view their
success in terms of the stock price. Transformation doesn't come
easy. It comes from hard work and ramping up new products and
services with new people and new technology, and we're doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind if people wonder if it can be done, this
transformation,'' he added. ``But I do mind if people wonder if it
can be done when it's being done. And it's being done here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
