<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6124 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-07 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DEAR RALPH: 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nader for president! You say you are serious this time, running
as the candidate of the Green Party, and you deride those who say
you should get out of Al Gore's way. Fair enough. Third parties are
an honorable, if frustrating, American tradition.
</P>
<P>
   What is puzzling to some of your old admirers is what you stand
for. You say the two major parties are practically Tweedledum and
Tweedledee _ there are ``few major differences'' between them.
Sure, they are both awash in campaign money that keeps them close
to business. But no major differences? Are you serious?
</P>
<P>
   Take one of your concerns, the environment. When Newt Gingrich &AMP;
Co. took control of the House, Republicans tried to gut the
country's environmental protection laws. They were stopped by
President Clinton's skillful use of the veto and veto threats. A
Republican from Texas, where environmental regulation is in the
hands of the polluters, is not likely to be that kind of president.
</P>
<P>
   Or take law. You and I first met in law school. You have used
the legal process well, and I believe you must still have a deep
concern for law and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective Republican candidate has spoken admiringly of
the judicial record of Justice Clarence Thomas. The Democrat would
almost certainly make appointments to the Supreme Court on the
model of President Clinton's moderate liberal choices, Justices
Ruth Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer. No major difference?
</P>
<P>
   It is surprising that you pay little or no attention to one area
where there is in fact little difference between President Clinton
and the Republican Congress _ and the records of both are abysmal.
That is civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   Federal habeas corpus, a fundamental safeguard of freedom, was
ravaged by legislation signed without objection by President
Clinton. The Republican Congress cut off funds for a handful of
resource centers that provided lawyers for prisoners on death row,
many of whom had been represented by incompetent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The Counter-Terrorism Act, drafted by the Clinton
administration, imported into our law the loathsome practice of
trials on secret evidence. The Immigration Act of 1996 compelled
the deportation of people who had committed trivial crimes years
before the act was passed.
</P>
<P>
   By attacking those affronts to due process and American decency,
a third-party candidate could have a real impact. He could shake
the major parties' indifference and touch the country's conscience.
Don't you care?
</P>
<P>
   What you mainly seem to care about these days is free trade. You
are against it _ or say you want it with so many ifs and buts that
it amounts to the same thing. You and your organization, Public
Citizen, led the way to the Seattle protests against the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   You talk about the importance of seeing that other countries
have laws like ours to protect fair labor standards, the consumer,
pure food and the environment. Those are fine ideals. But the
effect of insisting that other countries meet our standards before
we trade with them would be, as you must know, devastating.
</P>
<P>
   What South Africans need is jobs; about a third of them are
unemployed. The same is true in most of the developing world. Yes,
we should worry about underpaid child workers in Asia producing
goods for the American market. But efforts that focus attention on
such cruelties have been quite effective. To use, instead, the
blunderbuss of stopping or handicapping trade would make life
harsher for all.
</P>
<P>
   Free trade benefits Americans enormously, too. Your great early
achievement was to bring General Motors to heel. But what really
forced reform on GM, and gave us all better cars, was competition
from Japanese and other imports.
</P>
<P>
   Your protectionist stance has put you in bed with some of the
most reactionary forces in this country. You are a twin of Pat
Buchanan on the issue. The New Republic reported that Public
Citizen's Global Trade Watch got money from Roger Milliken, the
far-right South Carolina textile magnate who has bankrolled the
conservative cause from Barry Goldwater on.
</P>
<P>
   Protectionism would destroy our prosperity and make the world's
poor even more miserable. It is a strange platform for the Ralph
Nader who says he speaks for the weak and the neglected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
