<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EPISCOPALS-LUTHERANS(     07-07 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISCOPALS-LUTHERANS(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPISCOPALIANS NEAR ALLIANCE WITH BIGGEST LUTHERAN GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Episcopal Church and the nation's largest Lutheran
denomination moved closer Friday to creating a formal alliance in
which they would recognize each other's traditions and share
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelming approval of an accord known as ``Called to Common
Mission'' by the Episcopal House of Bishops at the church's annual
convention here left only a vote by the church's other chamber, the
House of Deputies, to enact the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The 800 deputies, who are lay people and clergy, were expected
to approve the accord in a vote scheduled to be held no later than
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the policy-making body of the Evangelical Lutheran
Church in America, the nation's largest Lutheran denomination with
5.2 million members, approved the accord last year.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of both churches said Friday that final passage would
reflect an historic accomplishment, ending 30 years of
conversations between the two churches, which have similar
theological positions and liturgies but significant differences
about the role and authority of bishops. In the Episcopal Church,
bishops are regarded as progeny of Christ's disciples and are
elected for life. Lutheran bishops serve six-year terms, largely as
administrators, before returning to their roles as pastors.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is one indicator that the ecumenical movement may
have regained momentum after several decades in which it was
declared all but dead. The Lutheran church voted in 1997 for full
communion with three churches in Protestantism's Reformed
tradition: the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), the United Church of
Christ and the Reformed Church in America. Other longtime efforts
are underway to unite Christian churches, with supporters citing
the prayer of Jesus in the Gospel of John 17:11 that all his
followers ``may be one.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Concerning the alliance with the Episcopal Church, ``It has been
a long process, and I'm delighted,'' Lowell Almen, the secretary of
the Lutheran group and a guest at the Episcopal convention, said
after the 204 bishops voted, with only a dozen or so dissenting.
``God is doing a new thing in the life of the church. This
represents a moment in church history that is very significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Epting, the Episcopal bishop of Iowa who played a major
role in writing the accord, called it ``an ecumenical
breakthrough'' that could help encourage similar agreements between
the church and other denominations. Already, he said, the Episcopal
church had begun conversations with the Moravian Church in America,
a Protestant denomination, and the Presbyterian Church.
</P>
<P>
   The vote by the deputies would align two churches that represent
nearly 8 million congregants and would end several years of bumpy
negotiations in efforts to bring the two denominations closer.
After an initial proposal was written by members of both churches
in 1990, it came up for its first votes of approval in 1997. The
Episcopal Church passed it overwhelmingly, but the Lutherans failed
by six votes to reach the majority needed for passage.
</P>
<P>
   A committee with representatives from both churches wrote a
compromise document; that proposal was approved Friday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the accord, though it does not combine the two
churches, allows each to recognize and embrace the other to the
extent they can share ministers, places of worship and other
resources. In addition to the symbolic significance, church leaders
said, the arrangement would benefit urban and rural regions where
one church is hard-pressed to serve all its members because of
inadequate buildings or lack of personnel. Churches in such areas,
for example, could share one pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders said the accord would also encourage local
churches to work together on projects they would perform
separately, like relief and missionary efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
