<HEADLINE>
PREGNANT FACTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 09, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Happily, teen pregnancy rates in the United States have been
dropping. But when it comes to comparisons with other countries,
the United States looks bad. Too often pop music offers more
straight talk to teens than politicians do. As a result,
government-funded programs can be oddly mute. Focusing on
``abstinence only,'' some mention contraception solely to discuss
failure rates. And too many teenagers don't get the information
they need.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the Alan Guttmacher Institute highlights teenagers'
needs in its Guttmacher Report on Public Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The encouraging drop in teen pregnancy rates is 17 percent from
1990 to 1996, according to Guttmacher researchers. They link a
quarter of the decline from 1988 to 1995 to increased abstinence
and three-quarters to better use of contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon, however, to celebrate. US pregnancy rates remain
close to levels in Belarus, Bulgaria, and the Russian Federation,
complains Jacqueline Darroch, Guttmacher's vice president for
research.
</P>
<P>
   Many European countries and Canada have a far better record of
preventing teen pregnancies despite what some Americans consider a
more permissive attitude. It isn't that teenagers in those
countries are less sexually active than in the United States, but
that they have better access to counseling and birth control.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly embarrassing is a comparative look at France, where
a national campaign promotes contraceptive use. Some radio and
television ads are addressed to adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't forbid sex, but you can ask young people to be
responsible,'' Bridget Dusseau, an editor at a French news agency,
says in the report. This honest comment might get her fired if she
were doing US government work.
</P>
<P>
   Are French efforts outrageous? Apparently not. From 1992 to
1996, estimated adolescent abortion rates in France are a low 10.2
per 1,000 women, compared to 29.2 in the United States. French
adolescent pregnancy rates are estimated at 20.2 per thousand
women, compared to 83.6 in the States. Some 900,000 American teens
between 15 and 19 become pregnant each year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this record, the United States shouldn't just mimic
French programs. It must make its own progress.
</P>
<P>
   Basic communication should improve. ``Abstinence only''
campaigns claim the moral high ground, but they also discourage
meaningful public debate and ignore the reality of many
adolescents' lives. Why not just send information-needy teenagers
to doctors? Some go, but less than a third say they've discussed
how to prevent pregnancy or sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   More public dollars should be better targeted on such efforts as
preventing repeat pregnancies among teenagers _ about one in five
births to teenagers or an estimated 110,000 births in 1998.
Research shows successful prevention programs stress life skills
and a pointed message about using contraceptives to prevent repeat
pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Pregnancy prevention remains the best way to reduce the
incidence of abortion and, with some forms of birth control, the
spread of many sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   States can reach out by using the State Children's Health
Insurance Program _ set up by Congress in 1997 _ to expand
insurance coverage and reproductive health services for teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the United States dominates the information age, it
should make revolutionary leaps in providing teenagers with the
best, most thorough information available on avoiding pregnancy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
