<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OILFED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED TO THE PUMPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 09, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal Reserve policy has aimed primarily at reining in a
spirit of exuberance that threatened to turn strong growth into a
runaway boom. The Fed's principal concern has been that inflation,
a minor factor for more than a decade, would make a return and put
the economy into a tailspin. Now a new factor, rising energy
prices, deserves a prominent place in Fed thinking because of the
impact it could have on American economic psychology.
</P>
<P>
   The recent surge in oil prices has been downplayed because
energy represents a smaller slice of the overall economic pie than
it did during earlier spurts in 1967 and 1980. It now represents
about 3 percent of economic activity compared with about 6 percent
in the earlier years.
</P>
<P>
   Energy nevertheless is a part of everyone's life. People were
troubled by last winter's jump in heating oil prices and angered by
the current leap in gasoline prices. While there has been no
indication that higher prices are causing people to lower the
thermostat, shut off the air conditioner, form car pools, or buy
smaller cars, there clearly is frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The situation remains volatile. Saudi Arabia's announcement on
Wednesday that it would increase oil production by an additional
500,000 barrels a day was welcome. It had an immediate impact of
lowering crude oil prices around the world, but they remained above
$30 a barrel in most markets. Furthermore, the effect of the
increased production will take some months to be felt in actual
supplies of refined products on hand. The danger remains of another
surge in home heating oil prices this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty has never been a helpful ingredient in building
consumer or investor confidence. There is a real danger that energy
cost gyrations could infect decisions in other areas, to the
detriment of continued economic growth, especially with job growth
slowing, as reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed will have to keep a close watch on matters to avoid
over-restrictive policies if confidence erodes in the new energy
environment. It held steady on interest rates last month; it should
be prepared to move quickly toward lower rates if oil prices show
any signs of curbing an otherwise healthy economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
