<HEADLINE>
ENCHANTING BUT DARKER HARRY POTTER BOOK 4 IS WORTHY OF HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKEN DENN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The three-word answer for Harry Potter fans everywhere:
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's good.
</P>
<P>
   How good?
</P>
<P>
   In the generally accepted Potterific Scale of 1 to 10 _ in which
Book 1 in the wildly popular series rates an 11, Book 2 slips to a
10, and Book 3 surges to a 12 _ the madly anticipated fourth book
settles in around an 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' released to the public
at midnight Friday, is darker than the first three books detailing
the young orphan's magical adventures _ think of the sort of mood
shift that came between J.R.R. Tolkien's ``Hobbit'' and
``Fellowship of the Ring.'' Also, for the first time a Harry book
ends on a somber note.
</P>
<P>
   Book 4 doesn't have the emotional resonance of the best parts of
Book 3, focusing more on adventures than introspection. But it does
provide a satisfying depth for several characters in author J.K.
Rowling's carefully imagined world, including new insights into
Professor Severus Snape, Hagrid the groundskeeper and even the evil
Lord You-Know-Who.
</P>
<P>
   And the book keeps up the awesome inventiveness, deadpan humor
and gripping pace of previous installments, despite a 732-page
count that gives ``Goblet of Fire'' the heft of a decent
dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   (Warning, Warning, Warning: Potter fans may want to stop reading
here, unless they want to know details in the plot the book's
publisher has guarded as zealously as an Azbakan prisoner.)
</P>
<P>
   Refreshingly, Rowling tinkers some with the series formula. For
instance, she starts with a chapter featuring the evil Lord
Voldemort rather than hero Harry, and dominates Harry's year at the
Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry with a ``Triwizard
Tournament'' of challenges rather than the magical game Quidditch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's tradition to spare.
</P>
<P>
   The Sorting Hat is back, with a newly written song to boot.
(``It's got to be a pretty boring life, hasn't it, being a hat?''
comments Harry's friend Ron Weasley. ``I suppose it spends all year
making up the next one.'')
</P>
<P>
   Wronged outcast Sirius Black, eating rats for sustenance, keeps
a godfatherly eye on Harry's welfare. Quidditch is still Harry's
favorite game, with the book's first chunk dedicated to the
Quidditch World Cup (Ireland vs. Bulgaria), with a dark faction of
fans rioting in a scary rally against Muggles (non-magical people).
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Rowling flawlessly knits her plotlines together, with
seemingly casual early details taking on meaningful force by the
end. (Ever wonder why Hogwarts student Neville Longbottom lives
with his grandmother? It turns out to matter.)
</P>
<P>
   And as usual, Rowling slips in sly jokes that keep adults
entertained too (``Moi?'' says a hefty woman accused of giantess
blood. ``I 'ave big bones!'')
</P>
<P>
   The book focuses less on the funny-to-fascinating details of
life at a magical boarding school, with more attention on the
coming showdown _ it's a seven-book series _ between the good
wizards on Harry's side and the Death Eater followers of evil.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most-hyped aspects of the book pre-publication _ that
Harry and his friends would discover the opposite sex _ is fun but
not earthshaking. The romances, such as they are, are old-fashioned
for the real 14-year-old set, with on-target agonies about whom to
invite to the Yule Ball and a light-handed lecture against favoring
beauty over brains.
</P>
<P>
   The book doesn't hit every note perfectly, though.
</P>
<P>
   The previous timeless atmosphere is jarred a bit with mentions
of Playstations and Aqualungs.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a subplot with the characters called house elves _
whose dialect will grit the teeth of anyone who hated Jar Jar Binks
of ``Star Wars'' notoriety _ creating a parallel between the elves'
lives and slavery, which hovers uncomfortably between seriousness
and humor.
</P>
<P>
   The book's scarier sections are certain to re-ignite a debate
over whether younger children should read the book, technically
aimed at ages 9 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   A beloved character faces brief torture; another character (as
Rowling forewarned) is killed; there's one scene with a chopped-off
hand and another with magical curses that could easily raise the
hackles of protective parents. (``Abracadabra!,'' for instance,
will never have the same ring, now that Rowling has co-opted it as
the fatal ``Avada Kedavra'' spell.)
</P>
<P>
   But the book is unquestionably aimed at children, regardless of
its older fans, and adults often forget the horrors in older
children's classics that go over young readers' heads. It seems a
shame to deny the book's intended audience the creative world of
``Goblet of Fire'' simply because of its honesty in including doses
of both good and evil to illustrate the battle between the two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
