<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ALCOHOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
.08 NATIONWIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, July 10, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the past two decades, the country has made great progress in
keeping drunks off the road and reducing the toll of accidents they
cause. But alcohol remains the single biggest factor in fatal
accidents, and it is past time to take the next step against drunk
driving: establishment of a national blood-alcohol limit of .08
grams per deciliter.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Senate passed a transportation appropriations
bill that includes a provision requiring states to adopt this
standard or lose federal highway money. The House has no such
clause in its appropriations bill, so it will be up to a conference
committee this month to decide whether the US moves toward a
nationwide standard, like the nationwide minimum drinking age of
21.
</P>
<P>
   The .08 provision is bitterly fought by the beverage and
restaurant industries, which claim it will ensnare casual, social
drinkers. But as the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
notes, to reach the .08 level, a 170-pound male would have to throw
down at least four 12-ounce beers on an empty stomach. A 137-pound
female would have to drain at least three beers in an hour on an
empty stomach.
</P>
<P>
   At the .08 level, the ability of a driver to brake, steer,
change lanes, exercise good judgment, or focus attention can
decrease by as much as 60 percent. A driver with a blood alcohol
level between .05 and .09 is 11 times more likely to be killed in
an accident than drivers who have had nothing to drink.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen states already have the .08 limit; most others set it
at .10. In Massachusetts, judges and juries can infer from an .08
reading that a driver was criminally impaired, but the test result
alone does not necessarily prove that. The Cellucci administration
has filed bills to make an .08 reading proof by itself, but the
Legislature has not gone along.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of a national .08 standard would bring this state and
others into line. The one House member from this state on the
transportation conference committee, John Olver, favors the .08
limit, which also has the endorsement of the Clinton
administration. Congress could improve the safety of the nation's
roads by turning a deaf ear to the lobbyists and adopting the .08
standard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-ART-NYT &LR;      07-07 1014
</HEADER>
