r s BC-RAC-DAY-LADN     07-07 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY RETURNS TO HOME AWAY FROM HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ At times, it appears that Pat Day was born
to win horse races. He's a four-time Eclipse Award winner, he's led
the nation in victories six times and is third in lifetime wins
behind only Laffit Pincay Jr. and Bill Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   But the 46-year-old Day is most dangerous when a $1 million
purse is at stake. The veteran jockey has won a record 21
million-dollar races, and he will try to add to that total Sunday
when he rides Cat Thief in the Grade I Hollywood Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Day has enjoyed past success at Hollywood Park, winning nine
Grade I races and 12 stakes overall at the Inglewood oval. It's his
home away from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the main reason for my success there is that I've been
well-mounted,'' Day said by telephone this week from Louisville,
where he is about to wrap up his 28th riding title at Churchill
Downs. ``The horses I've ridden have been very well-prepared by
their respective trainers, and of course you have to have some
breaks in the races. Obviously, things have gone our way there.''
</P>
<P>
   Day rode his first million-dollar winner, Wild Again, in the
inaugural Breeders' Cup Classic at Hollywood Park in 1984. He
remembers the race like it happened yesterday, how he had to
overcome a three-horse driving, bumping finish with Gate Dancer and
Slew O' Gold and then sweated out a 10-minute stewards' inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember what I had for breakfast,'' Day joked, ``but
I've been blessed with the ability to recall horses in races and
their idiosyncrasies and any problems they might have had in the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Day said Wild Again was a handful that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd been tryin to get out basically from the time we went
under the wire the first time,'' he said. ``After a quarter-mile
into the race, the remainder of the race, he was leaning out pretty
severely. When we came off the turn and into the stretch, given as
hard as my horse had been running up to that point, when Slew O'
Gold ranged up on the outside of me, I really thought that my horse
would just hang it up. I don't believe I've ever ridden a horse
that tried any harder than he did in the stretch run, or showed any
more courage under fire than he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wasn't sure when I went under the wire if I had won
or if Gate Dancer had won. When I spoke to the stewards, I told
them my horse had been trying to get out basically the whole way
and that I did what I thought was a quality job of maintaining a
straight course while trying to keep him running. I wasn't sure if
I had drifted out and caused any of it.''
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy delay, the stewards ruled Gate Dancer was the
cause of most of the bumping between the three horses and Wild
Again's number stayed up.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 20 more million-dollar victories for Day, none
in the Gold Cup. When he won the race aboard Blushing John in 1989,
it was a $500,000 event. Blushing John was named top older male
horse that year.
</P>
<P>
   Blushing John was beaten by Sabona in The Californian, the final
major steppingstone to the Gold Cup, but Day said he was confident
he could reverse the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rode him in the Gold Cup the way I probably should have
ridden him in The Californian,'' he said. ``He relaxed back off 'em
early, went after the horses when he was ready and drew off in the
stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Day has won four Breeders' Cup races at Hollywood Park,
including two in 1987 when he guided Epitome to victory in the
Juvenile Fillies and Theatrical to the winner's circle in the Turf.
He also won aboard 2-year-old champion and Horse of the Year
Favorite Trick in the 1997 Juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Day will be aboard a horse he knows quite well. He's
ridden Cat Thief in 13 of the horse's 26 lifetime starts, including
victories in last year's Swaps Stakes at Hollywood Park and the
Breeders' Cup Classic at Gulfstream Park in November.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief is the type of horse that can frustrate both a trainer
and his jockey. He's won only four times, mostly because he's head
strong and refuses to give his best effort every time out,
according to Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like playing cat and mouse with him, it's more a
head game with him,'' Day said. ``You can't manhandle him or get
real aggressive with him or he gets aggressive back. So you gotta
kind of finesse him into the race, and hopefully you can conserve
him to the last three-sixteenths of a mile because he'll give you
that burst, that short acceleration to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember riding him in the Fountain of Youth and the Florida
Derby last year, two races he barely lost and could have won, and I
thought he was wimping on me. I say he wimped because I felt he got
right down on the wire and was not persevering for me. I didn't
ride him the remainder of the spring and then I got back on him for
the Swaps and he showed some tremendous tenacity that day, some
trem endous courage under fire. He was headed by General Challenge
at the top of the stretch, fought back gamely and was not to be
denied. It was just a very gutsy effort. But he doesn't do that all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   So which Cat Thief can we expect to see Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know for sure what you're dealing with when the
doors open,'' Day said. ``And he doesn't give you a fair indication
in the post parade. Some horses, maybe when they fire big, they'll
be really on their toes and bouncing and slightly lathered up over
the shoulders. And then maybe they'll be dull and lethargic in the
post parade and they run dull. He warms up basically the same way
every time. There's no real indication until you actually get into
the race.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the stakes are high, both Day and Cat Thief have proved
they can be difficult to beat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
