<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-IRWIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNY IRWIN GREW UP WITH THE SPORT OF RACING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes Kenny Irwin profile text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ His first racing event came at an age when many
youngsters are working to master multiplication tables instead of
racetracks. Kenny Irwin was just 6 years old, and his early
interest in the sport would translate into later success, including
rookie of the year honors on four racing circuits.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Indianapolis native and Charlotte, N.C.,
resident died Friday in a pre-qualifying crash at New Hampshire
International Speedway. It was the second tragedy at NHIS in less
than two months, and it left many NASCAR drivers to once again
reflect upon the talent, character, and promise of a fellow
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably go back 10 years with him, racing midgets,'' said
Mike Bliss, referring to the United States Auto Club Skoal Midget
Series, where Irwin posted eight victories and 20 runner-up
finishes in five seasons (1991-95). ``We weren't the best of
friends, but we raced against each other. We were competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart, also an Indiana native, said he met Irwin in 1991,
when both were running for the rookie of the year title at the
Indianapolis Speeddrome. He said their competition generated a
``love-hate relationship'' _ and a rivalry that continued to the
Winston Cup level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through nine years of rivalry, though, there's been a mutual
admiration and respect for one another and for what each other
could do in a racecar,'' said Stewart, the 1999 Winston Cup rookie
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart added that Irwin was the toughest competitor he has ever
faced. ``It didn't matter whether it was a sprint car on pavement
on Friday night, or a midget on dirt on Saturday night, or a Silver
Crown car on dirt on Sunday. You knew you had to be on your game
because if you weren't, he was going to beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin captured his first rookie honor in 1993, in the
Stoops/Freightliner Sprint Car Series. He captured another rookie
title the following season in the USAC Silver Crown Series and
finished second in the overall standings in 1995. He was the
National Midget Series champion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Irwin captured rookie of the year honors in the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series after posting two victories, seven top-5,
and 10 top-10 finishes. He ended the season 10th in the points
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin's fourth rookie of the year honor helped put him on the
map, because it came in the Winston Cup Series, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That year, he started in 32 races (finishing 28) and earned his
first pole position in his 36th career start (he raced four times
on the circuit in 1997). He also became the highest-starting rookie
in the history of the Brickyard 400 with a fourth-place qualifying
effort.
</P>
<P>
   He finished 1998 with one top-5 and four top-10 finishes, and
became the first rookie to top $1 million in earnings in a full
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this a thousand times since I started Winston Cup:
Kenny's part of the reason I got here because he pushed me to make
myself better each week,'' said Stewart. ``There's not a lot of
guys who have worked any harder than Kenny has to get where he's
gotten in his racing career.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1999, Irwin was beginning to enjoy the fruits of his labor.
He was named driver of the No. 42 BellSouth Mobility/Ericsson
Chevrolet on the Winston Cup circuit and also competed in 15 NASCAR
Busch Series events in the same car.
</P>
<P>
   He never won a Winston Cup race (his best finish was third at
the prestigious Daytona 500 last season), but being added to the
BellSouth team prompted him to speak with much enthusiasm about
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Many drivers spoke about Irwin's demeanor, and many uttered the
same words used to describe Adam Petty, the 19-year-old who was
killed May 12 in the same area as Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny was one of the young drivers who was full of energy and
he always had a smile,'' said Ricky Craven. ``That's what I liked
about him; he was always able to stop by and say a few words.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Park, who Friday questioned whether the NHIS track should
be investigated because of the tragedies, said he believed the
drivers should conduct themselves the remainder of the weekend with
a show-must-go-on demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Adam and Kenny would want the show to go on and I believe
they will be watching down on us,'' he said, referring to Sunday's
thatlook.com 300. ``It's just sad that they won't be with us. Both
(racers) were devout Christians, so I know they are in good
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Craven, who fought back emotions Friday, said: ``This is as
uncomfortable as it gets. Nothing prepares you for this. You're
aware of the risks, but nothing prepares you for this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
KENNY IRWIN AT A GLANCE &QL; 
 &QL; 
Age: 30 &QL; 
Hometown: Indianapolis &QL; 
Marital status: Single &QL; 
Notable: Rookie of the Year on the Winston Cup circuit in 1998 ...
Six top-10 finishes in 1999 in 34 starts ... Had won $886,370 this
season ... Rookie of the Year on the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series
in 1997 ... Began racing on the USAC circuit before switching to
NASCAR. &QL; 
 &QL; 
This season: &QL; 
