<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR VENUS WILLIAMS, SINGLES TITLE HER JUST DESSERT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TEN-WIMBLEDON) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ There were drive-by shootings that jangled
the nerves of the residents who flinched through life in Compton,
Calif., but the sound that still lingers in the head of Venus
Williams has nothing to do with gang grudges.
</P>
<P>
   For a spindly child who was barely bigger than her racket
handle, there was nothing better to perk up Williams' ears than the
faint music-box jingle from the ice-cream truck rambling toward the
tennis courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you know, maybe living in Compton isn't like the most
desired place to live, not in the top 100,'' Williams said with a
sly smile after her semifinal victory against her sister, Serena,
on Thursday. ``But I had a great time. I still miss the ice-cream
trucks. They had the best ice-cream trucks. Spent all my allowance
on the ice-cream trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   She's a grown-up now. And with nearly $5 million in career
earnings, she is a 20-year-old who has made the leap from
Dreamsicles to strawberries and cream. After an improbable rise
with the aid of her father's unorthodox ways, she is in position to
make history. If Williams can counter the power of the defending
champion Lindsay Davenport on Saturday, she will become the first
African-American woman since Althea Gibson to win Wimbledon. And if
she captures this title, Venus Williams will join her sister Serena
Williams as a Grand Slam winner. No sisters in tennis history have
each won Grand Slam titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't go on no `ifs,' like `If this happens,''' Richard
Williams said after signing autographs on the grounds Friday.
``We're here to make things happen. We're here to set any kind of
history for anyone who wants to see history. I understand Althea
Gibson won a singles title here, and we're here to follow in the
footsteps she laid.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport could be the snag in the grand plan. Beneath the hype
whirling around every move made by the Williams sisters and every
word uttered by their father, Davenport has just blended into the
colorful scene. No one would know it from the bravado and
confidence gushing from the Williams' family, but Davenport has
handled Venus Williams over the years, winning nine out of the 12
matches they've played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played her a lot in the past, and a lot of times I found
the key was, you know, find a way to get her serve back,''
Davenport said. ``You have to get them back deep so she obviously
doesn't have put-away shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams craves the soft, short floaters off her
opponents' return. Her favorite shot is the swinging forehand
volley, a weapon she used to dismantle top-ranked Martina Hingis in
the quarterfinals. She also put away her little sister with it on
occasion during the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   And Friday, the awkwardness of the sisters' semifinal was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not easy,'' said Richard Williams who did not watch the
match but was there to console Serena after losing to Venus. ``I
went home with Serena. You could see the tears in her eyes. She
hates to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, the smile was back for Serena Williams after
she laughed, joked and shared a doubles win with her big sister.
Together, they advanced to the women's doubles final after
defeating Anna Kournikova and Natasha Zvereva in straight sets. And
with that, the Williams sisters became the first African-American
team to reach the doubles final at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great tournament,'' Richard Williams said. ``It's
been phenomenal for the family. I think if Venus is serious, no one
can touch her.'' Three years ago, Venus Williams had a chance to
take the U.S. Open title long before her little sister won it last
summer. But at age 17, she wasn't savvy enough to beat Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my third Grand Slam to play in,'' Venus Williams
said. ``I wasn't even full-time on the Tour. I didn't understand
any strategy as far as, let's say you're down a breakpoint, and
maybe you should get your first serve in. Things like that never
came to my mind. It was totally different circumstances, yeah. It's
extremely different from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, everything has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's come so far,'' Richard Williams said. ``The first day I
took Venus out there on the courts, I knew she was a champion. The
reason I knew it was that I was working with three other girls who
were much older than she was. And I had a shopping cart with 550
balls in there. And those three girls were taking so long to hit
them. I had to patronize them to get them to do it. Venus never
wanted to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stopped her, she'd start crying. It got to the last
ball, and she'd say, `Say, last ball.' To this day, I still say,
`last ball' to her. I walked home, and I told my wife, `We have a
champion.' And she said, `you're just a proud father.' She was
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In what seems like an instant, Venus Williams has gone from the
gangly child in Compton with the ice-cream fascination, to the
statuesque center of attention at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know it's my life,'' Venus Williams said. ``The whole time
I've had a great time. I've had a great life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
