<SLUG> BC-GORE-260&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE FAVORS DELAY IN A FEDERAL EXECUTION, BUT NOT NATIONWIDE
MORATORIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURGETTSTOWN, Pa. _ Vice President Al Gore said Friday that he
backed the Clinton administration's decision to postpone the first
federal execution in 40 years but did not support a nationwide
moratorium on executions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a long-time death penalty supporter, spoke as the White
House indicated that the execution of Juan Raul Garza, now
scheduled for Aug. 5, would be postponed to await Justice
Department regulations for death row inmates to follow in seeking
clemency from the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do support the decision to put these clemency procedures in
place and, pending that, to hold off on this particular case,''
Gore said at a late afternoon news conference while campaigning in
the battleground state of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   But he drew a line, at least for now, between the temporary
reprieve and any broader halt to executions because of questions of
racial or geographical disparities in application of the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not yet seen evidence that to me would justify a
nationwide moratorium,'' Gore said. ``If such evidence emerges, I
would not hesitate to support that step. But I have not seen it
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore and Bush both support the death penalty, the issue
has gained some prominence in the presidential rate because of the
decision by Gov. George Ryan of Illinois, a Republican, to declare
a moratorium on the death penalty in his state after evidence came
to light that at least a dozen death row inmates were innocent of
the crimes for which they were convicted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On his campaign trip, Gore continued his week-long assault on
pharmaceutical companies and accusing Bush of being the candidate
of the industry.``I will lead the fight for you and not for the
powerful,'' Gore told a group of the elderly at a senior citizen
center in Bridgeville. ``The HMOs and insurance companies are
supporting my opponent. I am fighting for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a half-hour later, he declined to criticize his own chief
media adviser, Carter Eskew, for the revelation that he had once
tried to obtain a lucrative public relations contract from the
pharmaceutical industry to help fight legislation like Gore's own
proposal for a Medicare prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported on a memo to the industry from
Eskew and his former public relations firm, BSMG Worldwide, arguing
that prescription drugs could become a central issue of the 2000
presidential campaign and proposing a public relations drive to
``chill support'' for legislative efforts on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he countenanced such a proposal by Eskew, Gore said:
``You'll have to ask him that. What he did before he worked for me
is something you'll have to ask him.'' He called the efforts by
Eskew and his former company a ``completely separate matter'' from
his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would ask Eskew to speak to the press about his
former business activity, Gore said, ``Sure, but that's up to
him.'' Eskew did not return a call to his office. Gore's aides said
they did not contest that the memo was genuine.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Gore accused Citizens for Better Medicare, a
group started by the drug industry of running a media campaign that
was ``polluting the airwaves.'' Democrats than tied the group to
the Bush campaign by noting that the firm of Alex Castellanos, the
media consultant working on the ads, had done work for the Bush
campaign placing its television commercials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
