<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOBS REPORT ADDS TO EVIDENCE ECONOMY IS SLOWING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a disastrous May, American companies added modestly to
their payrolls in June, creating 206,000 new jobs, the Labor
Department reported Friday _reinforcing the impression that the
economy is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Job creation in the private sector has now fallen from an
average of 244,000 a month in the first quarter to only 110,000 a
month from April through June. But if companies are reluctant to
hire, they are still doing so in sufficient numbers to keep the
unemployment rate at only 4 percent in June, down from 4.1 percent
in May _ the lowest levels since the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic growth is slowing, but gently, so far,'' said James
Glassman, a senior economist at Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The coming and going of thousands of census takers skewed the
overall job numbers in June as they had in May. The total number of
jobs created in June _ covering government employees as well as the
private sector _ was only 11,000. That was mainly because 190,000
census takers, having finished their work, left the Census Bureau's
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   In May, however, 356,000 census takers were hired, swelling the
total job count to 171,000. Without them, private sector employment
fell by 165,000, the largest decline in eight years and the first
of any size since the economy began to soar in the mid-1990s. The
May job loss had been estimated originally as 116,000, but was
revised Friday to 165,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have about 428,000 temporary census takers out
there, and they will come off the payroll, probably in July and
August,'' said Thomas Nardone, chief of the division that prepares
the employment data at the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration acknowledged that the new job report
adds to the evidence that the economy is slowing. ``We do see signs
of moderation,'' said Labor Secretary Alexis Herman, ``but the
economy is still steady and stable and strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices soared Friday in response to the new evidence of
slowing, the view being that the Federal Reserve will be less
likely to raise interest rates at its next policy meeting, on Aug.
22. Rising rates encourage investors to switch their money out of
stocks and into interest-bearing investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another weak month would kill an August rate hike,'' Ian
Shepherdson, chief domestic economist for High Frequency Economics,
advised his clients Friday, referring to the June job report.
</P>
<P>
   But some Wall Street economists argued that while job creation
may be slowing, inflation remains an issue, even in a weakening
economy, and the Fed will have to deal with it. Labor shortages and
competition for workers, this argument goes, must eventually force
up wages and then prices, although that has not happened yet to a
significant degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is discounting any further Fed rate increases,
which I think is a mistake,'' said Peter Hooper, chief domestic
economist of Deutsche Bank North America. Mortgage rates and other
consumer rates, he argued, are not yet high enough to dampen demand
sufficiently to discourage price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Others noted that average hourly earnings for production
workers, representing about 75 percent of the 131.6 million people
in the work force, rose by 5 cents in June, to $13.71, as the
Bureau of Labor Statistics reported Friday. The increase in May had
been only 2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   When viewed over 12 months, the increase is a mild 3.6 percent.
But since January the average hourly pay for production workers
turns out to have risen at an accelerated 4 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hourly wage increase was not comforting at all,'' said
Joel L. Naroff, president of Naroff Economic Advisors Inc. But the
National Association of Manufacturers saw the glass as half full.
It noted that recent improvements in productivity have more than
paid for the hourly wage increase. The productivity growth rate
measures an average worker's output during each hour on the job.
The higher the output, the more revenue the worker brings in for
his employer to pay for wage increases without raising prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wage path implies an underlying rate of inflation of only
about 1 percent a year,'' Jerry Jasinowski, president of the
National Association of Manufacturers, said in a statement. The
manufacturers have been arguing against any further Fed rate
increases, insisting that more will slow the economy too much.
</P>
<P>
   There have been six rate increases since June 1999 totaling 1.75
percentage points, and their impact on demand helps to explain why
the economy has begun to slow down, economists say. Other reasons
are also cited. One is gasoline price increases, which divert
family income from other spending. Another is heavy buying of
homes, cars, appliances, furniture _ to the point that demand is
sated.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market wealth effect no longer has its old kick,
others argue. With stock prices going sideways in recent months, or
falling in the high-tech sector, consumers no longer feel as
confident about their wealth. And a strong dollar is restricting
exports, particularly manufactured exports.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the job growth in June came in the service sector,
particularly business services, which added 54,000 jobs, and in
retailing, which added 49,000 jobs, most of them at restaurants.
Consultants led the growth in business services, with healthy
increases also in temporary help, health services, engineering and
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Employment in the financial sector seemed to show the effects of
the slowing economy and higher rates. Jobs in this sector fell by
6,000 last month and 20,000 so far this year, with cutbacks in
commercial and mortgage banking, insurance and real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Construction employment, which has fluctuated sharply with the
weather, grew by 3,000 jobs in June, raising the average monthly
gain to 20,000 this year, down from 25,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the June figures gave evidence of the tight labor market.
The unemployment rate for women who support families fell in June,
as it did for teenagers and people with a high school education or
less. The number of people holding part-time jobs because they
could not get full-time work also fell.
</P>
<P>
   For blacks and Hispanics, however, the unemployment rate, which
had jumped in May, failed to fall back in June. And among the
unemployed, the percentage of job leavers _ people who quit a job
confident they can get another in a strong economy _ fell by 1.1
percentage points in June, to 12.1 percent, its lowest level in
months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
