u i BC-SAFRICA-AIDS-1100(2TA     07-07 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-AIDS-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN PRESIDENT CONFRONTS AIDS, AND CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SCI-AIDS) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ It was just past midnight when the phone
jangled in the home of Malegapuru Makgoba, one of South Africa's
most influential scientists. To his astonishment, he heard the
voice of President Thabo Mbeki rumbling across the line.
</P>
<P>
   The president was thumbing through scientific journals, surfing
through cyberspace and pondering the AIDS epidemic that is ravaging
this country. He was calling for advice late that January night,
but he ultimately disregarded Makgoba's counsel and began exploring
the work of two Americans who argue that HIV does not cause AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Mbeki's interest in such a theory _ though he has
never explicitly adopted it _ exploded in the world's newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent doctors accused Mbeki of dabbling in pseudoscience
while people were dying. Even government officials wondered why the
president had unleashed such a furor. ``Why not just keep quiet?''
asked Joel Netshitenzhe, the chief of government communications,
describing the concerns of some anxious officials.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday Mbeki will confront many of his critics, including
Makgoba, when he addresses thousands of researchers here on the
opening day of the 13th International Conference on AIDS. He will
stand before them, the leader of a country swept up in the plague,
with his reputation bruised and his credibility questioned.
</P>
<P>
   But if he has stumbled in his handling of the AIDS crisis here,
his struggle has also offered rare insight into the thinking of an
intensely private leader in his first year in office.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two months, as he has tried to clarify his stance,
Mbeki has painted a self-portrait of a restless intellectual, a
meticulous hands-on manager who rarely delegates decisions and a
chief executive who challenges convention, even when advisers
suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't go into this work, into this office, in search of
popularity,'' Mbeki said, according to Netshitenzhe, when some
officials suggested that the president should have shied away from
the fray. ``If there are issues to be dealt with, they need to be
pursued.''
</P>
<P>
   For South Africa, it is a striking shift in substance and style.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Mandela, the country's first democratically elected
leader, delegated many of his responsibilities, serving as a
charismatic caretaker president. Mbeki thrives on details, closely
manages his cabinet and often analyzes important matters way into
the night.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's critics say this means that the president sidelines his
own ministers and experts. His supporters say this means his
ministers must be prepared to study the issues as carefully as the
president does. In practice it means that all but his most capable
of ministers sometimes fade from public view.
</P>
<P>
   For instance it was clearly Mbeki, not the health minister, who
drove the government's inquiry into the causes and treatment of
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   He was the one who came across the research by two American
biochemists, Peter Duesberg and David Rasnick, who argue that
poverty and malnutrition _ not the human immunodeficiency virus _
cause AIDS. He was the one who began questioning the safety of the
commonly prescribed drug AZT after reading criticism of the drug on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki contacted local and foreign researchers, surrounded
himself with books and journals and consulted with the minister of
health when he came across medical terms he did not understand. And
when he noticed opinions that challenged established views, he did
not hesitate to pursue them.
</P>
<P>
   He is, after all, no stranger to challenging the establishment.
During the apartheid years, he was among the first members of the
African National Congress to argue that negotiation with whites _
not armed revolution _ would lead to the demise of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   As president, he has been willing to challenge his own allies,
the labor unions, by taking a tough stance on labor negotiations
and vowing to speed privatization and to relax some protections for
workers, a position that has helped strengthen investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
   And it was only natural, officials say, that Mbeki would turn
his scrutiny to AIDS. According to the United Nations, South Africa
has the largest number of people living with HIV, an estimated 4.2
million of its 44 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally, he's raising these issues because in South
Africa, in our region, we've got to find, we have to find the
necessary solutions to enable us to deal with this pandemic,'' said
Essop Pahad, the minister of the office of the presidency and one
of Mbeki's close friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if he wants to understand something, he will not rely only
on other people's views,'' Pahad said in an interview. ``He wants
to understand it for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki is not scientifically trained, but he was an outstanding
student in South Africa and earned a scholarship to the University
of Sussex in England, where he received a degree in economics.
</P>
<P>
   His critics say the controversy shows how Mbeki's
single-mindedness and reluctance to defer to experts can be risky.
Even some government officials worry that Mbeki's ruminations on
AIDS (and the media's simplification of his views) may have
undermined efforts to prevent the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Mbeki's consultation with the two Americans was
widely broadcast on television and radio here. And counselors say
they are encountering people who assume they can engage in risky
sexual behavior because the president has suggested that HIV is not
the real cause of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much international consternation over Mbeki's
suggestions and the impact they may have that 5,000 scientists from
across the world signed a declaration affirming that HIV causes
AIDS. The statement was published this week in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are outraged at what's happening,'' said Mary Caeser,
the national coordinator of the AIDS Legal Network, a human rights
and service organization. ``While the president has the prerogative
to address any issue, people feel that the manner in which he is
handling the issue is irresponsible. It's created confusion. We've
lost ground in terms of the work we have done.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has already begun a quiet retreat. Mbeki, who
angrily described the criticism as a ``campaign of intellectual
intimidation and terrorism'' in a letter to President Clinton,
began tempering his comments during a visit to the United States in
May.
</P>
<P>
   This week the health minister, Dr. Manto Tshabalala-Msimang,
admitted in Parliament that government officials, including Mbeki,
were mistaken when they said AZT was too toxic to prescribe to
pregnant mothers. She said research showed that the benefits of the
drug clearly outweighed the risks, though she says it is still too
expensive.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And an international panel of scientists convened by Mbeki
disbanded this week without making any proclamations on the
question of what causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Netshitenzhe and Pahad emphasized that Mbeki did make important
points that were rarely mentioned, including the inability of
Western science so far to cope with the disease in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The president highlighted the differences between the virus in
Africa, which is typically transmitted heterosexually, and the
strain in the West, which is most commonly transmitted through
homosexual contact and intravenous drug use. And the officials
praised him for being in the forefront of a push for a vaccine
developed in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Makgoba, who has become one of Mbeki's fiercest critics,
nevertheless says the president should get credit for financing
research into a vaccine and for being willing to evolve in his
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Makgoba admits, he was angered by the president's
public musings about AZT and by his decision to consult with the
American researchers. But he describes that as ``water under the
bridge.'' In hindsight, he says, the whole issue has helped him
better understand the man who is leading the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a continuous learner,'' said Makgoba, who heads the
Medical Research Council, the South African equivalent to the
National Institutes of Health. ``He wants to understand things.
He's basically a man who wants to exercise his power with knowledge
derived from his own understanding of things. That sets him apart
from presidents in the Western world, where most people rely on
being fed information from advisers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means he doesn't take accepted views easily,'' Makgoba
said. ``Sometimes it's part of his strength. It can also be his
weakness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
