<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6151 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-PARENTS-ART-2TAK     07-07 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PARENTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PRESIDENT AND MRS. BUSH, IN RARE INTERVIEW, DISCUSS THEIR SON'S
PROSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BUSH-EXCERPTS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine _ In a rare face-to-face interview about
his son's presidential campaign, former President George Bush said
Friday that Gov. George W. Bush would emerge victorious in November
largely because American voters periodically craved change, and
because President Clinton's conduct in office had sharpened that
appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush, who sat with his wife, Barbara, for a
nearly hour-long interview at the family' compound here, said that
Vice President Al Gore's ties to Clinton would not allow him to
present himself credibly as a fresh start, and that Gov. Bush's
ability to do so would prove decisive.
</P>
<P>
   The former president also cited that same cyclical impulse in
the electorate as the reason he was defeated in 1992, after one
term in office, by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was the victim of people wanting change,'' said
Bush, who served as vice president under President Ronald Reagan
for two terms before winning the presidency in 1988. He described
voters' sentiments in 1992 as ``eight years of Reagan, four years
of Bush, we want a change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think the same thing is true now,'' he said. ``I think
people kind of like change, like the idea of change from time to
time. I think that works for George's benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Mrs. Bush, the former first lady, also said that that
they thought the notion of ``Clinton fatigue'' was real, and that
their son's frequent pledge to ``restore honor and integrity'' to
the Oval Office was one that would resonate with voters who felt
that those virtues had indeed been compromised under Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't even debatable, in my view,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that the Bushes' joint interview Friday was one of
only three or four they had done over the last year, and their
comments were striking for several reasons, chief among them the
way in which Bush interpreted both his and his son's presidential
fortunes in terms of historic forces outside their control.
</P>
<P>
   In assessing his son's prospects for victory, Bush dwelled
longer on the country's itch for something different than on the
Texas governor's record and positions on issues, though he did
offer hearty praise for both. And in chalking up his own defeat in
1992 to that same itch, he rejected the prevailing view that he
lost because he failed to articulate coherently any domestic agenda
or to run as spirited a campaign as Clinton did.
</P>
<P>
   The former president and the former first lady also spoke more
harshly of Clinton's behavior in office than they had usually
allowed themselves to in the past. And while they and the Texas
governor have flatly dismissed suggestions that his candidacy was
an act of redemption and revenge, his parents' words and demeanor _
especially his mother's' _ suggested that they had not left 1992
completely behind them.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, they indicated a sensitivity to President
Bush's legacy. Mrs. Bush, almost as an aside, murmured that the
good economy now was really her husband's doing, and the former
president mentioned that he was bothered by Clinton's assertions
that Gore was perhaps the best vice president ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to argue that on my own behalf,'' Bush said,
referring to his own years as vice president. ``We had the, you
know, drug interdiction program. We had the deregulation task
force. I headed up the anti-terrorist task force. I took the case
for American missiles to Germany, the Pershings. I mean, there was
a lot of substance there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Monica Lewinsky affair and Clinton's
impeachment had hurt the country in real, meaningful ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a diminution of respect for the office of the
presidency, and it's not just here, it's abroad,'' he said, adding
that voters' concern about that ``is going to manifest itself on
election day.''
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton's had initially come up, Bush signaled that she and
her husband would take a pass on the topic, in accordance with a
long-held vow not to speak ill of Bush's successor.
</P>
<P>
   But minutes later, Bush was discussing Americans' lowered
expectations for public officials, and when her husband said she
could not blame that entirely on Clinton, she responded, ``Oh, I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes also addressed head-on the persistent questions about
whether their son had enough knowledge about foreign affairs to
lead the nation. George Bush _ a former ambassador to the United
Nations, envoy to China and director of Central Intelligence who
campaigned for the White House on his foreign policy expertise _
acknowledged that his son did not know as much as he did when he
did when he became president.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``He knows every bit as much about it as Bill
Clinton did.''
</P>
<P>
   Did his son know as much as Gore?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's had eight years of experience there,'' the former
president acknowledged. ``But the way I should be judged on whether
I knew foreign policy is by the kind of people I had around me.
Because I didn't know all this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You get good people,'' he added, echoing his son's frequent
refrain that a president principally assembles a team, delegates
responsibilities and makes final decisions based upon good advice.
``George knows enough to do that and enough about the world to have
good judgment on his own at this point,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, unprompted, he returned to the question of his son's
preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going back in my mind,'' he said. ``You had Reagan,
Carter, Clinton. What was their foreign affairs experience? They
got elected president.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush then chimed in with a reference to Gore's awkward
toast, during a visit to China in 1997, with Li Peng, who had
ordered the violent crackdown on protesters in Tiananmen Square in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we ought to think of Al Gore in China at the
time that he was caught with the champagne glasses,'' she said.
``I'm not going to think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing?'' Bush said, acting displeased with her
acidic interruptions but never really seeming so. ``You're not
going to be in this interview if you're going to start talking like
that. George will call and he'll be furious.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes have kept a fairly low public profile throughout
their son's presidential campaign, taking care not to overshadow
him, to invite criticism that he was simply riding on his family's
name, or to make accidental statements that could become
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Republican convention just a few weeks away, they
decided to grant a few interviews. They are clearly eager to make
the case for his candidacy. And they realize that the nostalgia
that many Americans now feel for them can work to their son's
advantage. (``Time heals a lot of wounds,'' the former president
said.)
</P>
<P>
   And they clearly have a hard time containing their pride in what
could be a historic circumstance. If George W. Bush is elected
president, it will be only the second time in U.S. history that the
son of a president ascended to the same post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mind-boggling for me,'' the former president said during
the interview, which began in the living room of the main house,
continued over a lunch of lobster salad on a rear terrace
overlooking the Atlantic, and ended when he had to rush off with
his son Jeb, the governor of Florida, for a 12:30 p.m. tee time at
a nearby golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush, who joined his parents for lunch, said that his
brother George was benefiting from a Republican yearning to take
back the White House _ a desire so strong that the party was
managing to paper over internal divisions that had fractured it in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years in the wilderness brings a higher tolerance for
diversity,'' Jeb Bush said, adding that 12 years in the wilderness
had made the Democratic party rally in a similar way around Clinton
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you looked at Bill Clinton's record as governor of
Arkansas, he was given a huge break by groups that were anxious to
have a Democrat in the White House,'' Jeb Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not make any sort of similar appraisal of his
brother's record, he later added, ``Well, I think the same thing
applies this year and benefits George, rather than Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Former President and Mrs. Bush acknowledged that in 1992 or 1993
or even the beginning of 1994, they never expected a day like this
to come. Bush left Washington as something of a pariah in the
Republican Party, a man who had acquiesced to a tax increase and
lost the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want to have anything to do with me,'' he
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   And George W. Bush had never really demonstrated the sort of
political ambition that his brother Jeb had. When he told his
mother that he planned to run against the incumbent Texas governor,
Ann Richards, in 1994, she told him he would lose. His mother was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the difference between then and now, his father
said, ``I'm amazed _ still amazed _ at the way he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents said that they never doubted that he had the talent
and temperament for politics and governing, and they praised his
performance as governor, saying that he had set priorities, stuck
to them and delivered on his promises.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked about the reason for his short trajectory from
new governor in January 1995 to presidential hopeful as early as
1998, his father again cited an external reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was that he was elected governor of the second
biggest state in the nation, and then he was re-elected with 70
percent of the vote, and anybody who's governor of a big state
probably thinks, `Hey, I could be president','' the former
president said. ``And somewhere in there, I don't know where it
was, George made up his mind. He didn't come ask us,
incidentally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If George weren't running for president,'' his father added,
``whoever was the nominee of the Republican Party would surely be
looking at him, among others, to be vice president. It's a six-inch
putt. Because of the importance of the electoral votes and the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he was not getting involved in his son's search for
a vice president, and he unequivocally denied rumors that he might
act as an intermediary to convince Gen. Colin Powell, a close
friend, to reconsider his reluctance to take the job. He said that
Powell was unequivocally unwilling.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he said, he reserved the right simply to be an
extraordinarily proud father, generous with emotional support but
not with advice on strategies or issues. ``If you asked me, life or
death, You've got to tell me how big the tax cut is that George is
proposing, I couldn't tell you,'' he said. ``I don't give a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Both former President and Mrs. Bush had generally kind words for
the current vice president, Al Gore, saying that when they were in
the White House and he was a senator, they had met and liked him.
When asked whether Gore had gone overboard, during the impeachment
proceedings, by calling Clinton one of the greatest American
presidents, Bush expressed sympathy for the political bind in which
Gore found himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you accept the vice presidency, then you've got to be a
loyal vice president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when the whole nation is embarrassed by something,'' he
added, ``that loyalty can hurt you in terms of your own
credibility. And if you waffle on it, that hurts you. It's a
Catch-22.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Greatest president, though?'' Mrs. Bush asked, referring to
Gore's remark. ``In history?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're saying too much,'' Bush told her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
