<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6156 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-SHOE-SALES-ART-$ADV09     07-07 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOE-SALES-ART-$ADV09-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WALK ON THE WILD SIDE STIRS THE SHOE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For shoe seismologists, the fourth-floor women's shoe department
at Saks Fifth Avenue in Manhattan is a prime place to detect early
tremors.
</P>
<P>
   To please its demanding, moneyed clientele, Saks specializes in
delivering the newest, comeliest creations from Spain and Italy
before other retailers do. But while the department is nearly
always chock-full of well-pedicured women, they are arguably not
its most ardent clientele.
</P>
<P>
   The capacious salon is an important hunting ground for
trend-spotters _ the stylists from mass-market shoe designers who
need to know what will soon be the retail rage from Denver to
Dubuque.
</P>
<P>
   And last February, Saks sent off powerful shock waves. The
store's shelves were stocked with purple paisley-print wooden
wedges, tiger-striped thongs in neon jungle greens and gold-mesh
pumps with laminated gold heels. Imagine the types of shoes that
Jerry Garcia might have designed in the throes of a Grateful Dead
concert and you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, shoes at other retailers and on feet everywhere
were equally dazzling. The chunky black pump that had been the
standby for everything from pants suits to summer minis was looking
a little too chunky. Instead, cool mavens were wearing gingham
print open-toed pumps in the office, multicolored embroidered and
beaded slides or suede moccasin-sneaker hybrids in the park and on
the street, and python-print sandals with dizzying come-hither
heels as soon as the sun went down.
</P>
<P>
   This sensory attack was not just the fashion indulgence of a few
wayward designers; it was a coordinated industry assault from
merchants like Bloomingdale's and design houses like Steve Madden
and Via Spiga. Despite the overall boom in consumer spending, shoe
sales have grown at a minuscule 1.8 percent a year for the last
decade, according to Footwear Market Insights, an industry research
organization based in Nashville. That is in keeping with historical
growth going back to the 1940s, but disappointing in comparison
with the 1980s, when, fueled by the athletic craze, shoe
consumption jumped about 6 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   So the footwear industry had to tackle a problem that now and
then plagues consumer industries from clothes to cars: When cash
registers stop ringing, how do you entice consumers to go out and
buy more?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, in a word, was revolution, not evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by current psychedelic clothing styles and able to
exploit new technologies that easily allow fancy embellishments
like beading, shoemakers are dreaming up fantasy styles that have
never been seen before. And they hope that their exotic new
confections will re-ignite consumer interest with a passion.
</P>
<P>
   The changes affect women's fashion shoes at all price levels.
Some children's shoes and even some men's footwear, usually very
conservative, are getting an infusion of shade and attitude, too.
(Even the staid Brooks Brothers is selling slide-on sneakers in
nubuck for men with style acumen.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has been in a rut,'' sighed Fawn Evenson,
president of the Footwear Industries of America, a trade group.
``All that you see out there is a desperate attempt to change
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Going for a bit of brightness and whimsy sounds obvious enough _
even Apple Computer scored big when it thought to market its wares
in shades brighter than beige _ but it also carries risk. Business
history is replete with newfangled fashions and products that
consumers refused to buy (remember the maxi-skirt?), and retailers
and manufacturers alike must walk a fine line between attracting
and alienating customers.
</P>
<P>
   For the shoe industry, the move is a surprisingly bold
experiment. Over most of the last decade, women seemed to want to
buy only one thing: black. Or, more specifically, Evenson said,
``black-leather, square-toed, fat-heeled.''
</P>
<P>
   About 362 million pairs of women's dress and casual shoes were
sold at retail last year, according to Footwear Market Insights,
and roughly 85 percent of them were black or brown, according to
Mike Kormos, the organization's president.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Boettge, president of the National Shoe Retailers
Association, the trade group of the independent retailers, agreed.
``We got into a black key that was just incredible,'' Boettge said.
``The first five colors were black, black, black, black and
black.''
</P>
<P>
   That preference struck fear into the hearts of manufacturers and
retailers alike: The more that footwear became separated from the
rest of fashion, the less likely that women would feel compelled to
refill their shoe closets with any frequency. ``You can't keep
selling black dumb shoes, when women already have seven pairs in
their closet,'' Evenson said.
</P>
<P>
   So now the bet is whether season-shifting colors and the latest
decorations can bring out the average shopper's inner Imelda
Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   Changing fashions, of course, got shoe designers into the color
bind in the first place. For a long time, many American women
obeyed the fashion dictum to coordinate the color of their shoes
with that of their clothing. A turquoise sundress required
turquoise slingbacks, and a red suit called for power red pumps.
</P>
<P>
   But sometime in the 1990s, the New York-centric affinity for
black and neutral outfits became the uniform for women elsewhere.
Some trace the trend to the rise of the designer Kenneth Cole,
whose pared-back urbanite look has been a major influence for the
last five years. Whatever the reason, black, once strictly for
winter and evening wear, suddenly became ubiquitous. Even in the
South, the signature, post-Memorial day white pumps went the way of
hand-churned ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   But what sartorial caprice can take away, it can return as well.
And lately the neutral-shade monopoly has been overthrown. Janet
Moran, vice president and divisional merchandise manager for shoes
at Saks, thinks she can place her finger on the moment when things
went wild. ``It goes back to the Gucci runway collection for the
spring, 1999,'' she said. ``Tom Ford did the beaded jeans and
Hawaiian prints. He did it at his level and then everyone
followed.''
</P>
<P>
   By this year, ready-to-wear collections were ablaze in colors
(magenta, mandarin, lime), patterns, embellishments (beads,
feather, embroidery) and novelty materials (both real and faux
python and crocodile).
</P>
<P>
   With their pent-up creative juices suddenly freed, the most
influential shoe designers ferociously began offering their own
interpretations of the season's biggest trends. There was color _
as in suede moccasins by J.P. Todd in a power-pastel rainbow of
lilac, burnt orange and lemon frappe. There was decoration, as in
Dolce &AMP; Gabbana's romantic-as-a-spring-picnic-in-the-Tuscan-hills
slides, in white satin, embroidered with strawberries on the vine.
(The seeds and leaves on the strawberries are actually tiny black
and green beads.) And there was novelty, most influentially
represented by the understated round-toe 1940s-style dance pumps in
ostrich by Prada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Designers wanted to do something pretty and this year it was
quite fun,'' said Stuart Weitzman, whose privately owned label is a
department store mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Department stores, which increasingly rely on shoes and
accessories as a profit center, have followed the designers' leads
and bet big on out-there offerings. Nordstrom, which specializes in
carrying a particularly large shoe selection, estimates that it had
three times more color on its sales floor this spring than a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion is not the only influence on shoe offerings. Some of
this year's most whimsical creations would not have been available
in the mass market if not for new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   New techniques let shoemakers enamel heels in the same durable
paints that carmakers like Mercedes-Benz use to coat their
vehicles. Titanium fillers allow heels to be sculpted into the most
improbable shapes and heights, while sustaining strength. One of
Weitzman's popular evening designs has the foot-coddling portion of
the shoe perched on a rhinestone-studded, pyramid heel that narrows
to a tiny pinpoint beneath the foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like an optical illusion,'' he said. ``We definitely
could not have made that five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, decorations like multithread embroidery had to
be done mostly by skilled artisans, meaning that the process was
impractical for shoes priced below $100.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are all sorts of automated machines that make these
embellishments doable at $70 retail, not $250. And because the new
machines, unlike artisans, will work in any country, they let
manufacturers shift even more production to places like China,
where the remainder of the labor can be done at much lower cost.
</P>
<P>
   Because the savings in labor costs are mostly passed on to the
consumer, profit margins are no greater on these shoes than on
unadorned Mary Janes. Companies stand to make big money only on big
volume.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the advantage of the machines is not only that they can
spangle and bead clothing and footwear, but that they are also
doing a really good job of it. The factories, for example, work
with the same nylon cord used by commercial fisherman to catch
60-pound tuna. That solves one age-old footwear problem:
decorations can now be fastened to stay on past the first week of
wear.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is improved leather imprinting that makes
crocodile and python skins real enough to fool a taxidermist.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has also aided in making the mass market as swiftly
fashion-responsive as the upper echelons of the shoe business have
long been, but in a way that dismays high-end shoemakers: it also
greatly speeds the copying of their designs.
</P>
<P>
   Trend-spotters for an American design house shopping in Paris
``can take a digitized picture of a shoe they like, and it can be
beamed to a factory in China within an hour,'' said Boettge, of the
shoe retailer association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The factory can then make a sample, send it by FedEx back to
the company's office in Boston within 36 to 48 hours,'' he added.
``They can then decide to put it into production for the U.S.
market, with a total turnaround of less than two months.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, there are plenty of examples that prove his point.
``We've had two shoes from Prada, one in silk linen, the other
denim-colored, that we copied for the U.S. market,'' said Alan
Abbott, director of sales and marketing at Majilite, a leading
fabric provider for shoes and handbags, based in Lowell, Mass. ``It
takes no longer than two months. Leathers can be done in two weeks.
We are extremely proficient.''
</P>
<P>
   So with the shoe industry casting out new lines, the question
is: Are women responding to the bait? Retailers say their gamble
has been rewarded. ``Our customers have strongly embraced'' the new
patterns, said Jack Minuk, Nordstrom's vice president for shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Moran at Saks agreed, adding that sales in her shoe departments
were ``outpacing sales in the rest of the store.''
</P>
<P>
   NPD, a market research firm based in Port Washington, N.Y., that
tracks shoe sales in department stores only, says that in the first
quarter of this year, women's shoe sales rose 10 percent, even as
the sales percentage of black shoes declined by a little under a
point. Meanwhile, the number of pairs sold with animal print
patterns increased sixfold and the number with platform heels rose
70 percent, NPD said.
</P>
<P>
   But Boettge, who represents the independent shoe sellers, says
he is disappointed. ``It has helped, but it hasn't ignited the
market,'' he said. ``People are buying, but they are not throwing
out their old wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why merchants expect that next season will be even
wilder: thigh-high red python boots, open-backed slides for winter
and platform heels towering above 6 inches. Dream on, shoe
designers, dream on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
