u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-CRASH-REAC     07-07 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-CRASH-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING GOES ON, DESPITE GLOOM OVER TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SMITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ For Team SABCO, its priorities forever shifted at
11:23 a.m. when Kenny Irwin was killed in a crash on Turn 3.
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest of the field, practice and qualifying runs
continued for Sunday's New England 300. For the rest of the day at
New Hampshire International Speedway, it was, for the most part,
business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   The show went on.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if it were up to Bobby Labonte, the doors to his and every
other NASCAR trailer would have closed as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't have bothered me to close the garage and go
home,'' said Labonte, a nine-year veteran of the Winston Cup
Series, who stayed and finished 20th in Friday's qualifying. ``I
think that would have been more respectful to Kenny than practicing
30 minutes after that happened. We probably should have just gone
home and started over tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd just rather not even be here. Some people are different.
That's just my thought. Everybody can always say, `He was doing
what he loved' and `He'd want everybody to keep going.' Well, he
ain't here to say that for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Spencer had similar feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, I know there's nothing we can do about it, it's in
God's hands, but everything just went on,'' said Spencer, who
finished 18th. ``Everything just went on and that really bothers me
a lot. That bothers me more than anything. We all feel it, you
know, and you think that we don't feel that. But every competitor
in here and every person in this garage area feels like the best
thing we can do is load up and go home, but we know we can't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Crashes may be common in the sport, but that doesn't take any
sting out of what happened here Friday or what happened here May
12. Irwin's death came eight weeks after an accident took the life
of 19-year-old Adam Petty, son of NASCAR driver Kyle Petty and
grandson of the legendary Richard Petty.
</P>
<P>
   Petty, like Irwin, also crashed on Turn 3. The sharp corners on
the 1.058-mile track leave little room for error or mechanical
malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real long straightaway and you got no banking in the
corners,'' Labonte said. ``When something like that happens, it's a
critical area to be in trouble because you are going so fast with a
sharp corner like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident stunned Irwin's fellow drivers, for whom the race
is now secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes everything else not really seem to matter,'' said
Dale Jarrett, who in 1998 and '99 was a teammate of Irwin's on the
Robert Yates Racing Team. ``It's just very unfortunate. I'm just
glad to be able to say I knew him as a teammate, but more than
anything else, he was a friend and we've all lost a good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton finished fourth in the qualifying race, something
that now means very little to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be a good starting spot for us, but that's all
minuscule compared to what's gone on here today,'' Burton said.
``It's a real sad day here. Qualifying and racing and everything
else is way less important than what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows you how fragile life is. It's bad to even be here
today, but we have to do our business.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll have to do the same through the weekend. The tragic loss
of Irwin will make their jobs much tougher to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say that you won't be yourself for the weekend,''
Labonte said. ``The whole weekend here won't be the same as it
would have if that hadn't happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
