<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-BAHRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAHRES STUNNED BY SECOND FATALITY IN EIGHT WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Two months. Two crashes. Two deaths.
</P>
<P>
   A day that could have provided a little bit of closure for Bob
and Gary Bahre and the racing fraternity at New Hampshire
International Speedway instead became another black and fatal
Friday at the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Eight weeks to the day that his grandson, Adam, crashed and was
killed in Turn 3 during a NASCAR Busch Series practice session at
the track, Richard Petty was in the infield media center late in
the morning and talked about his family and its loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Bahres were in the audience and afterward met with Petty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard came up today and gave me a big hug,'' Bob Bahre said
later Friday. ``That meant the world to me, you know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Wounds might have been closing just some.
</P>
<P>
   They were about to be ripped wide open again. Just about the
time Bob Bahre and Richard Petty got together, Kenny Irwin, 30, hit
the concrete wall. Also in practice. Also in turn Turn 3.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the afternoon, NASCAR announced that Irwin, too,
had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a few knots in your gut, I'll tell you that,'' Bahre
said. ``It's one of those bad things. This time, I was up in the
office. It's just, you ask, Why? You know?''
</P>
<P>
   Why.
</P>
<P>
   It was the operative word Friday and likely will be around the
track and around the racing world in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Why New Hampshire International Speedway? Why Turn 3? Why two
fatalities in back-to-back events? Why now?
</P>
<P>
   ``By the same token, the 10 years we've gone with no incidents
should provide some evidence,'' said Gary Bahre, Bob's son and the
track president. ``That's got to be taken into consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation started with stuck throttles and drivers talked
about the track and how NASCAR should look into barriers to protect
them from solid walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, there's no question it's mechanical,'' Bob
Bahre said of both crashes. ``Both cars went straight in. You're
just going down the backstretch and going straight in. If the guy
lost it turning or something it would be one thing. I mean, this is
like a dragstrip.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bahres somberly watched the Modified race that followed the
practice session and qualifying and kicked off their first Winston
Cup weekend of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not criticizing anybody or anything, but in the 10 years
we were without anything like that, count how many guys were killed
skiing,'' Bob Bahre said. ``That doesn't make this any better, I'm
not saying that at all. It's one of those unfortunate things.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the Bahres had problems with the surface of
their track tearing up and they fixed the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, drivers mentioned those barriers that are becoming
popular at some tracks and are more forgiving than concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace talked of a bump going into Turn 3 that racers
must handle.
</P>
<P>
   The track, the Bahres said, is as smooth as racing surfaces
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``This racetrack is as safe as any other racetrack I've raced
on,'' said Ricky Craven, who starred here and throughout the North
before moving South and qualified fifth Friday. ``I don't know if
you call it an oxymoron, or what, to say that a racetrack is safe.
But this track is not unsafe, absolutely not. When a driver loses
control of his race car for whatever reason, mechanical, a cut
tire, whatever the case may be, then he's not in control and then
it becomes dangerous. But other than that this is a safe sport.''
</P>
<P>
   But it has been anything but safe the last two events here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel awful about it, my father feels awful about it,'' Gary
Bahre said. ``We feel awful for Kenny Irwin and awful for Kenny
Irwin's mom and dad. It's just really tough for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Two events, two deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The racetrack owners take the same approach as the racecar
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like anything, you could be working on a construction
site and a guy gets killed,'' Bob Bahre said. ``It bothers you, but
you just have to go back to work. It bothers you, but at the same
time, God forbid, you just don't want it to happen again. But it
did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
