<SLUG> BC-ERVING-SON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOPSY RULES OUT SUICIDE IN DEATH OF BASKETBALL GREAT'S SON 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANFORD, Fla. _ Sheriff Don Eslinger of Seminole County said
Friday that the 19-year-old son of basketball legend Julius Erving,
Cory Erving, whose body was found in a pond on Thursday by
searchers, did not commit suicide. Eslinger said there were no
obvious signs of trauma, but he declined to dismiss the possibility
of foul play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cause and manner of death have not been determined,
pending further tests,'' the sheriff told reporters here. He said
an autopsy had ruled out suicide, but a toxicology report was not
ready. Cory Erving had a history of drug problems and had completed
five rehab programs.
</P>
<P>
   Seminole investigators found his body on Thursday afternoon in a
pond about a half-mile from his family's residence in the affluent
Alaqua Lakes neighborhood. They had dragged 36 bodies of water in
three counties before finding him about 20 yards from shore,
submerged in his 1999 Volkswagen Passat.
</P>
<P>
   The windows were up and Erving was not wearing a seat belt. The
airbags had not been deployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an obligation to provide information to the family and
find some resolution,'' Eslinger said. ``We don't want to speculate
or draw false conclusions. We want to maintain our objectivity in
this case. We want to look at all possible scenarios.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sheriff's Department plans to enlist help from the Florida
Highway Patrol in reconstructing the scene and to make a mechanical
inspection of the vehicle, a department spokesman, Steve Olson,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eslinger said it had been determined that Erving was in the same
clothing that he wore on May 28, when he went to a nearby bakery to
pick up some bread for a family party. He called his father to say
he would be home in 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last communication his family had with him.
</P>
<P>
   Eslinger described the Ervings as ``grief-stricken.'' Pat
Williams, the president of the Orlando Magic, who was instrumental
in hiring Erving to work for the team three years ago, talked to
Erving Friday, and said he was coping with the reality of losing a
son.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some closure,'' Williams said. ``He used that word to
me several times. I think the unknown was what was so hard for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Erving, who achieved his basketball fame with the Philadelphia
76ers, issued a statement. It said in part, ``We have learned a lot
from this tragedy and we will be a stronger family as a result. The
Erving family will go forward from here. We have no other choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was a 76ers executive when Erving played there,
said he envisioned Erving becoming a spokesman for the campaign
against drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Julius for a long time,'' Williams said. ``He
didn't tell me this, but I just believe he will not want his son's
life to have ended in vain. I see him using what happened in a
positive way. I see him speaking out against drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Cory Erving had been missing for 16 days that
his family made his disappearance public. His father at first
offered a $25,000 reward for information about his whereabouts.
Three days later he increased that to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   That produced hundreds of phone calls to a special number, but
no significant leads.
</P>
<P>
   Cory Erving began using drugs at age 14, his father said, after
bad grades eliminated his chance of being a schoolboy athlete. He
operated between two distinct worlds, immersing himself in metro
Orlando's drug culture, while usually returning to a million-dollar
home.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Erving said that in recent years his son seemed to become
more determined to straighten out his life. Embarrassed early in
his school years about having a learning disability, he eventually
received his high school equivalency diploma at Seminole Community
College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
