<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GREENE-CORRUPTION0708     07-07 2306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENE-CORRUPTION0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Visionary'' alleged to be prominent figure in government
corruption cases
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Commerce Club in downtown Atlanta was filled with
the usual crowd: elected officials, county employees and, most
important, political contributors. But in this familiar setting for
a fundraising reception in the fall of 1998, Juanita Hicks recalls,
one newcomer stood out.
</P>
<P>
   George H. Greene moved through the crowd, shaking hands,
introducing himself, introducing other people to one another. He
was, Hicks remembers, working the room with an intensity unmatched
by any candidate at the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he would strike you is that he knew everybody,'' said
Hicks, the clerk of the Fulton County Superior Court. ``That he
knew people.''
</P>
<P>
   Who Greene knew and how he knew them have now become key
elements of a federal investigation into corruption in local
government.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the fundraiser and through 1999, authorities say,
Greene was paying bribes to Fulton County Commissioner Michael
Hightower. Greene's intent, they say, was to help his firm, Sable
Communications Co. of Georgia Inc., win county technology contracts
worth millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Greene has pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court, as have
Hightower and Josh Kenyon, the former chief of staff to two county
commission chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   And this may be only the start. Greene, 55, whose company also
had contracts with the city of Atlanta and other public agencies,
has agreed to assist the ongoing federal investigation. In
exchange, he may receive less than the maximum sentence of 10 years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty pleas and the pledge to help federal authorities
appear to cast Greene as a central figure in what could be one of
the farthest-reaching public corruption cases ever in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Greene declined requests for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But his lawyers and friends depict Greene as a victim. They say
he was drawn into a bribery scheme by a system that forces honest
business people to pay off government officials to win government
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that this fellow never did a thing wrong,
as far as I know, until he got caught up in this situation in the
county and the city,'' said Jeff Bogart, one of Greene's lawyers.
``He ran a pretty clean ship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't been a one-man crime wave all his life,'' said
another of Greene's attorneys, Wilmer Parker III. ``He's not a
mobster.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth about George Greene, though, is more complicated than
the tale spun by his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his own description of who he is turns out to be at
least exaggerated, if not fabricated, according to interviews,
court records and government files.
</P>
<P>
   He said he graduated from the University of Miami. He did not.
</P>
<P>
   He said he founded a chamber of commerce for black-owned
businesses in Miami. He did not.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had never been in trouble before the federal
corruption case. But he had been. In 1982, an insurance company
accused Greene of stealing premiums, and a judge ordered him to pay
the insurer more than $300,000. Greene was not charged with a
crime, however.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 12 years, Fulton County, the city of Atlanta,
and Grady Health System, among others, have paid his company
millions of taxpayers' dollars. It wasn't until he pleaded guilty
that government officials publicly questioned the deals. ``It's
amazing that they wouldn't do a background check,'' said Lee Parks,
an Atlanta lawyer who sued Greene in the insurance case. ``Or, if
they did, that they found it and didn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   A `VISIONARY' FALTERS
</P>
<P>
   Greene grew up in West Palm Beach, Fla., the son of a podiatrist
and a high school teacher. By the early 1970s, he was living in
Miami and something of an anomaly of the times: a successful black
businessman.
</P>
<P>
   He opened a string of insurance agencies, often in poor
neighborhoods that other insurers avoided. He never obtained an
insurance license, but hired agents to write policies _ mostly a
new kind of automobile coverage called ``no-fault.''
</P>
<P>
   As he expanded to other Florida cities, the namesake of the
George H. Greene Insurance Agency became something of a celebrity.
He taped his own radio ads, which ended with a catchy signature
phrase: ``Don't get caught without no fault.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was a visionary for African-American economic
development and business development here in the South Florida
area,'' said Wilbert Holloway, an executive with BellSouth in Miami
who has known Greene since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's vision extended well beyond South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   By 1980, he owned 22 insurance agencies in four states, at least
a half dozen in Georgia. The first Georgia office opened in 1976
with a ceremony that attracted local news coverage. Greene split
his time between Miami and Atlanta, where he kept a condominium.
</P>
<P>
   His agencies' main business was selling policies and collecting
premiums for American Interstate Insurance Co. of Georgia. Greene's
employees were supposed to deduct a commission _ 12 to 15 percent _
before forwarding the premiums to American Interstate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the employees sent the premiums _ which had totaled
about $291,000 by 1980 _ to a holding company Greene had set up in
Miami, according to court records. When American Interstate tried
to collect, the insurer alleged, Greene refused to pay.
</P>
<P>
   So American Interstate filed suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``George H. Greene has absconded with . . . funds owed to
American,'' the lawsuit charged. ``He has employed an elaborate
corporate shell game in an attempt to circumvent individual
liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene denied all the accusations _ that he had kept the
insurance company's money, even that he had done business with
American Interstate in Georgia. Bogart, one of his lawyers in the
current federal corruption case, characterizes the insurer's
lawsuit as ``a business dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Greene settled the lawsuit before it went to trial.
Superior Court Judge William W. Daniel of Fulton County ordered him
to repay the full amount that American Interstate had sought, plus
interest. The settlement totaled $335,812.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no defense to it,'' said Parks, American
Interstate's lawyer. The company never sought criminal charges, he
said, because ``the quicker way of getting the money back was the
civil suit. He had assets and was solvent.''
</P>
<P>
   After the case concluded, Parks said, Greene ``certainly
couldn't have done any more insurance work in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   A PROMOTIONAL BENT
</P>
<P>
   Greene's wife, Elaine, offered another reason for the demise of
their insurance agencies. The business, she told a city official in
Atlanta in 1994, had become ``too competitive,'' so they shifted
their efforts to another industry: cable television.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, the Greenes formed a company they called Sable Cable,
which sold commercial time on such networks as BET, the black
entertainment channel. Three years later, they opened a second
office in Atlanta and moved here.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenes took advantage of programs that required contractors
with local government agencies to hire minority-owned
subcontractors. Beginning in 1987, Sable Communications Co. of
Georgia was certified as a minority-owned business enterprise with
the city of Atlanta. Initially, the firm was registered to get
government work only in marketing and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, according to documents the company filed with the
city of Atlanta, Elaine Greene owned 75 percent of Sable's stock.
The head of its Miami office, David Levin, held the remaining
shares. George Greene was listed as the firm's manager, responsible
for ``all marketing and operations.'' But Elaine Greene had the
sole authority to write checks on the company's bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   George Greene became Sable's president in 1994, corporate
records indicate. By that year, Sable Communications had qualified
as a minority-owned subcontractor not just in marketing and
advertising, but also in cable television and telecommunications,
including pay telephones and long-distance service. It later added
installing fiber-optic cable to its repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Fulton County and Atlanta, Sable was hired _ usually as
a subcontractor to a much larger firm _ by MARTA (Atlanta's public
transportation system) Grady Memorial Hospital, the city of New
Orleans, the Louisiana prison system, Georgia Power Co. and others,
according to the company's promotional material.
</P>
<P>
   Sable's work got good reviews. IBM said Sable had ``performed
well'' on a government project, ``bringing it in on time and on
budget.'' TRW told Greene he was ``a man of (his) word'' who hired
``top drawer'' employees.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, Sable played up minor roles on major
projects.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a 1995 document the company gave Grady said that
Sable ``teamed'' with AT&AMP;T, BellSouth and two other firms to ``win
a 5-year contract'' to operate 1,400 pay phones at Atlanta's
Hartsfield International Airport. In fact, according to city
records, Sable, as a subcontractor, was a relatively minor party to
the deal. It borrowed $150,000 from AT&AMP;T and bought 74 telephones _
less than 6 percent of the total _ from the city for $13,500.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's depictions of himself also took on a promotional tone.
On a resume that he submitted to the city of Atlanta in 1996, he
said he was ``a successful entrepreneur'' with ``a passionate drive
and a constant quest for excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   That resume also contains assertions that can't be backed up.
</P>
<P>
   Greene claimed to have earned an ``A.S. degree'' from the
University of Miami in 1965. But Sandra Perryman, a spokeswoman for
the school's registrar, said records show Greene attended classes
only from September 1961 to January 1962. He received no degree,
Perryman said.
</P>
<P>
   Greene also said on the resume that he ``founded'' the
26-year-old Miami-Dade Chamber of Commerce, which promotes
black-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But when Dorothy Baker, the chamber's president and chief
executive, checked her founders' list, none of them were
``Greene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see his name,'' Baker said. ``These are our articles
of incorporation, and I don't see his name.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilbert Holloway, a friend from Greene's Miami days, recalled
that Greene once served as the chamber's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a leader of our chamber,'' Holloway said. ``He was not
one of the founding members of the chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   SUCCESS AND SCRUTINY
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Greene and his wife seem to have prospered. Elaine
Greene bought a Jaguar convertible, according to public records.
The couple built a cedar- and stone-sided house with its own tennis
court in an upper-middle class subdivision across the highway from
boxer Evander Holyfield's gigantic estate. They recently sold the
house for $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   The trappings of the Greenes' success have also included an
$800,000 Florida beach house that they bought in 1996 and sold for
$900,000 two years later.
</P>
<P>
   In both Florida and Georgia, George Greene formed an array of
companies, from a marketing firm to a steel-products distributor to
a formalwear store. Some prospered, others didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``George is an entrepreneur,'' said Cornell McBride Sr., a
prominent black businessman from Atlanta who described Greene as a
good friend. ``He truly understands a business. He's not really
restricted to any one area. . . . He has been able to shift his
interest and be successful in different things, learning those
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene also seems to have learned politics.
</P>
<P>
   From 1997 to 1999, Greene, his companies and members of his
immediate family donated more than $29,000 to 11 candidates for
city, county and state offices, according to campaign financial
disclosure reports. At the same time, several political officials
say, Greene became a prominent figure at fundraisers and other
political events.
</P>
<P>
   But with his visibility and success came scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have said little about how their
investigation of local political corruption developed. But they
have acknowledged that when investigators confronted County
Commissioner Hightower with allegations of corruption, he turned in
Greene. Subsequently, authorities said, Greene turned
investigators' attention to Kenyon.
</P>
<P>
   On June 8, Greene stood before U.S. District Judge Richard W.
Story and admitted that ``on several occasions'' in 1998 and 1999
he had given cash to Hightower, hoping to ``influence and reward''
the commissioner's role in awarding county contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is free on bond awaiting sentencing. His lawyer, Bogart,
would not say whether Greene is using this time to implicate
officials beyond those who have already been charged.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't clear how credible a witness Greene might make for the
government. His personal history and his recent guilty plea would
give a defense attorney ammunition to try to impeach his testimony,
said Jack Martin, an Atlanta lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any prior instances of wrongdoing _ especially dishonesty _ by
a government witness can be used by the defendant,'' Martin said.
But, he added, ``Cooperating witnesses are always someone who has a
checkered past.''
</P>
<P>
   McBride said he was shocked to see his friend on television,
entering the federal courthouse to face corruption charges. But the
blame, he contends, lies less with Greene than with forces beyond
his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say that after I hear about it, the one question I have
for all politicians and all governments is: Tell me any person who
has ever gotten a contract from a city or a county or a national
government without being politically connected,'' McBride said.
``Show me that one person.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, the system itself is kind of
defective.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
