<HEADLINE>
CIENFUEGOS TRIES TO REGAIN HIS TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Usually when Mauricio Cienfuegos does
something special, he pumps his fist like Tiger Woods. But after
scoring the lone goal in a 1-0 victory over Columbus on Tuesday,
the 32-year-old midfielder went a little bonkers.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he showed his trademark fist pump to the crowd at the Rose
Bowl, then he ran toward the Galaxy bench, leaping into the arms of
Dudley Hitchman, the team's assistant strength and conditioning
coach.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Cienfuegos' second goal of the season to go with a
paltry four assists. But in what has been a so-so season for the
four-time all-star, the burst of emotion explained how he felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mauricio has been at this game for a long time, he knows when
he is playing well and when he's not playing well,'' said Galaxy
coach Sigi Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy (9-5-7, 34 points) is hoping to win their second
consecutive match today in Miami, which would further extend their
playoff hopes and chances of catching Western Division leader
Kansas City (11-2-5, 38 points).
</P>
<P>
   To keep winning, Cienfuegos needs to keep producing.
</P>
<P>
   ``His (Cienfuegos') game of late hasn't been the quality and
standard he wants it to be,'' said Schmid. ``He's really trying to
lift his game so when he scored, all the emotion and energy came
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the inaugural season, Cienfuegos has been the team's
primary midfield general. But with so many changes, especially with
the acquisition of Luis Hernandez combined with losing fellow
playmaker Roy Myers to New York/New Jersey in order to acquire
Hernandez, Cienfuegos started losing his touch and timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never satisfied with your own performance but in this
case I knew I had to perform much better if this team was going to
start winning again,'' said Cienfuegos. ``I felt I needed to expose
myself more to my teammates and keep pushing the ball forward. I
have to drive this team and right now I'm getting a handle on it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid moved Cobi Jones to right midfield and shifted Simon
Elliott on the left to provide relief for Cienfuegos. It has given
Cien more room to operate and he is finding Hernandez and Jones in
space much easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a much better team than when Luis first
arrived,'' said Cienfuegos. ``We not only understand Luis and his
runs better, but everyone is feeling more comfortable with each
other since all of the changes were made.''
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, a long time member of El Salvador's national team,
passed Tampa Bay midfielder Carlos Valderrama Thursday as the top
vote getter for the MLS all-star match later this month in
Columbus. Cienfuegos thanked his countrymen for their support,
explaining that it was his popularity and not necessarily his
performance this season which resulted in 32,820 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's not sure if he will be selected to El Salvador's
national team when World Cup qualifying begins against Honduras
(July 16) followed by a match against fellow teammate Ezra
Hendrickson and St. Vincent and the Grenadines (April 23).
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to be part of your national team,
unfortunately our federation always waits till the last minute to
decide,'' said Cienfuegos.
</P>
<P>
   Two young players have said that Cienfuegos' time has passed him
bye and that he shouldn't be selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out in the paper and said they weren't convinced in
what I'll bring,'' said Cienfuegos. ``That's okay, I'm glad they
put their name to their opinions. I don't want to be an
inconvenience, I want what's best for my country but I know I still
have more to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   The way he's playing again, the Galaxy wouldn't mind if he was
left behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
