<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FENCING-IAGORASHVILI0     07-07 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENCING-IAGORASHVILI0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBy John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sorry guys, she's taken.
</P>
<P>
   During the men's Division I epee competition at the U.S.
National Fencing Championships Vahktang Iagorashvili walked over to
a large fencing bag. He pulled out a copy of the August issue of
Esquire, the one touting ``a Portfolio of America's 10 Sexiest
Athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   The cover girl for the issue is pentathlete Mary Beth Larsen.
Make that Mary Beth Larsen-Iagorashvili. The two pentathletes, both
of whom are fencing here this week, have been married a little less
than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither will make the U.S. Olympic team as a fencer,
both will be going to Sydney. Mary Beth will be in the first-ever
women's Olympic pentathlon competition and ``Vaho,'' as he's known,
will go as her coach.
</P>
<P>
   Fencing is one of five sports contested in the modern
pentathlon, along with riding, running, swimming and shooting. The
weapon used there is the epee, so pentathletes like to enter those
competitions when they can. On Friday, the U.S. men's pentathlon
team was out in force, although rising star Chad Senior stayed out
of the competition with a small injury. Mary Beth will compete in
the women's epee competition today.
</P>
<P>
   Vaho fenced Friday with a small contraption near his elbow. He
has an elbow injury from playing tennis and teaching fencing.
Although he's now 36, he still does quite well in the pentathlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was ranked No. 1 in the world,'' he said. ``This
year I'm still No. 5, even though I haven't competed much.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Vaho captured his third San Antonio World Cup title.
He was also on the U.S. team that crushed Russia and Hungary in a
World Cup team relay event to take the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he said, ``The rules said I could not compete in the Olympic
qualifier. Probably next year I will get my citizenship. I'm not
worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaho won a bronze medal for Russia in 1988 and was the Russian
national champion in 1991. Back then, Russia and his home country
of Georgia were splitting up. The Russians didn't want Georgians on
their team, and Georgia didn't have a team.
</P>
<P>
   About that time he came to the United States as a trainer to two
Austin pentathletes, Rob and Doug Stull. In 1996 he competed for
Georgia in the Olympics. He's been living in San Antonio the past
two years, where many pentathletes have trained, including Mary
Beth.
</P>
<P>
   She's 25, from Eagle, Wis., and is studying to be a
chiropractor. She dropped out of pentathlon for awhile after the
sport failed to make the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta. Instead,
she began doing triathlons. She returned to the pentathlon when it
was named a medal sport for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   As for his wife becoming a cover girl, Vaho said that was
something of a surprise and a lot more work that it looks like. He
said Mary Beth spent four hours to get that cover shot.
</P>
<P>
   After the Olympics, Vaho plans to compete in one more World Cup
meet and then retire from the pentathlon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
