<HEADER>
A6188 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-IRWIN0708-COX     07-07 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWIN0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Irwin's was a life full of racing
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kenny Irwin struggled to establish himself in Winston
Cup racing, but he was a winner and champion in just about every
other series in which he competed.
</P>
<P>
   From the same Indianapolis area that produced Jeff Gordon and
Tony Stewart, Irwin grew up on open-wheel racing before making the
move to stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin died Friday at the age of 30 after a practice-session
crash at New Hampshire Speedway. He was in his third full Winston
Cup season.
</P>
<P>
   He began racing at the age of 6. He formally started his United
States Auto Club career in 1991 at age 22, driving midget cars. Two
years later, he was rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Irwin also raced in the Silver Crown series and was
rookie of the year. A year later, he was the points champion. Irwin
won the USAC midgets series title in 1996 and also ran five races
in the fledgling NASCAR Craftsman truck series. His USAC midget
career included eight wins and 20 second-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin moved full-time to the truck series in 1997 and met with
immediate success: two wins, seven top-five finishes, a 10th-place
finish in the points race and the rookie of the year award. In only
his second truck-series start, he won the pole at Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   That August, the week of his 28th birthday, he was introduced as
owner Robert Yates' new driver for the fabled No. 28 Ford, to
replace Ernie Irvan for the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   He warmed up for his Yates debut by running four Cup races
toward the end of 1997. He started second and finished eighth in
his debut at Richmond, becoming the first driver in NASCAR's modern
history to start on the front row and finish in the top-10 in his
first race.
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth start for Yates in 1998, Irwin led much of the
Primestar 500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway and finished fifth. ``I was
thinking the whole year was going to be like that,'' he said, upon
going into an early season slump during which he failed to make the
field for the Coca-Cola 600 at Charlotte that May.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin rebounded by the end of the season, however, taking his
first career pole in the season-finale at AMS. He became the first
Winston Cup rookie to earn $1 million in a season and won rookie of
the year by 13 points over Kevin Lepage.
</P>
<P>
   His highlights that season incuded being the highest-starting
rookie in the history of the Brickyard 400, with a fourth-place
qualifying effort, and posting one top-five and four top-10
finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin opened the 1999 season by finishing third in the Daytona
500, which would turn out to be his best career finish in 87 Cup
races. But even before the season began, his relationship with
Yates was in trouble. He was criticized for being too fun-loving
and was taken to task for being seen too often shooting pool in
billiards parlors around Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Pool and golf were Irwin's other passions besides racing. He and
fellow Cup driver Mike Skinner occasionally got together for their
own friendly pool competition.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin had a better sophomore season than his rookie year, moving
from 28th in points to 19th. But late in '99, Yates announced that
he was letting Irwin go, and Irwin was hired to drive the No. 42
Chevrolet for Felix Sabates. He also was to drive 15 races for
Sabates' No. 42 entracked into the rear of Stewart's Pontiac on lap
147, sending it into the wall. Stewart climbed out of his car and
waited on the track for Irwin's car to come back around, tossed the
fire-shield pads from his shoes at the No. 28 Ford and attempted to
throw a series of left-handed punches into the cockpit area.
Stewart was reprimanded by NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
