<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6189 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-COURTS-ABUSE-2TAKE     07-07 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COURTS-ABUSE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD MOTHERS VICTIMIZED BY DOMESTIC ABUSE HAVE CUSTODY OF
CHILDREN? 
</HEADLINE>
   By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the supervising judge in Bronx Family Court, Judge
Clark V. Richardson spends most days presiding over one arduous
decision after another _ when to sever a mother's legal ties to her
child, when to throw a teen-age troublemaker behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   But these days there is a particularly vexing category of cases
on his docket: Richardson handles all of the cases in the Bronx
when the city's child welfare agency has removed children from
their homes because, in essence, one of their parents has been the
victim of domestic abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The city can take children into foster care if a parent is
believed to ``engage in acts of domestic violence.'' Its authority
to do so was strengthened by a 1998 state court ruling that
declared incidents of domestic violence in the presence of a child
to be sufficient grounds for a finding of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, Richardson said, that usually means that a mother
who is a victim of abuse can be accused of failing to protect her
children from danger. Often, she may have done nothing wrong or
negligent, but simply lacked the financial or emotional resources
to leave an abusive partner.
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, it falls to Richardson, and other Family Court
judges across the state, to decide whether those mothers get their
children back, and under what terms. After all, he and other child
welfare experts acknowledge, abusive parents can frequently be
players in the most tragic cases of child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   And so for Richardson, who deals daily with disputes of law and
love, violence and poverty, these cases present an especially
daunting exercise in balancing interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is difficult is that you're victimizing them twice,'' he
said of the mothers. ``On the other hand, you have the notion of
protecting the children. And they are not necessarily consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He cited two recent examples: in both, the city had taken
custody of children after a violent fight between their parents.
And in both, the women implored him to send their children back
home.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, a woman with a black eye stood before him,
claiming to have hurt herself by banging into a refrigerator. Her
husband sounded belligerent. Their 13-year-old daughter insisted
she had never witnessed any domestic violence at home. The judge
suspected she had been coached.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, a woman appeared alone, her arms pocked with
bruises, her face glazed by weariness. She told the judge of being
terrified of her husband. She agreed to move, to take her children
someplace where he would never find them. For the judge, the
questions were plain, if painfully hard to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Is it fair to punish an abused woman by taking her children
away? Is it wise to return children to a parent who has been unable
to shield them from the danger of an abusive partner?
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the judge, who under a pilot program sees all
such cases in the Bronx, ultimately allowed the children to return
home, but only after being assured that the women would make use of
counseling and other support services, he said. In the first case,
he waited even longer, until the couple acknowledged that there had
been a problem with violence in the home.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, such cases reflect an unintended consequence of
new and arguably enlightened perspectives on domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   It is now widely acknowledged that watching adults fight at home
_ and especially witnessing a parent being beaten _ can scar
children forever. Moreover, domestic violence can sometimes be part
of a package of dysfunction at home, a red flag for egregious forms
of child abuse and neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there's a close correlation between domestic violence
and child abuse,'' said Nicholas Scoppetta, commissioner of the
Administration for Children's Services, in an interview. ``Very
often where there's physical abuse of children, there's also
domestic violence in the home, in particular, when there's an
unrelated male in the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why, Scoppetta said, caseworkers routinely inquire into
domestic violence. The fact that one parent is abused, he asserted,
should not be the sole reason to remove their children, but if the
victim resists taking the steps necessary to protect the children _
by failing to keep the batterer away, for instance, or refusing to
move to a safe place _ the children should be removed for their
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials said they did not keep figures on how many
children were removed principally because of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a judgment call on the part of caseworkers,'' Scoppetta
said. ``I would hope they would make that call only when there's
evidence that the child is in imminent danger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we always get it right?'' he asked. ``I suspect it doesn't
always happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some women's advocates contend that the agency often does not
get it right. They have recently filed a class-action lawsuit
claiming that the city violates the due process of rights of
parents who have been victims of domestic violence by removing
their children.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of punishing the perpetrator, these advocates say, an
overzealous application of the law ends up punishing the victim.
That fear can keep victims of domestic violence from taking action
against their batterers, they say. And just as it can hurt children
to watch a parent being abused, they add, it can also hurt them to
be suddenly taken from that parent's care.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They offer the example of women like Sharlene Tillett, who was
accused of exposing her child to domestic violence even though the
child had not yet been born. Tillett, 29, was pregnant with her
second child last year when the baby's father, her ex-boyfriend,
from whom she had already separated, came to her apartment one
night and, in a bout of anger, began pummeling her.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time he had assaulted her, she said, but it
would be the last. She had decided, she said, to move to
California, where she had family, after the baby was born.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans unraveled the day she gave birth to a healthy baby
boy, whom she named Uganda. When a social worker at Jamaica
Hospital Medical Center asked about domestic violence as part of a
routine questionnaire, Tillett said, she answered candidly.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, in a move that she soon realized was a grave
mistake, she agreed to let the baby's father, Jamie Gray, take them
home from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   City records indicate that the social worker filed a complaint
to the state central register on child abuse and neglect. The next
day, child welfare caseworkers, accompanied by police officers,
carried away her 2-day-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Tillett was charged with child neglect. ``The respondents engage
in acts of domestic violence in the present of the subject child,''
the caseworker's report said.
</P>
<P>
   Tillett was also charged with not having a crib for the baby. It
did not help, she said, when she explained she was planning to move
to California. She had a plane ticket in hand, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It took Tillett seven weeks to get Uganda back, as well as 19
weeks of court-ordered workshops for domestic violence victims, 10
hours of classes on being a good parent and counseling once a week.
She now lives in a homeless shelter for battered women. The city
child welfare agency is continuing to monitor her case.
</P>
<P>
   Like Tillett, Sharwline Nicholson said she was wholly unprepared
for the arrival of the child welfare agency in her life. She, too,
had separated from the father of her second child. He had never
been violent until one wintry afternoon last year, when in an
apparent fit of jealousy, she said, he went to her Brooklyn
apartment unexpectedly, hurled whatever was in sight, and kicked
and hit her so severely that her arm was broken. The baby,
Destinee, was sleeping in another room; her 6-year-old son,
Kendell, was in school.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-boyfriend, Claude Barnett, fled. When the police and
paramedics arrived, Nicholson said, she asked a neighbor who
frequently watched her children to baby-sit until her cousin could
pick them up later that day. Knowing her children would be safe,
she said, she slept peacefully at Kings County Hospital that night.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, a child welfare caseworker called the
hospital. ``They said they had possession of my kids,'' Nicholson
recalled. ``I was devastated. I've always heard the worst when they
get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The city charged her and Barnett with child neglect. Barnett,
the court papers added, had hit the little boy in the mouth once
before. ACS officials also said Nicholson had not showed up in
court and had refused to move to a new apartment.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Nicholson denies that Barnett had hit Kendell. She
admits she missed one court appointment, citing a severe snowstorm.
And she calls the child neglect charges ``ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I called 911 I was bleeding so badly I knew I needed
medical attention,'' Nicholson, 31, a store cashier and part-time
student at Mercy College, said the other day. ``I didn't know I'd
end up down that road, that calling for help would escalate and I'd
end up losing my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   A Family Court judge in Brooklyn returned her children in a
week, while the child welfare agency continued to monitor her case.
Her case has since been closed, but Nicholson's outrage at the
child welfare agency remains.
</P>
<P>
   She is the lead plaintiff in a class-action lawsuit filed in
April against the agency, claiming that her due process rights were
violated. Carolyn A. Kubitschek, the lawyer who filed the suit,
said she did so to compel the city to better train its caseworkers,
so that children would not be removed just because a parent had
been abused.
</P>
<P>
   By everyone's admission, deciding when a child is safe with a
parent can be a nuanced, difficult question. The circumstances of
each family are different, as are the highly subjective approaches
of judges.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, the pilot project placing all such cases under one
judge was driven by the theory that doing so would bring a greater
uniformity to how those decisions are made.
</P>
<P>
   In the vast majority of the 35 to 40 cases that Richardson has
handled in the last six months, the city had removed the children.
And, in the vast majority of cases, he reversed the city's decision
and sent the children back home. When a parent has agreed to take
all the prescribed precautions, he said, it is unnecessarily harsh
to keep their children in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the worst thing to do at that point is to remove their
children,'' he said. ``Then that person has absolutely nothing,
nothing to hope for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
