<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-NHIS-TRACK-BOS &LR;      07-07 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHIS-TRACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHIS'S TURN 3: MORE BANKING NEEDED? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ From inside the Hills Brothers Coffee hauler,
neither the sound of screeching brakes nor the crash of metal
hitting concrete was heard Friday. Mechanic Mike Shiflett did not
know why he turned his head just in time to witness the crash that
killed 30-year-old driver Kenny Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Through the sliding glass doors at the back of the hauler,
Shiflett watched as Irwin skidded across Turn 3 at the New
Hampshire International Speedway. The tires of Irwin's No. 42
BellSouth car locked in place and left a trail of smoke leading up
to the initial impact. The right-front section struck the wall
first, while the rear end shot into the air. Then, the car flipped
onto the driver's side and scraped along the banking. At the start
of Turn 4, the vehicle flipped onto its roof and stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Once emergency crews rushed to the scene, crew members and
drivers began to piece together what happened and speculate about
what caused the crash. Many recalled a similar incident eight weeks
ago that claimed the life of 19-year-old Adam Petty. Friday's fatal
accident took place just yards from where Petty died. Concerns
about Turn 3, track safety, and hung throttles were raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw that, when a car hits like that and it goes up and
it disappears, that's big,'' said Shiflett. ``I thought it was
going to be on the other side of the wall. I thought it was going
to be hung up in the fence. But when I got to the back of the
truck, I saw it was on its roof. Most of the times you see these
cars crash and the guys get up and walk out of them. It kind of
gave me the willies because I heard it's the same place Adam hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Added America Online crew member Vance ``Weasel'' Howell, ``It's
sort of odd to have two people die on the same turn, but then again
this is racing. You get in a racecar and that's the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But many in the racing community were less resigned to fate and
more interested in finding fault with either the track or car. Some
drivers and crew members criticized the design of Turn 3, echoing
the sentiments of Ward Burton who said, ``Two means it's a problem.
I think it needs to be addressed.'' Burton suggested that the 12
degrees of banking be increased and others agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just on the very edge and this track is so flat,'' said
Mike Butcher, a crew member for the Petty Enterprises Hot Wheels
car. ``There's not a lot of banking to it so there's very, very
little room for error. Without a lot of banking in the turns, it
doesn't give anything for the car to lean on, You're more or less
on the verge of spinning out when you are in the turns.''
</P>
<P>
   Driver Rusty Wallace, who earned the pole position for Sunday's
New England 300, suggested the structure of the track might be
problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got long straightaways an tight corners and you've gotta
understand what you're getting into when you go there,'' said
Wallace. ``There's a big bump going into Turn 3 and you're flying.
Just about the time you're getting off the brake you go flying off
this bump down there and you know it's there. You've gotta
negotiate it, you've gotta shock for it, you've gotta spring for it
. . . All these racetracks have different personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   The most popular car-related theories involved a stuck throttle,
the same suspicion many drivers and crew members had following the
Petty crash. Coming down a straightaway, drivers are at full
throttle. When they come into a turn, drivers must get off the gas.
If the throttle does not come back, the driver cannot turn and
usually find themselves heading straight for a wall.
</P>
<P>
   During the morning qualifying session, several drivers guarded
against stuck throttles by placing a piece of metal over their
shoes, allowing them to pull the throttle up if it jammed. After
the Irwin crash, Wallace vowed to make the metal throttle release
mandatory in all his cars.
</P>
<P>
   Other rumors circulating after the crash involved brake failure
or a blown tire. But skid marks visible 100 yards before the
initial point of impact dispelled the notion of brake failure. A
flat tire was also considered a possible, but unlikely cause.
</P>
<P>
   Said Danny Shull, a crew member for the No. 32 Tide car,
``There's only one person who knows what happened and he's dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
