<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6192 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-SHOP-NATASHA-LYONNE-$     07-07 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOP-NATASHA-LYONNE-$ADV09-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUGH, TOUGH, BUT ON A ROAD TO LADYLIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By NANCY HASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Natasha Lyonne sat on a bench outside a coffee bar
near her Gramercy Park studio apartment last Tuesday, shuddering
slightly even in the 90-degree heat. She was detoxing from
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to breakfast,'' said the 21-year-old actress whose
quirky performances in ``Slums of Beverly Hills,'' ``American Pie''
and ``But I'm a Cheerleader,'' which opened this weekend, have
marked her as the New York doppelganger of such plump-lipped
ingenues as Neve Campbell and Jennifer Love Hewitt, a sort of
antistarlet. She lifted a large iced coffee to go and took a deep
drag of a Marlboro. Her voice was throaty, her tone ironic: ``Real
movie star stuff here, real glamour.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most people in her profession Lyonne spends much of her
time working in Los Angeles, but it takes a lot of imagination to
picture her tooling down Rodeo Drive in a BMW convertible or
lolling in the Hollywood Hills. Although she is only
5-foot-3-inches and waifish (the huge breasts she sported as the
focus of the comedy in ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' were
prosthetics), she walks like a truck driver. And swears like one,
too. Between drags of her cigarette (she carries both Marlboros and
Camel Lights because she ``likes to switch off''), her monologues
tumble out in a side-of-the-mouth stream of consciousness. Her
references careen from Ionesco to patent leather G-strings.
``Sometimes the things that come out of my mouth are mortifying,''
she conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her cultivated toughness, Lyonne's latest obsession is
``being a lady.'' She is tired of her old punk wardrobe of black
fishnets and leather. To prove it, she was wearing a Jill Stuart
halter dress in demure shades of brown. Stuart gave her the dress
to wear to a star-studded AIDS benefit in Manhattan the night
before. It set off Lyonne's eyes, which are huge beneath soft
spidery lashes. To complete the genteel image, she was now carrying
a big off-white fake alligator purse that she picked up for $2 at
the 26th Street flea market. ``I used to go to the airport in
fishnets and combat boots, and kids would call me Herman Munster,''
she recalled. ``That wasn't so great.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lyonne hasn't traded in her Doc Martens for the haute
vintage look now popular with many young women in the East Village.
``I'm so over polyester,'' she said. Nor does she cotton to the
``floraly'' sundresses that seem to be the uniform for her actress
peers in Hollywood. ``I prefer to look like that but gone a little
wrong. I'd rather confuse people.'' (In keeping with the spirit of
confusion, she has paired Stuart's dress with gold lame platform
sandals from Frederick's of Hollywood.) Lyonne insisted she was
sincere about giving herself a full-fledged fashion makeover. In
fact, she wanted to start that very minute. After a final
cigarette, she clumped off to Ferragamo, where she had read in the
paper there was a sale. ``Now that is a ladylike place, I'll bet,''
she said, hailing a cab.
</P>
<P>
   Once uptown, her expression grew a bit worried. Standing outside
the massive glass doors of the venerable shoe store, she looked
like a lost child. ``OK, men, I'm going in,'' she deadpanned to an
invisible Army brigade. The first thing that caught her eye was a
piece of luggage. She turned pale when the saleswoman told her it
cost $1,000. ``See, it rolls,'' the woman added, cheerily. ``Oh,
that makes all the difference,'' Lyonne said, moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Lyonne wandered over to survey the spectator pumps, considering
for a moment whether the matronly two-toned shoe might have camp
potential, but the impulse lasted only a moment. ``Even I am not
this crazy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After perusing a pair of $1,250 alligator stilettos, she asked
for a lady's room. A reproving salesman told her that the store's
restrooms were out of order. He suggested she go down the street to
Burger Heaven. ``OK,'' she said under her breath with a theatrical
scowl. ``So why don't you just say, like: `Get out of here, you
can't afford these things. Go back downtown, you loser.'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her grumbling during the trek to Burger Heaven, Lyonne
actually seemed perfectly happy playing the outsider. In two recent
roles, ``But I'm a Cheerleader'' and HBO's ``If These Walls Could
Talk 2'' she has played a lesbian, a stretch she shrugs off. ``It's
no big deal,'' said Lyonne, who like many of her Hollywood peers
thinks such concerns are dated. ``To me it's about as controversial
as the interracial stuff in `Guess Who's Coming to Dinner.'''
</P>
<P>
   She comes by such off-hand bohemianism honestly. Her mother was
the European-educated daughter of Holocaust survivors. She
describes her father as a bit of a shady character from Brooklyn.
``It was unclear what my parents did for a living,'' she said.
``They were the black sheeps of Auschwitz and Flatbush.''
</P>
<P>
   She spent the first eight years of her life in Great Neck, where
she and her family lived in Herman Melville's old house. They kept
a sheep on the rambling property, until one day it ``just
exploded.'' ``I had a rabbit that exploded, too,'' she added.
``Things like that happened to us. We were very weird.''
</P>
<P>
   The family moved to Israel, where Natasha's father became a
boxing promoter. Her parents' marriage broke up soon after, and her
mother brought her and her older brother to Manhattan. She has not
heard from her father since. Her grandmother offered to pick up the
cost of private school, but only if Natasha went to a yeshiva.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't fit in and ``got kicked out pretty easily,'' she
said, adding that she also got kicked out of army summer camp in
Israel when she was 15. ``I was wild. I broke a whole bunch of kids
out of the barracks in a covert nighttime maneuver. I was like
Bette Davis on crank.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lyonne got cast by Woody Allen in ``Everyone Says I Love You,''
when she was 16, a fact she recalled wistfully as she passed the
fortress-like Fifth Avenue headquarters of Harry Winston where one
of the film's musical numbers was shot. ``We could go in and just
say hi,'' she said brightly, as she glanced at the ornate gates and
improvised a little Fred Astaire glide. Then she got a bit
embarrassed over her own enthusiasm. ``Or maybe not.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the paycheck from ``Everyone'' that enabled her to buy
the small apartment near Gramercy Park when she was 18. She has
been financially independent ever since. For the last year, she has
been dating Edward Furlong, another young actor, who works mostly
in independent films. (After shopping, she planned to go to the
airport _ no ticket yet _ and hop a plane for Rome, where Furlong
is working.)
</P>
<P>
   Because her talents have been so much in demand lately, Lyonne
has put off going to college, though she was accepted at her first
choice, New York University. (In her entrance essay she compared
working with Allen to T.S. Eliot's ``Wasteland''). But part of her
longs to join the brainy set of young actors that includes the Yale
student Clare Danes and Natalie Portman, who is at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty good with ideas,'' she said, ``and that life really
appeals to me.'' Unlike those actors, she has not made enough money
to retire on. For her, $30,000 a year tuition would be a wipeout.
``I could ask my grandmother for the money, but I really have this
thing about being independent.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2 p.m., Lyonne had become disillusioned with the relentless
ladylikeness of Fifth Avenue. ``Let's go somewhere less phony,''
she said, after a browse through Fendi, where she just shook her
head at the price of the elaborately beaded accessories.
</P>
<P>
   She opted for a cab ride back downtown, to Ina, the designer
resale shop in NoLIta. ``This is more my speed,'' she said, trying
on a $100 pair of pink Prada hot pants. ``Though even these are
still overpriced, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she wound up with a straw fedora _ no fancy label.
``In my line of work you need something to keep the sun out of your
eyes,'' she said, sounding as though she worked construction
instead of movies. She glanced at herself in the store window.
``It's a look. It's not Ferragamo, but it's a look.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
