<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) SUGAR
BACKERS STICK WITH THE PROGRAM  
 By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WASHINGTON _ While opponents of
federal sugar subsidies raise Cain about the cost to taxpayers and
consumers, supporters of the controversial program have managed yet
again to keep the price supports intact.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before leaving for the Fourth of July recess, House backers of
the sugar program defeated the latest assault by sugar foes who
wanted to prevent the government from buying any surplus sugar
beyond the $54 million worth already acquired by the Agriculture
Department this year.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a new report that showed artificially high prices for
sugar costs users about $2 billion annually, hostile lawmakers said
it was time to turn off the federal spigot for sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us stop wasting taxpayers' dollars on the sugar program,''
said Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., who has tried unsuccessfully for
years to kill the aid.
</P>
<P>
   Farm industry allies argued it was unfair to try to rewrite the
sugar program in a spending bill. They said the proper time for any
revisions would be when Congress undertakes a sweeping review of
farm programs. A vote on Miller's amendment was blocked on
procedural grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Ewing, R-Ill., questioned the findings of the study by
the General Accounting Office and said candy manufacturers and
other large sugar consumers couldn't be counted on to pass on any
savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sugar prices are low and I have not ... seen any reduction in
candy bars or soda pop,'' observed Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Other defenders of the sugar program said critics are picking on
a plan that aids small farmers and puts food on American tables.
``If we complain about farmers, do not do so with our mouths
full,'' said Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., who represents the stage's
sugar-growing region.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent sugar victory, the fight will persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the height of absurdity,'' said Rep. Joe Hoeffel,
R-Pa. ``We encourage overproduction of sugar through subsidies and
trade restrictions and then when sugar is overproduced we buy it
and give it away to a third country for free.''
</P>
<P>
   RIVER PROGRAM ROLLING
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of a Clinton administration effort to revitalize U.S.
riverfronts won an easy congressional victory over conservatives
seeking to cut off funding for the American Heritage Rivers
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers representing districts that contain some of the 14
rivers given the special designation successfully struck language
from the agriculture appropriations bill that would have prohibited
any spending on the effort. Authors of the restriction did not even
bother to put up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said the program, seen by critics as a way to impose
more federal controls on private property, is misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decade from now, indeed 100 years from now, people will
recognize the American Heritage Rivers initiative coming from the
Clinton administration was one of the important environmental
initiatives,'' said Rep. Maurice Hinchey, D-N.Y. Rivers in Florida,
North Carolina and Louisiana are among those in the program.
</P>
<P>
   EMERGENCY AID
</P>
<P>
   With the budget surplus growing dramatically in recent
estimates, some lawmakers want to return the money to health care
facilities that continue to struggle with past spending reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Spencer Bachus, R-Ala., is calling for dollars to be
diverted to hospitals reeling from 1997 cuts made in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hospitals in Alabama are hurting,'' he said. ``Seventy
percent are operating in the red and 14 are predicted to run out of
money this year and could close. Improving the financial health of
our hospitals is crucial to maintaining the quality of health care
we've all come to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   His proposal drew widespread support in the House.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DOES GORE/GRAHAM SOUND?
</P>
<P>
   Was it an audition for a potential starring role in the fall?
</P>
<P>
   It cannot be mere coincidence that Vice President Al Gore
recruited Democratic Sen. Bob Graham of Florida to chat with
campaign reporters a few days ago about Medicare drug coverage and
the virtues of Gore's emerging plan.
</P>
<P>
   Readers of vice presidential smoke signals immediately seized on
the Gore invitation as evidence that Graham was being given an
opportunity to prove himself as a potential running mate. Graham
aides said he was sought out as a recognized Senate expert on the
potent campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Graham's name remains alive in the Democratic
veepstakes as does that of another Southerner, Gov. Jim Hunt of
North Carolina. Both could add competitive spice in states that
lean Republican in presidential contests.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0370 </DOCNO>
