<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6199 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-NHIS-FATAL-BOS &LR;      07-07 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHIS-FATAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH CLAIMS KENNY IRWIN, 30, AT NASCAR PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ For the second time in eight weeks, a pall was
cast over New Hampshire International Speedway after NASCAR Winston
Cup driver Kenny Irwin, 30, of Indianapolis, was killed Friday
morning during practice at the 1.058-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin's heavy wall impact occurred in almost the same spot where
19-year-old Adam Petty was killed May 12 during a morning practice
for a Busch Series race.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement released by Conord Hospital officials,
Irwin died from multiple injuries. Irwin, a third-year veteran of
the NASCAR Winston Cup Series, was in his first year as driver of
the No. 42 BellSouth Chevrolet Monte Carlo owned by car owner Felix
Sabates.
</P>
<P>
   After he spent his first two years with Robert Yates Racing as
driver of the No. 28 Texaco Havoline Ford Taurus, Irwin was hired
by Sabates to replace Joe Nemechek, whose only victory with Team
SABCO came last September at NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   At Sabates's request, Irwin's team withdrew from competition in
Sunday's thatlook.com 300 at NHIS and returned to its home base in
Charlotte, N.C. Team SABCO's other entry, the No. 40 Coors Light
Chevy driven by Sterling Marlin, was withdrawn from Friday's pole
qualifications but is expected to qualify Saturday and participate
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are deeply saddened at today's passing of Kenny Irwin,''
NASCAR president Bill France said in a statement. ``On behalf of
all of us at NASCAR and the entire NASCAR community, our deepest
sympathies, all our thoughts and prayers are with Kenny's family,
friends, and everyone at Team SABCO. Kenny was a fine competitor
and will be missed very much by the entire NASCAR community.''
</P>
<P>
   Although NASCAR officials declined to elaborate on what caused
the accident, many in the garage area speculated it was the result
of a stuck throttle, which was initially thought to have been the
problem in Petty's crash. NASCAR officials, however, ruled out any
mechanical problems in that crash.
</P>
<P>
   Track rescue workers had no sooner arrived on the scene to
extricate Irwin from his upended car when crew chiefs radioed their
teams to have their throttle rods and linkage inspected and
reinspected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very concerned, but without some answers it's pretty
hard to understand what happened,'' said NASCAR Winston Cup
director Gary Nelson, who indicated Irwin's car had been impounded
and taken to an off-site facility for further inspection. ``The car
is bent and twisted so much it's hard to figure out, as we're
looking at it, what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was on his first practice lap in a new car when the
accident occurred at 11:23 a.m. Traveling at approximately 150
miles per hour, the car hit the wall entering Turn 3, rolled over
onto the driver's side and skidded along the banking before landing
on its roof in Turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report from one driver, Scott Pruett, who
witnessed the accident from the observation perch of his team's
transporter, Irwin entered the corner at a high rate of speed
before hitting the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he went to turn in and all of a sudden he went
straight,'' Pruett said. ``He didn't lift and he went straight into
the wall. It looked like as he started to turn, he had the whole
thing locked up. He hit the wall pretty hard _ not at a straight 90
(degree angle), but almost a 45. He took a pretty good shot,
climbed the wall, and came down on (the driver's) side and just
slid all the way around on his side. Once he came to stop, he came
back down on his roof.''
</P>
<P>
   The fatality was another jarring blow to the NASCAR community,
which arrived here mindful of the circumstances surrounding the
loss of Petty Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrific,'' Pruett said. ``It's devastating for the sport
and the families. Whenever somebody gets hurt in this sport, it's
horrific. When it happens at the same track and the same place, we
need to take a closer look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Andrews, crew chief of the No. 1 Pennzoil Chevrolet driven
by Steve Park, said a stuck throttle could have resulted from any
number of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be something on the floorboard, it could be from a
malfunction on the carburetor, it could be something in the air
cleaner; several things could make a throttle stick, it doesn't
matter where you are,'' Andrews said. ``It's just mind-boggling
that it would happen here in two races, at two NASCAR events in a
row.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Park, ``New Hampshire had an impeccable record in previous
years, but what many people don't realize is that we go in excess
of 150 (miles per hour) here and anything can happen. We all know
the inherent risks of our job, but as I mentioned, you just don't
think New Hampshire would be a life-taking track.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if teams had cause for concern, Andrews said, ``I think
that's a concern throughout the sport anytime that happens. Even if
you're lucky enough to get off the throttle and get the motor shut
down before you hit anything, you're still going to do some damage.
That obviously didn't happen with Kenny. He didn't have a chance to
shut anything off.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd, driver of the No. 28 Texaco car, had experienced a
similar problem _ but not at NHIS. Still, he said the configuration
of the Loudon track, with its long straightaways and tight corners,
left little room to react to a stuck throttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had 'em stick before and it's not like there's a whole
lot a driver can do about it,'' Rudd said. ``If you get off the
gas, you might the car settled, but it's still going wide open.
You've got to get your foot on the brake, and that's about all you
can do. But when the motor is wide open and you get on the brakes,
though, it doesn't slow you down a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Track officials did not officially release word of Irwin's death
until 2:30 p.m., when Winston Cup qualifying was scheduled to
begin. Afterward, it overshadowed the effort of Rusty Wallace, who
won the pole position in record fashion with a lap of 132.089 miles
per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he managed to get through the remainder of the day,
Wallace said, ``I don't even know how to say that except that these
are days that make you really sit back and look at yourself in the
mirror and go, `Why do I do this?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
