<HEADLINE>
NADER'S IMPACT  
 PRECONVENTION DISPUTE IN PHILADELPHIA  
 CALIFORNIA BILL WOULD LIMIT CONTRIBUTIONS  
 GORE'S TENANTS LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Michigan voters consider a three-way presidential race
among George W. Bush, Al Gore and Pat Buchanan, the expected Reform
Party nominee, Bush and Gore are statistically tied, with Buchanan
coming in a very distant third, a new poll indicates. But when the
name of Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate, is added, Gore
slips well behind Bush, trailed by Nader and then Buchanan. Nader
appears to draw some labor support at Gore's expense because of
differences over trade issues. In a statewide telephone poll
conducted for The Detroit Free Press by the research group
EPIC/MRA, a research group based in Lansing, Bush drew the support
of 45 percent of likely voters, Gore 40 percent and Buchanan 4
percent. When Nader was added, Bush was the choice of 46 percent of
the voters, Gore 34 percent, Nader 8 percent and Buchanan 3
percent. The poll has a margin of sampling error of plus or minus 4
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CONVENTIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WORK DISPUTE IN PHILADELPHIA
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Philadelphia has agreed to try to resolve an
intensifying dispute between local unions and the network news
divisions that is threatening to disrupt preparations for the
Republican National Convention, according to several people with
knowledge of the negotiations. The fight, they said, has to do with
whether the locals have jurisdiction in network work spaces at the
First Union Center, where the convention will be held. Network
officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they had their
own employees to do wiring and installation and thus had no need
for local workers. Barbara Grant, a spokeswoman for Mayor John F.
Street, said, ``The mayor was approached to try to step in and sort
things out.'' Tim Fitzpatrick, a convention spokesman, said work
had not been delayed so far.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE STATES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A CAMPAIGN SPENDING LIMIT
</P>
<P>
   The California Legislature, worried that special-interest
contributions to campaigns for state offices have gotten out of
hand, has passed a bill aimed at limiting them. Should Gov. Gray
Davis sign the bill, as he has indicated he probably will, the
proposal will be put before California voters in November. Under
the measure, individuals could give no more than $20,000 to a
candidate for governor, though political parties could still
contribute unlimited amounts. Other statewide candidates could get
up to $5,000 per election from most sources, including individuals
and businesses, and $10,000 from ``small-contributor committees'' _
groups of at least 100 people who each chip in no more than $200 a
year and donate to at least five candidates. For legislative
candidates, the limits would be $3,000 from most sources and $6,000
from small-contributor committees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DEMOCRATS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE'S TENANTS MOVING ON
</P>
<P>
   The family renting a Tennessee home from Vice President Al Gore
is moving to Ohio _ with the help of seven volunteer movers and
officials from the Tennessee Republican Party. The moving team
arrived Friday at the home in Carthage to load two trucks with the
household goods of Charles and Tracy Mayberry and their four
children. Mayberry called Gore a ``slumlord'' last month, saying
she wanted to get his attention so that much-needed repairs would
be made. Gore promised to get the repairs done, but Mayberry
contends that nothing has happened. A Gore spokesman, Douglas
Hattaway, said all the repairs requested had in fact been made.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: No public events
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: No public events
</P>
</TEXT>
