<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EXCERPTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCERPTS FROM INTERVIEW WITH FORMER PRESIDENT AND MRS. BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (with BUSH-PARENTS)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine _ Following are excerpts from an interview
Friday with former President George Bush and his wife, Barbara,
about the presidential campaign of their son Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas:
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you confident your son will win?
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE BUSH. I think he'll win. Again, it's mind-boggling for
me, a former president, to think our son will be president. I think
a lot of it is that after this primary, where he took such a huge
pounding, the press had a massive love affair with John McCain _
nobody can question that, that's just objective, even from a
nonobjective guy _ but after that, there was a distorted view of
George, I think, and now . . . people are beginning to see what his
heartbeat is, what he's really like, that he's a decent person,
that he likes people, has done a good job in his state. I don't
think in the fall that the press is going to have the same love
affair with Gore that they had with John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why?
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE BUSH. Well, I think they don't like him so much.
</P>
<P>
   Q. For a good reason?
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE BUSH. Oh, I don't know about that. I'm going to leave it
to George's campaign to define Al Gore. He can identify with
people, and I think that's coming through. And also, they're going
to want change. And I believe there is a Clinton fatigue. And all
of these things will inure to George's benefit just as Gore will be
trying to have this good economy inure to his . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do you think there's Clinton fatigue?
</P>
<P>
   BARBARA BUSH. We took a vow. Can't break it. Never to speak
badly about your, your __
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE BUSH. We don't get into that because he beat me and then
it looks like a poor sport, but I did speak out once in the depths
of the Monica Lewinsky thing and said this is disgraceful. But I
think it's more than that very unhappy time period of impeachment.
I think it's change. I think I was the victim of people wanting
change: ``Eight years of Reagan, four years of Bush, we want a
change.'' And all the things that I felt strongly about never
materialized as issues. And I think the same thing is true now. I
think people kind of like change, like the idea of change from time
to time. I think that works for George's benefit. I don't think
Gore can present himself as a candidate of change. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q. That honor and integrity have been lost?
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE BUSH. There's been a diminution of respect for the office
of the presidency, and it's not just here, it's abroad. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does your son know as much about foreign affairs as you did
when you were elected?
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE BUSH. No. But he knows every bit as much about it as Bill
Clinton did.
</P>
<P>
   Q. As much as Gore?
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE BUSH. Gore's had eight years of experience there. But the
way I should be judged is . . . by the kind of people I had around
me. Because I didn't know all this stuff. You know, how much
reduction you can do on atomic weapons. But Brent Snowcroft did. I
didn't know how Gorbachev was going to react when the Iraqis
invaded Kuwait, but Jimmy Baker was over there the next day. . . .
You get good people. George knows enough to do that and enough
about the world to have good judgment on his own at this point. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   Q. If you were campaigning against your son, wouldn't you be
calling his tax cut too large?
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE BUSH. You won't believe this. I literally don't go into
the analysis of these issues. If you asked me, life or death,
you've got to tell me how big the tax cut is that George is
proposing, I couldn't tell you. I don't give a damn. Because I'm
out of it. I'm out of it. And I don't do television and I don't do
interviews because the minute I said I would differ with Jeb or
with George, you would have an obligation to rush down there and
say, ``Your nutty father doesn't agree with you, what do you
think?''
</P>
</TEXT>
