u f BC-NC-PAPER-SUIT-NYT &LR;      07-07 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-PAPER-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT OVERTURNS CONTEMPT CITATIONS AGAINST WILMINGTON,
N.C., REPORTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal appeals court in Richmond, Va., has overturned a
criminal contempt citation against a reporter who disclosed details
of a sealed legal settlement that were inadvertently handed over by
a court clerk.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter, Kirsten B. Mitchell, was following a lawsuit
brought by residents of a trailer park in Wilmington, N.C., against
Conoco Inc., a company whose operations, they contended, were
contaminating their water supply. When, in October 1997, a court
clerk gave the reporter a group of documents, one of which was the
$36 million settlement agreement, Mitchell used the material in an
article published the next day in her newspaper, The Morning Star.
</P>
<P>
   Conoco's lawyers requested that the federal judge who originally
sealed the document, W. Earl Britt, hold Mitchell and her
colleague, Cory Reiss, who was also writing about the case and
obtained information about the settlement from other sources, in
contempt. The judge found Mitchell guilty of criminal contempt and
also found her and the paper liable for civil contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Britt also upheld a demand from Conoco that Reiss should reveal
his sources. When Reiss refused, Britt held him in contempt and
ordered him jailed _ an order stayed by the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Thursday
overturned the conviction of Mitchell for criminal contempt of
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is simply no evidence whatsoever'' that would allow the
court ``to infer an intent to violate a court order or
confidentiality,'' the judges wrote. The ruling added that the
evidence ``all but confirms that Mitchell acted wholly innocently,
and certainly innocently insofar as the law is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court also reversed the contempt finding against
Reiss. When Britt originally sealed the settlement document, the
appeals court held, he failed to follow required procedural steps
and give interested parties, like newspapers, a chance to object.
</P>
<P>
   A third contempt citation against Mitchell and The Morning Star
was voided under the same reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Sasser, the lawyer for Conoco, said Friday that the
appeals ruling ``will make litigation more cumbersome and
expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time a party to a lawsuit wants to provide the court with
a document that it considers confidential, whether it's a chemical
formula that's a trade secret or the name of a child in a sexual
assault case, the party must engage in a minitrial with the
media,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I do think this additional layer of litigation will
add to the delays inherent in court proceedings'' and increase
public disrespect for the courts.
</P>
<P>
   George Freeman, an assistant general counsel for the New York
Times Co., which owns the Wilmington newspaper, said Friday that
the decision ``confirms the long-held principle that the media
cannot be punished for publishing truthful, newsworthy information
which it legally obtains.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the ruling ``emphasizes that judges can't
willy-nilly seal court documents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GUERNICA-DOCUMENTARY-     07-07 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUERNICA-DOCUMENTARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM COMMEMORATES LUFTWAFFE'S DEVASTATION OF BASQUE TOWN IN 1937 
</HEADLINE>
   By HERBERT MITGANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUERNICA, Spain _ Strolling around the serene square of this
Basque town not far north of Bilbao, it is hard to imagine the
scene as it was 63 years ago, when an indelible atrocity occurred
on the eve of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few outward marks of physical devastation are still
visible, but the human damage remains embedded in people's minds.
</P>
<P>
   If you tap the memories of the survivors of the German bombing
during the Spanish Civil War, and listen to local officials and
historians who are trying to turn one of the symbols of fascist
militarism into a place of peace and reconciliation, the time is
always April 26, l937. That Monday _ a crowded market day when
farmers from nearby villages came to Guernica to sell and exchange
livestock and produce _ was deliberately chosen by the Luftwaffe to
inflict the greatest number of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Now a new documentary film titled ``The Bombing of Guernica: The
Mark of Men'' has been produced by a peace research center here and
is being offered to public and commercial broadcasting stations all
over the world. It includes the voices of the people who survived
the attack. (The Basques call their most sacred town Gernika;
elsewhere, it's known by its Spanish name.)
</P>
<P>
   Before the civil war, Spain's Republican government commissioned
Picasso to create a painting for its pavilion at the Paris World's
Fair. After learning of the bombing, Picasso said, ``The painting
which I am presently working on will be called `Guernica.' Through
it, I express my abhorrence of the race that has sunk Spain in an
ocean of pain and death.''
</P>
<P>
   Working steadily in 1937, Picasso laid out ``Guernica'' in a
matter of weeks, creating an apocalyptic scene of grotesque and
mutilated human and animal figures depicted in tones of black,
white and gray. The painting now hangs behind bulletproof glass in
its permanent home at the Reina Sofia Museum in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   A permanent exhibition at the Guernica Museum in the center of
town documents the bombing with photographs and artifacts,
including bomb fragments bearing German markings. On that fateful
market day, a single fighter from the Luftwaffe's Condor Legion
circled the town, scouting the best target areas. The bells from
Santa Maria Church alerted the townspeople that an air attack might
be coming. A month before, the Condor Legion had bombed the nearby
town of Durango, a center of communications and armaments factories
behind Republican lines. The people of Guernica immediately built
several flimsy wooden shelters, protected by sandbags, around the
town center.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing began at 4:30 p.m. and continued for three hours.
Low-flying Junkers transports being used as bombers appeared over
the horizon, coming in waves, unloading thousand-pound bombs and
thousands of incendiary projectiles. The German squadrons were
protected by Italian fighter planes _ the first coordinated attack
by the forces of Hitler and Mussolini.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Luftwaffe's fighter planes, machine-gunning
anything that moved. Guernica was flattened in a day; hundreds of
people died from the bombs, shrapnel and fires. Nobody knew the
exact number of casualties because the town's population had
swelled on that market day.
</P>
<P>
   On one wall of the Guernica Museum is a framed letter from
former President Roman Herzog of Germany, dated March 27, l997. It
acknowledges that the Condor Legion was responsible for the attack.
``It was an indefensible act of aerial bombardment,'' the letter
says. ``The victims of this terrible atrocity suffered human
anguish. We renounce the bombardment by the German aviators and the
horror it caused. Now we call for reconciliation and peace between
our two peoples.''
</P>
<P>
   Copies of Picasso's working drawings for ``Guernica'' are also
on display in the museum. An accompanying note says that Picasso
produced 25 sketches a month after the news of the bombing reached
Paris. An oil painting, in the spirit of ``Guernica,'' covers an
entire wall of the exhibition. This triptych by Sofia Gandarias, an
artist originally from Guernica, shows the devastation caused by
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks from the Guernica Museum, on the first floor of a
small office building in the town square, is the peace research
center named, in Basque, Gernika Gogoratuz (Guernica Remembered),
where the new documentary was created. ``The horror of that day
marks the survivors forever,'' the film's narration says in part.
``What is more, they were forced to conceal the truth about the
crime committed against them during the four decades that Gen.
Franco's dictatorship held power. Now the survivors don't want the
remembrance of this horror to fall into oblivion.''
</P>
<P>
   A slogan accompanies the film: ``Forgive, but never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Guernica Museum will become the first peace museum in
Spain, thanks to the support of the government,'' said Iratxe
Momoitio Astorkia, the museum's director.
</P>
<P>
   Above the town square is a park dedicated to peace and
reconciliation. It includes a bronze sculpture by Henry Moore
called ``Great Figure in a Shelter.'' The sculpture, installed in
1990, was commissioned by the Basque regional government and paid
for by the Madrid government. The sculpture recalls the helmet
figures that Moore, a Loyalist sympathizer, executed during the
Spanish Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is a peace monument called ``Our Father's House,'' by
Eduardo Chillida. A tall, semi-abstract structure sheathed in
concrete, it was installed in 1988 to commemorate the 50th
anniversary of a historic moment that the people of Guernica hope
will continue to inspire those who seek to end the slaughter of
innocents everywhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
