u s BC-TEN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     07-07 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SAMPRAS NOW PLAYING FOR A LEGACY
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Vladimir Voltchkov was hanging in early
against Pete Sampras on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This was a semifinal matchup and the underdog from Brooklyn by
way of Minsk, Belarus, was one of the tournament's compelling
stories: no endorsements, and forced to borrow shorts and shoes for
his extended stay at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   On a gray day, a hopeful Wimbledon crowd pulled for a mammoth
upset by Voltchkov. He gave them hope by narrowly losing the first
set in a tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   But around the third game of the second set, Voltchkov realized
that Sampras, even with a leg injury, had become a freight train
and that he, Vladimir, was standing in its way. The defending
Wimbledon champion prevailed, 7-6 (4), 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he'll grow from this experience,'' Sampras said.
``His ranking will go up. He can probably get a contract now for
some clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, John McEnroe had spoken about how unlikely it was
Sampras would play for the U.S. Davis Cup team against Spain in a
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Since being named Davis Cup captain last year, McEnroe has
pressed Sampras to play in the century-old team competition.Sampras
skipped the first round because of a different injury but did help
the Americans beat the Czechs in April.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, who has become increasingly public in his efforts to
get Sampras on the team, thinks the Californian will use his injury
as an excuse to skip the latest round.
</P>
<P>
   ``When players go out there and see Pete Sampras totally
dominate, it's aggravating to have him say he's not feeling right,
McEnroe said Thursday. ``Pete talks about it, and it's like he's
saying: `If I lose, its because of the injury. And by the way, I'm
about to be in the finals again.'''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe may not fully understand Sampras, a champion who, in
many ways, is like Tiger Woods. The worlds they choose to in live
may only be an inch wide but may run miles deep. Woods focuses only
on golf and winning; all that matters to Sampras is tennis, winning
titles and being No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   It's not even about prosperity. Sampras will go for a record
13th men's Grand Slam singles title. He wants to win it here at
Wimbledon; if not, then at the U.S. Open. If Davis Cup becomes an
obstacle, he will remove it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for Sampras, the individual parts _ winning here Sunday or
at Flushing Meadows in September _ are more important than his body
of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, when you're going through the battle, you can't
think of your place in history or your legacy,'' Sampras said
Friday. ``It is the match at hand. That's the attitude you have to
have. You can't put that much pressure on yourself, looking at
breaking records. You wake up Sunday morning prepare for your
final. You know, when you're competing, you're in kind of your own
little world. You're not thinking about history
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, McEnroe explained why he was so passionate
about Davis Cup; how from the time he was a kid growing up in
Queens, Davis Cup tennis symbolized a love of game and country. How
can anyone not be serious about Davis Cup?
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, who last won Wimbledon in 1984, is 41, Sampras will
turn 29 in August. They are champions of different generations.
What they have in common is tennis _ and an exceptionally good life
gained through tennis. Presumably each wants to give back to the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Is playing Davis Cup somehow tied into giving back to the game?
``I don't know,'' McEnroe answered. ``That's a good question: I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Until he comes up with an answer, Davis Cup will remain for most
Americans little more than a curious artifact in search of a rhyme
or reason. Sampras has been in Davis Cup before _ giving his all,
playing hurt, winning the trophy _ only to feel like the soldier
who comes home from war and nobody cares.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe's challenge is to convert the passion and fire he has
for the event into a broader vision that accommodates interests _
as diverse as the game of tennis is rapidly becoming. Diverse as
29-year-old Pete Sampras to 19-year-old Venus Williams to
22-year-old Vladimir Voltchkov.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have to talk with young players the way Arthur Ashe, as
Davis Cup captain, talked to a young McEnroe _ about conduct and
civility.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe can't understand how players don't feel passionate about
Davis Cup; Arthur, refined and dignified, couldn't understand why
McEnroe behaved as he did.
</P>
<P>
   Right now Sampras doesn't get the Davis Cup. He gets Wimbledon.
He gets the U.S. Open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
