<SLUG> BC-GLF-WESTERN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENNINGER HAS NO MERCY FOR A VULNERABLE COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEMONT, Ill. _ With the course there for the taking, Brian
Henninger took full advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Both Henninger and Stephen Ames tied the course record Friday at
Cog Hill Golf and Country Club, shooting nine-under-par 63's that
continued a two-day birdie barrage at the Western Open.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, this is one of the more challenging stops on the PGA
Tour, but with lower rough and soft greens this year, players are
salivating as they reach the first tee.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Nick Price shot 63 to take the first-round lead.
Friday, it was Henninger's turn. He shot 33 on the front nine and
followed it with an eye-opening 30 that propelled him to the top of
the leader board. Meanwhile, Ames also shot his 63 in the morning,
moving him into second place, and setting up an interesting
weekend, with Tiger Woods lurking six strokes off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming for his third career tour victory, Henninger was at
11-under par at 133 over all, a stroke ahead of Franklin Langham
and two strokes ahead of five players who were tied at nine-under
par _ Ames, Price, Fred Couples, Stuart Appleby and Steve Flesch.
Woods was in the mix at five-under par after shooting a 69 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a challenge for Henninger, a 37-year-old tour
veteran, to hold off proven winners like Couples, Price, Woods and
Appleby. But Henninger is not seeking to end a long drought. He won
last year's Southern Farm Bureau Classic.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that the weekend would be a test, he also
said he was looking forward to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I continue to hit it good, I'm going to have a great
tournament,'' said Henninger, who is 121st on this year's money
list. ``It's tough, because you've got some world-class players up
there _ Nick, Tiger, Fred. Everybody has the talent to win out
here, but it's usually somebody that has experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself a world-class golfer, but they're the elite.
But this feels good. This feels great. I've been out here long
enough. I know I can play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   After making four birdies and a bogey on the front nine,
Henninger found a zone on the back with consecutive birdies on Nos.
11, 12 and 13, followed by an eagle at the par-5, 519-yard 15th.
The eagle was set up by an impressive second shot, a 3-iron from
211 yards that landed 6 feet from the pin. Call that adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can not usually hit a 3-iron that far, but I jacked this one
up big time,'' he said. ``It just exploded off the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Henninger followed that by making a 10-foot birdie putt at No.
16, and he could have set the course record if he had not missed an
8-foot birdie attempt at No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Henninger will start Saturday holding the lead,
while Woods will play catch-up. Friday's round was similar to
Thursday's opening round for Woods. He hit the ball well, but he
missed putts. Few people were counting out the world's No. 1
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm making my normal amount of putts, I'm right there next
to the lead,'' Woods said before heading to the putting green to
practice before dark. ``If I can get a few putts to go down early,
hopefully I can ride the momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Price, who started the day with a three-stroke lead, could
manage only a 72 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The wind was not much of a factor, but Ames teed off in the
morning, when conditions were nearly perfect for scoring. It was a
lot different than the conditions Ames faced early in his career,
when he played on the European Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play in Europe, you're playing adverse weather
conditions,'' said Ames, a 36-year-old native of Trinidad and
Tobago who lives in Canada. ``I think you have to be mentally tough
to play in those kind of conditions, week in and week out. Here,
this is paradise. Every shot I hit today came off the way I picture
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set for a hotly contested weekend on a course
where low scores can be had. Henninger has the lead. To keep it, he
will have to remain aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tour's getting so strong, you have to force yourself to
continue,'' he said. ``You can't slow down out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
