<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHINA BACKS LINUX SYSTEM OVER MICROSOFT'S WINDOWS
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders are concerned that the country is growing overly
dependent on Microsoft's Windows operating system, which controls
computers running everything from banks to President Jiang Zemin's
e-mail box.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chinese government, itself a master at monopoly, is
taking its case against Microsoft not to the courtroom but to the
marketplace, albeit with a bit of administrative fiat. It is
backing the Linux operating system, which was created by a Finnish
university student in 1991 and is distributed free to anyone who
wants it.
</P>
<P>
   FTC SET TO CHALLENGE HEINZ DEAL
</P>
<P>
   H.J. Heinz's proposed $185 million purchase of the closely held
Milnot Holdings, maker of Beech-Nut baby foods, was challenged by
antitrust enforcers who said the transaction would hurt
competition. The Federal Trade Commission voted 3-2 to challenge in
court the combination of Heinz with Beech-Nut, the No. 2 U.S.
baby-food producer. The FTC said the combination would mean that
just two companies, Heinz and Gerber, a unit of Novartis, would
control 98 percent of the U.S. market for prepared baby foods.
Shares of Heinz rose 31.25 cents, to $45.50 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   LESSONS FROM NEVADA FOR CONGRESS
</P>
<P>
   Nevada has adopted a prescription-drug program for the elderly
very similar to one approved last month by the House of
Representatives, but the program is off to a rocky start. Insurance
companies have spurned Nevada's invitation to provide coverage.
Nevada's experience offers ominous lessons for Congress, especially
Republicans, who want to subsidize insurance companies to entice
them into providing drug benefits to elderly and disabled people on
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD BANK REPRESENTATIVE CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank said this week that an eight-month investigation
found no evidence to support accusations that a former Russian
representative at the World Bank passed confidential information to
a Russian commercial bank in 1993. The bank did conclude that the
representative, Leonid Grigoriev, had established a business
relationship with the now defunct Inkombank, and that he received
$13,000 for out-of-pocket expenses from the bank in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   STUDENTS LEARN ART OF NEGOTIATING
</P>
<P>
   A group of some 50 students from two dozen countries
participated in the second Model WTO 2000 _ an idea that the World
Trade Organization hopes to export to universities worldwide. The
students, sequestered in a conference room in the WTO's building
with spectacular views of Lake Geneva, concentrated on long and
tough negotiations on the most sensitive trade issues, oblivious to
the sunny weather outside. The mock negotiators were able to spend
some time with the trade group's director general, Mike Moore, who
told them they were lucky that they did not have to ``go home and
sell'' their trade proposals to their parliaments.
</P>
<P>
   A CONTEMPT RULING IS OVERTURNED
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court in Richmond, Va., has overturned a U.S.
district judge's criminal-contempt citation against a reporter who
printed details of a sealed legal settlement after documents
describing the agreement were inadvertently handed to her by a
court clerk. The judges found that there was no evidence that
Kirsten B. Mitchell, a reporter for The Morning Star in Wilmington,
N.C., intended ``to violate a court order or confidentiality,'' and
that she acted ``wholly innocently.''
</P>
<P>
   EX-GM OFFICIAL TO FIGHT EXTRADITION
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance before a Spanish judge, the former General
Motors executive Jose Ignacio Lopez de Arriortua said he would
fight extradition to the United States. A grand jury in Detroit
indicted Lopez in May on six criminal counts related to accusations
that he stole company secrets from GM when he went to work for a
rival, Volkswagen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
