<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR TOP 3-YEAR-OLDS FACE OFF IN THE DWYER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ It will be one of the smallest fields of the
year, but also one of the most distinguished, and it will take the
stage Sunday at Belmont Park: Four colts will open the second half
of the racing season in the Dwyer, a race that will propel one
along the path toward the 3-year-old championship.
</P>
<P>
   In the 83 years the Dwyer has been run, it has been won by such
stars as Man O'War, Gallant Fox, Native Dancer, Nashua, Damascus,
Behrens and Coronado's Quest. This year's cast is loaded with star
quality.
</P>
<P>
   At the draw for post position Friday, the rail was won by Red
Bullet, winner of the Preakness; the No. 2 slot by Commendable,
winner of the Belmont Stakes; the No. 3 slot by More Than Ready,
fourth in the Kentucky Derby, and the outside gate by Albert the
Great, the swift rookie opening the second half of the season with
the aim of overtaking the veterans of the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've got the best 3-year-old,'' said Joe Orseno, who
trains Red Bullet. ``And he's going to prove it this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Zito, the trainer of Albert the Great, took the second-half
perspective.``People get caught up with horses who win the
classics,'' he said. ``There is still a long way to go and many
races to be run before championships are decided.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dwyer is the first major race of the second half, the
doorway to the Haskell at Monmouth, the Jim Dandy and the Travers
at Saratoga, the Woodward at Belmont and the Breeders' Cup Classic
at Churchill Downs in November. It takes horses a mile and
one-sixteenth for a purse of $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet runs with one distinction that none of the others
hold. In the Preakness, he outran Fusaichi Pegasus, who won the
Kentucky Derby and was presumed to be the star of the year. Red
Bullet has not run since the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent workouts, he has blazed away, speeding four
furlongs in 49 2/5 seconds and five furlongs in 59 2/5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect this race to be as tough as it came up,''
Orseno said. ``But we've had it marked on our schedule for some
time. He's fresh and has grown physically since the Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Orseno concedes that he is worried that a colt as fast as More
Than Ready might get the jump on his horse turning for home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Bullet is at his best when he settles and comes with one
run,'' he said. ``There is a possibility that More Than Ready can
shake loose.''
</P>
<P>
   More Than Ready looked like a speed demon last year when he won
his first four races. But his trainer, Todd Pletcher, decided to
skip the Breeders' Cup Juvenile after the colt lost the Futurity
and the Champagne. His patience was rewarded this year when More
Than Ready won the Hutcheson in a dead heat, ran second in the
Louisiana Derby and the Blue Grass, and ran a good fourth in the
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Commendable, trained by D. Wayne Lukas, ran 17th in the Derby,
skipped the Preakness, but then won the Belmont in a major upset.
He has not raced since, and his handlers are still looking for some
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he deserves some credit for the Belmont win,'' said
Mike Marlow, the assistant to Lukas in New York. ``But the Dwyer is
going to be a new ball game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
