u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT &LR;      07-07 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON URGES TAX CREDITS TO SPUR JOB GROWTH UPSTATE
</HEADLINE>
  By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORNING, N.Y. _ On Friday, Democratic candidate for Senate
Hillary Rodham Clinton proposed tax credits to stimulate job growth
among small businesses in the upstate region.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks came on the second day of a tour celebrating
her first year of campaigning for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech, Clinton called for a tax credit of up to $3,000 per
employee for small businesses that set up operations in communities
losing population _ like many of the towns she is visiting on this
campaign swing.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks to about 300 people, as well as at an earlier
appearance in nearby Elmira, Clinton highlighted economic issues in
a region that has been considered a Republican stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called for more federal funds to develop and
improve highways in western New York, and called for airlines to
bring more frequent and less expensive air service to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do everything possible to entice some airlines to look
more closely at the regional airports,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton continued her attacks on Rep. Rick
Lazio, her Republican opponent in the Senate race, this time for a
fund-raising letter sent earlier in the week by his campaign. In
the letter, Lazio said Clinton and her husband, President Clinton,
had ``embarrassed our country and disgraced their powerful posts.''
Lazio has said that he did not see the letter before it was sent,
but that he stood by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is a perfect example of how he tries to be all
things to all people,'' Clinton said. ``And it's part of the
typical political double talk that's marked his campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began her day in Ithaca, where she walked through the
Commons, a business district, and visited a coffee shop. She went
on to attend an outdoor rally in Elmira organized by labor groups
and Democratic Party officials.
</P>
<P>
   As in many of her campaign stops, Clinton evoked both cheers and
protests from onlookers. Friday's appearance in Ithaca drew an
especially vocal group of protesters complaining of the
continuation of the Navy's bombing on the Puerto Rican island of
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the Democratic supporters at both stops were groups of
protesters holding signs reading ``Stand by Your Man . . . in
Arkansas'' as well as other slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, Clinton said that she was not bothered by
such protesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have hundreds of millions of opinions,'' Clinton said.
``And I have no problem with anybody expressing their opinions in a
civil way. It doesn't bother me. It's part of the political
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Clinton departed from her typical pattern of riding in a
van with her staff and security detail by boarding the bus carrying
the reporters covering her campaign. For the 20-minute ride from
Ithaca to Elmira, she spoke with the reporters, reflecting on the
year since she formed an exploratory committee to run for the U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a great experience for me,'' she said, referring
to her first attempt at gaining elective office. ``I had to learn
how to be a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether the negative tone of the protesters' placards
gave her pause, Clinton said: ``Oh, they are amateurs. I have been
down this road for so many years. Even before I was married to Bill
Clinton, people had strong opinions about me. And it hasn't changed
ever since I was a little girl, and I don't expect it to change any
time before the end of this election. It is just part of the
background music of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
