<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6225 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN0708-C     07-07 2248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Like a log. Like a baby. With the fishes. Who cares? As long as
it is a good night's
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Rip Van Winkle, the Greek poet Epimenides and
Charles Perrault's Beauty are the only ones I can think of who had
too much sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep consumes about 20 years of a human lifetime _ or it
should. More than 100 million Americans of all ages, however,
regularly fail to get a good night's sleep. Some blame it on a
snoring mate, a neighbor's barking dog or too much to eat or drink.
Sleepless nights reduce worker productivity and increase
irritability. Need to know more about sleep cycles and disorders?
Ever wonder what causes a yawn? Think preschoolers are the only
ones who benefit from naps? Think again. This edition of the Greig
Files cannot guarantee a good night's sleep but does give you
something to read if you are sleepless.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT THE HECK IS SLEEP?
</P>
<P>
   A periodic state of relative inactivity for the mind and body.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep comes in two types: REM (rapid eye movement), during which
vivid dreams transpire, and nondreaming or dull dreaming non-REM
sleep. About 75 percent of every night is spent in non-REM sleep.
REM periods become longer as the night wears on. When sleep is on
its way, brain waves are progressively wider and taller than those
produced during waking periods. Brain nerve cells are firing in
concert _ like an audience clapping to the same beat _ to make
these waves slower.
</P>
<P>
   Think of going to sleep like going down a hillside.
</P>
<P>
   Stage one is a light sleep in which the brain and muscles begin
to relax on the way down the hill. At stage two, the brain's waves
are markedly wider, and heart rate and respiration slow. Sleep in
stages three and four is characterized by taller, wider brain waves
_ known as Delta sleep _ slower brain activity and noticeable body
recovery. If awakened during this stage, most folks feel lousy _
the total sleep cycle has been interrupted, and wakening from a
Delta sleep is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The final stage is REM sleep, which restores mental alertness
and is characterized by brain waves similar to those during waking
periods.
</P>
<P>
   This sleep cycle takes about 90 minutes to complete; then it's
back to the top of the hill.
</P>
<P>
   WHO SLEEPS AND FOR HOW LONG?
</P>
<P>
   The sandman of sleep is Dr. Peter Hauri, whose book ``No More
Sleepless Nights'' is the bible of bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   Newborns average 16 1/2 hours of sleep a day, and by six months,
14 hours. (Unfortunately for new parents, these hours are not
consecutive.) At age 2, this drops to 12 1/2 hours (split into 11
hours at night and 1 1/2 hour nap time). By age 6, children usually
drop the nap and stick with the 11 hours of sleep. By 10, a child
averages 10 hours of sleep; 13- to 20-year-olds need nine to 10
hours but seldom get it. On average an adult (regardless of age)
sleeps 7 1/2 to 9 hours.
</P>
<P>
   A common misconception is that the elderly need less sleep, but,
in fact, seniors log the same hours as other adults, only in
spurts, as routine napping returns to the sleep pattern.
</P>
<P>
   HELP! IS THAT MY CIRCADIAN CLOCK TICKING?
</P>
<P>
   Sure is. The circadian clock (from the Latin, circa, about; and
dies, day refers to the 24-hour daily rhythm driving everything
from humans to flowers. Sleep runs on this clock. The urge to sleep
in humans is very compelling between midnight and 6 a.m., and again
between 3 and 5 p.m. This clock's major signal? Light.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS THE MOST COMMON CAUSE OF SLEEP PROBLEMS?
</P>
<P>
   Bad sleep habits, notes Dr. David Duhon of the Sleep Disorders
Center of Central Texas. There are so many temptations at night.
Electricity and the light bulb are just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Computers, radios, television, stereos, shift work, part-time
jobs _ all conspire to cut into time traditionally reserved for
rest, if not for sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 10 percent to 15 percent of adults suffer from
obstructive sleep apnea syndrome, marked by snoring and uneven
breathing. WHAT DO JERKS HAVE TO DO WITH SLEEP? These are sleep
starts, also known as ``hypnic jerks,'' when drifting off to sleep.
Accompanied by a sense of falling, the jerks are ``a primitive
postural reflex,'' notes Duhon, a reminder that human ancestors
slept in trees for safety. Maintaining posture during sleep (not
falling out of the tree into a lion's mouth) was essential. The
jerking is a muscle reflex to the natural relaxation of sleep _
reaching out for an imaginary tree branch.
</P>
<P>
   BOSS, IS IT TIME FOR MY NAP?
</P>
<P>
   Sounds funny, but napping _ power napping, that is, of 30
minutes or less _ is one way to increase productivity. The body's
circadian clock is set for sleep at night but also during the
middle of the day. So it's not the el plato grande you had for
lunch that is making you sleepy, nor is it the droning of the staff
meeting. This is nature fighting for a few daytime ZZZZZs.
</P>
<P>
   A short nap is the most effective way to increase alertness.
Ever spy a co-worker dozing in the car? Has your head jerked back
while gazing at a computer monitor recently? Remember, more than 40
percent of Americans admit to taking a daily nap. By the by, women
feel more guilty about napping than men (there's a shock).
</P>
<P>
   Contact the World Nap Organization at
home.bluemarble.net/(tilde)amyloo/wno.html for napping survey
results. No time to nap? There is always the possibility of moving
to Spain for a daily siesta.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS INSOMNIA?
</P>
<P>
   This ubiquitous term means the inability to fall asleep or stay
asleep. It causes irritability, restlessness and anxiety. Mild
insomnia is characterized by a regular (but not daily) feeling of
not being rested, although routines are not impaired. Moderate
insomnia is a nightly experience and causes moderate problems
during waking hours. Severe insomnia occurs regularly and seriously
impairs work and social functioning. For more information on the 84
sleep disorders, visit the American Academy of Sleep Medicine at
asda.org.
</P>
<P>
   IS THERE A DOWN SIDE TO TRAVEL?
</P>
<P>
   Jet lag, the battle of the body against its environment.
Environment usually wins. Body time and local time at war? The
travel gurus at the Austin Diagnostic Center's Travel Clinic advise
common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Get adequate rest before traveling, reduce smoking and avoid
alcohol and caffeine, carry healthy snacks and avoid heavy meals,
increase fluid intake (8 ounces per hour during flight), exercise
(in-seat flexes, walk the aisle), sleep as much as possible on the
plane (pillow, blankets, earplugs and eye cover if necessary),
shower or wash hands and face when possible.
</P>
<P>
   So skip the free champagne (or at least drink less of it), grab
some shut-eye and drink water like a fish. Upon arrival, do not
immediately sleep but force yourself to live in the new time zone
day. Get some sunshine if possible.
</P>
<P>
   DID YOU DREAM A LITTLE DREAM?
</P>
<P>
   You bet you did. Everyone dreams (most in color, although it may
not be remembered that way) every night. And, no, having the same
dream repeatedly does not mean anything in particular. Keep a dream
diary to discern patterns. Certain dreams may replay during times
of change or stress. The Association for the Study of Dreams
reports dreams may be influenced by giving yourself pre-dream
suggestions. As for predicting the future? You might have more luck
becoming Greek and hightailing it to Delphi. Dreams as well as
their interpretation are personal, very personal.
</P>
<P>
   IS THERE A MONSTER UNDER THE BED?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   The monster may just be a nightmare, a normal occurrence.
Nightmares may be caused by medication, stress or illness. Think of
nightmares as a way to explore mental images. For a detailed flier
on nightmares, send a stamped, self-addressed envelope to the
Association of the Study of Dreams, P.O. Box 1166, Orinda, Calif.
94563. Nightmares should not be confused with night terrors, in
which the sleeper may scream and thrash about. Children may suffer
from such terrors and, when comforted by parents, often conquer
these terrors.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CAUSES YAWNING?
</P>
<P>
   Just reading the word, for one thing. No one knows why yawns
occur, only that they do. Theories abound.
</P>
<P>
   Yawns give a burst of oxygen when the body needs it. Or yawns
are a socializing event, alerting others in prehistoric tribes that
it is time for sleep. Or yawning is part of an overall stretch when
muscles need to prepare for work.You pick.
</P>
<P>
   Each explanation can be argued. If yawning occurs when oxygen is
needed, why don't athletes in the middle of strenuous exercise,
when more oxygen is beneficial, yawn? How difficult could it have
been to synchronize sleep in ancient times, when little or nothing
could be accomplished after dark? And if stretching prepares
muscles for work, why is yawning particularly frequent before
bedtime?
</P>
<P>
   Even without the whys of yawning, a few facts have been
established at the University of Washington, where such matters are
studied. Everyone yawns. The average yawn lasts six seconds, and in
humans,the earliest yawning occurs in utero, about 11 weeks after
conception. Children between 1 and 2 years old begin to participate
in contagious yawning. The incidence of yawning is increased when
the hypothalamus is injected with some neurotransmitters (e.g.
dopamine, nitric oxide) of test animals. Yawn.
</P>
<P>
   DOES MR. ED NEED AS MUCH SLEEP AS HUMANS?
</P>
<P>
   Not really, notes Duhon.
</P>
<P>
   The average equine and other large grazing animals such as
elephants and giraffes need only three hours per day. The
exception? Lions and tigers spend a great deal of the day asleep.
In contrast, chimpanzees sleep nine to 10 hours; gorillas, 12 to
15; and the South American owl monkey, 17 hours per day. Bats need
about 20 hours of shut-eye.
</P>
<P>
   Reptiles and fish do not ``sleep'' per se but have periods when
they are less sensitive to their environment. Some birds manage to
nap in flight. Neat trick _ but not as neat as fur seals and some
dolphin species, which manage to allow one hemisphere of the brain
to sleep at a time. This particular adaptation allows them to sleep
without drowning.
</P>
<P>
   And the king of all nappers? The Indus River dolphin, a blind
species living in swift river currents. This dolphin sleeps a total
of seven hours a day _ 4 to 40 seconds at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ARE YOU SLEEPLESS IN SAN DIEGO?
</P>
<P>
   That is what 17-year-old Randy Gardner was in the mid-1960s,
when he went 264 hours without sleep. There were, however, plenty
of cold showers, rock 'n' roll and caffeine to keep young Randy
awake. Before succumbing to Morphias, Gardner suffered slurred
speech, finally falling into a silent stupor. Although the
sleepless period was supervised, such stunts are dangerous. A
University of Chicago study showed that rats die when prevented
from sleeping for 2 1/2 weeks, reports Michael Cannell in Science
World.
</P>
<P>
   NIGHTTIME SUPERSTITIONS
</P>
<P>
   _ To rid yourself of possible aftereffects of bad dreams, spit
three times as soon as you wake up. _ The best night's sleep is had
in a bed facing south.
</P>
<P>
   _ If your bed faces east, you will be rich; west, you will
travel. _ Avoid nightmares by hanging socks or stockings over the
end of the bed with a pin stuck through them. _ To dream of muddy
water is to be warned of trouble or impending death. _ Dreaming of
lice portends some family member will be sick. _ Being sleepy after
dinner means company is coming. _ Daytime sleep induces fever,
especially in the summer. _ Never waken a person suddenly, lest his
spirit, which wanders during sleep, not have sufficient time to
re-enter the body. _ Sleeping on the left side invites heart
trouble. _ A woman who dreams of fish will have a baby.
</P>
<P>
   _ A dream told on Saturday will come true.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GET THE SLEEP YOU NEED
</P>
<P>
   Here are some sleep tips from the Mayo Clinic:
</P>
<P>
   _ Establish a regular bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get up at the usual time in the morning, even if you did not
have a restful night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   _ Read or watch television until becoming sleepy, rather than
trying to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   _ Set an alarm clock, but put it out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cut down time in bed by 30 to 60 minutes to deepen sleep. _
Exercise four to six hours before bedtime. _ Make the bedroom as
comfortable as possible. _ Eat a light snack. _ Take a hot bath two
hours before going to bed. _ Avoid alcohol. _ Avoid beverages
containing caffeine after lunchtime. _ Avoid tobacco. _ Deal with
worries before bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   LATE NIGHT ?
</P>
<P>
   Catch up, like payback, is . . . well, difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree missing your normal shut-eye one night, like
missing one meal, is not that debilitating. You can catch up the
next day by going to bed early or sleeping a bit later. But do not
delay. Waiting until the weekend to grab needed shut-eye only
compounds the sleep deficit and general malaise. Better yet, bank a
little extra sleep when a late night looms.
</P>
<P>
   FROM THE KEYBOARD: SLEEP INFO ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   _ www.websciences.org: The National Sleep Foundation _
www.thesleepsite.com: The Sleep Site _ www.rls.org: Restless Leg
Syndrome Foundation
</P>
<P>
   _ bisleep.medsch.ucla.edu: The Sleep Home Pages of the Brain
Information Services _ www.yawn.org: Young Adults with Narcolepsy _
www.nhlbi.nih.gov/about/ncsdr: The National Center on Sleep
Disorders Research of the National Institutes of Health _
www.sleepapnea.org: The American Sleep Apnea Associations
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
