<HEADER>
A6226 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-DEADLY-TRACK0708-     07-07 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DEADLY-TRACK0708-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Track claims another life
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Death is a possibility every time a person climbs
behind the wheel of a high-speed automobile. Winston Cup drivers
are fully aware of the extreme job hazard, but they don't like to
talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   However, when two drivers are killed in the same turn at the
same track in eight weeks, the racing community quickly speaks up.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin was killed on Friday after crashing in the third
turn of New Hampshire International Speedway, only a few yards
farther down the outside retainer wall where Busch driver Adam
Petty died on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two (deaths) means it is a problem,'' Ward Burton said. ``It
needs to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR needs to look into this tragedy, along with Adam's, to
prevent it from occurring again,'' Steve Park said. ``They need to
investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's incident had drivers questioning the safety of
1.058-mile track, the third turn and the engine throttles in
Winston Cup stock cars. Minutes after winning the pole for Sunday's
thatlook.com 300, Rusty Wallace wondered aloud about his
participation in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am, clearing tire rubber out of my eyeballs and grease
out of my fingernails and friends are getting killed _ these are
days that make you not want do it, I'll tell you that,'' Wallace
said. ``It really makes you question why you're doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire and Martinsville are mentioned by drivers as being
two of the most dangerous tracks on the circuit. Not due to high
speeds, but because of sharp turns required in the corners.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace has a safety suggestion for New Hampshire and other
tracks: flexible protection barriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan of these barriers after what I saw in (the Busch
race) at Watkins Glen,'' Wallace said. ``(Jimmie Johnson) hit and
flipped and the (barrier) softened the blow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's make sure our drivers are protected at the race track,''
Mike Bliss said. ``Let's make sure they can hit a wall and walk
away (with barriers).''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd said the difficult thing about New Hampshire is it
being a flat track. Drivers can build up fast speeds on the front
and back stretches, which may cause problems making a turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the hardest I ever hit anywhere was when I had a
throttle stick in a test session at Martinsville,'' Rudd said.
``You would think Martinsville would be the least place you'd worry
about getting hurt, but I think it sort of lures you to sleep
because the straightaways are so long and the speeds are very fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have any kind of mechanical problem at all, you don't
have time to recover from it and it's usually head-on into the
fence.''
</P>
<P>
   The final concern, which is growing among all race teams, is
about hung throttles. Most drivers speculated that Irwin's crashed
because his engine throttle got stuck. NASCAR declined to comment
on the cause of the wreck until further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers thought Petty's wreck was due to a stuck
throttle. NASCAR Chief Operating Officer Mike Helton said earlier
this week that there was ``no conclusive evidence'' to prove that
Petty crashed because of mechanical error.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to learn from this -- I'm going to my car right
now to look at what I can do for pulling the throttle back,'' Bliss
said. ``I needed to see what I can do in my race car to prevent
anything from happening if my throttle hung.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of the few people defending New Hampshire on
Friday was Adam's grandfather, Richard Petty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those (deaths) are circumstances beyond human control,'' Petty
said. ``There ain't nothing the matter with this race track.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys run these things at 200 mph. It's circumstances
with the way you stop that thing so quick. Your body just can't
stand it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
