<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NY-HODGES-GRANDSON-NY     07-07 0310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HODGES-GRANDSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANDSON OF DODGERS STAR IS CHARGED IN FRIEND'S ACCIDENTAL DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category ``a'')  
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The grandson of Gil Hodges, the first baseman for the
postwar Brooklyn Dodgers, was charged with manslaughter Friday
after he accidentally killed the brother of a man believed to be a
member of the Lucchese crime family, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges' grandson, also named Gil Hodges, is accused of killing
Lance Marino, the brother of Craig Marino, who was described by
investigators as a member of the Lucchese family.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Hodges, 26, and Marino, 27, both Brooklyn
residents, spent Thursday night drinking at the Northside Cafe in
the Williamsburg section of Brooklyn. Toward the end of the
evening, Marino fell asleep on the hood of Hodges' Range Rover,
which was parked outside the bar. Hodges drove off with his friend
still atop the car, the police said, and after about a mile, Marino
fell off, striking his head on construction debris. He was
pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn district attorney's office charged Hodges with
vehicular manslaughter, reckless endangerment, driving while
intoxicated and reckless driving. His lawyer, Vincent Romano, said
Hodges was ``in shock'' because he and Marino had been best
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Romano, who said he had also represented Marino before his
death, said Marino did not have any ties to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Marino, 30, Marino's brother, is believed to be a member
of the Lucchese crime family, said Kevin Davitt, a spokesman for
the Brooklyn district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gil Hodges played for the Dodgers during the 1940s and
'50s. He later managed the New York Mets, leading them to victory
in the 1969 World Series. He died in 1972.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
