<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6243 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-375&AMP;AD     07-07 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ AND THE YANKEES DERAIL THE METS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is the kind of season it has been for Al Leiter,
according to New York Mets Manager Bobby Valentine: He usually
pitches very well, and on the days he doesn't, the other team's
line drives are caught. Either way, Leiter usually wins.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter did not win Friday night, chiefly because the Mets
encountered a pitcher who was both lucky and good. Orlando
Hernandez mystified the Mets, allowing five hits and one run in
eight innings and leading the New York Yankees to a 2-1 victory
before a crowd of 54,132 at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was the opener of this weekend's four-game series, which
resumes on two fronts Saturday: an afternoon game at Shea, with
Dwight Gooden returning there as a starter for the Yankees, then a
night game at Yankee Stadium to make up for a rainout there on June
11.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night belonged to Hernandez (8-6), who held the Mets'
All-Star selections, Edgardo Alfonzo and Mike Piazza, hitless in
eight at-bats as he won his second start in a row since elbow
soreness sidelined him near the end of June. Leiter was nearly as
sharp, giving up only six hits and two runs over eight innings and
facing one batter over the minimum over his last seven and
two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's record dropped to 10-2, but he was nearly taken off the
hook in the eighth inning. Melvin Mora smoked a one-out triple to
right-center, and Derek Bell followed with a drive to deep right.
</P>
<P>
   Bell slowed to a trot: the ball was hit so high that it would
either be gone for a game-tying home run or right fielder Paul
O'Neill would catch it. O'Neill drifted back, jumped and with his
back at the wall, reached back and robbed Bell of a homer.
</P>
<P>
   Bell stopped just past first base, standing still for a bit and
wearing an expression that asked if that really had just happened.
Mora scored from third on the sacrifice fly, but the moment was
deflating, and Alfonzo flied out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera pitched a scoreless ninth inning, allowing a
two-out single to Todd Zeile after getting by Mike Piazza and Robin
Ventura. Rivera earned his 19th save by getting Jay Payton to fly
to right with a runner on first to end the game.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Mets' hitters had chances with runners in scoring position.
In the second, Ventura smacked a one-out double to deep center
field, but Zeile lined out and Payton popped out.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Agbayani led off the third with a single, and Leiter
sacrificed him to second. Mora bounced a bunt in front of the
plate, but he ran into the ball on his way to first for the second
out. Bell grounded out, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets' best chance over the first seven innings may have
been in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez walked the first two batters, then Agbayani came up,
swung at the first pitch, and hit a hard line drive up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez, looking more like a shortstop, leaped, reached
across his body and snared the ball. He turned and fired to Derek
Jeter covering second base for the second out. Payton, who was at
first, scrambled back to beat Jeter's throw and avoid the triple
play.
</P>
<P>
   And so it continued for the Mets. In another inning, Zeile
grounded sharply down the third-base line with one out; a few
inches to the right, and he would have had a double. Instead it was
foul, and Zeile wound up hitting a single. He never left first, as
Payton struck out looking and Agbayani lined out to first.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees got all the runs they would need in the first.
Leiter had allowed only one first-inning run this year, and his
first inning Friday night was easily his worst of the season. The
first five Yankee hitters reached base.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter may start Tuesday's All-Star Game, and he quickly
returned to the form that made him the National League's leader in
winning percentage (.909) entering Friday night's game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch led off the first with a walk, but before
Leiter's first pitch to Jeter, he picked Knoblauch off first. Then
Jeter lined a single to right, and O'Neill advanced him to third
with a ground single through the left side of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter got ahead of the next two hitters, but it made no
difference. With an 0-2 count against Williams, Leiter left a
fastball up in the strike zone, and Williams lashed it to right for
a single, scoring Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter tried a slider on 0-2 to the next hitter, Posada, who let
it go by for a ball. Posada got a fastball on the next pitch, and
ripped it to left, bringing in O'Neill from second.
</P>
<P>
   He retired Martinez on a fly to left and he struck out Spencer,
ending the inning. It took him 33 pitches to escape the first, but
Leiter was on his way.
</P>
<P>
   He worked 1-2-3 innings in the second, third, fourth and fifth,
and looked every bit the pitcher who had beaten the Yankees in his
previous three Subway Series starts. Leiter pitches on emotion, and
he thrives on the energy of Mets-Yankees meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very, very tough competitor,'' Valentine said. ``He
enjoys the rivalry stuff. He understands it and relishes the fact
that he's part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter didn't allow another base runner until Jeter reached on
an infield single to lead off the sixth, beating Mora's throw.
Again, Leiter got a pickoff, his eighth of the season, tying him
with Arizona's Brian Anderson for the National League lead.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter is third in the league in pitches per start, with an
average of 112 entering the game, and the pick-offs saved him some
pitches. But he had still thrown 95 through six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had thrown just 72 pitches through six, mainly because
the Mets were swinging early in the count. Half of the Mets' first
22 hitters had one- or two-pitch at-bats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
