<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COLUMN-GIULIANI-NY     07-07 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: INVITING AN INVASION OF PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reading about New York politics lately can make you
wonder if you've turned to the wrong part of the newspaper. A lot
of it sounds as if it ought to be on the television page, in an
article on a new daytime soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   This weeper has everything: politics, stymied ambition, a
marriage on the rocks, a bitter wife, whispers of an old love
affair, a new girlfriend and a cancer menace.
</P>
<P>
   Not satisfied with power, romance and disease? How about a
little crime?
</P>
<P>
   Throw in a tale about how the main character's father once did
prison time for an armed stickup and then became a leg breaker for
loan sharks. While you're at it, let's have an uncle who ran a
gambling operation out of his bar. And a cousin who was a wise guy
gunned down by the feds.
</P>
<P>
   For want of a better title, we can call the soap opera, ``As the
Mayor Turns.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been some year for Rudolph Giuliani, and it could
easily get worse because of revelations in two new books about him.
Details have dribbled out all week, none more startling than
criminal skeletons from the Giuliani family closet that are
described in Wayne Barrett's ``Rudy! An Investigative Biography of
Rudolph Giuliani'' (Basic Books).
</P>
<P>
   Things have been going so badly for the mayor that the first
instinct was to sympathize with him the other day when he asserted
his right to privacy and denounced ``the almost crazed atmosphere''
of the press probing into his personal matters.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking specifically about the medical treatment he plans
for his prostate cancer. But he might as well have been musing
about the electron microscope now trained on his love life and
family history.
</P>
<P>
   Watching someone's life being turned into a fishbowl isn't
pretty. First instincts are not always dead-on, though. Sympathy,
while still there, was joined by a second thought: that Giuliani
brought much of his privacy ordeal on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Who disclosed his cancer? He did, though it was after a reporter
saw him at a hospital. Why is it then surprising that New Yorkers
would be curious about how he deals with the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Who announced to the news media that he was separating from his
wife, Donna Hanover? He did _ before he even told her. Until then,
New York journalists had been most circumspect about his plainly
unhappy marriage.
</P>
<P>
   It was Giuliani who then showed off his new ``very good
friend,'' Judith Nathan. No reporter suggested to him that he take
Nathan one May evening on a 10-block stroll through a sea of
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   As for the revelations that his father, Harold, was an ex-con,
the mayor has not confirmed them. But he also has notably passed up
several opportunities to deny them. It is not clear if he even knew
Harold Giuliani had been in Sing Sing in the 1930s, a decade before
Rudolph Giuliani was born.
</P>
<P>
   A natural inclination was to agree with him the other day when
he said, ``My father died 19 years ago, and the details of his life
died with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet only four months ago the mayor did not think that Patrick M.
Dorismond deserved the same consideration after he was shot to
death, though unarmed, by an undercover police officer. Then,
Giuliani did everything he could to blacken Dorismond's reputation,
even releasing the dead man's juvenile court records. When critics
protested his tactics, the mayor brushed them aside. ``Privacy
interests and rights expire with you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So much for his faith in privacy. Shouldn't what is good for
Patrick Dorismond also be good for Harold Giuliani?
</P>
<P>
   The bigger question would seem to be whether the Giuliani family
secrets, if true, tell us anything about the mayor who has so
thoroughly dominated New York.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Mario Cuomo thinks not. ``I find it very difficult
to make a case that it is relevant unless you can show me the
connection between the father's conduct and the son's quality,'' he
said. ``And I don't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he's right.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be surprised if New Yorkers are fascinated that the
racket-busting mayor may have come from a mob-connected family. Or
if some wonder whether his war on the Mafia had something to do
with nasty things he saw up close as a young man. Or if some ask
why he is so unsympathetic to almost anyone who has had a brush
with the law when his own father's story, as Barrett said this
week, ``should tell Rudy something about the complications of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Those asking such questions may well be off base. But the
armchair psychoanalysis seems inevitable all the same, as
inevitable, perhaps, as further installments of ``As the Mayor
Turns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
