<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO'S CAMPAIGN HIGHS AND LOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He has taken a licking from a cow focused on his
khakis and a licking from the press focused on a fund-raising
letter attacking his opponent. In one day he was told by a
beer-clutching middle-aged man to ``kill'' his opponent and by an
elderly woman that his position generally favoring abortion rights
amounts to murder. He has heard people greet him as Rick while
others stood back, asking who he was.
</P>
<P>
   If Rep. Rick Lazio's 1,200-mile tour across the state this past
week seemed up and down, it apparently never fazed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a chance to talk about some of the issues I've been
working on in Washington,'' Lazio, the Republican Senate nominee,
said before heading to a factory outside Rochester and his final
stop at a Bronx hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At a later briefing, he turned unusually introspective as he
spoke of responding to issues of the day. He said the experience
had reconfirmed his goal ``to not let myself get too defensive when
somebody is saying something that bothers me, to try and take a
deep breath and answer questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, while traveling on a plane from Rochester to New York
City, he revealed some things he has missed because of the
campaign, such as a Bible study group he attends with a group of
fellow congressmen. He struggled to name the last movie he had
seen, relying on his wife, Patricia, to remind him that it was
``Pokemon,'' and said he had not read a book in months. The last
one was ``Tuesdays With Morrie.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spoke on a variety of topics in his five-day tour _ child
care, housing for the elderly, support for farmers, the desire to
lower taxes, all things that he said he supported through
legislation in the House. But like his first bus tour after winning
the nomination on May 30, pictures counted, too, particularly as a
camera crew shot material over three days for future commercials.
</P>
<P>
   That may explain the rocketing streamers fired off at two stops,
at rallies of fewer than 75 people in otherwise deserted parks. Or
the large American flag that dwarfed Lazio at a Schenectady rally.
Or why Michael Murphy, his chief strategist, sat on the bumper of a
red pickup truck in the town of Argyle's Independence Day parade,
directing Lazio, who was marching right behind.
</P>
<P>
   On a dairy farm in Burke, a few miles from Canada, Lazio changed
from a dress shirt to a blue-and-white checkered shirt before
sitting among bales of hay. With the camera on, he showed concern
as farmers talked about hard times. Later, his aides asked
reporters to step out of sight while the Lazios and their two young
daughters walked off into a gloriously green field with cows, for
some more filming.
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on when the commercials will be broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   In Saratoga Springs, they brandished American flags from a small
window on the bus that Lazio used for his swing across the state.
In Yonkers, they hurled hats and T-shirts at eager supporters. And
as he marched in an Independence Day parade in Lake Placid, the
daughters got on the microphone in the bus and called out, ``Vote
for my dad, he's great!''
</P>
<P>
   A little over a week after Chelsea Clinton coyly signaled that
she would be around a little more, now that her mother, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, was running for Senate, along come Molly and Kelsey
Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The debut of Molly, 8, and Kelsey, 6, has not attracted the
attention given to Chelsea Clinton, who was surrounded by reporters
at a recent City Hall news conference. But at least on this trip,
they have been front and center much of the time.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They have traveled with their father before but stayed largely
in the background or out of sight. This time they scampered about,
amusing onlookers with their antics, such as showing off
operating-room garb while Dad toured Bronx-Lebanon Hospital Center
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Having the family around _ Patricia Lazio is often by her
husband's side at campaign events _ helps bolster the mainstream,
family-man image that Lazio is striving to project. Lazio says the
family also helps relieve the stress of campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   But after summer vacation is over, he does not expect to bring
them on the campaign trail often.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure they do their homework,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As much as it had to do with talking over issues, Lazio's tour
was about getting his name and face out more _ particularly
important for a relatively unknown Long Island congressman in a
contest with the first lady of the United States. And on this, his
score was mixed.
</P>
<P>
   In a Yonkers diner early in the trip, a waitress who had served
the congressman and his family was asked her opinion of him. She
replied, ``What's his name again?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
