<SLUG> BC-NY-PIRRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRRO SETTLES PATERNITY SUIT IN INDIANA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  By COREY KILGANNON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A long-standing paternity suit against Albert Pirro
Jr., the husband of the district attorney for Westchester County,
New York, was settled on Thursday in Indiana, two weeks after
Pirro's conviction for tax fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The paternity suit, filed by the mother of a teen-age girl,
figured during Pirro's tax-fraud trial: prosecutors said that he
claimed money spent in fighting the suit as a business expense on
his tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro, a prominent Republican businessman who is married to
District Attorney Jeanine Pirro, was convicted by a federal jury of
improperly deducting $1.2 million in personal expenses as business
write-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, DNA testing indicated that Pirro, 52, was the father
of a teen-age girl whose mother, Jessica Marciano of Indiana, sued
him for child support.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Pirro in Indiana did not return a phone message
left Friday. Pirro's spokeswoman, Colleen Roche, confirmed that a
settlement had been reached, but said the court ruling kept her
from commenting or providing details.
</P>
<P>
   During the tax-fraud trial, several private investigators
testified that Pirro had hired them to help him fight the suit and
had paid them from one or more companies he owned.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer and Pirro family friend who once employed Marciano also
testified that Pirro had paid him to find hospital and divorce
records on her.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that these fees were included in Pirro's tax
deductions, which also included expenses for sports cars, cruise
tickets and furniture for the Pirros' home in Harrison, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano, who has married and now goes by the name Lynne
Lichtefeld, did not attend the tax-fraud trial, which ended June
22. She had been arrested May 30 at Newark International Airport on
a warrant for violation of probation in Florida related to a 1992
theft conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro was convicted along with his brother and accountant,
Anthony Pirro, on tax charges in U.S. District Court in
Westchester. Pirro is appealing the conviction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000707.0401 </DOCNO>
