<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-MESSIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSIER IS SET ON THE RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doug Messier, the father and agent of Mark Messier, indicated
that while other teams had expressed interest in signing him, the
Messiers were talking only to the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   And, Doug Messier said, the deal to bring Messier, a 39-year-old
free-agent center, back to the Rangers after his departure in 1997
could be done as soon as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had considerable interest, but we haven't responded,''
Doug Messier told The Canadian Press, a news agency, about other
teams seeking to sign his son. ``Mark is basically looking at
seeing what we can work out with the Rangers. We're just having
conversations and exchanging some ways that might make it possible
to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are believed to be close to a two-year, $11
million deal. But because Glen Sather, the Rangers' president and
general manager, is at the wedding of one of his sons in Banff,
Alberta, this weekend, Doug Messier said, ``We'll have nothing
until Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   According to several NHL officials, Sather is also close to
signing the free-agent defenseman Vladimir Malakhov.
</P>
<P>
   But the Messier deal would be the Rangers' signature signing
because their former captain led the club to the Stanley Cup in
1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
