<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARK-ROBBERIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO ROBBED IN CENTRAL PARK, UNDERSCORING RISE IN CRIME THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two people _ including a tourist from Israel _ were
reportedly robbed in well-trafficked areas of Central Park Friday
morning in incidents that did not appear to be related, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The daylight robberies followed weeks of embarrassing scrutiny
of safety and policing in Central Park, the crown jewel of New York
City's parks. On June 11, groups of men sexually assaulted 59
women, including tourists, in Central Park after the Puerto Rican
Day parade on June 11.
</P>
<P>
   Overall crime in the Central Park precinct is up 9 percent
through July 2 this year, compared with the same period last year,
police statistics show. And robberies have increased 32 percent
since 1999, with 33 during that period this year, compared with 24
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the robberies Friday reportedly occurred near the
Central Park Zoo at 6:40 a.m. Two men punched James Jonest, 43, of
Manhattan in the face and stomach and stole $253 and his jacket,
the police said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second robbery, reported by a tourist from Israel, the
tourist was walking near the Central Park Boathouse around 11:05
a.m. when a man demanded her money. The tourist, Mae Benhur, 23,
told the police that the man said he had a gun, but he did not show
one. The man stole Benhur's CD player, $20 and a $100 traveler's
check.
</P>
<P>
   Two other robberies occurred in Central Park during the past
week. On Sunday, three men reported being robbed at gunpoint in the
Conservatory Garden. On June 30, a picnicking couple reported being
robbed at gunpoint near Wollman Rink.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
