<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 07/07/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT149) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- RACE-COPS-10 -- Race colors
everything for Harlem narcotics detectives. New York City Police
Detective Johnny Gonzalez, right, himself Dominican-American, is an
investigator in Sgt. Maria Brogli's Harlem narcotics unit. For five
years before that, he was an undercover for Brogli, left, posing as
a drug user, a brown man disappearing into a brown neighborhood.
Brogli and Gonzalez on midnight surveillance at 605 West 141st
Street in uptown Manhattan. Brogli and Gonzalez noting a floor plan
for a raid the next day. (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT148) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- RACE-COPS-9 -- For five
years Detective Johnny Gonzalez of the Harlem narcotics unit was an
undercover for a white narcotics sergeant, posing as a drug user, a
brown man disappearing into a brown neighborhood. Smart cops like
Gonzalez, himself Dominican-American, know how to use race wisely,
how to turn race to their advantage to enforce the law. Detective
Christopher Vaughn left, and Sgt. Joe Simonetti, right, holding
Raymond Munez while Detective Johnny Gonzalez tries to pry from his
mouth the heroin he had been carrying, in uptown Manhattan. (Angel
Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT147) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- RACE-COPS-8 -- For five
years Detective Johnny Gonzalez of the Harlem narcotics unit was an
undercover for a white narcotics sergeant, posing as a drug user, a
brown man disappearing into a brown neighborhood. Gonzalez on his
police radio while waiting to take in Raymond Munez, rear, leaning
against car and guarded by Detective Christopher Vaughn at Broadway
and 137th Street in uptown Manhattan. Munez was arrested and later
indicted for drug possession. (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT146) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- RACE-COPS-7 -- For five
years Detective Johnny Gonzalez of the Harlem narcotics unit was an
undercover for a white narcotics sergeant, posing as a drug user, a
brown man disappearing into a brown neighborhood. Smart cops like
Gonzalez, himself Dominican-American, know how to use race wisely,
how to turn race to their advantage to enforce the law. Gonzalez
arresting Hector Espinal in a buy-and-bust in uptown Manhattan.
Espinal was indicted on a drug-selling charge and is scheduled to
go on trial. (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT145) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- RACE-COPS-6 -- Race colors
everything for Harlem narcotics detectives. It lies just beneath
the surface in an argument over tactics between a white sergeant
and a black undercover detective. Race is in the police radio
descriptions, and race amplifies the anger on the street when the
police drive up and arrest yet another dark-skinned man. Lieutenant
James Byrne and Sergeant Maria Brogli on Sherman Avenue in uptown
Manhattan after an arrest in a long-term case. Ramon Mendoza, rear,
in handcuffs, was indicted on a drug conspiracy charge. (Angel
Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT144) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- RACE-COPS-5 -- Race colors
everything for Harlem narcotics detectives. Sergeant Maria Brogli
of the Harlem narcotics unit, an Italian-American, could not do her
work without her undercover detectives, whose dark skin renders
them invisible on these streets. Sgt. Brogli searching a man in a
building on West 137th Street. No drugs were found. (Angel
Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT143) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- RACE-COPS-4 -- Cops do not
discuss race. It's too risky. They need to get along. Most police
work can be dangerous, but day in and day out, undercovers take
more risks. Armed and using a light-equipped bulletproof shield
called a bunker, Lieutenant James Byrne of the Harlem narcotics
unit prepares to enter an apartment on West 141st Street in uptown
Manhattan to serve a warrant. The narcotics team had already opened
the door with a battering ram. (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT142) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- RACE-COPS-3 -- Most police
work can be dangerous, but day in and day out, undercovers take
more risks. Smart cops in narcotics units know how to use race
wisely, how to turn race to their advantage to enforce the law. At
this raid of an apartment building by a Harlem narcotics team, led
by a white sergeant and lieutenant, crack cocaine was found. (Angel
Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT141) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- RACE-COPS-2 -- Smart cops
in narcotics units know how to use race wisely, how to turn race to
their advantage to enforce the law. Sgt. Maria Brogli, center,
glancing at statue, with Lt. James Byrne and Detective Johnny
Gonzalez behind her, has had much success with her Harlem narcotics
team. Among these undercovers, Brogli is a favorite, the rare white
sergeant with a reputation for listening to undercovers and
speaking up for them. On this particular day, however, a search of
an apartment, viewed from outside the front door, yielded no drugs.
(Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT140) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- SUB-RACE-COPS-1 -- Race
colors everything for Harlem narcotics detectives. New York City
Police Detective Johnny Gonzalez, himself Dominican-American, is an
investigator in Sgt. Maria Brogli's Harlem narcotics unit. For five
years before that, he was an undercover for Brogli, posing as a
drug user, a brown man disappearing into a brown neighborhood. The
very visible, white Brogli, an Italian-American, could not do her
work without her undercover detectives, whose dark skin renders
them invisible on these streets. (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   The following photos are also part of our daily photo report:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- ADV FOR SUN. JULY 9 --
AT&AMP;T-FUTURE -- Michael Armstrong, the chairman of AT&AMP;T, needed help
in telling investors that the company's core businesses had
stumbled. He turned to top Wall Street analysts for their advice.
The reaction from AT&AMP;Ts investors was swift and harsh. The
company's shares dropped rapidly, shaving more than $25 billion
from AT&AMP;T's market value. Armstrong, left, chairman and CEO of AT&AMP;T
and John C. Malone, chairman and CEO of TCI during a press
conference at AT&AMP;T headquarters. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JULY 9 --
SHOE-SALES -- The footwear industry has had to tackle a problem
that now and then plagues consumer industries from clothes to cars:
When cash registers stop ringing, how do you entice consumers to go
out and buy more? The answer, in a word, was revolution, not
evolution. Inspired by current psychedelic clothing styles and able
to exploit new technologies that easily allow fancy embellishments
like beading, shoemakers are dreaming up fantasy styles that have
never been seen before. And they hope that their exotic new
confections will re-ignite consumer interest with a passion. (Nancy
Siesel/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEGRIL, Jamaica -- July 7, 2000 --
JAMAICA-MISSING-EDITOR -- Claudia Kirschhoch, a travel editor for
Frommer's, vanished without a trace in Jamaica in late May. For the
last month, newspapers, radio stations and television programs have
been running reports on her disappearance every few days. Her
parents, Frederick and Mary Ann Kirschhoch, have been conducting a
methodical search for her throughout Jamaica. Mary Ann Kirschhoch,
left, talking with a woman in Negril, Jamaica, last month after
giving her a flier about Claudia. (Edward Wong/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- NY-COURTS-ABUSE -- Due to
the increase of domestic violence incidents in the presence of
children, a state court ruling declared the actions to be
sufficient grounds for finding a parent guilty of neglect. This is
particularly vexing for mothers who lack the financial or emotional
resources to leave an abusive partner. Judges are finding that they
must remove children from their homes for their own protection. For
many judges these cases present an especially daunting exercise in
balancing interests. Sharlene Tillett's son, Uganda, was taken away
at 2 days old. She was said to have failed to protect him when she
was beaten before his death. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MOORESTOWN, N.J. -- July 7, 2000 -- ADV FOR SUN. JULY 9
-- LOCKHEED-HIGHTECH-2 -- Lockheed Martin is looking to change its
market. It went from being the world's top military contractor to
part of a top group of contractors used by the government.
Currently its biggest business is selling sophisticated electronic
gear and integrating the most advanced equipment from different
suppliers, whether for military or peaceful purposes. Electronics
and integration have become the fastest-growing segment for
military contractors. The company is having a profound impact on
Navy programs like the Aegis ship-based weapons system. The USS
Arleigh Burke, which is the lead ship in the Navy's class of Aegis
destroyers. (Lockheed Martin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MOORESTOWN, N.J. -- July 7, 2000 -- -- ADV FOR SUN. JULY
9 -- LOCKHEED-HIGHTECH-1 -- The Lockheed Martin Corporation are
using ships that look like Navy cruisers for a different purpose.
They are used as labs where Lockheed Martin tests its ability to
knit together naval communications gear, sensors, radar and
controls used to fire weapons. Lockheed Martin, known as a maker of
military wares like fighters, missiles and rockets has quietly
transformed itself into a supplier of advanced military equipment.
A technician inspecting the face of a radar array. (Lockheed
Martin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine -- July 7, 2000 -- BUSH-PARENTS-2
-- Former President George Bush with his son Jeb, the governor of
Florida, in Kennebunkport, Me., Friday. Jeb Bush, who joined his
parents for lunch, says that his brother George was benefiting from
a Republican yearning to take back the White House, a desire so
strong that the party was managing to paper over internal divisions
that had fractured it in the past. ``Eight years in the wilderness
brings a higher tolerance for diversity,'' says Jeb Bush, adding
that 12 years in the wilderness had made the Democratic party rally
in a similar way around Clinton in 1992. (Paul Hosefros/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- COHEN-SULLIVAN-PROFILE --
ADV FOR SUN. JULY 9 -- H. Rodgin Cohen, a leading banking lawyer,
became chairman of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell, the New York law firm. For
more than 30 years, Cohen, 56, has been a sought-after counselor to
chief executives of the industry's largest institutions, including
the Bank of New York, First Union and Societe Generale. It is his
skill as an attentive counselor who not only understands the law,
but also how it is best applied in both business and politics, that
holds sway with clients. Cohen, at home with his dog Orion. (James
Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- July 7, 2000 -- SHRINERS-CELLIST-BOS -- Tad
Lietz, 12, uses his ability to create beautiful music as a means of
overcoming his disability. Lietz who was born without a left arm,
was abandoned shortly after birth in Ho Chi Minh City in Vietnam.
The Shriners, an international fraternity that supports a network
of hospitals offering free care to patients, have helped Lietz to
realize his lifelong dream of becoming a famous cellist, by fitting
him with a prosthetic left arm. Lietz, who uses his foot to work
the bow, during a performance at the Shriner's national convention
at the Hynes Convention Center in Boston, Wednesday. (Evan
Richman/The Boston Globe) Story moved on 070600. LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- July 7, 2000 -- GENETIC-TESTING-BOS -- Medicine
has begun a major shift toward being able to remedy the underlying
causes of diseases and away from relying on the diagnosis and
treatment of symptoms. Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc. has
developed a test for melanoma patients based on gene testing.
Initially focused on cancer, the diagnostic and genomic tests are
aimed at recovering patients who want to know whether the disease
is no longer active or will pose problems for them in the future.
The results could lead to more aggressive medical treatment and
counseling. Kenneth Conway, the company's president and Dr. Michael
Kaufman, vice president of medicine at Millennium's Predictive
Medicine group. (Jay Premack/The Boston Globe) Story moved on
070600. LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DETROIT -- July 7, 2000 -- ABOUT-CARS-MAZDA-2 -- ADV FOR
SUN. JULY 9 -- Mazda is looking to take back a share of the market
for sports utility vehicles. Designed and engineered in Japan, the
2001 Tribute is built at a Ford assembly plant near Kansas City,
Mo. The Tribute is aimed at the consumer who appreciates size,
refinement and substance. The Tribute maneuvers around corners and
rides as smoothly as a car. Mazda's Tribute has the potential to be
best in its class of smaller SUVs. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DETROIT -- July 7, 2000 -- ABOUT-CARS-MAZDA-1 -- ADV FOR
SUN. JULY 9 -- Recently, Mazda found itself without a sport utility
vehicle which meant that they were missing out on the hottest auto
fashion trend of the decade. Next month, Mazda receives a sport
utility vehicle from Ford called the Tribute and looks to have a
bright future. The Tribute has the potential to be the best in its
class in a booming segment of the car market. It is aimed at young
singles, couples and small families on budgets. Sales of small
sport utilities have more than doubled in the last four years and
further growth is expected both in the United States and overseas.
The interior of Mazda's Tribute SUV, 2001 model. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine -- July 7, 2000 -- BUSH-PARENTS-1 --
Barbara and George Bush in Kennebunkport, Me., Friday, in a rare
face-to-face interview about their son's presidential campaign. The
Bush's say that the notion of ``Clinton fatigue'' was real, and
that their son's pledge to ``restore honor and integrity'' to the
Oval Office would resonate with voters. Bush also says that Vice
President Al Gore's ties to Clinton would not allow him to present
himself credibly as a fresh start, and that Gov. Bush's ability to
do so would prove decisive. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- DIANA-ROSS-REVIEW -- Diana
Ross and the Supremes rekindled social and musical passions during
their recent concert at Madison Square Garden. It was a tribute to
three musicians who weren't onstage: Brian Holland, Lamont Dozier
and Edward Holland Jr. These men were responsible for the string of
hits that made the Supremes' songs classics. Ross, center, performs
with two former Supremes, Lynda Laurence, left, and Scherrie Payne,
right, at Madison Square Garden in Manhattan. (Ruth Fremson/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BRUNSWICK, GA. -- July 7, 2000 -- BRUNSWICK-SHIP-COX --
The Figaro, in background, a Roll On Roll Off cargo ship from
Singapore in Brunswick, Ga., after discharging its load of
automobiles. About 20,000 automobiles are usually on hand after
their arrival from sea, according to port officials. (David
Tulis/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) JERUSALEM -- July 7, 2000 -- ISRAEL-TEMPLE-DESECRATE --
In the second attack on a non-Orthodox site in two weeks, vandals
smashed a glass facade and spray painted ``Satan'' on the entryway
at a Reform college and temple. The institution is the Hebrew
College Jewish Institute of Religion, which educates Reform rabbis
and houses a Reform synagogue. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York
Times)LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- ADV FOR SUN. JULY 9 --
HAMBURG-RADIO -- Joan Hamburg is the type of radio host that
listeners yearn to hear. Hamburg dispenses useful information on
WOR radio in the warm, confidential manner women use when chatting
with their friends. Her audience consists of a million and a half
people -- mostly women over 30. Her audience, nearly twice the size
of those for competing talk shows, earns the station nearly $1
million a year in revenue, a remarkable figure for a daytime show.
Hamburg in a studio at WOR where she has been broadcasting for 21
years. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 7, 2000 -- ADV FOR SUN. JULY 9 --
FAKE-HANDBAGS -- There is a new breed of sidewalk shopper that have
style and can afford to pay retail prices but enjoy the thrill of
adding a $30 counterfeit item to their wardrobes. Where the
shoppers likely to inspect merchandise by street vendors were once
mainly office workers and tourists, now they are as likely to be
chic passers-by, clutching a genuine Prada shoulder bag or a tote
emblazoned with the real Gucci logo. Lauren Strax, a college
student from Houston, Texas, checking out handbags on 60th Street
in Manhattan. (Nancy Siesel/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
