<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-OVERSIGHT-N     07-07 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-OVERSIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CONSENT DECREE IS WILD CARD IN TALKS ON POLICE OVERSIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Pa., N.J.)  By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The police departments vary greatly in size and in
the issues they face. The communities they serve are just as
diverse: the small town of Steubenville, Ohio, the city of
Pittsburgh and the entire state of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But in each of these places, the federal government has found
that the police force engaged in systemic violations of civil
rights. And each local government, to avoid a federal lawsuit,
agreed to accept federal oversight to ensure that changes would be
instituted.
</P>
<P>
   New York City, which is now facing a similar lawsuit, has said
it will consider accepting some form of federal oversight as well,
and the looming question is whether the city will accept the
established model of monitoring or forge some new method.
</P>
<P>
   Already there are indications that the breach between what the
city and the Justice Department will accept is so large that it may
undermine any success in reaching an agreement that would forestall
the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in Brooklyn have said for months that they
are prepared to sue the city to force changes in what they
characterize as the ineffective way the New York Police Department
investigates and disciplines officers accused of brutality. Their
findings, which the city disputes, were based on a two-year inquiry
begun after the August 1997 torture of Abner Louima in a Brooklyn
station house.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiations in other places, the federal government has
insisted on largely similar types of oversight.
</P>
<P>
   In each, the parties signed an agreement that detailed the basic
reforms and standards that were needed, like new training regimens.
In each, they agreed to the appointment of an outside auditor who
would measure the police force's compliance. And in each, the
written agreement was filed in federal court as a consent decree so
that any disputes over compliance would be subject to the review of
a federal judge, who could levy sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Based on interviews with people who have been involved in or
briefed on the negotiations in New York, it appears that the city
and the federal government are close to agreeing on some policy
changes needed, and on the appointment of an outside auditor. But
the city appears to be balking at entering into a consent decree.
</P>
<P>
   City lawyers have said they are, in general, reluctant to enter
into consent decrees because such decrees transfer power over city
agency matters to a federal judge, who may be less versed in the
operations of the agency and the needs of the city.
</P>
<P>
   But one federal official involved in the negotiations said it
was difficult to envision any settlement that would not involve the
parties signing a consent decree, or some legal agreement that
resembled it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to the fact that there has to be enforceability
that respects the agreement between the parties,'' the official
said, ``that permits the aggrieved party to go in and get
compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they are negotiating possible reforms, New York
officials have consistently said the police force is a model of
restraint and does an effective job of disciplining officers who
use excessive force.
</P>
<P>
   Settlements in other places were tailored to address particular
problems. For example, the Steubenville agreement called for the
city to set up a system to allow residents to file complaints
against officers, a procedure already in place in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But all three settlements call for the appointment of an outside
auditor, whose selection is ratified by a federal judge. The
auditors are paid by the local governments, and they prepare
periodic reports that measure police compliance with the consent
decrees.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh, for example, is paying Public Management Resources,
a Texas consulting firm, $400,000 to serve as the auditor for five
years. The auditors, who prepare quarterly reports, measure the
city's compliance with 70 provisions in a 40-page consent decree,
including its progress installing a computer system to track
officer histories for evidence of excessive force or racial
prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Each settlement calls for the auditors' reports to be forwarded
to the Justice Department. If prosecutors believe that there is
evidence of noncompliance, they can bring an action in federal
court to have the local government held in contempt.
</P>
<P>
   The length of oversight can vary, depending upon the agreement.
Pittsburgh signed its consent decree in 1997, and its oversight
will last at least five years. At that point, the oversight can be
lifted if a judge finds that the police department has been in
substantial compliance with the consent decree for at least two
years.
</P>
<P>
   If New York were to refuse to sign a consent decree, both
parties could still sign a simple contract that would not require
court approval. But if the city failed to keep the agreement, the
federal government's recourse would be to sue for breach of
contract, experts said, instead of bringing a contempt motion in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Witold Walczak, executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union chapter in Pittsburgh, said the settlement there
needed to be a consent decree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody realizes,'' he said, ``that without the threat of an
enforcement action by a federal judge, none of the reforms would
have taken place.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary DuFour, the city manager in Steubenville, said a settlement
in New York would have to be considerably different from the one
that covers his city of 22,000 on the West Virginia border.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have almost twice as many officers as we have citizens,''
he said. ``Some of the issues are going to be very different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
