<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS 65 PERCENT OF FEDERAL DEATH-ROW INMATES ARE BLACK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
and STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 65 percent of federal inmates on death row are black _ &UR;  &LR; a
sixfold increase over the percentage of African-Americans executed
before Congress expanded the list of death penalty crimes, an
analysis of U.S. Bureau of Prisons data shows.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert told reporters Friday that
President Clinton is likely to postpone the Aug. 5 execution of
Juan Raul Garza, the only Hispanic ever sentenced to die for a
federal crime. The decision came a week after Clinton expressed
concern that race and geographic location influenced the decision
to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Siewert said Clinton is awaiting updated Department of Justice
clemency guidelines in an effort to give Garza every opportunity to
avoid the deuovW(`1wr
</P>
