<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6374 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-SHERER-NYT &LR;      07-07 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SHERER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY SCHERER, 81, BROADCASTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)   By ERIC V. COPAGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ray Scherer, a former White House correspondent for NBC News who
covered six presidents, from Harry S. Truman to Gerald R. Ford,
before becoming an executive for the RCA Corp., died on July 1 at
his home in Washington. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Scherer's career in broadcast journalism began in the infancy of
television, when technical limitations meant interviews that could
be no longer than two minutes. In 1956, he was among the first
journalists to broadcast live from the floor of presidential
nominating conventions. He was also one of the first to report live
from the White House and to have a live nationally telecast midday
news program.
</P>
<P>
   Scherer was born on June 7, 1919, in Fort Wayne, Ind. His father
was the business manager of The Fort Wayne Journal-Gazette, for
which the younger Scherer delivered newspapers when he was a
teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Valparaiso University in Indiana and served in
the Navy in World War II. He earned a master's degree in
international relations from the University of Chicago and became a
feature writer at The Journal-Gazette. He became a staff news
writer at NBC in 1947 and soon became an on-air reporter.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 foot 4 inches and 200 pounds, he had an on-screen presence
that radiated authority in the early days of television news
broadcasts. He once calculated that he had logged 250,000 miles on
various assignments in his 28 years as a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to covering the White House, Scherer reported on the
Pentagon, Congress and, for four years beginning in 1969, Europe.
He retired from journalism in 1975 and became a vice president with
RCA, at the time the parent company of NBC. He retired from that
position in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Scherer is survived by his wife of 48 years, the former Barbara
Hetzner; a daughter, Nancy, of St. Paul; a son, David, of
Washington; and two grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
