</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DEATHROW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FEDERAL DEATH ROW  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 8:
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government cannot by any measure of fairness carry out
executions when there is powerful evidence of racial discrimination
and geographic disparities in the imposition of federal death
sentences. The Clinton administration, which has been unflinching
in its support for capital punishment, is planning to take a small
step in the direction of justice by postponing the execution of
Juan Raul Garza.
</P>
<P>
   Garza, a migrant worker, was sentenced to death in 1993 under
federal law for three drug-related murders in Texas. He is
scheduled to die on Aug. 5, making him the first inmate to face
execution by the federal government in nearly 40 years. The White
House says it will postpone the execution to allow Garza to apply
for clemency from the president under new rules that the Justice
Department will issue soon.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary stay, though welcome, does not address the flaws
in the system that has condemned Garza. This page has long opposed
capital punishment on constitutional and moral grounds. At the very
least President Clinton needs to order a moratorium on all federal
executions until glaring inequities of race and geography can be
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The Garza case engages both issues. The government has long had
the duty of protecting racial minorities from discrimination. Yet
racial bias in the federal system is worse than it is in most
states. Of the 21 inmates facing federal death sentences, 17 are
members of racial minorities, and 13 of those are
African-Americans. These are overwhelmingly disproportionate
numbers. Indeed, there is a higher percentage of blacks on federal
death row than in the vast majority of death-penalty states,
including Texas and Alabama. Of the 199 cases in which the Justice
Department authorized the federal death penalty since 1988, 76
percent involved minority defendants, 52 percent of them
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The geographic disparities are also startling. Fourteen of 21
death row inmates are from three states _ Texas, Virginia and
Missouri. Nearly half of the death-penalty requests sent by federal
prosecutors to the Justice Department for review in recent years
came from a handful of federal districts. Yet there are many
federal prosecutors who have not filed any death-penalty requests,
even though there is no reason to believe that the nature of crimes
varies so greatly from city to city. But because prosecutors have
discretion in deciding what crime to charge and whether to offer a
plea bargain, the same crime may lead to death in one jurisdiction
but not in another.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is completing a report on these
disparities. Even Clinton last week acknowledged that he was
disturbed by the racial composition of the death row population and
the fact that ``what your prosecution is may turn solely on where
you committed the crime.'' He needs to act on his observations and
re-examine this grossly unjust system. He cannot allow the Justice
Department, which routinely investigates bias by state and local
governments, to operate a system that disproportionately condemns
minority members to death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
