<HEADER>
A6392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-BAKALY-NYT &LR;      07-07 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BAKALY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN ILL-CONSIDERED PROSECUTION  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 8:
</P>
<P>
   In a regrettable denouement to the Clinton impeachment drama, a
former spokesman for Kenneth Starr has been charged with criminal
contempt in an investigation of news leaks stemming from the Monica
Lewinsky inquiry. The former spokesman, Charles Bakaly III, is
scheduled to stand trial beginning next week, according to recently
unsealed court documents.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a front-page article that appeared in The New York
Times on Jan. 31, 1999, in the midst of President Clinton's trial
before the Senate. Citing ``several associates of Mr. Starr'' as
sources, the article reported that Starr had concluded that he had
constitutional authority to indict a sitting president, but had not
decided whether, or when, to seek such an indictment. Bakaly, who
resigned abruptly from Starr's office after an internal
investigation of unauthorized disclosures, said at the time and has
since maintained that he was not a source of the article.
</P>
<P>
   It is the policy of The Times not to discuss sources. But as a
general matter we look askance at crusades by the federal
government to prevent leaks, as they are almost always aimed at
damming up information the American people are entitled to know,
rather than safeguarding any legitimate secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The invocation of the criminal process against Bakaly is
particularly troubling in that the subject matter of the leak _ the
fact that Starr was considering indicting a sitting president _ was
obviously of great national moment. Moreover, a federal appeals
court ruled last September that there was no violation of grand
jury secrecy, and thus nothing illegal, in the discussions Starr
and his aides may have had with reporters about these
deliberations, either for direct attribution or on a background
basis.
</P>
<P>
   To pursue Bakaly under these circumstances on charges that he
lied to investigators seems unduly punitive and extreme. We would
have the same view if the dispute involved another newspaper or
broadcast news outlet. The government is serving no important
public interest with this after-the-fact witch hunt. Rather this
prosecution will chill the news-gathering process in a world where
the public must rely for crucial information on the willingness of
government officials to be forthcoming with reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-00 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
