<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SEASIA-ECON-1STLD-WRI     07-07 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEASIA-ECON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ECONOMIC GROWTH, SOUTHEAST ASIA'S STOCKS ARE SINKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS ``for'' to ``far'' in 7th graf)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Southeast Asia's economies are growing again. Its
stock markets are getting smaller.
</P>
<P>
   If that contrast sounds odd, it is. Last December, economists
and analysts predicted that 2000 would be a boom year for Asian
stocks and currencies. They said foreign investors, enriched with
gains in high-technology stocks, would snap up Indonesian rupiah,
Thai baht and Philippine pesos to buy stocks and bet on the
region's continued recovery from the financial crisis that began in
mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   Those forecasts have gone astray. Foreign investors have sold
Southeast Asian stocks and currencies for much of the year, helping
make several of the region's markets among the worst performing in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and fund managers attribute the sell-off to a
perception that Southeast Asia, despite an economic rebound,
remains a dangerous place to invest because of political
instability, corruption and a lack of technological sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's looking at fundamentals these days,'' said Rebecca H.
Patterson, a currency strategist at J.P. Morgan in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much investment funds from the United States, Europe
and Japan have sold is difficult to determine. Securities exchanges
in some countries, notably Singapore, do not release figures on
foreign trading.
</P>
<P>
   Lipper Analytical Services in New York says that so far this
year at least $230 million had been pulled out of United States
funds that make investments in Asian markets other than Japan's.
But that figure would tend to understate the situation, because it
includes funds investing in popular markets like South Korea,
Taiwan, China and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Figures from individual exchanges indicate where withdrawals and
investment losses are worst. The Philippine Stock Exchange reports
that foreigners have sold roughly $172 million more than they have
bought so far this year. In Thailand, foreigners have sold nearly
$700 million more in Thai stocks than they have bought. In
Indonesia, foreigners had a $20 million net withdrawal in the first
five months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the benchmark stock indexes in the region have dropped
25 percent or more, making the 7.5 percent year-to-date decline of
the Dow industrial average look modest. The exchange values of most
Southeast Asian currencies have also fallen sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's benchmark stock index is down 25 percent. Combined
with a 31 percent currency-rate decline, Indonesian stocks have
lost nearly 56 percent of their value in dollar terms this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that this may balloon into another crisis,''
said Steven Lim, who manages $500 million in investments in
Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia for Daiwa International, the
Japanese investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lim cites the problems of an Indonesian fishing company, Daya
Guna Samudera, to indicate how the investment statistics apply in
real terms.
</P>
<P>
   Daya Guna has exclusive licenses to catch and export fish and
shrimp from Indonesia's teeming eastern seas. With its costs in
Indonesian rupiah and its revenue in dollars, investing in Daya
Guna seemed like an obvious opportunity last year.
</P>
<P>
   But in December, the company informed investors that its catch
had fallen 15 percent from the previous year. A third of its crew
members, it said, had deserted to escape Muslim-Christian clashes
in the eastern islands, leaving many new fishing vessels idle and
the company in difficulty with creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Seen more broadly, missing fishermen are the least of problems
Indonesia is having with foreign investors now.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia, Muslim rebels in the west, secessionists in the
east and sectarian clashes on the islands in between have crippled
confidence. Skirmishing between President Abdurrahman Wahid, his
central bank chief and his cabinet have left the economy
rudderless.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat similar troubles are souring investor sentiment
elsewhere in the region. In the Philippines, insurgents in two
separate Muslim rebellions have brought bombings to the capital and
have kept 20 scuba divers hostage on a jungle island for nearly two
months _ situations that do little to entice foreign capital. Nor
has an insider-trading scandal involving a friend of President
Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Thailand is tamer. But a two-year court battle
between the founder of a local plastics maker and its bankers has
underlined the troubles still faced by Thai banks as they try to
recover the 40 percent of their loans that borrowers cannot or will
not repay. Banks make up roughly a quarter of the benchmark stock
index, leading Peggy Creveling, who heads Salomon Smith Barney's
research in Thailand, to ask, ``how can the market go up?''
</P>
<P>
   Malaysian stocks, which had been rising this year in
anticipation of their inclusion again in global market indexes,
have lately succumbed to the exodus of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
   And Singapore, famously stable and in the midst of an economic
liberalization campaign, is suffering the effects of living in a
tough neighborhood.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I don't get it,'' said Chia Yeng Boo, 53, a Singaporean
investor, as he watched local stock prices dwindle on a television
screen. ``The economy keeps getting better, but the stocks keep
going down.''
</P>
<P>
   Local investors expecting a flood of foreign funds this year
helped fuel a powerful rally late in 1999, particularly in
electronics and telecommunications stocks. Their logic: when
Nasdaq's bulls came to bank on a Southeast Asian recovery, they
would look for anything remotely related to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But smaller markets in the region lacked sufficient Internet
appeal for foreign investors. There were just not enough high-end
exports, dot-com stock offerings or flashy Internet market
statistics, analysts say, to match markets in Tokyo, Seoul, Taipei
and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq rout in technology shares in April made things even
worse. Investors, rather than seizing an opportunity to jump into
fundamental economic stories like Southeast Asia's, simply lost
their appetite for any risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
